<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HARTSBURG-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARTSBURG BRACES FOR MIGHTY CHALLENGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Craig Hartsburg won't get the chance to
rebuild the Chicago Blackhawks. Instead, he will try to help the
Anaheim Mighty Ducks rebound from one of their most disappointing
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg, fired by the Blackhawks after the team failed to make
the playoffs for the first time in 29 years, was hired as the Ducks
coach on July 21. Making the move to the West Coast and to the
Disney-owned Ducks is no less challenging than what he would have
faced if he stayed in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The Blackhawks were 30-39-13 last season, which led Hartsburg to
say just before his firing that the team needed a ``total
overhaul.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Ducks were 26-43-13, Hartsburg doesn't think the
Ducks need that kind of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are quality people here and I'm excited about the
opportunity,'' said Hartsburg, who became the Ducks third head
coach in 14 months.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg, who filled the NHL's last coaching vacancy after
Butch Goring turned it down, is happy to have another job, even if
it's with an organization many consider to be in a state of
disarray as it begins its sixth season.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks, with less than a month to go before training camp,
have yet to make a major free-agent signing, have an unproven
defense and suspect depth. But Hartsburg, who signed a three-year
contract worth just over $1.2 million, at least has the dynamic duo
of Paul Kariya and Teemu Selanne to work with after having
practically no offense in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a team that can skate and generate offense,'' he said.
``The area we need to focus on is to become a solid defensive team.
Our defense as a team needs to improve and not just the
defensmen.''
</P>
<P>
   Like deposed coach Pierre Page, Hartsburg worked under Jack
Ferreira in Minnesota. (Ferreira is the Ducks vice president.)
After finishing a 10-year career as a defenseman with the North
Stars, Hartsburg, three times an all-star, was hired by Ferreira as
an assistant coach for the 1989-90 season.
</P>
<P>
   Being Ferreira's friend didn't mean much in the way of job
security for Page, who lasted only 10 months. But Hartsburg did get
a good review from Pierre Gauthier, who had yet to take over as
general manager when Hartsburg was hired.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the franchise's guy,'' said Gauthier. ``I know Craig,
he's a solid hockey man and he's really grown as a coach. I feel
very comfortable with him being here. I did interview him when he
came through the second time around, and Jack had my full support
in hiring him.''
</P>
<P>
   But after his experience in Chicago, Hartsburg doesn't come to
Southern California with any preconceived notions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to be here for 20 years, but I'm not worried about
anything else but making the (Ducks) a team. If I was worried
(about job security) I'm not going to do a good job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be intense and have fun. If you're not enjoying
it, why bother?''
</P>
<P>
   After four years as an assistant in Philadelphia and one
successful head coaching stint in the Ontario Hockey League
(47-14-5 with Guelph), Hartsburg was 104-102-40 in three years with
the Blackhawks. Chicago made the playoffs twice before the miserly
ways of Chicago owner William Wirtz caught up with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very disappointed and hurt,'' Hartsburg said being fired
with two years left on his contract. ``But I had to move on.... I
knew I'd be back. I'm excited about the future, not worried about
the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago GM Bob Murray sounded apologetic when he announced
Hartsburg's firing. Most believe the move was ordered by Wirtz, who
was no doubt unhappy with his coaching calling for an ``overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Craig Hartsburg sold out his soul to try to get this team
going,'' Murray said. ``The things he tried to motivate this team
ran the gamut and nothing worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg's motivational techniques will be needed with the
Ducks. And, one of the first things he must address is his
relationship with Kariya. Already Hartsburg has had some private
conversations with Kariya, who was on the receiving end of a Gary
Suter cross-check that ended his season last Feb. 1. Suter,
Hartsburg and the Blackhawks were soon public enemy No. 1 among
Ducks fans, especially when Suter and Hartsburg doubted the
severity of Kariya's injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it didn't set off angry words (on both sides), we wouldn't
be worth a darn,'' he said. ``(But) to me it's over and done with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to Paul about it. I was protecting my side, they
were protecting theirs. Emotions were a little high and things were
said on both sides that probably shouldn't have been said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I was protecting Gary Suter, this year I'm only
concerned with protecting Paul Kariya.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows what Kariya and Hartsburg have said in private, but
before Hartsburg was named coach the Anaheim star said he could
play for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't hold a vendetta against everybody who says something
bad about you ... you can't hold grudges,'' Kariya said.
``Everybody says something to everybody else and you've got to deal
with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't have a problem with him personally. You've got
to take what's on the ice and leave it there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
