<HEADER>
A0497 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-EMANUEL-HNS &LR;      08-19 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-EMANUEL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Emanuel expects to help lead Bucs
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
TAMPA, Fla. _ During his playing career at Langham Creek High
School and Rice University, Bert Emanuel was drafted two times in
baseball and once in football, but he did not strike it rich until
the Tampa Bay Buccaneers gave him 16.4 million reasons to leave
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay waited to see if Atlanta would match its four-year,
$16.4 million offer to Emanuel, a transition free agent, but no one
in the Buccaneers organization was more nervous than quarterback
Trent Dilfer.
</P>
<P>
   As the clock ticked down on the seven-day deadline, Dilfer kept
his fingers crossed. After all, Emanuel was just the kind of
receiver the Buccaneers needed to play opposite Reidel Anthony, a
No. 1 pick in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I was excited and relieved when Atlanta didn't
match,'' Dilfer says. ``I'd been working on them (Buccaneers
general manager Rich McKay and coach Tony Dungy) to get him for a
year. I knew Bert would fit our system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only does he have outstanding speed, but the game's so
complicated, a receiver has to be able to adjust on the run, react
instinctively to blitzes and coverages and still catch the ball. He
can do all those things. That's why he's going to be a great player
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding Emanuel and top draft choice Jacquez Green with Anthony
gives the Bucs a three-receiver formation that has more speed than
a track team.
</P>
<P>
   If Emanuel were a cornerback lining up opposite Tampa Bay's
receivers, he would have one thought in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fear,'' he says. ``The fear of being outrun. It has to be in
the back of a defensive back's mind when he plays against us.''
</P>
<P>
   Few receivers are faster than Emanuel, who caught 65 passes for
991 yards (15.2 average) and nine touchdowns last season. In his
first three seasons with the Falcons, Emanuel had 46, 74 and 75
receptions.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons tendered him a one-year offer of $2.65 million
thinking no one would top it, but the Bucs stunned them. If Emanuel
ever had any doubts about not being allowed to play quarterback,
his position at Rice, they were put to rest when he was rewarded
with his new contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a position where I had no leverage because I was a
transitional guy, but this was the place I wanted to play,''
Emanuel says. ``The Bucs are a team on the rise, and I wanted to be
part of it. It's a young team with an outstanding coaching staff
and great management. The owners take care of their players. All of
that really attracted me to Tampa Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   After last season when the Bucs finished 10-6 and made the
playoffs for the first time since 1982, McKay and Dungy vowed to
improve the receivers. They wanted to find a go-to receiver for
Dilfer, who needed a favorite target to bail them out on
third-and-long and to stretch the defense to open up the underneath
routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have good receivers to win, and Bert's a great
one,'' Dilfer says. ``You can run the ball 80 percent of the time,
but the 20 percent when you're throwing it, those are usually the
biggest downs in the game. The receivers have to get open.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you consider what defenses are doing and how much they're
getting away with, you must have talented receivers. We were awful
at receiver previously. It was terrible, but they (management)
slowly improved that. Now, I think our corps is going to be one of
the better ones in the league. Speed at receiver is something we
can hang our hat on.''
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel doesn't want to be recognized just for his speed. He's
also smart and tough and runs precise routes.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he has been in the league for only four years, he
has to be a leader on a young offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leadership's important because it means you're stepping up and
making plays when the game's on the line,'' Emanuel says. ``That's
something I've been doing the last four years. It's something I've
prided myself on.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the Bucs have speed and talent at receiver, Emanuel
knows they will see different tactics from defenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some defenses will get in our faces and challenge us,'' he
says. ``Others will back off 10 yards and try to keep us in front
of them. It depends on what kind of corners they have. Teams that
don't have a lot of confidence in their corners will give us softer
coverage. We have to be able to adjust to whatever's thrown at us,
and I'm confident we will.''
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel has become a notorious slow starter in the preseason. In
his last preseason with the Falcons, he didn't catch a pass until
the last game. He doesn't have a reception in three preseason games
with the Bucs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This happens to me every preseason,'' he says. ``I was a
little concerned last year because I knew I'd be trying to get a
new contract, and we were learning a new quarterback (Chris
Chandler). I wondered what was going on. Then, everything fell into
place, and I had a good season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about it now. I've gotten kind of used to it.
I'm learning a new offense and working with a new quarterback
again. These things take time, but I know it'll all come
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel can't believe his good fortune in going from Atlanta to
Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like night and day, really,'' he says. ``The attitude
here is that when we step on the field, we're going to win. It
almost feels like we're playing on a different level than everyone
else. That's a mindset, but it's not something I've been used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Dungy can't believe his good fortune, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go after a restricted player, you usually don't get
those guys,'' Dungy says. ``When we found out Bert really wanted to
come here, we zeroed in on him and thought we might have a chance
to get him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We followed his career. Naturally, we liked him a lot. He
caught a lot of balls. He's still young. He's a high-class guy, the
kind we're looking for. He was productive every season, and he
improved every season. We just liked everything about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Just because he is being so well-paid doesn't mean Emanuel is
under more pressure. If he is, he doesn't show it, because he's so
calm and focused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I am,'' he says. ``My job title's not going to
change. You know, I've got to catch the ball and make plays. I've
got to score touchdowns. All they're asking me to do are the same
things I've been doing for four years. I'm just getting paid a
little bit more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
