<HEADER>
A0500 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-RDP-ART-1STLD     08-19 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-RDP-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1,150(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR CALLS LEWINSKY BACK TO TESTIFY BEFORE GRAND JURY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 5th graf for new material, adds 9 new grafs at end of story
and subs for re-editing throughout) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See also: EXCLUSIVE-CLINTON-LEWINSKY, CLINTON-VINEYARD,
CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-HILLARY, CLINTON-POLITICS, CLINTON-LEGAL,
CLINTON-SPEECH, CLINTON-VOICES with photo, CLINTON-PUNDITS,
CLINTON-CABINET, NY-CLINTON-SENATE, CLINTON-GORE) 
(sw) 
 By JAMES BENNET and DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Prosecutors opened a new line of inquiry into
President Clinton's actions on Tuesday, summoning Monica Lewinsky
to testify again to the federal grand jury here, on Thursday. It
was one of several signs that Clinton did not succeed in ending his
legal or political troubles by acknowledging an intimate
relationship with her.
</P>
<P>
   The move to bring Ms. Lewinsky back to the grand jury reflected
a decision by the Whitewater independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, to
pit her testimony against the president's to see whether there are
inconsistencies, according to people familiar with his strategy.
</P>
<P>
   That approach, a classic prosecutorial tactic, indicated that
Starr was trying to determine whether Clinton might have perjured
himself before the grand jury, a new subject for an investigation
that has already lasted seven months.
</P>
<P>
   New details emerged on Tuesday about what was described as a
warlike exchange during the president's testimony on Monday, which
was transmitted to the grand jury here. Although Clinton politely
shook hands with prosecutors before and after they squared off, the
questioning turned confrontational, with Starr threatening at
points to subpoena the president for further testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the session, Clinton read a statement to grand jurors
describing his physical contacts with Ms. Lewinsky, a person
familiar with his testimony said. After that point, he deflected
questions posed by Starr and prosecutors about the details of such
encounters. His private lawyers signaled an end to the four-hour
session before Starr and his team had finished.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton denied under oath, as he did later in his address to the
nation, that he had obstructed justice, lawyers said. Specifically,
they said, he testified that he had not asked his personal
secretary, Betty Currie, to retrieve from Ms. Lewinsky some gifts
that he had given her.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's private lawyer, David Kendall, said on Tuesday that
the president did not decline to answer any questions about
possible obstruction of justice. ``As to a very few highly
intrusive questions with respect to the specifics of his relation
to Ms. Lewinsky, he gave candid but not detailed answers,'' Kendall
said. ``This was to preserve personal privacy and institutional
dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Clinton family, the White House staff and the country
began on Tuesday to absorb Monday's extraordinary events, friends
of Ms. Lewinsky, like many Republican and Democratic officeholders
here, expressed disappointment with the president's speech. They
said that the president should have apologized directly to Ms.
Lewinsky and her family for his role in shoving them into a
maelstrom of legal and media scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's four-minute address left even some Democrats
complaining that he fell short of an apology and spoke more in
anger than in sorrow. Some said that they would have to await a
report by Starr to Congress before deciding whether the matter
should be set aside without impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, his wife, Hillary, and their daughter, Chelsea,
strolled to a helicopter on the South Lawn on Tuesday afternoon and
departed for a vacation on Martha's Vineyard. Aides said the
president would probably interrupt his trip for at least two public
events, putting into practice his argument on Monday night that it
was time to turn from the investigation to ``important work.''
</P>
<P>
   Before departing on Tuesday, Clinton spent more than an hour
with his foreign policy advisers, and he also worked the telephone.
His advisers said that he was mostly fielding supportive calls from
friends on Capitol Hill and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Assorted characters who had faded from Clinton's long-running
political drama abruptly reappeared on the stage. Dick Morris, once
Clinton's most valued political adviser, testified for nearly five
hours at the federal courthouse here about several conversations he
had with the president in January, after the Lewinsky case became
public. In a television appearance Tuesday night on Fox News,
Morris said that Clinton acknowledged to him in January that
``something'' had happened between him and Ms. Lewinsky and that
the president seemed to be wavering between unburdening himself to
the American people and keeping quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Morris theorized that Clinton might have been swayed to keep
silent by a confidential poll in January showing that the public
might not forgive him if he had lied under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Morris resigned during the Democratic National Convention in
August 1996, after it was disclosed that he had had an affair with
a prostitute. Starr's decision to call him to the federal
courthouse on Tuesday provided a sharp counterpoint to the
president's plea on Monday night to turn away from seamier aspects
of political life.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Paula Jones, whose sexual misconduct lawsuit against Clinton led
to the Lewinsky investigation, issued a rare public statement on
Tuesday. ``It is very important that Mr. Clinton and other men like
him learn that what Mr. Clinton did to me was wrong and that there
are consequences to taking advantage of other people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones said in her lawsuit that in 1991, when he was
governor of Arkansas, Clinton lewdly propositioned her in a Little
Rock, Ark., hotel room. Her lawsuit was dismissed by a federal
judge on April 1, but she is appealing the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that Mr. Clinton's lack of remorse for his
wrongdoing shows why it is so important that the trial court's
decision in my case be reversed,'' Mrs. Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton denied that he had propositioned Mrs. Jones, but in his
deposition in the suit in January he was asked whether he had had a
sexual relationship with Ms. Lewinsky. He denied such a
relationship under oath, unaware that Starr had begun investigating
whether he had tried to obstruct justice by covering up his
contacts with Ms. Lewinsky. Starr added the possibility that
Clinton committed perjury to his list of possible crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Though he admitted in his testimony Monday to ``inappropriate,
intimate physical contact'' with Ms. Lewinsky, Clinton said that he
had not committed perjury in the Jones deposition, lawyers familiar
with his sealed testimony said. The president said that the type of
contact he had with Ms. Lewinsky did not fit the definition of sex
used by the Jones lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   About midway through the questioning, Clinton lost his
notoriously volcanic temper at a question posed by a prosecutor.
Shortly afterward, there was a break for nearly one hour while
Clinton huddled with his lawyers in the doctor's office in the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   While they talked, an electronic system maintained by the Secret
Service that tracks the president's movements showed that he had
gone to the doctor's office, raising concerns among White House
staff members that he had fallen ill.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the White House on Tuesday, senior advisers to the president
were besieged with telephone calls from reporters asking whether
they felt betrayed by his private and public denials of a sexual
relationship with a former intern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never knew there were so many reporters who were worried
about our feelings,'' said John Podesta, the deputy White House
chief of staff. Asked how he felt, Podesta laughed loudly and said,
``I'm curled up in a fetal position,'' before quickly adding, ``I
am doing just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   White House advisers said that for the most part, Tuesday was
spent assimilating the revelations of Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Another official said that the White House was not overly
concerned about the mixed reaction on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all sort of queasy and trying to figure out the
political implications of this,'' he said. ``They don't want to get
too far ahead of the public in either direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest New York Times/CBS News Poll, taken on Tuesday
evening, found that respondents' opinion had not changed in the day
after the president's speech to the nation. In Monday night's poll,
for instance, 58 percent of viewers said they were satisfied with
Clinton's explanation. In Tuesday night's poll the figure was a
statistically indistinguishable 60 percent satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   The poll found that the public continued to be divided over
whether Clinton was involved in any obstruction of justice.
Thirty-three percent said accusations that he encouraged Ms.
Lewinsky to lie under oath were probably true, 32 percent said the
accusations were probably not true, and 31 percent said they did
not know enough to say.
</P>
<P>
   That division was almost exactly the same as measured last week
by a CBS News poll.
</P>
<P>
   The new poll, based on 509 adults nationwide who were
interviewed by CBS News last week, has a margin of sampling error
of plus or minus four percentage points. But polls conducted in
just one night are subject to additional error because of the
limited time available to contact people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
