<HEADER>
A0509 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-REDSOX-TE     08-19 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-REDSOX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX SWEEP PAST RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Rangers utilize right-hander John Wetteland as
their closer.
</P>
<P>
   Honestly, folks.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland, who made his most recent appearance eight days ago,
witnessed the Red Sox sweep yesterday's day//night doubleheader
from his perch in Fenway Park's right-field bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   (Great seat, eh?)
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Mo Vaughn, who served as the designated hitter,
ensured there would be no split of this two-game affair with his
seventh-inning, solo home run off right-hander Danny Patterson
(1-5) in the Red Sox's 5-4 victory in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox right-hander Pedro Martinez, who recorded 10 strikeouts
in 8 2/3 innings, surrendered one run on five hits and one walk in
a 4-1 victory in the afternoon opener.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Rangers concluded this grueling, eight-game swing
through Cleveland, New York and Boston with only two victories
during their nine-day excursion. The Rangers returned to Texas this
morning at least 1 1/2 and perhaps 2 1/2 games behind in the AL
West pending the result of the Angels' game against the White Sox
last night in Anaheim, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland pitched only once during this road trip. The
right-hander recorded his 32nd save during the Rangers' 2-1 victory
Aug. 11 against the Indians at Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the Rangers rendered their closer useless as the
Maytag repairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``A closer is only as good as his team,'' right-hander Tim
Crabtree said. ``We can't use him if we're not winning. We just
didn't get the game to John.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers instead placed the burden on right-handers Crabtree,
Patterson and Xavier Hernandez. Those three relievers _ whom
manager Johnny Oates relies on during the sixth, seventh and eighth
innings _ combined for nine appearances in the past four days
despite the postponement of Monday's scheduled game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bullpen is not strained,'' Oates said. ``It's those three
guys. We can't get to John.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers could not place the game on Wetteland's right
shoulder after Vaughn's seventh-inning home run. It gave Vaughn
seven home runs in 11 games this season against the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most teams have a `Mo,' but Mo is Mo,'' Oates said, ``and he's
put `Mo' hurtin' on us than most people, especially with the long
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers right-hander Rick Helling entered the sixth inning with
a 4-2 lead, but he surrendered a leadoff double to shortstop Nomar
Garciaparra and issued a walk to left fielder Troy O'Leary after
the latter fouled off six 3-2 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra and O'Leary eventually scored after a double by
first baseman Mike Stanley and a sacrifice fly ball from catcher
Jason Varitek. Helling threw 127 pitches though his 5 2/3 innings,
which forced Oates to summon Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander John Burkett (7-13) allowed only one hit to the Red
Sox through five scoreless innings in the afternoon game, but he
could not complete the sixth. The Red Sox tied the score on a
run-scoring double from third baseman John Valentin and took a 2-1
lead on a two-out single by O'Leary. Oates removed Burkett when
Stanley reached after being hit by a pitch to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox manager Jimy Williams summoned a pinch hitter in the
form of former Rangers center fielder Damon Buford, who greeted
left-hander Eric Gunderson with a two-run double on a 2-0 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   That would be an insurmountable deficit with Martinez (16-4)
pitching lights out and strengthening his bid as the No. 1
candidate to become the AL's 1998 Cy Young Award recipient.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to find a better pitcher than him,'' Oates said.
``He's a No. 1 starter. You can pencil him in for 20 victories
before the season begins, and there's not a half-dozen of them in
this league.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers return to The Ballpark in Arlington for an
eight-game home stand, but it will begin tonight with the first of
two games against the Central Division-leading Indians. The
Yankees, the major leagues' best team, arrive for a three-game
series beginning Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland might make an appearance, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
