<SLUG> BC-20TH-CENTURY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURER 20TH CENTURY CAUGHT IN MILLENNIUM'S NAME GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY CHRIS J. PARKER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Auto insurer 20th Century Industries Inc. has a
unique Y2K problem. In fact, some might say the Woodland
Hills-based company has a Y20C problem.
</P>
<P>
   That's because 500 days from today, it'll no longer be doing
business in the 20th Century. And who wants a company's products
that are a millennium old?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real issue but it's not a bad one,'' said William L.
Mellick, 20th Century's president and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Mellick said executives have been discussing what to do about
their company's name for several years. Shareholders also have
quizzed Mellick about it during the company's annual meetings the
past few years, but no changes are imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we have a brand name identification'' with 20th
Century, Mellick said. The company insures 1.1 million drivers in
California and Arizona and expects to begin offering insurance in
Oregon, Washington and Nevada before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   For now, 20th Century is happy to be, well, not part of the new
century. In fact, the company's main office at the Tishman Plaza is
being renamed the 20th Century Plaza once an 11-story tower is
built next to its current headquarters. The new office is expected
to open in December 1999, just in time to welcome in the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the company has taken out copyrights on such names as
21st Century Casualty Co. in case officials decide a name change is
necessary by the time the world's calendars change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've positioned ourselves so if that's the way to go, we're
ready,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &UR;  &QL;
</P>
