<SLUG> BC-NY-SUPERSIGN-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINE TO ERECT `SUPERSIGN' AT MIDTOWN BUS TERMINAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The intersection of 42nd Street and Eighth Avenue has
always been a lively marketplace but, until recently, not really
the sort to attract a blue-chip national advertiser.
</P>
<P>
   However, in the latest example of the changing commercial
climate along 42nd Street, Delta Air Lines has signed a three-year
sublease for space on the corner of the Port Authority Bus
Terminal, where it will erect a 3,000-square-foot supersign
sometime by the spring of next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty-Second Street is the most exciting out-of-home
opportunity in the world,'' said Jodi Yegelwel, senior vice
president and director of marketing at Transportation Displays
Inc., a division of CBS.
</P>
<P>
   TDI is an outdoor advertising company _ ``out-of-home media,''
as they say in the industry _ that holds a 20-year lease for signs
on the bus terminal from the Port Authority of New York and New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's sign will be one of six or so on an open steel framework
that is to wrap around the upper levels of the building, in front
of the distinctive 45-foot-high, X-shaped girders. The
900-foot-long steel grid will rise above and dwarf the current
billboard for the Showtime cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   The Port Authority requires that nothing on the grid interfere
with the ventilation and exhaust systems on the upper levels.
Effectively, that cuts in half the amount of space available for
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bus terminal is first and foremost for the 185,000 people
a day who use it,'' said Cherrie Nanninga, real estate director for
the Port Authority. ``We have to be ultra-careful about what is put
up, to maintain safety, comfort and convenience.''
</P>
<P>
   TDI will pay a percentage of the advertising revenue to the Port
Authority in lieu of rent, amounting to about $2 million a year.
The specific terms of the Delta deal were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Supersigns are a significant property investment. Advertisers on
the terminal must sign five-year leases (Delta was given a break
since it was the first tenant) and pay for design, construction and
installation, which can run into the millions of dollars, as well
as maintenance and utilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than buying a sign, this is a piece of real estate that
you're buying over a five-year period,'' said Brigg Dinley, the
business development director for special projects at TDI. ``It's
like buying a house.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that this house is seen every day by 185,000
commuters, along with a big percentage of the uncountable millions
of tourists, theatergoers and hotel guests in the area _ plus the
random New Yorker or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is such an important market for all airlines,'' said
Schuyler Wickes, the Delta account executive at the advertising
firm of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi in Atlanta. ``Delta is not a regional
carrier anymore. It's a major global carrier. This is an
opportunity to position Delta as exactly that.''
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging the intersection's raffish past, Wickes said that
was no longer a concern. ``That's not considered fringe these
days,'' he said. ``The infusion of hotels, the great American
corporations moving in _ that's the stamp of approval.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Cater-corner from the terminal, TDI holds a 20-year lease on the
E Walk retail and entertainment complex being built by Tishman
Urban Development Corp. As many as a dozen supersigns may go there,
said Donald Allman, chief operating officer of TDI.
</P>
<P>
   TDI also has billboards on sidewalk scaffolds along 42nd Street,
from Seventh to Eighth Avenues. ``We think they are the longest
signs in the world,'' Allman said.
</P>
<P>
   These include the 450-foot Showtime sign, a 430-foot NBC sign at
E Walk, a 387-foot Timberland boots sign where Forest City Ratner
is building an entertainment and retail complex, and a 76-foot sign
for Channel 2 (WCBS) in front of the Candler Building, at 220 W.
42nd St.
</P>
<P>
   That represents a quarter-mile of advertising already, but TDI
has more in store. In the fall, it will install seven temporary
advertising panels between the neoclassical columns of the Times
Square Theater, at 219 W. 42nd St.
</P>
<P>
   Cora Cahan, president of New 42nd Street Inc., a nonprofit
organization that holds the lease to the theater, said the sign
would generate about $100,000 over three months. The group will
apply that toward the construction of a new rehearsal space next
door. Ms. Cahan said the sign would be a ``playful'' addition to
the facade, which is eventually to be restored.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Levine, senior vice president at TDI, said, ``When the
signs are taken down, you won't know we were there.''
</P>
<P>
   No design details have been made public yet on the Delta sign.
But the airline offered a taste of its unusual approach last
summer, when it erected a ``living billboard'' in a parking lot
across from the bus terminal. This full-scale mock-up of the
fuselage of a jetliner was 44 feet long and 16 feet high, ample
enough to accommodate passengers and flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   The first airline supersign, for Trans World Airlines, was
erected in 1955 by Artkraft Strauss at Broadway and 43rd Street.
``It wasn't exactly a beautiful sign, perhaps, but it was
arresting,'' wrote Tama Starr and Edward Hayman in ``Signs and
Wonders'' (Currency Doubleday), their new book on spectacular
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Atop the billboard was a 45-foot-long model of a Lockheed Super
Constellation with spinning propellers, blinking running lights and
a cabin full of dummy passengers. In 1996, Artkraft Strauss
installed a 102-foot-long model of a British Airways Concorde at
Broadway and 42nd Street.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
