u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CITY-CHARTER-560&AMP;A     08-19 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CITY-CHARTER-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY CHARTER PANEL DROPS LATEST CAMPAIGN FINANCE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the latest in a series of hurried retreats, the
mayoral commission considering amendments to the city charter bowed
to sustained criticism Tuesday night and abandoned a campaign
finance measure that had been its main proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The commission said it would drop its proposal to bar candidates
from accepting campaign contributions from donors who do business
with the city. With little time left before its deadline, it said
it would switch to a far less ambitious effort at tackling campaign
finance regulations: a referendum that would prohibit contributions
from corporations.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's move came as a more far-reaching plan to
overhaul New York City's campaign finance system was approved
unanimously Tuesday by a City Council committee. The legislation
would be the first major change in the system in a decade, lowering
contribution limits and increasing aid to candidates from the
municipal treasury. If passed, it would become municipal law but
would not be part of the charter, which is essentially the city's
constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Many advocates of campaign-finance changes say the charter
commission's proposal to prohibit corporate contributions will have
little effect, since business people can still contribute as
individuals or through political action committees. But the
measure, however narrow, nonetheless would allow the commission to
accomplish the main goal Mayor Rudolph Giuliani had in establishing
it: blocking a referendum spearheaded by Council Speaker Peter
Vallone that would allow the voters to decide whether the city
should spend money to build a stadium for the Yankees in Manhattan.
Under the law, if a mayoral commission submits a charter amendment,
any referendum placed on the ballot by the Council is postponed
until the next election.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the commission's decision to back a proposal that would
have relatively little impact might give new ammunition to
opponents of the mayor who called his creation of the panel a
political ploy. The commission has already been attacked for
earlier ideas that it advanced and then abandoned, including one
that would have abolished the office of the Public Advocate and the
Independent Budget Office, both of which have earned the mayor's
enmity.
</P>
<P>
   Commission chairman Peter Powers said at Tuesday night's meeting
that it had dropped its broad proposal to bar candidates from
accepting contributions from donors who do business with the city
after receiving complaints that it was vague and confusing. The
commission never specified how it would define who is involved in
business with the $34 billion city government, raising the prospect
that any rules would be riddled with loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was based in large part on the input we got from the
public,'' Powers said of the decision to abandon the proposal.
``The thought was that it was too broad to actually reel in and
define.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and other prominent officials, including Vallone and
Public Advocate Mark Green, have all supported barring corporate
contributions in the city's campaign finance system, which
candidates voluntarily join. But some advocacy groups have said
that while they are not opposed to such a ban, it would have little
impact because donors find other ways of giving, often doing so as
individuals rather than through businesses. They have noted that
corporate contributions have long been banned on the federal level,
but that has not affected the size of the giving.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Despite the support from the upper echelons of city government,
some Council members have expressed misgivings about a ban, saying
that in their districts, stores and other corporate entities are
among their major donors.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone proposed a ban earlier this year, but then backed off
after hearing from Council members. The legislation approved
Tuesday by the Council's Committee on Government Operations does
not ban corporate contributions outright, but gives those
candidates who refuse them as much as four times the city financing
for their campaigns as those who do not. As a result, it has
garnered wider backing in the Council.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation is being pushed by Vallone, who is hoping to use
its passage to promote himself as a reformer as he campaigns for
the Democratic nomination for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has not indicated whether he will sign the Council's
bill. Tuesday, he questioned why it did not include a blanket ban
on corporate contributions, which he said he strongly favored.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a rule they follow on the federal level,'' he said. ``We
should be able to follow it here.''
</P>
<P>
   If both the charter commission's proposal and the Vallone
legislation become law, their differing provisions on banning
corporate contributions would create a legal conflict. It is
unclear how that conflict would be resolved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
