<SLUG> BC-NYC-NUDES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PORTRAIT OF PRIDE AND PAUNCHES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The cobblestone streets around Jessie Nebraska
Gifford's Vinegar Hill home are a no man's land of truckers and
intrepid artists _ of both the visual and stickup kind. This little
neighborhood, bordered by housing projects, the waterfront and the
Brooklyn Navy Yard, makes her feel isolated sometimes. But at least
she had the company of several nude men waiting to be framed.
</P>
<P>
   It was no setup. Seriously. Ms. Gifford is a painter who spent
her summer finishing a five-paneled portrait titled ``Some Nude Men
Working.'' Her subjects were friends and artists who posed for her
in their ``Full Monty'' glory. Actually, they had posed a few years
back for her camera, giving her a set of prints that she used for
an earlier show titled ``Seven Nude Men Think About Architecture.''
</P>
<P>
   The current series has more action (no, not that kind). She
rendered them in energetic poses with arms stretched wide, passing
and tugging among themselves. What they share in common is a sense
of pride and playfulness despite paunch, age or imperfection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at this guy, he's just so happy to be there,'' she said
of one middle-aged figure. She pointed out another and smiled
admiringly at his hairy torso. Her gaze skipped to yet another man,
balding and somewhat flabby. ``I chose them because I wanted people
who were confident in their skins. The thing about a nude person is
it's a form of architecture. It's a very basic thing of a human
being. The way they feel about being nude is depicted in these
pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   Prudes might say a naked man is no subject for a lady. Ms.
Gifford, who was raised in Omaha, still encounters that reaction
even from some collectors who have been buying her work for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the sort of thing my grandmother would say,'' Ms.
Gifford, 58, said. ``They think, especially from the era that I am
from, that it's pornographic to even think openly of nude men.''
</P>
<P>
   During a childhood visit to a museum, she asked her mother why
there were no paintings of nude men. Her mother replied _ with a
note of finality _ that women had more beautiful bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't, of course, until later that I went to the Sistine
Chapel that there were paintings of nude men if you looked far
enough,'' she said. ``There had to come a time when I began to
question my mother's opinions. Then I made up my own mind that I
was going to see about nude men.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the first show came to her a few years ago, after
she had returned to more traditional art after years of pursuing
abstract styles. She wrote letters to 13 friends, and six accepted
her invitation to allow her to shoot two rolls of film of them
posing for her. Her husband, Mel, also sat for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a very brave soul when it comes to that kind of an
experience,'' explained one of her models, Michael Weinstein, who
is a poet and retired accountant. ``I know when to say `yes.'''
</P>
<P>
   And when he saw the final result, he knew it was time for even
more acceptance. Of himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a human person, a perceptive person, a sensitive person
who wasn't afraid or ashamed of what he was doing,'' he said. ``If
anyone wanted to make anything of it, like the stuff in scandal
sheets, that was secondary. I had to grow up to what I saw.''
</P>
<P>
   These are real men, with real bodies, and Ms. Gifford celebrates
them in a way that makes them special. So what if American culture
seems obsessed with thin thinking? She knows others are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``A group of Russian people from out on the Island came and
stood around the gallery clapping, laughing and cheering,'' she
said of her earlier show of nudes. ``I noticed in the south of
France you get people with the most wrinkled skin, huge women,
wearing tiny bikinis.''
</P>
<P>
   She contrasted that with the ``little ladies'' and ``tiny
women'' she sees on the street or in fashion magazines. Sure, a
Cornell University study released this week found that men would
rather date those girls than bother with someone a little plumper.
But Ms. Gifford finds them not as interesting as people whose
bodies have to deal with gravity or age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not all skinny people are doing anything exciting except
having their picture taken,'' she said. ``Around NYU I see all
these skinny little girls. Then I see the ones with more body
carrying movie equipment. Smart people come in different sizes.
They're not ruled by being skinny.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
