<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-WATTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATTERS WANTS TO SETTLE IN WITH SEAHAWKS FOR LONG RUN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ind., Pa., Wash.)   (bl)  
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ricky Watters has a new condo on Lake Washington near downtown
Seattle. He has a new contract _ four years, $12 million, including
a $5 million signing bonus _ with the Seahawks. He loves music and
has written a new rap song with phrases like ``If I ran you over''
and ``bounce to this'' and ``built to last.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Ricky Watters has finally found a home.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a beautiful place, and I want to make this a home for
myself,'' he said recently. ``I want this to be my last stop
because there is no reason to go anywhere else. My game is like my
music _ I can still run you over, I'll make you bounce and I'm
built to last.''
</P>
<P>
   He is 29. He left Notre Dame and played running back for four
seasons in San Francisco and then played the last three in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Controversy always seemed to follow Watters.
</P>
<P>
   As a 49er, he said he didn't get the ball enough. As an Eagle,
he said he didn't get the ball enough. In both places, he got the
ball more than anyone else. Sometimes he looked selfish and
brooding and combustible. A problem child. A target.
</P>
<P>
   But he always produced. He gave both teams toughness in the
running game and soft hands from the backfield, which made
linebackers trying to cover him cringe. His volcanic makeup was
part of his game. He brings all of that to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks surely need it. Chris Warren, their longtime
signature back, is a Dallas Cowboy now. Last season, Warren led
Seahawks rushers with 847 yards; only four American Football
Conference teams featured a team-leading rusher with fewer yards.
Watters gained 1,110 yards last season in Philadelphia. He rushed
for 1,000 yards in four of his seven pro seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a long season in Philadelphia last year with all of the
losing,'' Watters said of the Eagles' 6-9-1 team, which finished
with three consecutive losses. ``It was rough on me and rough on
everybody else. We couldn't figure out what happened. That was
adversity, and I had adversity and success in San Francisco. We
were Super Bowl champions, but I never fit in there. Some of it was
my fault. Some of it was they didn't really understand what was in
my heart. But that's football _ in this game, not everyone is going
to be happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys I've played with, they understand me. My teammates
have always been there. They know where I'm coming from. They know
that I get on them, but I get on myself twice as hard. I really
criticize myself. And I push myself. I have a spirit that is
unquenchable. `'
</P>
<P>
   He is 6 feet 1 inch, 217 pounds. He is the jolt the Seattle
running game needs.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Seattle ran the ball 404 times and passed it 609
times. It was an 8-8 team that rode the arm of quarterback Warren
Moon and the hands of receivers Joey Galloway (72 catches) and Mike
Pritchard (64 catches).
</P>
<P>
   In the preseason, however, Seattle has beaten Dallas, 20-19, and
Indianapolis, 24-21, and lost to San Francisco, 24-21, while
running the ball 114 times and passing it only 91 times.
</P>
<P>
   Watters has rushed 24 times and the rookie back Ahman Green from
Nebraska has rushed 41 times. Both can take the football inside or
outside. Both run behind a line that includes the newcomers Kevin
Glover (center, from Detroit) and Brian Habib (guard, from Denver)
along with the mainstay tackle Howard (House) Ballard. Watters
looks to run the Seahawks out of anonymity and into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   It will not happen unless Seattle is unswerving in its
commitment to the running game. It will not happen unless Watters
is used in a variety of ways, running inside and outside and using
his pass-catching skills as a complement. It will not happen unless
the Seahawks tap into Watters' tremendous desire and view his
combustible nature as an asset rather than as a headache.
</P>
<P>
   Home for Ricky Watters means a lot. There is no place like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talent on this team is phenomenal,'' Watters said. ``We
have a great chance to win and do something special. We pretty much
have to put it on the line and not cut corners. And take care of
each other. And take care of home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
