<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' PLAYOFF HOPES FADING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ The Los Angeles Dodgers will start making a move
this week even if their players don't.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of a slump that continued Tuesday with a dreadful
6-4 loss to the Pittsburgh Pirates, the club will begin
interviewing candidates for the general manager's position.
</P>
<P>
   Interim GM Tom Lasorda has been given permission by the Florida
Marlins to speak to their GM, Dave Dombrowski, when the Dodgers are
in Miami on Thursday and Friday. When the Dodgers move on to
Atlanta for a three-game weekend series, Lasorda will talk to
Braves assistant GM Dean Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to have someone in place by the end of the season so
we can start to work on the team for next year,'' Lasorda said.
``There is a lot to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat surprisingly, Lasorda has decided he will not be the
one to take them there. Throughout his 20 years as manager of the
Dodgers, Lasorda said he loved his job but often dreamed about
putting together his own club. He will be 71 in September, though,
and doesn't see himself as the one to rebuild the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took this position because they asked me and I never thought
I would be doing it beyond this year,'' Lasorda said.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda has not backed away from the challenge of rebuilding the
team but has been stung by criticism of recent trades and his
alleged role in the June 20 firing of manager Bill Russell and GM
Fred Claire.
</P>
<P>
   Despite reports that he will be dismissed before the end of the
season, Lasorda is expected to finish out the year before turning
it over to the new man during the first week of October.
Dombrowski, who won the World Series last year with Florida, is a
favorite of the club's new owners at Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Dombrowski or Dean Taylor would not have liked what went on
Tuesday in front of 12,730 at Three Rivers Stadium. The Dodgers'
ninth loss in 13 games came against a team 11 games under .500 and
dropped them seven games back in the wild-card race with 37 to
play.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (62-63) had a 2-0 lead after back-to-back
second-inning home runs by Eric Karros and Bobby Bonilla. But this
remains a team that is not converting in the clutch dating back to
its last trip.
</P>
<P>
   The club went to the East Coast and batting .160 (13 for 81)
with runners in scoring position. At home, it was .160 (13 for 81).
Tuesday, it went 0 for 10 and lost despite three solo home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been the signature for team all year,'' Bonilla said.
``We still have a chance, but it's getting late. If we're still six
or seven back in the first week of September, we won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Carlos Perez (7-12), winless in his first three
starts with the club, wasn't going to get a victory this time,
either.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed a single and double to open the fourth and Jose
Guillen followed with a two-run single that tied the game. He then
allowed a two-run homer to third baseman Freddy Garcia, who entered
the game 10 for 20 since his recall from Triple-A.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reports on Garcia were that he was swinging a hot bat,''
said manager Glenn Hoffman, who knew his team shouldn't have been
beaten by a career minor leaguer with 174 big league at-bats. ``We
should have gotten this one, but that is not the way it is going
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers had a chance to go ahead in the top of the sixth
with runners at first and third on no outs. But Jason Schmidt, who
had a string of eight consecutive losses this year after starting
8-1, pulled it together.
</P>
<P>
   Karros, who was 10 for 20 lifetime against him, struck out.
Bonilla to ground into a double play to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the way I've hit Schmidt, I liked my chances,'' Karros
said. ``But I just didn't get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates pulled ahead 6-2 in the seventh after Tony Womack
opened with a single. One out later, Jason Kendall, who had a
string of six multi-hit games stopped, walked and Kevin Young
followed by a sharp one hopper past Bonilla at third.
</P>
<P>
   The ball rolled into the left-field corner and scooted past
Roger Cedeno for a triple, scoring Womack and Kendall.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Mondesi made it close with a two-run homer in the eighth to
chase Schmidt (10-9) and the Dodgers had the tying run at first in
the ninth when Mondesi flied out to end the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
