<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0532 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      08-19 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
PHILADELPHIA _ Getting at least seven innings from Jose Lima each
time he steps on the mound has become almost automatic.
<TEXT>
<P>
   So have victories.
</P>
<P>
   Both couldn't have come at a better time Tuesday night. With his
team in desperate need of a lift, Lima was more than willing to
oblige, allowing just four hits over seven innings as the Astros
snapped a two-game losing streak with an 8-2 victory over the
Philadelphia Phillies in front of 17,541 at Veterans Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell tied a season high with five RBIs, and Craig Biggio
had three hits for the Astros, who won for the ninth time in their
last 12 games and maintained their 7{-game lead over the Chicago
Cubs in the National League Central.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing he did pretty well was throw strikes,'' Astros
manager Larry Dierker said of Lima. ``All the rest of our pitchers
have had trouble throwing strikes in this series. The thing he does
well is give us seven innings almost every time. Sometimes, he gets
the ball up a little bit and gets hurt. When he doesn't do that, he
gives us seven innings and keeps the score down. That's why he has
a lot of victories.''
</P>
<P>
   For a pitcher who went through a monthlong winless drought
earlier this summer, Lima (12-6) now can't seem to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Lima was 0-3 with a 5.03 ERA from June 12 to July 17. But the
rejuvenated Lima is 4-0 with a 2.53 ERA over his past five starts,
two of which were complete games.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the 25-year-old righthander allowed only two runs _
both in the bottom of the sixth with the Astros already comfortably
ahead 6-0 _ in working at least seven innings for the 17th time in
26 starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Lima with impeccable timing, as the Astros had been shut
out 4-0 on four hits by the Phillies' Paul Byrd a night earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to give the club a chance to win every
ballgame,'' Lima said. ``If I can throw a complete game, I'll throw
a complete game. I know that we are going to win a lot of games. If
I give up three runs in the first inning, we are going to come back
and win, because we have a great team and can score some runs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, who have outscored the Phillies 54-25 in eight
meetings this season, put the outcome out of doubt early, scoring
three runs over the first two innings and adding three more in the
fifth. The six runs equaled the Astros' production over their
previous three games combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of guys on base,'' said Bagwell, who also
drove in five runs against Philadelphia on Aug. 7. ``We hadn't
scored a lot of runs in the last four games. It was nice to get
some runs early.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio, who went 3-for-4 but provided a brief scare in the
bottom of the first inning when he took an elbow to the rib cage
while chasing a fly ball, led off the game with an infield single,
stole second and advanced to third on a groundout by Derek Bell.
Bagwell drove in the first run with a bloop single to center field,
and Moises Alou followed with a hard grounder to shortstop that
Desi Relaford couldn't handle, allowing Bagwell to score.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell, who entered this series hitless in his previous 12
at-bats, is 5-for-9 with five RBIs against Philadelphia. He has hit
safely in 21 of his last 27 games and is batting .333 during that
stretch. Bagwell increased his RBI total to 83 for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He normally swings the bat well in Pennsylvania,'' Dierker
said of Bagwell. ``He struggled on the homestand but is starting to
come on again. He's kind of been a tease this year. Not that he's
having a bad year, but he hasn't been able to get hot and stay hot
three weeks in a month like he normally does. He's had hits in
spurts all year long.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Gutierrez singled to begin the second inning, and three
batters later, Biggio hit a blooper to right-center field to give
the Astros a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros weren't done, adding to their lead during a three-run
fifth. Once again, it was Biggio who served as the spark plug with
a leadoff double. Bill Spiers advanced him to third with a single
to right field, and Philadelphia starter Mike Grace (4-6) hit Bell
on the left hand to load the bases. Bagwell delivered a two-run
single up the middle, and Bell later scored on a grounder to second
by Carl Everett.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Phillies mounted a mini-rally in the sixth, it
was too late. Lima hit Doug Glanville with one out in the sixth and
walked Scott Rolen. Rico Brogna, who went 3-for-4, tripled to
center field on the next pitch to clear the bases. Lima walked
former Astro Bob Abreu but got out of the inning on Mark Lewis'
fielder's choice. Lima threw 27 pitches in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Lima allowed a leadoff single to begin the seventh but escaped
any further damage by getting Relaford to hit into a double play
and striking out Ruben Amaro.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I gave up those two runs, I didn't let it bother me,''
said Lima, who has registered seven of his 12 wins after an Astros
loss.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell added a two-run double in the ninth. Jay Powell and Doug
Henry combined to pitch two scoreless innings of relief, and Alou
made a pinpoint throw from left field to nail Lewis at home plate
to end the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
