<HEADLINE>
WOODS LEAVES TROJANS CAMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ Another unhappy quarterback emerged from USC
football practice on Tuesday when junior Quincy Woods bolted
training camp for at least a day after being told by coach Paul
Hackett he would not be considered for the top two positions on the
depth chart.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' absence could be permanent.
</P>
<P>
   He left UC Irvine on Monday night and took all his belongings,
including his clothes and fan. The only thing Woods left in his
apartment was his playbook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm urging him to consider a move to wide receiver but not
forcing him,'' Hackett said. ``I told him at this point he's not in
a position to compete at No. 1 or No. 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said he spoke with Woods three times on Monday and told
the quarterback to just ``veg'' and ``relax'' before deciding his
future. But Woods was clearly upset, and had not spoken to any
teammates on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect him to come back. I don't see him coming back
and playing another position,'' said John Fox, who is Woods'
roommate in training camp. ``Quincy's a quarterback, not a
receiver. I don't think he'll transfer; I just don't see him
playing football.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said he would let Woods remain at quarterback if the
redshirt junior wishes to stay at the position. Woods can transfer
to a lower-division school and be eligible this season, an option
he considered last year before staying at USC. He was 1 for 6 for 1
yard and one interception in the Trojans' first scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   It was just the latest unusual development for the quarterbacks.
Fox asked to switch to tight end last Thursday, aware of his
decreasing chance for playing time. Freshman Jason Thomas
considered transferring on Monday after Hackett told him he would
be no higher than third on the depth chart.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said he is not surprised by some of the emotional
reactions to his decisions regarding the quarterback position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a combination of things,'' Hackett said. ``I think it
happens anytime you have a new coach and a new system and new
philosophy. On top of that, we have an extraordinary group of young
people, particularly at quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   By eliminating Woods and Thomas from the top two positions, it
is all but official that freshman Carson Palmer is the backup to
starter Mike Van Raaphorst. Hackett reinforced, however, that Van
Raaphorst remains the starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike's the starter and we haven't even seen what he can do in
a game.'' Hackett said. ``It's his to lose and he hasn't done
anything to lose it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Soward sent off: Perhaps R. Jay Soward's comments about
undergoing an attitude adjustment are premature. Soward was kicked
off the field during practice after a verbal confrontation with
wide receivers coach Mike Wilson, who was upset with Soward's
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got mad,'' Soward said.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said he intended to speak to Soward on Tuesday night. He
already suspended Soward from the season opener for poor academic
performance during the spring semester.
</P>
<P>
   __ Harris gets MRI: Tight end Antoine Harris underwent a
magnetic resonance imaging test on Tuesday on his sprained right
ankle. No damage was revealed and he should be able to resume
practicing.
</P>
<P>
   __ More position changes: Running back Eric Reese has switched
to cornerback. Fullback Henry Wallace has moved to outside
linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Former Alemany tailback Miguel Fletcher spoke with Hackett on
Tuesday, and it was decided he will remain at tailback.
</P>
<P>
   __ No practice: USC has no scheduled practices at UC Irvine
today.
</P>
</TEXT>
