<HEADLINE>
PYGMY OWL ALERT AIMED AT CENTRAL ARIZONA DEVELOPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal wildlife officials are warning central Arizona
landowners for the first time that their developments could be
shrunk, delayed or even halted to protect an endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is the cactus ferruginous pygmy owl, a 7-inch-long bird
which last year stopped construction of a high school in the
quickly disappearing Sonoran Desert northwest of Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service is recommending that Valley
developers search for the bird to fend off lawsuits from
environmentalists and possible prosecution should a project hurt or
kill the owls.
</P>
<P>
   Developers are being asked to survey their properties as many as
three times over two years.
</P>
<P>
   But such a timetable could cause costly delays, according to the
Home Builders Association of Central Arizona, whose members
annually build nearly 25,000 homes in the Valley, mostly on
farmland and virgin desert.
</P>
<P>
   Pygmy owls once were common throughout southern and central
Arizona, federal biologists say, especially along streams and
washes lush with saguaros, mesquites, cottonwoods and other
vegetation that owls need for nesting and hunting.
</P>
<P>
   Because of urban sprawl and the damming of desert rivers, the
owl's numbers have dwindled in recent years to fewer than 20 in
Arizona, mostly in the deserts surrounding Tucson. Their near
extinction in Arizona led in 1997 to their inclusion on the federal
Endangered Species List.
</P>
<P>
   Following the listing, Fish and Wildlife was required to act to
increase owl populations. But the agency lacks the authority to
require surveys on private property. Instead, the agency made a
suggestion to Pima County landowners, urging them to voluntarily
search for pygmy owls before building.
</P>
<P>
   After studying the owl's historic range, the agency last week
expanded its suggested search areas to include undeveloped parts of
Maricopa County: north of Bell Road, east of Pima Road, south of
Southern Avenue and west of Arizona 303.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the surveys are being suggested this year in Yuma,
Graham, Greenlee, Gila, Santa Cruz, Cochise and Pinal counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're publishing these proposals to help landowners,
developers and other interested parties become more aware of the
pygmy owl, to help them determine if they have potential habitat
for the owl and to find ways to aid in the recovery of the pygmy
owl,'' said Nancy Kaufman, regional director of Fish and Wildlife
in Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   Such surveys are overdue, said David Hogan, desert rivers
coordinator for the Southwest Center for Biological Diversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona has always lacked necessary analysis of the effects of
development on our precious natural resources,'' Hogan said.
</P>
<P>
   However, environmentalists question the apparent willingness of
Fish and Wildlife to sacrifice owls if they are found in the path
of development. The federal owl survey guidelines released last
week call _ if owls are found _ for the development of Habitat
Conservation Plans, voluntary agreements intended to guide
development away from owls and the plants they need to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Once a conservation plan is approved by Fish and Wildlife,
landowners will be issued permits that would allow them to develop
their lands without fear of prosecution if they kill an owl or
destroy its habitat, according to the guidelines. Illegally killing
an endangered species can result in a year in prison and a $100,000
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan said his group will oppose the issuance of any ``take''
permits until owl numbers increase substantially.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Simplot, deputy director of the home builders association,
said doing owl surveys before development of private property is
premature. He suggested that such surveys be concluded first on
federal and Indian lands to determine the extent of pygmy owl
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   In surveys earlier this year, a search by state and federal
wildlife biologists turned up 34 owls, mostly in Pima County.
</P>
<P>
   Simplot said he would not tell his group's members to boycott
the surveys. But he questioned how much time and money they would
require.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is their money. This is their land. They're on the line
to bring it to development. It's important for them to be able to
proceed without unnecessary delays,'' Simplot said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Humphrey, spokesman for Fish and Wildlife, said the surveys
generally cost between $100 and $500, and are conducted by 10 firms
certified by his agency.
</P>
<P>
   Landowners who voluntarily conduct the surveys, Humphrey said,
are showing a ``good faith effort'' to avoid killing owls or
destroying their habitat.
</P>
<P>
   The Amphitheater Unified School District was sued last year by
the Southwest Center for Biological Diversity to prevent the
construction of a high school in an area where owls were known to
live. That lawsuit is pending before the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Simplot said owls found in the past in Maricopa County probably
represented the northernmost extent of their range.
</P>
<P>
   Humphrey said the last known pygmy owl in Maricopa County was
found in 1971. &QL; 
 &UR; Steve Yozwiak can be reached at 444-8810 or at
steve.yozwiak &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
