<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT CLIMATE NEAR, 2 IN ARIZONA GOP SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIANNE FLYNN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's combativeness and his failure
to apologize for his sexual relationship with a White House intern
have pushed House Republicans closer to a climate of impeachment,
say two Arizona GOP congressmen.
</P>
<P>
   But it will take a significant shift in attitude on the part of
the American public _ possibly on the strength of independent
counsel Kenneth Starr's report to Congress _ to ignite the House's
will and put any impeachment proceeding in motion, the congressmen
say.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Shadegg and Rep. Matt Salmon, both known as Republican
mavericks for bucking House leaders, agreed Tuesday that Clinton's
Monday night speech handed Republicans the weapons they will
require to impeach the president, if they decide to proceed. It is
clear from the address, both said, that Clinton lied about his
liaisons with former intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The key occurred in his testimony in the failed Paula Jones
sexual harassment lawsuit. Clinton denied under oath that he had
had any sexual relationship with Lewinsky. That constitutes
perjury, both said, and perjury is a felony, an impeachable
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I genuinely believe Bill Clinton could have put us in a more
difficult position if he had been contrite, if he had accepted
responsibility,'' Shadegg said. ``I think . . . he hurt his cause
dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, favorable presidential poll numbers are keeping
Republicans from criticizing Clinton or calling for his impeachment
or resignation, Shadegg and Salmon agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Morning-after polls indicated that two-thirds of the public want
Starr's investigation of the Lewinsky affair to end without
impeachment or resignation. Clinton's approval ratings remain in
the 60 percent range.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, there is no burning desire among Republicans in
the House or Senate to impeach the guy,'' Shadegg said. The payoff
is low since Clinton is a lame duck and Vice President Al Gore, an
only slightly more palatable alternative, would become president,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our party seems afraid of rocking the boat,'' Salmon said. ``I
don't believe there's enough political courage to go forward and do
what needs to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about whether the president committed wrong whether
this body will impeach him,'' Salmon said. ``This is strictly a
political question. If the public supports it, the House will
impeach.''
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether public opinion will change depends as
much as anything on the report of the special prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is expected to issue the report this fall. It would be
submitted to the House Judiciary Committee, which could vote to
open an impeachment inquiry if it finds sufficient evidence. At
that point, the panel would hold hearings to obtain evidence, and
that could be a long process of calling many of the same witnesses
Starr called in private, and of studying the same evidence.
</P>
<P>
   If after all of that the president still had not been
embarrassed into a resignation, the Judiciary could draft articles
of impeachment, much like criminal charges, for approval by the
full House, which would act like a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   If the House approved the articles of impeachment, the matter
would be referred to the Senate for trial, and the president could
be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   Those who were most likely to know what course the House would
take were among the quietest people in Washington on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich issued a statement saying that
everyone should keep their powder dry until they hear from Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., House Judiciary chairman, said much the
same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If and when the independent counsel sends . . . a report, it
is reasonable to expect answers to many as-yet-unanswered
questions. It is our constitutional duty to provide a fair, full
and independent review of these facts in the proper context,'' Hyde
said.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon wants the inquiry to be sooner, rather than later. Salmon
said that he was joining fellow Arizona Republican Rep. Bob Stump
in signing onto a bill that would force the Judiciary Committee to
open an impeachment inquiry immediately. The bill, sponsored by
Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., has 23 co-sponsors, mostly conservative House
members. &QL; 
 &UR; You can reach Adrianne Flynn at (202) 662-7262 or at
adrianne.flynn &LR; pni.com
 &UR; via e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
