<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
 
McDOWELL'S CAREER AT CRITICAL JUNCTURE 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Jack McDowell's right elbow is like a string
on one of his guitars; it could snap at any moment. Then again,
it's one thing to have one of your riffs interrupted in a dusky
club and something else altogether to have your baseball career
terminated in front of some 30,000 screaming fans.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows the precariousness of his situation better than
McDowell, a pitcher/musician who'll take the mound anyway tonight
when the Anaheim Angels open a two-game set against Detroit. It
will be the Van Nuys native's first start since an abbreviated and
agonizing appearance on May 31.
</P>
<P>
   No one, least of all McDowell, knows how much faith to place in
his elbow, which hasn't been right since he had surgery to remove
loose cartilage in May 1997. Any resemblance he bears to the
pitcher who won the 1993 Cy Young Award is merely skin-deep.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it? McDowell, who has suffered through two stints on the
disabled list this season, might have lost a little velocity on his
split-finger fastball, but his ferocity is the same as it always
was.
</P>
<P>
   When you have the Texas Rangers nipping at your ankles, it helps
to have a pit bull on the mound, which is why the American League
West-leading Angels are throwing McDowell to the Tigers and holding
their collective breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that compared to three years ago he
doesn't have as good of stuff,'' said Angels manager Terry Collins.
``What he will do is pitch with what he's got. He will make
pitches. He will not give in. He will not get shaken if he gives up
a big hit. He's a warrior.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also a realist, which is why there was nary a hitch in his
delivery when the Notre Dame High graduate said, ``I know my days
are limited. There's an urgency to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't doubt McDowell's determination. You only hope the
tendons and muscles surrounding his right elbow are as stubborn as
the rest of him.
</P>
<P>
   When last seen in a major-league uniform, McDowell, 32, was
throwing batting practice to Minnesota. The Twins teed off on him
for 10 hits and five earned runs in 32/3 innings. After the Angels
rallied to win 6-5, the pitcher told Collins, ``I can't do this.
I'm hurting myself. I'm hurting the club.''
</P>
<P>
   That admission, coming from the same guy who had begged to stay
in the last game he pitched before going on the disabled list the
first time, in late April, was so scary, the 1998 season flashed
before Collins' eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Talking before the Angels' game Tuesday against the Chicago
White Sox, Collins cringed at the memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, if this guy says he's hurting, he's really in
trouble,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   McDowell's days of pitching pain-free, like his seasons of
leading the AL in complete games, are behind him. But as long as
McDowell has The Glare, opponents best beware.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yes, I've seen it,'' Angels shortstop Gary DiSarcina said
with a chuckle. ``I remember in 1995, when he was pitching for the
Yankees, it was late in a 2-2 game, there were two outs and a man
on second and he hung me a curve. I got a hit and the run scored
and that look he gave me, it was like, `I let  &UR; !ital! &LR; you &UR; !off! &LR; 
get a hit off me.'''
</P>
<P>
   That's nothing. McDowell has been known to stare menacingly at
any batter rounding the bases after having the audacity to hit a
home run off him. During his year with the Yankees, which was
sandwiched between six seasons with the White Sox and two in
Cleveland, he once gave the Bronx fans the middle finger.
</P>
<P>
   So music critics, consider yourselves warned; you may get
feedback when reviewing ``Feedbag,'' the second CD released by
Stickfigure, the alternative-rock band that McDowell fronts.
McDowell, who plays guitar and bass and sings, wrote and produced
all the songs on the band's first CD, ``Just a Thought.''
</P>
<P>
   McDowell suspects there'll be more than the usual number of
thoughts rattling around his brain tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be, I was comfortable with my game. I didn't have
to think about every pitch,'' he said. ``Now there's going to be a
little more figuring things out as I go along. It's going to be
about how quick I can make adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   That'll come as news to all the batters who thought his mind,
before his elbow started acting up, worked like chess master Bobby
Fischer's.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a smart pitcher,'' said Angels center fielder Jim
Edmonds. ``I never had much luck hitting (off) him. He seems like
he works you differently every at-bat.''
</P>
<P>
   McDowell, like most creatures with sharp claws and teeth, gets
even meaner when he's wounded. Get a few runs off him early and
he's liable to wipe that smile right off your face by the sixth or
seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   Said DiSarcina, ``He's tough as nails.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is, will he be as rusty?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
