<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES DEFEAT ROYALS, 3-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Chad Curtis has been hitting so badly of
late, Yankee Manager Joe Torre said before Tuesday night's game
that ``we need a Hoover vacuum cleaner'' to clean out Curtis' swing
``and start over.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis then waited until the 13th inning on Tuesday night before
beginning anew, smacking a tie-breaking single and propelling the
Yankees to a 3-2 victory over Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just his approach,'' Torre said of Curtis, ``and today he
had it through the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, the Yankees swept their 10-game season series
with the Royals, the first time they have swept a season series
from any team in any year not affected by labor strife.
</P>
<P>
   Mariano Rivera had blown a 2-1 lead in the ninth inning, when
the Royals scored the tying run on a sacrifice fly _ Rivera's first
blown save since June 1.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams, who had three hits on Tuesday night and leads
the American League with a .358 average, opened the 13th inning
with a single. With two outs, Kansas City's Matt Whisenant threw a
fastball high and wide by a couple of yards, Williams taking second
as catcher Mike Sweeney retrieved the ball from the backstop.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis, in an 0-for-15 slump and recently in the habit of
flailing at anything within a yard of home plate, then smashed a
grounder through the middle to score Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm usually pretty good at going, `See the ball, hit the
ball,''' Curtis said after the game. ``For whatever reason, I've
been out of rhythm for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real frustrating stretch to know you've got some
ability and can help the team, and you're not doing it for a
prolonged stretch of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Borowski pitched the 12th and 13th innings for his first
victory with the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   After Monday night's 7-1 loss to the Yankees, Johnny Damon, the
Royals' center fielder, walked into the weight room, feeling
drained from a night of playing in sweltering midsummer heat, and
was shocked by what he saw. Joe Girardi, who had just caught nine
innings, was lifting weights, and so were Tino Martinez, Paul
O'Neill and Scott Brosius, 10 to 15 Yankees in all, Damon guessed.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are 92-30, on track to establish the best record in
this century. They have beaten the Royals soundly, outscoring them
by 78-20. To Damon, the sight of so many Yankees diligently going
through their conditioning is one of the signs that they are taking
nothing for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time, when a team's in first place, you don't see
guys run out every ground ball,'' Damon said. ``And the Yankees
hustle every time. They go out and they play us hard to the very
last.
</P>
<P>
   ``With us, there are times when we play a team like Tampa Bay or
Oakland, and sometimes we don't take them seriously, even though
their record is like ours but we know they're not as good as the
Yankees. But the Yankees, they go after everybody like it's a
do-or-die situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Damon sat at a table in the middle of the Royals' clubhouse,
three hours before Tuesday night's game. ``I'm pulling for them to
be one of the best teams of all time,'' he said of the Yankees.
``There have been games when it doesn't seem like we have competed
with them, and if there is a team like that, I would hope they are
one of the best teams of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a lot of class guys over there, humble guys, guys
who really work hard. Last night, after a hot game, they're in the
weight room, working out, trying to better themselves even more.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams propelled the Yankees into the lead tonight leading off
the second inning, slugging a fastball over the center-field wall,
his third home run in three days. It would not have been a stretch
to think one run was all that the Yankees' starter, Orlando
Hernandez, needed. The right-hander has allowed just 2 runs and 14
hits, with 33 strikeouts over 33 innings, for an 0.82 earned run
average in his last four starts. Tonight, he threw a lively
fastball with impeccable control.
</P>
<P>
   He was replaced by Rivera with runners on first and second and
two outs in the eighth. Rivera got out of the inning when Martinez
made a nice barehanded play on a chopper.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez needed only 27 pitches to get through the first three
innings, allowing only a ground single. Jose Offerman doubled with
two outs in the fourth, but Hernandez struck out Dean Palmer on
three pitches.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth inning, Hernandez made a mistake, his two-seam
fastball running over the plate enough that Larry Sutton could
extend his arms and drive the ball, his shot carrying over the
center-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   All night, the Royals were griping about Umpire Jim McKean's
strike zone. Pat Rapp walked Martinez and Chili Davis with one out
in the sixth and began barking toward the plate. Bruce Kison, the
Royals' pitching coach, went to the mound to calm Rapp, but he
tried to fire a fastball past Darryl Strawberry, who whacked it
directly at Offerman at second base.
</P>
<P>
   The ball landed just in front of Offerman and seemed to explode,
hopping off the glove that Offerman held out in self-defense.
Martinez raced home for a 2-1 lead the Yankees could not hold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 0134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
