<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0551 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MCELROY-HNS &LR;      08-19 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCELROY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
McElroy puts Cardinals behind him
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
TAMPA, Fla. _ Leeland McElroy never will forget draft day 1996. It
was April, and McElroy was in New York at the NFL's invitation. It
was going to be the greatest day of his life.
</P>
<P>
   McElroy's family and friends in Beaumont and College Station
would be watching on ESPN. It never crossed their minds he might
not be a No. 1 draft choice. After he ran the 40-yard dash in 4.21
seconds at the Indianapolis scouting combine, it wasn't a question
of whether McElroy would be drafted in the first round; rather, it
was how high he would go in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   In his first three seasons at Texas A&AMP;M, McElroy became one of
the best and most exciting multipurpose backs in the country.
Because everyone told him he would be drafted in the first round,
he elected to bypass his senior year with the Aggies.
</P>
<P>
   Then came that fateful April day. McElroy suffered like no
other. As the No. 1 picks were called out from behind the curtain
to shake the hand of commissioner Paul Tagliabue on center stage at
Madison Square Garden, McElroy never moved. As each name was called
_ each not his _ the camera focused on McElroy, whose emotions went
from sadness to shock.
</P>
<P>
   When he finally was taken by the Arizona Cardinals in the second
round, McElroy's knees were so weak that he wobbled when he tried
to stand. That day signaled the beginning of a tailspin that didn't
end until last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The draft hit me hard,'' McElroy says during a break in
two-a-day drills for his new team, the Tampa Bay Buccaneers. ``It
was a turning point in my career. I tried to deal with the
situation, but it took a shot at my confidence. I wondered if I
could play in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   Two seasons later, McElroy isn't the only one wondering.
</P>
<P>
   To say his two years with the Cardinals were a nightmare might
be an understatement. As a rookie, one of the outstanding
multipurpose backs in Southwest Conference history rushed for 305
yards, caught five passes, scored two touchdowns and averaged 21.3
yards on kickoff returns.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, McElroy rushed for 424 yards, caught seven passes,
scored two TDs and didn't return a kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to doubt myself,'' he says. ``I started to question
my ability. From the draft through my two years with the Cardinals,
that was definitely the down time in my career.''
</P>
<P>
   McElroy never will be more than a footnote in the long, pathetic
history of the Cardinals. When they waived him in early July, he
returned to the place where he had experienced his greatest
conquests on the football field _ College Station.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went back to A&AMP;M to take classes since I need 15 hours to
get my degree (business administration),'' he says. ``I was
wondering about my future, wondering if I was going to play
football.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Buccaneers called to tell McElroy he had been claimed
on waivers, he traded in his desert fatigues for a bathing suit and
sunscreen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me they liked me coming out of college and they
didn't care what happened at Arizona,'' he says of the Bucs.
``Everybody has accepted me with open arms, and nobody has really
mentioned what happened the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new situation, and I'm excited to play for the
Buccaneers. I'm trying to do everything I can to show them they
didn't make a mistake and that the things they thought about me
coming out of college were correct.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Tony Dungy is building one of the fastest and quickest
offenses in the NFL. He claimed McElroy to compete for the backup
job behind halfback Warrick Dunn. McElroy (5-9, 212) is larger than
Dunn (5-8, 178), but both are quick with exceptional speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We scouted Leeland in college, and when the second round
began, we saw him and (fullback) Mike Alstott still available,''
Dungy says. ``Leeland went one pick ahead of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bucs selected Alstott, who is one of their best players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We liked Leeland's speed and quickness, and we wanted to find
a way to best utilize him,'' Dungy says. ``When he became
available, it was an easy choice for us. He hadn't been real
productive for the Cardinals, but you never know exactly what goes
on in someone else's system. When he got here, we told him what we
think he can do, what's expected of him.''
</P>
<P>
   McElroy hasn't disappointed the Bucs. After three preseason
games, he leads the team in rushing. He is running second-team
behind Dunn and loving every minute of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like people are wondering what happened to me,''
McElroy says. ``Can I play? Am I one of those guys that's lost in
the shuffle? When I was in Arizona, I began to ask those same
questions. It was a very depressing time in my life, but looking
back, I feel like it was something I had to go through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned a lot from it, and I don't think I'd change
anything, because it made me a stronger person. Now, I feel like I
have something to prove, but at the same time, I'm not going to put
any added pressure on myself.''
</P>
<P>
   McElroy has 21 carries for 102 yards (4.9 average) and one
touchdown on a 25-yard run. The Buccaneers also want to look at him
on kickoff returns.
</P>
<P>
   Because he has enjoyed such a good camp and preseason, McElroy
is getting a lot of praise from his teammates and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really helped me,'' he says. ``I came from a situation
where they had given up on me, insinuated that I couldn't play
anymore and released me. It feels really good to be here and have a
chance to play for a Super Bowl contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having fun playing, like I did at A&AMP;M. I may have lost
that with Arizona. I think the game became more of a job that
became harder and harder every week. When you're not winning,
you're not having fun. I love the direction this team is headed.
It's hard to describe exactly how I feel, other than to say how
much I've been blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   McElroy turned to his spirituality to withstand booing by the
fans and criticism by the media for two years with the Cardinals.
He is a devout Christian, and his firm belief in God helped him
overcome the pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christianity has helped me,'' he says. ``Knowing God's in
control of everything helped me be at peace with the situation. I
put God first, family second and football third.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was released by the Cardinals, my wife (Vinita) and I
prayed about it. I was very disappointed things didn't work out in
Arizona, so we put it in God's hands and hoped for a more
legitimate opportunity to showcase my skills in an organization
that's a little farther ahead of Arizona. Now, when I look back, I
realize it was just another phase of my life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe that because I experienced failure, I'll sure
know how to handle success.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
