<HEADLINE>
NEW FACES LOOK AWFULLY FAMILIAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Anaheim Angels manager Terry Collins said he
couldn't imagine a trade that would make his team any better than
it will be with the addition of two new players he'll have in
tonight's lineup against the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Jack McDowell will make his first start since May 31,
when elbow problems landed him on the disabled list. Darin Erstad
will play for the first time since Aug. 3, when he suffered a
strained left hamstring. He'll start at first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, you're getting quality people back,'' Collins
said. ``It's like getting new blood.''
</P>
<P>
   McDowell signed an incentive-laden contract _ $1 million base
with potential to reach $6 million _ but it hasn't exactly worked
out with all his time on the DL. But with the team in a pennant
race, McDowell says he's satisfied to come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy I'm in a position where I can help us out,'' he
said. ``Coming back wouldn't have made any difference if we were 10
games out.''
</P>
<P>
   McDowell said despite a 2{-month layoff he won't be nervous when
he takes the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something to be nervous about,'' he said. ``It's
something to be locked in about.''
</P>
<P>
   McDowell has been on the active roster since Saturday, when he
began serving his four-game suspension for his role in the June 2
fight in Kansas City. But with Erstad activated today, someone must
go.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said reserve outfielder Reggie Williams will start
tonight's game to give Garret Anderson a rest, meaning the likely
odd man out is first baseman Chris Pritchett. Pritchett would stay
if someone was put on the disabled list instead, and Craig Shipley
has been bothered lately with a sore hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   __ Up-Hill battle: Pitcher Ken Hill (elbow) pitched on Tuesday
night for Single-A Lake Elsinore at Stockton in what was supposed
to be his final rehab start. He was supposed to make 90 pitches but
made only 70 in four innings. He gave up four runs (three earned)
and five hits while walking five and striking out two.
</P>
<P>
   Hill was expected to be activated to start on Sunday against
Toronto in Anaheim, pushing Chuck Finley back a day to start
against the Yankees in New York. Now, though, the situation might
be a little clouded.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Charlie O'Brien has started throwing as part of his
rehab for a broken right thumb but there is no timetable for his
return.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
