<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0561 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-ROCKIES-1STL     08-19 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ROCKIES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS SWEEP DOUBLEHEADER FROM ROCKIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout) (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There were no boos for Mike Piazza on Tuesday night,
only standing ovations.
</P>
<P>
   For one of the few times since since he was acquired on May 22,
Piazza was treated like a hero. And not just by who was left of the
21,611 on hand who had braved showers to see the New York Mets win
the first of their three doubleheaders this week. Piazza's
teammates, who have begun to tease the All-Star catcher about his
dour mood, seemed genuinely happy for him.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? Piazza delivered perhaps the biggest hit as a Met _
a bases-clearing, pinch-hit, three-run double to lift the Mets to a
6-3 victory over the Colorado Rockies in the second game of a
doubleheader. In the opener, Piazza singled in a run in a 6-2
victory that saw four Mets (not Piazza) hit home runs.
</P>
<P>
   The sweep, in the first of three doubleheaders this week for the
Mets, put them a season-best 13 games over .500 and percentage
points ahead of the Cubs in the National League wild-card chase. It
was the Mets' fourth doubleheader sweep of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, who is now 3 for 3 with the Mets as a pinch-hitter,
could even be heard telling a joke. When kiddingly asked if he
would go to the bench for the good of the team in light of his
pinch-hitting success, Piazza laughed and said: ``Whatever it
takes. But I'd be the highest-paid pinch-hitter in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked afterward if he felt it was his biggest hit as a Met,
Piazza said: ``Yeah, probably. But I like to think all of them are
big.''
</P>
<P>
   Mets Manager Bobby Valentine said: ``That's as big a hit as
we've had this year. That was a blast. Vintage Piazza.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza's double off the left-hander Chuck McElroy with two
strikes and the Mets trailing, 3-1, capped a two-out rally that
began with a John Olerud single off the Rockies' right-hander John
Thomson. Colorado Manager Don Baylor then called on McElroy to turn
the next batter, Todd Hundley, around to the right side of the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy was sound. The switch-hitting Hundley was 1 for 12
with 11 strikeouts and 1 walk hitting right-handed when the day
began. But McElroy, who never even came close to the strike zone,
walked Hundley on four pitches. And up stepped Brian McRae.
</P>
<P>
   On a 2-2 count, McRae hit a dying quail pop-up toward second.
But no one decided to try to make the catch. The ball plopped in
front of second baseman Mike Lansing, as both McElroy and first
baseman Todd Helton helplessly watched the play. McRae had a
75-foot hit. And the bases were loaded for Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, they were loaded for Carlos Baerga. But Valentine
sensed that this was the moment. And Piazza did not fail. With the
crowd on its feet and cheering noisily, Piazza took a ball, then
fouled three consecutive pitches straight back _ a sign that he was
closing in on McElroy.
</P>
<P>
   On McElroy's fifth pitch, Piazza delivered his three-run double
to make a winner out of Mel Rojas (5-2). And, after Lenny Harris
drilled his first homer of the season, a two-run shot off the
former Met Jerry DiPoto in the eighth, John Franco closed out the
sweep for his 26th save.
</P>
<P>
   In the opener, Edgardo Alfonzo, Hundley, Olerud and McRae hit
home runs off Pedro Astacio to support Al Leiter (12-4).
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the defense kept us in the game, the homers put us
in front and Al battled all the way against a very good-hitting
team,'' Valentine said between games, speaking of the Mets' first
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Lopez and Olerud provided the best defensive gems behind
Leiter, who surrendered 10 hits but allowed just 2 runs in 8
innings before Turk Wendell pitched a scoreless ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't particularly sharp,'' said Leiter, who labored
through 135 pitches in his first start in eight days. ``And I
didn't feel like I was as complete today. But any time you allow
two runs in eight innings against a Colorado team, I'll certainly
take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the game, Leiter decided to abandon his changeup and
curve and, in his words, ``resort back to what you know best,
which, for me, is hard in.''
</P>
<P>
   That resulted in a lot of cruelty to some Colorado bats _
especially the ones swung by Lansing, Dante Bichette and Larry
Walker.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm right and the ball's moving a lot, I break a few
bats,'' Leiter said. ``I got three of Lansing's and Bichette a
couple of times. And Walker might've been the most mad. He might
have had a lucky bat or something. I know for him tonight it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Not nearly as lucky as the Mets' bats were for Leiter.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley's second homer of the season was his first at Shea since
he hit his 30th (and last) home run last Sept. 8, before
reconstructive elbow surgery. On Tuesday, Hundley belted a 2-1
pitch from Astacio into the bullpen in right to lead off the fourth
and give Leiter a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter had earned it. In the top of the fourth, the left-hander
had left the bases loaded after his defense failed him. Alfonzo
began the fourth by throwing high to first on a grounder to third
by Bichette and pulling Olerud off the bag at first. The miscue was
Alfonzo's first since June28, snapping a streak of 42 games without
an error.
</P>
<P>
   Vinny Castilla followed with a double over third and just out of
Alfonzo's reach, putting two Rockies in scoring position in a 2-0
game.
</P>
<P>
   But Leiter came back to strike out Helton and retire Lansing on
a pop-up to short. After an intentional walk to Kirt Manwaring,
Leiter struck out Astacio to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the whole game,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter said: ``Three years ago, if I had runners on second and
third with nobody out, they're both scoring. Just through lack of
confidence. And that's just the difference between having a good
year and a bad year.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Rockies went 0 for 6 in the first four innings with
runners in scoring position. The Mets, meanwhile, scored in the
first on a single by Piazza that scored Tony Phillips from third.
Phillips had led off the inning with a single to center, taken
second when Alfonzo was hit by a pitch, and then taken third on a
force-play grounder.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' next two runs came on solo homers by Alfonzo (his
ninth, to left, leading off the third) and Hundley.
</P>
<P>
   In the Mets' fifth, Olerud blasted a two-run homer (his 17th)
some 419 feet to straightaway center field two batters before McRae
looped his 19th home run, a solo shot, to the opposite field in
left.
</P>
<P>
   It gave Leiter a 6-2 cushion, more than enough, it turned out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
