<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGERS SLAM MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The whole idea for left-handed relievers, the reason
they are coveted so highly and paid so much, is to retire
left-handed hitters. It's one of the basic tenets of the game.
</P>
<P>
   They are known as specialists, frequently asked to defuse a
situation by getting one key out. Greg McCarthy is supposed to
disarm bombs, not allow them.
</P>
<P>
   But in McCarthy's past two outings, Dave Niehaus has been
pulling out the rye bread for the other team.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Higginson walloped a grand slam to propel the Detroit
Tigers to a 7-6 victory over the Mariners on Tuesday night before
24,136 fans at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy also gave up a grand slam to Carlos Delgado in his last
outing last Wednesday in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Higginson's blast spoiled an otherwise heroic evening for Alex
Rodriguez. The Mariner shortstop went 5-for-5, scoring two runs and
knocking in two more to give him an even 100 RBIs. He did not hit
his 36th home run, but he stole his 37th base in the continuing
40-40 quest.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez equaled a club record for most hits in a nine-inning
game while raising his average to .311.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez would have preferred a victory over an 11-game hitting
streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason I come out is to win,'' he said. ``I'd like to
sneak one hit in there, but I'd go 0-for-5, 0-for-6 as long as we
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from A-Rod's assault, the M's looked at more of the same,
troubling numbers and statistics. They are now 4-20 in one-run
games. They lost to the 49-74 Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's Seth Greisinger showed up with a 1-7 record. Seattle's
Bobby Ayala appeared in the fifth with a 1-8 record. Guess who
lost.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala preceded McCarthy in the sixth inning. The right-handed
reliever was greeted indifferently with a smattering of applause.
Five minutes later, customary boos rang out from the bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Ayala stressed that he still wasn't talking to
the media. During the game, Ayala showed that he still can't bring
it in clutch situations, his ERA mushrooming to 6.71.
</P>
<P>
   Taking over for starter Paul Spoljaric, Ayala allowed three
straight hits, the final one by Deivi Cruz tying the score 3-3.
Ayala did strike out Paul Bako and Joe Randa but walked Brian
Hunter in between to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   That was when McCarthy trotted in, soon to be seen trudging off.
Missing with his first two pitches to Higginson, McCarthy tried to
whistle a fastball across the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The pitch sailed high and inside and Higginson launched it off
the facing of the second deck, high above the ``T'' on the National
League scoreboard in right field.
</P>
<P>
   Stationed in front of the Office Depot sign, right fielder Jay
Buhner did not even move his feet. He took a slight turn to his
left and watched the ball sail over his head. Randy Johnson could
not have grabbed that one.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy stood on the mound with the look of a beaten man,
because he was. The 29-year-old from Shelton, Conn., had reduced
his ERA to 2.50 until he showed up in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Higginson said he got the pitch he was anticipating. Mariners
manager Lou Piniella said McCarthy shook off a breaking ball and
decided to bring the heat instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 2-and-0 and I knew he couldn't walk me,'' said
Higginson, who belted his 21st homer of the year on his 28th
birthday. ``I was looking for a fastball. He threw it inside, right
where I was looking for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Higginson took his trip around the bases and then pointed to the
bullpen at reliever Doug Bochtler, who had given him a haircut
earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lucky haircut,'' said Higginson.
</P>
<P>
   In his last two outings, McCarthy has given up four earned runs
in one-third of an inning. That computes to 108.11, or off the
charts. His next appearance might be in Tacoma, although Piniella
did not suggest a demotion afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has given up big home runs,'' Piniella said. ``His job is
to get left-handed hitters out.''
</P>
<P>
   Another lefty, Spoljaric, started for only the second time this
season and struggled early. Before the first inning ended, Bob
Wells was warming up in the bullpen, prepared to take over.
</P>
<P>
   Spoljaric found catcher John Marzano's glove but could not
locate the plate. The left-hander walked four batters in the first
inning, three in succession, the final two with the bases loaded,
giving Detroit a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. drove in his 102nd run in the third and added
his 103rd in the sixth. He needs eight more RBIs to become the 14th
player in baseball history to have 400 RBIs in three consecutive
seasons. It has not been accomplished since 1948-50 by Vern
Stephens. Lou Gehrig has the record of 509 from 1930-32 (174, 184,
151).
</P>
<P>
   Griffey failed to deliver in the eighth. With runners on second
and third and Detroit in front 7-5, Tigers manager Buddy Bell chose
to have right-hander Matt Anderson pitch to the Mariner slugger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, I wouldn't have preferred to do that,'' Bell said.
``I had to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey struck out, and Edgar Martinez came through with his
second sacrifice fly, leaving the Mariners a run short.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
