<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAKWS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD LEAGUE SPRINGBOARD FOR SEVERAL SEAHAWKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Riddick Parker went two years ago to prove he
could play football at the next level. Kerry Joseph and Mike Croel
went this year to prove they could play new positions at any level.
</P>
<P>
   Their ultimate destinations are the same: The NFL. But each
decided a side trip to the World League would help them reach their
goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me to get back into the league, it was something I had to
do and something I wanted to do,'' said Croel, who was NFL
defensive rookie of the year in 1991 as a linebacker with the
Denver Broncos but was out of the league last season after being
released by the Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football is still in my blood, and (the World League) was
something I wanted to do so I could get on back,'' he said. ``I'm
here, so it was good for me and I enjoyed it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks have been intertwined with the development of the
spring league.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Sinclair is a two-time Pro Bowl defensive end who has
collected 25 sacks the past two seasons. But in 1992, he was a
struggling second-year player who needed to prove to himself that
he had the prowess to make it in the NFL. So Sinclair agreed to
play for the Sacramento Surge in the second season of the
developmental league. He had 10 sacks that spring and has since
blossomed into one of the better defensive players in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Jon Kitna has the brightest of futures. But last
year, he had yet to display the talents and intangibles that now
are so apparent. Kitna needed to play after spending his rookie
season the practice squad. Play he did, leading the Barcelona
Dragons to the World League title last year. Kitna has since
developed into one of the better stories in the league.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the Seahawks have 10 players on their 82-man roster
who have roots in the World League, and as many as seven could
still be around after the final cut to 53 on Aug. 30 _ Sinclair,
Kitna, Parker and linebacker James Logan for sure, and possibly
Croel, Joseph and center Greg Bloedorn.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Broncos and Kansas City Chiefs (13 each) and Miami
Dolphins (11) went to training camp with more World League
refugees. Most teams have four or five.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a few teams that really put a lot into scouting the
World League, and we're one of them,'' said Bill Quinter, Seahawks
pro scouting director. ``It's just another way to find talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinter spends three weeks at the World League's preseason
training camp in Atlanta and then reviews video of every game with
the help of assistant pro scouting director Tag Ribary.
</P>
<P>
   They compile files on players who might be able to help the team
_ now and in the future.
</P>
<P>
   When the Seahawks still needed a fourth defensive end the week
before training camp started, they signed Croel. When injuries
decimated their middle linebacking crew in the season opener, they
added Jamie Baisley, a member of the World League champion Rhein
Fire.
</P>
<P>
   The World League, which was called NFL Europe this spring, is
not the NFL. But as Quinter puts it, ``If a player can dominate in
that league, he's going to have a chance to come to this level and
compete for a roster spot.''
</P>
<P>
   That's all most of these players are seeking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually went to the World League as a quarterback. I had
the option if I wasn't starting to do other things,'' said Joseph,
who was a quarterback at McNeese State and with the Cincinnati
Bengals in 1996, a running back with the Washington Redskins last
summer and a safety for the Rhein Fire this spring. ``So I decided
to switch to defensive back. I thought that would be a good
position for me to get back into the NFL. I made the switch and it
worked out well for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks have developed a reputation for being World League
friendly. Coaches and agents will call Quinter with possible
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of them become players, of course. But it's worth a
look, and the chance to be looked at.
</P>
<P>
   ``My focus when I was over there was getting back in the NFL,''
said Parker, a defensive tackle who sat out the 1995 NFL season and
then spent the 1996 season on the Seahawk practice squad after
playing with the Rhein that spring. ``I always thought I had what
it takes to play in this league. But first I just had to prove it
to myself, and then I had to prove it to the people who would give
me the chance to show it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 0225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
