<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0578 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI     08-19 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEVELAND BROWNS' REVIVAL WARRANTS CHEER FROM SEAHAWKS FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It is tough to gauge exactly how rabid Seahawk fans
will again become in the upcoming season or two.
</P>
<P>
   Will the leather-lunged and stalwart Seahawk supporters _ the
good ol' No. 12's who made the Kingdome one of the loudest stadiums
in the galaxy _ return to their former level of ear-puncturing
zeal?
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to tell, even as the new Paul Allen Seahawks give all
appearances of a team on the road to postseason contention.
</P>
<P>
   Why is it hard to tell? Because Seahawk fans have not been put
to the ultimate test _ not like football fans in Cleveland, where
the beloved Browns have been missing in action for two seasons,
going on three.
</P>
<P>
   True, the Seahawks appeared to be Los Angeles-bound before Allen
bought them, but now they have become one of the most
free-spending, up-and-coming franchises in the league. Meanwhile,
Clevelanders watched in anger as their home team went south, and
east, to Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's time for the Browns to get back to business, too, if
only to prove the good fight can be won. Wednesday, the good people
of Cleveland take another step closer toward reclaiming a vital
part of the city's history.
</P>
<P>
   In an Atlanta hotel, National Football League owners will listen
to proposals from seven different groups, all fervently jockeying
to become the new owners of the soon-to-be-revived Browns.
</P>
<P>
   There is a serious group that includes former Browns stars
Calvin Hill and Paul Warfield. Another includes comedian Bill
Cosby, former Miami Dolphins coach Don Shula and former Browns
quarterback and Clevelander Bernie Kosar. Still another interested
owner is billionaire banker Alfred Lerner, who has former San
Francisco 49ers president Carmen Policy as his front man.
</P>
<P>
   In short, there is no shortage of rich people who believe they
can get even richer just by owning the history-rich Browns. Why
else would the hopeful owners be bidding upwards of $350 million
and more?
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting will be Seahawks president Bob Whitsitt,
</P>
<P>
   representing Allen, the Microsoft co-founder who handed over
$200 million to take the beleaguered home team off Ken Behring's
inept hands.
</P>
<P>
   Fans in Seattle and any other city where the future of the local
NFL team has suffered through shaky times should lend serious moral
support to Clevelanders. Browns fans deserve the richest, most
loyal owners they can get.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks and Browns do not share much NFL history. Or do
they?
</P>
<P>
   On a less-than-memorable Christmas Eve afternoon, they played
the 1994 season finale in Cleveland's old Municipal Stadium. It was
a lousy game played on a miserable day. Cold, gray, rotten _ not
only because of the bone-chilling December weather by Lake Erie,
but because such bad stuff was in the air for both franchises.
</P>
<P>
   Seahawks coach Tom Flores would soon be fired, quarterback Rick
Mirer would soon be exposed as a bust, and worst of all, Behring
was getting restless. On Feb. 2, 1996, he announced that he was
hijacking the team to Los Angeles, leaving Seattle's NFL legacy up
for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks' team colors, logo and records were meaningless to
Behring. His only objective was to set up shop in Tinseltown, where
he dreamed other money-hungry developer types would build him a
stadium and the NFL would reward him with their blessing to be the
league's sole entity in one of the nation's biggest TV markets.
</P>
<P>
   But then there was the matter of that pesky little lawsuit, the
one filed by King County and the state of Washington, demanding
that Behring and the Seahawks honor their Kingdome lease and remain
in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   All the publicity and the fear of federal court justice were
just the things to scare off Behring's L.A. suitors. He could make
no deal in L.A. Instead, he was forced to make the one deal in
Seattle with a man for whom $200 million is pocket change.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking back, it would be fair for Seahawk fans to give some
credit to the good people of Cleveland for the relatively easy
survival of the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   When former Browns owner Art Modell made an airport runway deal
to ship his team to Baltimore, Cleveland fought back. It was the
pain and suffering and the good fight led by the fans and
politicians in Cleveland that forced the NFL to put the Browns'
logo, colors and team records in a special trust.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the NFL set to award the Browns' colors, logo and
records to a new owner, the Browns are getting closer to their
revival. Next August, the old Browns will become the new Browns
when the first preseason game is played at the new Municipal
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, it was the inalienable right of Cleveland to retain
its NFL heritage that set the stage for Behring's inability to
weasel out of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Go, Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
