<HEADLINE>
HUSKY RECEIVER SHOWCASES SHEAR TALENT IN HIS DORM ROOM BARBER
SHOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For a lot of Washington football players, Tuesday was
a bad hair day. There will be many more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some clippers,'' transfer wide receiver Dane Looker
explained innocently. ``I cut my own hair. I learned that from a
roommate at Western Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   In the dormitory housing the Huskies use for two-a-day drills,
Looker's teammates dropped in for haircuts. Several linemen,
including tight end Chris Lang, Chad Ward, Tony Coats opted for a
shaved head.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Brad Hutt, the center, who wanted a 'do like the
character Kooch in the movie ``Vision Quest'' _ something like a
cross between a mohawk and a coonskin cap. Linebacker Todd Johnson
chose a longish mohawk. Another linebacker, Jeff Johnson, ordered a
shaved head with a tail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bathroom (in the dorm) looks like a big old dog shed his
hair,'' Looker said.
</P>
<P>
   Explained Lang, ``It's just for fun, something to do during
two-a-days to liven it up a little.''
</P>
<P>
   COATS CLEARED: Coats, who had been held out of sprinting drills
because of an accelerated heart rate that afflicted him recently,
received clearance and was running hard Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   IFS ANDS MUTTS: Looker hasn't been spending all his time playing
barber. Lambright says he ``catches everything.'' One sideline
reception on a deep ball from Brock Huard Tuesday caused Huard to
break into a shaky rendition of their alma mater's fight song at
Puyallup ... DB Renard Edwards, one of three Walla Walla JC
transfers, is in camp after obtaining his two-year degree ... WR
Patrick Reddick has been out of action with a continuation of a
spring knee problem. Reddick, who showed great promise as a
freshman last year, had a cyst removed months ago and still has a
tender spot ... Lambright says the rest of the week will feature
``real heavy hitting,'' due in part to the importance of the Sept.
5 opener at Arizona State, plus the need to get an early look at
freshmen who might figure in ... RB Maurice Shaw (hamstring) sat
out again and likely won't be full speed by the first scrimmage
Saturday ... PK Nick Lentz has a quadriceps pull, but Lambright
expects him back soon. Also kicking are walk-on Jim Skurski and two
mystery guests, WRs Joe Jarzynka and Jon Minter ... Lambright says
the punting competition is roughly even, with holder Sean
O'Laughlin and Seattle Prep/St. Olaf's transfer Ryan Fleming
battling.
</P>
</TEXT>
