 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No 398- August 19, 1998   We are offering the
following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. CELEBRITY ENDORSERS CAN BE RISKY BUSINESS What happens when
celebrities are caught in compromising situations while wearing
designer labels with which they have no commercial association? For
example, Hugh Grant wearing a Tommy Hilfiger cap when arrested for
soliciting a prostitute, or Monica Lewinsky wearing a Donna Karan
beret to a November 1996 photo opportunity with President Bill
Clinton? In this report, company executives discuss the impact of
these unplanned product placements. By Eric Wilson. From Women's
Wear Daily. 1,000 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
LUTHER VANDROSS BROADENS HIS RANGE Perennial Grammy god Luther
Vandross has been called the ``Frank Sinatra of R&AMP;B'' in Billboard
magazine. It's a term of endearment that he cherishes. ``I loved
it. I couldn't have loved anything more, because it implies
longevity,'' Vandross says of the Sinatra comparison. ``It implies
a standard that's hard to keep or measure up to.'' By Steve Morse.
From The Boston Globe. 1,000 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
VINCE VAUGHN : A 'SWINGER' BRANCHES OUT Vince Vaughn has hit the
extremes in the movie world - his two biggest roles to date have
involved starring in the microbudgeted independent hit
``Swingers,'' and getting eaten by a dinosaur in Steven Spielberg's
extravagant ``The Lost World : Jurassic Park.'' Now he's filling in
the gaps with four upcoming films, including ``Return to
Paradise,'' and the controversial remake of ``Pyscho.'' By Ian
Spelling. 1,300 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
JASON PATRIC, THE ANTI-STAR, REBOUNDS FROM 'SPEED 2:
</P>
<P>
   CRUISE CONTROL' Jason Patric grew up with show business in his
blood, but that doesn't mean he's truly at ease with being a star.
In fact, he would rather someone else get all the attention. Like
it or not, the attention is on him with his new movie ``Your
Friends and Neighbours,'' the most sexually provocative film of
1998 (it's a modern immorality tale about three couples who examine
the intimacy between husband and wives, friends and neighbours.)
Patric discusses his career and his rebound from the unsuccessful
film ``Speed 2.'' By Cindy Pearlman. 1,400 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 5.
'SCOTTY' PRAISES SPIELBERG FOR 'SAVING PRIVATE RYAN' James Doohan
is best known for playing the role of ``Scotty'' - as in ``beam me
up Scotty'' - on ``Star Trek.'' But he's also a World War II
veteran of Canada's armed forces. In this interview, Doohan talks
about D-Day and praises Steven Spielberg's film ``Saving Private
Ryan.'' He also says the fans got it wrong - it was ``Beam me up,
Mr. Scott.'' By Jerry Tallmer. 1,400 words + photos.
_____________________________________________________________ 6.
WESLEY SNIPES Wesley Snipes has had a hit and miss career. In this
article he discusses his next role in the new science fiction movie
``Blade.'' Snipes also talks about his production company, Amen Ra
Films, and his hopes to have more control over his career. By Ian
Spelling. 1,200 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 7.
FACE VALUE : WESLEY SNIPES Vance Lehmkuhl offers a cartoon view of
Wesley Snipes in his new sci-fi film ``Blade.''
_____________________________________________________________ 8.
WHEN AN OLDER WOMAN ROMANCES A YOUNGER MAN It's no big deal when
Warren Beatty, Jack Nicholson, Michael Douglas, Clint Eastwood or
Harrison Ford romance and win the hearts of their leading ladies
(most of whom are young enough to be their daughters.) But what
happens when the tables are turned, the woman is 40 and the object
of her desire is 20? Add to the mix the fact that the couple are
black and you have a story that is perfect for a Hollywood movie :
``How Stella Got Her Groove Back,'' (based on Terry McMillan's book
about her affair with a much younger man. ) Actress Angela Bassett,
says she grabbed the part because ``the story deals with universal
themes while asking some important questions.'' By Ivor Davis.
1,000 words + photos. (N/A Great Britain and Australia.)
_____________________________________________________________ 9.
DREW CAREY'S NEW GAME IN TOWN Based on a British perennial TV show,
the comedy game show ``Whose Line Is It Anyway'' is hosted by Drew
Carey. It is being touted as one of the funniest shows on the air.
Carey talks about his delight in his first encounters with
improvisational comedy and why he thinks that, laugh for laugh,
this may be television's funniest show (four comics perform
unrehearsed scenes, based on suggestions from a studio audience.)
By Andrew Ryan. From Canadian TV Guide. 1,400 words.
</P>
