<SLUG> BC-A-VIENNESE-VACATION-TRAVEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S DOING IN VIENNA 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
</P>
<P>
   (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
</P>
<P>
   TWO COLOR SLIDES are available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   (HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY
TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR
PAGES! SEE ABOVE FOR A SALESPERSON IN YOUR TERRITORY.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JANE PERLEZ &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Austrians are always celebrating somebody's anniversary,
most often that of a musician or composer. But this year, instead
of Mozart or Schubert, it is Empress Elizabeth, fondly known as
Sissi, who was assassinated 100 years ago at age 61 in Geneva after
a disastrous marriage and tormented life.
</P>
<P>
   Images of the slim, handsome young princess with cascades of
brown hair flowing down her back and a demure smile are all over
Vienna. Elizabeth was 16 when she married her cousin, Emperor Franz
Joseph, in 1854. A Bavarian, she quickly came to dislike the
strictures of court life in the Austro-Hungarian Empire and she
escaped by writing poetry, riding horses and having a villa built
on Corfu.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the salute to the imperial past, Vienna has become a
livelier, more international city in the last few years. The
effects of the opening up of the former Communist bloc can be
subtly felt in the languages spoken in the cafes and on the trams,
and in glimpses of newly affluent Russians who park money here.
</P>
<P>
   Austria, its neutrality maintained since 1955 after the
withdrawal of the four occupying powers, has decided for the moment
against joining NATO. But for the second half of 1998, Austria has
assumed the presidency of the European Union and is flaunting its
adhesion to Western Europe by showing off its revitalized
industries and exports, including its high-quality wine. Vienna has
become a gateway to Eastern Europe with daily flights by Austrian
Airlines to even some of the most out-of-the way cities that nine
years ago were behind the Iron Curtain.
 &UR; EVENTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The immortal Sissy is at the heart of a three-part exhibit,
``Elizabeth _ Eternal Beauty,'' that is taking place in three
different parts of the city. At Schonbrunn Palace, her summer
residence, the early period of her marriage comes to life in the
fabulous apartments where she wrote and entertained.
</P>
<P>
   Portraits, paintings, the diamond star she wore in her hair,
clothing and photographs are on display. Admission is about $7.80
(at the exchange rate of 11.5 schillings to the dollar). Open daily
till Oct. 31, 8.30 a.m. to 4.30 p.m.; phone (43-1) 811-130, fax
(43-1) 812-1106.
</P>
<P>
   At the Hofburg, the Imperial Palace, Elizabeth's residential
apartments are also open. A ``pictorial survey'' of her travels,
telegrams, letters and other documents are on display. Open daily 9
a.m. to 5 p.m., Admission $6.95; (43-1) 533-7570, fax (43-1)
533-7570.
</P>
<P>
   At the Hermes Villa, Lainzer Tiergarten, in the Vienna Woods,
where the empress went horse riding, objects from her personal life
and samples of her poetry are on view. Admission, $6. Hours:
Tuesday to Sunday 10 a.m. to 6 p.m.; (43-1) 804-1324.
</P>
<P>
   Another special event dedicated to Sissi is scheduled for Sept.
26, when music from the 17th to the 20th centuries will be
performed at the Schonbrunn Palace by a 27-piece orchestra, the
Concilium Musicum Wien. Tickets, $47, can be ordered from (43-1)
53601. Information: (43-1) 811-130, fax (43-1) 812-1106.
</P>
<P>
   The City Hall Film Festival is an unusual chance to see some of
the best performances by opera companies from around the world.
Until Aug. 30, a large screen is on the square in front of the Town
Hall _ the Rathausplatz _ for free nightly screenings of films of
concerts, operas, operettas and ballets. The full program is
printed in the Vienna Information list, which is available at any
hotel or information booth or from (43-1) 52550.
</P>
<P>
   The Kunstforum, 8 Freyung, is a centrally situated museum with
continually changing exhibits from home and abroad. From Sept. 3 to
Nov. 29, the focus will be ``The Color Red in Russian Art,''
covering the last 600 years. The works include icons, 19th-century
folk art and paintings by Chagall and Kandinsky. Revolutionary
propaganda posters will also be among the 120 works. Hours: 10 a.m.
to 6 p.m., daily, Wednesday to 9 p.m. Admission: $8; (43-1)
711-915-5737.
</P>
<P>
   Every summer, a temporary stage on a leafy space on the Danube
Canal adjacent to Rossauer Laende Street, about five minutes from
the city center, is home to Summer Stage. Chamber music and jazz
alternate over several weekends for evening concerts. Traditional
cuisine is served at self-serve outdoor restaurants close to the
stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Egon Erwin Kirsch _ The Roving Reporter'' is on view at the
Jewish Museum Vienna until Sept. 27, honoring the 50th anniversary
of the death of Egon Kirsch, a Prague-born journalist who became a
master of European-style literary reportage. He was one of a number
of European journalists who joined the Communist Party and worked
in the Soviet Union during the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Photos, documents and personal belongings that had been hidden
in Eastern European archives show his travels through Russia,
Ukraine, the Caucasus and China. The museum is open Sunday to
Friday, 10 a.m. to 8 p.m. through September, and Sunday to Friday
10 a.m. to 6 p.m., and Thursday to 8 p.m. in October. Admission is
$6; (43-1) 535-0431.
</P>
<P>
   More than 130 of Picasso's works belonging to his housekeeper
and chauffeur, Jacqueline and Maurice Bresnu, will be on display
until Aug. 30 at the Kunsthaus, 13 Untere Weisgerberstrasse (43-1)
712-0495. These works in ``Picasso: The Secret Collection'' are not
masterpieces, but they have a certain charm and piquancy. They
include pencil and felt-pen drawings, watercolors and portraits, as
well as ceramics. Open daily 10 a.m. to 7 p.m. Admission for the
exhibit: $7.80; free on Monday.
 &UR; SIGHTSEEING &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Naschmarkt has thrived for several centuries. Starting near
the Karlsplatz and running a few blocks south, immigrants from
Turkey, the Middle East and Asia run food stalls where you can buy
kebabs, spices and fresh fruits from around the world. Open Monday
to Friday 6 a.m. to 6:30 p.m., Saturday to 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Applied Arts, locally known as MAK, at 5
Stubenring, features the best of the early 20th-century Wiener
Werkstatte. A stunning display of the changes in furniture design
is a reminder that Vienna is not just a place of heavy baroque.
Admission for permanent exhibits is $2.60, special exhibits, $7.80.
Open Tuesday to Sunday 10 a.m. to 6 p.m., Thursday to 9 p.m.;
(43-1) 712-8000, fax (43-1) 713-1026.
</P>
<P>
   You can almost hear a zither playing during Vienna in the
Footsteps of the Third Man, a tour by subway and on foot to
shooting locations of the movie based on Graham Greene's novel. A
highlight is a walk through the underground canal system. The tour
meets every Friday at 4 p.m. at the main exit of Stadtpark subway
station on the U4 line. Fee: $15.50.
</P>
<P>
   Austrian Gallery Belvedere, a Baroque castle at 27 Prince
Eugenstrasse, is where the Austrian constitution was signed in
1955. But the real attraction is the 19th- and 20th-century art,
with paintings by Gustav Klimt, Egon Schiele, Oskar Kokoschka and
Richard Gerstl. Admission: $5; (43-1) 795-570.
 &UR; WHERE TO STAY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With 40 comfortable rooms, Pension Domizil, 14 Schulerstrasse,
(43-1) 513-3199, fax (43-1) 512-3484, is one of the best values in
what can be a very expensive city. It is in the heart of the city,
two blocks from St. Stephen's Cathedral. The rooms are furnished in
a traditional, spare style. With breakfast, a double is $130.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Furst Metternich, 33 Esterhazygasse, (43-1) 588-700, fax
(43-1) 587-5268, is in a 19th-century building tucked away on a
side street in the Sixth District, near the popular shopping area
of the Mariahilferstrasse. The hotel has 55 rooms with contemporary
furnishings for $145, including breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Budget: Pension Stadtpark, 7 Landstrasser Hauptstrasse, (43-1)
713-3123, fax (43-1) 713-3123, has 21 doubles at $82, including
breakfast. This traditional, family-run establishment with bright
rooms and high ceilings is near the Stadtpark.
</P>
<P>
   Luxury: The service is discreet and the copious wood paneling
shines like a mirror at the Hotel Sacher Vienna, 4
Philharmonikastrasse, (43-1) 51-456, fax (43-1) 51-456-810. Many of
the 108 rooms and suites are decorated in luxurious fabrics with
exquisite antique furniture. Doubles start at $365, including
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Radisson SAS, 16 Parkring, (43-1) 515-170, fax (43-1) 512-2216,
occupies what was a grand palace. The rooms are stylishly decorated
in a mixture of traditional and modern, some looking over the leafy
Stadtpark. The hotel has 245 rooms, including 49 suites. Standard
doubles: $335.
 &UR; WHERE TO EAT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Zum Schwarzen Kameel (The Black Camel), 5 Bognergasse, (43-1)
533-8125, which serves typical Viennese cuisine amid wood, tile and
brass from the early 1900s, opened in 1618 (Beethoven is said to
have been a customer). There is a 10-table restaurant and a
separate roomy bar and buffet area with delicious open-faced
sandwiches (spinach and red caviar), casseroles and cheeses, wines,
beer and coffee. Closing time is 7 p.m. so the main meal is lunch,
when the signature dish is boiled beef with creamed string beans
and two sauces: chive and apple horseradish. A meal for two is
about $120, including an Austrian wine.
</P>
<P>
   Locals have taken to Do &AMP; Co (pronounced Doe and Coe, after the
name of the owner, Dogotan Attila) in the Haas House, 12
Stephansplatz, (43-1) 535-3969. It is decorated with crisp white
table cloths and upholstered chairs, and has an outdoor terrace
facing St. Stephen's. The menu is international _ a Thai-inspired
crispy pork salad, for example, and there is a sushi bar. Main
courses center on fish (like a tower of roasted Atlantic tuna that
is a specialty), wienerschnitzel and beef. A meal for two, with an
Austrian cabernet sauvignon costs about $130.
</P>
<P>
   Collio Restaurant, in the Hotel Triest at 12 Wiedner
Hauptstrasse, (43-1) 589-18-133, takes some of its culinary
inspiration from Trieste, which used to serve the Austro-Hungarian
Empire. Designed by Terence Conran, the long room with blue chairs
and metal tabletops extends into the garden, where dinner is also
served until the fall. Lamb tenderloin with olive crust and thyme
sauce is one of the chef's specialties. A meal for two with wine
costs about $95.
</P>
<P>
   A wine bar and wine store are part of Zum Finsteren Stern (To
the Dark Star), which is on a small cobbled street at 3-5
Sterngasse, in the old Jewish quarter. Lunch, informal but
