<HEADER>
A0914 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RIDE-THE-ROCKET-TRAVE     08-19 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIDE-THE-ROCKET-TRAVEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCORDE'S 21ST BIRTHDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY
TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR
PAGES! SEE ABOVE FOR A SALESPERSON IN YOUR TERRITORY.)
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By EVERETT POTTER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It was the pointed, down-turned nose, the sleek profile and the
sheer speed of the Concorde that impressed everyone 21 years ago.
They still do. So British Airways is marking the 21st birthday of
the aircraft that brought supersonic flight to the well-heeled
masses by declaring 1998 ``The Year of the Concorde.''
 &HT;    ``She is a 21st-century airplane,'' says Capt. Mike Bannister,
flight manager for British Airways' Concorde fleet. ``She looks
like she is a very fast and sophisticated airplane. And as they
say, if it looks right, it probably flies right.''
 &HT;    British Airways currently has seven Concordes, and Air France
has five. In honor of the anniversary, British Airways has mounted
a traveling exhibition called ``Ride the Rocket,'' using the
insider's nickname for the plane. The exhibition will visit all 22
cities served by British Airways this summer and fall, including
Denver, Houston, Dallas, Miami and Los Angeles. Naturally, it
includes a genuine Concorde nose.
 &HT;    A ``Ride the Rocket'' contest in conjunction with the exhibition
offers trips to London on the Concorde as prizes. In addition,
anyone purchasing a ticket on British Airways before Aug. 31 and
completing travel by the end of September is eligible to win one of
the 100 grand prizes of a trip for two on the Concorde and three
nights at a London hotel.
 &HT;    For details, contact British Airways Holidays, 7520 Astoria
Blvd., Jackson Heights, N.Y. 11370; 800-AIRWAYS.
 &HT;    Why all the fuss about a 21-year-old plane? Because nothing has
ever been built that surpasses it. A typical crossing takes about
three hours and 10 minutes, at an average speed of more than 1,000
mph. The plane's current speed record was set by British Airways in
February 1996, covering the distance from New York to London in two
hours, 52 minutes and 59 seconds.
 &HT;    ``Concorde can go at twice the speed of sound for over three
hours with 100 passengers, 10 crew and the best wines and cuisine
in the sky,'' Bannister says. ``You're traveling 23 miles a minute,
yet a coin can be set on edge on the flight deck and won't waver.''
 &HT;    Inside, the Concorde has two-by-two leather bucket seats that
would not be out of place in a sports car, and windows that are
noticeably smaller than those on subsonic aircraft.
 &HT;    Ten to 12 minutes after taking off, the Concorde reaches Mach 1
at about 30,000 feet. Ten minutes later it hits Mach 2, at which
point it is typically above 50,000 feet, eventually reaching a
cruising altitude of about 58,000 feet. It is the closest most
passengers will ever get to seeing what an astronaut sees.
 &HT;    During the flight, the famous Concorde nose heats up to about
250 degrees Fahrenheit. The pilot's view from the cockpit
encompasses a 270-degree arc, which means that Bannister, his
co-pilot and his flight engineer are looking out at a quarter of a
million miles of the Earth's surface.
 &HT;    ``It's a very beautiful aircraft to fly, very responsive and
very powerful,'' Bannister reports. ``It's an agile performer, a
thoroughbred rather than a cart horse, a sports car rather than a
truck. Pilots adore flying it.''
 &HT;    Flying at close to 60,000 feet, the Concorde encounters fewer
problems with weather than a conventional jumbo jet does at 35,000
feet. Bannister explains that ``the weather finishes at around
42,000 feet,'' which means that the Concorde is flying above storms
and turbulence.
 &HT;    Passengers report feeling refreshed when they step off the
plane. It's not just three hours in the air vs. the more
conventional six or seven hours on a trans-Atlantic flight. It's
because Concorde's cabin is pressurized to simulate a more
comfortable altitude of 4,900 to 5,900 feet vs. 7,250 feet on
subsonic long-distance flights.
 &HT;    About 80 percent of the Concorde's passengers are business
travelers _ and about 80 percent of them are repeat travelers.
Speaking of business, Bannister claims that Concorde's numbers
anticipate world business cycles.
 &HT;    ``We have the same shaped curve over the last 10 years as
London's FTSE (Financial Times Stock Exchange) has,'' he says,
``but we go up or down just ahead of it. It's because the folks
we're carrying are the people making major economic decisions.''
 &HT;    They're making money too. The one-way fare on the Concorde is
$5,456, while a round-trip ticket is $9,165. But British Airways
Concorde Vacations offers less-expensive air-hotel packages.
 &HT;    The plane can also be booked in conjunction with a
trans-Atlantic crossing on the Queen Elizabeth II. For passengers
in either Queens Grill or Princess Grill class, an upgrade to
return on the Concorde is $495. For passengers traveling in the
Caronia Grill, it's $795. And for those in the Mauritania Grill,
the upgrade runs $1,295.
 &HT;    For more information, contact Cunard, 6100 Blue Lagoon Drive,
Miami, Fla., 33126; (800) 221-4770.
 ---- 
 &HT;     (Everett Potter is a New York-based free-lance writer.)  
 &HT;     c.1998 Everett Potter  
