<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0973 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     08-19 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, Aug. 19, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Thursday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DNA-HEIRS (San Francisco) _ On June 20 on the Pacific island of
Saipan, a backhoe operator made a startling discovery at the villa
of the late Larry Hillblom, billionaire founder of Redwood
City-based DHL Worldwide Express and alleged father of as many as
eight illegitimate kids. By LANCE WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   WILLIE-BROWN (San Francisco) _ So many developers are so close
to San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown that city officials are turning
to outside consultants to screen proposals for major real estate
projects. The move, taken at the direction of the mayor's office,
is aimed at blunting charges of favoritism. By CHUCK FINNIE.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-REAX (San Francisco) _ Saddened. Embarrassed.
Disappointed. That's how Democratic leaders in California described
their reactions to President Clinton's admission of adultery and
deceit. With the November elections fast approaching, political
analysts say the party should add another adjective: worried. By
ZACHERY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-GOV (Fresno, Calif.) _ In the heart of the Central Valley,
the second gubernatorial debate was billed as a forum on the earthy
issues of agriculture, water policy and suburban sprawl. But
Republican Attorney General Dan Lungren and Democratic Lt. Gov.
Gray Davis spent much of the hour Tuesday bickering over abortion,
the death penalty and whether the state should issue education
vouchers. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   PESTICIDES (San Francisco) _ Nearly 4 million Californians live
within a half-mile of places where large volumes of potentially
toxic pesticides have been used, according to a new study by the
California Public Interest Research Group. By DIANA WALSH.
</P>
<P>
   FESTIVAL (San Francisco) _ The Burning Man Festival, a happening
or be-in celebrating self-expression, has for the last eight years
been held over the Labor Day weekend in the Black Rock Desert 100
miles north of Reno, Nev. This year, for the first time, a Burning
Man preview is being held in San Francisco where it all began in
1986. By DAVID BONETTI.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RUBLE-DEVALUATION (San Francisco) _ Boris Khodursky had just
arrived in San Francisco from Russia when he got the news from a
reporter: Russian President Boris Yeltsin had devalued the ruble,
slashing its value by one-third. The visitor was not pleased. By
DAVID ARMSTRONG.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREER-BOOSTS (San Francisco) _ Sometimes the very things that
helped us get to one level on a job are stopping us from moving
ahead _ or even staying employed. That's one of the main themes
behind ``Jump-Start Your Career,'' a thought-provoking book by Lois
Frankel, a Southern California psychotherapist and consultant. By
DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-HEMLINES (Undated) _ This fall marks a defining moment
in the century's fashion history, as women make the shift from
short to long hemlines. While some will cry foul, that they will
not be the pawns of fashion designers, longer hemlines are merely a
trend whose time has come _ again. By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN. (Photo
available on New York Times photo service)
</P>
<P>
   GUM-DISEASE (Albany, N.Y.) _ The next time you open up and say
``aaaaaah,'' don't be surprised if your doctor takes a closer look
at your gums. Research shows that the health of our mouths can have
an impact our overall health, and several new studies point to a
link between gum disease and heart disease. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-PREVIEW-PACK (Undated) _ Listen up, women. I'm probably
breaking some secret guy code by telling you this, but I've got a
job to do _and, besides, it is only fair: If your man watches ``The
Rat Pack,'' the new HBO movie on Frank, Dean, Sammy and the boys,
and he doesn't admit afterward to being a tad jealous, he's lying.
By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   DOCTOR-REGGAE (San Francisco) _ Dr. Cosmo Fraser, chief of
geriatric nephrology at San Francisco's Veteran's Administration
Hospital, has just released his second reggae album. And he
maintains his double life so well that many of those he works with
are not aware of his non-medical pursuits. By CRAIG MARINE.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FALL-LEAVES (Boston) _ Bus tours are definitely not for those
who don't like people, all kinds of people. It is a land cruise.
Two meals a day are included, breakfast and dinner. Lunch is on
your own and that's usually when it is time for a little exploring.
But in the Northeast, it can be a colorful way to see the autumn
splendor. By JULIE COOPER. (Photos available on Wieck database)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BONDS (San Francisco) _ Barry Bonds will turn 400 some time
in the next two weeks. The ``400'' of which we speak refers to home
runs, and when you combine that figure with the 438 stolen bases he
has amassed, it will make him the first player in major-league
history to combine the two feats. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ I don't know. Maybe I'm angry at
Clinton because my family is from New England, and we have a higher
standard of hypocrisy. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 1119EDT &QL; 
