<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0986 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-CHERNOBYL-$AD     08-19 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-CHERNOBYL-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LETTER FROM BELARUS: SUFFERING STILL FROM THE FALLOUT OF
CHERNOBYL
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Thursday, Aug. 20 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DRUZHNY, Belarus _ This forlorn town, with its crumbling
apartment blocks and almost treeless landscape, looks more like the
site of a nuclear accident, not a refugee for people who lived
through one.
</P>
<P>
   But here, far from the fallout of the world's worst nuclear
accident, is where Soviet authorities 12 years ago decided to
relocate about 1,000 men, women and children from Chernobyl, in
neighboring Ukraine -- where the world's worst nuclear accident
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Druzhny was what passed for a newly built Soviet
development town. About an hour's drive southeast of Minsk, the
capital, it was not a community, merely a collection of hastily
erected apartment buildings and paved roads to accommodate the
proletariat.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the buildings are run-down, the roads are Swiss cheese
and the survivors are virtually forgotten. But the problems live
on, especially for the maturing children of Chernobyl, who have
grown up sick and face an adulthood of fear.
</P>
<P>
   The wretched post-Soviet economy of Belarus means that most are
unable to find jobs. Needed medicines are difficult to obtain,
wildly expensive or both as the state-run health care system
sputters. Latent maladies from radiation exposure materialize like
haunting nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people who came from Chernobyl just say, 'To hell
with our problems. Let it be. Let's just finishing living this
miserable life,''' says Elena Butkovskaya, 43, who lost her husband
to a brain tumor last year and worries about her 17-year-old son,
Andrei, who has developed an untreatable heart condition and
respiratory problems.
</P>
<P>
   But Butkovskaya, a woman with close-cropped, thinning hair and
sunken eyes, will not let it be.
</P>
<P>
   She has made it a mission to improve life in Druzhny, primarily
through her work with the non-profit Belarusian Fund for the
Children of Chernobyl.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the accident in 1986 more than 2 million
Belarusians were exposed to high levels of radiation, with only a
belated warning and action from the Soviet government. Thousands
were relocated from an wide evacuation zone around the plant, 2,000
square miles in Ukraine and Belarus tainted by nuclear
contamination and closed to humans.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, cancers, congenital malformations and other medical
problems plagued the survivors.
</P>
<P>
   The people of Druzhny have only a small, ill-equipped infirmary
to provide care. Tiles are peeling off the walls. The concrete
floors are bare.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional fallout is difficult, too.
</P>
<P>
   In more than one case in Druzhny, there have been distressing
family squabbles over budding love, a unique type of post-Soviet,
nuclear-age Romeo and Juliet story: He is from Belarus. She is from
Chernobyl. Their families are against the marriage and plagued by
questions of whether she can bear children, whether he will be
happy if she cannot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who wants a wife who already has had an operation and cannot
have children and will have to take drugs all her life?'' says
Butkovskaya.
</P>
<P>
   For her son Andrei, the prospects are dim. His health problems
forced him to abandon his studies for now. His job prospects are
dismal even with a college degree.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, there were plans to build a nuclear power plant next
to the town. The nuclear power plant never came, but neither did
the jobs it would have provided.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people had very good jobs and good salaries working at
Chernobyl and they wanted the money no matter what the risks,''
Butkovskaya says. ``But we live for our children and our
grandchildren. From my point of view, it would be better to light
candles and ride a horse than to live with the dangers and
psychological problems of living next to a nuclear power plant.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
