<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1017 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-INTEL-WEB-HNS &LR;      08-19 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTEL-WEB-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL PROMOTION STIRS ETHICAL DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By MATT BEER   
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Think the World Wide Web is slow? Intel Corp. is
paying mainstream Web publishers to make it even slower.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to sell more chips with more power, the Santa
Clara, Calif.-based computer chip maker is pumping money into a
program to entice _ some say pressure _ Web site creators to post
large, complicated graphics on their sites. Web content creators
are heeding the call.
</P>
<P>
   The program, dubbed ``Optimized Content,'' encourages Web sites
to use large, complicated graphics that slow down a computer's
processor when they are downloaded from the Internet. An
accompanying message informs a user that a faster, Pentium II
microprocessor would make those pictures run smoother and faster.
</P>
<P>
   Optimized Content is also another ember in the slow-burning
debate over the mixing of advertising and editorial content on Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're asking us to do is turn our sites into a
demonstration of their products,'' said Peter Horan, a senior vice
president of Boston-based IDG, publisher of computer magazines like
Computerworld and PC World, the ``for Dummies'' how-to book series
and their related Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to optimize our content for our readers, not for
Intel,'' Horan said.
</P>
<P>
   The program, formally called ``Intel Inside Optimized Content,''
subsidizes advertising on sites that post large, complicated
pictures and special effects. According to Intel, the program is
designed to encourage Web sites to design content that ``on a
faster processor provides a perceivable benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheri Maat, manager of Intel's ``Intel Inside'' program, said
the company is not interested in controlling a site's content.
``We'd be a lot smoother if we were going to do that,'' she said,
adding that the program is meant to seduce a user into buying a
faster processor.
</P>
<P>
   Intel normally reimburses PC makers 50 percent of their
Web-based advertising costs when they use the ``Intel Inside'' logo
on Web-based ads. Under the Optimized Content program, Intel kicks
in 75 percent of a PC maker's ad costs if the Web site features
complicated graphics. The qualifying sites have to contain wording
that says a Web page is better viewed with Intel's faster Pentium
II-equipped machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hell of an incentive,'' said one Web editor who asked
not to be named. ``PC companies are going to advertise on sites
where they pay only 25 percent of the costs, as opposed to sites
where they have to pay for half of the ad.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, launched last September, was updated July 15. The
program has been embraced by many of the giant Web publishing
concerns, including Wired Digital, Ziff-Davis, C/Ne, and CMP Media.
Web sites that use the program say it's simply a way to help
introduce cutting-edge technology to Web users.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would never, absolutely never, compromise our editorial
integrity,'' said Dan Farber, vice president and editor-in-chief of
ZDNet, the on-line presence of Ziff-Davis publications. ``The whole
basis of our success is the quality and respect of our journalistic
ethics.''
</P>
<P>
   Farber said Ziff-Davis joined the Intel program after creating
an elaborate three-dimensional site map for the ZDNet Web site.
Farber points out that there is a simpler site map available for
users and that no other pages in the ZDNet Web site are optimized.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turns out that that particular site map qualifies us for
the program,'' Farber said. ``No content is being altered for it.
No user is being forced to have their experience of ZDNet slowed
down. This whole thing has been blown out of proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Andrew De Vries, spokesman for Wired Digital, said the
Intel program was used briefly last year, but a major Wired Digital
site, fully qualified under the Intel program, is slated to unwrap
soon.
</P>
<P>
   `Generally, we design content that's good for our readers,'' De
Vries said, ``but we also keep advertiser considerations in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Horan said the seduction of ad dollars can cloud editorial
judgment at Web sites.``They don't view it as a conflict,'' he
said, ``but IDG does. How much of a site is inconsequential? Either
you cross that line or you don't.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the inaugural issue of the media watchdog magazine Brill's
Content, Web sites, especially the giant portal pages of Yahoo and
Excite, were criticized for failing to indicate which advertisers
paid to be designated as recommended links.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape has raised eyebrows when it began a smart Web search
feature that automatically recommends sites to users that in some
cases and without notice are financial partners of Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things start small,'' Horan said, ``but they grow. We
have to start openly discussing them before it ruins the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a discussion that could happen sooner rather than later.
According to Ad Age magazine, Intel devotes an estimated $7.5
million to subsidized Web site advertising. Maat said 60 percent of
subsidized Web advertising goes to optimized Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-13-98 1458EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
