<SLUG> BC-CPT-GEOCITIES-INTERNET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEOCITIES AGREES TO FTC STRICTURES ON INTERNET PRIVACY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an effort to protect the privacy of Internet users, the
Federal Trade Commission has approved a consent decree with the
Internet-hosting company GeoCities. The decree settles an FTC
complaint alleging that GeoCities misused personal information
obtained from the company's two million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``GeoCities misled its customers, both children and adults, by
not telling the truth about how it was using their personal
information,'' said Jodie Bernstein, director of the FTC's Bureau
of Consumer Protection. But GeoCities denies any wrongdoing, and
the decree does not constitute an admission of guilt.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC action comes two days after GeoCities went public on the
Nasdaq stock exchange. Shares of GeoCities fell $7 to $38 1/2
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   GeoCities is based in Santa Monica, Calif. The company runs an
Internet ``community'' where members create their own Web sites in
``neighborhoods'' shared by members with similar interests.
</P>
<P>
   CMG Information Services Inc. of Andover, Mass. owns 31 percent
of GeoCities. Guy Bradley, a partner in CMG's Internet investment
unit, said that the company had been caught up in the growing
controversy over the use of personal information gathered from the
Internet. ``Basically, GeoCities wasn't doing anything wrong, but
the FTC was looking around for somebody to make an example of,''
said Bradley. ``It feels a little like a storm in a tea cup.''
</P>
<P>
   CMG invests in several leading Internet companies, such as Lycos
Inc., an Internet search service used daily by millions of people.
Bradley said that CMG's control over these firms' privacy policies
varied by the size of CMG's investment in the companies. But, he
added, ``in all the companies I'm involved with, we try to avoid
doing anything which results in personal information being given
out.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not how the FTC saw things. GeoCities collects personal
information about people who sign up for Web sites. According to
the FTC, GeoCities broke a pledge to share the information only
with advertisers selected by the member. In addition, GeoCities
provided outside marketing firms with such information as members'
marital status and education, though the company had promised that
such information would be released only with a customer's approval.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC also charged that GeoCities set up a children's Internet
club, which collected personal information about children. The
agency says that GeoCities concealed its ownership of the club, and
the fact that it was compiling information about the children who
signed up.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, GeoCities will promise not to engage in
these practices. In addition, the company will post a privacy
policy statement telling how it uses the information it collects.
GeoCities will also have to get parental consent before requesting
information from a child. The company will delete its database of
information about children, and give adults the option of having
their information deleted as well.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Rotenberg, executive director of the Electronic Privacy
Information Center, praised the FTC action. But Rotenberg did not
think the agency went far enough, because GeoCities is free to sell
information about users, as long as users are notified.
</P>
<P>
   Rotenberg favors federal legislation limiting the corporate use
of information gathered at Web sites. Otherwise, said Rotenberg,
``You're going to have to read each privacy policy at each Web site
to decide whether or not it works for you.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-13-98 1839EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
