<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER BUYING A COMPUTER, KEEP A 30-DAY PRICE WATCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By LONNIE BROWN   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, you've shopped around for that big-ticket home computer and
paid the money for it, or bought a new toy to hook up to one, or
have finally gotten a laptop with a screen larger than a postcard.
You bought it at the lowest price.
</P>
<P>
   Friend, your shopping trip is not over.
</P>
<P>
   You may still have 30 days left from the day of your purchase to
continue shopping for a lower price. And if you don't keep checking
prices, you could wind up paying more - possibly several hundreds
of dollars more - than you might have.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, my wallet is thicker with more than $300 worth of
20s and 50s, simply because I took the time to keep reading the
advertisements after I made my purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Big chains make the pledge that if the price drops within 30
days of your purchase, you can present the receipt of your
purchase. If you find it advertised at a lower price, bring the
competitor's ad in with the receipt. If it's in stock, you can have
the price difference refunded - and in some cases, 10 percent of
the difference to boot for your time.
</P>
<P>
   When a Toshiba Satellite 335CDS laptop was advertised for $2,000
(minus a penny to make it look less expensive), it was a drop in
the previous $2,200 asked for the machine. It was a good price for
a lot of computer.
</P>
<P>
   A Toshiba 2055CD Satellite laptop had served me well for several
years, but with only 12 megabytes of memory and a smallish hard
drive, it was unable to handle some of the tasks I wanted it to do.
</P>
<P>
   The 335CDS is a great little computer: Pentium 266 megaHertz; a
12.1-inch screen with vivid colors; 4.1 gigabyte hard drive; 56K
modem on a PCMCIA card; and a built-in CD and floppy drive. I've
come to like the feel of the Toshiba keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   The 335CDS, like the old laptop, has a cursor control that
sticks up from the middle of the keyboard. It looks something like
an eraser head on a pencil, and it works well enough. I had
expected I would have plugged in a regular mouse to use instead,
but the arrangement worked so well for me that I never bothered.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, I finally decided to buy the laptop. Office Depot
had it at the same price as everybody else: $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after the purchase, while looking through the computer
ads, there was the 335CDS in a competitor's ad: ``Price break!
$1,700.'' (That wasn't the exact price, but what's another penny
among friends?)
</P>
<P>
   Yep. By the time I got to the store, I didn't need the
advertisement from the competition to prove my point. Office Depot
had received notice from Toshiba of the price reduction and
refunded the difference.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, a friend of mine was telling me about a laptop
he'd just purchased. A Toshiba, with a 266-based Pentium processor.
He'd bought it at Circuit City about three or four weeks before and
paid $2,000 for it. I told him he'd better hurry back to Circuit
City and get his $300 back.
</P>
<P>
   He was unaware of the price reduction. He went to the store that
afternoon to ask about it. He got his money, but if he'd waited two
more days, he would have been past the 30-day ``we'll meet any
lower price'' guarantee offered by Computer City.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, this is the third or fourth time that I've
managed to recoup part of the purchase price of a computer or
related item through a price reduction. I've missed getting a
rebate on some items because the price dropped 40 or 50 days after
I made a purchase.
</P>
<P>
   (A friend of mine and I have a theory that manufacturers wait
until they receive our warranty cards in the mail, then at least 31
days later, drop the price of the item we purchased.) The $300
windfall was the biggest yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding money'' like that isn't likely with any other consumer
product outside the computer industry. Everyday appliances like
washers and large refrigerators aren't in a highly competitive
market. Smaller electronic items like scanners and CD-ROM drives
don't have a lot of room to make price drops of hundreds of
dollars, although nobody will turn down getting a $10 or $20 bill
back should the price go lower.
</P>
<P>
   But desktop and laptop computers are becoming the hand-held
calculators of the 1970s: more powerful, smaller, faster and
cheaper. Prices are tumbling, partly because the strong U.S. dollar
affects the cost of products made overseas and partly because of
rapid reductions in the cost of components (random-access memory is
but a fraction of its cost a year or so ago).
</P>
<P>
   So don't stop shopping after the purchase is made. Take the
receipt, put it in a safe place, and mark the date 30 days away
from the date of the purchase on the calendar to return to the
store to check the price. During that period, watch the ads for the
same product.
</P>
<P>
   It's advice that pays off. In this most recent case, let me
count the ways - all 300 of them.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. An
archive of his recent computer columns is on the Internet at
http://www.theledger.com/data.htm.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-14-98 1609EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
