<SLUG> BC-LUNCH-LOVE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lunchbox Letters: Pack sandwich, apple, chips and mug, and one
more thing: a long-distance hug
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   From first grade until graduation day, Courtney Garton always
managed to slip in the last word.
</P>
<P>
   Usually somewhere between the sandwich and chips.
</P>
<P>
   His daughters, Adrienne and Cara, got used to finding the notes
that Garton would compose as he got them ready for school.
</P>
<P>
   Half-asleep at 6 a.m., he would put ballpoint pen to napkin as a
small way of reminding them that he cared. As a divorced parent, he
couldn't be with them as much as he hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Cara, now 25, gave her dad a shoebox full of
the lunch-bag notes and said he should make them into a book.
</P>
<P>
   He did _ after 99 rejections from publishers.
</P>
<P>
   But Garton made it big when he got on Oprah. How? By sending her
a blue Mickey Mouse lunchbox with the book, a granola bar and a
napkin poem inside.
</P>
<P>
   It went like this:
</P>
<P>
   My book's enclosed for you to see.
</P>
<P>
   After reading it, I hope you'll agree
</P>
<P>
   That it invokes spirit _ not ennui.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it'll make you jump with glee,
</P>
<P>
   Or laugh out loud _ hee hee.
</P>
<P>
   But for me, the key
</P>
<P>
   Would be
</P>
<P>
   A good on-air review, Ms. Winfrey.
</P>
<P>
   Now Napkins: Lunch Bag Notes From Dad is in its third printing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a way of giving advice without giving advice,'' Garton
says from his home in Annapolis, Md. ``Face it, kids don't like
lectures.''
</P>
<P>
   So he used a few lines of shaky rhyme to talk about anything:
boys, cars, money, friends.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, his daughters' friends caught on and would make the
girls read the notes aloud at the lunch table. Adrienne and Cara
ended up peeking in their bags beforehand for embarrassing ones.
</P>
<P>
   Garton taught math for eight years and now owns four hat shops.
``I'm no parenting guru,'' he says. ``I just kind of stumbled on
something.''
</P>
<P>
   He wrote his last note in 1991, when Cara graduated but says he
will write for his grandchildren. The first is expected in
December.
</P>
<P>
   The messages should be familiar. ``Really, it's boys and cars
and money and friends,'' he says. ``Have things changed much?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
