A1041 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUNCH-SIDE20-COX     08-19 0141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUNCH-SIDE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A lunchbox Longfellow offers advice
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I'm not a poet by any means,'' author Courtney Garton says.
Here, his recommendations for the rhymingly challenged:
</P>
<P>
   1. Take five to 10 minutes of quiet time to think.
</P>
<P>
   2. Use a scrap piece of paper for brainstorming.
</P>
<P>
   3. Think of something happening in the life of your child, maybe
something that you want to talk about but need to break the ice a
little first _ ``Cars, sex, drugs, rock-and-roll, tattoos, body
piercings, whatever!'' Garton says.
</P>
<P>
   4. Think of key words, then go through the alphabet for words
that would both rhyme and make sense.
</P>
<P>
   5. Scribble down what comes off the top of your head. Chances
are, that will be the best way to say it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
