<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 20-COX &HT;    Love story close enough to perfect
 &HT;    By Emily Minor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   She fell for him a year ago Thanksgiving. He came to her door,
late, carrying Budweiser and champagne. ``He's got the best
stories,'' she enthuses. ``He's so full of life and I was just in
heaven.'' That was in November.
</P>
<P>
   In January, he met her dad and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   In February, he met her sister and her brother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   In March, he met her mother and her oldest nephew.
</P>
<P>
   In September, they're getting married.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there's going to be a wedding with all the trimmings. The
table arrangements. The old railroad lanterns that are being
rewired and used for lights. The tiny bottles of bubbles. The
carefully stenciled terra cotta pots with the pink impatiens
inside. It's all going to come together Labor Day weekend, God
willing. And it appears He is. For this is a match we thought might
never happen.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't there when my friend Peggy met her Harry. Even if I had
been, I doubt they would have noticed. But I think theirs might be
the best love story I've heard in quite a while. She's 41; he's 42.
Neither has been married. There's no ex-wife, no children visiting
just on the weekends, no big alimony payments. All the baggage is
theirs, just theirs.
</P>
<P>
   They fell for each other on the lonely beaches of the U.S.
Virgin Islands. That's where she moved a year ago May. She'd had it
with the busy corporate life in St. Paul, Minn. So she chucked the
nice paycheck and sold the house in the city and the cabin on the
lake. She stared confidently at the 401(k) balance, packed the cat
and the dog and shipped her life to St. Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   The view from her house on the cliff was beautiful, but, my, how
she missed her sister and her mother and her nephews. My, she was
lonely.
</P>
<P>
   And that's when Harry met Peggy. ``I really had kind of given up
hope,'' she says now.
</P>
<P>
   But, there he came on Thanksgiving day, cocktails in hand. He
was wearing a grin as big as hers. ``I'll tell you something about
Harry,'' her father's wife said after they'd met him for the first
time. ``He's always going to fish, and he's always going to work
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   And that made Peggy smile even more.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, their story isn't perfect. What love story is?
The first time Peggy told Harry she loved him, there was dead
silence. Oh great, she thought. But then, the very next day, Harry
piped up and said he loved her too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't sound sad,'' she told him. ``This is a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm scared,'' said Harry, who proposed a few weeks later. Then
he bought his bride-to-be a diamond-studded toe ring, all of which
is wonderful proof positive dreams really can come true. Even when
you're staring at 41 and have pretty much given up hope.
</P>
<P>
   So tonight, when your kids are whining about school and you have
to remind your husband to take the garbage to the curb and your
feet hurt and your back aches and the bills need to be paid, go
ahead and grab a smile off Peggy and Harry's almost-perfect little
love story. They won't mind. And remember, what they don't know
can't hurt them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
