<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: When and why was Burma's name changed to Myanmar? Where does
the name come from? Can you provide some brief history, please?
</P>
<P>
   A: The governing regime adopted the name Union of Myanmar in
1989. Myanmar derives from the Chinese words mian (meaning strong)
and the suffix -ma (meaning honorable). Myanma was the country's
original name. And it also has been called by yet another name,
Pyidaungzu Myanma Naingngandaw.
</P>
<P>
   The site of the ancient Mon and Burman kingdoms, Myanmar was
officially called Burma during the British colonial period,
starting in 1886, at which time it was a province of India. In
1937, the British separated Burma from India. In 1941, during World
War II, the Japanese invaded Burma and occupied it until it was
liberated by Allied forces in 1945. Burma achieved independence
from the British in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   The civilian government was overthrown by a military coup in
1962, when a revolutionary council intent on creating a socialist
Burma was established. Long-simmering public dissatisfaction
erupted in 1987-88 into widespread antigovernment rioting that the
military eventually suppressed by force.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can one write a letter of support to Kenneth Starr?
</P>
<P>
   A: The address: Kenneth Starr, Office of Independent Counsel,
1001 Pennsylvania Ave. N.W., Suite 490 North, Washington, DC 20004.
</P>
<P>
   Q: News reports continually say that Kenneth Starr's
investigation has cost more than $40 million. What is Starr's
salary?
</P>
<P>
   A: As reported previously, Starr's Washington office says he is
paid on an hourly basis, based on an annual salary of $118,000. He
cannot make more than $118,000, a spokeswoman said, regardless of
the number of hours he puts in. He and his staff are paid by the
U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia. Starr
reportedly also receives $1.1 million a year from his law firm.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I noticed that there were no black soldiers in the movie
``Saving Private Ryan.'' Didn't black soldiers serve in integrated
units in World War II?
</P>
<P>
   A: Officially there were no integrated combat units in World War
II, although some noncombatant or support troops fought alongside
whites in, for example, the Battle of the Bulge. President Harry
Truman integrated the armed forces in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does devalued currency mean in terms of spending power
and in tourist dollars for a person visiting a country that has
devalued its currency? Has the U.S. ever devalued its currency?
</P>
<P>
   A: Generally, if a foreign country's currency is pegged to the
U.S. dollar, you'd get more bang for your buck when it is devalued.
Travelers from the United States should have greater spending power
in that country. In the short term, travelers should realize
savings on most services, such as hotels, restaurants and possibly
air fares _ if the airline ticket is purchased overseas, that is.
And imports from that country also would be generally cheaper. And
no, the United States has never devalued the dollar, chiefly
because it is not pegged to any other country's currency.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Didn't something happen to the dollar during the
administration of President Richard Nixon that reduced its value
against foreign currencies? What was that, if it wasn't
devaluation?
</P>
<P>
   A: On Aug. 15, 1971, Nixon announced without warning an
immediate 90-day freeze on wages, rents and prices; and the end of
the traditional convertibility of the dollar into gold, in effect
freeing the dollar for devaluation against other currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon conceded that the dollar would float downward in value
against some currencies and that foreign goods and travel would
cost Americans more, but, ``laying to rest the bugaboo of what is
called devaluation . . . if you are among the overwhelming majority
of Americans who buy American-made products in America, your dollar
will be worth just as much tomorrow as it is today.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the ending of the dollar's convertibility into
gold was in effect a devaluation, Treasury Secretary John Connally
said, ``No, I would not use the word 'devalue,' simply because I
don't know what's going to happen. . . . For all I know, the dollar
may rise with respect to certain countries, it may go down in
relation to other currencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I saw a picture in the newspaper of President Clinton smoking
a cigar. Is the White House smoke-free?
</P>
<P>
   A: According to the White House Comment Line: ``It's the
president's house, so he can smoke in his house _ but the White
House is smoke-free.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has the government come forth with an official travel ban to
Kenya or Tanzania?
</P>
<P>
   A: The State Department has lifted the travel warning dated Aug.
7, when the U.S. embassies in those two African countries were
bombed by terrorists. But American citizens are still advised to
exercise caution while traveling there.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I send a manuscript to Steven Spielberg?
</P>
<P>
   A: DreamWorks, the Los Angeles entertainment company founded by
film director Spielberg, producer Jeffrey Katzenberg and music
producer David Geffen _ for copyright and other legal problems _
does not accept unsolicited manuscripts. But you could query
Spielberg's office beforehand. He can be reached at Amblin
Entertainment, 100 Universal City Plaza, 477; Universal City, CA
91608.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why are there expiration dates on bottled water?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sealed water, says Evian Natural Spring Water spokesman
Michael Neuwirth, is safe to drink indefinitely as long as it is
kept in a dry, cool place. Due to certain state requirements, Evian
elects to place an expiration and production date on its product.
Various state departments of health and other food and beverage
regulatory bodies impose different requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did the tradition begin of playing bagpipes at police
memorial services and funerals? It's done all the time, including
last month at the Capitol Rotunda for the two officers who were
shot.
</P>
<P>
   A: The practice of using bagpipes at the funerals of
firefighters and police officers began in the 19th century in
Northeast cities _ particularly in New York and Boston, where many
of the members came from the ranks of Irish and Scottish
immigrants. The use of bagpipes at funerals was a tradition in the
Scottish military. In America, the playing of bagpipes spread to
other cities and became standard even when the police officer or
firefighter was of Irish or Scottish descent.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If a person is elected to the House of Representatives for
one term, which is two years, or to the Senate for one term, which
is six years, and that's the only term they serve, are they
entitled to a pension?
</P>
<P>
   A: Senators and representatives, like other federal employees,
must serve a minimum of five years to become eligible for pension
benefits. For senators, one term would be enough. But
representatives wouldn't accrue five years' service until midway
through their third term.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
