<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1044 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS20-TAKE     08-19 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS20-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED: Q: If a person is elected to the House of
Representatives for one term, which is two years, or to the Senate
for one term, which is six years, and that's the only term they
serve, are they entitled to a pension?
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does the ``D'' in D-Day stand for? How was the name
chosen?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are several explanations, but according to the Web site
of the U.S. Army's Center of Military History _
http://www.army.mil/cmh-pg/faq/ddaydef.htm _ the term ``D-day'' is
used for the day which a combat attack or operation is to be
initiated. It designates the day of the operation when the actual
day has not yet been determined or where secrecy is essential. The
letter is derived from the word for which it stands: ``D,'' day of
the invasion. D-day for the invasion of Normandy was set for June
6, 1944, and that date has been popularly referred to ever since by
the short title D-Day.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent article reported that white welfare recipients are
leaving the rolls faster than blacks or Hispanics. Rather than
listing numbers, can you list percentages of the people in the
various racial categories who are on welfare?
</P>
<P>
   A: Here the most recent figures on welfare clients from the
Department of Health and Human Services. The numbers are from June
1997, the most recent national data: 34.5 percent white, 37.3
percent black, 22.5 percent Hispanic, 3.3 percent Asian, 1.3
percent Native American, 1.1 percent other.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why is the FBI investigating the embassy bombings in Africa?
Why not the CIA?
</P>
<P>
   A: The FBI has primary jurisdiction for investigating domestic
and international terrorism. Whenever a U.S. citizen is killed as a
result of terrorism, the FBI has the authority to investigate it.
But it would be incorrect to assume that the CIA is not involved.
The CIA and State Department also would take part in the
investigation, said Celestine Armstead, spokeswoman for the Atlanta
division of the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If President Clinton had changed his mind and refused to
testify before Kenneth Starr's grand jury, would he have been
subject to imprisonment like Susan McDougal?
</P>
<P>
   A: The answer is no. The reason is that to grant indictment
authority to the judicial branch would be to place that arm of
government above the executive branch, which the Constitution
explicity does not do. In fact, it would have been very difficult
for Clinton to back out. Starr, the independent counsel, subpoenaed
Clinton last month to appear before the grand jury. The Supreme
Court has never decided whether a president could be compelled to
respond to a subpoena, leaving that question open.
</P>
<P>
   The point of Clinton's testimony was to avoid a constitutional
clash over precisely that question. In return for Clinton's promise
to testify, Starr withdrew his subpoena. If Clinton had backed out,
Starr certainly could have reissued the subpoena, and Clinton would
then have had the option of responding to it or challenging it
before the Supreme Court. If he lost and still refused, he could
not be jailed for contempt, but he could be impeached. The House
would vote on whether to impeach, and the Senate would try the
impeachment case.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Which presidents appointed the current U.S. Supreme Court
members?
</P>
<P>
   A: Chief Justice William Rehnquist was appointed by Richard
Nixon in 1972. Gerald Ford appointed Justice John Paul Stevens in
1975. Ronald Reagan's appointments to the court are Sandra Day
O'Connor in 1981, Antonin Scalia in 1986 and Anthony Kennedy in
1988. George Bush appointed David Souter 1990 and Clarence Thomas
in 1991. President Clinton has made two appointments to the court:
Ruth Bader Ginsberg in 1993 and Stephen Breyer in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How are the members of a federal grand jury chosen?
</P>
<P>
   A: Members of a federal grand jury are chosen randomly from the
voter registration lists of the federal judicial district in which
they live.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What can you tell me about Judy Smith, Monica Lewinsky's
spokeswoman?
</P>
<P>
   A: Smith was hired as the Lewinsky family spokesperson in May. A
veteran media relations specialist, Smith was President George
Bush's deputy press secretary and runs her own media relations and
public relations firm in New York. Smith also was deputy director
of public information and associate counsel in the office of
Iran-Contra independent counsel Lawrence Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why is Portugal involved in talks on the fate of East Timor?
Didn't the Portuguese leave East Timor after a revolt in 1974?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Portuguese colonized East Timor in 1520, and, while there
were subsequent colonization attempts by the Spanish, Dutch and
British, Portuguese rule was affirmed by treaties in 1860 and 1893.
The Japanese occupied the territory in World War II, but it was
returned to Portugal after the war. After Portugal announced its
intention to decolonize East Timor in the 1970s, a civil war broke
out in the territory. Indonesia invaded in 1975 and annexed East
Timor the following year. That annexation has not been recognized
by the United Nations, which still officially regards Portugal as
the territory's ``administering power.'' The U.N. has sponsored
talks between Lisbon and Jakarta since 1983 aimed at finding an
internationally acceptable solution to East Timor's future.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In ``Saving Private Ryan,'' in the scene where they were on a
bridge at the end of the movie, what did Capt. Miller (Tom Hanks)
say to Ryan (Matt Damon). It was unintelligible, but I'm sure it
was important.
</P>
<P>
   A: Hanks said to Damon: ``Earn this.'' In other words, be a good
person and live a good life so all these people who died trying to
save you won't have died in vain.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It seems like hurricanes in the Atlantic are getting a late
start this year. What is the latest date that the first hurricane
formed in the Atlantic, and what is the latest date the last one
formed?
</P>
<P>
   A: Although hurricane season officially begins June 1 and ends
Nov. 30, storms can form before and after this period. According to
the National Hurricane Center in Miami, the earliest storm ever
recorded in the Atlantic was on March 7, 1908; the latest ever
observed was on Dec. 31, 1954. Neither storm hit the U.S. mainland.
The earliest storm to hit the mainland was Hurricane Allison, which
struck Florida's Panhandle on June 5, 1995. The latest was an
unnamed storm that struck on Nov. 30, 1925. Prior to 1950, storms
were not given names, but were tracked by numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happened to Buddy, the golden retriever used in ``Air
Bud''?
</P>
<P>
   A: Buddy developed cancer shortly after the filming of ``Air
Bud'' was completed last year. His right rear leg was amputated,
and he died in February. Six dogs were used in the filming of the
sequel, ``Air Bud: Golden Receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
