<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yes, that's Santa at the mall
 &HT;    By Ricardo Ga(accent)ndara
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It just doesn't seem right, this
battery-operated, hip-swaying Santa Claus belting out ``Jingle Bell
Rock.'' On a department store shelf. In sweltering August.
</P>
<P>
   He's cute, but Santa already? What's next? A stuffed Cupid on a
heart-shaped box of chocolates?
</P>
<P>
   Foley's $50 ``Jingle Bell Rock Santa'' hits shoppers like a
sackful of toys when they get off the escalator on the third floor
in the Highland Mall store in Austin. There's Santa singing and
singing and singing, juiced on an Energizer.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Applegate, 36, couldn't believe it. He walked by, shook his
head and motioned toward Santa as if to slap him. ``No, not you.
You're way too early, Santa,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea turned him off, he said, but he stopped anyway to check
the price. ``I was curious,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Children, of course, are drawn to the display like ornaments to
a tree. A little girl cooed: ``Santa, Daddy, Santa. Look.'' Dad
rolled his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Elise de Compiegne, Foley's representative, understands the
ambivalence of some customers. ``We're mindful it's 100 degrees and
it's back-to-school. However, there is no denying that Christmas is
the most popular season of the year, and some people do think about
and plan for Christmas year-round,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Foley's employees at the Highland Mall store report the musical
Santa is singing his way into shopping bags. They've restocked the
display. And $12 stuffed elves, reindeer, snowmen, mice and
soldiers are also selling at a brisk pace.
</P>
<P>
   We're not done.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-September, Foley's trim-a-home department will begin to
look a lot like Christmas, too, starting to sell decorations,
cards, wreaths and garland.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Ga(accent)ndara is a staff writer for the Austin
American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
