<SLUG> BC-SENTINEL-BUYS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sun-Sentinel buying S. Fla. papers group
 &HT;    By Marguerite M. Plunkett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM, Fla. _ The Sun-Sentinel Co. of Fort Lauderdale
recently said it will buy the South Florida Newspaper Network, a
chain of weekly papers that circulate from Miami to Vero Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The company would not reveal the sale price.
</P>
<P>
   Sun-Sentinel Co. President Bob Gremillion said the purchase
helps speed the company's growth, expands the number of potential
readers and advertisers, and provides a new place to promote its
newspaper and other publications.
</P>
<P>
   ``The umbrella company wants to find a way to service as many
readers and advertisers as possible,'' he said. ``This is great.
There's not huge duplication here.''
</P>
<P>
   The South Florida Newspaper Network, based in Deerfield Beach,
publishes 33 free community papers with a total circulation of
700,000. Publications include the Jewish Journal, Boca Thursday,
the Boynton Beach Times, and the Forum papers in Greenacres,
Wellington and the Treasure Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper network, with revenue of about $30 million, also
publishes magazines including Traditions, which circulates at The
Breakers hotel in Palm Beach, and House &AMP; Condo.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun-Sentinel Co., owned by public company the Tribune Co.
(NYSE: TRB, $66.75), publishes the daily newspaper of the same name
in Fort Lauderdale, with circulation of 260,000 daily and 370,000
on Sunday in June. It also has on-line operations and publications
such as South Florida Parenting magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase extends the reach of the Sun-Sentinel general
audience newspapers into the Treasure Coast from its circulation in
Broward, Dade and Palm Beach counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm personally delighted to have the Sun Sentinel Co. as our
parent,'' said Bruce Warshal, chief executive officer of the weekly
chain. ``It's a substantial and well-respected company.''
</P>
<P>
   Warshal and Chief Operating Officer Scott Patterson will
continue to run the chain as a separate business from the Sentinel
Co. Warshal said Sentinel employee benefits will not even be
adopted by the South Florida Newspaper Network.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to keep them on board,'' said Gremillion. who is also
publisher of the Sun-Sentinel newspaper. ``This isn't one of those
scenarios where they get bumped off later.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men had minority stakes in the chain with majority owner
Riverside Co., but will have no ownership interest under the
Sentinel deal. They will be employees of the Sentinel Co., Warshal
said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither would reveal how much the deal was worth or whether they
were paid in cash or stock.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart Kohl of Riverside, who was chairman of the South Florida
Newspaper Network, was unavailable for comment Tuesday. Riverside
Co. was the majority owner.
</P>
<P>
   No changes are expected for the 350 staffers at the South
Florida Newspaper Network. The chain also will also keep the same
name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe our community papers will get a little better,'' Warshal
said, however. ``Our profits were going to interest payments to the
bank. Now we can take that money and invest in better equipment and
be a little better.''
</P>
<P>
   But overall, he said, ``we really anticipate running the same
way, lean and mean. We don't intend to bloat our staff, nor do we
intend to lay anyone off.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper also said the editorial voice will be independent
from the Sun-Sentinel. ``We will continue our focus and be a very
local source for news and advertising,'' Patterson said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which Gremillion expects will be completed by the end
of September, is subject to approval by the Federal Trade
Commission, but no challenges are anticipated by Warshal or
Gremillion.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish Journal includes six newspapers in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The South Florida Newspaper Network's Palm Beach and Treasure
Coast papers are: the Jewish Journals, the West Boca Times, Boca
Thursday, The Boynton Beach Times, the Vero Beach Forum, The Martin
County Forum, the Port St. Lucie Forums, the Fort Pierce Forum, the
Wellington/Royal Palm Beach Forum, Greenacres/Lake Worth/Lantana
Forum, the Boynton Beach Times, the Boca Raton Business Journal,
and the Delray Beach Times.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
