<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 11:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1047 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN20-COX     08-19 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 20-COX &HT;    TAAS stunting growth for some
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ We post drug-free school zones. We post gun-free
school zones.
</P>
<P>
   I want that: my children free of dangerous influences. That's
why I want this posted where my children study: ``TAAS-FREE SCHOOL
ZONE.''
</P>
<P>
   That's right _ I want zones on school campuses where the mention
of the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills will cause federal
marshals to emerge, injunctions in hand, to form a human shield
around any child who has a grasp of basic skills and doesn't need
the TAAS rat-tat-tat.
</P>
<P>
   Expel TAAS from schools? No.
</P>
<P>
   As with smoking sections in restaurants, schools should have
designated areas where it would be legal to factor TAAS into every
task, from breathing to blinking.
</P>
<P>
   But right now just about every grade-schooler is inhaling these
fumes in Texas public schools. It is stunting much growth.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is right to feel good about the steadily increasing number
of students passing TAAS. Those numbers are a grapefruit in the
face of those who blast public schools as unable to teach children
who lack basic skills.
</P>
<P>
   But those basic skills are what TAAS is all about, little more.
TAAS is not about excellence. It's about competency. Whether used
to assess schools or students, TAAS measures the stump, not the
tree.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is drawing raves nationally for dealing with intractable
academic deficiencies using a content-linked measuring device and
insisting on accountability. The credit is deserved.
</P>
<P>
   But that linkage is also a problem, and it's a serious problem.
When content and accountability are affixed so tightly to the
basics, students who already have a handle on those basics are
fixed in place, brain cells frying in the deep fat of boredom.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, in schools' life-or-death struggle to get as many
as possible to pass TAAS, particularly at the elementary level,
classes spend inordinate time on TAAS objectives _ like some
students' sorest subject, math _ to the exclusion of such things as
geography, science, history, all those things children need to
become well-rounded individuals and citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Recently I spoke to a fourth-grader whose family was going to
San Antonio for vacation. Perfunctorily, I asked him if they would
be going to the Alamo. The question drew a blank. Ala-what?
</P>
<P>
   I submit to you: This is a scary symptom of TAAS fixation. It's
TAAS asphyxiation.
</P>
<P>
   A grade-school teacher, after wrapping up TAAS, was heard
exhaling: ``This means now we can teach some science,'' or social
studies, or . . .
</P>
<P>
   But wait. There were but a few days left in school. And anyway,
said another teacher. ``What this means is we start on next year's
TAAS.''
</P>
<P>
   How to implement my plan for TAAS-free school zones? This is
quite simple. In every school, have a TAAS-testing room, yes, a
designated TAAS zone. There, students individually would log on to
a secure, supervised computer program and demonstrate their mastery
of the skills in question.
</P>
<P>
   If they pass, they test out. No more TAAS. Not one utterance,
with federal marshals at the ready. If they fail, they need a more
intensive basic-skills emphasis, and federal marshals should
guarantee they have it.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, now the whole school year leads up to TAAS, making it
the end-all, the be-all. It shouldn't be. Certainly it shouldn't be
for students who could be benefiting so much more by taking wing
and exploring their world and their creative abilities.
</P>
<P>
   This is education as it should be. Under the metal lid of TAAS,
education becomes a 32-ounce mason jar. That may be filling for
some. For others, it just leaves them thirsty.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
