<SLUG> BC-NEWSLETTERS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Newsletters, cards offer personal touch
 &HT;    By Kim Tyson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Eastside Cafe's ``Garden News'' offers its
customers tips on how to compost and get rid of bugs without
pesticides, while Holland Photo's newsletter sends clients warnings
about new X-ray equipment hurting film.
</P>
<P>
   Both Austin companies are among a growing number of small
businesses that have found newsletters help them create closer
relationships with their clients as they compete against larger
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Eastside, a 10-year-old restaurant on Manor Road, began sending
customers a quarterly newsletter six years ago. The four-page
publication features gardening tips, recipes, and news of Eastside
salsas and salad dressings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way for us to directly reach our customers,'' says
Dorsey Barger, co-owner of Eastside.
</P>
<P>
   More and more small businesses are starting to use newsletters
to distinguish themselves and their products and services from
bigger competitors, says Larry Gresham, a professor at the Center
for Retailing Studies at Texas A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all a part of relationship building,'' he says.
``Anything you can do to make your customer feel like they have an
ownership in the business and are important to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Personal thank-you notes, cards after a purchase, and follow-up
phone calls to check with the customer are other ways that the
owners of small companies can do this.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent newsletter, Eastside Cafe's garden manager, David
Kolosta, writes about exploring nature by gardening with his young
son _ supporting the image the Manor Road restaurant is trying to
build as a family-oriented business that cares about the
environment and uses organically grown produce in its recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Barger says sending tips gleaned from growing herbs and
vegetables in the restaurant's garden is a subtle way to remind
customers to come by if they haven't eaten there lately. As an
extension of its efforts to reach out to its customers, the
restaurant also holds weekend gardening workshops in the spring;
200 children attended last May's sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Besides mailing the free newsletter, the restaurant keeps a
stack of newsletters available for patrons waiting for a table _
often 30 minutes or more at lunchtime.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Holland says his Holland Photo spends about $16,000 a year
to send out newsletters quarterly to 4,000 of its regular
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have a blurb about a new camera. New Internet copyright
laws, new X-ray machines that are cooking film that are now a
problem,'' says Holland, who began the newsletters three years ago.
Holland Photo gears its products and services to commercial,
professional and advanced amateur photographers.
</P>
<P>
   Holland says he uses the newsletter to pass along information he
has picked up from the dozens of magazines, newsletters and other
information he receives from manufacturers that also may be helpful
to his customers. Recent issues included information about a new
location it has opened in North Austin with another shop and
Holland's view of how the industry is changing because of digital
photography.
</P>
<P>
   While large companies with branch stores also attempt to have
close relationships with regular customers, Gresham, of Texas A&AMP;M,
says small companies can be in a better position to track their
regular customers, interact with them personally and tailor their
products and services to meet their customers' needs. ``That's
really the advantage small businesss retailers have is the ability
to know their customers,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-08-18-98 2047E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
