<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 11:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1060 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-AQUIFER20-COX     08-19 0429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-AQUIFER20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Part of Edwards Aquifer on rise
 &HT;    By Rebecca Thatcher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The southern portion of the Edwards Aquifer, a
vast underground water sourcethat provides drinking water to San
Antonio and surrounding cities, is finally starting to refill.
</P>
<P>
   After a summer that was so hot and dry that lawns turned brown
and investigators prowled neighborhoods looking for illegal
sprinklers, the San Antonio area has been getting the soaking it
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Recent cloudy skies dumped as much as 10 inches of rain on
Uvalde County, west of San Antonio, but left just .17 of an inch at
Robert Mueller Municipal Airport in Austin. Although the San
Antonio International Airport recorded no rain this week, it has
received 2.76 inches of rain in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aquifer has been steadily going up,'' said Jeannie Janes,
a spokeswoman for the Edwards Aquifer Authority, which manages the
southern section of the aquifer. For the first time all summer, the
Edwards Aquifer climbed above drought level, meaning that water
conservation measures in the area may be relaxed in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
   But the story is different in the Austin area. The Barton
Springs section of the Edwards Aquifer, which is separate from the
section that runs under San Antonio, has received little recharge
from the lighter rains that have fallen here. Only .42 of an inch
has fallen at Robert Mueller Airport this month.
</P>
<P>
   Onion Creek, one of the main creeks that feeds the Barton
Springs section of the aquifer, remained empty Tuesday, said Bill
Couch, general manager of the Barton Springs/Edwards Aquifer
Conservation District.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are nice showers and they green things up, but we have
not gotten any recharge,'' Couch said. ``It's just not happening
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Towns throughout the area continue to ask residents to conserve
water. Under Austin's voluntary water conservation program,
residents can water today if their address ends in 0 or 9.
</P>
<P>
   Though rainfall in the Austin area has been light,
today'sforecast calls for a chance of precipitation, and Austin
should eventually get a good soaking, said Larry Peabody, a
meteorologist with the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next week it may be Austin that gets all the rain and the
flooding. Like they say, what goes around comes around,'' Peabody
said.
</P>
<P>
   Peabody said the the weather will get hot again, but not as hot
as it was in earlier this summer and not for as long.
</P>
<P>
   The high today and Thursday should be in the low 90s.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
