<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 12:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1098 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BATS-ADJUSTMENT20-COX     08-19 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BATS-ADJUSTMENT20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Making the adjustment
 &HT;    By Patrick Brannan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   From Little Leagues to college baseball, players grow up using
aluminum bats. But anyone who has hopes of reaching the big leagues
must learn to work with a wood bat as much as possible. And the
adjustment from an aluminum to wooden bat can be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a new experience,'' said North Carolina Wesleyan senior
Andy Jones of his first Coastal Plain League summer season.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is now in his second year with the Rocky Mount Rockfish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to hit it on the barrel. I just wanted to try and
make solid contact,'' he said. ``But after the first couple of
weeks, I got used to it. It's just an adjustment to try and hit it
sweet.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockfish teammate Jason Dubois seems to have made that
adjustment, having stroked 17 homers and knocked in 51 runs this
summer with the wood bat. Rockfish manager Bob Keller attributes
that to dedication and hard work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is Jason was forced to make a mechanical
adjustment and use his hands more, let the hands, the pitcher and
the ball do the work,'' Keller said. ``He found some success doing
that. One of the biggest mistakes guys get when they get that wood
bat in their hands, they start to over-rotate their upper body and
get a lot of excessive movement, that they have to muscle up a
little more. If you can learn to swing with the hands, you're going
to be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   If a player can make the adjustment, it can pay off in the long
run, even if he never gets a chance to play professionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it helps a lot, especially for the guys that come out
of this league swinging a wood bat and then go home and continue
it,'' Keller said. ``Swinging that wood bat is going to help them
increase their bat speed. Guys with good bat speed can have more
holes in their swing and get away with it, to a certain amount.''
</P>
<P>
   That seemed to be the case for Jones, who started the spring
college season on a hot streak, stroking the ball around the field.
But at the end of the year, his 1998 numbers were slightly lower
than his previous year's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be a big benefit,'' former Wesleyan coach
Mike Fox said. ``But hitting is such a difficult thing. He started
out real well, but then had some ups and downs.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones agreed: Using a wood bat helped him early on.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning, it really (helped),'' Jones said. ``I felt
like I played in a real solid league. When you come back with the
aluminum, you feel like you can mash. You feel like you've got
unbelievable bat speed. Then after a month or two, it's back to
normal.''
</P>
<P>
   The bat or the player?
</P>
<P>
   Players today are getting bigger and stronger. Just a generation
ago, a player as tall as 6-9 J.R. Richard was an anomaly. Now, it's
rare to see any major leaguers shorter than 5-11. In addition,
there's no doubt that today's players are often on a strict
strength program. Mark McGwire's forearms have been measured at 17
inches in diameter. That's larger than the average man's neck size.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fine line,'' Keller said. ``You're starting to look at
a lot of players in the big leagues like McGwire, (Jose) Canseco
and some of these guys that have been on serious weight programs
for years. It used to be in the old days, it wasn't acceptable to
be a baseball player and a guy who lifted weights. Now there's been
a strong trend to that. You have a lot of guys taking weight
protein supplements, creatin, stuff like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, some of the most important coaches in collegiate
athletics are the strength coaches, in every sport. Whether it's
football, baseball, basketball, the strength coaches are some of
the most influential coaches that you have. I know at Georgia
State, we take that guy real seriously and he has our guys on a
strong weight-conditioning program.''
</P>
<P>
   Dubois knows the combination of stronger athletes and lighter
bats has had an effect on the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's going to get bigger,'' Dubois said. ``But they're
making the bats lighter, so it's more to the hitter's advantage. So
it gives them the upper edge.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no telling how quickly baseball's hitting records would
fall if McGwire or Tony Gwynn were allowed to use an aluminum bat.
It's conceivable that the single-season home run record could reach
100, or hitters might break the .400 mark on a routine basis.
</P>
<P>
   Fans love homers and high-scoring games, but would the prospect
of five- or six-hour slugfests get old in a hurry?
</P>
<P>
   What can be done?
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA, along with other organizations, is taking a close look
at the continued development of bats and is trying to bring
aluminum bats more in line with wood.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the NCAA Baseball Rules Committee is examining the
issue this week. Fox, named head coach at the University of North
Carolina this spring, recently completed a six-year term on the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time was spent on bats, `` Fox said. ``I hadn't
given it much thought, but after seeing some video and statistics,
it got me to thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Breidenthal, staff liaison with the NCAA Baseball Rules
Committee, says the committee is looking at a conflicting issue:
trying to ensure player safety while preserving the integrity of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hard decision to make,'' Breidenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the NCAA has tried to develop a measurement of
a bat's performance, called a BPF. It's a measure of the rebound of
a ball off a bat shot from a cannon at a set speed. The BPF has
been measured at speeds as high as 110 mph, although the committee
is trying to set a limit of 93 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the National Federation of State High School
Associations announced new guidelines for bat performance, based on
wood bats. The new standards will be announced by Oct. 31 and take
effect in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR:
</P>
<P>
   What 1998 Division I batting leaders would have accomplished
with aluminum bats, based on a 162-game season:
</P>
<P>
   Batting average: .464, Pat Magness, Wichita State (major league
record: .426, Nap Lajoie, 1901)
</P>
<P>
   RBI: 295, Damon Thames, Rice (major league record: 190, Hack
Wilson, 1930)
</P>
<P>
   Home runs: 102, Kevin Mench, Delaware (major league record: 61,
Roger Maris, 1961)
</P>
<P>
   Doubles: 99, Robert Gonzales, New Mexico (major league record:
67, Earl Webb, 1931)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
