<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 12:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1099 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOODEN-BATS20-COX     08-19 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODEN-BATS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Do metal bats take the ballance out of baseball?
 &HT;    By Patrick Brannan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1961, Mike Gillespie scored the winning run in the College
World Series as Southern California defeated Oklahoma State 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, when Gillespie coached the Trojans to their 12th CWS
title, he had a little more breathing room as Southern Cal defeated
Arizona State 21-14.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 CWS set 13 offensive records as the eight teams
combined to bat .318 and belt 62 home runs, shattering the previous
records of .303 and 48, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   So why the explosion of offense at the college level?
</P>
<P>
   Many are pointing to bats as the culprit. New standards may be
set on aluminum bats, while others would like to see the NCAA bring
wooden bats back to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see all of college baseball go to wood bats,''
Georgia State assistant Bob Keller said. ``I've always felt that
way, but even after being here in Rocky Mount this summer and
watching how much crisper the game is, it's played like it's
supposed to be played.''
</P>
<P>
   Keller, the hitting instructor at Georgia State, is the head
coach of the Rocky Mount Rockfish this summer. His experience this
season has strengthened his stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``With wood bats, you can play percentage baseball and have a
greater chance for success,'' Keller said. ``If we draw the infield
in with a wood bat, and a guy hits a hard ground ball, the chances
aren't as good of it getting through as if it were with an aluminum
bat. That ball is going to come off the bat a lot harder, a lot
faster and might get through the infield. It takes away some of the
strategy from the manager.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, college team batting averages have risen 16 points,
scoring is up 14 percent, and home runs have increased 54 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, team earned run averages have risen almost a
full run a game in three years.
</P>
<P>
   What's in the bat?
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of differences between aluminum and wooden
bats, besides the sound of the crack or the ping.
</P>
<P>
   The larger the diameter, the bigger the hitting area.
</P>
<P>
   A wooden bat must be solid, and therefore the weight is usually
contained in the barrel. Baseball rules state a bat can not be more
than 2 3/4 inches in diameter at its greatest spot. But most wood
bats never reach that limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most are 2 1/2 to 2 5/8 inches,'' Louisville Slugger executive
George Manning said. ``Aluminum bats are 2 3/4 and the weight is
distributed.''
</P>
<P>
   Most aluminum bats are hollow and extremely light. The NCAA
allows the difference between the bat's weight and length to be no
less than five. For example, a 33-inch bat can weigh just 28
ounces. That limit will be four for the 1999 season and may drop
further if new standards are inacted.
</P>
<P>
   Weight is the key, because contrary to popular opinion, it's bat
speed that makes a ball travel farther - the ability to whip the
bat head through the hitting zone with the greatest force.
</P>
<P>
   Aluminum bats also have a greater hitting area, usually called
the sweet spot. Rawlings has developed a metal bat with a 10-inch
sweet spot. Worth is preparing to release a new aluminum bat which
contains piezoelectric dampers to control the amount of vibration
in the bat. The bat is supposed to allow the hitter to hit the ball
harder and extend the sweet spot down into the handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``A wooden bat has a smaller sweet spot,'' Rawlings wooden bat
marketing director Tom Nailor said. ``But a ball can travel farther
if you hit it just right with a wood bat.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, when a batter gets jammed with a wooden bat, he's
more likely to break it, allowing the fielders to react to the
change in the ball's direction. With an aluminum bat, a jammed
batter can still hit the ball hard enough to carry over an
infielder's head.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics don't lie
</P>
<P>
   Amherst College coach Bill Thurston, the NCAA baseball rules
editor, is involved in a study of college hitters and pitchers who
play in wood bat summer leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Thurston followed 90 Division I hitters with at least 70 at-bats
in the Cape Cod Summer League and 60 pitchers who threw at least 25
innings. The ball used in that league is the same one used in many
college leagues, so he could rule that out as a variable.
</P>
<P>
   He then compared the summer wood bat statistics to each player's
college regular-season numbers with aluminum bats, taking into
consideration the number of games played.
</P>
<P>
   Thurston's study showed batting averages fell 107 points when
batters used wood compared to aluminum. Slugging percentages were
down 226 points. And with aluminum bats, batters hit a home run
every 25 at-bats, compared to every 74 with wood.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the batters in the study hit over .400 with aluminum
bats and 31 more hit at least .350. But not one of those same
players hit over .350 in the Cape Cod League, and only five were
able to bat better than .300.
</P>
<P>
   In his study, Thurston found pitchers' ERAs decreased an average
of 2.10 runs per pitcher. Two lowered their ERAs over five points
and seven dropped more than four runs per game.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve saw their ERA shrink by three runs. In addition, each
pitcher allowed an average of 2 1/2 fewer hits per nine innings.
</P>
<P>
   There are always exceptions to the rule. Rocky Mount Rockfish
outfielder Jason Dubois hit 17 home runs with a wood bat this
summer, after just seven round-trippers as a Virginia Commonwealth
freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Dubois doesn't have one answer as to why his numbers have
jumped, though he said he tends to swing a wood bat more during
practice and the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swinging a wood bat helps,'' Dubois said. ``I've been swinging
a wood bat for five years now.''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, he played in a league in which he was allowed to
use either wood or aluminum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used wood most of the time,'' Dubois said, ``until I found
somebody that was throwing mid-90s and then I broke out my
aluminum, just because it was easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like wood over aluminum, because it feels more natural.
You're actually using more power with wood than you are with
aluminum. Most aluminum bats now are so springy, that you hit a
ball and it goes in about a quarter of an inch and then shoots
right off.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
