<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1101 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BATS-EXPENSE20-COX     08-19 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BATS-EXPENSE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Getting the best bang for your buck
 &HT;    By Patrick Brannan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the ping that makes cash registers ring.
</P>
<P>
   Aluminum bats were first produced in the 1970s as a cheaper
alternative to wood bats. Batmakers promised unbreakable aluminum
bats would last longer than breakable wood, at a reasonable cost.
At the time, the cost savings of aluminum bats allowed youth
leagues, high schools and colleges to save money by making the
switch.
</P>
<P>
   But that isn't the case any more.
</P>
<P>
   As any parent of a baseball player knows, the price of aluminum
baseball bats continues to rise. The newest top-of-the-line models
easily cost $300. A new Worth bat, which will include piezoelectric
shock absorbers, will retail in the neighborhood of $280.
</P>
<P>
   Compare that to the current price of wood bats, which retail for
around $20. Of course, the quality of the bat you can purchase at
your local retailer is far from what Mark McGwire is using. But you
can now buy 15 wood bats for the price of some aluminum bats.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest advantages of aluminum bats is that they
supposedly last longer. But as manufacturers have made the walls of
hollow aluminum bats thinner to make the bat lighter, aluminum bats
are cracking and denting much more easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aluminum bats don't last long at all,'' North Carolina
Wesleyan's Andy Jones said. ``They tell you not to hit under 65
degrees. It's worse than a wood bat (in some cases).''
</P>
<P>
   Most companies will allow you to return an aluminum bat if it
cracks or dents. Jones said that sometimes can be as often as every
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Some college programs don't purchase bats at all, because of
contracts with aluminum bat companies. Louisville Slugger sponsored
both Arizona State and Southern California, the two teams that met
in the 1998 Division I College World Series final.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason that many college coaches haven't spoken out
about the bat issue. They don't want to bite the hand that feeds
them. But as is the case in most businesses, if somebody's given a
free ride, someone else has to pick up the tab.
</P>
<P>
   Amherst College coach Bill Thurston stated in his study on the
difference between wood and aluminum bats: ``If thousands of these
high-performance bats are being given to programs under contract
each year, it is understandable why the price of the bats to
non-contracted programs (college, high school, individuals) has
risen so dramatically in recent years.''
</P>
<P>
   Schools with smaller athletic budgets get by because players
often provide their own bats. Former North Carolina Wesleyan coach
Mike Fox said he hadn't bought a large number of aluminum bats for
the Bishops in several years.
</P>
<P>
   Cost is one of the biggest factors for colleges. But is it still
cost effective?
</P>
<P>
   There are now special wood bats which are supposed to be less
breakable. Most are coated with a special fiberglass, or have some
sort of composite material included. The Coastal Plain League has
provided its teams with composite wood bats the past two years, but
most CPL players were still willing to spend $20 on a wood bat of
their own choosing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our cost is about $100 per bat,'' said Mark Cryan, CPL
director of operations. ``We use about eight to 10 bats per team,
or about $800 per season.''
</P>
<P>
   Cryan said if the league switched to true wood bats, the cost
would be approximately $2,500 per team.
</P>
<P>
   A sudden shift in policy by the NCAA may leave many programs
scrambling to find the funds to purchase wood bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason college favors aluminum bats, like anything else,
money is the big factor, it's the driving force,'' Georgia State
assistant coach Bob Keller said. ``They say money is the reason why
they won't go to wood. There are some ways to get around it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys are going to break wood bats more, so your turnover ratio
of having to buy bats is obviously going to be more. The problem
you have there is that there are only a handful of programs in the
country that have enough money to go switch over to wood. While
that's nice, there's more programs that are small-time programs
that don't have money to be continually buying wood bats.''
</P>
<P>
   Bat manufacturers want the NCAA to fully evaluate the issue
before rushing to any conclusions. Obviously, they don't want to
lose out on the millions of dollars aluminum bats bring in every
year.
</P>
<P>
   Thurston noted that there are several reasons why bat companies
are against reducing the explosive power of metal bats, with
profits coming out on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would severely reduce the profitability margin of the
bat,'' Thurston said. ``It allows other bat manufacturers (who
presently don't have the high-tech engineering capacities) to
compete in the market, and reduces sales because the bats would be
more durable and not need to be replaced as often.''
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR:
</P>
<P>
   Easton Sports, one of the two major aluminum batmakers, has
filed a $267 million pre-emptive lawsuit against the NCAA, alleging
unlawful restraint of trade.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA this week approved rules changes designed to reduce the
impact speed of aluminum bats by Aug. 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to let them know that this is a serious change,'' said
Jim Easton, the chairman of Easton Sports, which is one of the two
biggest manufacturers of aluminum bats. The other is Louisville
Slugger, and together the two companies produce about 40 percent of
the 500,000 aluminum bats manufactured annually in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
