<HEADLINE>
VIEWS OF AUTUMN SPLENDOR BLOSSOM FROM A BUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Photos available on Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE COOPER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There's a long line at the Sheraton's breakfast buffet
the first Sunday in October. A really long line. But then I
remember: There are a number of tour buses hitting the road this
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Autumn Highlights of New England'' _ Globus bus tour's AB
1004 _ is just one group of 45 among this throng of people piling
breakfast meats, potatoes, eggs and sweet rolls onto their plates.
</P>
<P>
   There is much more to a fall foliage tour than leaves and
lobster.
</P>
<P>
   The week is one Kodak moment after another:
</P>
<P>
   _ At Quechee Gorge in Vermont, hordes of tourists gather to
stare at what the brochure calls ``Vermont's Little Grand Canyon.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The water rushes up through Thunder Hole at Acadia National
Park along Maine's rocky coast.
</P>
<P>
   _ The gondola ride at Wildcat Mountain is a 360-degree view of
the Presidential Range and Mount Washington Valley in New
Hampshire. Winds of 230 mph have been recorded here _ luckily, not
the day I share a gondola to the top with one of my bus mates.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Bar Harbor, Maine, the owner of The Song of the Sea takes
down a set of bagpipes and plays a tune. The shop, which stands on
the waterfront, sells Celtic instruments.
</P>
<P>
   _ The General Store in Bath, Maine, opened in 1790, has a
celebrity saleswoman on duty. Patti Page (the ``Singing Rage'') has
a home here and she poses for pictures, sells her own brand of
maple syrup and tapes of her music.
</P>
<P>
   A light rain is falling as the bus leaves Boston at 8 a.m. _ the
quest for fall foliage has begun. Globus tour guide Jim Ayres, a
native of Canada, introduces bus driver Jerry Torp of Green Bay,
Wis. Ayres met most of the group the night before over wine and
cheese at a hotel reception. Both guide and driver are consummate
professionals, always sporting jackets, ties and smiles for
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   The passengers are quiet; perhaps it is the rain, or the
near-empty Boston streets.
</P>
<P>
   Ayres gives a warning for diabetics _ ``Don't forget to eat!'' _
and explains the rotation of seats once a day. Then he provides a
general idea of how things work.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an emergency washroom in the back _ the less we use it,
the better off everybody is,'' he says good humoredly. (There is
nothing wrong with this toilet, but luggage is piled in front of
the door. It does beat waiting in line at the rest stops.)
</P>
<P>
   My seatmate is Betty Reardon, a chipper woman who lives at a
Missouri retirement community. Betty is traveling with her
sister-in-law and her friend, who sit behind us and never exchange
a word with Betty on the bus. Betty's on her second bus tour but
she doesn't even pack a camera; she explains that her late husband
was the photographer in the family.
</P>
<P>
   Abe Claproth and Shawn Golden, in their 40s, are probably the
youngest couple on the bus. The Southern Californians are also
taking their second bus tour. Golden says that Claproth, a computer
designer for Xerox, needs to let go and relax _ ``and let someone
else drive.'' Claproth keeps his video camera always at the ready
and pans through the window. But it's evident that he is relaxing
later when he sleeps through Wiscasset, whose sign proclaims it
``the prettiest village in Maine.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayres gives fair warning that this first day is going to be a
tight schedule. We make some rest stops and photo stops in the
first few hours before arriving at Kennebunkport _ summer/fall home
of George and Barbara Bush. The closest we get is a drive by the
Bush family home (wave and watch for Secret Service agents).
</P>
<P>
   The Bushes have a beautiful home right on the water, but we have
only 40 minutes off the bus to discover Kennebunkport. (The next
day I meet a man from another bus tour who ran into Bush at the
Kennebunkport pharmacy. He says the former president shook hands
with all the tourists there.)
</P>
<P>
   The colors of Maine are the golds, reds, browns and oranges of
autumn. The canopy of leaves is like a bridge of color.
</P>
<P>
   When the sun finally makes an appearance at 11:30, we barely
notice. The colorful leaves have painted the gray day.
</P>
<P>
   Freeport is a one-hour and 15-minute stop. This is an outlet
store town, the biggest and most famous of which is the L.L. Bean
Store. Open 24 hours a day and 365 days a year, the store is packed
on this Sunday. Down the street is the outlet store where
discontinued and overstocked items are slightly reduced.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's in Maine sometimes offers lobster rolls for $5. I
find a delicious lunch with the help of a Freeport store clerk. She
directs me to the Chowder Express, a casual lunch counter where I
get a cup of seafood chowder ($4.50) and a vegetarian Syrian
roll-up ($3.95).
</P>
<P>
   Fortified, I do a little window shopping at the Bean store
before stepping back on the bus.
</P>
<P>
   That first day there are a lot of missed photo opportunities _
roadside fruit stands with pumpkins and local flea markets, signs
that proclaim ``Fresh Lobsters _ Packed to Travel.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
