<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1116 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FALL-LEAVES-2NDTAKE-H     08-19 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALL-LEAVES-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 BOSTON: x x x Packed to Travel.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   The former woolen mill town of Camden is a 30-minute stop and
there is an arts and crafts fair going on and a picturesque harbor.
Some of the passengers are grousing about the pit stops.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the bus reaches the Bar Harbor Lobster Bake at
Hull's Cove, all is forgiven as we dig into plates of fresh steamed
lobster, steamed mussels, corn on the cob and blueberry cake. The
placemats have instructions, and the dining staff is very helpful.
There's also steak and halibut for the non-lobster eaters.
</P>
<P>
   Keep eating like this, and I will be forced to jog behind the
bus.
</P>
<P>
   Bus tours are definitely not for those who don't like people,
all kinds of people. It is a land cruise. Two meals a day are
included, breakfast and dinner. Lunch is on your own and that's
usually when it is time for a little exploring.
</P>
<P>
   Hanover, N.H., home of Dartmouth College, tests my theory that
the best pizza is found in college towns. On a warm (high 60s),
sunny day as the students loll around the green campus, I stumble
upon The Brick 'n' Brew, where a single slice of veggie pizza is
$2.25 and a meal by itself.
</P>
<P>
   But lunchtime isn't the only time for exploring. On my own,
there is a chance to discover the walking path at Lake Placid. On a
stop at Lake George, I find the re-creation of Fort William Henry
(``Last of the Mohicans'') and watch the boats Mohican and
Minne-Ha-Ha depart for the lake excursion.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny public libraries in Lake Placid, N.Y., and Camden, Maine,
put out used books for sale, perfect for a bus traveler to browse.
</P>
<P>
   While some points of the tour are rushed, there is plenty of
time to explore the Norman Rockwell Museum in Stockbridge, Mass.,
and the Billings Farm near Woodstock, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Rockwell, the beloved artist whose work graced Saturday
Evening Post covers, is a favorite of many Americans regardless of
age. But the familiar images seem especially poignant to senior
citizens who best remember his photolike, detailed paintings.
</P>
<P>
   The museum houses the world's largest collection of original
works by Rockwell, along with changing exhibits of other
illustrators. There also is a film, the Rockwell studio from his
home and a museum store with prints, books, cards and gift items.
</P>
<P>
   At the Billings Farm &AMP; Museum, visitors discover what life was
like in an old-fashioned dairy farm. It was established in 1871 by
Frederick Billings, a Vermonter known for his work as a
conservationist and a pioneer in scientific farm management.
</P>
<P>
   At the working dairy farm you can tour the 1890 farm house,
watch workers milk the jerseys, pet the massive shire horses or
pick out a pumpkin. Sample some homemade ice cream, learn about
farm life in the 19th century or watch a docent bake a pie in a
cast-iron stove.
</P>
<P>
   At Fort Ticonderoga in New York, history buffs watch the
colorfully garbed historical re-enactors recall pre-Revolutionary
America and life in the Adirondacks.
</P>
<P>
   While no one can dare predict when the fall colors will peak,
early October is bursting with color.
</P>
<P>
   Bus driver Torp, who has spent weeks driving leaf peepers around
New England, says he has seen fall tours from green leaves to no
leaves. His favorite tour, says this seven-year veteran of driving,
is the Canadian Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors are drawn to New England for more than leaves. There
are fall festivals, special events, end-of-year sales and outlet
stores. A bus tour seems to be good way to ensure a room at the inn
at the end of a day of sightseeing.
</P>
<P>
   A leaf peeper's guide from New Hampshire's White Mountains
explains the many varieties of trees, from the quaking aspen that
turn yellow to the red of the Tupelos, the bright red of the
American Mountain ash to the purple of the sumacs.
</P>
<P>
   But you don't have to be a horticulturist to enjoy the changing
vistas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
