<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUM-DISEASE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS TAKING A CLOSER LOOK AT THE HEALTH OF PATIENTS' GUMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The next time you open up and say ``aaaaaah''
during a physical exam, don't be surprised if your doctor takes a
closer look at your gums.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physicians are becoming aware that (their patients) can't
really be healthy unless their mouth is healthy,'' said Dr. Reed
Ference, an Albany periodontist, a dentist who specializes in gum
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Research shows that the health of our mouths can have an impact
our overall health, and several new studies point to a link between
gum disease and heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are still trying to figure out the details of that
connection. But they believe the same bacteria that causes gum
disease may also trigger formation of the plaque that blocks or
hardens arteries.
</P>
<P>
   One study reported that people with periodontitis had a 25
percent greater risk of coronary heart disease than others.
</P>
<P>
   Gum disease has also been linked to bacterial pneumonia. And
another study shows that gum disease may increase a woman's risk of
having a low-weight baby because bacterial toxins released into the
bloodstream interfere with fetal development.
</P>
<P>
   If you're surprised that gum disease can have such far-reaching
consequences, you're not alone.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and dentists are also coming to terms with the fact that
their two professions are more closely linked than traditionally
thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were taught at the time that infections in the mouth don't
infect other areas of the body,'' Ference said.
</P>
<P>
   The mouth, however, has long had the reputation for harboring
hundreds of nasty bacteria. ``A human mouth is incredibly dirty,''
Ference said. ``You've probably heard that a human bite is worse
than a dog bite.''
</P>
<P>
   Gum disease is caused by plaque or bacteria that naturally
accumulate on the surface of teeth and gums. If we don't remove the
plaque with regular brushing and flossing, it will eventually
harden into tartar, and will, in time, erode healthy gum tissue and
lead to tooth and bone loss.
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms may include red, swollen or bleeding gums, loose teeth
and chronic bad breath.
</P>
<P>
   Though brushing and flossing is the best defense against plaque,
they don't guarantee protection against gum disease. There are
other risks, including smoking, a poor diet, chronic health
problems like diabetes, stress, and intimate contact with somebody
who has gum disease.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Radler, a Conrail conductor, doesn't know why or how he
got it, especially since he was always brushing his teeth, even at
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a disease,'' he said. ``You can drink orange juice and
still get a cold.''
</P>
<P>
   He blames a former dentist for not diagnosing the problem when
he first started getting minor infections in his mouth two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and sons used to kid me, you spend so much time
brushing and cleaning your teeth,'' said Radler, who lives in
Westerlo, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   But last fall, he ended up in the emergency room with an abscess
in his cheek. Radler, 48, decided to switch dentists and is today
undergoing periodontal treatment for the affected teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Radler isn't surprised by the research indicating a connection
between dental and overall health. When he first started getting
infections, he didn't feel well. ``Most of the time I felt like I
had no energy, headaches, sick to my stomach. You'd never think of
connecting it to your teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, after gum surgery and bone grafts, ``I feel a lot
better,'' he said. His heart, by the way, is fine.
</P>
<P>
   Ongoing research should tell reveal more about how the
body-mouth connection works, especially as it relates to heart
disease.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Ference hopes word will get out that regular
dental care is just as important as seeing a physician.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not just treating mouths, we're treating patients,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
