<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1122 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEART-STUDY-LIFEBEAT-     08-19 1863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-STUDY-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANDMARK HEART STUDY TURNS 50 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 Includes a 350-word sidebar on other long-term studies 
 By RICHARD A. MARINI 
 c.1998 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joseph Antonioli says he wasn't just happy when, in the early
1970s, he was asked to become a guinea pig in the Framingham Heart
Study. He was thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was, like, an honor to be asked,'' says the boyish high
school math teacher. He's sitting in the living room of the home he
shares with his ``significant other,'' Leah Heffron, in Framingham,
Mass., a town of 65,000 southwest of Boston. ``My parents were two
of the original participants in the study and I hope someday that
my three sons will be able to participate, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Antonioli's wish that his kids be poked and prodded, X-rayed and
ultrasounded once every four years says a lot about the
groundbreaking health study.
</P>
<P>
   The Framingham Heart Study, a part of the National Heart, Lung,
and Blood Institute, is the longest ongoing epidemiological study
in medical history, and perhaps the single most important. It's
certainly the most famous. Indeed, there's a good chance that even
someone who doesn't know his, er, aorta from his elbow may have
heard of it. Framingham, for example, was among the first studies
to confirm that high cholesterol, high blood pressure, and smoking
all cause heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Because this granddaddy of all epidemiological trials is
celebrating its 50th anniversary in September, we decided to visit
Framingham to see if the study that has taught us so much about
hardening of the arteries, hasn't, after half a century, developed
a bit of atherosclerosis itself.
</P>
<P>
   Antonioli was especially excited on the day we met. That's
because he was scheduled to undergo his quadrennial medical exam in
the Framingham clinic the following day. You see, Antonioli
recently turned 50. It was a sobering milestone for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was only 53 when he had his first stroke,'' Antonioli
explains. ``So I said to myself, 'Hey, I'd better do something.''
And so, for the first time in his life, he's eschewing hamburgers
and Twinkies for turkey sandwiches and apples. ``I'm almost to the
point where broccoli isn't so bad,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time Framingham has prompted such drastic
lifestyle changes. Prior to the study, many medical experts
believed that atherosclerosis was simply an inevitable side effect
of aging. ``The concept that you could modify your behavior to
avoid or even reverse this hardening certainly wasn't widely
accepted, and in some quarters was actually disparaged,'' says Dr.
William Kannel, former director of the study and professor of
medicine and public health at Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   Framingham dispelled these and other myths. And while it's still
called the Framingham Heart Study, investigators today also study
the causes of such illnesses as Alzheimer's disease, osteoporosis,
arthritis, eye disorders, kidney disease, even hearing defects.
</P>
<P>
   The study developed out of the fact that, following World War
II, cardiovascular disease was the nation's No. 1 killer,
accounting for half of all deaths. While small studies and
anecdotal evidence had suggested that some people _ cigarette
smokers, for example _ were more prone to developing the disease,
the U.S. Public Health Service decided to launch a large-scale
study to find out why.
</P>
<P>
   The initial participants (or ``cohort'') included 5,209 healthy
residents between 30 and 60 years old.
</P>
<P>
   To help ensure compliance, both husbands and wives were
enrolled. ``We figured the wives would nag their husbands to come
in to be tested,'' laughs Kannel, who joined the study in 1949.
That bit of New England pragmatism made Framingham one of the first
studies to include data on both men and women, and led to the
discovery that women tend to lag about 20 years behind men in
developing heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in 1971, the study enrolled Antonioli and 5,123 other
children of the original cohort (and their spouses) in a second
study. This ``offspring study'' gives Framingham two generations of
data _ an almost unprecedented achievement.
</P>
<P>
   On any given day, a half dozen or so of the cohort and offspring
are in the study's first-floor clinic, wearing hospital gowns and
shuttling from room to room filling out questionnaires and
undergoing medical tests. Offspring visits last about four hours,
twice as long as the original exams. Many of the original cohort
are too frail for the tests introduced in recent years, such as a
lung-function test that requires blowing hard into a thin tube for
10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the investigators go to great lengths to accommodate
their elderly charges. ``If they can't make it in, we'll go to
their homes, or to those living in nursing homes,'' says clinic
director Dr. Joanne Murabito.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to these and other outreach efforts, about 85 percent
make it in for their regular appointments. And those who miss one
are likely to show up the next time around. Most drug-company
studies figure on the same dropout rate after only two years.
</P>
<P>
   For both cohort and offspring, the benefits of participation are
obvious. Although they're not paid, every two to four years they
receive a medical checkup that consists of a complete blood workup,
bone scan, eye exam and other high-tech tests. It's all free and,
as part of the study's contract with the town, results are
forwarded to the participants' family doctors with their
permission.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've always been on the cutting edge,'' says Edward F.
Clinton, 46, an architect and, along with eight other siblings (two
of whom have since died in accidents), is a member of the offspring
study. ``The first time I ever heard the term 'ultrasound' was at
Framingham.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, perhaps the study's most curious finding is the lack of
effect that being in the study has had on the health of the
individual participants _if you look at statistics, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   For example, more than two-thirds of the original cohort, who
spent much of their lives as research subjects in a trial looking
at the causes of cardiovascular disease, have since died. The most
common cause of death? Cardiovascular disease, still the No. 1
cause of death overall in the entire U.S.
</P>
<P>
   And while the second generation of participants, like their
peers, have lower cholesterol rates, lower blood pressure and are
less likely to smoke, they're also fatter, on average, than their
parents _ just like their peers. In other words, having the study
here hasn't made Framingham a hotbed of healthy living.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's unrealistic to expect people to swim upstream
against their culture,'' Kannel says. ``Not only are people eating
more, we've also engineered physical activity out of our daily
lives. Today, people have to join a health club to get the kind of
exercise their grandparents used to get working on farms or doing
some other form of manual labor.''
</P>
<P>
   So is there another 50 years in Framingham's future? Study
director Dr. Daniel Levy, doesn't look quite that far down the
road. He does, however, have a 30-year plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent our first 50 years looking at environmental factors
such as diet and smoking and their effects on disease,'' he says.
``Now we're using molecular genetics to explore how genes are
responsible for high blood pressure, obesity, high cholesterol,
Alzheimer's, and so forth.''
</P>
<P>
   Levy is also spearheading the Omni Study, in which 500 members
of Framingham's minority communities have been enrolled. It is
designed to see if established risk factors affect minorities
differently than the original cohort and offspring.
</P>
<P>
   But the most far-reaching of Levy's plans is recruitment of a
third generation of participants _ the grandchildren of the
original cohort. This study _ the one Antonioli hopes his three
sons will be asked to join _ would put Framingham in the unique
position among studies of having three generations of data to
investigate.
</P>
<P>
   As for Joe Antonioli, we phoned him after his checkup. His
numbers weren't perfect, but things are headed in the right
direction. And a scan of his neck revealed a suspicious speck,
perhaps the first sign of some narrowing of the carotid artery.
While troubling, it was spotted early so his doctor can keep a
close eye on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm on the right track,'' Antonioli says. ``Today was
the last day of school. Last year I'd have celebrated with a big
steak, or maybe some hamburgers. This year, we're having chicken
stir-fry.''
</P>
<P>
   ----
 &UR; (Richard A. Marini is a San Antonio-based writer.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR
</P>
<P>
   Here are snapshots of some other important, large-scale clinical
trials:
</P>
<P>
   Nurses' Health Study
</P>
<P>
   Year started: 1976
</P>
<P>
   Study subjects: 121,700 female registered nurses.
</P>
<P>
   Purpose: Examine the link in women between hormones, diet,
exercise, and other life-style factors and a wide range of chronic
illnesses, including breast cancer, heart disease and diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Major findings (so far): Postmenopausal hormone replacement
appears to decrease the risk of heart disease and all-cause
mortality, but may increase breast-cancer risk.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Physicians' Health Study
</P>
<P>
   Year started: 1982
</P>
<P>
   Study subjects: 22,071 male physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Purpose: Study the effects of low-dose aspirin on heart attack
and of beta carotene supplements on cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Major findings (so far): Low-dose aspirin reduces risk of heart
attack; beta carotene supplements neither reduce nor increase risks
of cancer and heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Cardiovascular Health Study
</P>
<P>
   Year started: 1989
</P>
<P>
   Study subjects: 5,888 men and women 65 years of age and older.
</P>
<P>
   Purpose: Investigate the similarities and differences in risk
factors for cardiovascular disease between older individuals and
those in middle age.
</P>
<P>
   Major findings (so far): Many older adults have unrecognized
cardiovascular disease, which may not cause obvious symptoms but
does affect life span.
</P>
<P>
   Women's Health Study
</P>
<P>
   Year started: 1992
</P>
<P>
   Study subjects: 40,000 post-menopausal female nurses.
</P>
<P>
   Purpose: Examine the effects of low-dose aspirin and vitamin E
supplementation on heart disease and cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Major findings (so far): None to date.
</P>
<P>
   Women's Health Initiative
</P>
<P>
   Year started: 1993
</P>
<P>
   Study subjects: 164,500 post-menopausal women.
</P>
<P>
   Purpose: Study the causes and prevention of cardiovascular
disease, breast and colorectal cancer, and osteoporosis based on
such variables as diet, hormone replacement, calcium/vitamin D
intake and lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Major findings (so far): None to date.
</P>
</TEXT>
