<SLUG> BC-MEASURE-YOUR-FITNESS-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU MAY BE LESS FIT THAN YOU THINK
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 Color slide of the new FitnessAge fitness-assessment product is
available. Will be mailed to LifeBeat subscribers on Aug. 18. 
 (EDS.: Fashn Inc. is cq.) 
 By KEN McALPINE 
 c.1998 
 North American rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ask someone for a frank assessment of his fitness and you're
likely to hear something like: ``I may not look like I did in high
school but I'm certainly not as fat as Joe Dorf down the street.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if you're diligent about exercise, working out
regularly with great gusto, you may not be as fit as you think.
</P>
<P>
   Recently I sat in the office of Dr. Larry Golding while he
explained science's concept of fitness. An exercise physiologist,
the 72-year-old Golding is one of the most respected names in the
fitness field, holder of just about every honorarium imaginable,
including a distinguished professorship at the University of Nevada
Las Vegas where he teaches and does research.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have to realize that there are really three different
kinds of fitness _ flexibility, aerobic conditioning and
strength,'' said Golding. ``A lot of people lift weights and they
say, `Well I'm fit'. They're not fit. They're very fit in a limited
way. So you play tennis? Well that's better than not doing
anything. But there are studies that show that sports don't give
you much fitness and sometimes no fitness at all. Which is why
there isn't a serious athlete in the world that plays his sport to
get fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Golding paused for his conclusion: ``There are plenty of people
out there who think they are pretty fit. But I do think there is
some delusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Voy was more blunt. Voy now has a family and sports
medicine practice just down the road from Golding's office. But for
years he has been involved with some the world's greatest athletes,
including a stint as chief medical officer for the U.S. Olympic
Committee, which is how he came to oversee world class athletes in
40 sports.
</P>
<P>
   The white-smocked Voy folded his hands on his desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Athletes in various sports think they're in great shape. It's
interesting to note that they're not.''
</P>
<P>
   How fit are you really? At first glance the question might seem
strictly an exercise in vanity. It's not. Certainly your health,
genes and good fortune factor into how long and how well you will
live; no amount of pushups will stave off certain cancers or an
onrushing Peterbilt. But fitness is critical to your daily well
being and longevity too.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 the surgeon general issued a report that, possibly
because of its complexity and size (275 pages), was largely ignored
by the public. But the report's conclusions _ based on proven
research by the country's most respected fitness minds _ were
understandable enough. Inactivity, concluded the report, kills
about 250,000 American each year.
</P>
<P>
   Since you're reading this, this statistic obviously doesn't
include you. And since you are still conscious, your brain is
already unrolling a worn carpet of thought. I'm alive and kicking.
Why, I may even be young. Fitness testing is for middle-aged lardos
like Joe Dorf.
</P>
<P>
   Golding, of course, has heard this before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I once had a professor who would say in lectures that we start
to dodder at about 26,'' he said. ``People would sit up and say,
`I'm 30. You mean I'm middle-aged?' Well, yes. Physiologically you
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Why should you test your fitness? Well it just might provide a
wake up call.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why I came to Las Vegas. I had received a call from
someone at Fashn Inc. The company, she claimed, had developed a
fitness test that was clear and simple. It would be packaged as a
CD Rom. You popped the disk into your home computer, performed a
few fitness tests, then punched in the results of your tests. The
program mulled them over, and, presto, in a matter of seconds you
received your true fitness age. The CD Rom was dubbed FitnessAge,
and the company would soon be selling it to the public for $70.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I was skeptical. Fitness has its legitimate
practitioners, but it also is home to more quacks than a duck
flyway. But the idea of a simple, objective fitness measure was
appealing. Better still, Golding and Voy had lent their names and
their expertise to the product, nit picking the fitness details to
make sure the FAShN folks got it right. (Both consulted on the
CD-Rom, receiving only expenses).
</P>
<P>
   And so I sat in FAShN's tidy offices listening to Steve Brazell,
the company's creative and marketing director, explain what
FitnessAge would do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program tells you simply how old you are,'' explained
Steve Brazell, Fashn's creative and marketing director. ``Your
chronological age doesn't matter. It's how old your body is.''
</P>
<P>
   The software behind these calculations was complex, said
Brazell. But what the user ended up with was brutally clear. You
might be 38 by the calendar, but your fitness age might allow you
to collect social security.
</P>
<P>
   Seated in front of a computer, Brazell marched me through a
sample, a 57-year-old man who had performed the 3-minute step test,
pushups, sit-ups and waist and hip measurements the program
required to calculate one's age. Along with the ability to crunch
these facts, FitnessAge also contained some other innovative aids,
among them a library that explained fitness terms, outlined the
risk factors of inactivity (``Not exercising is worse for your
health than smoking'') and offered exercise prescriptions to
implement a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Brazell clicked the mouse and the anonymous guinea pig's results
flashed up on the screen. At 57, he had the cardiovascular fitness
of a 79-year-old, the strength of a 49-year-old, the flexibility of
a 35-year-old and the body composition of a 56-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   We may have been looking at one of Golding's delusional souls;
someone who went to the gym three days a week to lift weights and
stretch, and so considered himself in fine shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoa,'' said Brazell, eyeballing the gent's heart and lung
tally. ``This guy's in big trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   I might have made light of his failings, but I was up next.
Brazell punched in my particulars, height, weight, resting heart
rate and age. Then while Brazell and some coworkers watched, I
marched through the FitnessAge tests. The procedure took 30
minutes, and it might have taken less time, had the three of them
not had such a jolly good time mocking my weaknesses, specifically
my flexibility which fell somewhere between stone and tungsten.
This made sense since, though I workout regularly, I never stretch.
</P>
<P>
   When I finished Brazell entered the numbers and clicked the
mouse. At 38, my fitness age was 26, which will be a source of some
pride as soon as I can bend over to tie my shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Having an objective measure of your fitness, said Golding, is
certainly important as both a stick and a carrot. It can let you
know how far you've fallen and, assuming that lights a fire under
you, follow-up fitness tests at regular intervals can provide
wonderful incentive by showcasing your tremendous improvements.
</P>
<P>
   But owning up to delusion is just a step, said Golding, and it's
certainly not the most important one.
</P>
<P>
   Golding smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to have the desire to begin with.''
</P>
<P>
   ---------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ken McAlpine is a free-lance writer based in Ventura, Calif.) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
