<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 12:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1128 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-BATTLES-LIFEBE     08-19 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-BATTLES-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHICH PARENT-KID BATTLES ARE WORTH FIGHTING? 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By AVA L. SIEGLER 
 c.1998 Child magazine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kids don't come into the world with good judgment, good manners
or even good sense. A large part of your job as a parent is finding
ways to get your kids to want to do what they should be doing.
</P>
<P>
   You could easily spend every waking moment engaged in a battle
to get your child to do the right thing. That's why it's so
important to learn to pick your battles.
</P>
<P>
   But how can you decide when an issue is worth fighting over? Or
when you need to take hold of something or not?
</P>
<P>
   To preserve good times, try to organize the behavioral traffic
in your family before you act. Is your child's behavior (digging in
the garden) acceptable?
</P>
<P>
   In this green-light area, no battle is needed. Or is your
child's behavior (running into the street) unacceptable? Then
you're in a red-light area, and it's important.
</P>
<P>
   But most parent-child problems occur in the yellow-light area,
where you're not sure whether the behavior (such as jumping on the
bed) is worth fighting over.
</P>
<P>
   What battles are you most likely to encounter? What
developmental issues are revealed by them? And how can you manage
the fights you choose? Let's examine each age by age:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1 1/2 to 3 years &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Toddlers seem willing to engage endlessly in struggles over the
smallest things (``I don't want a broken pretzel; I want a whole
one''). But your toddler is not just contrary. She's trying to
develop an independent sense, and one way she does this testing her
strength against yours.
</P>
<P>
   You're still the boss, and she's at your mercy; by challenging
your authority she builds her own (``Mommy gave me a different
pretzel!'').
</P>
<P>
   Also, your child's recent mastery of mobility can lead her to do
things that may be out-of-bounds, like floating her rubber duckie
in the toilet.
</P>
<P>
   This means that your no is constantly being challenged by her
wish to go. Because judgment has not caught up with her desire, her
behavior can be unreasonable.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to communicate red-light areas clearly. If you
take things as they come, you'll battle all day long. Instead, take
every opportunity to help your child internalize rules by
verbalizing them as you go along (``We always hold hands when we
cross the street.'')
</P>
<P>
   The most worthwhile battles involve safety and security
(``Two-year-olds can't cut their apples with knives.'')
</P>
<P>
   Try to sidestep other issues, particularly on food or clothing.
These can provoke a toddler because they're ones in which you still
exercise much control.
</P>
<P>
   When you pick battles, you want to be able to resolve them, and
a stubborn toddler can defeat all your efforts (force-feeding is a
setup for disaster).
</P>
<P>
   Remember, too, that your toddler's mischief is often motivated
by curiosity. You may feel she is impossible when you find your
pantyhose on the floor, but to her, it's just exploring.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 3 to 6 years &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Your pre-schooler is gaining control over his own body. His
insistence on self-reliance can cause many battles, since a child
this age is often trying to push you away - yet still needs help
(``I can tie my shoes, Daddy'').
</P>
<P>
   As your pre-schooler goes into the world, he also becomes more
aware of vulnerability. This realization causes his behavior to
alternate between clinging and defiance.
</P>
<P>
   Battles at this age are most likely to be over bedtime
(pre-schoolers hate exclusion from grownup activities) and bodily
care (when he was younger, his body was under your control; now
he's struggling to bring it under his).
</P>
<P>
   Because children this age alternate between progressive and
regressive, one moment your child may want to sleep outside in a
tent, and the next may want you to wipe his tushy!
</P>
<P>
   To help your child integrate his wishes with his growing skills,
be sure to praise his accomplishments and try to avoid battles that
deflate his pride (criticizing the mess he made in the kitchen
instead of the good job he did mixing cookie dough).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 6 to 10 years &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By this age, your child has a firm sense of an independent self
and has learned many skills that will help her take care of
herself. Now she must leave the purely ``play days'' of early
childhood and move into the world.
</P>
<P>
   This shift is reflected in battles over homework, TV, and
chores, all characteristic of grade-schoolers. Since these are
years when your child will be learning habits for a lifetime,
battles are worthwhile, but you'll need to find a way to help your
child cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   This is a good time to encourage your grade-schooler to create a
study and chore routine (working at her desk with a comfortable
chair before dinner, then set the table).
</P>
<P>
   Children this age may still need you to remind them that it's
time for homework, but this doesn't mean yelling about
irresponsibility (``I can't believe it's 8 o'clock and you haven't
even begun to study your spelling words!'').
</P>
<P>
   By age 9 or 10, if she forgets to study for a test she'll need
to suffer the consequences and learn from them. Engaging in battles
with a school-age child or rescuing her at the last minute
interferes with her ability to learn.
</P>
<P>
   Also, try to avoid battles about friends, interests, or TV
choices (unless unsuitable). Kids this age are beginning to define
their own tastes, and your criticism can interfere with their
burgeoning self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 10 to 12 years &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Your pre-teen may seem to be revisiting his toddler years,
provoking the same kind of encounters that you remember from when
he was 2! But pre-teens bring a new level of risk and danger to the
battleground.
</P>
<P>
   When a 2-year-old refuses to eat, his favorite strawberries can
tempt him, but when an 11-year-old does so, a possible eating
disorder looms.
</P>
<P>
   When a 3-year-old ``runs away'' after an argument, he may hide
under the bed, but with a 12-year-old, he could be out all night.
This means that, more than ever, it's important to pick battles
carefully.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them are apt to be about your pre-teen's wish for more
freedom (``Why can't I ride my bike to Joe's house?''). You need to
engage in these battles because they offer a chance to emphasize
that with freedom comes responsibility (``It's five miles away. If
I let you ride alone, you'll have to call me when you get there'').
</P>
<P>
   While reasoned discussion is always better than arguing, when
reason doesn't work you'll need to stand firm. Pre-teens may ask
for a lot of liberties, but they still need restraints. Even if
they protest, limits help them feel cared for. Blaming you for
curfews lets them remain ``cool'' with their friends.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid picking battles over his friends (criticism increases his
loyalty), clothing, or music he listens to. Save energy for things
that really matter, like smoking and drinking.
</P>
<P>
   By picking battles carefully and matching them to your child's
developmental needs, you'll be able to keep your connection to him
as he grows.
</P>
<P>
   -------
 &UR; (Ava Siegler is a child psychologist and author of ``The Essential
Guide to the New Adolesence.'') &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
