<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT ELVIS CROONS MORE TALL TALES 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A friend said to me: ``You're not satisfied? For
a president to go on TV, grovel, confess to adultery, that's not an
apology?''
</P>
<P>
   My friend also asked what was wrong with what the president did
with Monica Lewinsky. Didn't that kind of stuff always go on in the
White House?
</P>
<P>
   This is a version of an argument my mother always answered with,
``Just because all the kids do it, that doesn't make it right.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't know. Maybe I'm angry at Clinton because my family is
from New England, and we have a higher standard of hypocrisy. (As
such, I admit that I resent Clinton for contributing further to the
ruination of Martha's Vineyard, which was a peaceful place in the
'50s and '60s, with discreet summer people who kept their adultery
and celebrity low profile.)
</P>
<P>
   Back to the point: Clinton is the only president I know who has
confessed to doing ``it,'' as in ``It was wrong,'' with a young
woman, one who isn't his wife, in the Oval Office. What's
irritating is that he didn't really confess. He said he ``had a
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky that was not appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton didn't really apologize either, except to say ``I must
take complete responsibility for all my actions,'' something he has
been avoiding for years. Still, he played word games like the
semantic grandmaster of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't even confess that he lied to the American people. He
spoke in fudge words, saying he ``misled'' people and left a
``false impression.'' He said his answers about his affair with
Monica Lewinsky were ``legally accurate'' but he did not
``volunteer information.''
</P>
<P>
   It was as if George Washington had been caught, ax in hand,
saying, ``I cannot leave a false impression, I had a relationship
with the cherry tree that was not appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, and if the tree had fallen without Ken Starr in the
forest, it wouldn't have made a sound.
</P>
<P>
   What a faker, this Clinton. Monday night he didn't even fake
groveling. His was the angry face of a spoiled child caught doing
what he'd always gotten away with. He didn't bite his lip in fake
contrition, as usual, but spent more than half of the speech
snapping at special prosecutor Ken Starr for ruining his life, his
family's life and, I suppose, his place in history.
</P>
<P>
   Never trust a president who worries about his place in history.
Never trust a man who can't think of the consequences when he's
attracted to an employee almost as young as his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Harry S. Truman, the master of plain speaking, said, ``The only
thing new in the world is the history you don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Truman had to deal with the death of FDR, the atom bomb, the
Marshall plan, the need to integrate the armed forces, the blockade
of Berlin and the airlift, the Korean War and a Douglas MacArthur
who wanted to invade China.
</P>
<P>
   Truman had history thrust upon him and he had to act without
regret. He said he made decisions and never looked back. He did the
right things as he saw them.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been a passive partner to history. He avoids
decisions. He does the right things according to polls. It's his
bad luck to live in uninteresting times for a chief executive, and
all-too interesting times for the Internet and the news media. It's
our bad luck to be inundated by horrible jokes and one-liners about
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The sign on Truman's desk famously said, ``The buck stops
here.'' Clinton should have had a sign on his desk in his own
language: ``The critical lapses in judgment and personal failures
for which I am solely and completely responsible stop here.''
</P>
<P>
   They didn't stop, though. Too bad they started. The randy old
buck's place in history stopped there.
</P>
<P>
   Barring major world crises in the next two years, Clinton's
place in history definitely won't be with Truman, who didn't care
about his place in history.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the three recent presidents who were consumed by
visions of their place in history, John F. Kennedy, Lyndon B.
Johnson and Richard M. Nixon. So far, Clinton's place seems to be
with Kennedy's libido, Johnson's paranoia and Nixon's Checkers
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton should have named his dog Spot and brought it on TV. We
could have called the strange national event ``the out damned Spot
speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Damn, I'm tired of jokes and outrage about this, even my own. I
just feel so let down by this bum I voted for six years ago and
welcomed as the young Elvis who would lead us.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know whether this graying Elvis has another comeback in
him, or whether he's doomed to be a mall-walking joke.
</P>
<P>
   We're not mad at Clinton because he committed adultery. We're
mad because he lied to us, conned decent aides and supporters into
backing up his lies, and continues to play games about whether he
lied.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists argue about whether there is such a thing as sex
addiction, but that's irrelevant. We know there are compulsive
liars.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I'm being too hard on this man, who is a modern
politician, after all. Perhaps I should use Clinton's language, and
substitute ``misled'' for ``lied.''
</P>
<P>
   What we have here is a case of astoundingly arrogant
misleadership.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
