<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUBLE-DEVALUATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS BLASE ABOUT ECONOMIC MANEUVERING IN MOSCOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Boris Khodursky had just arrived in San
Francisco from Russia when he got the news: Russian President Boris
Yeltsin had devalued the ruble, slashing its value by one-third.
</P>
<P>
   The information was relayed by his son, Arkagy Khodursky, as the
men stopped in at a Russian bakery Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Khodursky was not pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who have the least amount of money will be hurt the
most,'' he said through his son, who has lived in the United States
for six years.
</P>
<P>
   He had no comment about Yeltsin, who devalued the ruble on
Monday, but the younger Khodursky was bluntly critical of the
Russian president, who insisted last week that he had no intention
of devaluing the currency to shore up the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeltsin is not very clever. He does things through trial and
error, and he makes many errors,'' Arkagy Khodursky said. ``He is a
typical Russian leader. Back through the time of the czars, they
are not well-educated, except for Lenin. They make decisions
emotionally. I hope this latest move on his part will work out.''
</P>
<P>
   The news about the ruble was just beginning to hit home in the
Outer Richmond District, where San Francisco's prominent Russian
community is clustered around Russian churches, delicatessens,
bakeries and bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   At Russian Books, proprietor Nina Sapelkin said her customers
were talking generally about tough times in their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   One of her customers, translator Irina Dyatlovskaya, said she
regularly shipped goods back to Russia to help relatives. Often,
she said, she sends books published in the United States that are
unavailable back home or that are cheaper for her to buy here.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the latest troubles could spark a new influx of
Russian immigration to the United States, Dyatlovskaya said
Washington wouldn't allow it. ``It's hard for Russian people to get
a visa to even travel here,'' she said. ``Not over there, but here.
The U.S. is afraid they will not go back.''
</P>
<P>
   Retired engineering consultant Alex Sapelkin said, ``I send
money. We all send money in U.S. dollars so they (relatives) can
open dollar accounts in banks.''
</P>
<P>
   In Russia, he said, ``There is barely enough to live. Right now,
there will be less. Everything is going up. Your salary of $200 a
month will now buy only $150.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will affect the government,'' he said.
``Russia doesn't have anybody to substitute for Yeltsin.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Jewish Community Center, where many former Soviet Jews
congregate, there is little talk about the ruble.
</P>
<P>
   Luke Howitt, a language coordinator at the center, said most of
the clients ``are too poor to care or know anything about the
ruble.''
</P>
<P>
   Howitt said his clients spoke ``about the disoriented way that
Yeltsin is leading the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, when Russia launched its free-market reforms, many
Russians have kept their savings in dollars to protect themselves
against inflation and fluctuations in the ruble. Russians keep the
brunt of their savings hidden at home.
</P>
<P>
   For businesses, devaluation did not appear to portend a panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole Russian devaluation doesn't matter a heck of a lot
for the U.S.,'' said economist Jacob S. Dreyer, a Russian
specialist and head of JDA International, a consulting firm in
Alexandria, Va. ``I don't want to be too coy about that, but it
doesn't amount to much more than a big traffic jam.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, U.S. companies exported $689 billion in goods and raw
materials. Of that, $3.4 billion went to Russia, according to the
Commerce Department. Only $4.3 billion of the $871 billion in
imported goods came from Russia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 1256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
