<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1165 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAMAICA-WHIZKID-$ADV2     08-19 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAMAICA-WHIZKID-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JAMAICAN GOVERNMENT LOOKS TO WHIZ KID IN DREADLOCKS TO GET
TOE-HOLD IN CYBERSPACE
 &HT;    With photos placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Aug. 23 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINGSTON, Jamaica _ He swoons over the Spice Girls. He mouths
off to his mother. He signs his name by drawing a smiley face --
flanked by dreadlocks.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this seemingly typical 13-year-old boy -- Makonnen David
Blake Hannah -- holds a lot of sway on this sunny Caribbean island
of 2.5 million people.
</P>
<P>
   As the government's new technology consultant, the fidgety
teenager has the ears of Jamaica's most-influential politicos, with
a direct line to the Ministry of Commerce and Technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want him to keep me abreast of new technology,'' said
Phillip Paulwell, Jamaica's Minister of Commerce and Technology.
``It is the young people who know about computers.''
</P>
<P>
   Paulwell, 36, began using computers three years ago. Hannah's
been honing his skills for 10.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister P.J. Patterson appointed Paulwell only last
January to head what was a newly created ministry on a
tourist-dependent island that's still, for the most part, a
technological wasteland.
</P>
<P>
   Globally, some 60 percent of all new jobs will require
technology-based skills by century's end, which doesn't bode well
for Jamaica, where only 35,000 to 40,000 people have logged on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Hannah, who relishes karate and fast Japanese cars, the
focus of his ever-changing site on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   He's been charged with advising the government on computer
hardware and software and visiting schools to talk to young people
about the advantages of using computers.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it makes him Jamaica's youngest-ever government
advisor, the one-year appointment doesn't seem to faze the worldly
youngster, who's visited several U.S. cities. His favorite? New
York and Orlando, by far. The best part may be the honorarium that
comes with it: a few dollars a week he'll use to go watch movies.
</P>
<P>
   The cocky, self-assured adolescent who collects National
Geographic magazines and reads science textbooks for fun taught
himself how to program computers and clean up viruses. He's also an
accomplished Web page designer. Yet he speaks of these skills with
the nonchalance of someone who's just mastered inline skates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can program a little bit, and I'm good at system design,
advanced Windows, DOS usage, stuff like that,'' said Hannah, with
saucer-like eyes and an easy laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Hannah was raised in the nice, solidly middle-class neighborhood
of Mona Heights, where streets have sidewalks, and neighbors might
include journalists and low-level politicians.
</P>
<P>
   An intermittent child actor, Hannah appeared on Nickelodeon a
few years ago in a segment that featured children from around the
world. For his part, Hannah showed viewers how much mildew had
accumulated on a coconut he'd left under his bed for a week.
</P>
<P>
   Hannah parlayed a handful of acting gigs into an invitation to
attend the Chicago Children's Film Festival in 1995, which is where
he met Paulwell, who came away duly impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just extremely intelligent and full of energy,'' Paulwell
said. ``He knows more about computers than perhaps anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike another homegrown celebrity, Jody-Anne Maxwell, 12, who
won the National Spelling Bee last May, Hannah is not a product of
Jamaica's public school system.
</P>
<P>
   Hannah's mother, novelist Barbara Blake, pulled her son out of
school at age five after a teacher scolded him with a smack on the
hand for questioning whether Jesus was really white.
</P>
<P>
   He's been home-schooled ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've taught him what's relevant, and computers are all we have
to save us from a very poor education system,'' said Blake, who was
introduced to computers by an American friend. ``We live in a
global community and the computer is the best way for children to
be able to connect to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake is a doting mother with strong opinions. She credits her
son's intelligence to six years of breastfeeding.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his mother, Hannah comes from a long line of
eccentric -- yet cerebral -- ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   His grandfather, Evon Blake, was a famous journalist who decades
ago launched a Newsweek-like magazine in the Caribbean called
Spotlight. He had a penchant for pipes and white, shark-skin suits,
and is credited with breaking the color barrier here in the 1940s
by jumping into a whites-only swimming pool at a posh hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always had Life and Ebony magazines around the house, and
my father used a pen as his weapon,'' Barbara Blake said. ``My
father always encouraged me to think, which is what I've always
tried to pass on to my child.''
</P>
<P>
   And she has.
</P>
<P>
   Her son's as preoccupied with computers as other teenage boys
might be with girls.
</P>
<P>
   But he hardly looks the part of government advisor.
</P>
<P>
   A talented soccer player, he wears an Adidas jogging suit and
dreadlocks that stretch the length of his arms -- his matted
tendrils have never been cut.
</P>
<P>
   The rope-like locks draw double-takes, but are actually a tenet
of his family's faith in the Rastafarian religion.
</P>
<P>
   Loosely based on Christianity, Rastafarianism stresses the
back-to-Africa teachings of Jamaican pan-Africanist Marcus Garvey
while advocating black unity. To believers, Ethiopia is like Eden.
</P>
<P>
   The most famous Rastafarian was reggae music star Bob Marley,
with whom Hannah shares a birthday on Feb. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his unconventional appearance, Hannah says he mixes
easily with government types.
</P>
<P>
   He e-mails Paulwell almost every day and meets with him once a
week face-to-face.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to know what is on the Internet,'' Hannah said.
``He's real cool so he's easy to work with.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent editorial in the daily newspaper here showed Paulwell
and Hannah in front of a computer playing Pac Man and sucking on
lollipops.
</P>
<P>
   But, according to Paulwell, Hannah's job is nothing to snicker
at.
</P>
<P>
   Technology has yet to gain a toe-hold in Jamaica, some 550 miles
south of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The island's future, Paulwell contends, rides on the knowledge
of the young. And that knowledge must be more technology-based.
</P>
<P>
   The precocious prodigy has his work cut out for him.
</P>
<P>
   Jamaica, like other less-developed islands, has been locked for
years out of the technology market because of high costs. A
computer with a 200 megahertz Intel Pentium processor that sells
for $520 in the United States would cost at least $1,200 in
Jamaica. With a per-capita income of about $1,500 a year, most
people here can't afford a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Jamaica's in the midst of an economic recession that's left one
in three people living in poverty and nearly half of all young men
aged 16 to 25 unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   The government's goal to put a computer in all of Jamaica's 997
public schools by the year 2000 is deceptively simple: many have
yet to install a phone line.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of our teachers have never even used computers before,''
said Jean Beaumont, who provides computer training to teachers.
``Some find them complicated, and others are just very afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, government officials warned that
date-recognition software -- a problem known as the ``millennium
bug'' -- won't be corrected before Jan. 1, 2000, and probably not
until the year 2004.
</P>
<P>
   But while his country struggles to gain some ground
technologically, working for Microsoft Inc. someday is what's
mostly on the mind of Hannah, who seems hungry for the trappings of
American mogulism.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dream would be to meet Bill Gates,'' Hannah said, turning
suddenly serious. ``The man has revolutionized the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
