<P>
   ECONOMY-COLUMN-RAMSEY (Undated) In February 1912, two months
before the sinking of the Titanic, the American Smelting and
Refining Co. closed its arsenic mill at Everett, Wash. Today the
same company, Asarco, is faced with an incriminating stain in the
city soil. At issue are both science and law, both of them
uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   By Bruce Ramsey. (story will move in the ``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-COLUMN (Undated) It's heartening to learn that Bill
Clinton is capable of embarrassment. At least, he says he is _ for
what little that's worth. He told us Monday night that he
``misled'' us and his family about his sexual relationship with
Monica Lewinsky out of ``a desire to protect myself from the
embarrassment of my own conduct.'' Was he embarrassed as well about
having persisted in a lie for seven months? He didn't say. It also
should put our minds at rest to learn Clinton never pressured
anyone to lie under oath. Of course, he's hardly a credible source
of information on that question. Or on any other question, for that
matter. How can we ever again believe anything this man says?Let's
face it: Bill Clinton is finished.
</P>
