<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-COLUMN-RAMSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARSENIC AND OLD EVERETT _ QUESTIONS OF SCIENCE AND LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In February 1912, two months before the sinking of the Titanic,
the American Smelting and Refining Co. closed its arsenic mill at
Everett. Today the same company, Asarco, is faced with an
incriminating stain in the city soil.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are both science and law, both of them uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   The science is the question of how much arsenic it takes to make
people sick. Since the 19th century, arsenic has been associated
with cancers of the testicles, skin and lung among smelter workers
who inhaled arsenic dust. But would children at play be at risk
from arsenic in the soil?
</P>
<P>
   Scientists don't know. ``There are no good studies that are
directly looking at harm from soils at these levels of exposure,''
says Jim W. White, toxicologist for the state's Department of
Health.
</P>
<P>
   White's department released a study in 1993 of people who grew
up near Asarco's Tacoma smelter. As kids they had inhaled the air
had played in the dirt. The study found no increase in cancers
decades later.
</P>
<P>
   The Everett site was covered with houses from the 1940s to the
1990s. There was no surge in cancers.
</P>
<P>
   But safety is more complicated than that. It depends on what
level of confidence you want. (The state would like the risk to be
one in a million). It depends on how much dirt you assume a child
eats per day. (The state assumes 200 milligrams.) It depends on
whether you assume arsenic is dangerous at trace amounts. (The
state assumes it is.)
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency, which had jurisdiction over
Asarco's Tacoma site, set the cleanup standard at 230 parts per
million or ppm. The state Department of Ecology's standard for an
industrial site is 200 ppm; for a residential site, 20 ppm. Its
model actually says 2 ppm, but natural dirt often has 20. Mary
Burg, Ecology's manager for toxics cleanup, says, ``We don't make
people clean up cleaner than nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Asarco first offered a cleanup to 230 ppm, then 100. The state
is holding out for 20. Which is appropriate? White, the state's
toxicologist, says his review of hundreds of articles on arsenic
suggests that ``20 is an appropriately protective level.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also a statewide standard applied to many other sites,
Burg says. ``What Asarco is asking us to do is to throw that out
the window, and go back to arguing every site.''
</P>
<P>
   Asarco hired consulting toxicologist Mary Beck, formerly of the
EPA. She says 20 ppm is based on a linear model that assumes any
amount above zero is bad. Humans need a bit of arsenic, she writes,
and that we get more of it from food than we'll ever get by licking
dirty fingers.
</P>
<P>
   I consulted a third toxicologist, Prof. David Eaton, director of
the University of Washington's Center for Ecogentics and
Environmental Health. He has ``substantial concern'' about arsenic
in soil at more than 1,000 ppm, and little concern at less than
200.
</P>
<P>
   Would he accept the company's offer of 100?
</P>
<P>
   ``I would,'' he said. ``I don't think the difference in the risk
between 20 and 100 is measurable.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference in cost is considerable. Asarco has spent $10
million in Everett and has done little more than buy 37 houses. On
the wall of its office there is a map of that arsenic stain. It is
brightly colored, with concentrations of above 1,000 ppm at the
plant site, then fades in concentric rings. ``To chase 20 parts per
million, you could keep going and going,'' says site manager Tom
Aldrich.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the legal issue. The 20-parts standard was set
under the Model Toxics Control Act, an initiative written by
environmentalists and passed by Washington voters in 1988. On July
30, Asarco challenged the law in Thurston County Superior Court. It
argues that to impose the standards of 1988 on actions taken in
1912 is ``fundamentally unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el1l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   That argument has been tried and lost. But that was before
Eastern Enterprises v. Apfel, which the U.S. Supreme Court handed
down June 15. In a 5-to-4 ruling, the high court struck down a law
that forced coal companies to pay health premiums for former
workers. The law, wrote Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, ``is unrelated
to any commitment that the employers made or to any injury they
caused,'' and ``operates retroactively, reaching back 30 to 50
years.''
</P>
<P>
   She and Justices Rehnquist, Scalia and Thomas called that a
taking of private property; Justice Kennedy saw it as a violation
of due process of law.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing the case in ``Toxics Law Reporter,'' law professor
Alfred Light called the ruling ``an implicit invitation'' to
challenge clean-up laws with retroactive liability.
</P>
<P>
   Asarco is offering Everett as a test case, arguing both the
science and the law. Its case, says Ecology's Burg, ``strikes at
the heart of the Model Toxics Act.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Ramsey is a reporter and columnist for the P-I. His e-mail
address is bruceramsey(at)seattle-pi.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 1314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1193 &Cx1f; tth-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      08-19 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY SHOULD WE EVER BELIEVE ANYTHING BILL CLINTON TELLS US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SOLVEIG TORVIK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's heartening to learn that Bill Clinton is capable of
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   At least, he says he is _ for what little that's worth.
</P>
<P>
   He told us Monday night that he ``misled'' us and his family
about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky out of ``a
desire to protect myself from the embarrassment of my own
conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Was he embarrassed as well about having persisted in a lie for
seven months? He didn't say.
</P>
<P>
   It also should put our minds at rest to learn Clinton never
pressured anyone to lie under oath. Of course, he's hardly a
credible source of information on that question. Or on any other
question, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   How can we ever again believe anything this man says?
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it: Bill Clinton is finished.
</P>
<P>
   He's demeaned the presidency and himself. He may hang on by his
fingernails and manage to complete his term, but he will not be
attending to the business we hired him to tackle.
</P>
<P>
   He's an exceedingly troublesome, high-maintenance,
low-productivity employee whose ongoing legal difficulties will
cost us, his employers, even more millions. Meanwhile, the
controversy over his behavior will further paralyze the government.
</P>
<P>
   Not once during his short, forced mea culpa Monday night did the
``s'' word ever cross Clinton' lips. The ``s'' word being shame.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no other word than shame to describe what Clinton's
base behavior has brought to the presidency and to the nation. It
has further lowered the public's respect for politicians and for
the country's political system. This is dangerous for our democracy
and harmful to the republic.
</P>
<P>
   In the past when Clinton has had to confess his transgressions
in public, he's been a perfect picture of contrition and humility.
He's a master manipulator, and he's had lots of experience in
manipulating people into giving him yet another chance.
</P>
<P>
   We should have seen what was coming: This was a man who smoked
marijuana but didn't inhale; one who avoided the draft but who
didn't really try to dodge it.
</P>
<P>
   These incidents telegraphed a pattern of convenient
compartmentalizing of bad behavior, of the hair-splitting and
evasion that has become the hallmark of his disappointing
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has all the earmarks of a man without a moral center.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night there was none of that calculated humility that has
served him so well in the past. There were excuses, however: He
didn't tell the truth about his behavior because he was trying to
protect his family. But the time to think of protecting his family
was before indulging himself with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Almost lost in the din of legalistic and political parsing of
the scandal are certain fundamental elements of this sordid chapter
of American history that need to stay front and center:
</P>
<P>
   First, we didn't elect Clinton to turn the Oval Office and its
precincts into a pornographic playroom.
</P>
<P>
   We have no right to expect perfection in presidents; Jesus
Christ is not standing for office. But where much is given, much is
expected. So we do have every right to expect a certain standard of
decent behavior from those we honor with leadership of the nation.
If presidents cannot be expected to comport themselves within the
basic bounds of decency and propriety, of whom can we ask it?
</P>
<P>
   Nor did we elect Clinton to gratify his sexual appetites with
the hired help _ however compliant.
</P>
<P>
   Monica Lewinsky may fit the archaic, pre-Sexual Revolution
definition of a loose woman, but there's no escaping the fact that
Clinton was the most powerful man on the planet and she was a
powerless intern as young as his own daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The country is littered with hapless ex-bosses who lost their
jobs over much less appalling sexual impropriety with subordinates.
Feminist blather about consensual sex to the contrary, Clinton had
the classic advantage of power in this calamitous conjugation of
two needy people. Even if Lewinsky threw herself at him, he,
supposedly, is the grown-up here.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a grown-up, however, what we have in the White House
is an admitted liar, a world-class hypocrite who pays lip service
to ``family values'' and a man of incredibly flawed judgment in
whom we have vested the awesome responsibility of commander in
chief of the world's sole superpower.
</P>
<P>
   But if this man cannot control himself, how can he be entrusted
with the immense power of the presidency?
</P>
<P>
   Clinton repeatedly has asked for our trust but repeatedly has
shown that he is to be neither trusted nor believed. His political
legacy is a long list of broken promises. In short, he is not a man
of his word.
</P>
<P>
   Who's going to take him seriously? He's become a smutty joke.
</P>
<P>
   How can a man thus crippled govern?
</P>
<P>
   The personal tragedy of Bill Clinton is that he's uniquely
gifted with talent for leadership but has shown himself unfit to
lead. His was a presidency of great promise, but he's thrown it
away.
</P>
<P>
   If he truly cares about his family, Clinton should seek
professional treatment.
</P>
<P>
   And if he truly cares about the nation, there's still one
honorable, redeeming thing left for Bill Clinton to do: resign.
</P>
<P>
   Solveig Torvik is a member of the P-I Editorial Board. E-mail:
solveigtorvik(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
