u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-HILLARY-BOS &LR;      08-19 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HILLARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBDUED HILLARY CLINTON SIGNALS A STEADY LOYALTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton is a politician who said, ``I
feel your pain.'' Tuesday, it was Hillary Rodham Clinton's pain
that was palpable.
</P>
<P>
   The usually ebullient first lady walked silently _ no waves or
smiles or small talk with her husband _ across the White House
South Lawn to a waiting helicopter. She clutched the left hand of
daughter Chelsea, who held onto the president with her right.
</P>
<P>
   As the Clintons left for a vacation on Martha's Vineyard, Marsha
Berry, the first lady's spokeswoman, stated the obvious when she
said, ``This is certainly not one of the best days of her life.''
President Clinton admitted to the nation Monday night that he had
an extramarital affair with former White House intern Monica S.
Lewinsky and had not told his wife the truth about it until last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lord knows what that conversation must have been like,'' said
Jane Moss, a professor of women's studies at Colby College and a
Wellesley College classmate of Mrs. Clinton's. ``She's got to be
hurt. &UR;  &LR; She has to be in great pain to have the entire universe know
her husband was fooling around with a 21-year-old in the White
House, right under her nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to admire Hillary's grace in these extraordinarily
hard times,'' Moss said. ``She's a woman of dignity in a Jerry
Springer world.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the country does admire Mrs. Clinton. Her approval
ratings in opinion polls have never been higher. She is somewhat
more popular among women than men, and recent polls have shown her
support growing among older, Republican women who initially were
cool to a feminist first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Some note that it took a very traditional role _ that of the
long-suffering spouse _ to get the public to embrace Mrs. Clinton,
who came to the White House in 1993 as a career woman and policy
wonk. Others recognize that the first lady has never been more
powerful than she is right now, with her husband's future
depending, in part, on whether his family can forgive him.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Mrs. Clinton called Berry to offer some reassuring
words, which were relayed to the staff and the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is committed to her marriage, and she loves her husband
and her daughter very much,'' Berry said. ``She believes in her
husband, and her love for him is compassionate and steadfast. She
is clearly uncomfortable with how her personal life has been made
so public.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry said Mrs. Clinton, a Methodist, also was relying on ``a
strong religious faith.'' The Rev. Jesse Jackson visited the White
House Sunday night, reportedly at the request of 18-year-old
Chelsea Clinton, to pray with Mrs. Clinton and her daughter for two
hours. Jackson later praised Mrs. Clinton for her strength and love
of her husband.
</P>
<P>
   To some, it seemed far-fetched that the savvy Mrs. Clinton was
the last to know what the majority of Americans, according to the
polls, already believed: that the president had committed adultery
with Lewinsky and was lying about it. ``She certainly was misled,''
Berry said. ``She learned the nature of his testimony over the
weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is, after all, history: In his January deposition in
the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit, the president admitted
he had sexual relations ``once'' with Gennifer Flowers, the woman
whose allegations about a 12-year affair nearly ended Clinton's
1992 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find Mrs. Clinton to be kind of an enabler in all of this,''
said Michael Cromartie, a senior fellow at the Ethics and Public
Policy Center, a private group. ``How many times will it take until
she says, `My status and career aren't as important as this man who
abuses my covenant relationship with him?' She's made a calculated
career bargain, and it doesn't square with the principles of her
feminism.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last seven months, Mrs. Clinton's calculations have been
focused mainly on deflecting allegations against her husband about
the Lewinsky investigation. In January, she emerged as the
president's staunchest defender, firmly denying that he had had an
affair and accusing independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr and a
``right-wing conspiracy'' of hounding her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on the ``Today'' show, Mrs. Clinton was asked
hypothetically if a president should resign if he committed
adultery and lied about it. ``If all that were proven true, I think
that would be a very serious offense,'' Mrs. Clinton said. ``That
is not going to be proven true.''
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer and political strategist, Mrs. Clinton was intimately
involved in preparations for her husband's testimony before Starr's
grand jury Monday, and White House aides say she had a hand in
making the president's televised confession as defiant as it was
contrite. Few doubt that she will continue to play a critical role
as the drama unfolds in the weeks and months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is politically ambitious, she is personally ambitious, she
has values she wants to advocate, and she has a continuing stake in
being seen positively,'' said Richard Winters, a professor of
government at Dartmouth College. ``I don't see these interests
being advanced by sinking back, being silent, and not standing by
her man.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Mrs. Clinton believe she has the political skills to
keep a stiff upper lip through what promises to be a difficult
period. But they also say they expect considerable private pain for
her while the president tries to ``reclaim my family life,'' as he
pledged Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Chambers, a former Democratic leader in the New Hampshire
Legislature, remembers when the Gennifer Flowers story broke during
the primary campaign in the state. Publicly, Mrs. Clinton was
poised; in private, she cried, Chambers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not cynical enough to think she does what she does to save
her career or his,'' Chambers said. ``I think she decided a long
time ago that sticking it out, for the sake of her husband and
daughter, was the wisest thing. It's what a lot of women do.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandy Grunwald, a political consultant and old friend of the
Clintons, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is one of the people who actually took the `for better or
worse' vow seriously, and boy, has she gotten both,'' Grunwald
said. ``I'm sure it's tough. It's corny, but she loves the guy. I'm
sure she was furious, but that doesn't mean she gives up on her
marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Brian McGrory of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
