r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAREER-BOOSTS-HNS &LR;      08-19 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREER-BOOSTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYEE STRENGTHS CAN TURN INTO WEAKNESSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The best skill you can ever have in any job is
the ability to read the handwriting on the wall. Unfortunately for
a lot of workers _ particularly seasoned ones _ the messages seem
to be written in invisible ink.
</P>
<P>
   We all know our strengths, or at least we think we do. But
sometimes the very things that helped us get to one level are
stopping us from moving ahead _ or even staying employed.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the main themes behind ``Jump-Start Your Career,''
a thought-provoking book by Lois Frankel, a Southern California
psychotherapist and consultant. The book, which used to be called
``Overcoming Your Strengths,'' offers several quizzes and case
studies that might open your eyes about why you have problems in
your current job or why you aren't moving up or getting hired the
way you should.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about the book is that it doesn't get into
psychobabble and the ``find the work you love'' theme, which have
been hammered to death, but instead brings up points that are easy
to overlook: things women tend to do more than men that weaken
their communication skills, how being a perfectionist can get you
in trouble, even that sometimes people can be too good looking for
their own good.
</P>
<P>
   My two cents: One big career mistake people often make is being
too comfortable. They find a job they're ready to hold for the rest
of their career in a seemingly stable company, so they stop doing
things like networking and paying attention to what's happening in
their industry.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does that make them less effective as employees, it
leaves them in a tough position if they get fired or the company
goes out of business. They are no longer up to date on industry
trends and they have a weak network, two huge obstacles to landing
another job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to remember that once you need a relationship,
it's too late to build it,'' Frankel writes. ``This is what makes
building relationships on an ongoing basis so important. It can't
be done simply for the purpose of knowing that you might have to
call on it at some time. It must be done because you value people
and your relationships with them.''
</P>
<P>
   She says workers need to understand the quid pro quo, offering a
favor in exchange for another favor. Business usually isn't done as
bluntly as that, she adds, but people are more likely to do favors
for those who have done favors for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without realizing it, we are exchanging things with people all
the time,'' she writes. ``Many relationships fail when the quid pro
quo isn't recognized or when it changes without the consent or
acknowledgment of one or both of the parties.''
</P>
<P>
   People often underestimate the importance of ``doorway
conversations'' in career success, Frankel says. They are so
concerned with doing their job to perfection that they don't
realize that a crucial part of it is working well with others,
gaining respect and support from colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   People often are misled about this, she adds, because employers
might hire them based on technical skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once on the job, however, when the playing field is level with
equally qualified employees, it is the more subtle behaviors that
differentiate the fast-trackers from those who remain stagnant.
Those with superior interpersonal skills, combined with technical
capability, are perceived as a more valuable asset than those who
exhibit only technical competence.''
</P>
<P>
   People who are particularly good looking can run into the same
kind of plateau, Frankel warns. In the book, she describes how she
told one salesman to tone down his looks because they were blocking
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``People didn't take him seriously,'' she writes. ``They
couldn't get past his looks. His colleagues tended to feel somewhat
inferior in his presence and sabotaged his efforts by withholding
essential information and upstaging him at sales conferences.''
</P>
<P>
   The way other people perceive you is crucial to your career,
Frankel says, and people often sabotage themselves through their
behavior. She says many women weaken their communication skills by
asking questions instead of making statements, or apologizing when
a misunderstanding has occurred even though it wasn't their fault.
</P>
<P>
   She gave the example of employees who want a day off. Many women
ask if they can have the day off, Frankel says, while men often
simply say they are taking the day off and expect the boss to speak
up if there is a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our society, we expect children to ask permission, not
adults,'' she writes. ``When women ask permission, they set
themselves up to hear `no.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
