<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SANCTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US `ARMS PROLIFERATION' IS BUSINESS AS USUAL IN RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In her tiny office at the end of a maze-like corridor
in a sprawling Moscow research institute, Ludmila Khromova hardly
resembles a threat to America's national security.
</P>
<P>
   But to the Clinton administration, Khromova, in her 40s, a
bespectacled physicist in a denim dress, personifies one of the
biggest dangers the United States faces: the proliferation of
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Washington considers INOR, the company of which Khromova is
president, to be the mother of all proliferation nightmares - a
financially strapped Russian defense enterprise that is selling its
technology to buyers with ready cash, no matter who those clients
are or what they plan to build.
</P>
<P>
   INOR was one of seven Russian enterprises hit with US sanctions
last month for allegedly selling sensitive weapons technology to
Iran, which is trying to develop ballistic missiles that can carry
nuclear warheads. INOR agreed last fall to supply Iran with special
metal alloys that the U.S. alleges could be used to make long-range
ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, just days after Iran tested a medium-range missile
capable of hitting Israel and US military installations in the
Middle East, President Clinton signed an executive order barring
INOR and six other entities from trading with American companies or
receiving US government assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that halting the proliferation of weapons of mass
destruction is ``one of the toughest security challenges we face''
and vowed to punish any other firms that spread sensitive weapons
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Khromova denies that her company did anything wrong. In an
interview at INOR's rented two-room office at the Chermet Research
Institute, Khromova acknowledged that she made a deal with an
Iranian partner. Although she refused to give details, Khromova
insisted that what she sold could not be used to make rockets. She
claimed that she had no idea why Iranians needed the alloys.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't tell me what they were making, and I didn't ask,''
Khromova said. She pointed to a stack of Russian newspapers on her
desk, opening one to a story about the US sanctions. ``I found out
more from these newspapers about what we are supposedly building in
Iran than I ever knew. To them I say, thanks for the
advertisement.''
</P>
<P>
   A small, private company formed amid the ruins of the old Soviet
defense industry after the breakup of the USSR, INOR is mired in a
deep financial crisis caused by clients who cannot pay for their
orders. Khromova said the biggest culprit is the Russian
government, which accounts for between 30 and 40 percent of INOR's
orders but never pays its debts. As a result, INOR, like many
Russian companies, has trouble paying its employees, most of whom
work at two production facilities located outside of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Khromova says that she does not troll for buyers. ``They usually
find us,'' she said. This was the case with her Iranian contacts.
</P>
<P>
   According to her, the deal did not violate Russia's existing
export laws. ``Under the law, these alloys are not forbidden,'' she
said. ``But if they say we cannot sell them, we won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Khromova is not sure what the US sanctions will mean to her
company. ``We don't have any contracts with Americans, we never
have, and we never will,'' she said. ``They'll probably forbid me
from going to the States. But that doesn't bother me. Our country
is no worse than yours.''
</P>
<P>
   A far more immediate problem for Khromova is the authorities in
her own country. Russian law enforcement agencies notified her
recently that INOR and eight other companies are under
investigation for possible violations of Russian export laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government announced last month, prior to the US
sanctions against seven of the enterprises, and on the eve of a
visit to Moscow by Vice President Gore, that it would press
criminal charges against any company found to have illegally sold
sensitive weapons technologies.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to INOR, the enteprises hit with sanctions include
two research institutes, Grafit and Polyus; Glavkosmos, a
state-owned company that sells space industry equipment abroad; the
Baltic State Technical University in St. Petersburg; and two
private companies, Europalace 2000 and MOSO, which allegedly tried
to ship Iran 22 tons of special steel that could be used to build
the body of a long-range rocket.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. and Israel have accused Russia of helping Iran develop
its nuclear weapons program by training students, providing missile
technology and building a nuclear power plant in southern Iran.
Russia and Iran deny the accusations and say the plant is for
civilian use.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government has denied helping Iran, and for a while
denied that any Russian companies were involved. That line changed
after Russian officials stopped the 22 tons of special steel at
Russia's border with Azerbaijan earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, President Boris Yeltsin has on several occasions
promised to crack down on exports of sensitive weaponry and
military known-how that violate non-proliferation agreements Russia
has signed. Last month, Yeltsin ordered his Cabinet to draft strict
new rules on exports of technologies which could be use for
military, as well as civilian, purposes.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, U.S. officials and Russian analysts have criticized
Russian laws and export procedures as ineffective in preventing
transactions of sensitive technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's sanctions, and the Russian government's moves to crack
down on illicit exports, may have taken some pressure off the White
House and removed one of the nagging issues of US-Russian relations
on the eve of Clinton's planned visit to Moscow in early September.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts in Moscow suggest that the Clinton administration has
decided to focus on individual companies, rather than the Russian
government as a whole, in exchange for Russian promises to work
more effectively to stop the sale of lethal technologies in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Congress, which in recent years has tended to be more suspicious
of Moscow's intentions than the White House, has pushed for broader
sanctions against Russia, which some on Capitol Hill believe is
actively involved in arming Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials privately express consternation with this
view. They say that official Moscow has no interest in arming its
traditional competitor in the Caucasus region with missiles that
could reach a large swath of southern Russia.
</P>
<P>
   But Khromova and other representatives of enterprises hit with
US sanctions said that their deals with Iran were made with the
full knowledge and acquiescence of the Russian government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our leaders are setting us up,'' said Nikolai Semyonov, head
of the foreign trade relations department of Glavkosmos. ``We
worked with the government, and got all our permission from them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
