<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGLICAN DECLARATION INCREASES PRESSURE ON GAYS, LESBIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Edouard Fontenot abandoned the religion of his birth _ the
Southern Baptist Convention _ for the Episcopal Church because he
believed it gave a warmer welcome to gay men like himself.
</P>
<P>
   So when news came out of England that the world's Anglican
bishops had voted to declare homosexuality ``incompatible with
Scripture,'' Fontenot felt slapped. The Episcopal Church is the
American branch of Anglicanism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's incredibly hurtful to get these vicious
missives,'' said Fontenot, who lives in Boston with his partner,
Christopher Bellonci. Fontenot and Bellonci were ``united'' in a
blessing ceremony last year at St. John the Evangelist Episcopal
Church.
</P>
<P>
   The Anglican resolution, which also opposed ordaining
homosexuals or performing same-sex commitment services, was passed
by the bishops last week at their once-a-decade conclave. It is not
binding, because each of Anglicanism's 37 provinces are run
autonomously. But people like Fontenot, a doctoral candidate in
theology and psychology at Boston University, and other advocates
of gay rights, say the bishops' proclamation sends out an ugly
message.
</P>
<P>
   These are difficult days for gays and lesbians and their
supporters. They are coming under increasing pressure from
religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week the highest court of the United Methodist
Church, the nation's second-largest Protestant denomination, ruled
that Methodists who bless the union of same-sex couples could face
discipline as harsh as removal from ministry and expulsion from the
church.
</P>
<P>
   A liberal Methodist caucus supporting gay rights, the
Reconciling Congregation Program, immediately issued an angry
statement lashing out against the church's ``deplorable and
theologically unsound'' declaration.
</P>
<P>
   And several conservative groups allied with the Christian right
have run advertisements denouncing homosexuailty and declaring that
gays and lesbians can be ``converted'' to heterosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Christians say they are reacting to what they
describe as a aggressive gay rights movement that is undermining
family values and threatening fundamental Biblical tenets.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side liberals respond that conservative believers
are hiding behind the Bible to justify homophobia in the same way
Scripture was used _ and still is _ in some Christian denominations
to prevent women from becoming ministers.
</P>
<P>
   The Lambeth Conference, as the gathering of Anglican bishops is
called, also highlighted a geographical divide on controversial
moral issues. That divide will likely become wider as Christianity
spreads across the developing world.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the bishops supporting a strict response to gay concerns
were from Africa and Asia, places where Anglicanism is growing
rapidly, in contrast to England and North America, where the number
of members has declined.
</P>
<P>
   Some liberal bishops and gay advocates complained that prelates
from the developing world were lobbied hard by conservative
American and English bishops working to gain ideological allies.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it has become increasingly clear that not just within
Angicanism but within many Christian denominations there is
widespread resistance to what many in Latin America, Asia and
Africa perceive to be a left-leaning American Protestant Christian
establishment. And, it is apparent that neither side on the
homosexual issue or on the wider issue of Biblical authority, plans
on yielding its position.
</P>
<P>
   After the Anglican leaders voted on the resolution on
homosexuality, 146 of the 750 bishops at Lambeth signed an open
letter to gay and lesbian Angicans apologizing ``for any sense of
rejection.'' The letter was signed by Bishop M. Thomas Shaw, leader
of the Diocese of Massachusetts, the Right Rev. Barbara C. Harris,
suffragan bishop for the diocese, and five other Epsicopal bishops
from New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our deep concern that you not feel abandoned by your
church and that you know of our continued respect and support,''
the letter read.
</P>
<P>
   For his part Fontenot, like many gay and lesbian Episcopalians
in the area, say he feels largely welcomed in this diocese. ``I was
forced out of my family's religion and I've made a stand not to be
forced out again,'' he said. ``I'm going to continue to take a
stand and make sure my understanding of the Gospel is
articulated.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Religion Notes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Pope John Paul II is taking the Roman Catholic message to space
_ cyberspace that is. Starting Aug. 15, which Catholics celebrate
as the Feast of the Assumption, World Wide Web surfers began
hearing his teachings live via a new website: http://www.vatica.va.
</P>
<P>
   There people will be able to hear and see John Paul recite his
Angelus prayers on Sundays, conduct his general audience on
Wednesday and follow his pilgrimages across the globe.
</P>
<P>
   _Is there a link between being religious and blood pressure?
That's what some researchers at Duke University believe.
</P>
<P>
   Elderly people who study the Bible, attend religious services or
pray on a weekly basis were 40 percent less likely to have high
blood pressure than those who did not take part in similar
religious activites, researchers found.
</P>
<P>
   While not entirely sure why active religious participation
lowers blood pressure, some researchers believe faith and religious
involvement provides a support system that helps people deal with
stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sense of meaning and kind of comfort that religious
beliefs provide make them more resistant to stresses both physical
and social,'' Linda George, another co-author of the Duke Study,
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   _Reader Feedback: Several readers took issue with a column
featuring a new book by Roger LeBlanc, ``Relativism as Religion:
Tracing Its Historical Roots to the Modern Day Crisis,'' which
addresses the question of papal authority. ``Mr. LeBlanc's views
must disturb not only the very Roman Catholics he excoriates,''
writes the Rev. Robert A. Mackie, interim pastor of Mystic Side
Congregational Church in Everett, Mass., ``but most certainly must
and does offend non-Roman Catholics, both of whom, of late, have
had to put their tolerance and patience with the extravagances of
the current Pope into overdrive.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
