<HEADER>
A1208 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-GROOVE-BOS &LR;      08-19 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-GROOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN GET STELLA'S GROOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURA YUEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The whoops in the movie theater audience first broke out when a
tank-topped Winston Shakespeare, a man with sculpted body and
disarming eyes, appeared on screen. At a first-weekend showing of
``How Stella Got Her Groove Back,'' the 20-year-old Jamaican
character created a buzz among women of all ages, not excluding the
motherly and grandmotherly.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the shower scene, in which 40-year-old Stella couldn't
resist joining her young paramour after seeing him lather up alone.
Still later, female roars virtually erupted during a love scene in
which Stella, played by the striking Angela Bassett, 40 herself,
wore a speechless face of painful exhilaration.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a sensitive beau half her age, Stella got her groove
back, again and again and again.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing wrong with it,'' Cambridge moviegoer Mary
Washington, 45, said of the film's pairing of an older woman and
younger man. ``It's great _ I'm looking for one. Can you print
that? Mary Washington ...''
</P>
<P>
   Much to audience delight, the movie, released Friday, reverses
Hollywood's trend of matching older men with younger women. In a
time when Warren Beatty, Robert Redford, and Jack Nicholson _
nearly senior citizens _ can play strapping men who win the hearts
of attractive women in their 20s and 30s, this film may be the
first to seriously buck outdated social mores concerning age and
gender. According to the movie patrons hollering their approval,
it's about time.
</P>
<P>
   For a year, there's been plenty of the opposite phenomenon. In
``Bulworth,'' there was Warren Beatty, 61, playing leading love to
Halle Berry, 31; in ``Six Days, Seven Nights,'' it was Harrison
Ford, 56, and Anne Heche, 29; in ``The Horse Whisperer,'' Robert
Redford, 61, and Kristen Scott Thomas, 38; and in ``As Good as It
Gets,'' Jack Nicholson, 61, and Helen Hunt, 35.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's horrible,'' Gail Hardenbergh, a couples therapist from
Sudbury, said of the bias. ``That's a male producer's fantasy,
there's no doubt in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Terry McMillan book-turned-movie, the struggle between
Stella and Winston, played by newcomer Taye Diggs, is central to
the story line. How do two people, bonded by love yet disparate in
age, reconcile their differences in maturity and experiences? And
how do they face the double standard employed by friends who
wouldn't even flinch if the ages were reversed?
</P>
<P>
   It may be just a movie, but ``Stella'' touches on a stigma many
older women face in real life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all breaks down to a discrimination of women _ more
importantly, the discrimination of women's sexuality,'' said Dishon
Mills, 22, whose wife, Afrika, is 2 years older. ``When a young man
engages in a lot of sexual activity, he's seen as someone who's
sowing his wild oats. When a woman does it, she's seen as a
whore.''
</P>
<P>
   But that stereotype is slowly fading as baby boomers age, said
Francesca Antognini, a psychologist at McLean Hospital in Belmont,
Mass. Baby boomers, often considered a well-educated generation,
are beginning to understand that women reach their sexual peak
later than men do _ around 35, compared with men, who hit their
peak in their late teens or early 20s.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you match a younger man with an older women, sexually it
can work quite well,'' Antognini said. ``There's more of a pairing
there.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, older men pursued younger women because of a
``biological imperative,'' Antognini explained. Whereas men can
remain sexually reproductive past their 70s, women can no longer
bear children after menopause. Middle-aged women thus fared
unfavorably when compared with younger women.
</P>
<P>
   But now, older women are countering that image, as they put a
greater emphasis on fitness, and more people acknowledge that women
can be sexually active as they grow older. In addition, women can
more easily establish their own identities through growing career
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Stella, for instance, is a career woman of corporate success,
not to mention a woman blessed with radiant beauty. That the
awestruck Winston should remark to Stella upon first meeting,
``I've never seen a 40-year-old woman that looks like you,'' shows
how a stereotype of middle-aged women can be turned on its head.
</P>
<P>
   But Stella also lapses into frustration with Winston, whose idea
of a good time includes a bowl of Cocoa Puffs and renting the
lowbrow ``Booty Call.'' Real-life Stellas and Winstons must grapple
with differences in both culture and development.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a huge gap in experience, growth, and needs,'' said
Kathryn Ford, 30, of Lexington. ``I think it would be hard for me
to cope with. If the man is 20, he's just out of the young adult
period, maybe graduating from college. At 40, you're done with your
first marriage, and maybe even have children. How are you going to
accommodate those differences in your relationship?''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Williams, 27, who saw the movie Saturday night, didn't
mention any glitches she has encountered in dating a 21-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got no problem with it, because I'm doing it myself,''
Williams said with a secretive smile.
</P>
<P>
   Care to share what it's like?
</P>
<P>
   ``Mmmm. You got to try it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
