<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER MEXICO, PATRIOTS ARE IN HARMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Memories have faded. Some have been lost altogether. Call it
selective amnesia.
</P>
<P>
   It has been several months since the Patriots were eliminated
from the playoffs by the Pittsburgh Steelers. When those around the
team are asked now about the finger-pointing that went on between
offense and defense after that 7-6 loss, the subject is treated as
a fabrication of the media or at least as something blown far out
of proportion.
</P>
<P>
   Things were said in the emotion of the moment, you are told.
They were gone from the players' minds shortly thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Moot.
</P>
<P>
   Lost memories.
</P>
<P>
   But if there was such a rift, then the Patriots' 21-3 exhibition
victory over Dallas in Mexico City Monday night before more than
106,000 screaming fans would have gone far in repairing it.
</P>
<P>
   All the defense ever has wanted is for the offense to take
advantage of its hard work. If the defense makes a strong stand,
pinning the opponent in its own territory, the message to the
offense is: Take advantage.
</P>
<P>
   And so that happened Monday night. There was a bonding, you
might say.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' first-unit defense, which allowed Dallas into New
England territory only once in the first half, had its finest
moment when it stuffed a fourth-and-inches from the Cowboy 39 in
the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Aikman handed off to Darryl ``Moose'' Johnston, who did his
darnedest to get through the line. Instead, he was thrown back for
a 2-yard loss when the front wall of the defense _ Chad Eaton and
Willie McGinest, in particular _ refused to yield.
</P>
<P>
   The expressions on the faces of the Patriots as they walked off
the field were exuberant, triumphant. It was almost as if they were
telling the offense: ``We've done our part, now you do yours.''
</P>
<P>
   One good deed inspired another, as the offense responded in
kind. Drew Bledsoe, who has struggled with the timing of the new
offense, was not about to let this defensive stand go unrewarded.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe directed the Patriots to a touchdown in six plays,
completing two passes and letting Sedrick Shaw do the rest. Shaw
gained 15 of the 39 yards, including a 9-yard touchdown run around
left end, getting sprung loose by a nice block from rookie tight
end Rod Rutledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just great to be able to make something of the great
play of the defense,'' said Bledsoe, who was 9 of 14 for 69 yards.
``The defense has played great in camp and all of last year and
it's time the offense start to live up to what we feel we can do.
When the offense puts up points after a great defensive stand, that
just gets everybody going. It means you're executing on both sides
of the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Eaton's brute strength in a tremendous rush up the middle
that made the play and allowed McGinest to make the last hit on
Johnston. And Eaton was the first defensive player to rush onto the
field after the score to congratulate the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton was immense in the middle of the line, while McGinest got
constant pressure on the quarterback and Ferric Collons was tough
against the run. Dallas didn't get into Patriots territory until 13
seconds remained in the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys up front did a tremendous job,'' said Ty Law, who
intercepted a Jason Garrett pass just before halftime and sprinted
26 yards for a touchdown. ``When they're getting that kind of rush
on, it makes it easier for everyone behind them. And when the
offense takes advantage like that, it provides us with a comfort
zone that we can make plays and the offense will put points on the
board.''
</P>
<P>
   Law spoke of past frustrations, how respect for the defense as a
unit still eludes them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows the Patriots as Drew Bledsoe, Terry Glenn, and
Curtis Martin,'' he said. ``We're playing in their shadows right
now. We're not getting the respect we deserve, but as long as we
get the respect of teammates and coaches, that's fine. Though we
would like to get the respect nationally as a great defense.''
</P>
<P>
   While good karma between the offense and defense has taken a
while to develop, Law said fingers never were pointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't point fingers because we're a team,'' said Law. ``We
know the offense is going through yet another system and that takes
time. I was talking to Michael Irvin before the game and he said it
took two years to get it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, of course, was a prime part of the Ernie Zampese offense
in Dallas. Now Irvin is learning a new system while Zampese is
teaching the old Dallas system in New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offense made progress tonight and that's what we wanted to
see,'' said Law.
</P>
<P>
   It was progress, but not midseason form.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the timing was much better,'' said Bledsoe, who did
miss a wide-open Shawn Jefferson and later Glenn for what would
have been touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not to the point where we're as good as we're going to be
in the regular season, but it's getting there slowly but surely.''
</P>
<P>
   In a perfect world, the Patriots would use Saturday's game
against Washington to get their act together and then treat the
Philadelphia game at Foxborough the following week as a dress
rehearsal for the season opener. But they still need to show
progress offensively.
</P>
<P>
   The defense, meanwhile, is just trying to perfect what it is
doing and slowly introduce blitz packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just picking up the offense until they get it
together,'' said Law, ``but when they score like that, that just
makes us want to play harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Law doesn't seem overly concerned about the right cornerback
position, which is being manned by Chris Canty, but warns,
``Regardless of who it is, we want to get it solidified. There's no
guarantee I can stay out there healthy for 16 games, so we need to
be strong there.''
</P>
<P>
   Law says the biggest difference he sees in the defense from last
year is McGinest, who is healthy again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a No. 1 draft pick,'' sais Law. ``He has that type of
talent and he's just playing so well right now. It's incredible
what he does for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
