</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'S DIMINISHED, BUT NOT DESTROYED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``At no time did I ask anyone to lie.''
</P>
<P>
   No, but he asked us to believe. Him.
</P>
<P>
   So the ``I never had sexual relations with that woman'' becomes
``while my answer was legally accurate'' that something sexual did
transpire, and ``it was not appropriate ... it was wrong ... a
lapse in judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornered at last before the grand jury by the four-year, $40
million posse whipped up by Kenneth Starr, President Clinton
finally owned up to ``a false impression'' he wove about his
involvement with Monica Lewinsky, and acknowledged he ``misled
people _ even my wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's many enemies rejoice. He is unmasked, yet again, in
the most embarrassing of postures, the presidential pantaloons down
around his ankles. Our No. 1 Citizen got caught with his drawers
down; authority embarrassed is authority diminished. His enemies
crow. His friends? They too are diminished. Only 30 percent of
Americans, by the time Clinton began his excruciating grand jury
testimony Tuesday, still believed his tortured claims of innocence.
Staffers and friends who tried to rally are let down as well.
</P>
<P>
   Bill, alas, is a trimmer. Has been from the word go. But his
shading of unpleasant truths, the wash-and-polish jobs, the spin,
the well-on-the-other-hand-you-could-look-at-it-this-way, the
lexicographical legerdemain with which he so adroitly carved his
path up from asphalt-sided shack in Hope to 1600 Pennsylvania
Avenue, had never landed him in the sheepdip as this one did.
</P>
<P>
   His evading the draft, his denial of the Gennifer Flowers
affair, the gyrations of Whitewater, all the petty scandals that
stuck to Bill and his train like the Golden Goose of nursery rhyme,
added to the legend of Slick Willie, the boy who got away with it.
He is a hoper and a groper, always was, and we knew it, certainly
by the time of his second election, though he never struck me as
being crooked about money, or the type to harass a woman who'd say
no.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton understood early that politics was a game won by
addition, not subtraction. As long as he could find a wider
audience to succumb to his eyelid-fluttering appeals, to be your
pal, your protector, your strong right arm, he could outweigh the
enemies with the new friends. But he eventually just ran out of new
audiences to conquer. He had to come back to the same old crowd on
this one. Like the Music Man in River City, the old salesman
couldn't hop on the train and ride to the next town; he was stuck
in this one.
</P>
<P>
   He may be a trimmer, some allies muttered, but he's our trimmer.
His enemies are our enemies. The people who oppose him are the same
people who oppose us; ergo, he's our guy. Who are you with in the
daily battles? Bill? Compared to whom? To Bush? Bob Dole, Newt
Gingrich, Trent Lott, Jesse Helms? Pat Buchanan, Orrin Hatch?
</P>
<P>
   Diminished but not destroyed is Clinton today. Impugned, but not
impeached. He'd be awfully hard to reelect, but he's not eligible
for reelection. He's got a year and a half to go, and not even
those nitwits in Congress think they can dump him out before his
lease expires.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nobody's business but ours,'' he says of his efforts to
win back the confidence of his wife and daughter after this ghastly
event. But the lying is everyone's business. ``Even presidents have
private lives,'' he shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   Would that it were true. But in the modern media environment,
nothing is private, sacred, or beyond traducing. The collateral
damage from the Clinton scandals will include future presidents,
and the Americans who will be less adequately led, because of the
culture of scandal the media cultivate.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents will be less safe and secure, because a Secret
Service guard can be blackmailed or intimidated or co-opted by an
aggressive prosecutor-on-the-make. There will be capable candidates
who will not risk the exposure of a campaign, because they, or
their spouse, or kids, or their brother-in-law, did something weak
or fallible or craven.
</P>
<P>
   The concentric circles prescribing just what is acceptable and
what is controversial in a politician's private life just got a lot
smaller, and the smaller those circles get, the more people they
rule out from consideration for leadership. Our presidents pick
thousands of job-holders. No president appointed women, blacks and
other minorities as much as Clinton did. That should be weighed in
the assessment of his untruths.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointed but not surprised by Clinton's priapic
predilections, I remain unconvinced by his enemies' arguments. This
was not a firing offense. One of the senators loudest in
threatening impeachment hails from a state where the Washington
Post counts 30,000 polygamists. Kenneth Starr's tactics and
political alliances put him squarely in the category of rogue
prosecutor. Starr gave a speech two years ago in Detroit raising
public questions about Clinton's ``spousal integrity.'' To me, that
was a fatal giveaway to the Whitewater prosecutor's intention to
get personal on the president.
</P>
<P>
   In sum, what Clinton did with Monica and afterword was, to go
alphabetically: asinine, bathetic, clumsy, deplorable, empty,
fatuous, gross, humiliating, injudicious, jerky, knuckleheaded,
lame, mendacious, naive, oleaginous, piggish, queasy, ridiculous,
stupid, tacky, unsalubrious, vexatious, weasely, xanthic-tinted
(yellow), yahoo-ish, and, ultimately, zany.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
