</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW LOOK FOR JADED UNION SQUARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO It is the boutique capital of the Pacific Rim, the
shopping destination of millions. Yet the retail district of San
Francisco surrounds one of the least lovely parks in America.
</P>
<P>
   Union Square, faded and jaded, is about to be rehabilitated. To
attract shoppers and visitors again, planners aim to discourage two
other urban groups: street people and skateboarders.
</P>
<P>
   Older than its Boston counterpart, Copley Square, the space has
been redesigned several times. Cities have discovered that market
rules of economics also apply to aesthetics: when most people avoid
urban spaces, others fill the vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   The 1960s version of Copley Square, praised by critics but
quickly deserted, became a hangout for the homeless and for
skateboard nation. In the 1990s, grass and trees replaced pavement,
making the space popular again.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the reverse is under way. Trees and shrubs are gone from
the site and soon, ``it will be 75 percent plaza and 25 percent
grass. It's 50-50 now,'' says Michael Fotheringham, one of two
landscape architects redesigning Union Square.
</P>
<P>
   Bounded by Powell, Post, Stockton and Geary Streets, the
2.6-acre square was a generous gift from Mayor John White Geary in
1850. Although the city plan of surveyor Jasper O'Farrell was only
three years old, San Francisco real estate was as hot in the Gold
Rush as it is now. The park was baptized in the Civil War when
orators railed against the Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   Towering above the square is a Spanish-American War monument to
Admiral George Dewey, hero of the battle of Manila Bay in 1898.
Celebrating an American military victory may offend this city's
politics, but because the column survived the earthquake and fire
of 1906, it has totemic status. Its venerability is noted in solemn
inscriptions: ground broken by William McKinley on May 20, 1901,
and dedicated by Theodore Roosevelt on May 14, 1903, when
presidential visits to California were rare.
</P>
<P>
   No one in San Francisco has an answer to the homeless problem,
but, Fotheringham says, ``The impact won't be what it is today. Our
office overlooks the square and we're watching the social dynamics
of that space. This is why benches will be a last resort in
providing seating. What happens is the daily users, the ones who
basically live in the square, will claim the bench and then they
line the walkways. Or they're lying on the lawn.''
</P>
<P>
   Visitors now recoil at bodies sprawled at the four corner
entrances to the hilly park. The redesign will quadruple the size
of each opening, making it more visible to the street. Although his
partner, April Philips, says ``This space is for all people,'' new
midblock pedestrian entrances will also crowd out the euphemistic
`daily users.''
</P>
<P>
   Temporary seating is one solution, but, Fotheringham asks,
``Where do you store 500 chairs when you're not using them?''
There's little room in the garage underneath, built in 1942, when
California had fallen in love with the automobile. The 1,200 cars
must remain, the city says.
</P>
<P>
   Skateboarders pose another problem. ``We want to have
flexibility for fashion shows, arts festivals, flea markets, and
jazz festivals. This plaza has to look great when its empty and
when it's full,'' Philips says, as she also insists, ``This park is
not meant for skateboarders.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been studies on how you detail something,'' she
says, ``whether it has a curve or an angle, how high it is, how
slanted it is, where a board can go up or not, and breaking up long
surfaces.''
</P>
<P>
   With the St. Francis Hotel rising majestically over Powell
Street, cable cars clanging up the hill, theaters nearby, and
shoppers zooming in and out of stores, Union Square should be an
ideal oasis at any hour.
</P>
<P>
   When a park is empty, it is not ideal. At 10 p.m. on a recent
night, adolescent skateboarders were twirling around the monument
as artfully as Admiral Dewey navigated Manila Bay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
