<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELCOME TO THE FARCE PHASE OF US HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 
  (itals)``Hegel remarks somewhere that all great world historic
facts and personages appear, so to speak, twice. He forgot to add:
the first time as tragedy, the second time as farce.''(unitals)
<TEXT>
<P>
   KARL MARX &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For those of us of a certain age, it is as if we are living our
lives all over again. Waiting up in the evening to hear a dramatic
presidential address. Wondering if Congress will consider articles
of impeachment. Curiosity about the family _ how are they taking
it?
</P>
<P>
   We've seen this movie before. Back before John Dean's hair
turned white. In a time when Dan Rather actually reported and broke
news rather than looking bored and haggard while reading it. As
Yogi Berra correctly remarked: It's deja vu all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Tragedy: Having exhausted all possible avenues, Richard Nixon
and Henry Kissinger, according to Bob Woodward and Carl Bernstein's
bestseller ``The Final Days,'' drop to their knees in the White
House and pray for the future of the republic.
</P>
<P>
   Farce: The Rev. Jesse Jackson, grooming himself to be the Rabbi
Baruch Korff of the Clinton administration, provides spiritual
guidance to the first family in its time of trial _ and then blabs
about it on live TV.
</P>
<P>
   Tragedy: Kept in the dark by the Kennedy administration, UN
ambassador Adlai Stevenson denies US complicity in the Bay of Pigs
invasion in an emotional address to the General Assembly in 1961.
The unsuccessful invasion of Cuba turns out to have been a CIA-run
affair.
</P>
<P>
   Farce: Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and two Cabinet
colleagues, William Daley and Donna Shalala, rush in front of
television cameras in January to denounce the ``false allegations''
of the Monica Lewinsky case. Ooooooops.
</P>
<P>
   Then: Edward Bennett Williams, top lawyer at the powerhouse
Washington law firm of Williams &AMP; Connolly, counsels Washington
Post editor Ben Bradlee to print the Pentagon Papers.
</P>
<P>
   Now: David Kendall, Williams &AMP; Connolly's top lawyer and the man
standing between Bill Clinton and some serious trouble, also has a
major media win to his credit. Representing the National Enquirer,
Kendall green-lighted one of his client's greatest scoops ever _
that the flamboyant Las Vegas pianist Liberace was dying of AIDS.
Another red-letter day for the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Then: On Monday night, the ever-chatty Dick Morris let slip that
he had worked on Clinton's ``1982 apology.'' Huh? This was a ploy
that Morris and the Clintons dreamed up to get their boy back into
Arkansas politics after he had become the youngest defeated
governor in American history. According to Clinton biographer David
Maraniss, Morris counseled the young ex-governor ``to recognize
your sins, confess to them, promise to sin no more, and then sin no
more.''
</P>
<P>
   It worked. Arkansas voters reelected Clinton to four consecutive
terms as governor.
</P>
<P>
   Now: Will 1998's carefully crafted non-apology work? Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   Then: As the second-youngest man to be elected president,
Clinton initially reveled in comparisons with John F. Kennedy and
Franklin Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Now: Clinton is quoted as saying that Ulysses S. Grant, one of
our magnificently failed presidents, ``got a bum rap.'' Grant the
man has been ably rehabilitated by a brilliant and sensitive
biographer, William McFeeley. (Grant, of course, had a
distinguished military career, material unavailable to any putative
Clinton chroniclers.) Will Clinton be so lucky, and have to wait a
hundred years?
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, during the previous nadir in her husband's
fortunes _ his embarrassing washout at the 1988 Democratic National
Convention _ Hillary Rodham Clinton remarked, ``Political history
remakes itself every 24 hours. Every day is an opportunity to make
a new speech.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet no one wants to hear a president deliver a speech on
this subject, ever again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
