<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1234 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORMON-MISSIONARIES-A     08-19 1367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORMON-MISSIONARIES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORMON FOOT SOLDIERS MAKING INROADS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tenille Roberts and Amanda Williams are privates in a formidable
army.
</P>
<P>
   Their uniform is a pressed white shirt, ankle-length skirt, and
sensible walking shoes. Their weapon is a Spanish version of The
Book of Mormon.
</P>
<P>
   Their battlefield is the streets of Boston's Dorchester,
Mattapan, and Jamaica Plain neighborhoods, and anywhere else in the
city where souls need saving.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here because the Lord wants us here,'' said Williams,
riding a bus through the Roslindale section and cheerfully asking
strangers if they had read the Mormon gospel. ``We're here to offer
people the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   And the number of people across the country, and around the
world willing to embrace that truth has been, in the view of many
religious scholars, nothing short of phenomenal.
</P>
<P>
   During the last quarter-century, the Church of Jesus Christ of
Latter-day Saints has been among the nation's fastest-growing
religious communities.
</P>
<P>
   Even in New England, a region where the church has not always
been active, Mormons are becoming more visible, with an increase in
members from 37,700 in 1988 to 53,500 today. The increase has led
to the building of a soaring and controversial temple in Belmont,
Mass. to serve the burgeoning Mormon population. The temple, which
some neighbors complain will be too big and cause traffic problems,
is one of 16 planned or being built worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, Mormons number 5 million, a million more than a
decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a church that knows what it's doing and does it
incredibly well,'' said Rodney Stark, a sociologist at the
University of Washington. ``In a span of a short time they have
become a major religious force, and there are no signs that their
growth is going to slow down anytime soon.''
</P>
<P>
   A key factor in the church's impressive track record has been
the zeal and work of young Mormons like Roberts, 21, and Williams,
22. The ``sisters,'' as they are called, are two of 58,000
missionaries worldwide spreading the Mormon message.
</P>
<P>
   It is a massive army of true _ and unpaid _ believers that no
other Christian faith comes close to matching. The Roman Catholic
Church, by comparison, has about 6,000 missionaries worldwide,
according to church officials.
</P>
<P>
   Going on a mission is a rite of passage for young Mormons. And
even though male missionaries outnumber female ones by about four
to one, a growing number of women are taking up the call to
evangelize.
</P>
<P>
   The Mormon church also has begun training its missionary
spotlight on urban areas and communities with large concentrations
of blacks and Hispanics. Roberts and Williams learned Spanish
during their missionary training in Utah primarily so they could
focus on Hispanic women. Women missionaries in the church tend to
evangelize to other women.
</P>
<P>
   What distinguishes missionaries like Williams and Roberts from
those in other Christian faiths, religious scholars say, is the
intense attention they pay to ``investigators,'' as potential
converts are called. Roberts and Williams typically work the Boston
streets from 10 a.m. to 9:30 p.m. six days a week. They will talk
to anyone who will listen _ on buses, on the subway, or on the
sidewalk. They will visit and revisit those people who hint that
they want to learn more about the church.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent rainy afternoon, Roberts and Williams sat inside
Rosemery Szymanski's kitchen in Roslindale, &UR;  &LR; reading from a Spanish
translation of the Book of Mormon. It is the second visit Mormon
missionaries have made to her apartment in as many days.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of stuff in here that I don't understand, but
I'm very curious to learn,'' Szymanski said. Williams and Roberts
nodded. ``There's stuff in here that I remember reading in the
Bible, but a lot of new stuff too. I didn't know about Jesus coming
to America,'' she told them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Roberts told Szymanski: ``I promise you that when you read the
book the spirit is going to shake you up and tell you that this is
the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts and Williams made an appointment to visit Szymanski in a
few days for more readings and study.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice that the missionaries take the time to talk to you
about God; that's important to me,'' Szymanski said.
</P>
<P>
   The Book of Mormon, the key church scripture and what separates
Mormons from other churches tracing their roots to Jesus, is
believed to have been translated by Joseph Smith, the founder of
Mormonism.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who was born in 1805 in Sharon, Vt., and who moved to New
York as a teenager, claimed that Jesus appeared to him and told him
to start the Church of Latter-day Saints, which Mormons believe to
be the only true Christian church.
</P>
<P>
   Smith translated the Book of Mormon from gold tablets he is said
to have found in New York. The tablets, Mormons believe, tell the
story of how Jesus appeared in North America shortly after he was
crucified, to an ancient people related to the inhabitants of
biblical Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Szymanski, &UR;  &LR; Roberts and Williams next called on
Kathy Burgos, 29, who was baptized into the Mormon church last
month. Burgos is still learning about the faith, and Roberts and
Williams had made an appointment with her to continue her studies.
A former Roman Catholic, she said Masses left her uninspired.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Catholic church I didn't feel like I was getting
anything, but when I went to the Mormon church you could just feel
the warmth,'' said Burgos, a single mother of two young boys,
sitting inside her dimly-lit, cramped kitchen &UR;  &LR; in Dorchester's
Ashmont neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there are always people visiting here to study the Bible
or just to talk. That's really nice. They have become people I can
trust and discuss things with.''
</P>
<P>
   Creating a support system for members or prospective members is
a crucial aspect of the Church of Latter-day Saints, which promotes
the idea that strong families are divinely ordained.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jan Shipps, a noted scholar of Mormonism, the faith
does especially well in urban neighborhoods _ like the ones where
Williams and Roberts spend much of their time _ filled with broken
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church is able to provide a kind of surrogate family to a
lot of alienated people,'' said Shipps, a retired professor of
history and religious studies at Indiana University in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   When Burgos mentions that she is thinking of painting her
apartment, Roberts and Williams eagerly volunteer to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't comprehend until I got here how much work this was
going to be,'' Williams said. ``This is all we do, this is all we
think about, this is all we dream about.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I wanted to be a missionary since I was little girl. There
are a lot of people out here who need to hear the gospel.''
</P>
<P>
   She admits to getting discouraged at times when people she tries
to talk to have no interest in hearing about Mormonism. But she
persists, she says, because her belief in her faith is unshakable.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got the truth, a lot of people sense it and they
are at least willing to listen,'' Williams said, riding yet another
bus and carrying a knapsack filled with several copies of The Book
of Mormon and other church tracts. ``When you have the true gospel
in your life, you want to share it with others.''
</P>
<P>
   The Church of Latter-day Saints gains converts at a pace of
318,000 every year. At this rate, Stark estimates, the number of
Mormons worldwide will climb from 10 million today to 267 million
by 2080, placing the church among the world's major religions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here you have these polite, well-dressed, earnest young people
walking into some really tough neighborhoods and willing to talk to
people and convince people about the rightness of their faith,''
said Shipps, the scholar of Mormonism.
</P>
<P>
   ``They go knocking on doors and reach out to folks on the
margins of society that not a lot of other religious communities
are paying attention to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 1332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1244 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SPEECH-BOS &LR;      08-19 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SPEECH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT TO SAY? MRS. CLINTON AND LAWYERS WON THE DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dusky gray light spread through the expansive
windows of the White House solarium as President Clinton, his wife,
his lawyers, and his political advisers gathered stone-faced Monday
night to plot the most pivotal speech of his presidency: his public
confession to lies and adultery.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was at times melancholy and at times testy. Clinton
had just finished four hours of exhaustive grand jury testimony.
Hillary Rodham Clinton had recently learned that her husband had
again violated their marital vows. Some political aides had been
told only that day that Clinton had lied to them in denying his
sexual affair with Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   And together, on an excruciating deadline, with the television
networks already blaring word of a 10 p.m. address, they gathered
once again to try to make wine from old grapes in the political
career of Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, according to those present, the president took the
side of his wife and lawyers rather than that of his political
advisers in deciding to lash back at independent counsel Kenneth W.
Starr for the four-year investigation that lurched from the
Whitewater real estate dealings to the Lewinsky affair. From that
meeting, and from Clinton's own hand, came the pointed five-minute
speech that has been criticized in many quarters for being long on
defiance and short on contrition.
</P>
<P>
   The session served as the climactic behind-the-scenes episode
during what was the most extraordinary day of the Clinton
presidency. It began with a lengthy morning meeting with lawyers
and ended with a solemn gathering of advisers late at night. In
between, Clinton twice appeared before a camera in the historic Map
Room, the first time to speak to a grand jury in the US District
Courthouse, the second time to address the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Clinton privately labored over his speech in
the confines of his upstairs study. Sometime Sunday night or Monday
morning, it was typed up by one of his lawyers and hand-delivered
to White House counselor Paul Begala later on Monday with orders to
refine and clarify it, according to those familiar with the
process.
</P>
<P>
   What Begala and other speechwriters and aides were given was a
hard-line text bordering on a constant rant, according to
officials. Quickly, they redrew not only the words, but the tone,
injecting contrition and even apology where Clinton had placed
attack.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton testified, and the rest of the White House seemed
frozen, waiting, a small battery of aides pounded on a computer
keyboard trying to strike the right note.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Clinton concluded his testimony at 6:25 p.m., he
met with his lawyers, then summoned his political aides to the
solarium, where, in somewhat happier times, Mrs. Clinton used to
cknduct imaginary conversations with Eleanor Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Present were White House hands such as senior strategist Rahm
Emanuel, chief of staff Erskine Bowles, presidential advisers Doug
Sosnik and Begala, and deputy chief of staff John Podesta. Each of
them pleaded the case with Clinton to take a softer line, to offer
an explicit apology, to soft-pedal his remarks on Starr.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, Clinton's lawyers, particularly David E.
Kendall, saw no need for an apology, according to those familiar
with the discussion. Mrs. Clinton wanted to vent her anger at
Starr, whose investigation had led to her public humiliation.
Clinton, fresh from hours of contentious questioning, and
frustrated over months and years of investigation, was himself
angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were three positions: a hard, hard line, a much softer
line by the political people, and a middle position, which was the
speech he made,'' said an involved official. ``People might say,
`Really, that was the middle position?'''
</P>
<P>
   Added the official: ``Everyone was polite. He was going to do
what he wanted to do anyways.''
</P>
<P>
   By 9 p.m., the group had wrapped up the speech, more by
necessity than by agreement. Clinton rushed to the Map Room to
conduct a pair of rehearsals, the aides around him grim and without
the jocularity that often precedes major speeches. At 9:30, Clinton
walked upstairs for a final makeup session.
</P>
<P>
   At 10:02, his voice unusually tight, and the bags under his eyes
heavy, Clinton delivered the speech. Afterward, some friends and
family called on the telephone. A few aides gathered around in the
residence, but the mood was heavy, not congratulatory.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Clinton met privately with some of those aides,
according to press secretary Michael McCurry. But by their own
statements, many have yet to come to terms with the events of the
week and the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 1334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
