<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1249 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      08-19 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BREACH OF TRUST TAKEN PERSONALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suddenly, ordinary questions of everyday life are grave
questions of state.
</P>
<P>
   Now, more than ever, everyday Americans believe the problems the
president faces are the very same problems they face. Now, more
than ever, everybody has an opinion on the leading questions of the
day. Now, more than ever, everybody is an expert. Now, more than
ever, your view and your neighbor's are just as important as the
president's, and maybe more dispassionate _ or sound.
</P>
<P>
   And now that the principal White House issues are trust and
betrayal, affecting the president's family and his friends, and
not, for example, fast-track authority to permit the president to
negoatiate trade agreements on an accellerated schedule, everybody
is involved in the national debate.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons this period has been so jarring to Americans
is the unusual tension between the personal issues that face the
nation, like lying and fidelity, and the more traditional political
issues that confront the country, like the expansion of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization and ways to combat the Year 2000
problem that threatens vital computer systems. Now the personal
seems ready to supplant the traditional.
</P>
<P>
   One set of issues is accessible to everyone; the other is the
purview only of specialists. One applies on the playground and in
the workplace and at the dinner table; the other is confined to the
Council on Foreign Relations, congressional committee chambers and
university seminar rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Although the weeks and months ahead will clarify Americans'
views of Bill Clinton, they may be even more important for the way
they clarify Americans' views on a series of issues that define the
nation's social character as much as its political character: the
difference between truth and falsehood, the nature of trust, the
sanctity of the marriage bond, the meaning of forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Almost never has the nation's political life prompted such
searching social questions, a national inquiry with the potential
of shaping the personal lives and outlook of the very people the
nation's leaders are supposed to reflect.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, most American political crises have involved
political questions, critical but theoretical. This political
crisis involves personal questions, all the more critical because
of their practical application in the lives of millions.
</P>
<P>
   During the American Revolution, Americans were forced to examine
the relationship between individualism and authority, perhaps the
fundamental question of civic life. During the Civil War, Americans
were forced to examine the relationship between property and
liberty, perhaps the basic question of social life.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Clinton presidency is forcing Americans to examine the
deepest and most difficult questions of their intimate lives,
questions that are at the root of our assumptions about family and
fidelity. The president is forcing us to face hard questions: Does
the truth have shadings? Is it permissible to deceive a loved one
to protect a loved one? Is it permissible to deceive a nation to
protect that nation's sensibilities? Are there some questions that
are so personal that they do not deserve an honest answer?
</P>
<P>
   The president's late-hour acknowledgement that he did have a
sexual affair with former intern Monica S. Lewinsky was not
surprising _ but it was nonetheless startling. For months the
affair was a suspicion. Now it is an admission. And that change _ a
jolt to the nation _ may change the level and nature of support for
the president.
</P>
<P>
   But first Americans will have to come to grips with the broader
questions surrounding the president, his character, and his
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The most important question for the future of the Clinton
presidency is clearly: What is the relationship between a leader's
private conduct and his public performance? The most pressing
question for the nation may be even more sweeping: What is the
nature of forgiveness, and what transgressions are unforgivable?
</P>
<P>
   It is clear now that Clinton hid behind legalisms when he
claimed he never had a sexual relationship with Lewinsky, much as
he hid behind convoluted language when he claimed, six years ago,
that he never broke the laws of the nation, an artful dodge to
conceal that he was abroad when he experimented with marijuana.
Confronted with his deception, he then claimed he did not inhale.
</P>
<P>
   Public-opinion polls have been showing for the past seven months
that few people care about Clinton's private life. The polls have
shown, moreover, a growing suspicion that Clinton did have sexual
relations with Lewinsky. The Pew Research Center survey showed that
52 percent of Americans believed that was ``definitely'' or
``probably'' true in February, compared with 70 percent who felt
the same way last month. At the same time, two Americans out of
three believe that it was likely Clinton lied about the affair.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of but 24 hours, it now is clear that the sexual
relationship that Bill Clinton denied ever conducting did, in fact,
occur.
</P>
<P>
   The president's acknowledgement that he had a narrowly defined
physical relationship with Lewinsky is one of the most dramatic
presidential reversals ever. When Franklin Roosevelt turned from
his vow to balance the budget and when Dwight Eisenhower retreated
from his denials that Americans were conducting airborne
reconnaissance flights over the Soviet Union, they were motivated
by forces of national survival and security. President Clinton's
acknowledgement was motivated by the impulse for political
survival.
</P>
<P>
   This is a humiliating turn for him, and a potentially
devastating one.
</P>
<P>
   The currency of leadership is trust. Americans give it freely
but reclaim it frequently. Twice the people handed their trust to
Bill Clinton, and repeatedly during the past seven months they
reaffirmed it. In the American system, however, the leader is
beholden to those he leads. The future of his presidency is now in
the hands of those who put him in the White House in the first
place _ and will be determined by the answers to the perplexing
questions that, unwittingly and unwillingly, he has placed before
all of us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
