A1250 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      08-19 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BANE OF NORMAL; VIBE'S FIRST FIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long before Marilyn Manson stripped down, slapped on fright
make-up, and ticked off Wal-Mart, there was Wendy O. Williams. In
the late 1970s-early 1980s, she was the maniacal leader of the
Plasmatics, a New York-based punk-metal outfit so visceral they
made the Sex Pistols look like the Captain and Tennille. They sang
rude songs like ``Butcher Baby,'' chain sawed electric guitars, and
blew up a Chevy Nova on Tom Snyder's old late-night show,
``Tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1988, she was little more than a rock 'n' roll footnote. Then
she became news again when she put a bag over her head and killed
herself with a .38 handgun in April. In the current  &UR; Spin &LR; , Joy
Williams crafts a stunning coda to a punk maverick who checked out
when her life simply became too normal. At the time of her death,
Williams was 48, and living in Storrs, Conn., which Joy Williams
(no relation to her subject) describes as ``green in the way only
the northeast Connecticut landscape can be green, a thick,
stultifying, clogged, limp, breathless green.'' She had just lost
her job in a health store, and thought herself pathetic for suing
for unemployment benefits. This was hardly the life for a woman
once roughed up by cops after she was arrested for simulating
fellatio on a sledgehammer during a Milwaukee show. The simple life
was no good life, and to reclaim herself, Williams had to erase
herself. ``Her self was gone,'' Joy Williams writes. ``She had
always wanted only to be herself, and she wasn't anymore, she was
with out a self.'' Joy Williams writes with the pungent wail of a
Plasmatics song, but finds a way to speak with compassion, even
reason, about an unspeakable act.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's been five years since  &UR; Vibe &LR;  crashed the party as an urban
version of Rolling Stone for the hip-hop nation. The mag founded by
Quincy Jones toasts its half-decade with its ``Juice'' issue which,
at a hefty 312 pages, is heavy enough to cause injury.
Appropriately, Vibe slaps Hollywood heavyweight Will Smith on its
cover, and sends writer Mike Sager to unveil how Smith went from a
jug-eared wiseacre Philly rapper to a &UR;  &LR; movie star who routinely
commands an eight-figure salary. Over a game of golf _ on his own
course _ Smith considers his appeal, which Sager explains as this:
``White people see him as lovable and nonthreatening; most brothers
and sisters see him as being down ... at least as down as he ever
was.'' Smith, who turned down his acceptance into the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology in 1987, says he's in an enviable position
since in some circles since the notion of a black movie star is
still considered an oxymoron. ``... I'm not supposed to be here in
the first place. And there's an entire country of black people _
who whether my movie is good or not _ want me to win. Black people
aren't going to let me go anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same issue, there's a fascinating time line that recalls
all that has gone down on Vibe's watch _ the ascension of Quentin
Tarantino and Sean ``Puffy'' Combs; remarkably prescient
predictions of success for Usher, Missy ``Misdemeanor'' Elliott,
Erykah Badu, and the Spice Girls; and death, too much meaningless
death _ Eric ``Eazy-E'' Wright, Selena, Tupac Shakur, and the
Notorious B.I.G.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Out of London, there's  &UR; Frank &LR; , not to be confused with the
lesbian folk singer Phranc. It's a magazine for women, and yes,
there's an awful lot of space given to fashion, fashionable people,
famous people, and what famous, fashionable people wear while
attending fashion shows _ Vogue's Anna Wintour is wrapped in a
``never PC, but ever immaculate'' fur, as is Allure's Polly Mellen,
while Harper's Baazar's classy Liz Tilberis opts for timeless
cashmere.
</P>
<P>
   But in the middle of those yummy Hermes sweaters and leather
Louis Vuitton mules, there's Jane Bussmann's provocative, biting
essay, ``Death Becomes Us.'' She argues that ``suffering is the new
currency,'' that nothing these days is more transforming than
death, disease, and disaster _ for the living as well as the dead.
Christopher Reeve was a lightly regarded actor until his paralysis
in a riding accident earned him a bestseller and a standing ovation
at the Academy Awards. Last summer's overwhelming mourning of
Princess Diana put a permanent quiver in the British stiff upper
lip, and remade their classic reserve as boundless pathos. Nothing
succeeds, says Bussmann, like sudden death. ``In life, the media
may dismiss you, but when that biopsy report comes in bad, you
become its special-needs baby,'' she writes. ``It's a telling
reflection on the newsmakers that only cancer had the power to
transform Linda McCartney in their eyes from the Beatles-stealing
veggie food vendor into a front-page saint.'' Ouch. And while the
piece is presented from a distinctly British point of view, make no
mistake that such post-mortem revisionism is just as popular on
this side of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cigar Aficionado &LR; , the magazine for those convinced they are
hipper and sexier with a big, smelly, smoking thing in their
mouths, has lippy actress Gina Gershon on its cover, but the real
worthwhile read is Marc Wortman's feature on amateur baseball
leagues for men over 30. Some &UR;  &LR; of the players are former big
leaguers like one-time Red Sox pitcher Bill Lee. But most are
regular guys _ stockbrokers, factory workers, teachers. They're the
guys who've gotten thin on top, thick in the middle, and leg out a
triple on balky knees. Some of the participants first played the
game on sandlots back when Babe Ruth was parking balls in the upper
decks of stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   It's a poignant story, a tribute to all who still love baseball
for the pure, splendid, and beautiful game it is. ``In an era when
the game of baseball has taken some hard knocks at its top
levels,'' Wortman writes, ``old guys playing a boy's game just for
the love of it make it easy to believe that summer will never
end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
