<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1256 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADOPTION-SECRET-2ND &LR;  &UR;      08-19 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADOPTION-SECRET-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 (Reating for all needing; moved originally July 30.)  
 CAMBRIDGE, Mass.: ... her father.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``You mean your mother didn't tell you?'' they asked
incredulously.
</P>
<P>
   Now she had a new nationality -- ``I always knew I wasn't half
white,'' she muses today -- but not a name to go with it. That came
within weeks, when her sister found among their mother's belongings
what appeared to be a Japanese birth certificate on which three
words were written in English: Clemente Morales Torres. More
digging produced an address book with an entry for a Maria and
Miguel Torres in Dorado Beach, Puerto Rico. Brock wrote to the
address, but her letter was returned unopened. ``I thought my
father had died or didn't want to see me,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   What she didn't know was that an entire family had been waiting
-- praying -- for her arrival for decades. She didn't know that the
grandmother she'd never met had pasted a halo of Brock's baby
pictures on her bedroom mirror, or that an aunt carried a faded
photograph of her in her wallet. (More people who knew the secret.)
``It was really strange, like being famous and not knowing you're
famous,'' Brock says.
</P>
<P>
   She knew none of this, of course, when she arrived by chance at
a convention in Dorado Beach four months after her mother's death.
Or when she asked a hotel desk clerk how she might track down
someone in the area and he suggested she try any number of old
restaurants where locals hang out. Or when, in the first restaurant
she entered, the cook announced that he knew the brother of one
Clemente Morales Torres. Or when the cook fetched a young man named
Rafi, who said he was related to Clemente Morales Torres and that
Torres had indeed been in Japan after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   But Brock got a pretty good idea what was coming when she told
Rafi that Torres might be her father and he nonchalantly replied:
``Yeah, I think so.''
</P>
<P>
   The next few hours were chaos. She was taken to meet her uncle,
the proprietor of a nearby store. She was whisked to an elegant
home where she met her two aunts, one of them weeping as she pulled
Brock's baby picture from her wallet. She was hurried to another,
more modest, home where her elderly paternal grandparents -- Miguel
and Maria, no longer living at the address to which Brock had sent
her letter -- were waiting. ``My grandfather embraced me and cried
and mumbled things in Spanish,'' Brock says. ``Then I sat between
the two of them on a couch while they held my hand and talked in
Spanish.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing was, they all knew. They all knew of the young man who
had joined the Army, gone to Japan, fallen in love, fathered a
child, and come home alone. They had prayed for the child's arrival
in their midst, and the prayers had finally been answered. Even as
the father of the little girl had gone away to live on the US
mainland, even as he was now working as a cab driver in New York,
they had waited.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an amazing thing,'' says Brock, ``that they had loved
me dearly but had never known me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rita Brock talked to her father for the first time on the
telephone from Puerto Rico the next morning. He told her that he'd
met her mother in a US hospital in Japan where he'd been an orderly
and she'd been a nurse. He explained that he and Ayako had lived
together for six months after Rita was born, and that he'd been
shipped to Korea. He told her she'd been named after actress Rita
Hayworth, who is part Hispanic. And he conceded he hadn't kept in
touch with Ayako, finally receiving a letter from her announcing
that she'd married and that he should never try to contact her or
their daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cried a lot,'' Brock says of that first conversation. ``He
said several times that he had wanted to find me but had wanted to
respect my mother's wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brock did not, she recalls, have any strong feelings about
this voice at the other end of the line. To her, it seemed she was
simply having a polite conversation with a stranger. ``He just
seemed like some guy that I was supposed to know but didn't feel
any connection to,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Later they would meet face to face in New York. Torres would cry
again, but Brock still didn't know what to feel. ``It was a numbing
experience in some ways,'' she recalls. ``Many of my assumptions
around the experience had been shattered. I'd thought it would be
hard to find him. I thought people might be unhappy to see me. So I
couldn't connect to the intense euphoria in Puerto Rico. More than
anything, it was bewildering.''
</P>
<P>
   It still is. Four times divorced, Torres, now in his early 70s,
lives in Chattanooga, Tenn., where he is a part-time security
guard. Brock, herself divorced with no children, sees him only
about once a year. He signs his cards, ``Dad.'' She calls him
``Clemente.'' ``He really doesn't know me in the way a father would
know me,'' says Brock. ``We don't have those shared experiences.
He's not someone I would go to for help. . . . It's hard to imagine
him as my father. Mostly he's this person who connects me to this
very interesting family in Puerto Rico.'' Describing herself as
``half Puerto Rican but not culturally Puerto Rican,'' Brock says
she'd eventually like to live on the island, at least temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, she still wonders why her mother never told her the
secret. And she wishes she had. She muses aloud about the
difficulties her mother must have faced in raising a mixed-race
child within a xenophobic culture. And hadn't Ayako Brock written
in longhand to Clemente Torres in March 1953, when she told him not
to contact her, ``If necessary to tell (Rita) I will tell her about
you?'' But she never did tell her, except by leaving a document in
a metal box as she was dying.
</P>
<P>
   ``She probably had some intent to tell me, but the longer she
waited the harder it got,'' Brock theorizes.
</P>
<P>
   After she had learned the secret and found her birth father,
Rita Brock visited her adoptive father's family in rural
Mississippi. When she told her Aunt Pearl Gilmore that she'd
discovered she wasn't Roy Brock's daughter and that her father was
really Puerto Rican, the older woman didn't blink. Yes: she knew,
too. Heck, Aunt Pearl allowed as how just about everyone knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way to do it,'' Aunt Pearl declared, laughing.
``You tell people something but don't tell them it's a secret. That
way they won't talk about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
