<SLUG> BC-VENTURE-INVESTORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH YIELDS MAKE FUNDS WORTH A WAIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHANA R. SCHOENBERGER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even as the stock market flirts with a correction, the venture
capital market appears to be headed for a banner year, and venture
capitalists say investors are flocking to their funds with good
reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main reason is because the returns to date have been
phenomenal,'' said Arthur J. Marks, a general partner in the
Reston, Va.-based venture capital firm New Enterprise Associates.
``That's what attracts the money.''
</P>
<P>
   From an outsider's perspective, venture capital funds are a
risky investment. Fully one-third of venture-backed start-ups fail,
Marks says, and businesses that do survive may not yield the
returns that investors want.
</P>
<P>
   But to a venture capitalist _ and to increasing numbers of
institutional investors, including pension funds and university
endowments with stock-market winnings to invest _ the venture
market looks like the place to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bright people with creative ideas who can create valuable
companies will always be an opportunity that we will be investing
in,'' said Barry J. Fidelman, an Atlas Ventures general partner.
</P>
<P>
   Part of venture capitalists' optimism can be traced to their
patience for their investments. While stock market investors may
envision selling shares quickly, venture capital funds typically
invest for the long term, expecting to wait three to five years, or
longer, before a venture company makes money for the fund through a
sale or initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   This longer perspective means venture funds seek out tomorrow's
hot investments, not the bestsellers of today.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're looking for is market segments that are going to
experience rapid market growth over the next few years,'' said
Stephen J. Gaal, who has worked for venture capital funds for 20
years, and who now runs Gaal &AMP; Co. in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the investments appear to be paying off for fund
investors. Paul J. Ferri, a general partner with Matrix Partners in
Waltham, says the high-tech start-up companies in which Matrix
venture capital funds invest can yield 10 percent to 100 percent
returns annually, a figure he calls ``off the charts.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Howard Anderson,president of the Yankee Group and a
partner in Wellesley's Battery Ventures, says about 20 percent of
the companies his funds back are successful, yielding about a 40
percent annual &UR;  &LR; return.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, venture capitalists say they expect a downturn in
the venture market over the next several years, an inevitability,
they say, in a cyclical process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, the venture community is going to face the same
kinds of corrections the stock market seems to be confronting right
now,'' said Katherine C. Ives, senior vice president of Atlantic
Capital Corp. in Boston. But venture capitalists remained
optimistic about the venture market's prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the amount of capital that's now available to venture
firms, given that we've been in a basically strong economy, it's
unlikely that over the next decade the returns are going to be as
good as they were in the last decade,'' Gaal said. ``On the other
hand, my guess is that venture capital investing will be the best
asset class to be investing in over the next 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side of the venture capital boom, Gaal said, are the
venture business owners themselves, who benefit directly from
venture capital investments in the companies they start.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big picture is this is a great time to be an
entrepreneur,'' he said. ``Technological change is at an all-time
high, and availability of capital is at an all-time high.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
