<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1265 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENTURE-QUARTER-BOS &LR;      08-19 1650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENTURE-QUARTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR N.E. FIRMS, LURE OF START-UPS REMAINS HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reaffirming their confidence in Yankee ingenuity, venture
capital funds pumped $379.5 million during the second three months
of 1998 into 86 New England companies preparing to launch products
and services, ranging from automation to auto repair.
</P>
<P>
   Software developers and Internet-based companies dominated the
firms tallied by The Boston Globe/PricewaterhouseCoopers Money Tree
Survey, as they have in almost every quarter since the survey began
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The regional list also encompassed medical pioneers, retail
stores, two companies with ideas about selling coffee, and 16
communications start-ups, including the maker of voice-actuated
office phone systems and a cellular-phone rental firm.
</P>
<P>
   Just under 10 percent of the funding went to a single firm,
Praecis Pharmaceuticals Inc. of Cambridge, which is on the home
stretch in developing a drug to control prostate cancer and
received $37.8 million to carry out final clinical trials and begin
pilot production.
</P>
<P>
   The second-quarter total investment was down markedly from the
$534.2 million put into start-up New England companies in the first
quarter by venture firms, which use cash pooled by pension and
endowment funds and from wealthy individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick M. Gray, partner in the global technology industry group
at PricewaterhouseCoopers, called this a statistical fluke,
accentuated by the fact that New England's most prominent
entrepreneurial sector, &UR;  &LR; software, typically needs less money than
other industries to bring products to market.
</P>
<P>
   ``New England always seems to lack in the really large deals,''
Gray said _ such as the $50 million venture funds advanced to a
Texas company to explore for oil in Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
   Gray noted that the combined investment total for the first half
of this year, $913.8 million, is the highest in the survey's
history. He predicted that activity should pick up because demand
for investment opportunities is high. If the second-quarter decline
``is the start of a trend,'' he said, ``we're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The PricewaterhouseCoopers survey is the successor to The Boston
Globe/Price Waterhouse Venture Capital Survey. Its new name results
from the July merger of two of the nation's largest accounting
firms, Price Waterhouse and Coopers &AMP; Lybrand, &UR;  &LR; each of which
previously conducted its own quarterly venture capital survey.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the survey found venture investment during the
period at a 3 1/2-year high of $3.7 billion, up nearly 12 percent
from the first quarter of 1998 and 26 percent more than the second
quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   California's high-technology region, Silicon Valley, again was
the leading venture money magnet, with 224 companies sharing almost
$1.25 billion in funding, one-third of the US total. Nearly 48
percent of that Silicon Valley investment was in software and
information services companies.
</P>
<P>
   New England held on to second in national rankings with 10.1
percent of investment, up almost 15 percent from the period in
1997. Massachusetts accounted for 87 percent of that investment.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeast placed third, with $348.2 million, half of that
going to communications and health care companies. Texas was fourth
with $290.4 million in venture investment.
</P>
<P>
   Although less strong than in the past, communications was an
important sector in New England, with support going to products and
services ranging from network management software to the low-power
radio transmitters being developed by PinPoint Corp. of Bedford to
help hospitals keep track of wheelchairs and other movable
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   A New York hospital is testing the system now. PinPoint plans to
use the $8 million it got from APV Technology Partners, Prism
Venture Partners, and others to begin marketing in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Praecis Pharmaceuticals plans to use its $37.8 million financing
for final-round human clinical trials of its peptide-based
pharmaceutical and to begin pilot production operations to satisfy
federal requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Praecis's president and chief executive, Malcolm Gefter, said
those final human tests will begin next month.
</P>
<P>
   Venture fund managers said their interest in entrepreneurial
investment is undiminished by uncertainties in broader markets.
Although these firms commonly expect annual returns of 50 to 60
percent on high-risk investments, they do so knowing ideas can take
years to create a profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our time horizon is much different than an investor who is
trying to make good money this year,'' said Howard Anderson, a
partner at Battery Ventures, in Wellesley, and president of the
Yankee Group, a technology information and consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Strong stock market gains and a long string of successful
start-ups have fueled the supply of venture capital. Additionally,
endowment funds have joined pension funds in placing up to 5
percent of their investment portfolio into venture funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a pretty flush environment,'' said James
Iuliano, president and chief executive of E Ink Corp. of Cambridge,
recounting how he solicited the $15.8 million the company won in
first-round financing to develop a way to print electronically on
paper. ``It is fairly easy to get immediate interest for a
high-quality deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even a one-time shortage of managers to guide new companies is
evaporating, said Arthur J. Marks, partner at New Enterprise
Associates, a Reston, Va., venture fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be hard to recruit experienced CEOs to run a
venture,'' Marks said. ``Now it is, `I want to work for a small
company. Corporate America has limited careers.'''
</P>
<P>
   One start-up seizing on this shift in corporate perspective is
Lexington Software Associates. It now manages a global network of
consultants offering technical support for a software tool,
ClearCase, widely used by software developers but no longer
supported by the company that makes it.
</P>
<P>
   Cam Collins, vice president for sales and marketing, said
Lexington is using $1,050,000 from Brook Venture Fund and Private
Equity Funds LLC to build an engineering and training center in
Westford and add employees. He said sales will approach $3.5
million this year and $7 million in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Coming at development from another angle, VentureCom Inc. of
Cambridge got $9 million to hire more people to perfect and market
programs that drive factory machinery from a central computer,
using Microsoft's NT and CE operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Dexter-Smith, VentureCom's chief executive, said the
product is meant to make computer-controlled systems
multifunctional &UR;  &LR; and as compatible with each other as parallel
office desktop systems are now.
</P>
<P>
   In Acton, Indus River Networks Inc. will deploy its $8.7 million
funding from One-Liberty Associates, Canaan Partners, New
Enterprise Associates, and Pioneer Capital Partners to begin
marketing its Internet-based communications system, designed to
link corporate field personnel with the home office without risk to
security or privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Promising to save users 50 to 80 percent on corporate phone
bills, the system attracted broad investor interest, Indus River
chief executive Per Suneby said. ``We were oversubscribed,'' and
turned away some proposed contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Another major funding round, $16 million, went to Silknet
Software Inc. of Manchester, N.H., to increase marketing and sales
of its system that lets telephone call centers answer customer
inquries via the Internet. Silknet estimates that 50 to 70 percent
of all questions now answered by voice are asked frequently. Its
system steers customers to find the answers via the World Wide Web
on their own, and if that fails, to communicate with technical
experts via e-mail _ at less cost per call.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting a trend, Silknet's financing included investors with
an inherent understanding of the product _ among them,
computer-chip maker Intel Corp. and an arm of CMG Information Group
Inc., which specializes in Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   Several start-up company executives said tapping sources that
already understand the product saves time. N-Able Corp. of Danvers,
which is developing credit-card sized devices to ensure security in
automated bank transactions, got much of its $6.5 million
second-round funding from an affiliate of Chase Manhattan Bank and
from Cambridge Samsung Partners, affiliated with Samsung, the South
Korea computer-chip company.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can always find money, but you really want to find
strategic money,'' said N-Able's chief executive, Jeff Grammer.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Sterling Collision Centers Inc. of Natick, which is
building a national chain of auto body repair shops, got its
$25 &UR;  &LR; million of second-round funding from Conning Insurance Capital
Funds of Hartford and Berkshire Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Conning, which gets its cash from insurance companies and
specializes in supporting start-ups with with industry ties, was a
logical source because Sterling proposes to cut repair costs by
improving relations between shops and insurers, said Jonathan
McNeill, cofounder and copresident of Sterling.
</P>
<P>
   Berkshire, in turn, has a history of funding companies whose
primary strategy is consolidation in fragmented industries. ``We
knew they would immediately grasp the potential of our business
plan,'' McNeill said.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling owns 30 auto body shops in and around eight US cities
and expects to have 50 by next year. It proposes to cut costs as
much as 20 percent by reducing time in negotiations among insurers
and shop operators. ``The goal for the consumer is, `Give me my car
back,''' McNeill said. ``Right now that takes 13 days, although the
work takes only two days. The rest of that time is spent
haggling.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe correspondent Chana R. Schoenberger contributed to this
article.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
