<SLUG> BC-LOTUS-MICROSOFT-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LOTUS POSITION: NOTES MAKER CHALLENGES MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo and a graphic are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; When Lotus Development Corp.'s chief executive, Jeffrey
Papows, strode to the front of a Senate hearing room last month to
join a parade of executives blasting Microsoft Corp.'s business
practices, he was doing an about-face.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Papows had tried to duck the controversy over
whether the software giant uses its dominance in computer operating
systems to unfairly stifle competition in other parts of the
software market. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   After all, Lotus, a Cambridge, Mass. unit of International
Business Machines Corp., has a complex relationship with Microsoft.
It is both a technology partner and a competitor. For that reason,
Papows preferred not to toss rocks at Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   So why the change of heart?
</P>
<P>
   One reason, it would seem, is that Microsoft _ which a few years
back walloped Lotus in the spreadsheet market it virtually invented
and once dominated _ is again breathing down Lotus's neck in the
emerging market for messaging and groupware _ software that lets
distant employees collaborate on a single project or document.
</P>
<P>
   Lotus also pioneered that market in late 1989 with the
introduction of Lotus Notes, following it up with an Internet-based
product called Domino. Today, Notes has more than 25 million users
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1996, the Redmond, Wash.-based Microsoft introduced a
competing product called Exchange _ and it is gaining fast, with
about 16 million copies installed in just two years.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter of this year, Exchange outsold Notes for
the first time, 3 million copies to 2.7 million, according to
figures supplied by Lotus. Although it was Lotus' third-best
quarter ever, it was a milestone that clearly has Lotus worried. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The company is reorganizing its North American sales division
and bringing in new management in hopes of holding off Microsoft's
charge. And IBM &UR;  &LR; is stepping forward to promote Notes as an
integral part of its electronic commerce business strategy,
something it didn't do initially after buying the company in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure is more intense,'' Papows acknowledged in a
recent interview. But he insisted that the heat was being generated
internally and was not coming from IBM, which paid $3.2 billion for
the company, largely to get its hands on Notes.
</P>
<P>
   Papows rejected the notion that his decision to testify against
Microsoft, after resisting for so long, was a desperate attempt to
place blame for his company's shrinking market share.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fair question,'' conceded Papows, who had been pestered
to testify for months by Senator Orrin G. Hatch of Utah, the
Republican chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee, which is
investigating allegations that the world's largest software company
engages inmonopolistic business practices.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch finally wore him down, Papows said, with a personal
appeal. ``He said, `I've talked to a lot of people in the industry,
and not only are you not helping me protect your industry, the fact
that you are not visible on this issue is a deterrent to getting
other CEOs to testify.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He said it was a responsibility I was shirking. Frankly, that
cut pretty deep,'' Papows said.
</P>
<P>
   Papows said that he testified reluctantly, that he was careful
to emphasize that the companies have a good relationship overall,
and that he is not among the legions of ``Bill-bashers,'' people
who love to hate Bill Gates, Microsoft's billionaire chairman.
</P>
<P>
   He told the committee he was concerned that by bundling its
Exchange messaging software, at little or no cost, with other
popular office software, Microsoft was driving prices on groupware
down to zero, effectively locking out other competitors, including
Lotus Notes.
</P>
<P>
   He also complained that Microsoft was using its dominance of
operating systems, which control a computer's basic functions, to
force computer makers to pre-load Exchange onto their machines,
again locking out competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you own the bridge &UR;  &LR; and control the toll gate, pretty
soon you get to decide what kind of cars get across the bridge,''
Papows testified.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft officials declined to comment on Papows' testimony.
</P>
<P>
   But even Papows admits that some of Lotus's problems are of its
own making.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while IBM and Lotus officials maintain that the 1995
buyout was good for both companies, they admit that they probably
goofed by not trying to leverage IBM's enormous market presence to
help Lotus fend off Microsoft Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a mutual mistake by not more prominently and visibly
linking the companies strategically,'' Papows said. ``We were so
manic about maintaining Lotus as a separate brand identity, that we
didn't do a lot to run Domino and Notes as part of IBM's e-business
ads.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
