<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1270 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOTUS-MISCROSOFT-2ND &LR;      08-19 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTUS-MISCROSOFT-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... e-business ads.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IBM officials agree. ``Perhaps if we had positioned Domino as
the crown jewel of our e-business offering sooner, it would have
blunted their success, but it probably would not have resulted in a
major forestalling of the Microsoft juggernaut, given some of their
business tactics,'' said Mark Elliot, general manager of worldwide
sales and marketing for IBM's $13 billion software business.
</P>
<P>
   Although sales of Lotus Notes are still growing dramatically,
the inroads that Microsoft Exchange has made, especially in North
America, are worrisome.
</P>
<P>
   Industry sources say US sales last quarter of Lotus Notes were
$90 million behind the company's plan, but Papows called the number
``grossly exaggerated.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he acknowledged that Lotus's North American business has
not performed as well as in other regions of the world, where
Microsoft is barely a factor.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the company is overhauling its North American
operations, bringing in a new manager with increased
responsibilities. Mike Laginski is a Papows protege who joined
Lotus five years ago, but left shortly after IBM bought the
company.
</P>
<P>
   He returned recently to take control of North American
operations and helps fill a void created by the departure of a
Deborah Besemer, a highly regarded Lotus executive who left last
November to become chief executive of SystemSoft, a Natick software
company.
</P>
<P>
   While reorganizing its internal operations, Lotus officials have
also mounted a public campaign to counter a damaging article that
appeared recently in Forbes magazine entitled &UR;  &LR;  ``The Decline and
Fall of Lotus.''
</P>
<P>
   The article said that IBM's purchase of Lotus had turned sour,
and that many large Lotus customers were ripping out their Notes
systems in favor of Microsoft Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Infuriated Lotus officials are demanding a retraction, and,
meanwhile, are moving to try to calm anxious employees and
customers who have spent millions installing Notes systems. Forbes
says it is standing by the story.
</P>
<P>
   Papows says it is true that some of Ltus's large customers are
installing Microsoft Exchange for corporate e-mail purposes, but
says they are retaining Notes for its advanced collaborative
features, many of which Exchange does not have.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft agrees, but says its Exchange customers eventually
plan to replace Notes because they don't want to maintain two
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Baan Co. in Reston, Va., a major producer of business management
software for large companies, is one highly visible defector from
the Lotus camp.
</P>
<P>
   John Douglas, director of information technology, said that Baan
took a critical look last year at its Lotus Notes installation,
which served about 5,000 users worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Notes implementation here was pretty abysmal,'' said
Douglas. ``There were a lot of hardware issues, and the cost of
administration was high.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas grants that the advanced groupware features of Notes are
superior to those of Exchange, but added that Baan was mainly
interested in a straightforward messaging system. In that
department, Douglas said, Exchange gets top grades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am absolutely shocked at the amount of hardware it takes to
run Exchange _ or the lack thereof,'' Douglas said, adding that he
needed 40 server computers to run the Notes system. Today, Baan
runs an Exchange system that supports 10,000 users _ twice as many
as the Notes system it replaced. But Exchange requires just three
servers, powerful machines that link PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Baan is a major business ally of Microsoft in the development of
high-end business software. But Douglas said that this played no
part in the decision to switch to Exchange. ``We didn't even
contact IBM or Microsoft,'' said Douglas. ``We made the decision
internally.'' And Baan turned a deaf ear to Lotus's efforts to
reverse the decision. ``Notes is a good platform,'' said Douglas.
``It's just not for us.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, M&AMP;I Data Services, the data processing
division of Milwaukee-based Marshall &AMP; Ilsley Corp., left
Microsoft's older e-mail program, Microsoft Mail, to jump on the
Notes bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Wallace, director of technical infrastructure, said his
company wanted to create an Intranet, a private network based on
Internet standards, with the ability to route forms around the
company, and other collaborative features, and found Exchange
couldn't do the job without a lot of expensive add-on software.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found the Domino-based solution was one third of the cost of
the Exchange-based solution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who track the groupware market say the Forbes article
was way off track.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lotus is not declining, it is not falling,'' wrote Dan Rasmus,
an analyst with Giga Inforamtion Group Inc. of Norwell, shortly
after the Forbes story was published. ``Lotus is in fact holding
its own against Microsoft where other companies have not.''
</P>
<P>
   Another prominent research firm, Gartner Group of Stamford,
Conn., says it'll be mid-2001 before Microsoft catches Lotus in
sales of groupware, and points out that Exchange still dramatically
lags behind Notes's collaborative features.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game is far from over, and Lotus is in a very good spot, a
very defensible spot'' said Ian Campbell, an analyst with
International Data Corp. of Framingham.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a two horse race and we're neck and neck,'' said Papows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Hiawatha Bray of the Globe staff contributed to this story.)
</P>
</TEXT>
