<SLUG> BC-TV-PREVIEW-PACK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HBO OFFERS A COMPELLING LOOK AT SINATRA AND THE RAT PACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Listen up, women. I'm probably breaking some
secret guy code by telling you this, but I have a job to do _ and,
besides, it is only fair:
</P>
<P>
   If your man watches ``The Rat Pack,'' the new HBO movie on
Frank, Dean, Sammy and the boys, and he doesn't admit afterward to
being a tad jealous, he's lying.
</P>
<P>
   Don't argue, guys. You are.
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra's crew gets to party all they want, where they want,
when they want, another bourbon and cigarette and finger-snap away.
Movies _ as in acting in them _ are a pleasant diversion, something
to do for a gas. They look equally cool in tuxes or sweaters. To
top it off, nobody, nobody, can sing like them.
</P>
<P>
   And women? You want to talk women? They are always on the
fringes, waiting to be selected for a night of whatever.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rat Pack,'' a 118-minute movie that premieres Saturday at
9 p.m. EDT (check local listings), covers a sliver of Sinatra's
days and nights in the late 1950s and early 1960s. It doesn't tell
the whole story of arguably America's greatest entertainer, but the
movie is a compelling glimpse of a man much more complex than his
dem-dese-dose persona.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with a historical movie like this is, we are at
first jolted when we see performers playing performers. Ray Liotta?
That's not Sinatra. Don Cheadle? He's not Sammy Davis Jr. Joe
Mantegna as Dean Martin? Well, forget that one. You buy into that
you are watching Martin from the moment Mantegna appears on the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rat Pack'' does not strive for imitation (the songs are
dubbed in from the actual singers). The biggest compliment you
could pay to a movie like this is that after 20 minutes or so, you
forget you're watching Liotta and Cheadle and Mantegna and find
yourself lost in this glitzy world that included actor Peter
Lawford (Angus Macfadyen), comedian Joey Bishop (Bobby Slayton) and
other assorted players.
</P>
<P>
   As 1960 dawns, Sinatra and Co. are the kings of Las Vegas and
California. Women flock to them, as well as their friends like John
F. Kennedy (William Petersen) and mobster Sam ``Momo'' Giancana. In
fact, one woman, Judith Campbell (in real life Judith Exner)
eventually beds both Kennedy and later Giancana.
</P>
<P>
   He has friends, power and women, but Sinatra wants to be a
bigger player in a bigger game: presidential politics. Sinatra
decides JFK is the man to lead the country. Just to make sure that
happens, Frank enlists the help of his close friend Momo to secure
the results of the West Virginia primary and in Illinois in the
general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did it, Dino, we did it,'' Sinatra tells Martin on election
night. ``We're going to the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. While JFK liked Frank _ and the women who came with
that friendship _ Bobby Kennedy was leery of the crooner's
associations with mobsters. Bobby ends up nixing a planned visit by
the president to Frank's Palm Springs spread _ which he expanded
solely for the president. It is the ultimate treason, one that
forever turns Sinatra against Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Liotta brings Sinatra's intensity, while Mantegna exudes the
aloofness of Martin. But the standout of the movie is Cheadle
(``Bulworth,'' ``Out of Sight''), who captures the complexity of
Davis in his role as friend/mascot of Frank.
</P>
<P>
   All these guys bust on each other, both behind the scenes and on
stage. No ethnic or racial slur is out of bounds because there is
no malice intended. But the barbs still sting, as evidenced when
Davis, zinged with a watermelon joke, doubles over in laughter and
turns his back to the audience _ to hide a restrained grimace.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis is quick to remind his angered fiancee, who is white,
that it was Sinatra who first discovered him, and who was a kindly
friend after a car accident cost him an eye. Sinatra would serve as
Davis' best man _ even though criticism and, in some quarters,
hatred ran high over an interracial marriage. Friends do that sort
of thing.
</P>
<P>
   The party doesn't last forever, and members of the Pack soon
fray and fade into irrelevance after the landing of the Beatles.
``The whole world is drunk and we are just the cocktail of the
moment, pal,'' Martin said at a party, foreseeing the
not-too-distant future.
</P>
<P>
   Over time the boys did get back together occasionally, but it's
more of a nostalgia act. Eventually they died off. ``I miss my
guys,'' an aged Frank says in the movie backstage before one of his
later shows. ``I miss my guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra died May 15 at 82, after production began on the film
(the Sinatra family did not cooperate with movie). But, man, did he
live a party we'll never know.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, it's enough to make a guy just a little bit jealous.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
