<HEADLINE>
MGI PROPERTIES PLANNING LIQUIDATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Later this week, big real estate investors will start getting
packages in the mail meant to tickle their interest in eight rare
portfolios of property.
</P>
<P>
   The 64 buildings themselves are nothing out of the ordinary:
suburban commercial space, some city office buildings that won't be
mistaken for trophy towers, and a group of industrial properties.
Ballpark value: up to $450 million.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the property special is that it will all be
liquidated out of MGI Properties Inc. of Boston, a real estate
investment trust that decided shareholders would be better off if
it stopped trying to buck the market and simply cashed out.
</P>
<P>
   Liquidations are not unprecedented, but they are rare in the
world of real estate investment trusts. One other Boston-based
trust, Property Capital Trust, has nearly completed a liquidation
under a plan adopted at the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   MGI first floated its plan in June and directors formally
approved the idea last week. Shareholders will get proxy material
within weeks and vote in October. MGI shares were trading at about
23 when the liquidation idea was first announced, and trust
executives have since estimated they could raise $30 to $33 per
share in a liqudiation. The stock finished Tuesday at 27 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate investment trusts, investing in all types of
properties, have taken a pounding all year. The Bloomberg REIT
index, which tracks the performance of 161 public trusts, is down
11.1 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But the liquidation of MGI has as much to do with the
development of real estate stock investing than the sector's
current lack of popularity. Big real estate investment trusts have
become dramatically bigger, winning most of Wall Street's interest
and important financial advantages at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   MGI was unlikely to succeed in a world where bigger was better
and getting bigger all the time. Always a medium-sized trust, MGI
has struggled to interest investors in its smaller properties and
faces a future of relatively high capital costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably looks to people like a result of the fact that
REIT stocks are in the dumper right now,'' said Barry Vinocur,
editor of Realty Stock Review. ``But this is the end of what has
been a long-standing frustration on the part'' of MGI chief
executive Pearce Coues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a very responsible move by management to
basically say, we don't see a way to maximize shareholder value,''
said Vinocur. He thinks other smaller and midsized trusts will have
to face up to the same problem soon.
</P>
<P>
   Coues declined to be interviewed and other MGI executives said
they were unable to discuss the decision until proxy materials had
been mailed.
</P>
<P>
   By public real estate trust standards, MGI is an old-timer.
Formed in 1971, it survived the financial disasters of the
mortgage-REIT era as a hybrid trust that made loans and invested in
real estate. MGI executives saw great values in New England
commercial real estate by 1992 and started to reposition its
portfolio, once heavy with apartment building investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a screaming buy to us,'' said Phillip Vitali,
MGI's treasurer. The timing turned out to be impeccable, but MGI
never put the kind of money others would spend behind the call.
</P>
<P>
   But MGI took small bites from the beginning. It has bought about
$50 million of real estate a year, mostly within Route 495. Many of
the properties are worth $3 million to $12 million, far less than
the values of downtown showcase buildings big real estate
investment trusts prefer today.
</P>
<P>
   MGI financed its purchases in part by going to the stock market
twice, raising about $27 million in 1993 and another $44 million
early last year.
</P>
<P>
   Compare that to Beacon Properties Corp., which went public in
1994 with a collection of high-profile Boston buildings and sold
out to Equity Office Properties Trust last year.
</P>
<P>
   Beacon went to the stock market seven times in three years to
fuel its aggressive buying plans, raising nearly $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Today, MGI seems to believe it can't get people to appreciate
the value of a smaller scale. Or perhaps its managers just see a
market top too high to resist. Whatever the reason, some REIT
analysts don't want to see MGI go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had hoped they would keep at it because I'm very happy to
see companies with different approaches in the market,'' said Fred
Carr of the Penobscot Group, which tracks public real estate
trusts. ``Somebody with that kind of buy low, sell high sense, you
don't want them to disappear from the market.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The director of the State Rating Bureau, which helps set
insurance rates on everything from autos to health to workers'
compensation, resigned Tuesday on his 12th anniversary with the
Massachusetts Division of Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Steven D'Amato, who has headed the rating bureau for nearly
seven years, said ``a lot of factors'' went into his decision to
leave, but declined to elaborate. ``I can tell you I'm not leaving
because the auto industry is asking for a 15 percent increase in
rates. I would have looked forward to fighting that.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato, 40, did not outline any specific job plans, but said he
expects to continue working on insurance issues. ``I want to prove
you can leave the division of insurance without working for an
insurance company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His resignation is effective Sept. 8. A spokesman said the
division expects to name an interim replacement soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
