<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-HMO-SENIORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HMOS HIT UNLIMITED PRESCRIPTION COVERAGE FOR SENIORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For years, seniors in Massachusetts have enjoyed a
unique benefit under state law _ unlimited prescription drug
coverage for those who join Medicare health maintainance
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   That benefit, the most generous in America, could soon
disappear.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs, backed by federal regulators, are arguing that a 1997
federal law exempts them from Massachusetts regulations &UR;  &LR;  requiring
unlimited drug coverage, and other benefits called for by state
law.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is the only state that requires unlimited
prescription coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of curtailed drug benefits has alarmed senior
advocates, and incensed state regulators who insist that HMOs
comply with Massachusetts law. More than 211,500 seniors in the
state belong to HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I simply will not stand by and let these benefits be cut,''
said Acting Governor Paul Cellucci, who fired off a strongly worded
letter Tuesday to Donna E. Shalala, US secretary of health and
human services, urging her to require HMOs to comply with
Massachusetts standards. Shalala's office declined to comment, as
did the US Health Care Financing Administration, an agency under
HHS that regulates Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   State health officials say they have tried for months to clear
up the apparent conflict by approaching HCFA, but the agency hasn't
responded.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some HMOs are proceeding with plans to scale back
drug benefits, beginning January 1999. The move in Massachusetts
comes amid similar measures by HMOs across the country to cope with
soaring drug costs and reduced Medicare reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Massachusetts proposals awaiting federal approval: &UR;  &LR; 
_Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Massachusetts said it has applied
to &UR;  &LR;  the federal government for permission to cap prescription drug
coverage at $1,200 a year and charge $60 in monthly premiums for
its BlueCare 65 HMO. Medex Gold, a ``Medigap'' product seniors buy
to supplement their traditional Medicare coverage, will continue to
offer unlimited drug benefits, as required by state law.
</P>
<P>
   _Harvard Pilgrim Health Care, which has about 60,000 seniors in
its First Seniority HMO, has proposed to offer a maximum of $800 in
prescription drug benefits per calendar year at no charge to
seniors in Eastern Massachusetts, sources familiar with the filings
said. In Western Massachusetts, seniors would pay a $25 monthly
premium.
</P>
<P>
   Tufts Health Plan, which operates Secure Horizons, the largest
Medicare HMO in the state, said it had filed a request with HCFA to
sell a plan with limited drug benefits, but declined to reveal its
figures.
</P>
<P>
   Fallon Community Health Plan in Worcester is still planning to
continue offering an unlimited drug plan in 1999, according to Jay
Egan, co-executive director of Fallon. But Egan said that could
change.
</P>
<P>
   HMO executives say they are caught in a dilemma. The Balanced
Budget Act of 1997 frees Medicare HMOs from state benefit mandates.
Health plans say they would like to offer unlimited drug benefits.
But if any single plan becomes the only one in the market with full
drug benefits while others limit benefits, only the sickest seniors
needing the most medications _ who are the most expensive seniors
to insure &UR;  &LR; _ &UR;  &LR; would flock to the plan with unlimited benefits, HMO
officials say. That would make the plan's &UR;  &LR;  potential losses
staggering, executives say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harvard Pilgrim believes that the best public policy would be
for every Medicare HMO in Massachusetts to offer full drug
coverage,'' said Patti &UR;  &LR; Embry-Tautenhan,  &UR;  &LR; a spokeswoman for
Harvard. ``However, unless all Medicare HMOs offer full drug
coverage, it would be financially irresponsible for us to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   While all HMOs can theoretically agree to offer only unlimited
drug benefits, such an agreement could violate state antitrust
laws, &UR;  &LR; according to Alan Raymond, a spokesman for Harvard Pilgrim.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond one way to assure all HMOs comply with state law is for
the state Division of Insurance to secure a court ruling requiring
health plans to adhere to state law.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Klein, a spokesman for the Division of Insurance Tuesday
said court action ``is definitely an option, if we feel companies
are in violation of state law.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Klein said the division is working with the state attorney
general's office on the issue. Barbara Anthony, chief of the
attorney general's public protection bureau, said, ``It's our
position that state law applies in this matter.'' She declined to
say whether her office would be pressing the case in court.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates in Massachusetts are stewed over what they see as a
retreat by HMOs. ``It's outrageous,'' said Geoff Wilkinson,
executive director of Massachusetts Senior Action Council. ``This
is the kind of greed and self interest that leads consumers to
demand HMO reform.''
</P>
</TEXT>
