<HEADER>
A1285 &Cx1f; tth-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      08-19 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY SHOULD WE EVER BELIEVE ANYTHING BILL CLINTON TELLS US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SOLVEIG TORVIK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's heartening to learn that Bill Clinton is capable of
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   At least, he says he is _ for what little that's worth.
</P>
<P>
   He told us Monday night that he ``misled'' us and his family
about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky out of ``a
desire to protect myself from the embarrassment of my own
conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Was he embarrassed as well about having persisted in a lie for
seven months? He didn't say.
</P>
<P>
   It also should put our minds at rest to learn Clinton never
pressured anyone to lie under oath. Of course, he's hardly a
credible source of information on that question. Or on any other
question, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   How can we ever again believe anything this man says?
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it: Bill Clinton is finished.
</P>
<P>
   He's demeaned the presidency and himself. He may hang on by his
fingernails and manage to complete his term, but he will not be
attending to the business we hired him to tackle.
</P>
<P>
   He's an exceedingly troublesome, high-maintenance,
low-productivity employee whose ongoing legal difficulties will
cost us, his employers, even more millions. Meanwhile, the
controversy over his behavior will further paralyze the government.
</P>
<P>
   Not once during his short, forced mea culpa Monday night did the
``s'' word ever cross Clinton' lips. The ``s'' word being shame.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no other word than shame to describe what Clinton's
base behavior has brought to the presidency and to the nation. It
has further lowered the public's respect for politicians and for
the country's political system. This is dangerous for our democracy
and harmful to the republic.
</P>
<P>
   In the past when Clinton has had to confess his transgressions
in public, he's been a perfect picture of contrition and humility.
He's a master manipulator, and he's had lots of experience in
manipulating people into giving him yet another chance.
</P>
<P>
   We should have seen what was coming: This was a man who smoked
marijuana but didn't inhale; one who avoided the draft but who
didn't really try to dodge it.
</P>
<P>
   These incidents telegraphed a pattern of convenient
compartmentalizing of bad behavior, of the hair-splitting and
evasion that has become the hallmark of his disappointing
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has all the earmarks of a man without a moral center.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night there was none of that calculated humility that has
served him so well in the past. There were excuses, however: He
didn't tell the truth about his behavior because he was trying to
protect his family. But the time to think of protecting his family
was before indulging himself with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Almost lost in the din of legalistic and political parsing of
the scandal are certain fundamental elements of this sordid chapter
of American history that need to stay front and center:
</P>
<P>
   First, we didn't elect Clinton to turn the Oval Office and its
precincts into a pornographic playroom.
</P>
<P>
   We have no right to expect perfection in presidents; Jesus
Christ is not standing for office. But where much is given, much is
expected. So we do have every right to expect a certain standard of
decent behavior from those we honor with leadership of the nation.
If presidents cannot be expected to comport themselves within the
basic bounds of decency and propriety, of whom can we ask it?
</P>
<P>
   Nor did we elect Clinton to gratify his sexual appetites with
the hired help _ however compliant.
</P>
<P>
   Monica Lewinsky may fit the archaic, pre-Sexual Revolution
definition of a loose woman, but there's no escaping the fact that
Clinton was the most powerful man on the planet and she was a
powerless intern as young as his own daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The country is littered with hapless ex-bosses who lost their
jobs over much less appalling sexual impropriety with subordinates.
Feminist blather about consensual sex to the contrary, Clinton had
the classic advantage of power in this calamitous conjugation of
two needy people. Even if Lewinsky threw herself at him, he,
supposedly, is the grown-up here.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a grown-up, however, what we have in the White House
is an admitted liar, a world-class hypocrite who pays lip service
to ``family values'' and a man of incredibly flawed judgment in
whom we have vested the awesome responsibility of commander in
chief of the world's sole superpower.
</P>
<P>
   But if this man cannot control himself, how can he be entrusted
with the immense power of the presidency?
</P>
<P>
   Clinton repeatedly has asked for our trust but repeatedly has
shown that he is to be neither trusted nor believed. His political
legacy is a long list of broken promises. In short, he is not a man
of his word.
</P>
<P>
   Who's going to take him seriously? He's become a smutty joke.
</P>
<P>
   How can a man thus crippled govern?
</P>
<P>
   The personal tragedy of Bill Clinton is that he's uniquely
gifted with talent for leadership but has shown himself unfit to
lead. His was a presidency of great promise, but he's thrown it
away.
</P>
<P>
   If he truly cares about his family, Clinton should seek
professional treatment.
</P>
<P>
   And if he truly cares about the nation, there's still one
honorable, redeeming thing left for Bill Clinton to do: resign.
</P>
<P>
   Solveig Torvik is a member of the P-I Editorial Board. E-mail:
solveigtorvik(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
