<P>
   JOURNAL-CHERNOBYL _ DRUZNY, Belarus _ Fear continues to haunt
these Chernobyl survivors, who fled their contaminated town
following the world's worst nuclear accident 12 years ago. About
1,000 men, women and children of Chernobyl were relocated to
Druzny, a grim Belarussian town built amid a swamp. Here, living in
dilapidated apartment blocs, they have largely been forgotten by
the authorities, left to struggle with the legacy of the accident.
The children of Chernobyl are growing up -- sick, unable to find
jobs, scared to bear their own children, and short of necessary
medicines. And the cruelest irony of all: For years following
Chernobyl, the government of Belarus planned to build a new nuclear
power plant beside them in their new town of Druzny. Finally, two
years ago, those plans were shelved. But the result was bittersweet
-- no plant meant no new jobs, which means continued economic
hardship for many. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
