<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REGGAE-DOCTOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DR. COSMO' PRESCRIBES NEW MEANING FOR REGGAE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CRAIG MARINE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Cosmo Fraser can get the same fire in his eyes
talking about the way kidney failure can negatively affect the
brain as he can discussing the merits of the current crop of reggae
artists.
</P>
<P>
   Which may seem strange until you understand that Dr. Cosmo
Fraser, chief of geriatric nephrology at the Veterans
Administration Hospital in San Francisco, has just released his
second reggae album. And he maintains his double life so well that
many of those he works with are not aware of his non-medical
pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they do find out, they get a funny look on their face to
see if I am serious, but then they love it,'' Fraser says. ``And I
love it when I play a concert and look into the audience and there
are all these doctors and scientists swaying to the beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Fraser is sitting in his cramped office in one of the maze of
buildings on the sprawling hospital campus. Among the piles of
paper on his desk are some of the scads of articles he has had
published in medical journals, including the classic ``Fatal
Central Diabetes Mellitus and Insipidus Resulting from Untreated
Hyponatremia: A New Syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll talk your ear off about kidneys if you're interested, but
for the moment, it's music that's on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think reggae used to be more creative than it is today,'' he
says contemplatively. ``Nowadays, the emphasis is so much on the
beat, getting the strong beat, that many of the other elements have
become secondary _ things like the melody, or the message. I
strongly believe that of all music, reggae should have some kind of
message, whether about love or social activism _ something that
speaks to people beyond the hypnotic beat.''
</P>
<P>
   That commitment comes through on Fraser's new record, ``Fire
This Time,'' released on Ginger Girl Records and distributed by
Ruff Stuff Records. He records under the name Cosmo, and his songs
are loaded with tales of love and justice and struggle. Make no
mistake about it, Fraser has some reggae heavyweights on the
record, musicians who have recorded with Bob Marley and Toots and
the Maytals. They provide a solid, melodic background to Fraser's
smooth, firm vocals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a doctor who plays music,'' Fraser says easily. ``This
isn't just some little hobby with me. This is a passion.''
</P>
<P>
   Fraser, in his early 40s, came to the United States from Jamaica
with his family when he was 19. He always sang, winning contests on
the island as well as in his adopted homeland. Growing up, music
was everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Jamaica, when you are riding your bike, there is a
different song coming out of every house,'' he says. ``There is
music in the birds chirping, in almost every sound. It was a great
place if you were interested in music _ the love of music was
encouraged.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, so was the love of learning. Fraser studied computer
science and electrical engineering before becoming interested in
medicine. Whatever he does, he does full force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know when I am on stage that the audience has no idea about
my second career,'' he says. ``And that's how it should be. Music
feeds the creative part of my soul, it helps make me a more
complete person.''
</P>
<P>
   Fraser is serious enough about his music that he is kicking
around the idea of taking some time off from his medical work to
devote to his reggae career. He talks about the possibility of
hooking up with a major tour soon, although nothing is set and he
is hesitant to jinx things by talking too much about what might
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have accomplished quite a lot in the medical field,'' he
says simply _ and modestly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I feel most strongly about my music,'' he smiles,
putting a large hand over his heart. ``It is what calls to me right
now, what gives me the most satisfaction. I'd like to find out
where it might take me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
