<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERB-GARLIC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARLIC: THE GARDEN'S BRIGHTEST BULB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL NUCKOLS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABCs: Garlic is a compound bulb composed of up to 15 cloves,
enclosed in a papery sheath. Garlic is an annual that reaches 12
inches in height.
</P>
<P>
   Growing conditions: Plant from cloves in October, 2 inches deep
and 6 inches apart. Plant in rich soil in full sun or some shade.
</P>
<P>
   Companion plants: Keeps aphids off roses. Also, interplant with
eggplant, cabbage, tomatoes and fruit trees.
</P>
<P>
   Food pairings: Butter, cheese, bread, beans, meats, fish,
poultry, vinegar, tomato sauce, eggplant and other vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   TOMATOES STUFFED WITH HERB CHEESE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   8 large, ripe Italian plum tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces low-fat Neufchatel cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces chevre or feta cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon EACH fresh basil, mint, parsley and thyme, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Cut tomatoes in half lengthwise and scoop out seeds. Drain and
reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Place cheeses, garlic, herbs, salt and pepper in a mixing bowl
and stir to blend well, or mix in a food processor. Add a little
milk, olive oil or lemon juice if mixture seems too dry. (It should
be loose but moist enough to hold together when pressed.)
</P>
<P>
   Spoon some of cheese mixture into each tomato half. Serve as is
or broil to brown the cheese slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 177 calories, 9 grams fat, 20
grams carbohydrates, 8 grams protein, 23 milligrams cholesterol,
502 milligrams sodium, 47 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Beautiful Easy Herbs'' by Laurence Sombke (Rodale Press,
$27.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   WHOLE ROASTED GARLIC WITH ASADERO OR BRIE CHEESE AND
TOMATILLO-CILANTRO SALSA
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   4 whole bulbs garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   For the tomatillo-cilantro salsa:
</P>
<P>
   1/3 pound tomatillos, husks removed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 small white onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 fresh serrano chile, stemmed
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 bunch fresh cilantro or flat-leaf parsley, stemmed
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces asadero or brie cheese, cut into 4 equal pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 loaf French bread
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare garlic bulbs for roasting, remove excess papery skin
but leave bulbs whole. Cut off top 1/2 inch of each bulb, exposing
tops of individual cloves. If some clove tops remain uncut, take a
little slice off each with a paring knife to expose the inside.
</P>
<P>
   Place garlic bulbs, cut sides up, in a deep-sided casserole or
loaf pan and add water to reach halfway up sides of bulbs. Drizzle
olive oil evenly over tops of bulbs. Cover tightly with aluminum
foil and place in oven. Bake until cloves feel soft, about 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, prepare salsa. Place tomatillos, onion, garlic, chile
and water in a blender or food processor fitted with the metal
blade. Add cilantro or parsley and whirl until smooth. If preparing
salsa ahead of time, do not add cilantro or parsley until just
before serving, because it will lose its flavor and bright green
color. Makes about 3/4 cup salsa.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, preheat broiler. Place 1 piece of cheese on each of 4
flameproof serving plates. Run plates under broiler until cheese
just begins to melt, 3 to 5 minutes. Be careful not to allow cheese
to melt into a puddle. Place a garlic bulb next to cheese and flood
plate with salsa. Accompany with French bread. Give each diner an
oyster fork to lift garlic cloves whole from their skins for
spreading onto bread.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 423 calories, 27 grams fat, 31
grams carbohydrates, 14 grams protein, 43 milligrams cholesterol,
870 milligrams sodium, 58 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Cafe Pasqual's Cookbook: Spirited Recipes From Santa Fe/ by
Katharine Kagel (Chronicle, $18.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
