A1355 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-HEMLINES-ART-     08-19 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-HEMLINES-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEMLINES COMING DOWN FOR THE FALL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Thursday, Aug. 20) 
(Eds.: Photo available on NYT photo service) 
 
By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This fall marks a defining moment in the century's fashion
history, as women make the shift from short to long hemlines.
</P>
<P>
   While some will cry foul, that they will not be the pawns of
fashion designers, longer hemlines are merely a trend whose time
has come _ again.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1986 when the miniskirt burst on the fashion scene for
the second time, following its first blush of success in the '60s
and '70s. It took awhile for women to warm up to the mini again,
but it was not long before all hemlines adjusted upward. Now they
are headed south again.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors make this fall's longer skirts feel right.
First, women have embraced the long, body-skimming slip and tank
dresses for several seasons. This summer, they have become almost a
uniform, especially in the superheated Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Women like the ease and comfort of the long dresses that swish
around their legs, allowing them to wear knee-highs or no stockings
and still show their ankles to best advantage. They'll want more of
these styles come fall.
</P>
<P>
   Second, women admire the costumes from the romantic movie
``Titanic,'' as well as the clothing they see cinema stars wearing
for the Academy Awards ceremony and in magazine style stories.
Female movie stars have supplanted supermodels as style heroines.
</P>
<P>
   A third reason longer skirts may be slated for success this fall
is because of accompanying trends _ sweaters, thick wools and
tweeds, fur trims and luxury goods and fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these trends looks better _ looks ``right'' _ when worn
with a long skirt, whether just below the knee, at midcalf or at
the ankle. Most designers agree that it is difficult to make a
miniskirt look luxurious _ or elicit women's investment clothing
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The final, perhaps overwhelming reason women may embrace longer
hemlines is that the key piece of clothing for fall _ the
``uniform,'' if you wish _ is the long, black, A-line skirt.
</P>
<P>
   In a fluid fabric, usually slit up one side, this skirt can tie
together many pieces already in most closets _ sweaters, jackets,
white or colored cotton or silk shirts _ and it allows women a
transition from their comfy summer dresses. And this long skirt
looks as good with boots as it does with flat shoes or high heels.
</P>
<P>
   But long is not confined to skirts. This fall's styles seem to
revolve around longer jackets. Even if they're of normal length,
the waists are nipped in a bit so the jacket appears longer.
</P>
<P>
   Other manifestations of long include longer sleeves on sweaters
and jackets, some that run on past the fingertips and demand to be
pushed up the arm. Sweaters and knit tops extend to tunic length,
offering women the benefit of a long, lean look. And overcoats are
seven-eighths length for casual wear or swashbuckler long and full
for dress.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to thinking long, women always turn their
attention to their hemlines. Chances are that most will find that
the longer suits and dresses in stores this fall look more ladylike
and feminine. Simply put, they go hand in hand with today's more
serious outlook.
</P>
<P>
   A good gray suit with a slim skirt that falls below the knee is
an investment in career dressing. A good black wool dress that
falls straight to midcalf with only a tiny slit at the back hem is
another long-term choice.
</P>
<P>
   Pick a long knit or jersey dress with long sleeves that could be
worn day or evening. With flats or short boots and a leather bag,
it goes to work, lunch, shopping or carpooling. With pearls or
glittering accessories and strappy sandals, it goes out after dark.
</P>
<P>
   An unusual aspect of several New York designer collections was
the longer, elliptically shaped skirt. Slim at the hips, it flares
out to a sort of squashed balloon shape over the knees, then rounds
back in at midcalf or at the ankles.
</P>
<P>
   Sound strange? It also looked otherworldly and made walking
difficult for the models. Chances are that few of these will show
up on store racks for fall.
</P>
<P>
   One trend for winter that could cause women angst is that of
wearing coats shorter than skirts. Most New York runways featured
coats slightly below the knee over dresses that fell to midcalf or
near the ankles.
</P>
<P>
   This trend makes for a ``poor'' look, as in ``she's so poor, she
can't afford a new coat to cover her dress.'' Nevertheless, we are
destined to see it, because it has already been adopted by those
who dote on Prada, Gucci and Dolce &AMP; Gabbana styles.
</P>
<P>
   A few aberrations aside, this fall's new lengths will probably
be popular with most women who seem ready for a change in fashion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 1426EDT &QL; 
