<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHWESTERN CRAB CAKES FROM DEAN FEARING'S FILE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anna Capriotti of Arlington, Texas, would like the recipe for
crab cakes served at The Mansion on Turtle Creek. Here's Dean
Fearing recipe from ``Southwest Cuisine'' (Grove Weidenfeld, $30).
</P>
<P>
   PAN-FRIED CRAB CAKES
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   1 extra-large egg, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon curry powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon celery salt
</P>
<P>
   1/3 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   3 or 4 drops Tabasco sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound fresh jumbo lump crab meat, picked clean of shell and
cartilage
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 to 2 tablespoons dry bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup corn oil
</P>
<P>
   In mixing bowl, combine egg, mayonnaise and seasoning. Add crab
and enough bread crumbs to absorb excess moisture. Toss to blend
well, but don't overmix. Mixture should be just firm enough to hold
together. Adjust seasonings as desired. Form into 12 patties and
place on waxed paper in cold place for 20 minutes to dry slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Pour oil into skillet to depth of 1/2 inch. Place over high heat
and heat to 350 degrees. When temperature is right, gently add crab
cakes and fry for about 3 minutes per side or until golden brown on
both sides. Don't crowd pan; fry in several batches if necessary.
Drain on paper towel and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 68 calories, 15 grams fat, 2
grams carbohydrates, 14 grams protein, 152 milligrams cholesterol,
358 milligrams sodium, 68 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   More muffins: Bette Johnson of North Richland Hills, Texas, saw
our request for muffin recipes and sent the following.
</P>
<P>
   ALMOND POPPY SEED MUFFINS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 30
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 3/4 cup evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   2 cups vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   4 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon almond extract
</P>
<P>
   1/4 to 1/3 cup poppy seeds (to taste)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 325 degrees. Line 30 muffin cups with paper
liners. In a large mixing bowl, beat together eggs, sugar,
evaporated milk, milk and vegetable oil. Sift together baking
powder, salt and flour. Gradually add flour mixture to egg mixture,
beating until well-combined. Add the extracts and poppy seeds,
stirring only until well-combined. Using a 1/3-cup measure, pour
batter into muffin cups. Bake for 25-30 minutes or until toothpick
inserted into center of muffin comes out clean.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 185 calories, 7 grams fat, 27
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 47 milligrams cholesterol,
147 milligrams sodium, 32 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
