<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1390 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     08-19 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S `PAST TIME' IN ALL SORTS OF WAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You call that an apology? You call that closure?
</P>
<P>
   ``Mea culpa,'' my eye.
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to President Clinton to insist on having it both ways:
to claim that he is taking ``complete responsibility'' for his
actions and in the next breath to blame somebody else for the mess
he's in.
</P>
<P>
   That's Slick Willie for you. He smoked marijuana but didn't
inhale. He caused pain in his marriage but didn't have an affair.
And now he admits that he ``misled'' people but can't bring himself
to say that he lied.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was on television for just over four minutes Monday
night, delivering a speech that had been touted as his ``mea
culpa'' for having an affair with Monica Lewinsky and trying to
cover it up. He spent much of the time complaining about
independent counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   If this was an apology, it was an odd one. The words ``I'm
sorry'' never crossed Clinton's lips.
</P>
<P>
   If the president's speech was a confession of previous lies and
illicit sex, it was odder still. He acknowledged only that his
relationship with Lewinsky was ``not appropriate.'' His earlier
statements and nonstatements, he said, ``gave a false impression.''
</P>
<P>
   A false impression?
</P>
<P>
   A false impression is conveyed by ``Honey, I got in a little
late last night'' when in fact you got home two minutes before the
alarm went off this morning. You give a false impression when you
say, ``I had a rough day at work,'' when in fact you had a bad
morning but you spent the afternoon playing golf.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton looked us in the eye and said, ``I did not have
sexual relations with that woman,'' he was doing a lot more than
giving a false impression. He was lying through his teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, most of us knew he was lying, which means that this
half-baked confession he tried to palm off the other night was no
big surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Only the most naive and hopelessly devoted Clintonite could have
believed him when he denied the affair with Lewinsky. Sure, plenty
of Americans ``hoped'' he was telling the truth, but just about
every public-opinion poll indicated that most people were aware
that he was lying.
</P>
<P>
   The polls also indicated that most people didn't care. Even as
Clinton's ratings for honesty and integrity revealed that his
constituents didn't trust him as far as they could throw him, his
job approval marks zipped along in the 60-plus range. As Clinton
sat down to testify before Starr's grand jury on Monday, one poll
gave him a job approval score of 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton testified and offered up his so-called apology, a
``USA Today''/CNN/Gallup poll suggested that the number of
Americans who held a favorable opinion of him plunged 20 points to
40 percent. But his job approval rating stayed high: 62 percent.
</P>
<P>
   So here's the deal: Most citizens of the world's lone remaining
superpower know that our nation's commander in chief is a
dishonest, untrustworthy creep _ but they don't care because he's
doing a good job as president.
</P>
<P>
   Makes you proud to be an American, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   The pundits are saying that we'll have to wait a few days or
weeks before we draw any conclusions about the impact _ or
nonimpact _ of Clinton's grand jury testimony and post-testimony
remarks. But early polls say that most Americans have had it up to
here with Starr's investigation and with the media's inexhaustible
fixation on Clinton's sexual proclivities.
</P>
<P>
   They want the ordeal to end.
</P>
<P>
   And why shouldn't they? It isn't news to most Americans that
Clinton is a compulsive philanderer and a pathological liar. His
reputation along these lines was well-established and
well-publicized long before he lapsed into inappropriateness with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   If Starr has proof that Clinton broke the law, he needs to hand
it over to Congress as soon as possible so that the House of
Representatives can decide whether the president ought to be
impeached. Clinton's ``mea culpa'' may have been a flop, but one
line rang true:
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it is time _ in fact, it is past time _ to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
