A1434 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TWOODESSAS-TEX     08-19 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWOODESSAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAN ODESSANS PLANNING BIG BARBECUE FOR UKRAINIAN ODESSANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ When the Chuck Wagon Gang of Odessa in West
Texas decides it wants to put on a feed, little things like
geography, politics, cultural and language differences don't matter
much.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-seven members of the 250-member group will pack their
cooking supplies the first week of September for a trip to their
city's namesake, Odessa, Ukraine. It is a journey the group has
planned for nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gang has been messing with this idea for a long time,
about 10 years,'' said Jerry Hensley, a trip coordinator. ``It is
fairly complicated. This year we decided to do it, and we contacted
our U.S. representative, Larry Combest. He sent a letter to the
State Department and got their approval.''
</P>
<P>
   Hensley said the two Odessas have exchanged about 700 e-mail
messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an advance trip,'' he said. ``But it is so far away,
and there is the language barrier _ but I believe we've about got
it now. We've got all our tickets and all our visas. If we don't go
now, we've wasted a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   The Odessa Chuck Wagon Gang was formed in 1940 to help promote
Odessa and West Texas. The group patterned itself after the old
chuck wagon cooks of early cattle drives. They cook their beef over
open pits, with a pot of beans on the side.
</P>
<P>
   The Chuck Wagon Gang has served meals throughout the United
States. It served more than 40,000 plates at the Grand Ole Opry;
and 30,000 at Klondike Days in Edmonton, Canada. The group has
traveled to Scotland, Norway, Costa Rica and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever they go, the menu is always the same: Texas barbecue,
pinto beans, pickles, onions, coleslaw, iced tea, bread and coffee.
</P>
<P>
   In Ukraine, however, there won't be any iced tea. That is a
strange notion to the Odessans, Hensley said. ``I think we'll be
serving Coke,'' he said. ``If not, lemonade.''
</P>
<P>
   The group will cook ``West Texas barbecue beef,'' Hensley said.
``We'll have coleslaw, pinto beans, pickles and onions.'' The beef,
however, will not be from Texas. A local slaughterhouse will
provide the inside round the Gang uses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did ship over a bunch of foil pans to use as serving
pans,'' he said. ``We also shipped some napkin packs, containing
napkins, toothpicks, plastic utensils, salt, pepper and sugar.
Everything else, we're buying over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Special grills have been built in Ukraine to handle the
barbecue. There is also a specially built, 200-gallon bean pot.
</P>
<P>
   The Gang plans to feed about 1,200 Odessans, including 500
businessmen, 100 expatriates, 100 members of the Odessa
Philharmonic Orchestra, and about 500 orphans and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the advance trip, we saw that the orphanage was very, very
poor,'' Hensley said. ``We decided helping them would be a part of
this trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoes are a common need for the children at the orphanage. Chuck
Wagon Gang members at first thought of taking several hundred pairs
with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found out that we could buy good quality shoes there,
cheaper than we could take them with us,'' Hensley said. ``We can
buy good shoes for $8 or $9 a pair. We're hoping to buy about 300
pairs. Missionaries living there are already getting the sizes.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the advance party made an immediate gift of $400 to
the orphanage. They were later told that it was the largest single
donation the orphanage had ever received. It was used to buy a
washing machine.
</P>
<P>
   Odessa, Texas, it has always been said, was named by Russian
railroad workers laying tracks for the Texas and Pacific Railway
back in the 1880s. Somehow, the motion of the tall prairie grasses
reminded the workers of their homeland. Some say this was because
the swaying grasses resembled the wave action of the Black Sea;
others say it was the vastness of West Texas that reminded the
workers of home.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, Odessa, Texas, and Odessa, Ukraine, look nothing
alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their city doesn't look anything like ours,'' Hensley said.
``They have a very nice town, but there are a lot of trees; it is a
seaport. It doesn't look like Odessa, Texas, at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Each member of the Chuck Wagon Gang has paid $2,400 for the
trip. An advance team will leave Sept. 5; the others will follow
Sept. 8.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
