<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1479 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-HNS &LR;      08-19 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PREDICAMENT WOULD NOT HAVE HAPPENED IN EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
   News Analysis  
 (For use by New York Times New Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ With few exceptions, the predicament President Clinton
finds himself in over the Monica Lewinsky affair wouldn't have
happened in Europe, where chiefs of state are tacitly regarded as
above the law.
</P>
<P>
   Only in Britain could a prime minister find himself challenged,
as Clinton has been, about his personal sexual behavior. Elsewhere,
no one would ask questions. Yet even if queries were raised,
government leaders could lie flagrantly _ many have _ and be
confident of getting away with it.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Britain, there would be no question of legal
proceedings. Nor would a delinquent prime minister face impeachment
_ although impeachment is a concept developed under British law.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he or she would be called on to appear before the House
of Commons. Since a majority of members invariably belong to the
prime minister's own party, a generally unfriendly reception would
bring about the PM's instant resignation.
</P>
<P>
   However, in the rest of Europe it's well established that
government leaders, whatever they may have done, are treated more
leniently than ordinary citizens.
</P>
<P>
   According to French historian Didier Camus, ``It is the old
monarchical principle at work. In the old Europe, kings in theory
could do no wrong, and the law did not apply to them. Something of
that idea has lingered on. A difference is still made in people's
minds between rulers and the rest of us.''
</P>
<P>
   In France, the late President Francois Mitterrand secretly
housed his lover and their daughter at public expense in a
government apartment throughout his 14-year presidency between 1981
and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors about the situation surfaced regularly, but when a
Mitterrand biographer published details of it in 1993, there was
virtually no reaction. Presidential critics didn't demand an
investigation into whether there had been a misuse of state
property, although that was clearly so. The matter was simply
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1990s, Italy has gone through an almost non-stop
string of government corruption scandals that destroyed most of the
postwar political parties and touched nearly every leading
politician. But none has served time in prison. Those found guilty
of graft have received suspended sentences. Some, like onetime
Prime Minister and Socialist Party chief Bennino Craxi, have been
discreetly allowed to leave Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Former Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi, who rose to political
prominence in the wave of reform that followed the scandals, is now
himself accused of attempting to bribe tax officials. But Italian
legal specialists say everything has been arranged so that the
worst he is threatened with is a six-month suspended sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Guilio Andreotti, another former prime minister, has been on
trial for the past four years accused of collusion with the Mafia.
He is 79 and analysts have predicted the case won't be wound up
during his lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when they are arrested and put on trial, which is seldom,
powerful European politicians rarely suffer severe consequences,''
Camus noted. ``The system works like that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 1529EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
