<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GOV-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATES SPAR OVER CALIFORNIA'S DEATH PENALTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRESNO, Calif. _ In the heart of California's Central Valley,
the second gubernatorial debate was billed as a forum on the earthy
issues of agriculture, water policy and suburban sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican Attorney General Dan Lungren and Democratic Lt.
Gov. Gray Davis spent much of the hour Tuesday bickering over
abortion, the death penalty and whether the state should issue
education vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates' most extended argument of the evening came on
the issue of the death penalty, which both support.
</P>
<P>
   Davis went on the attack first, criticizing Lungren for
``distorting'' his votes in the Assembly on death-penalty issues
during the first debate in San Diego when he accused Davis of
voting twice to subvert the state's death-penalty law.
</P>
<P>
   Before the debate, Davis' staff passed out a letter from Rep.
Gary Condit, D-Calif., saying Davis supported his ``major
death-penalty legislation'' in 1985, the same vote Lungren brought
up in San Diego, and that anyone who suggests Davis is not 100
percent pro-death penalty is misleading the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is you're for the death penalty and I'm for
the death penalty,'' Davis told Lungren, ``and you're trying to
deceive people on some procedural votes, and I think we need to get
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Lungren, however, said he believed Davis and other Democrats at
the time were involved in an effort to make ``fig-leaf votes'' on
the death penalty while at the same time attempting to weaken the
law or voting against attempts to strengthen it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I defended the death penalty,'' Lungren said. ``You fooled
around with the death penalty. You made fun of the death penalty.
You played games with the death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point during a shouting match over the issue, Davis told
Lungren to ``get real.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate at California State University at Fresno was the
second in a series of five televised forums leading to the Nov. 3
election. The next debate is scheduled for Sept. 23 in Sacramento,
followed by October matchups in the San Francisco and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lungren and Davis will spend tens of millions of
dollars on television commercials, the debates are an effort to run
a campaign the old-fashioned way, focusing on issues. Lungren just
finished a traditional bus tour of the Central Valley and Davis
planned a four-stop bus trip Wednesday from Fresno to Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   During the debate, the clearest divisions between the two
candidates emerged over the issues of abortion and some education
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren, for instance, said he supports vouchers, tax dollars
given to parents to send their children to private schools. Davis
said he would support vouchers only as a last resort.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something fundamentally wrong when we allow the
bureaucracy to dictate what we are doing with the kids, when
obviously things are failing,'' Lungren said. ``I think vouchers
will ... be the greatest injection of competition in order to
kick-start the schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said the better answer would be to improve standards for
the state's 6 million public school children and hold teachers to
higher standards and peer review.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe vouchers are an easy answer to a tough problem,''
Davis said. At a news conference after the debate, he said he would
consider them only after every other education reform failed.
</P>
<P>
   On abortion, Davis pointed to Lungren's vote, while in Congress,
for the Human Life Amendment, which would have made abortions
illegal even in the case of rape and incest. And he noted that
Lungren voted 10 times to deny federal funding for abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've made it clear that you don't trust women to control
their own bodies,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren, without saying whether he really wanted to deny the
victims of rape and incest the right to an abortion, countered with
a vague explanation that he simply was trying to provoke debate on
the issue of abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're asking, `Did I engage in debate as to whether or not
it's a great thing to have millions of abortions,' you're
absolutely right,'' Lungren said.
</P>
<P>
   After the debate, Lungren said he wished the focus had been more
on agriculture, water and education issues important to the Central
Valley, but blamed Davis for bringing up abortion and other wedge
issues. Davis said he wasn't troubled about the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren avoided direct criticism of Davis' close political
association with President Clinton, who helped the Democratic
candidate raise more than $3 million last week during a one-day
swing through California.
</P>
<P>
   When Davis was asked about the president's admission of having
an inappropriate relationship with a former White House intern, he
said he accepted Clinton's apology and would welcome the president
in a return visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said what he did was wrong. He said it was a critical lapse
of judgment,'' Davis said. ``I accept his apology and I think it's
time to move on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
