<HEADER>
A1518 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-BREAST-CANCER     08-19 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-BREAST-CANCER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATIONWIDE STUDY CITES KEY ELEMENTS OF GOOD MANAGED CARE PLANS
FOR BREAST CANCER TREATMENT
 &HT;    By DANIELLE SHOOK
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Early detection, a comprehensive tracking program
and a care coordinator are among the key elements that managed care
plans should provide breast cancer patients, according to a
yearlong study released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The American Association of Health Plans and The Commonwealth
Fund, a health research foundation, asked 1,000 health plans
nationwide, serving more than 140 million people, to submit their
approaches to breast cancer treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Of the submitted proposals, four companies were chosen as the
best on the following criteria: patient satisfaction; overall
effectiveness; innovation and creativity; quality, relevance and
validity of the program's internal evaluation; and the ability for
other health plans to replicate and implement the program.
</P>
<P>
   The health care providers _ Humana Health Plan of Chicago,
Keystone Mercy Health Plan of Pennsylvania, Kaiser Permanente of
California in partnership with WIN Against Breast Cancer, and Blue
Cross/Blue Shield of Massachusetts in partnership with the American
Psychological Association _ developed the following questions women
should ask their health care plan provider:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Does your health plan have an aggressive and effective system
to remind and encourage patients to receive breast cancer
screenings?
</P>
<P>
   Early detection through mammography, clinical breast exam and
self examination are critical. More than 90 percent of women whose
cancer is detected and treated in its early stages are cancer-free
after five years. Health plans must develop systems for ensuring
members know about and utilize breast cancer screening services.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Does your health plan have a comprehensive tracking system to
ensure every patient's treatment progress is carefully monitored at
all times?
</P>
<P>
   Breast cancer becomes increasingly serious as it progresses.
Timeliness is as important as quality when it comes to treatment.
Health plans should develop safeguards to ensure a full range of
breast cancer care is delivered quickly and thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Does your health plan have an effective tracking system to
monitor physician practices?
</P>
<P>
   Managed care plans can develop systems to track individual
physician's practices. This allows doctors to compare therapies
utilized by others, and provides ways for health plans to identify
physicians whose practices fall outside established guidelines.
This also ensures practitioners use current treatments and
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Are your health plan's breast care centers accredited by the
American College of Radiology and certified by the U.S. Food &AMP; Drug
Administration, and have all radiologists received advanced-level
mammography certification?
</P>
<P>
   Mammograms must be of the highest possible quality. An effective
mammogram can detect a tumor up to two years before a doctor or
patient does. But poor handling of the films and inexperienced
staff doing the readings can result in tumors being missed. The FDA
has listed certified breast care facilities for each state at
http://www.fda.gov/cdrh/faclist.html. ((CQ))
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Does your health plan make breast care more accessible to
low-income women by conducting community-based support?
</P>
<P>
   Mammography and other breast care services should be accessible
to women living in poverty. Breast cancer affects all races, but
death rates are much higher among women of low socio-economic
status, because cancer is often detected at later stages when it is
more aggressive and deadly.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Does your health plan provide breast cancer patients access to
important mental health and emotional support services?
</P>
<P>
   Breast cancer brings up emotional issues regarding femininity,
sexuality and body image. Health plans should offer breast cancer
patients support when dealing with the effects of the disease on
their body, mind, and spirit.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Does your health plan provide patients with a ``breast care
coordinator'' to offer additional support, helping to evaluate
treatment options, monitor treatment progress and identify
additional services?
</P>
<P>
   Women with breast cancer have to make tough decisions about
complicated treatment options. Health plans should provide a
designated staff person _ such as a breast care coordinator _ to
help women decipher information, track their treatment progress and
offer general support.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Does your health plan supply breast cancer patients with
important treatment information in an easy-to-understand format?
</P>
<P>
   Women rely on their health care providers to supply information
to help them make informed choices. Health plans should develop a
standard set of materials and offer it in a variety of easy-to-use
formats. Materials should be written in language and literacy
levels appropriate for the audience.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Does your health plan invest in research programs to evaluate
the effectiveness of pairing alternative therapies with traditional
medical treatments?
</P>
<P>
   Health plans should explore additional methods to provide care
to breast cancer patients, including participating in supplementary
programs. Group psychotherapy programs work as effective companions
to medical therapies, and may increase survival times.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Does your health plan gauge patient satisfaction and program
effectiveness by conducting opinion surveys among patients with
breast cancer?
</P>
<P>
   Health plans need to ask women for their input. Patient
satisfaction is a key for measuring the success of a program and
will assist the plan in providing more comprehensive service to
other breast cancer patients.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
