<SLUG> BC-LOTUS-MICROSOFT-ART-SUB-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LOTUS POSITION: NOTES MAKER CHALLENGES MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (Eliminates graphic.)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; When Lotus Development Corp.'s chief executive, Jeffrey
Papows, strode to the front of a Senate hearing room last month to
join a parade of executives blasting Microsoft Corp.'s business
practices, he was doing an about-face.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Papows had tried to duck the controversy over
whether the software giant uses its dominance in computer operating
systems to unfairly stifle competition in other parts of the
software market. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   After all, Lotus, a Cambridge, Mass. unit of International
Business Machines Corp., has a complex relationship with Microsoft.
It is both a technology partner and a competitor. For that reason,
Papows preferred not to toss rocks at Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   So why the change of heart?
</P>
<P>
   One reason, it would seem, is that Microsoft _ which a few years
back walloped Lotus in the spreadsheet market it virtually invented
and once dominated _ is again breathing down Lotus's neck in the
emerging market for messaging and groupware _ software that lets
distant employees collaborate on a single project or document.
</P>
<P>
   Lotus also pioneered that market in late 1989 with the
introduction of Lotus Notes, following it up with an Internet-based
product called Domino. Today, Notes has more than 25 million users
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1996, the Redmond, Wash.-based Microsoft introduced a
competing product called Exchange _ and it is gaining fast, with
about 16 million copies installed in just two years.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter of this year, Exchange outsold Notes for
the first time, 3 million copies to 2.7 million, according to
figures supplied by Lotus. Although it was Lotus' third-best
quarter ever, it was a milestone that clearly has Lotus worried. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The company is reorganizing its North American sales division
and bringing in new management in hopes of holding off Microsoft's
charge. And IBM &UR;  &LR; is stepping forward to promote Notes as an
integral part of its electronic commerce business strategy,
something it didn't do initially after buying the company in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure is more intense,'' Papows acknowledged in a
recent interview. But he insisted that the heat was being generated
internally and was not coming from IBM, which paid $3.2 billion for
the company, largely to get its hands on Notes.
</P>
<P>
   Papows rejected the notion that his decision to testify against
Microsoft, after resisting for so long, was a desperate attempt to
place blame for his company's shrinking market share.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fair question,'' conceded Papows, who had been pestered
to testify for months by Senator Orrin G. Hatch of Utah, the
Republican chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee, which is
investigating allegations that the world's largest software company
engages inmonopolistic business practices.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch finally wore him down, Papows said, with a personal
appeal. ``He said, `I've talked to a lot of people in the industry,
and not only are you not helping me protect your industry, the fact
that you are not visible on this issue is a deterrent to getting
other CEOs to testify.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He said it was a responsibility I was shirking. Frankly, that
cut pretty deep,'' Papows said.
</P>
<P>
   Papows said that he testified reluctantly, that he was careful
to emphasize that the companies have a good relationship overall,
and that he is not among the legions of ``Bill-bashers,'' people
who love to hate Bill Gates, Microsoft's billionaire chairman.
</P>
<P>
   He told the committee he was concerned that by bundling its
Exchange messaging software, at little or no cost, with other
popular office software, Microsoft was driving prices on groupware
down to zero, effectively locking out other competitors, including
Lotus Notes.
</P>
<P>
   He also complained that Microsoft was using its dominance of
operating systems, which control a computer's basic functions, to
force computer makers to pre-load Exchange onto their machines,
again locking out competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you own the bridge &UR;  &LR; and control the toll gate, pretty
soon you get to decide what kind of cars get across the bridge,''
Papows testified.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft officials declined to comment on Papows' testimony.
</P>
<P>
   But even Papows admits that some of Lotus's problems are of its
own making.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while IBM and Lotus officials maintain that the 1995
buyout was good for both companies, they admit that they probably
goofed by not trying to leverage IBM's enormous market presence to
help Lotus fend off Microsoft Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a mutual mistake by not more prominently and visibly
linking the companies strategically,'' Papows said. ``We were so
manic about maintaining Lotus as a separate brand identity, that we
didn't do a lot to run Domino and Notes as part of IBM's e-business
ads.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 1559EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1539 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOTUS-MISCROSOFT-2ND &LR;      08-19 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTUS-MISCROSOFT-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-SUB-BOS  
 (Eliminates graphic.)  
 UNDATED: ... e-business ads.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IBM officials agree. ``Perhaps if we had positioned Domino as
the crown jewel of our e-business offering sooner, it would have
blunted their success, but it probably would not have resulted in a
major forestalling of the Microsoft juggernaut, given some of their
business tactics,'' said Mark Elliot, general manager of worldwide
sales and marketing for IBM's $13 billion software business.
</P>
<P>
   Although sales of Lotus Notes are still growing dramatically,
the inroads that Microsoft Exchange has made, especially in North
America, are worrisome.
</P>
<P>
   Industry sources say US sales last quarter of Lotus Notes were
$90 million behind the company's plan, but Papows called the number
``grossly exaggerated.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he acknowledged that Lotus's North American business has
not performed as well as in other regions of the world, where
Microsoft is barely a factor.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the company is overhauling its North American
operations, bringing in a new manager with increased
responsibilities. Mike Laginski is a Papows protege who joined
Lotus five years ago, but left shortly after IBM bought the
company.
</P>
<P>
   He returned recently to take control of North American
operations and helps fill a void created by the departure of a
Deborah Besemer, a highly regarded Lotus executive who left last
November to become chief executive of SystemSoft, a Natick software
company.
</P>
<P>
   While reorganizing its internal operations, Lotus officials have
also mounted a public campaign to counter a damaging article that
appeared recently in Forbes magazine entitled &UR;  &LR;  ``The Decline and
Fall of Lotus.''
</P>
<P>
   The article said that IBM's purchase of Lotus had turned sour,
and that many large Lotus customers were ripping out their Notes
systems in favor of Microsoft Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Infuriated Lotus officials are demanding a retraction, and,
meanwhile, are moving to try to calm anxious employees and
customers who have spent millions installing Notes systems. Forbes
says it is standing by the story.
</P>
<P>
   Papows says it is true that some of Lotus's large customers are
installing Microsoft Exchange for corporate e-mail purposes, but
says they are retaining Notes for its advanced collaborative
features, many of which Exchange does not have.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft agrees, but says its Exchange customers eventually
plan to replace Notes because they don't want to maintain two
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Baan Co. in Reston, Va., a major producer of business management
software for large companies, is one highly visible defector from
the Lotus camp.
</P>
<P>
   John Douglas, director of information technology, said that Baan
took a critical look last year at its Lotus Notes installation,
which served about 5,000 users worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Notes implementation here was pretty abysmal,'' said
Douglas. ``There were a lot of hardware issues, and the cost of
administration was high.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas grants that the advanced groupware features of Notes are
superior to those of Exchange, but added that Baan was mainly
interested in a straightforward messaging system. In that
department, Douglas said, Exchange gets top grades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am absolutely shocked at the amount of hardware it takes to
run Exchange _ or the lack thereof,'' Douglas said, adding that he
needed 40 server computers to run the Notes system. Today, Baan
runs an Exchange system that supports 10,000 users _ twice as many
as the Notes system it replaced. But Exchange requires just three
servers, powerful machines that link PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Baan is a major business ally of Microsoft in the development of
high-end business software. But Douglas said that this played no
part in the decision to switch to Exchange. ``We didn't even
contact IBM or Microsoft,'' said Douglas. ``We made the decision
internally.'' And Baan turned a deaf ear to Lotus's efforts to
reverse the decision. ``Notes is a good platform,'' said Douglas.
``It's just not for us.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, M&AMP;I Data Services, the data processing
division of Milwaukee-based Marshall &AMP; Ilsley Corp., left
Microsoft's older e-mail program, Microsoft Mail, to jump on the
Notes bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Wallace, director of technical infrastructure, said his
company wanted to create an Intranet, a private network based on
Internet standards, with the ability to route forms around the
company, and other collaborative features, and found Exchange
couldn't do the job without a lot of expensive add-on software.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found the Domino-based solution was one third of the cost of
the Exchange-based solution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who track the groupware market say the Forbes article
was way off track.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lotus is not declining, it is not falling,'' wrote Dan Rasmus,
an analyst with Giga Inforamtion Group Inc. of Norwell, shortly
after the Forbes story was published. ``Lotus is in fact holding
its own against Microsoft where other companies have not.''
</P>
<P>
   Another prominent research firm, Gartner Group of Stamford,
Conn., says it'll be mid-2001 before Microsoft catches Lotus in
sales of groupware, and points out that Exchange still dramatically
lags behind Notes's collaborative features.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game is far from over, and Lotus is in a very good spot, a
very defensible spot'' said Ian Campbell, an analyst with
International Data Corp. of Framingham.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a two horse race and we're neck and neck,'' said Papows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Hiawatha Bray of the Globe staff contributed to this story.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
