<SLUG> BC-CIR-MAKING-WAVES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW WAYS TO MAKE WAVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By CATHERINE GREEMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a muggy August day, two 8-year-old boys stand shoulder-deep
in water, waiting for the next wave so they can bodysurf to shore.
As they bob up and down, trying to dunk each other, one of them
points toward the horizon and screams, ``Look out, here comes a
huge one!''
</P>
<P>
   No, they're not at Jones Beach or the Jersey Shore but at the
wave pool at the Splish Splash Water Park in Riverhead, N.Y. Water
parks across the country are using technology to manufacture
artificial waves for your bobbing and riding delight _ and look,
Ma, no sand in your suit.
</P>
<P>
   How do the water parks coax water to move in directions it would
never otherwise go? In the wave pool at Splish Splash, waves are
produced by blowing tremendous gusts of air into the water at
different intervals, much like the way real waves are produced
except that the wind has to be manufactured.
</P>
<P>
   Lining the back of the wave pool, called Surf City, are six
watertight concrete vaults, or caissons. Each caisson is basically
a box with one open side facing into the pool.
</P>
<P>
   In a building behind the pool, there are three 150-horsepower
turbines, which suck air into the building through vents and
produce air currents. These air currents are sent to compressor
tanks and then into large valves, which connect to the caissons.
</P>
<P>
   The valves open and close in quick succession to shoot the air
into the caissons and from there into the water.
</P>
<P>
   Each turbine can produce enough air for a wave measuring a foot
and a half high, and three turbines working together can produce a
wave more than four feet high. Surf City has eight different waves:
a diamond, a right diagonal, a center peak V, a right split roller,
a left diagonal, a side peak V, a left split roller and a big
roller. Each one is produced by blowing air into one or more of the
caissons at different intervals.
</P>
<P>
   Letting air flow into caisson one, for example, then into
caisson two a second later, then caisson three, and down the line,
forms a left diagonal breaking wave. Firing air into caissons one
and six at the same time produces a wave that comes together at
giant peaks down the center _ a diamond. Letting air into all six
caissons at once produces a big roller.
</P>
<P>
   The wave patterns are controlled by a programmable logic
controller, a sort of master control panel a short distance from
the turbines. (A programmable logic controller is also used in
industrial applications to receive and monitor data from sensors on
all the system components.)
</P>
<P>
   If a turbine overheats, or a valve doesn't receive a strong
enough air current, a sensor will signal the controller, which will
shut the whole system down.
</P>
<P>
   The wave programs are preset in 10-minute patterns. After every
10-minute period, the controller shuts the turbines off, letting
tired swimmers make their way to the concrete shore and letting new
swimmers in. Lifeguards, including one eyeing a series of video
cameras, can press one of several emergency stop buttons, signaling
the controller to halt the turbines.
</P>
<P>
   Another ride at Splish Splash, the Lazy River, pushes water _
and people, sitting snugly in inner tubes _ across a flat,
1,300-foot-long surface. Water gets sucked into grates positioned
every couple of hundred feet along the floor of the river, where it
travels via large pipes to one of three pumping stations in the
park.
</P>
<P>
   The pumping stations then pressurize the water and shoot it
through valves, where it is injected back into the river through a
series of openings, also situated along the floor of the river.
</P>
<P>
   If producing four-foot-high waves and a moving river aren't
worthy enough water-technology feats, Chip Cleary, president of
Splish Splash, said in the future the park may install a Master
Blaster, a water roller coaster ride that uses turbines and pumps
to inject water into the bottom of a flume and then move it up
hills.
</P>
<P>
   When it falls, according to the manufacturer, NBGS International
of New Braunfels, Texas, it can move faster than many traditional
roller coasters. (For a virtual test ride, go to the company's
site, www.nbgsintl.com/blastTXT.html.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 1603EDT &QL; 
