</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAINE-SUMMER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUEBERRY DAYS; LOG-FIRE NIGHTS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JULIE V. IOVINE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vacationers with a puritanical streak are drawn to Maine, where
stark blue skies and towering evergreens meet jagged gray rocks and
the endless high-low seething of ocean tides. Here, even leisure
activities have an edge, whether it's knuckling down to sail in a
stiff wind or charging up graveled hills on a bike. Writers like
E.B. White and Robert McCloskey have found Maine rich in material
for moral tales of innocence unsettled by nature's
unpredictability. Ralph Lauren and Martha Stewart can only dream of
bottling this essence of virtuous American simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long way from Cincinnati, where Nancy and Barron Krody
live in the winter. The couple _ she teaches prekindergarten, he
runs a marketing and design firm _ started coming to Maine more
than 30 years ago, when their two children, Margo and Eric, were so
small they didn't have to bend over to pick the blueberries. About
18 years ago, the Krodys decided to stake a more permanent claim,
calculating that their children, now grown, would be more likely to
visit them in Maine than in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   On Penobscot Bay _ not far from the hills encountered in
McCloskey's homespun children's classic ``Blueberries for Sal'' _
houses are simple, styled by time and the weather.
</P>
<P>
   The Krodys bought theirs sight unseen in 1980. ``We'd heard it
was going to be available out on a gam,'' Mrs. Krody said, using
boaters' slang for the informal chats that develop between boat
crews moored alongside one another. They knew the spot from sailing
past on their way toward Bucks Harbor, another McCloskey landmark.
The house itself _ a gray shingled cottage with green shutters and
a stone and log foundation _ was nestled too deep in the pines to
be visible, except for the floating dock attached directly to a
huge boulder plunging into the sea. ``The site was so beautiful it
didn't really matter to us what the house was like,'' she said,
``though it turned out to be perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   The cottage was built in 1927 for an engineer by Ferd Clifford,
a local lobsterman. In those days, the place could be reached only
by boat. It's not much easier today: a dirt road ends a
quarter-mile from the house. Visitors must trek the last 300 yards
through dense woods carpeted in moss. Groceries and luggage are
brought in by cart; the mail is picked up only sporadically. When
the Krodys moved in, there were still plenty of kerosene lamps
around in case the recently installed electricity failed. An
eternal spring up the hill provides a reliable source of water.
</P>
<P>
   The two-story cottage has a birdhouse verticality. The site,
which slips down to a wide cove, is so steep that even the ground
floor feels lodged in tree branches. Tall double-sash windows are
grouped in twos, and the space in between is lined with bookshelves
_ it's the kind of place where an Emerson or a Thoreau might
contemplate the meaning of self-reliance. The first-floor ceiling
is low, but painted white, along with the insides of the window
frames, to brighten the room.
</P>
<P>
   The requisite wood-burning stove stands at the ready, with an
armchair for reading and a couch for napping within reach of its
radiant glow. The dining table opposite the galley kitchen has
window seats; they were built in by a previous owner, a minister
who liked woodworking. Examples of his handiness give the place its
shipshape personality: a desk fit into a window; knickknack drawers
tucked between exposed 4-by-4 studs.
</P>
<P>
   On the second floor, another living room attests to the
importance of the huddling factor. It can get extremely cold in
Maine, even in summer. An imposing fireplace made of stones hauled
up from the beach dominates the large room, which is open to the
rafters. The starkly simple pendant ceiling lights were rescued
from an old school in Cincinnati that was about to be demolished.
</P>
<P>
   Adjoining the living room are two tiny bedrooms _ really just
beds stowed behind a plank wall. In one, it's necessary to kneel on
the bed to reach the curtain-covered closet; the other has only
clothing hooks.
</P>
<P>
   During the day, light floods the entire floor, thanks to a
double set of folding french doors _ an unusual design flourish in
a rustic cottage of the 1920s _ that open onto a long screened-in
sleeping porch. Mrs. Krody leaves the doors open even when there's
a fire roaring. Much of the furniture was adopted from the two
previous owners or picked up locally. Not long ago, furnishings
could be delivered only by a schooner beached down in the cove,
then carried up through the woods. Mrs. Krody ordered her couches
from Pottery Barn; they were carted the last quarter mile from the
road. ``They said they could ship anywhere,'' Mrs. Krody said.
</P>
<P>
   A porch surrounding the house is wide enough on one side for
four Adirondack chairs that look out toward Deer Island in the
distance. A smaller balcony, shaded by fir and spruce, faces the
cove; it's large enough for only a sun-bleached table and four
mismatched chairs. This is where the Krodys have lunch: mussels
collected at low tide from the cove are edible, as are the
chanterelles culled from the damp recesses of the woods. By
evening, however, it's the mosquitoes who feast.
</P>
<P>
   Summers are for sailing and working on the house. Krody has
inherited the minister's wood shop as well as a habit of tinkering.
Mrs. Krody likes to visit the Blue Hill antiques fair that takes
place each summer on the fairgrounds, described in E.B. White's
``Charlotte's Web.'' In search of locally made folk art, she also
visits an old decoy maker on Deer Island and the prison shop in
Thomaston, which sells inmates' woodwork. ``I like junktiques,''
she said. ``And I'm in no hurry. It would be too boring if the
place were done all at once.''
</P>
<P>
   Projects are always under way. To enlarge a dining-room table,
Mrs. Krody's daughter, Margo Blutt, a former dancer with the New
York City Ballet, took the old extension leaf stored in the rafters
and painted it urchin-shell green, a folksy way to disguise how
much the table itself had worn over the years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the Krodys undertook a more ambitious plan, to rebuild
a dilapidated bunkhouse on their point into a three-bedroom cabin
for guests. Earl Clifford, the Krody's caretaker, and his son, Earl
Jr., descendants of the lobsterman who put up the main house, built
the new cabin. Clifford told the Krodys not to bother hiring
architects, that he could do it from a sketch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he'd have his own way of doing things,'' Krody said,
``and that would probably be the best way.'' So, Krody sketched on
graph paper the outlines of a simple gabled house with a wide
porch. Mrs. Krody requested that the interior be finished with two
``napping nooks,'' as she called them, like those she'd seen in a
magazine article about an island house near Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The cabin reveals its contemporary age. An expansive kitchen
with a large country table that upstages a wood stove reflects the
cultural shift from yarn-spinning around the fire to socializing
with the cook. The bedrooms _ one of them formerly held six bunks _
are no longer strictly utilitarian, but truly comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   The little cottage in the woods is now a compound ready for
reunions. But for Mrs. Krody, the old-fashioned pleasure of
gathering around the big stone fireplace in the main house remains
the most idyllic of moments in their Maine sojourns. ``I love it
when it's cold in August,'' she said as the fire crackled and
popped.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
