<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1553 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-MODEM-UPGRADE-NYT     08-19 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MODEM-UPGRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UPGRADE GAME OF STOP-AND-GO 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (jt)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Usually I am at peace with my decision not to be an early
adopter of new technology. Given the choice between spending a
hundred hours debugging some brand-new, whiz-bang bit of gadgetry
and, say, raising my three children, I have opted for motherhood.
</P>
<P>
   So I did not mind a bit when my husband recently ordered a
Micron Millenia computer that runs at a slightly faster speed than
mine. I even managed a tight smile when it arrived with a pair of
Advent speakers that dwarfed mine. But when he pointed out that his
modem connected nearly twice as fast? That I could not bear.
</P>
<P>
   It was time to upgrade my U.S. Robotics 56K modem, a moment I
had been dreading since I bought it last spring. The problem was
that my modem's x2 technology, on which it relied to introduce
itself to other modems, was incompatible with the K56flex
technology my online provider used. So my 56K modem never
downloaded information any faster than 28.8 kilobits per second.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the International Telecommunication Union, a United
Nations agency, announced technical specifications for a new
standard, the v.90, for all 56K modems. Most major online services
and carriers _ including America Online, PSI Net, UUNet and
Mindspring _ have recently announced upgrades to their own
networks.
</P>
<P>
   On my husband's newer modem, the v.90 standard was installed in
the factory, effectively blowing the doors off my modem. My only
chance to catch up would be to download a software patch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are probably the last person left on earth who hasn't
upgraded,'' my husband goaded me from his computer, where he
frisked like a dolphin in a vast sea of online information.
</P>
<P>
   I actually took comfort in those words, realizing that the early
adopters of upgrades had probably already worked out any kinks that
might have arisen in the six months since the v.90 standard was
announced.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, obtaining the software patch from the U.S. Robotics
support site  &UR; (www.usr.com/home/online) &LR;  shouldn't take more than
five minutes, with the aid of a Modem Update Wizard that I could
quickly download from the same site. But first, I decided to
perform a test at  &UR; www.3com.com/56k/need456k/linetest.html &LR;  to make
sure my home phone line was capable of sending data at a speed of
56 kilobits per second. ``The vast majority of phone lines can,''
Jim Thomsen, a product manager at 3Com, which owns U.S. Robotics,
assured me in a telephone interview. ``But some older phone lines
might have problems.''
</P>
<P>
   My phone line passed the test (time spent: 2 minutes),
emboldening me to try to download the Modem Update Wizard. This is
where I hit my first minor glitch: the connection between my
computer and the server where the wizard resided kept stalling. It
took me nearly a dozen tries to download the program (time spent: 1
hour).
</P>
<P>
   Next, I ran the wizard, which instructed my modem to phone a
U.S. Robotics server in Illinois (I had to pay for the
long-distance call). The capable wizard told the server my modem's
Device ID number, then waited patiently while the server flipped
through a catalog of software patches to find the right one. The
process seemed to be going smoothly _ in fact, I briefly considered
asking the wizard for some child-rearing advice _ but then the
trouble started.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of completing its task, the wizard suddenly informed me
via an on-screen window that an upgrade for my model was ``not yet
available.'' This seemed unlikely since my modem was one of the
most popular models on the market. But I repeated the process a
couple of times to double-check. Same result (time spent: 30
minutes). Confused, I phoned Thomsen (time spent: 5 minutes). Was I
doing something wrong? ``I don't think so,'' he said. ``We designed
the wizard to be pretty straightforward.''
</P>
<P>
   While Thomsen went off to check out the problem at his end, it
occurred to me to wonder whether this whole process was in vain.
What if my online provider, GST Whole Earth Networks, had not
upgraded its system yet to the v.90 standard? I could be wasting a
lot of time here only to find out _ eventually _ that my modem was
still incompatible with my online provider.
</P>
<P>
   And in fact, a phone call to GST Whole Earth Networks' technical
support line (time spent: 10 minutes) seemed to confirm my worst
fears. The bad news was that the online provider, with headquarters
on the West Coast, leased phone lines on the East Coast _ where I
dial in to the network _ from UUNet. According to information
available to technical support, UUNet had not upgraded my local
dial-up.
</P>
<P>
   Next, I phoned UUNet to find out when the line would be upgraded
(time spent: 15 minutes). ``Whole Earth Networks gave you the wrong
information,'' said Alan Tassel, vice president of marketing at
UUNet. ``Our network is fully deployed to handle v.90. We announced
the upgrade last month.''
</P>
<P>
   I called GST Whole Earth Networks again, this time reaching
Dylan Larson, a product manager who said the confusion probably
arose because the online provider was still in the process of
upgrading to v.90. ``It's changing from day to day,'' he said,
explaining why the technical support staff did not have current
information (time spent: 15 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Thomsen from 3Com phoned to tell me that he had
solved the Modem Update Wizard's problem (time spent: 10 minutes).
``I don't know how it happened, but maybe a system administrator
made every catalog entry unavailable while he was doing
maintenance, and then when he brought it up again, he didn't hit
the switch on that particular entry,'' Thomsen said. ``It should
work now.''
</P>
<P>
   It did (time spent: 5 minutes). Soon after, I saw my modem's
speed jump to well above 50 kilobits per second. Am I annoyed by
the fact that I spent more than two and a half hours trying to
upgrade? No, because now my modem runs slightly faster than my
husband's. I suspect it will take him at least a hundred hours to
figure out why.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
