<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1556 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-INNOCENCE-GAME-NY     08-19 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-INNOCENCE-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRINGING EXTRA PASSION TO A FINE ROMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (jt)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The word ``nuance'' does not generally describe interactive
media. In most digital environments, the impetus is to race ahead
with both guns blazing, solve all the puzzles, beat the big bad
boss and never look back _ only ahead, to the next product. They're
like theme restaurants that pack tables and jack up the music so
that you'll eat and leave as quickly as possible. How refreshing,
then, to find the digital equivalent of a candle-lighted bistro,
tucked away on some side street, where patrons are encouraged to
stretch a few cups of coffee into literary conversations that last
for hours.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Nick Bantock's Griffin and Sabine trilogy, Ceremony of
Innocence (Real World, CD-ROM for Mac and PC, $59.95), is an
epistolary romance between two artists, one of whom may be a
figment of the other's imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Like the books, Ceremony of Innocence takes the form of
illustrated letters and postcards. But whereas the paper version
presented page-mounted envelopes and the illicit thrill of opening
someone else's mail, the CD-ROM translates each missive into an
audiovisual collage of handwriting, typewriting, animation, film,
music and spoken words.
</P>
<P>
   In the wrong hands, this sort of layering ends up a mess. But in
Ceremony it works, because there is nothing amateurish in the
production. When you hear a letter read aloud, you believe it,
because the voice belongs to Isabella Rossellini, Paul McGann or
Ben Kingsley. This is the work of trained artists. It's not just
technically impressive. It is genuinely sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   And in many ways, Ceremony surpasses its printed source. For
example, a photorealistic painting of a goldfish and a broken
wineglass is an arresting image on the page. But on the screen it
becomes a fable: the glass is intact, and the goldfish is swimming
inside. Move the cursor across the glass, and the fish becomes
agitated, circling frantically. Click on it, and the wineglass
rings, as would a real glass, with different sound depending on
where you strike it. Click repeatedly and quickly, and the glass
will eventually shatter. You hear the sound, and you jump. You feel
responsible, and aghast, as if you'd broken a real glass.
</P>
<P>
   When was the last time you felt emotionally accountable for
anything you did with a computer mouse?
</P>
<P>
   There are fancifully drawn creatures on most cards, and the
mouse will sometimes scare them off. Or vice versa _ a mechanical
cat can swat the cursor away with its tail. A mythological animal
may eat your cursor, and you will see it trapped in the creature's
belly. At other times, there is no cursor at all, and the mouse
will pass across the screen invisibly, rustling images into motion
like leaves in a breeze.
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes, the picture's workings reveal themselves slowly.
You're forced to be patient and really look, slow down and really
notice what's going on and read the image on the screen the way you
would read a painting.
</P>
<P>
   When was the last time anything on a computer screen inspired
you to be still? That's not what interactive media trains us to do.
The vast majority of software trains us to absorb, process and
discard information as quickly as possible. Churn through the data.
React instantaneously. If something takes more than three seconds,
click for more stimulation. If immediate gratification is not
forthcoming, abandon ship. If nothing else, this CD-ROM makes you
realize the extent to which people have been programmed by
computers.
</P>
<P>
   The face of each card and envelope poses a different question
about the relationship between pixels on the screen and the person
at the keyboard. You don't have to answer these questions. You
merely have to recognize that they exist, that all the metaphors
about pointing and clicking and cursors and mice are up for grabs.
Suspend your assumptions and the riddle unravels. The envelope
opens and falls away, and the correspondence continues.
</P>
<P>
   The story is the payoff and, in a sense, a mirror of the
viewer's experience. Every postcard and letter is a link in the
transcontinental romance between artists who write to each other,
each seeking his or her perfect opposite. The story alternates
between voices, but also between pictures and words. The visual and
the verbal stories intertwine and inform each other here, just as
the characters do.
</P>
<P>
   The viewer alternates as well, between the front and the back of
each card, between the outside of each envelope and the letter
inside, between the visual riddle, which demands interaction, and
the epistolary narrative, which simply unfurls. On the face of the
card, your presence matters. On the back, the characters are acting
and you're just watching. It's a correspondence between you and the
story. And it's a duet between the written and the spoken word, as
you hear the text read aloud and see the handwriting appear, then
fade, with the sound. There is a correspondence in this work,
wherever you look. It's like a fractal _ a pattern that repeats
itself on every scale.
</P>
<P>
   Even when you turn off the computer, the counterpoint persists
because the digital story is the perfect dual opposite of the paper
story. When you go back to the printed image after seeing it on the
screen, you cannot help imagining it in motion. When you read the
letters, you can almost hear the words spoken aloud. Ceremony
leaves a phantom trace on the page. It becomes a ghostly
counterpart to the books, and to Griffin and Sabine's extraordinary
correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin and Sabine couldn't have done better themselves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail address: Herz(AT)nytimes.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
