<HEADER>
A1566 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-PIRATE-RADIO-ART-     08-19 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-PIRATE-RADIO-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FCC TAKES A HARDER LOOK AT `MICRORADIO' STATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Fla., Ill.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For five years, Richard Edmonson snuck the sounds of defiance
from his living room and into his community. As operator of an
unlicensed radio station called San Francisco Liberation Radio, he
wedged his way onto the airwaves, using a vacant frequency to
broadcast 12 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   The programming included news, music and shows like ``Voices of
the Rebellion,'' which focused on homelessness issues, and ``Time
Out,'' a program for children, often with a left-wing political
lesson.
</P>
<P>
   To his hundreds of appreciative listeners, Edmonson has been
Patrick Henry with an FM frequency, but to the Federal
Communications Commission, he is a criminal. In its lexicon, he and
dozens of other operators of unlicensed low-power radio stations
are ``pirates'' who interfere with licensed programming and with
air traffic control frequencies, creating a safety hazard.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, a crackdown by the FCC has led to the closure
_ often voluntary _ of some 250 unlicensed stations; on Tuesday,
the FCC announced that it seized radio equipment from 15 unlicensed
stations in Miami. Edmonson, fearing the FCC's wrath, shut down his
own station in June, but he has done so with characteristically
defiant sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the FCC truly supported free speech, they would be doing
everything in their power to make microradio happen,'' Edmonson,
45, said. ``Instead, they're trying to stamp it out.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in a new twist in the labored debate over the fate of
tiny community radio stations, the FCC appears to be doing both. It
is at once aggressively pursuing and shutting down microradio
stations, while also exploring for the first time whether it is
possible to license low-power players on the crowded airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   The debate goes to the heart of how the airwaves are defined in
the United States and who has access to them. Increasingly, the
access belongs to major corporations: since the enactment of the
Telecommunications Act of 1996, the radio industry has
consolidated, leaving control of stations in the hands of powerful
media companies.
</P>
<P>
   William E. Kennard, the FCC chairman, said in an interview that
he was deeply troubled by this trend, which he said ``threatens the
diversity of voices'' on the radio dial. ``With consolidation,
radio has become the province of multibillion-dollar
corporations,'' Kennard said. ``The loss of small religious
stations and local programming is very unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Under his direction, the FCC for the first time will consider
licensing radio stations that broadcast below 100 watts of power,
compared with 50,000 watts for typical major radio stations. In a
procedural but symbolic move, the FCC this year asked for public
comment on three petitions calling for licensing of microradio
stations.
</P>
<P>
   The public comment and rebuttal period ended July 24, and the
FCC said it received more than 200 comments, which it characterized
as an unusually high amount of feedback. Now, the FCC will evaluate
the remarks and determine whether to put forth a refined proposal
for licensing the stations.
</P>
<P>
   Kennard said there was nothing inconsistent in his efforts to
crack down on unlicensed stations and to find room for low-power
stations on the radio dial. He said the matters represented two
separate issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's not some discipline to this process, the spectrum
just won't work,'' he said. ``We can't have pirates just signing
onto frequencies as they choose and broadcasting willy-nilly on the
airwaves.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis Hiken, a lawyer for Edmonson, said proponents of licensing
microradio had found at least one other reason for optimism: Since
Kennard is the first African-American chairman of the FCC, he may
exert particular effort to increase the falling share of minority
ownership of radio stations. That ownership fell to 2.8 percent in
1997, from 3.1 percent in 1996, according to the Commerce
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Should Kennard and the FCC ultimately seek to establish
provisions to license microradio, they will face stiff opposition
from the National Association of Broadcasters, a powerful lobbying
group that represents mainstream radio interests.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The association vigorously opposes licensing microradio on the
grounds that it will interfere with existing stations and that it
will be impossible for the FCC to police the stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``To interject new stations into an FM band that is already
highly concentrated is just flat wrong,'' said Jeff Baumann, the
association's executive vice president for law. ``We're opposed to
a microradio service, pure and simple.''
</P>
<P>
   The broadcasters association contends that diversity on the dial
has actually increased in recent years, arguing that consolidation
has given major corporations more resources to expand programming
and to try out new formats.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Baumann said the market should decide _ and is
deciding _ what programming gets on the air, and that the airwaves
should not be open to anyone who happens to have a transmitter.
</P>
<P>
   The mass market, he added, clearly is not interested in the
likes of radio stations like Radio Free Berkeley, Steal This Radio
on the Lower East Side, Black Liberation Radio in Decatur, Ill., or
San Francisco Liberation Radio.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the barrier to entry is low. Start-up costs for
low-powered stations add up to hundreds of dollars, including the
price of a transmitter and basic studio equipment.
</P>
<P>
   To open his station in 1993, Edmonson cobbled together the
necessary hardware in the $650-a-month one-bedroom apartment he
shares with his girlfriend and the station co-founder, Jo Swanson.
</P>
<P>
   The equipment is now scattered among the other living-room
accouterments: a microphone, a mixer and a compact-disk player sit
on a hand-made wooden table; a chair for guests of the show sits
across the room, near the bicycles and the couch.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonson said the 40-watt signal of his station, located near
the ocean on the west side of San Francisco, traveled at most 10
miles in any direction over the 93.7 frequency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely gave you a different political slant than you'd
hear on commercial radio or even National Public Radio,'' said Tom
Burghardt, a regular listener. ``The music was good; there were no
commercials. What more could you ask for?''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonson said he had 350 listeners at any given time, although
he said he didn't know how many regular listeners tuned in and
could only tick off the names of a handful of die-hards. What's
important, he said, was that he was able to broadcast views from
outside the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   And he insisted his frequency did not interfere with other
California stations that shared the station's frequency, including
a station in Sacramento. ``You could barely hear their signal when
we were off the air,'' Edmonson said.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonson pulled the station off the air for good on June 17, the
day after a federal judge enjoined another pirate station, Radio
Free Berkeley, from broadcasting. United States District Court
Judge Claudia Wilkins rejected the Berkeley station's argument that
the government had violated its right to free speech by not
permitting it to broadcast without a license.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonson said because his station was so similar to Radio Free
Berkeley, he figured the decision applied equally to him. He has
since turned his makeshift radio station into a writing room,
spending his days penning a book on the struggles of the microradio
movement and his ideas for the future.
</P>
<P>
   The sounds from his living room are pessimistic. ``It's a great
loss for the community,'' he said of his station's closing. ``It
has tragic implications for free speech.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 1618EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1568 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-ONLINE-COLLECTING     08-19 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-COLLECTING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SALE: POLITICAL MEMORABILIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wash., W.Va., Ohio)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By STEVEN R. KNOWLTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At exactly 9:15 p.m., the electronic gates opened. For the next
90 minutes, button collectors from across the country pored over
the latest list of political buttons for sale: $156 for a John W.
Davis (1924), $104 for William McKinley and his 1900 running mate,
Theodore Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Lest frenzy swamp reason, all orders sent by e-mail to the
seller, Stephen E. Cresswell, in this first 90 minutes were filled
at random. ``When it was strictly first come, first served, people
were rushing so to get their orders in that they'd miss things, or
order things they didn't really want,'' Cresswell said of the
activity at his site (www.msys.net/cress/list.htm), which sells
hundreds, even thousands, of old political campaign buttons every
month.
</P>
<P>
   The reach and immediacy of the Web are becoming irresistible for
history buffs and collectors of political paraphernalia, even among
those who see impulse as the enemy and whose collections tie them
so tangibly to the past they love.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Windisch, one of the nearly 50 collectors who placed an
order, was rewarded with an enameled brass Benjamin Harris item
from 1888. A research chemist in Richland, Wash., Windisch happened
onto Creswell's List two years ago, when he was looking to put
together a collection to pass along to his son, Tommy, then 2.
</P>
<P>
   Cresswell's sales are popular among academics and other
professionals, perhaps because of his job as a history professor at
West Virginia Wesleyan College near his home in Buckhannon, W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   His monthly sales list is sprinkled with descriptions that show
his passion, like this one: ``Though the price is not high, I
believe this is one of the most important pieces of history ever
offered on Cresswell's List. From Bleeding Kansas of the 1850s
comes this rare paper ballot ... $36.'' It sold the first night.
</P>
<P>
   Windisch is trying to keep his collection modest. He is forgoing
the popular (and expensive) buttons called jugates (pronounced
JOO-gits), which feature two candidates' pictures and can run into
five figures. Instead, Windisch is going after buttons with names,
not pictures, and wants to accumulate the major candidates for
president going back as far as he can without breaking the bank.
</P>
<P>
   That will probably mean to 1840, when the candidate William
Henry Harrison waged the first media campaign. In the absence of
even newspaper photographs, a favorite medium was the brass lapel
pin touting the hero of the Tippecanoe Indian battle and his
running mate, John Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   Brass tokens from that campaign were stamped in huge numbers and
can be found today for around $20.
</P>
<P>
   Other sites have different personalities. Among the most popular
is EBay (at pages.ebay.com/aw, click on Collectibles, then
Political), where several hundred dealers and individuals have
auctions going at any one time.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran buyers caution neophytes that EBay can be addictive.
Closings are timed to the minute and as electronic bids pour in, an
auction is something like speed chess: a thrill for true believers,
an oxymoron for everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   But button collecting is still mostly an in-person or mail-order
operation. One of the biggest still-mostly-by-mail auction sites is
run by Allan Anderson in Troy, Ohio. Anderson maintains a Web page
(www.erinet.com/aaauctn) to announce his auctions and sell a few
items but said the great bulk of his business comes from his
quarterly printed catalog.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would like to beef up his Web site to show current
high bids from auctions in progress, but that will have to wait.
His Webmaster goes off to college this fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
