<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1586 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-THEGOVERNESS-TEX     08-19 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-THEGOVERNESS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPRIETY AND PASSION IN VICTORIAN BRITAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some early reviews of ``The Governess'' have called the film
stiff and dull; others have called it one of the better movies of
the year. Watching the film, one gets the sense that the first
group of critics stopped paying attention after the first hour,
about the time the second group started.
</P>
<P>
   The movie changes from a ``Masterpiece Theatre''-style
ponderousness to erotically charged melodrama at the midway point,
as if someone had flipped a switch. But the latter half is done
with enough grace and delicacy to keep it from looking like some
pretentious late-night cable entry (you know, like this spring's
``Dangerous Beauty'').
</P>
<P>
   It is also the first movie to take advantage of Minnie Driver's
unique beauty, and the first since ``Circle of Friends'' that her
acting skills have been fully exploited. Since ``Circle,'' she has
frequently been relegated to understanding/long-suffering
girlfriend roles, as in last year's ``Good Will Hunting.'' She
received an Oscar nomination for that, but she gives a better
performance here.
</P>
<P>
   Driver plays Rosina Da Silva, the oldest daughter in a Sephardic
Jewish family in 1840s London. When her father dies, leaving her
family deep in debt, she adopts the name Mary Blackchurch and hides
her Jewish background to take work as a governess for a Catholic
family in Scotland. When she enters the home of the Cavendishes,
you might think she has walked into a road company of ``Rebecca:''
the servants don't trust her, the mother is coldly formal, and the
little girl in her care is a demon child. It doesn't take
Rosina/Mary long to let the little girl know who is boss, though.
</P>
<P>
   But Mary has a harder time controlling the men of the house _
and her own libido. Mr. Cavendish (Tom Wilkinson) is conducting
early experiments in photography, and they intrigue Mary enough
that she starts working with him. Those scenes are a little
heavy-handed _ they almost have a ``Let's put on a photo show!''
quality _ but they lead to an inevitable romance, and the movie
picks up then. Writer-director Sandra Goldbacher makes up for the
predictability of the affair by taking it to unexpected depths,
especially after the movie's slow-moving first half.
</P>
<P>
   When the affair starts, it's as if the movie is achieving its
own sexual release, but Goldbacher doesn't coil the early scenes
tightly enough to make the release entirely satisfying. Driver,
however, shows a fearlessness she has not before demonstrated as an
actress, finding new layers in what becomes an obsessive passion.
Wilkinson is her match, in what can only be called a Jeremy
Irons-ish role after Irons' work in ``Damage'' and ``Lolita.'' If
they occasionally get a little histrionic, blame it on Goldbacher,
who not only doesn't rein them in, but appears to be egging them
on. Things only get more extreme when the Cavendishes' prodigal son
Henry (Jonathan Rhys Meyers) shows up and falls for Mary.
</P>
<P>
   In her first film, Goldbacher shows a lot of confidence, which
makes the flaws all the more aggravating. She appears to be
interested in the differences and similarities between Jews and
Catholics in early Victorian England, but she oversimplifies them
radically.
</P>
<P>
   For all its problems, ``The Governess'' has much merit, thanks
largely to the performances but also to Goldbacher's feel for
atmosphere. She uses music and colors well, with a haunting Middle
Eastern-influenced soundtrack and striking blacks and reds. Her
screenplay may occasionally be forced, but its novelistic qualities
are impressive, especially for a first feature. It's an ambitious
movie, and it will be interesting to see what happens if Goldbacher
learns from her mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Governess''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Sandra Goldbacher
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Minnie Driver, Tom Wilkinson
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ nudity, sexual situations and dialogue
</P>
<P>
   Length: 114 minutes
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
