<HEADER>
A1599 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-ONLINE-PSYCHICS-N     08-19 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-PSYCHICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 REQUESTING THE GUIDANCE OF AN ONLINE PSYCHIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID KUSHNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wondering if you'll get that new job? Meet that special someone?
See the Tampa Bay Buccaneers in the Super Bowl? Every day, legions
of seekers take their questions, however mundane, to legions of
psychics: on the street, on the phone, on the tube, and,
increasingly, online.
</P>
<P>
   Sammye Souder of Raleigh, N.C., who works as the psychic
``Sammye'' online, had been practicing for years off line when a
friend suggested she see clients over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Now one of her primary marketing tools is a site through America
Online. Like most Web psychics, she offers traditional phone
appointments, plus personal e-mail readings (not to mention selling
her homemade barbecue sauce, ``Sammye's Sumptuous Sauce'').
Customers fill out an online form with their credit-card numbers,
birth dates and questions. Sammye responds in a couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   A true clairvoyant need not perform a session in person, she
said in an interview. ``I have the capacity to tune in to people
when they send me e-mail,'' she said. ``Their message has their
energy because they sent it; I can pick that up.''
</P>
<P>
   Michele Anderson, another online psychic, says she believes
e-mail or online chat can interest clients who might not ordinarily
seek out psychic guidance. ``The Web does not have the same warmth
as a personal meeting,'' she said, ``but it offers anonymity to
someone who might be concerned about a serious issue.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Ms. Anderson's clients, Zachary Stuart, a New York actor,
said not all Web psychics are created equal. While he said he's
satisfied with Ms. Anderson, ``I had a couple experiences online
that were really quite the joke,'' he said in an e-mail message.
``The connection the psychic made with me and the things I was told
had absolutely nothing to do with who I was whatsoever. It was
humorous how `wrong' my first couple readings were. It seemed so
very generic I requested refunds.''
</P>
<P>
   Exchanging metaphysical energy over the wires isn't cheap. The
Psychic Internet charges customers by the word length of the
psychic's reply: $35 for what's called a ``quick hit'' reading of
200 words to $175 for an 1,800-word ``e-mail comprehensive.'' One
customer wanted to find a job in biotechnology sales. According to
the tarot cards' answer, part of the Psychic Internet site, the job
seeker was talented but suffered from a Type A personality and
needed therapy. (This customer is in luck: There are plenty of
online therapists.)
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone has to pay for a premonition. Many free sites are
harnessing the power of age-old and new-age oracles. Ouija boards
abound on the World Wide Web Ouija; players rest their fingers on
the mouse, telepathically sliding the cursor over the letter board
on screen.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993 the World Wide Web I Ching has brought the ancient
Chinese ``Book of Changes'' into the digital era. To simulate the
throwing of the three yarrow sticks, surfers type in a question and
then click a button on screen. The resulting hexagram reading is
revealed with a traditional explanation under each heading.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gamson, an avid I Ching user, likes the immediacy of the
online version. But it doesn't quite evoke the mystical experience
he conjures off line, which includes candles and incense, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process leading up to receiving an oracle is as important
as the oracle itself,'' he said. ``It is a period of clearing the
mind similar to meditation. You simply can't get that by watching
the Web browser load the next page.'' Also, he noted, ``It's
essentially just a random number generator.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, random generator programs, which spit out responses
each time a button is clicked, inform a sublegion of psykitsch
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens emulate the erstwhile Magic 8 Ball. The creator of Kurt
Cobain's Magic 8 Ball promises that the Punk Poet of Grunge is
standing by on the other side, ready to help you tackle the big
questions. Visitors type in queries and then click on Kurt for a
response. Using random sound files from old Nirvana interviews, the
site answers with casual obliqueness: ``Yes, no, maybe so, kind of,
sort of.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how dependable are online psychics? When asked, a pudgy
automated psychic called The Dack Head had this to say: ``Could you
rephrase the question in a way that would make me care?''
</P>
<P>
   For those who need to know what's in their future, here are some
World Wide Web links.
</P>
<P>
   SAMMYE: members.aol.com/sammyes/donna.htm
</P>
<P>
   THE PSYCHIC INTERNET: www.wholarts.com/psychic/
</P>
<P>
   WORLD WIDE WEB I CHING: www.facade.com/attraction/iching/
</P>
<P>
   WORLD WIDE WEB OUIJA: www.math.unh.edu/black/cgi-bin/ouija.cgi
</P>
<P>
   KURT COBAIN'S MAGIC TALKING 8 BALL: www.xworld.com/cobain/index.
html
</P>
<P>
   ASK THE DACK HEAD: toybox.asap.net/shockmon/dackpage.html
</P>
<P>
   MICHELE ANDERSON: newvision-psychic.com/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
