<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1612 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-COMPUTER-TUTORS-A     08-19 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-TUTORS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAND ON FOREHEAD? IT MAY BE TIME FOR A COMPUTER DOCTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By BONNIE ROTHMAN MORRIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At 10 p.m. every Sunday, Stephen Negron receives a telephone
call from a person in distress. Roger Garvin was interrupted by a
caller during his 49th birthday party, and was on the phone for an
hour. Jim Mulcahy got his own party interruption during a St.
Patrick's Day bash, a call that kept him away from the beer and his
friends for 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   These men are not volunteer firemen or suicide help-line
workers. They are computer tutors, or computer doctors, or geeks,
or just plain nerds _ the people whose job it is to help other
people figure out their computers. And when their clients and their
clients' computers are on the brink of a breakdown, these tutors
jump to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   When they started their businesses, phone calls outside of
business hours were not in the game plan. Experts in machinery that
no one else seemed to understand, their business mission was
simple: to help those whom they fondly refer to as ``normal
people'' or the ``technically challenged'' learn how to use their
computers.
</P>
<P>
   That mission has changed along with their roles. Tutors have
become nursemaids, confidants, friends. They are like psychiatrists
who make house calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marketing guys will tell you that the computer does
everything and you have to know nothing to do it,'' said Garvin,
owner of Results Technologies, a computer consulting business in
Brea, Calif., near Los Angeles. ``That's drivel. That's like
tossing the car keys to a 16-year-old and telling him to go have
fun. Cars are simple, but you need to learn how to use them.''
Personal computers are now in 42 percent of American homes,
according to Odyssey, a market research company based in San
Francisco, and the need for people who can teach their owners how
to run them is growing.
</P>
<P>
   Computer tutoring is an unregulated industry. Anyone who knows
one program better than another can call himself or herself a tutor
and charge $50 to $100 an hour for his services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Wild West out there,'' said Negron, who left full-time
computer consulting for a permanent job at ABC Inc. as a programmer
and analyst because, he said, there were too many unqualified
people calling themselves tutors. ``They were pests making a lot of
messes.'' Now he tutors part time.
</P>
<P>
   The people who hire computer tutors are often small-business
owners who may or may not be home-based; neophytes who want to use
a computer for household tasks and hobbies, or people who are
making upgrades _ say, from Windows 3.1 to Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   Some are switching from a Macintosh to a PC or vice versa. They
range in age from children to senior citizens. Many are new to
computing and want to use their machines to get onto the Internet
and send e-mail. Except for the kids, most are scared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very frightened of my first computer,'' said Martha P.
Nochimson, a former soap opera writer who now is an author and
professor at Mercy College in Dobbs Ferry, N.Y. ``It was like when
you had your first baby and the slightest little thing happened and
you'd become totally unhinged.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nochimson bought her first computer at the urging of a
technologically adept colleague. She called him so often with
questions, he started dodging her calls, and she said she realized
she needed to develop a little self-sufficiency. Then she found
Negron.
</P>
<P>
   ``The object of what we do is to work ourselves out of a job,''
Negron said.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching clients how to run their computers is only part of what
these consultants do. Some advise on computer purchases, even
accompanying clients on shopping trips. They set up the computers,
recommend software, provide the training and offer support, solving
inevitable glitches that flare up to torment their clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the help desk for people who don't work for a
corporation,'' said Mulcahy, a tutor in Bronxville, N.Y., who
traverses the metropolitan area in a black '92 Acura Integra
emblazoned with the logo of his company, Computer Tutor (AT) PCI.
</P>
<P>
   While most tutors prefer to get involved with their clients
right when they buy a computer, many jump in only after hardware
mistakes have already been made.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Sorby, owner of Sorby Contracting in Briarcliff Manor,
N.Y., bought a computer for his business and called Mulcahy to set
it up. Once Mulcahy checked out the goods, he told Sorby that he
had bought the wrong computer for the job, which included running
engineering software.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they returned the machine and bought another. Sorby
even saved some money. He still had to learn how to run the
computer, though. Mulcahy took care of that, too.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Most computer tutors say that teaching people how to use a
computer offers them the greatest satisfaction. There are a few
caveats: this is true primarily if the student is willing to spend
time outside of ``class'' to work on his computing skills. The mix
of student and teacher must also be right. Some trainers cannot
adjust their techie language to basic English.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, tutors say that lesson one is often helping
students overcome their fear. ``If they're in a mind-set where the
computer is going to give them grief, people freak out,'' Garvin
said. ``You have to be a counselor to find out why and then move on
to the training.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the silly questions start. A client of Mulcahy's called him
in a panic one evening because his computer wouldn't boot up. He
instructed the client to remove the diskette from his floppy drive
and press any key to continue.
</P>
<P>
   The man started screaming that he couldn't find the ``any'' key.
Mulcahy calmly told him it was next to the ``something'' key. The
man finally relaxed. Problem solved.
</P>
<P>
   Many times problems are not so easily fixed, of course,
especially when files or programs disappear. Then computer tutors
arrive like white knights to rescue the files. If they cannot fix
the problem, they will know where to go for help: manufacturers'
help lines, the Internet or books.
</P>
<P>
   Mulcahy even calls the help lines for clients himself, sparing
them the torture of listening to recorded music for minutes on end
and the confusion of speaking to a technician whom they might not
understand.
</P>
<P>
   At times, there are problems even tutors cannot solve _ when the
computer actually breaks, for example, as Ms. Nochimson's did when
she was facing a deadline. Negron lent her a laptop computer to
help her out of her jam. ``I didn't ask him for it,'' she said.
``It was very princely. He's like a merry little conductor on the
choo-choo of computers.''
</P>
<P>
   Before hiring a computer tutor, ask yourself what you want him
or her to do for you. Computer tutors, unlike software trainers who
are expert in one program, offer a range of services to their
clients, from buying the hardware to providing phone support when
the computer crashes.
</P>
<P>
   The industry is unregulated, so interview prospective tutors and
check their references before your first session. Then, find out if
the tutor meets this criteria: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KNOWS THE HARDWARE Many tutors will help clients buy their
computers, add hardware or decide what kind of phone lines they
need. Some will even go to the computer store or take part in
conference calls to help clients buy hardware over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   KNOWS SOFTWARE AND HOW TO USE IT Trainers have their favorite
programs but should know which software is most appropriate for
each user and teach you how to use it. Many will also recommend
Internet providers and an e-mail system and train on that, too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKS YOUR LANGUAGE Tutors should be able to make technology
plain, not intimidating and confusing. Often, they recommend
reference books.
</P>
<P>
   HAS OUTSIDE RESOURCES Despite the white knight syndrome, tutors
don't know everything. A good one will know where to find the
answers. If you present a tutor with a problem he or she cannot
solve, don't expect to be charged for the time it takes to find the
solution. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few other hints: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EXPECT TO PAY $50 to $100 AN HOUR Many tutors require you agree
to a minimum number of hours before they starting consulting work.
Beware of the tutor offering a deal.
</P>
<P>
   UNDERSTAND THE PHONE-TIME POLICY Emergency phone help, even for
the silliest question, is an integral part of the tutoring
experience and tutors expect these calls. If calls can be
dispatched in five minutes, there is usually no charge. After that,
the clock generally goes on.
</P>
<P>
   BEWARE OF THE HELPFUL FRIEND who fiddles with your computer to
help you fix something, and then disappears. Your files could
vanish, too _ along with the friendship. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tutors, beloved by clients, are not so generous when describing
their clients. Here are some of their pet peeves:
</P>
<P>
   _ Clients who don't practice.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clients who just want it fixed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clients who refuse to upgrade their computers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clients who keep upgrading when they don't need to.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clients who tinker when they don't know what they are doing,
and can't remember what they did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 1636EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1618 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-HOME-MADE-CDS(2TA     08-19 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-HOME-MADE-CDS(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPILING YOUR `GREATEST HITS' ON DISK 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By MATTHEW MIRAPAUL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every music collection has one _ the hourlong compact disk
acquired solely for the sake of a three-minute song. The bait might
have been a popular single that sizzled on a summer movie
soundtrack or a nostalgia-inspiring hit that gleamed in the middle
of a golden-oldies collection, but many listeners are lured into
sinking $15 on an unfamiliar album after catching one hook-laden
tune on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   For Philip David Morgan, an insurance-rate assessor in Saint
James, N.Y., the culprit was ``Save Our Souls,'' by the
singer-songwriter Happy Rhodes, which he first heard on a local FM
station. Although he has since become a fan of Ms. Rhodes' music,
Morgan acknowledged that the decision to buy her 14-track disk
``The Keep'' for that one song ``isn't exactly what I'd call
swift.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, 36, subsequently discovered a better way. Through custom
CD Web sites, he assembles full-length disks composed of individual
tracks that appeal to him. So far, he has obtained four of these
made-to-order compilations, including one he dubbed ``The Beggars'
Ball.'' It is a mix of reggae, '60s-era pop and alternative rock,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at custom-CD sites said the manufacturing process may
occur within seconds of an order being received and that a
70-minute disk can be ``burned'' in less than 20 minutes; buyers
must still wait several days for their order to be delivered via
the mail. Some sites also permit customers to pick out cover art
and, if the CD is intended as a gift, to write personal liner notes
that will be laser-printed on the sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   Creating a custom disk is slightly more expensive than buying a
new release. Each song costs about $1, and the bill for the
finished product ranges from $18 to $25. The price is a bargain,
though, compared with what it would take to purchase the source
CD's separately.
</P>
<P>
   Custom-CD services began to emerge on the Web last fall, and
there are now at least nine of them. (K-Tel International plans to
start a similar service this month.) The growth of such sites has
been stunted by the major record labels, reluctant to cannibalize
sales by licensing their hit-saturated catalogs to the custom
sites. As a result, the sites tend to be stocked with loads of
moldy oldies and a slew of jazz, blues and reggae tracks from
independent labels.
</P>
<P>
   Licensing restrictions pose further difficulties. On the
Musicmaker.com site, songs from the Fantasy Records catalog cannot
be mixed with another label's. At Customdisc.com, selecting more
than three cuts by certain artists is forbidden. Performers without
major-label record deals are less constrained by these limitations,
and several sites exploit this by focusing on up-and-coming artists
signed to independent labels.
</P>
<P>
   Although site executives tout custom CD's as a convenient
alternative to making audio cassette compilations, be prepared to
spend a significant amount of time at the task. Even with a
reasonably fast Internet connection, searching through thousands of
tracks can be a chore, especially when one encounters six
renditions of ``Some Other Time'' by Bill Evans on the
Musicmaker.com site.
</P>
<P>
   Once the tracks are picked, sequencing them sensibly is next.
Morgan ponders tempo, tone and key signature when arranging his
disks, and conceded that it may take him two or three visits to
build a disk to his liking. ``Sometimes it still ends up wild,'' he
said. Despite this, he is considering making a jazz-themed CD as an
anniversary present for his sister and brother-in-law. Please, try
not to spoil the surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Large Roster Of Jazz Giants: WWW.MUSICMAKER.COM
</P>
<P>
   The Music Connection Corp. was founded by record industry
executives who used their knowledge to amass on the Musicmaker.com
site one of the largest rosters of high-quality titles that can be
had from a custom-CD service. Because the company's first deal was
with the esteemed Fantasy Records label, the 100,000 songs on the
site include gems by jazz giants like Miles Davis, John Coltrane,
Wes Montgomery and Thelonious Monk. Bruce Block, vice president of
business development for the Reston, Va., company, said he expected
to have one million songs licensed to the service by year-end,
although it might take some months to load them on the site.
</P>
<P>
   Licensing limitations prohibit mixing Fantasy tracks with
material from other labels, so it is not possible to construct a
greatest-hits disk by the blues great John Lee Hooker that combines
cuts drawn from different labels. The restriction on Creedence
Clearwater Revival _ the band's tracks can't be mixed with any
other performers' _ is even more vexing, but frustration may fade
with the realization that one could easily make three full disks
composed of different versions of the Monk classic `` 'Round
Midnight'' performed by top Fantasy artists like Sonny Rollins and
Freddie Hubbard.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, the Monk title is listed throughout the site as ``
'Round About Midnight,'' a reminder that search operations are only
as good as the database being scoured. Fortunately,
Musicmaker.com's is one of the better ones, frequently supplying
track-personnel, songwriting-credit and album-source information
that can clarify results. It would be helpful, though, if searches
also scanned the entries for supporting players, especially on jazz
titles on which the accompanists can be as important as the
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   While the bland, frame-heavy site is unlikely to win any
graphic-design awards, Musicmaker.com has some nifty features that
some of the competing services have yet to duplicate. For example,
tracks can be rearranged numerically instead of repositioned by
using up-down arrows to move each song one notch at a time. An
on-screen button will start the audio-preview function and play all
of an artist's song excerpts in sequence. Having trouble filling a
disk? A program will supply suggestions based on the preferences of
like-minded visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Disks from Musicmaker.com cost $9.95 for the first five songs,
and CD's can contain up to 20 cuts or 70 minutes. Additional songs
are $1, and any track longer than 5 minutes costs 20 cents for each
extra minute _ a penalty assessed on lengthy jazz tracks. A
collection of 15 instrumentals by the bluegrass guitar virtuoso
Tony Rice cost $22.66, including $2.95 for shipping and handling.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cutting-Edge Dance Music For the Club-Going Crowd:
WWW.CDUCTIVE.COM
</P>
<P>
   This site, whose name is pronounced ``seductive,'' is for anyone
interested in contemporary dance music. Taking a niche approach,
Group K Inc., in New York, has installed 5,000 tracks from the
electronica genre on its sleek site, including cuts by such
standard-bearers as Roni Size, Goldie and Howie B.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who do not intend to spend a dime may enjoy exploring
the site, which is subdivided into a dozen categories with exotic
names like ``illbient'' and ``trip-hop/leftfield.'' Generous
45-second song samples for tracks by Funki Porcini, Yerbouti and
others give a good sense of the flavor of each tune, and the site
is regularly refreshed with hot titles _ a necessity for a genre in
which hits are often short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   The site's founders, Alan Manuel, John Rigos and Thomas Ryan,
met while attending business school outside Paris in 1996. An
entrepreneurism class sparked Manuel to propose forming a custom-CD
business. With planning sessions taking place in the Rex Club, a
leading techno-music venue in Paris, the focus on electronic dance
music seemed obvious. The trio set up shop in New York last year.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan said: ``The guy behind the counter at a specialty deejay
shop expects you to know the most minute details about the most
obscure label in Iceland before he'll give you the time of day.
There's really no good way for you to get to know this music unless
you have a friend who's into it. We decided there must be a lot of
people who feel left out by this system.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently so. Since the site went up in December, sales have
doubled every month, Ryan said. He is the partnership's music
expert, spending hours in the dance club Twilo in Manhattan and the
deejay-oriented shop Temple Records in the East Village to scout
out the trendiest new material. Cductive also is scheduled to
introduce a new area devoted to independent rock music next month.
</P>
<P>
   Disks from Cductive can be up to 72 minutes long. They cost
$4.99 for the first song and 99 cents for each additional, but
tracks taken from the company's promotional samplers are free,
which can help hold down the cost. A 15-cut collection of acid-jazz
and big-beat titles cost $18.87, including $2.99 for shipping.
</P>
<P>
   All the disks ordered for this article sounded good, but most
relied on vintage material. Only the Cductive disk, with its
cutting-edge ambiance and booming bass beats, managed to knock the
socks off this listener's ears.
</P>
<P>
   Oldies, With a Few Detours: WWW.CUSTOMDISC.COM
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, when David Gould was courting the woman who would
become his wife, the couple spent evenings in his Gramercy Park
apartment listening to ``Love Train'' by the O'Jays and other songs
from his huge collection of vinyl records.
</P>
<P>
   ``It occurred to me during one of these sessions that if we
could put this experience onto a CD, that would be a great
business,'' Gould recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, after a bad round of golf, he suggested the
custom-disk idea to his Harvard Business School classmate Nicolas
Darveau-Garneau, who immediately envisioned it as a Web-based
venture. After graduating, the two set up shop as Custom
Revolutions Inc. in the basement of their Upper West Side apartment
(their offices have since moved to Connecticut) and opened
Customdisc.com in March.
</P>
<P>
   The company has licensed about 165,000 songs. Half of them have
been posted on the site, which has just been updated with a crisp
new graphic design.
</P>
<P>
   The tracks are all over the map, from 3,500 chart-topping
singles like ``Love Train'' to a poem read by the author Ursula Le
Guin. There is a decent selection of classical entries, and more
contemporary songs by the Pharcyde, Brand New Heavies, Tone Loc and
Suicidal Tendencies are due to be added soon.
</P>
<P>
   The company is still ironing out a few bugs as it upgrades the
site, so search-error messages like ``Page 7 of 3'' that occurred
with Netscape's browser should end soon.
</P>
<P>
   More disconcerting, though, is the site's approach to
alphabetizing performers by their first names, so that Martha
Reeves is listed under the M's instead of the R's.
</P>
<P>
   And if you search by song title, be sure to start with the T's,
where you will find ``The Lady Is a Tramp,'' ``The Great
Pretender'' and all the other songs that begin with ``The.'' The
multiple movements of symphonic works are not always clearly
marked, and some sleuthing may be required to determine the
composer.
</P>
<P>
   Customdisc.com charges $5.99 to start building a 70-minute CD of
up to 25 songs, with most costing 99 cents. Licensing limitations
prevented me from assembling a CD with more than three cuts by the
singer-songwriter David Wilcox, but I did manage to construct a
25-track oldies CD while maintaining the reassuring message ``There
are currently no errors in your order.''
</P>
<P>
   The final price was $33.17, including $2.43 for shipping,
perhaps making it the most expensive CD in my entire collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 10-track CD will cost $15.99,'' Gould noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we see it, people can spend the same amount of money
and just get one or two songs,'' he added. ``And if they had to go
out and buy traditional CD's to get the same 10 songs, they would
spend three or four times that.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Names but So-So Titles: WWW.MY-CD.COM
</P>
<P>
   This site's magic moment occurred just as Tyler Peppel was
thinking about how Oompala, his software company, might use the
Internet to personalize entertainment. ``Around that time, my
assistant's boyfriend gave her a CD he recorded for her with only
one special song on it,'' Peppel recalled from his San Francisco
office.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the romantic gesture, Peppel pitched the custom-disk
idea to financial backers, and MY-CD Inc. was born as a separate
enterprise. Edward A. Bennett, former president of VH1, was brought
in to run the New York company. The site was opened in May and
already offers 16,000 cuts. It is especially strong in jazz and
blues. The rock music area has some star-studded acts, including
Fleetwood Mac and Santana, but their major-label hits are
noticeably absent. Track annotation is sparse, so listening to the
audio samples is essential to insure that the version of a song you
have selected is the original you truly want.
</P>
<P>
   The MY-CD site was recently overhauled, but some bugs still need
to be worked out. As I tried to compile a collection, the software
lost my order every time I tried to go back a page to review it.
The company vowed to fix this soon.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, I did succeed in creating a custom disk, combining
all the tracks from the avant-samba composer Arto Lindsay's ``Mundo
Civilizado'' with 9 of the 11 cuts from his ``O Corpo Sutile''
album for about half the price of the two CD's bought separately.
In the bargain, I lost the song-lyric translations and original
cover art. Disks from MY-CD cost $16.99 and are limited to 25
tracks or 70 minutes. With shipping, the total for the Lindsay disk
was $19.48.
</P>
<P>
   All of the custom-CD sites hope to reach the same level of
success as Peppel's assistant and her beau. The couple, he
reported, is ``living happily ever after.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
