<HEADLINE>
BARRY BONDS IS WORTH HIS WEIGHT IN DOLLARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Barry Bonds will turn 400 sometime in the next
two weeks, but there seems to be remarkably few parties being
thrown in honor of the big day. Strange.
</P>
<P>
   The ``400'' of which we speak refers to home runs, and when you
combine that figure with the 438 stolen bases he has amassed, it
will make him the first player in major-league history to combine
the two feats. Yet nobody seems all that overwhelmed by the
occasion. Weird.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it seems oddly fitting that Bonds will likely hit No.
400 on the road, because his legacy with the San Francisco Giants
seems oddly muted, even after nearly six years' faithful service.
Even after you allow for the fact that Bay Area ball fans have
always hesitated to take to imported stars, from Willie Mays on
down, there's something missing here. I mean, 400 homers and if you
weren't paying really close attention, you wouldn't know it.
</P>
<P>
   Kind of makes you wonder if, after almost 1,000 games, Barry
Bonds is ever going to hit it big here _ if, after more than $52
million in salary, he has repaid the investment.
</P>
<P>
   This is not be a treatise on whether Bonds is a nice guy or not,
largely because sportswriters are no better suited to make such a
judgment than any other clothesline gossip. Oh, we try to make
sweeping generalizations on people's inner workings the same as
anyone else, but our success rate isn't much better than that of
the average presidential defender.
</P>
<P>
   So let's ask the question a different way than it's been asked _
not by tooling around his brain, but around his deeds. It is, after
all, the way he has always been asked to be evaluated, and he has
played here long enough to deserve a home game for a change.
</P>
<P>
   Try the numbers first. He is a .305 hitter in his time with the
Giants, has hit 222 homers and driven in 630 runs. He has played 96
percent of his team's games in that time and has never been on the
disabled list. The most you can say in opposition to his on-field
performance is his occasionally casual response to balls he feels
he didn't hit properly, but those aren't reflected in the
statistics. On that basis, he is not assailable. If he is paid for
his numbers alone, he has earned the check.
</P>
<P>
   Try the leadership issue. He said he wasn't going to be a leader
in the conventionally defined way when he got here, and he hasn't
been. He has not been the one to stand up holding the tattered flag
and yell through the hail of bullets at his fallen comrades,
``C'mon, boys, let's go take that hill.'' He hasn't even been the
cheeriest clown in the overfilled circus Volkswagen.
</P>
<P>
   He has provided inspiration through numbers, but not by nature.
The answer to this question, then, is to ask not whether the Giants
would have paid this much money for a hitting machine, but whether
they expected leadership from him when they signed him. If they
did, they heard only what they wanted to hear. Still, by their
definition, he came up well short. Why else would general manager
Brian Sabean have tried to trade Bonds before he traded Matt
Williams in 1996?
</P>
<P>
   Try the standings. The Giants with Bonds are 29 games over .500,
which figures to an annual record of 82-78. They have one
postseason, a three-game sweep at the hands of the now fictional
Florida Marlins, and a near-miss in 1993. He was part of three
divisional winners in Pittsburgh. At these prices, the management
probably thought it was getting more than this, based on the
difference between the percentage of Bonds on the roster (4) and
the percentage of his salary on the total payroll (this year,
roughly 20 percent, although in earlier years he was nearly 30
percent of the figure). Again, less than anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Try the crowds. Again, you cannot separate Bonds from the other
factors here than you can from the rest of the team, but most
operators believe that your star should bring people to see him. As
it turns out, the Giants' chief marketing tools in Bonds' time here
are manager Dusty Baker and a ballpark that hasn't been built yet.
Neither of these is an ideal marketing strategy, and Bonds has
shown no indication that he wants to market anything more than his
presence in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in his time here, the Giants broke their attendance
record in 1993, then set their second- and third-best attendances,
and would have had a fourth if not for the strike of 1994. While he
hasn't overcome the Giants' self-defeating dynamics (over-maligned
stadium, over-hyped new stadium, three losing records in five
years, lots of other pastimes, the strike), neither has he been the
drag he is perceived to be.
</P>
<P>
   Try the salary. Ah, the central question at last. Bonds' salary
is going to skyrocket into eight figures this coming year when his
new contract kicks in, and if the club picks up his option for
2001, it will have paid him nearly $80 million. Alonzo Mourning
makes more and has delivered less. Until this year, Michael Jordan
made less and delivered more. The Giants thought they were getting
something closer to Jordan. On this, Bonds has missed, but only if
you don't believe that money for athletes long ago had lost all its
meaning.
</P>
<P>
   On balance, Bonds has not been the all-fired steal the Giants
imagined him to be in December of 1992, but he surely cannot be
considered a waste, either. With him, the Giants have been a
slightly above-average but less than nationally riveting team.
Without him, Peter Magowan would never have made any noticeable
splash as an owner, and may have never convinced anyone that he was
a serious enough operator to build a ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   If you look at it that way, yes, he's been worth the money. But
if you see the ballpark not as a cash cow for the century ahead but
as a debt factory that could weigh down the stockholders just as
long, then maybe he wasn't a help at all.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Barry Bonds has been worth the money, but only
depending on the question you ask. These past few years may never
be known as the Bonds Era, and his 400th homer may not cause
spontaneous parades to fill the streets, but imagining this time
without him is nearly impossible. If that isn't worth $80 million,
it comes close enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
