<SLUG> BC-BLUESMAN-LEGACY-1000(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT JOHNSON'S MUSICAL INFLUENCE _ AND HIS MYSTERIOUS LEGEND _
LIVE ON
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by BC-BLUESMAN-ACOUSTIC) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sixty years ago this month, a Mississippi-based blues musician
died.
</P>
<P>
   We don't know what he died of.
</P>
<P>
   We don't know where he's buried.
</P>
<P>
   We don't know what became of his guitar.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Johnson was only 27 when he died Aug. 16 in Greenwood,
Miss., a small town north of Jackson and just east of Indianola,
where B.B. King grew up.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, few people outside his family and friends even
noticed. Johnson was, at best, a regional star: He had released a
handful of 78s, none of them national hits. He was not rich and,
perhaps, was barely solvent.
</P>
<P>
   He traveled constantly, from small Delta town to small Delta
town, over to Arkansas and at least once up into the Midwest,
playing at Saturday-night parties and on street corners, doing
anything from his own haunted blues to jukebox favorites, whatever
would keep the coins coming.
</P>
<P>
   And yet for the past 35 years, this thin man with long, spidery
hands has remained the most legendary bluesman _ acoustic or
electric, black or white _ of all time.
</P>
<P>
   On its own, his work is stunning: The combination of his
unmatched slide guitar playing and intense singing and songwriting
has never been equaled.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond that, his songs formed the bedrock of the song
structures and lyrical outlook that, via Muddy Waters, Howlin' Wolf
and others, defined electric Chicago blues _ the starting point for
everyone from the Rolling Stones to Led Zeppelin to Eric Clapton to
the Fabulous Thunderbirds.
</P>
<P>
   There is literally not a single blues band that hasn't played a
Johnson song, or a song that is based on or influenced by a Johnson
song. Before being ``rediscovered'' by white blues and folk
fanatics in the '60s, his music had already survived for decades
simply because of its potency, and from the many black blues
artists who adapted it and made it their own.
</P>
<P>
   He was not the first bluesman, or the first to have an impact on
other bluesmen, but his legacy has extended further and shows no
sign of diminishing.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson sang of having hellhounds on his trail, of need and
abandonment, with a searing emotional tone that, even all these
years later, makes the hair stand up on the back of the neck. An
eerie, scary immediacy endures as he sings of restlessness on ``I
Believe I'll Dust My Broom'' and ``Walking Blues,'' about inner
turmoil (constantly, but perhaps most eloquently on ``Stones in My
Passway''), of violence on ``Me and the Devil Blues'' and ``32-20
Blues,'' and of soul-destroying loneliness on the epic ``Cross Road
Blues'' and ``Love in Vain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the art _ it's like asking what makes W.B. Yeats' poetry
survive,'' says author Peter Guralnick, who has written extensively
about Johnson. ``It just achieves a standard of art that other
blues didn't. Johnson took a conscious approach to the music that
allowed him to exist outside the framework of the music. He just
aimed higher and had a gift that took his work to a higher plane.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, of course, there's the legend: The stories of a
handshake deal with the devil at midnight at a deserted crossroads
(seven years of unmatched skill as a bluesman for his soul is the
bargain said to have been struck), the constant wandering, the
mysterious death at a young age, the burial in an unmarked grave.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Johnson dichotomy: We feel that his songs take us as
far into his soul as we can possibly go, but his shadowy death _ he
is said to have been poisoned by a jealous husband _ is a fitting
end to his life.
</P>
<P>
   We know Johnson recorded twice, in 1936 in San Antonio and in
1937 in Dallas. And for years Johnson was only a voice: Only two
photographs have been made public, both only in the past few years.
For most of the time that men like Keith Richard, Eric Clapton and
John Hammond have revered him, Johnson has been, literally,
invisible.
</P>
<P>
   The music is still what matters most, at least to those like
bluesman Corey Harris. Harris was a disc jockey and amateur
bluesman back in 1989 or 1990, when a friend gave him a tape of
Johnson's music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew about him, but when I heard it I thought it was a bit
strange,'' said Harris, who has recorded several well-received CDs
for Chicago's Alligator Records. ``It's like I `felt' the songs. It
wasn't just toe-tappin' music _ it wasn't something you kind of
listened to and carried on a conversation. It was so up in your
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings it to you _ he doesn't just say, `I'm feeling kind
of bad today.' He's gonna tell you exactly what it is and detail
it. He communicates a feeling with words and in the end, you're
left with that feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past several years, the two photographs and the 41 songs
released in 1990 as ``The Complete Recordings'' were assumed to be
all there was left of Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   But two tantalizing nuggets recently have come to light: a newly
discovered alternate take of ``Traveling Riverside Blues'' and the
holy grail of blues fanatics, what is believed to be actual
``film'' of Johnson in performance.
</P>
<P>
   Blues archivist Alan Lomax had the take of ``Riverside'' in his
collection, and it will appear on the Sept. 15 CD reissue of ``King
of the Delta Blues Singers,'' the 1961 LP that made such an impact
on young white American folk fans and English blues-rockers.
</P>
<P>
   MORE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The snippet of silent 16mm film is owned by Memphis blues
memorabilia collector Leo ``Tater Red'' Allred. According to New
York blues guitarist and researcher David Rubin, who has seen the
film, Johnson is on screen about 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   He is seen from the waist up, wearing a hat and a harmonica rack
(which may seem odd, as he never played harmonica on a record). He
looks straight into the camera and ``actually plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin remembers being stunned at viewing the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dead giveaway is the fingers _ it's those long, long
fingers. It's him,'' he says. ``You see people on the street, cars
_ and him playing. It was the thrill of a lifetime. We were truly
transfixed watching this, and I've heard other people who have seen
it started crying.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten seconds of one of the greatest musicians of all time. It's
not enough, not for any fan, but considering the rest of Johnson's
life and death, it's perfectly fitting.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Johnson lived by night, on the move, doling out his art
in anguished, impassioned snippets _ only one of his songs,
``Terraplane Blues,'' is three minutes long _ and then vanishing
into the collective imagination of blues fans around the world.
</P>
<P>
   We imagine what we can't know, make up our own visions of him
walking down a lonely country road, or playing a raucous party, or
recording in some makeshift studio. And whatever else, we can
always listen again, and wonder.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, ultimately, it comes down to the music,'' Guralnick
says. ``He saw his songs as finished pieces of art, and he
crystalized both the Delta blues tradition and the more popular
blues of the day, people like Leroy Carr and Scrapper Blackwell and
the Mississippi Sheiks. And the music will be there after the myth
of Robert Johnson goes away.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman covers pop music for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 1646EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
