<SLUG> BC-BLUESMAN-ACOUSTIC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE BLUES DONE RIGHT _ ACOUSTICALLY, THAT IS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies BC-BLUESMAN-LEGACY) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The heyday of acoustic blues was from the late 1920s _ when
Dallasite Blind Lemon Jefferson became a star _ through the '30s,
after which the advent of the electric guitar made it somewhat
irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   But the acoustic legacy of Robert Johnson continues. John
Hammond, Rory Block, Taj Mahal and Johnny Winter have cut acoustic
tunes. And a number of currently popular bluesmen are following in
Johnson's footsteps:
</P>
<P>
   KEB' MO': This California native (whose real name is Kevin
Moore) uses the old acoustic blues styles but has found his own
voice with incisive, thoroughly modern folk-blues songwriting. His
first, eponymous CD in 1994 featured two Johnson covers; his 1996
CD, ``Just Like You,'' had one.
</P>
<P>
   COREY HARRIS: Based in Virginia, Harris is known for deep,
``deep'' Delta blues, including songs popularized by Son House, one
of Johnson's mentors. His ghostly slide and brooding vocals are
obviously in the Johnson mode. Both 1995's ``Between Midnight and
Day'' and last year's ``Fish Ain't Bitin''' are excellent
evocations of the Depression-era blues.
</P>
<P>
   ALVIN YOUNGBLOOD HART: Hart is as hyper-eclectic as bluesmen
get: His second CD, ``Territory,'' includes everything from
impressive takes on country blues such as Skip James' ``Illinois
Blues'' to a version of a slippery, almost-hard-rock Captain
Beefheart instrumental _ ``Ice Rose'' _ to a ska tune, ``Just About
to Go.'' And most of it is very good.
</P>
<P>
   CHRIS WHITLEY: Whitley first gained national attention with the
stark, dusty, sexually charged folk-blues of ``Living With the
Law.'' He made a stunning return to his solo acoustic roots this
year with ``Dirt Floor,'' recorded in one day.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's a new compilation of Johnson songs by a bona
fide blues-rock legend: Fleetwood Mac founder Peter Green, who
wrote ``Oh Well'' and ``Black Magic Woman,'' has just released
``The Robert Johnson Songbook,'' 14 classics done with help from
guitarist Nigel Watson. The style is not straight acoustic Delta
blues; the songs feature bass, drums, piano and, occasionally, a
backing vocal group.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 1651EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
