<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1686 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      08-19 0265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCREEN SAVER: OUT OF A JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Do you really have to use a screen saver to prevent burn-in,
or is computer screen technology more advanced these days? What's
the best type for protecting the monitor? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Screen savers have become an art form unto themselves over
the years, so it's sometimes hard to remember that they were
originally designed to serve a very practical function. When
monochrome monitors were the standard, a file left on the screen
for a long time could leave a ghostly pattern on the glass, burned
in by the constant light needed to display the image.
</P>
<P>
   With modern color monitors, burn-in is not the problem it used
to be, but a small risk remains. An image left on a laptop LCD
screen for an extended period can leave a ghostly reminder, but
unlike desktop monitors using cathode-ray tubes, LCD screens can
rebound from this, erasing the ghost after the screen is off for a
while.
</P>
<P>
   Many computer systems will automatically put the screen in
``sleep'' mode if there is no activity for a specified period of
time.
</P>
<P>
   Some computer professionals say that elaborate animated screen
savers hog system resources and may wear out the phospors faster.
So a dark, simple screen saver could be best for preserving the
life of your monitor. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Circuits invites questions about computer-based
technology, by postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York
Times, 229 West 43d Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail
to QandA(AT)ytimes.com.(end italics)
</P>
</TEXT>
