</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING Q &AMP; A 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LESLIE LAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perennial Snapdragons? Absolutely
</P>
<P>
   Q. A friend is trying to find perennial snapdragons for her home
garden but can't find anyone who sells them. Do they exist? Can we
find them in the Delaware area?
</P>
<P>
   A. Your friend will find perennials if she finds any at all,
because the common snapdragon (Antirrhinum majus) isn't really an
annual. It's a short-lived perennial that will overwinter anywhere
temperatures stay above 10 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In such places, snapdragons are usually done in by fungus
disease, not frost. They are susceptible to snapdragon rust,
anthracnose and botrytis, and they often rot in the cold, damp
weather of early spring. Those vulnerabilities explain why they are
usually categorized as annuals in spite of their true nature.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps your friend was hoping that perennials would look better
than the ever-squattier, ever-duller snapdragons in garden centers
in spring. Fortunately, all she has to do is grow from seed to
enjoy all sorts of beautiful varieties, including many that have
been bred for rust resistance. They are usually categorized by
height, from eight-inch dwarfs to three-foot giants. Flowers may be
the classic lipped tube or a more open, flatter shape called azalea
or butterfly-flowered. Double and single, ruffled and smooth, they
come in every color but blue.
</P>
<P>
   Snapdragons take a long time to flower. They must be started
early to give a long season of bloom. Gardeners in the
10-degree-and-below belt have to begin indoors around Valentine's
Day, but everywhere else seeds can be planted in fall and wintered
outside as young plants.
</P>
<P>
   Delaware is right on the edge, so if your friend is in a warm
part of the state or has a protected place in the garden, she can
give outdoor planting a try. Seeds sown now will make good growth
before winter sets in and will be ready to take off as spring
comes.
</P>
<P>
   If a cold frame is available, start them there. Otherwise,
choose a sheltered spot where they will not be buffeted by strong
winds. Avoid southern exposures, where the plants may be subjected
to repeated freezing and thawing. Press the very tiny seed into the
ground and water well, but don't cover with soil _ snapdragons need
light to germinate (which will take several weeks).
</P>
<P>
   If you already have plants you like, give them their best shot
at survival by keeping them weeded, removing spent flowers and
getting rid of any foliage that looks diseased. Don't fertilize
after mid-August; you want the plant to concentrate on toughening
up, rather than making new growth.
</P>
<P>
   Snapdragon seeds are widely available. The Brighton Rock strain,
which resembles the parti-colored varieties popular in the 19th
century, is offered by Select Seeds Antique Flowers, 180 Stickney
Hill Road, Union, Conn. 06076-4617; (860) 684-9310 (catalog $1).
The beautiful velvety red Black Prince is sold by Pinetree Garden
Seeds, P.O. Box 300, New Gloucester, Maine 04260; (207) 926-3400
(free catalog).
</P>
<P>
   One Tough Clematis
</P>
<P>
   Q. For three years, I've watched my clematis rise from its
planter and climb aggressively up its trellis, only to wilt and die
once it gets two and a half or three feet tall. The soil appears to
be good. The plant gets full sun until about 1 p.m., and I feed and
water it regularly. What can I do to keep this from happening?
</P>
<P>
   A. It sounds as if your plant is afflicted with a fungus disease
called clematis wilt, which has no cure. But it also sounds as if
you've got a tough plant, since it isn't dead yet. To reward its
perseverance, start by getting rid of every trace of the diseased
foliage. Then repot it in new soil, burying it about an inch deeper
than before. Don't feed it until next spring, and then only
sparingly until it is well along. Be sure the soil stays barely
moist, not waterlogged.
</P>
<P>
   The standard wisdom on clematis is ``head in the sun, feet in
the shade,'' because the plants appreciate cool soil around the
roots. Since yours is in a container, there's a good chance that as
the season warms up, the soil will be doing the same, and that just
when the plant most needs cool roots, they are instead being fried.
This is most likely to be a problem if the container is on a stone
patio or other hot spot. Dark colors absorb heat, too. If your
container is anything but pale, it might be wise to paint it or use
a light-colored one.
</P>
<P>
   Death to Bugs. All Bugs?
</P>
<P>
   Q. This is my first year to have a garden. I have corn,
tomatoes, onions, bell peppers and cucumbers. I have encountered
some minor insect problems and was wondering what insecticide I
might be able to use on everything, as well as around my house.
</P>
<P>
   A. Surely not EVERYTHING! Not the beneficial ladybugs that eat
bad actors like aphids. Not the harmless little wasps that keep
whiteflies at bay. Not the . . . well, you get the idea. It's
natural to want to get rid of damaging insects, and it certainly
would be convenient if one product fixed every problem, but gardens
_ even the simplest ones _ are fantastically complex ecosystems
where one size never fits all.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds as if you are in an ideal place to start out right.
Your insect problems are still minor, and you haven't yet started
poisoning everything in sight and wiping out all your helpers.
Natural predators need a wide variety of habitats. Encourage them
by planting lots of different flowers, vegetables and herbs. Keep
your plants healthy; sick ones are much more likely to suffer from
insect attacks.
</P>
<P>
   And get one of the many books that have pictures of good and bad
bugs in it; for example, ``The Organic Gardener's Handbook of
Natural Insect and Disease Control'' (Rodale Press, 1992). Armed
with such a guide, you'll be able to tell friend from foe, and how
to have at the latter without doing harm to the former.
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to:
</P>
<P>
   Garden Q&AMP;A
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times
</P>
<P>
   229 W. 43rd Street, New York 10036, or by e-mail to
gardening(AT)nytimes..com.
</P>
<P>
   Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished
questions cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
