<HEADER>
A1712 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLIND-GARDENER-ART-2T     08-19 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLIND-GARDENER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BRAILLE OF BUDS, STEMS AND FLOWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MAC GRISWOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHELTER ISLAND, N.Y. _ Gardening has few heroes, being generally
an unheroic pastime, but William Price, 84, is surely one of them.
Blind for more than 50 years, he does all his gardening by himself,
once someone else turns the soil with a rototiller in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody else has set foot in this garden to work in it except
me,'' Price said with uncharacteristic fierceness the other day,
standing in his 45-by-50-foot plot of vegetables and flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Raising plants from seed (he collects some himself), laying out
rows, planting, weeding, watering, picking, staking the remarkable
dahlias he has grown for years and finding and squishing tomato
worms _ surely, one of a gardener's most satisfying and grisly
tasks _ Price does it all. ``I found a four-inch one the other day,
and it really gave me the chills,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like some modest 19th-century hero who acted as if it was all in
a day's work Price will complain about tomato worms but not much
else. Certainly not about the osteoporosis that is doubling him
over, nor the arthritis in his feet, nor the fact that he is among
the 10 percent in the world of the visually impaired who are
totally without sight. He does not want to emphasize the
difficulties of blindness but simply to point out that there are
lots of ways to get around them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he's a resourceful and courageous man, Bill figures
out ways to do these things on his own,'' said Betty Bird, the
senior vice president for rehabilitation at the Lighthouse, the
national nonprofit association for the visually impaired and who is
also blind. ``Most people, when they lose their vision, don't know
what their options are. They don't believe they can do it. It's
beyond their imagining that they could garden for pleasure. They
need encouragement. Bill got past that point. He took life and ran
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Price has retinitis pigmentosa, a hereditary progressive
degenerative disease of the retina, which slowly narrows vision to
a pinpoint and, in his case, after that to nothing. By the age of
30, he had lost his sight entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Before that happened, however, he worked in a brokerage house
and went to the State University Agricultural and Technical College
at Farmingdale, N.Y., which explains how he learned garden
techniques, but not how he learned to adapt them to his darkened
world or how he developed his remarkable memory.
</P>
<P>
   After agriculture school, he farmed and gardened, bracing
himself for the day when the lights would go out. During those
years, he amassed a large visual vocabulary of plants and flowers
and developed a grasp of space, mass and volume.
</P>
<P>
   The 1880s farmhouse where he lives for six months of the year
with his wife, Elaine (who is sighted), stands at the edge of
Coecles Harbor. (They spend the other months on Johns Island, S.C.)
They married, he for the first time, 22 years ago, and moved to
this house in 1981, but Price has known summer on Shelter Island
since he was a boy growing up in Brooklyn, where his father was a
surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   The screened porch looks over a sunburned lawn to a water view
crowded with sailboats. ``I can see where I am out there,'' Price
said, remembering his childhood sailing days and adding that his
disability gives him certain advantages, like being able to garden
at night and not having to see the large television satellite dish
that is now part of the view.
</P>
<P>
   The usual shrubs that flower in August _ rose of Sharon,
buddleia, abelia, hydrangea, perpetual flowering roses _ were
cheerfully blooming their heads off. Price gets up early and waters
them.
</P>
<P>
   Walking through the garden, Price picked lettuce and dill, so he
could make egg salad sandwiches for lunch. (He does all the cooking
for the two of them.) Then he made a beeline for his pride and joy,
his dahlias. Most are named after friends or donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's Allie, tall and yellow, with a large flower,'' he
said. ``And there's Andy, short, but also with a large flower.'' He
has known some of these varieties since the time when he could see
them.
</P>
<P>
   From the shapely look of his dahlias, it is clear that Price
also knows the architecture of plants. Disbudding, nipping off some
buds to insure that the ones that remain will be bigger, means
gauging which buds to lop off. More remarkable for someone who
cannot see is his instinctive judgment about form, being aware of
each bud and balancing the framework of stem and foliage to get
maximum sun and space for the flowers. Texture and form, he says,
are what he is after in the garden, far more than fragrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fragrance is a sighted person's concept of what a blind person
would enjoy,'' Ms. Bird said. ``Texture is more important to the
blind. But they leave lacy or tiny flowers _ those little
gossamer-type plants _ to the sighted. The visually impaired
usually like things such as tulips, sedums or roses, things they
can get their hands round to feel the shape.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no obvious clues that Price's garden belongs to a
blind person, but subtle indications are there. The paths are
Braille for his feet: one path is floored with wood chips; another
with old boards, and still others are plain dirt. In the spring,
Price lays out two fishing lines and plants seeds between them to
get his rows straight.
</P>
<P>
   He once had dreams of becoming an architect, and he annually
memorizes his handsome garden layout: New Zealand spinach, rows of
green beans, limas, tomatoes neatly staked and tied, eggplant,
peppers, zucchini. Finding the ripe vegetables is done by touch he
said. He pointed out the wax and yellow beans, the chard and
carrots. Marigolds and orange cosmos filled out his rows; he grows
them from seed he saves every year. He also knows his way by the
texture and shape of flower and foliage. And, he said, ``I know all
the weeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone else who gardens in the Northeast, he has a mortal
enemy: hungry deer. So, with a little help from Mrs. Price, he
strung the top of his garden fence with electric wire.
</P>
<P>
   The bright yellow of the wire and the red of the conductors seem
to add something to the garden, a doughty sense of enclosure and
protection. Inside the fence is a thick border of cosmos and
invasive purple loosestrife, which he concedes is hard to control.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As he headed across the lawn to the house to make lunch, he
commented that he thought the hydrangeas someone gave him were too
high for the scale of the yard. How did he know? By touch, of
course, he said, but also by an innate faculty that helps him
understand proportion and space.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bird believes that Price has heightened ``object perception
capability.'' Research has shown that people can perceive objects
without seeing them because of a change in pressure in the
semicircular canals of the inner ear.
</P>
<P>
   Everything he touches helps Price orient himself. Three old
field junipers stand a few yards south of the garden, and to watch
him put his hand on the bark is to see him check out his location.
Sometimes, however, he does get lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``This morning, I was wheeling a barrowload of blackweed down to
the pile by the beach _ I'd never put that stuff in my compost _
and I got a little off course on my way back,'' he said. The
remarkable thing is not that he got lost but that he routinely
negotiates the long slope to the beach with a full barrow of weeds
at age 84 _ and blind, of course.
</P>
<P>
   How does he do any of it? Like those dahlias. When he digs up
the tender tubers, how does he keep them organized each winter so
that he can replant them in the spring. He has his own system:
``Boxes of different sizes, shapes and textures,'' he answered.
``Andy goes into an old copper boiler.''
</P>
<P>
   Lunch over, Price announced that he had to be getting back to
work. Like all gardeners, he was thinking about the future; like
only the best gardeners he had the energy and the stamina to make
his vision come true. That afternoon, he said, he was going to fill
that wheelbarrow with bricks and begin laying out a new path.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
