<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1719 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARD-ARTS-CENTER-ART-     08-19 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARD-ARTS-CENTER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM GEHRY, A BILBAO ON THE HUDSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANNANDALE-ON-HUDSON, N.Y. _ Bard College, a small liberal arts
school on 550 acres here, wants to build a knock-your-socks-off
building, a sculptural shell to show off music, drama and dance.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by Frank O. Gehry, an architect who is basking in the
triumph of his Guggenheim Museum in Bilbao, Spain, the $24 million
Bard Performing Arts Center would have some of the same sweeping,
fluttering silvery roofs, some of the same draftsman-defying curves
as its Spanish sibling-under-the-skin _ and some crinkles thrown
in.
</P>
<P>
   To townspeople, preservationists and Bard's president alike, the
860-seat arts center might well be another of Gehry's architectural
coups, a mecca for architectural pilgrims and lovers of the
performing arts. It could also be a draw for this bucolic region
studded with stately homes _ in an area still reeling from the IBM
plant closings that knocked more than 20,000 workers off the
payrolls four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one problem.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people think it's in the wrong spot.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the Gehry structure is designed to nestle in a ravine
next to another of Bard's performing arts buildings. The site is
305 feet from the Saw Kill creek, across from land owned by
Montgomery Place, whose mansion and grounds are listed on the
National Register of Historic Places and are seen by 30,000
visitors a year. While the new center would not obstruct Montgomery
Place's view of the Hudson, it would look out over a pristine,
backwoods lake and dam rhapsodized by A.J. Downing, one of the most
famous of 19th-century romantic landscapers.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents are worried that the 105-foot stainless steel, glass
and concrete building will be seen above and through the trees from
the mansion's numerous trails _ and Lucy Kuriger, director of
Montgomery Place, fears it might even be visible from the columned
porch of the 1804 classical revival house itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It needs to be moved back,'' said Richard Jenrette, the
well-known financier, house restorer _ and neighbor. On June 15,
Jenrette expressed his concerns in a letter to the planning board
of Red Hook, the township that includes the hamlet of
Annandale-on-Hudson. The town has been asked to grant a variance to
allow the center.
</P>
<P>
   Jenrette is joined in his concern by other preservationists and
environmentalists. The State Parks Department ``strongly
recommends'' that the center be moved somewhere else _ or be
reduced in height. The National Park Service worries that the
construction will pose ``a threat'' to the historic district,
according to letters to the planning board.
</P>
<P>
   In his own letter, Jenrette said the building would ``despoil
the single most important area of natural beauty in Dutchess
County.'' The siting of the proposed building, he wrote, ``seems
almost vindictive.'' At the end of his letter, he asked, ``If the
proposed Frank Gehry structure is going to be beautiful, why not
stick it in a place where Bard can enjoy all sides?''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, even Gehry asked the same question of Bard's
determined president, Dr. Leon Botstein, who is also the conductor
and music director of the American Symphony Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``I argued with him a lot,'' Gehry said. ``Your first take is:
when you have this beautiful building, why put it down there?'' If
the building were in the center of the campus, he said, ``it would
make it a more important building.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Gehry was convinced by the arguments of
Botstein, whom he called ``a genius.'' ``He's vehement: He's not
building it just to build an edifice, for fluff,'' he said. The new
center, the architect said, must be ``part of the teaching
experience'' and relate to the two adjacent arts buildings, which
will become part of what Botstein sees as the campus arts complex.
</P>
<P>
   The building has to be massive, Gehry added, because it must
work for orchestra, opera, theater and dance. It must be almost
100-feet high because of the flies _ the area above the stage that
holds the scenery.
</P>
<P>
   Both Botstein and Gehry agreed that to move the building would
require a completely new design and more money because the center
was designed to be used with the older arts building next door _ to
share dressing rooms, for example. ``If you moved the building,
everything would be more complicated and a lot more expensive,''
Botstein said, adding that compared with other liberal arts
schools, Bard has a small endowment: only $82 million. (Vassar, 35
minutes away, has an endowment of $555 million.)
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 3, Bard volunteered to submit an environmental impact
statement by Oct. 1. Officially, everyone is waiting _ although
Botstein vows to start construction in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the public relations maneuvering goes on. Botstein
invited Jenrette to tour the campus. For another visitor, he
brandished a stack of glossy snapshots as thick as a plumber's
thumb, purporting to show that balloons raised to the height of the
proposed building could barely be seen from across the Saw Kill.
For their part, the preservationists show photomontages that
purport to show just how looming the new building will be _ even
when the leaves are out in summer.
</P>
<P>
   Was Jenrette convinced?
</P>
<P>
   ``I softened my position,'' he said. ``Leon had some reasons. I
don't think he MEANT to be mean and hateful. But I still think they
should move it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
