<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTECTING CHILDREN FROM ON-LINE PREDATORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wash.)   (af)  
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After logging on to a chatroom for timid people, ``Britny02''
said she had just moved to a new town and was interested in
learning new things. Within half a minute, Britny02 was receiving
messages from a man who said he was significantly older and wanted
to know about what sort of new things she was interested in
learning, if she had ever messed around with a boyfriend, and if he
could call her. Soon three or four other men were propositioning
her too.
</P>
<P>
   In a Seattle classroom, six parents of elementary school
children stared in disbelief as the dialogue flashed on their own
terminals and the potential child molesters ``groomed'' the young
girl.
</P>
<P>
   The parents were attending a seminar on Internet safety led by
Seattle vice detective Leanne Shirey. Fortunately, ``Britny02'' was
fictitious, an online pseudonym created, typos and all, by Det.
Shirey. But the problem ``Britny02'' illustrated was all too real.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't surprised by how quickly we got the guy to come out
of the woodwork,'' Detective Shirey said. ``That's exactly what we
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored by a volunteer group of public and private security
experts and local and federal law enforcement officials, the
seminar provided parents with tips for protecting their kids from
online predators, the first such seminar in the country, according
to Detective Shirey.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something every police department in the country could
offer within two years for free,'' said the detective, who is
working with federal law enforcement trainers to expand the
seminar. ``A lot of parents don't understand computers, or how to
learn about Web safety when they're told to go to this Web site for
more information. We're the generation with the blinking 12:00 on
the VCR.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents at the seminar were taught how to search for secret
e-mail addresses their children may have obtained (try searching
for your child's name on the e-mail search pages of four11.com or
lycos.com) or postings they may have made on newsgroups _ search in
www.dejanews.com).
</P>
<P>
   Parents even learned how to read their children's e-mail if
necessary, even without knowing the password _ by checking under
the child's screen name in the Organize folder of some programs.
</P>
<P>
   Terri Dowling, an attendee whose 14-year-old son uses the
Internet, was amazed by how quickly children can find trouble even
when they aren't looking.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can decide oops, I'm in the wrong place, if they want to
learn about the White House and end up in a porno site,'' she said,
noting addresses like www.whitehouse.com, porn sites discussed at
the seminar that are accidentally visited by students who had
intended to visit government sites instead.
</P>
<P>
   Parents using filters or blocking devices on the computer should
understand the limitations of software, Detective Shirey said. She
also stressed that if someone on line tries to lure a child to a
face-to-face meeting, the police should be notified immediately:
the average child molester reaches 100 victims before ever being
caught.
</P>
<P>
   Other tips of the day: kids shouldn't use their ages, birthdays
or graduation years in their screen names, as child molesters can
search for such numbers when trolling for potential victims. And if
parents want to keep their own passwords secret for long, they
should avoid obvious ones. (Pet names, for example, are easy for
kids to figure out.)
</P>
<P>
   And if a child has a pager, parents might need to keep an eye
out for suspicious incoming numbers or numeric messages like 1-2-3,
a code for ``I love you.'' Consider getting a duplicate pager if
strange messages come in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids know you don't give out your phone number, but pedophiles
will say, `here's my number, call collect,' '' and the child's
number will show up on the molester's phone bill, Det. Shirey said.
From there, using a reverse phone directory like one at lycos.com,
it's not hard to find full names and street addresses.
</P>
<P>
   The most common mistakes parents make include letting a child
have a computer in his or her room, or letting the screen face a
wall instead of the middle of a common room, Det. Shirey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent so much time getting our kids on the Internet,'' she
said, ``but we didn't get the parents there first.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
