<HEADER>
A1747 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LINCOLN-PHOTO-800&AMP;add     08-19 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINCOLN-PHOTO-800&AMP;add-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS IT THE EARLIEST LIKENESS OF THE MAN ON THE $5 BILL?  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since the small, leather-encased oval daguerreotype of
someone who looks like a young Abraham Lincoln surfaced a few years
ago, experts have been arguing about it. If the picture, made
around 1843, is of the 16th president, it would be Lincoln's first
likeness, predating a daguerreotype in the Library of Congress that
was made between 1846 and 1849. It would be a major historical
discovery.
</P>
<P>
   The image in question, known as the Hay Wadsworth daguerreotype,
has thus faced all kinds of scrutiny: by a forensic anthropologist,
a criminal identification specialist, a photographer who ``aged''
the image by computer and two medical experts who analyzed the vein
pattern in the subject's hand. Most of them think it is Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   But skeptics persist, led by the doubter-in-chief, Lloyd
Ostendorf, 77, of Akron, Ohio, the surviving co-author of ``Lincoln
in Photographs'' (Morningside Press, 1985). ``I have no questions
about what that is, and it's not Lincoln,'' he said, reeling off a
dozen physical characteristics, from the big, sharp nose to the
too-small ears, that do not match Lincoln's.
</P>
<P>
   Now the market will decide. The owners, Robert and Joan Hoffman
of Pittsford, N.Y., a suburb of Rochester, have consigned the
daguerreotype to Christie's, which is to auction it on Oct. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very daring move,'' said Harold Holzer, the author
of 12 books on Lincoln and the Civil War. (He is also chief
spokesman for the Metropolitan Museum of Art.)
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high. If it is the first daguerreotype of Abraham
Lincoln, it could fetch $1 million, Lincoln scholars estimated. And
if it is not? ``It's worth $5 or $6 on the antique photograph
market, maybe $50 at tops,'' Ostendorf said.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's, while bullish, is not pushing too hard. In the
catalog, it will describe the work as ``Portrait of a Gentleman,
Believed to Be Abraham Lincoln, Aged 34.'' The estimate is $200,000
to $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, the record auction price for a Lincoln memento of
any sort is $1.54 million, set in 1992, for an 1857 draft of his
``house divided'' speech opposing slavery. The record for a
daguerreotype is $189,000, set in 1995, for ``The Capitol
Building'' by John Plumb, circa 1846.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I can add this to the gallery of Abraham Lincoln
images carte blanche,'' said Rick Wester, director of Christie's
photography department. ``Christie's needs to be realistic about it
and say there is a possibility that it is not Lincoln.''
</P>
<P>
   Caveat emptor, in other words. Auctioneers frequently sell items
they cannot identify precisely, of course. Christie's and Sotheby's
do not guarantee anything made before 1870, and they often label
Old Master paintings as ``circle of'' or ``school of'' particular
artists, for example. Sometimes, buyers do more research and the
attribution may change to a more highly valued artist _ or to a
less respected one.
</P>
<P>
   Daguerreotypes, which are one-of-a-kind mirror images, pose
particular problems of their own. They became common only in 1839,
and the process, the early lenses used and the required harsh
lighting distort the picture of the sitter.
</P>
<P>
   The Hoffmans _ he is an antiques dealer and she an educator at
the Strong Museum in Rochester, N.Y. _ refuse to disclose what they
paid for their treasure, but they knew they had to make a case for
it. If the Hay Wadsworth image is Lincoln, it depicts him as a
beardless member of the Illinois State Legislature, 17 years before
he was elected president and before his new wife, Mary Todd
Lincoln, a socially prominent banker's daughter, spruced him up.
But the public knows Lincoln as he is depicted on the $5 bill, on
the penny and in his majestic marble memorial in Washington, always
with the beard he grew after he was elected president. Many people
would no doubt have a hard time reconciling the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always surprised that people think people will age the way
they do in movies,'' said Holzer. ``But faces really change _ noses
droop, things sag, a lot can happen.'' He added that the Library of
Congress' daguerreotype was originally doubted, too, requiring
Lincoln's son Robert to authenticate it three times.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Holzer is not entirely convinced. ``I think the
possibility exists that it could be Lincoln'' is his most forceful
verdict after reviewing the supporting evidence and writing two
articles about it.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 1717EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1748 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LINCOLN-PHOTO-2NDTAKE     08-19 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINCOLN-PHOTO-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: about it.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   That evidence is varied. Allen Phillips, a photographer, used a
computer to line up facial features of five later images of Lincoln
and easily ``dissolved'' or ``morphed'' the daguerreotype image
into the last known photo of him, taken in April 1865, the month he
was shot. Albert Harper, a forensic anthropologist, measured such
things as forehead height, nasal height, mouth contour and other
facial elements and found matches with later Lincoln portraits.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Buberger, a dealer in antique photographs and the
daguerreotype's most ardent champion, traced the travels of
itinerant photographers in 1843 and found at least two who visited
Springfield, Ill., where Lincoln lived that year. Buberger, who
helped the Hoffmans and who, some experts said, harbored hopes that
he would sell it for them on commission, even called in Dr. Henry
Lee, the forensic scientist whose testimony helped acquit O.J.
Simpson. Lee agreed with those who think the portrait is genuine. (
Hoffman said that all the experts volunteered their expertise. ``No
one ever charged us or anyone else for the research,'' he said.)
</P>
<P>
   The vein analyses, on the other hand, were mixed. Dr. Ralph
Leonard, a medical professor at Wake Forest University, concluded
that the vein patterns in the daguerreotype did not match
Lincoln's. But Dr. Blaine Houmes, the deputy medical examiner in
Cedar Rapids, Iowa, and a Lincoln photo collector, said they did
correspond.
</P>
<P>
   In pursuing the consignment, Christie's relied most heavily on
the work of Lewis Sadler, the head of the Biomedical Visualization
Laboratory at the University of Illinois at Chicago. Sadler
developed an identification process that feeds mathematical
``facial maps'' into a computer model and sifts the data for
matches. To test the daguerreotype, he mapped it and three other
Lincoln images and mixed them with 300 other facial maps of white
males. He got three matches _ with the three other Lincoln
portraits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have observed this type of clustering only in cases where we
had photos of the same individual and in the case of identical
twins,'' Dr. Sadler wrote. ``I would have to conclude that there
was nothing to indicate that this was not a photo of Abraham
Lincoln.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't deny that,'' Wester of Christie's said. ``Everything
else is human opinion.'' Believers are also buoyed by the
daguerreotype's provenance, which shows a strong yet circuitous tie
to Lincoln. The Hoffmans bought the image from George Feeley, an
antiques dealer in Caledonia, N.Y., shortly before he died in 1993.
Feeley, Hoffman said, was the private liquidator for the Wadsworth
family. Senator James W. Wadsworth Jr. was married to Alice Hay,
who was the daughter of John Milton Hay, Lincoln's private
secretary (and later Secretary of State under Presidents William
McKinley and Theodore Roosevelt).
</P>
<P>
   Hay and Lincoln were close. During the Civil War, Hay moved into
the White House, and Hay, some historians say, was the only person
there who referred to Lincoln by his first name. Documents show
that the Lincolns gave Hay many artifacts, including a lock of the
president's hair, letters and two copies of the Gettyburg Address,
as well as a scrapbook of Civil War news clippings.
</P>
<P>
   Descendants also say that they recall seeing the daguerreotype
in the Wadsworth household.
</P>
<P>
   To which Ostendorf said, so what? ``Everybody has pictures of
family and friends. If that's convincing provenance, I'd like to
see unconvincing provenance.'' Scholars said many look-alikes sent
Lincoln and his family their own pictures, and Hay might have had
one of those.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
