<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE STEALTHY WAYS TO SPY ON EMPLOYEES  
 LESS EXPENSIVE PDAS COMING, WITH FEWER FEATURES  
 GOVERNMENT SEEKS BETTER KEY TO LOCK SECRET DATA  
 UNSOLICITED JUNK E-MAIL NOW OFFICIALLY CALLED SPAM  
 REMOTE CONTROL FOR PC CAN ENHANCE PRESENTATIONS  
 VATICAN PLANS MORE WEBCASTS OF AUDIENCES BY POPE  
 SMITHSONIAN ROBOT TO HAVE KID-FRIENDLY SWEET TOUCH  
 TURNING A CURSOR INTO AN AD JUST FOR LAUGHS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Employers increasingly are finding ever sneakier ways to watch
their employees' every keystroke. A new generation of software has
emerged that allows managers to record not just which Web sites
employees browse but which programs they use, which memos they
write, any e-mail they send _ in short, every single move they make
on their computers.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, WinWhatWhere Corp., a Kennewick, Wash., software
company released a program called Investigator that according to
the company makes and stores a record of every keystroke, mouse
click and command entered on a PC. The program costs $285 for each
desktop computer on which it is deployed. (The per-desktop price is
lower for larger purchases.)
</P>
<P>
   In June, Tech Assist Inc., of Largo, Fla., began distribution in
North America of ``Desktop Surveillance,'' a comprehensive computer
monitoring program made by Omniquad in the United Kingdom. The
software costs $55 per computer and has been on sale in Europe for
about eight months.
</P>
<P>
   Each program allows employers to hide the fact that the software
is running. In the case of Desktop Surveillance, a log of the
employee's activities can be automatically e-mailed to a
supervisor, unbeknownst to the employee.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from Tech Assist and WinWhatWhere said they had
decided there was a market for their products, after hearing what
they said was tremendous demand from employers concerned about
employees wasting time on company computers. They said employers
also want to use the recorded events if the employees bring, or are
defendants in, lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Richard Eaton, president of
WinWhatWhere(www.WinWhatWhere.com) said his company, which
specializes in monitoring programs for home and business, struggled
with whether to produce software that could be used to invade
employees' privacy in such minute detail.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of turmoil internally about monitoring
keystrokes,'' Eaton said. ``It just seemed like too much, but it
was the No. 1 request from our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Less Expensive PDAs Coming, but With Fewer Features
</P>
<P>
   Furthering its efforts to become known as the maker of no-frills
gadgets, Royal Consumer Business Products next month plans to begin
selling a low-cost Personal Digital Assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Royal, a subsidiary of one-time typewriter giant Olivetti, will
offer its $99 PDA, called Da Vinci, with such basic features as
handwriting recognition and an address book. Two weeks later it
plans to start shipping Da Vinci Pro, a slightly souped-up and
pricier version with a slot for a modem card and full fax and modem
capability.
</P>
<P>
   The trade-off for consumers who buy the lower-priced Royal line
(compared with $300 or more for other PDA brands) is that it has
fewer features than other power-packed PDAs. For instance, Royal
left out such functions as an expense manager, which it says few
PDA owners use anyway, said Robert J. Robinson, executive director
of marketing for Royal.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said that the economy PDAs were part of the company's
business plan to offer lower-cost versions of electronic gadgets.
For instance, Royal sells paper shredders for less than $30 and the
most basic of electronic organizers for under $10, Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only so many features you can put on before a
product gets too complicated,'' Robinson insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the Da Vinci lines do have one optional feature not found
on other personal digital assistants. For an extra $29.95,
consumers can buy a very small folding QWERTY keyboard that plugs
into the back of the PDA.
</P>
<P>
   Government Seeks Better Key to Lock Up Top-Secret Data
</P>
<P>
   The government plans to pull back the curtains on Thursday on 15
candidates for one of the tougher job assignments that the 21st
century has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates all are algorithms, one of which likely will be
chosen as the basis for the government's standard encryption system
in the coming century. The National Institute of Standards and
Technology (NIST), a branch of the Commerce Department, plans to
unveil the contenders at a cryptography conference in Ventura,
Calif., north of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Bulman, spokesman for NIST, said the agency wanted to
pick the winning algorithm by 2001. Before then, leading
cryptographers will take their cracks at cracking and refining the
system. Ultimately, the code will be the basis for encrypting data
for the federal government agencies, along with banks and financial
institutions, Bulman said.
</P>
<P>
   In June, researchers cracked the existing data-scrambling code,
known as the Data Encryption Standard, or DES. DES uses a 56-bit
key _ which is a measure of how many possible password keys protect
a system. But yes, size does matter in cryptology too, and the new
algorithm will be substantially harder to crack because it will use
128-, 192- and 256-bit keys, Bulman said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Unsolicited Junk E-Mail Now Officially Called Spam
</P>
<P>
   It's official: Spam is more than a meal. If there was any doubt
about the popularity of the word ``spam'' as a derisive name for
unsolicited e-mail, the New Oxford Dictionary has officially
chiseled it into the lexicon
</P>
<P>
   The latest version of the New Oxford Dictionary of English,
published last Thursday, defines the word as ``irrelevant Internet
messages sent to a large number of people.''
</P>
<P>
   The inclusion of the definition was noticed immediately by the
Coalition Against Unsolicited Commercial E-mail, a lobbying group
pushing for anti-spam legislation. ``I guess it's official,'' said
a board member, John Mozena. ``Spam is not just for breakfast
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Remote Control for PC Can Enhance Presentations
</P>
<P>
   Television users who live and die by the remote control soon may
have a counterpart device for their computers. Interlink
Electronics Inc. of Camarillo, Calif., has begun public
demonstrations of the FreedomWriter, which the company plans to
market as a remote control for the computer.
</P>
<P>
   The handheld wireless device can be used as a mouse and touch
pad, allowing users to surf the Net, read e-mail, even enter text
using a handwriting-recognition feature.
</P>
<P>
   The company is initially marketing the FreedomWriter as a
business tool, for use in presentations. The company says the $199
device, which goes on sale in November, can be used by a presenter
to annotate slides and annotate text with a stylus.
</P>
<P>
   Vatican Plans More Webcasts of Audiences by the Pope
</P>
<P>
   Recently the Roman Catholic Church streamed live video and audio
over the Internet of Pope John Paul II's address on the Feast of
the Assumption, the celebration of Mary's ascension into heaven.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first papal Webcast but not the last: The Vatican
plans to post the pope's regular Wednesday audiences and Sunday
Masses over the Internet on the Vatican Web site (www.vatican.va).
</P>
<P>
   Smithsonian Robot to Have a Kid-Friendly Sweet Touch
</P>
<P>
   The Smithsonian Institution is creating a robot that not only is
user-friendly but looks user-friendly too: It can smile and even
offer candy to strangers.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists from Carnegie Mellon University and the University of
Bonn in Germany created the robot, named ``Minerva'' after the
Roman goddess of wisdom. The scientists hope to use the exhibits at
the Smithsonian to test the robot's ability to navigate a crowded
room without bumping into objects or people.
</P>
<P>
   Minerva is equipped with sensors that allow it to determine if
something, or someone, is in the way. It also has two video cameras
for eyes, which capture what Minerva ``sees.'' The images then will
be displayed on the Internet site for the Smithsonian museum's
Lemelson Center for the Study of Invention and Innovation
(www.si.edu/nmah/lemel), which is sponsoring the robot's visit.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to refining the robot itself, the scientists also
hope Minerva will help children feel comfortable with technology,
and will familiarize them with robots. To prepare children for the
new technology, they are relying on an old-fashioned trick: A box
of candy will be placed on board the robot to encourage youngsters
to approach.
</P>
<P>
   The robot will be on duty from from Monday to Sept. 5 in the
museum's ``Material World'' exhibit, which shows the impact on
people's lives of the use of wood, metal and synthetic materials.
</P>
<P>
   Turning a Cursor Into an Ad Mainly Just for Laughs
</P>
<P>
   To view the newest form of advertising on the Web, you don't
have to point and click. Just point and look.
</P>
<P>
   Comet Systems Inc., a New York company, has begun licensing
software that can turn the cursor itself into any graphic or
animation. On Sept. 9, Comedy Central (www.comedycentral.com), one
of the cursor's early adopters, will debut the technology on its
Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the Comedy Central site will be able to surf with a
cursor that looks like the animated characters ``Kenny,'' from the
show ``South Park,'' ``Dr. Katz'' from the show of the same name,
or the comedy network's logo. Visitors must first download the free
Comet Systems software, which takes little more than 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The year-old Comet Systems (www.cometsystems.com) is marketing
its malleable cursor as a way for companies to get their messages
across in a pointed fashion. For instance, the 1-800-Flowers site
is going to feature a cursor that morphs into a price tag when it
is scrolled over certain sale items; other times it is a red rose
beside ``1-800.''
</P>
</TEXT>
