<HEADER>
A1810 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-ROLLER-COASTERS-1     08-19 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ROLLER-COASTERS-1STLD-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLL COASTERS TAKE A RIDE FROM WILD TO WIRED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio, Pa., Nev., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (Eds: Please use this version)  
 (af)  
 By VERNE G. KOPYTOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Passengers on the Riddler's Revenge roller coaster squealed with
exuberance and panic, from the initial 15-story plunge right
through to the last of six fearsome spirals, many at freeway
speeds.
</P>
<P>
   The scene inside the ride's control room, a windowless office
underneath the ride platform here at Six Flags Magic Mountain
amusement park in suburban Los Angeles, was considerably more
subdued.
</P>
<P>
   One man sat gazing into a computer screen; at his side, inside a
cabinet that stretched the length of a Cadillac, some complicated
hardware performed acrobatics of its own, with no allowance for
dizziness.
</P>
<P>
   From the safety announcements played as passengers wait to get
on board to the photographs of screaming riders sold at the exit,
technology plays a starring but seldom-seen role in the operations
of roller coasters.
</P>
<P>
   As riders are whipsawed around a track in apparent pandemonium,
it is machines and not people that insure that the cars whiz down
the track at the right speed, do not collide and do not hit
obstacles that block the route.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day of the ride operator with a lever and brake is
history,'' said Jim Blackie, director of maintenance at Magic
Mountain. ``It's all computer controlled.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, on the Riddler's Revenge, billed as the nation's fastest
and tallest stand-up roller coaster, the job of a ride operator is
similar to that of a flight attendant: make sure that the automatic
safety bars are secure and that stuffed animals are stowed away.
Starting a train is accomplished with no more sweat than ringing a
door bell.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy lifting is left to two Allen-Bradley PLC-5s, which are
the size of encyclopedias but serve as the brains of a massive
control system built primarily by Rockwell International's
Allen-Bradley unit. Sitting in an air-conditioned room under the
station platform, they provide a full set of instructions to the
massive control system built around them every 20 to 40
milliseconds. Behind steel cabinet doors, red and green lights
flash as the trains round the track.
</P>
<P>
   Roller coaster control systems may often be referred to as
computers, by Blackie and others. But manufacturers are resolute in
using the term ``programmable logic controller'' to describe the
innards of theme ride technology. ``They look something like a
computer, they act like computers, but they're not as finicky as a
computer,'' said Kristen Carter, spokeswoman for Rockwell
Automation, a major producer of theme ride controls.
</P>
<P>
   Built to focus on their assigned task, these systems are
designed to operate without rest and always with utmost precision,
Ms. Carter said. In contrast, she said, personal computers and
mainframes may pause momentarily if given new instructions and are
more susceptible to temporary failure.
</P>
<P>
   Though relatively silent, the Allen-Bradleys are hard at work.
Before each roller coaster takes a lap around the track, the check
and then double-check with a backup program between 100 and 150
features on the ride that may affect safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can dream it, these computers can do it,'' Blackie
said. For example, the station operator cannot dispatch the roller
coaster unless sensors along the track tell the computers that the
route is clear. Called the block system, a standard feature
throughout the industry, two cars cannot enter the same zone
anywhere along the track without making the Allen-Bradleys shut
down the ride.
</P>
<P>
   Before computers, this job was left to human operators who had
to keep a constant eye on the track and their hands on a lever that
served as a break. High technology has taken their place and has
allowed as many as five trains to circulate at one time on some
coasters, compared with only two or three trains under manual
control.
</P>
<P>
   Removing the human element from nearly all aspects of roller
coaster operations is no accident, said Walt Davis, vice president
of Togo International, a roller coaster manufacturer in Cincinnati.
Automation is more reliable than part-time amusement park workers,
who may be faced with disturbances in the station, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to make the control systems as idiot-proof as
possible,'' Davis said. ``Suppose an unruly kid distracted the
operators and his friend came over and started pushing buttons. We
don't want to give them the flexibility of changing things.''
</P>
<P>
   But can technology be trusted to control such a potentially
dangerous ride as a roller coaster, particularly given the
knowledge that technology can sometimes go haywire? Davis said that
computers may indeed ``have a bad day'' but that they can be
programmed to tell operators when their circuitry gets
temperamental.
</P>
<P>
   The passengers on Riddler's Revenge have their first contact
with the ride's computer while waiting in line, with automated
theme music and warnings to the passengers to pull down their
safety harnesses as far as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Once out of the chute, the coaster encounters an incline that
inspires even the most fearless of riders to brace their feet
firmly on the floor and squeeze handholds.
</P>
<P>
   At the bottom of the hill, the roller coaster's brains put the
lift system on slowly, so the train can engage without a jolt, then
release it at the designated speed at the summit.
</P>
<P>
   From there, gravity takes over, as does the spinning, lurching
and screaming. Barring any problems, the train will return to the
station three minutes after it left to pick up another load of
passengers. Of course, things do not always run so smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For example, when Riddler's Revenge shut down recently,
stranding passengers on the track, technicians found the reason on
a personal computer that sits on a folding table in an unpainted
corner of the control room. Hooked to the mainframe, the computer
indicated with a coded message, deciphered with a logic diagram,
that a fuse had blown in the station.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the repair took only a few minutes, Blackie said, adding
that a similar malfunction 20 years ago could have taken hours to
repair because technology at that time was unable to tell engineers
where a defective part was located.
</P>
<P>
   Though amusement park engineers rely heavily on computers for
maintenance, they do so only to a point. At most parks, workers
inspect roller coasters every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will park a train on the tracks and run another by to see
if there will be an accident,'' said Jeffrey Budgeon, managing
director of planning, engineering and maintenance at Hershey Park
amusement park in Hershey, Pa. ``We want to make sure that the
computer is doing what it is supposed to be doing.''
</P>
<P>
   If a minor problem develops, the computers that control roller
coasters will merely warn technicians rather than shutting down the
ride. Some obstacles, like those caused by extreme weather, may be
easily fixed. For example, roller coasters run faster in hot
temperatures and more slowly in cold.
</P>
<P>
   On the Manhattan Express roller coaster at the New York, New
York casino in Las Vegas, Nev., technicians can activate a special
computer program to compensate for the harsh desert climate. One of
the computer's remedies is to adjust the speed of each train as it
begins its descent from the top of the first incline. It can also
slow a roller coaster car in mid-lap by applying the brakes when
sensors tell the computer that the train is speeding.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan Express control system also monitors wind gauges
high on the ride. If headwinds get too strong, the computer alerts
technicians because trains may have trouble returning to the
station.
</P>
<P>
   Some roller coasters have the additional protection of infrared
light beams that give an alarm when there is someone or something
blocking the track. If a light beam is broken, the computer stops
the ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times when a bird has flown through or a squirrel
has run across and shuts down the ride,'' said Dennis Speigel,
president of International Theme Park Services, an amusement park
consulting business in Cincinnati. ``But that's OK, because safety
is so important.''
</P>
<P>
   Though there have been deaths on roller coasters in recent
years, they appear to be more often the result of reckless rider
behavior and safety belt failures than computer malfunctions,
according to reports by the United States Consumer Product Safety
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   No one has died as a result of computer failure since 1980, when
a 13-year-old girl was killed in a collision of two trains at the
Great America amusement park in Santa Clara, Calif., according to
the agency.
</P>
<P>
   It is most likely that the future of roller coaster technology
will rely even more heavily on computers, Speigel said. Part of
that role, he said, will almost certainly be in operating a new
propulsion system that uses hundreds of electromagnets along the
track instead of gravity and a chain.
</P>
<P>
   Only a computer can control the system since magnets must be
powered in sequence and in microsecond bursts. The few roller
coasters that already employ this technology can accelerate cars to
60 miles an hour as fast as a Porsche, Speigel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology is advancing at such a pace now that it's not the
computers that are limiting roller coasters,'' he said. ``It's the
stresses that you can put on a body. You can only take so many
G-forces and so much of your eyes bulging out.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the standard computer in the industry is the
Allen-Bradley. With stacks of motor drives and a tangle of wiring,
the system is used to control everything from ocean liners to most
major amusement park rides.
</P>
<P>
   On the Riddler's Revenge, the influence of technology reaches
all the way to the exit, where passengers can buy photographs of
themselves in mid free fall. A high-speed camera alongside the
track takes pictures each time a train swoops by and immediately
sends the digital images to a computer in the sales booth.
</P>
<P>
   Though computers have an impact on nearly every facet of the
ride, most of the passengers were focused less on what happens
behind the scenes and more on what happens when the forces of
gravity begin to act on a human body that is being inverted and
flung around curves.
</P>
<P>
   Most were like Jackey Escobar, 14, who, after holding a hand
briefly to her stomach, talked about the perils of spinning upside
down. ``I feel like everything is going to come out,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
