<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-COMEDY-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Comedian Frye should have stopped with Nixon
</P>
<P>
   By Phil Kloerc. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   A quarter-century ago, when another president, Richard Nixon,
was in trouble, comedian-impressionist David Frye was all over him
like a 5 o'clock shadow, knocking out a devastatingly twisted Nixon
regularly on Johnny Carson's ``Tonight Show'' and other gigs. But
time has not been kind to Frye, who's back with a Clinton spoof
after years spent _ where? Omaha dinner theater? His Clinton
impression is barely adequate, well below the late Phil Hartman's,
on this series of PG-13 riffs on the president's sex life. Just
when you think he's hit bottom (Clinton double-dates with O.J.
Simpson, whom Frye does like an African-American Walter Brennan),
he finds a new low (Clinton goes to Dr. Ruth for counseling). It's
a laugh-free comedy album that's utterly pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton: An Oral History''
</P>
<P>
   David Frye. Miramar. 20 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: F
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
