A1818 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-COUNTRY-COX     08-19 0311
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-COUNTRY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Welcome, Dolly; we missed you
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Turn on the porch light and heat up the coffee: Dolly Parton has
come home. After spending years as one of country music's most
inconsistent artists by splitting her sound between that of
barefoot mountain girl and Hollywood disco diva, she's finally
returned to what she does best: uncluttered Smoky Mountains tunes
that showcase her mockingbird-sweet voice.
</P>
<P>
   Every tune was penned by Parton during a three-month retreat to
the Tennessee cabin where she grew up. She says she ``fasted and
prayed'' and asked God to help her in a time when she didn't know
``exactly what I should be doing in my musical career or in my life
at this point.'' Now, Parton has made the heavenly decision to put
her haunting voice front and center, harking back to her unpolished
days with Porter Wagoner.
</P>
<P>
   The title track opens with a brooding Jimmie Rodgers guitar,
over which Parton warbles a poignant personal tale of midlife
malaise. There's the required whippoorwill ballad (``Blue Valley
Songbird''); a ``Jolene''-inspired story song (complete with
recitation intro) about old man Zeke, who's waiting for the time
``When Jesus Comes Calling for Me''; and even a hard-core bluegrass
tune (``Time and Tears'') that would make Ralph Stanley smile.
</P>
<P>
   There are two drawbacks: Parton can't keep her painted toes out
of her spiked heels entirely, and she throws in a couple of tunes
that are pop drivel (``The Salt in My Tears'' and ``Honky Tonk
Songs''). But, overall, this album is a happy return to Parton's
roots that, surprisingly, are as strong as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hungry Again''
</P>
<P>
   Dolly Parton. Decca. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Dolly comes home.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 1734EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
