<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-REVIEWS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Audio Reviews: The latest word on the latest sounds
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray, Howard Pousner, Al Levine, Steve Dollar, and
Richard L. Eldredge
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Confessions of Fire''
</P>
<P>
   Cam'ron.
</P>
<P>
   Untertainment Records. 19 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   As hot as Cam'ron's ``Horse &AMP; Carriage'' single is now, it's
disappointing that his ``Confessions of Fire'' debut album just
simmers. Song after song, Cam'ron relies on the same start-stop
delivery that makes ``Horse'' rhythmically infectious. But
infectious _ song after song, for a total of 19 _ becomes
monotonous. The drone is tolerable, however, thanks to the often
interesting production, the well-written ``D Rugs'' and the
inclusion of popular barker DMX (``Pull It''), Mase and his lazy
bravado (``Horse,'' ``We Got It''), R&AMP;B's Usher (``Feels Good'')
and Faith's incredibly beautiful vocals on ``Prophecy.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Since''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Buckner. MCA. 16 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   On his third album, hopeless romantic Richard Buckner seemingly
equates love with a thousand points of light. The former Atlantan
writes of a ``moonless'' couple, a woman whose ``spark was fine,''
of leaving a lover with ``shadows on my eyes'' and of a dream
couple ``dancing close and drunk in the spray of lights.''
Surprising, then, that Buckner and producer John David Foster have
wrapped this heartbreak in such fiery, rockin' songs. In tunes like
``Believer'' and ``Goner w/ Souvenir,'' acoustic strumming gives
way to molten electric lead playing by Dave Schramm, among others.
Few singer-songwriter albums sound this great. But, in a way, the
hot playing only tends to emphasize Buckner's limited vocal range.
Too bad harmonizer extraordinaire Syd Straw is around for only one
of the 16 cuts.
</P>
<P>
   -- COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``Leave a Mark''
</P>
<P>
   John Michael Montgomery. Atlantic. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   John Michael Montgomery is going to go down as one of the great
country balladeers of our time, for two simple reasons: He keeps
finding great songs for that mellow voice, and he seems stuck in
3/4 speed. The few rockers on his seventh album are largely
forgettable, making the weepers (``Little Cowboys Cry'' and the
title track about the painful souvenir of love lost) and the
midtempo, heart-heavy numbers like ``I Don't Want This Song to
End'' and ``Cover You With Kisses'' really stand out. Maybe he sold
off his dancing shoes at the Grundy County Auction.
</P>
<P>
   -- JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   ``Moving Portrait''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Douglas. DIW. 9 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   If jazz ever gets around to having its own Lollapalooza,
trumpeter Dave Douglas could book the whole thing with his
never-ending array of concept bands. Besides fronting the
Balkan-themed Tiny Bell Trio, a string group, and a combo that
features accordion genius Guy Klucevesek, among others, Douglas
also ventures into the jazz mainstream. This latest endeavor is one
of the player-composer's best, built around a trio of Joni Mitchell
songs (``Roses Blue,'' ``My Old Man'' and ``The Same Situation'')
that provide launching pads for delicately phrased explorations.
The group context (Bill Carrothers, piano; James Genus, bass; Billy
Hart, drums) glows with a subdued intensity, like a sunset through
frosted glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I Remember Miles''
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Horn.
</P>
<P>
   Verve/Polygram. 9 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   The emotional depths explored by this veteran pianist-vocalist
on her latest studio release would require scuba gear for most
artists. Horn's heartfelt valentine to her late mentor, Miles
Davis, is so intense at times that other recent Davis tributes lose
some sheen in comparison. By focusing on tunes such as ``I Fall in
Love Too Easily,'' ``Baby, Won't You Please Come Home'' and ``Basin
Street Blues,'' Horn beautifully conveys the scope of their musical
relationship in discreet, understated tones. She incites shivers
when she sings ``honey from a horn so sweet'' on the closing
number, ``Blue in Green.'' Not only does she pay tribute to Davis,
but to her own immeasurable talent as well.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
