<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Korn harvests familiar crop
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite its goofy name _ which, even with the fascist-looking
``K,'' brings to mind not so much post-apocalyptic industrial
mayhem as ``Hee Haw'' or a foot ailment _ Korn manages to kick up a
fairly intimidating ruckus. The Bakersfield, Calif., group mixes
equal parts Metallica and Nine Inch Nails (with a dash of rap) into
a sonically dense stew, then garnishes it with vaguely sinister
imagery. ``Something takes a part of me,'' screams vocalist
Jonathan Davis, before degenerating into a satanic scat.
</P>
<P>
   The formula seems to be working. Korn's 1996 opus, ``Life Is
Peachy,'' debuted at No. 3 on the Billboard albums chart, and the
video for the featured track ``A.D.I.D.A.S.'' became an MTV staple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Follow the Leader'' should put the band in the Top 10 again,
since it sticks hard to ``Peachy's'' crunchy, growly blueprint.
Unlike its influences, Korn doesn't seem interested in stretching
its parameters to include ballads, a la Metallica's ``The
Unforgiven,'' or techno beats, such as the ones that propel Nine
Inch Nails' ``The Perfect Drug.'' As such, the relentless,
lumbering groove grows tiresome.
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, Korn is capable of big statements. ``All in the
Family'' imagines a war of words between a gangster rapper and a
fey, goth-industrial singer (shades of Trent Reznor) and culminates
in the chorus ``I hate you, / You hate me; / It's all in the
family.'' Such adroit observations deserve a more adventurous
musical setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Follow the Leader''
</P>
<P>
   Korn. Immortal/Epic.
</P>
<P>
   13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   The verdict:
</P>
<P>
   Kalifornia kombo delivers more sound and fury, signifying a rut.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
