<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Stella's' groove eclipses lyrics
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Basically, all this ``Stella'' soundtrack has is groove. It's
what keeps you into Stevie Wonder and Wyclef Jean's ``Mastablasta
'98'' even while Jean sings the reworking of Wonder's reggae single
in an annoyingly pinched way. It, in hip-hop/soul form, is what
makes Shaggy and Janet Jackson's ``Luv Me, Luv Me'' kind of
interesting long after you realize that all Jackson is really doing
is giggling, cooing and ``ooh boy-ing'' throughout. The groove,
too, in the form of an INXS sample of ``Need You Tonight,'' is what
seems to slow rapper Big Pun down on his team-up with Beenie Man on
``Make Me Sweat.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyrically, who knows or remembers what Boyz II Men (``Your Home
Is in My Heart'') or Mary J. Blige (``Beautiful'') are actually
saying underneath Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis' sweeping, pleasing
production?
</P>
<P>
   And coming after the brilliantly penned Babyface soundtrack that
accompanied the first Terry McMillan movie adaptation, ``Waiting to
Exhale,'' expectations for this release are high, lyrically and
musically. But they are met only on the reunion of the original
configuration of London's Soul II Soul (Jazzie B and Caron
Wheeler), back together on ``Free Again'' with more than just
incredible groove.
</P>
<P>
   ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back'' soundtrack
</P>
<P>
   Various artists.
</P>
<P>
   Flyte Tyme. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Stella and anyone else should find groove to spare
here. And that's kind of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
