<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-APOSTLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A re-markable performance by Robert Duvall is backed by a strong
supporting cast
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Apostle'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   The greatest actors are magicians. They make themselves
disappear. That's what happens with writer, producer, director and
star Robert Duvall's slow-moving but beautifully observed character
study about a Pentecostal preacher who finds out that being a holy
man and being a good one aren't always the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   We meet Texas preacher Euliss ``Sonny'' Dewey making his rounds
from one tent meeting to another, testifying with other white
clergymen, with Hispanics and African-Americans. When his wife
(Farrah Fawcett, solid in a small role) says she wants out of the
marriage, it ignites a violence in Sonny that sends him on the lam
to small-town Louisiana. There, as he restores an old church and
gathers new congregants, the film transforms the idea of redemption
from an elusive concept to something tangible, a hands-on state of
active pursuit. The strong supporting cast includes Billy Bob
Thornton, June Carter Cash and Miranda Richardson. And Duvall is
remarkable. His utter lack of condescension toward Sonny is
bolstered by a scientifically precise understanding of the man.
It's a small miracle. Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Recommended movies with Robert Duvall: ``To Kill a
Mockingbird,'' ``The Godfather,'' ``The Godfather Part II,''
``Tender Mercies,'' ``Apocalypse Now,'' ``The Great Santini,''
``Rambling Rose,'' ``Sling Blade.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
