<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Here's the curriculum for home schooling
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   School days, school daze.
</P>
<P>
   It's that time of year again. Time to go back to reading,
writing and 'rithmetic.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most students (and teachers), the movies love going back
to school. Pictures with classroom or campus settings typically
provide a tempting blend of desirable demographics (all those
14-to-24-year-olds to identify with) and juicy, star-friendly
roles. So get out your No. 2 pencils and prepare to take notes.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``THE BLACKBOARD JUNGLE'' (1955)
</P>
<P>
   For whom the school bell tolls: Glenn Ford stars as a committed
young teacher facing school board apathy, classroom boredom and
vicious students (led by jaded juvenile delinquent Vic Morrow).
</P>
<P>
   Most likely to succeed: Look for a young Sidney Poitier as the
``good'' student and natural leader. More than a decade later, he
switched to teaching in ``To Sir With Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Go to the head of the class if you knew: The movie was banned in
Georgia because it showed desegregated classrooms. The Atlanta
Constitution filed suit and took the case to the Supreme Court in
an attempt to lift the ban.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``FAST TIMES AT RIDGEMONT HIGH'' (1982)
</P>
<P>
   For whom the school bell tolls: Loosely based on Cameron
(``Jerry Maguire'') Crowe's undercover expedition into the wilds of
high school in the early 1980s, Amy Heckerling's film offers an
enjoyable array of student types and rising stars (including Phoebe
Cates and Jennifer Jason Leigh, daughter of ... Vic Morrow).
</P>
<P>
   Most likely to succeed: Sean Penn made his breakthrough with his
memorable surfer-dopehead character.
</P>
<P>
   Go to the head of the class if you knew: This was the first film
for Eric Stoltz, Forest Whitaker and Nicolas Cage.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``IF ...'' (1968)
</P>
<P>
   For whom the school bell tolls: Malcolm McDowell leads a surreal
revolt at a British boys' school.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely to succeed: McDowell. Soon afterward, he starred in
Stanley Kubrick's ``A Clockwork Orange.''
</P>
<P>
   Go to the head of the class if you knew: Director Lindsay
Anderson did a kind of Further Adventures of Mick, McDowell's
character, in 1973's ``O Lucky Man!''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``FERRIS BUELLER'S DAY OFF'' (1986)
</P>
<P>
   For whom the school bell tolls: The title character (Matthew
Broderick) plays hookey in style with Mia Sara and Alan Ruck.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely to succeed: Director John Hughes, who mined
box-office gold out of a number of high-school-themed flicks,
including ``The Breakfast Club,'' ``Sixteen Candles'' and ``Some
Kind of Wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Go to the head of the class if you knew: This is former Vice
President Dan Quayle's favorite movie.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``THE PRIME OF MISS JEAN BRODIE'' (1969)
</P>
<P>
   For whom the school bell tolls: In Edinburgh in the 1930s, a
flamboyant teacher (Maggie Smith) makes an indelible _ and possibly
unhealthy _ impression on her chosen circle of students.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely to succeed: Smith won an Oscar for her performance.
Of her win, the Academy's then-president, Gregory Peck, said,
``This is great. Now you can see it's not rigged.'' (Smith wasn't
the best-known nominee.)
</P>
<P>
   Go to the head of the class if you knew: Smith won her second
Oscar, this time in the supporting category, in 1978 for
``California Suite.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``LOVE STORY'' (1970)
</P>
<P>
   For whom the school bell tolls: Ali MacGraw and Ryan O'Neal
cavort around Harvard Yard while learning that love means ...
</P>
<P>
   Most likely to succeed: MacGraw snagged an Oscar nomination and
a marriage proposal from the film's producer, Robert Evans.
</P>
<P>
   Go to the head of the class if you knew: Michael Douglas, Jon
Voight and Beau Bridges were among those who turned down O'Neal's
role. David Birney, Ken Howard and Christopher Walken were among
those who auditioned and failed.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``STAND AND DELIVER'' (1988)
</P>
<P>
   For whom the school bell tolls: It's the true story of Jaime
Escalante, a teacher in East Los Angeles who inspired his students
to learn calculus and pass the advanced placement exam. And that's
not the whole story.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely to succeed: Edward James Olmos, who not only got an
Oscar nomination for playing Escalante but also helped finance the
film. It was made for $1.7 million and grossed more than $30
million.
</P>
<P>
   Go to the head of the class if you knew: Olmos pulled a Robert
De Niro and gained 40 pounds for the role.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``SCHOOL DAZE'' (1988)
</P>
<P>
   For whom the school bell tolls: Spike Lee's second movie is
about conflicts between assimilation-minded and Afrocentric
students at fictional Mission College (it was filmed at Atlanta's
Morehouse College).
</P>
<P>
   Most likely to succeed: Laurence _ then still going by Larry _
Fishburne, who solidified his post-``Apocalypse Now'' career
playing a campus leader who gives the students a wake-up call.
</P>
<P>
   Go to the head of the class if you knew: At the Los Angeles
premiere, a movie-struck 19-year-old finally got to meet his idol,
Spike Lee. The kid's name? John Singleton.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
