<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-REVIEWS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini views: Reviews of the latest out on video
 &HT;    By Steve Murray and Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- ``Kundun'' (PG-13) _ The first hour of Martin Scorsese's
biopic of the Dalai Lama's early life whets your expectations.
Scorsese channels his prodigious filmmaking skills into a
mesmerizing child's-eye view. He delights in the normal kidness of
the young Dalai Lama. But it's the far superior half of an
overlong, unfocused movie. At its best, ``Kundun'' helps us
rediscover the pleasures of space, silence, simplicity. And it has
moments of breathtaking imagery. Once the film enters the political
realm, with China threatening the borders of Tibet, the air (or the
script) proves too thin to sustain the director's vision. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Newton Boys'' (PG-13) _ Richard Linklater's movie about
the most successful bank robbers in U.S. history engages in some
pretty nifty larceny of its own. It lifts a moment here, a shot
there, a tonal shading wherever from two of the best outlaw
pictures of the late 1960s: ``Bonnie and Clyde'' and ``Butch
Cassidy and the Sundance Kid.'' The boys, a quartet of rambunctious
Texas brothers, did their robbing between 1919 and 1924, hitting
more than 80 banks. They never killed anyone, never stole from
women or children and, most amazingly of all, lived to a ripe old
age. Best known for low-budget wonders (``Dazed and Confused''),
Linklater shows us that he can handle a Hollywood budget as well as
anyone. The cast includes Ethan Hawke, Matthew McConaughey, Skeet
Ulrich and Vincent D'Onofrio. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Borrowers'' (PG) _ This adaptation of Mary Norton's
classic children's series about teeny folk who live under
floorboards and inside walls is a victim of timing. The plot _ how
the Borrowers team up with a normal-sized boy to foil an evil
developer (John Goodman) _ is a rehash of ``Mouse Hunt'' and the
``Home Alone'' movies. Though the effects are certainly effective,
you sense that the book's charm has been scuttled by the jacked-up,
too-familiar action scenes. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
