<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1851 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLAG-BURNING-HNS &LR;      08-19 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAG-BURNING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORTERS OF FLAG AMENDMENT PLAN AD BLITZ AS SENATE VOTE NEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Supporters of a proposed constitutional amendment
that would give Congress the power to ban flag desecration said
.MDNM/Wednesday they would launch a television ad campaign to
pressure Senate opponents to change their minds.
</P>
<P>
   The television spots, sponsored by the Citizens Flag Alliance, a
coalition of 130 civic and veterans' groups pushing the amendment,
will feature celebrities such as Tommy Lasorda, general manager of
the Los Angeles Dodgers; entertainer Wayne Newton; and John
Schneider, an actor who played Duke on the television show ``Dukes
of Hazard.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the ads, to be aired next week in California,
Illinois, Maryland, North Dakota, South Dakota and Washington
state, Tommy Lasorda, seated in baseball bleachers, tells people
that ``Our flag is precious and deserving of respect.''
</P>
<P>
   .MDNM/Another commercial uses images of flags burning,
interspersed with a young boy reciting the Pledge of Allegiance.
The ad ends with the message: ``When they desecrate the flag and
you stay silent, they burn us all. Break the silence.''
</P>
<P>
   Retired Army Maj. Gen. Patrick Brady, chairman of the
Indianapolis-based flag alliance, told .MDSD/.MDNM/a news
conference that the organization intends to ``reclaim and restore
the Constitution'' by gathering support for the amendment. If
approved, it would become the 28th amendment to the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the Supreme Court ruled that burning the flag was a
right protected by the First Amendment's guarantee of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of this and past efforts to outlaw malicious
destruction of the flag say it would trample an individual's right
of self-expression.
</P>
<P>
   Brady, however, argued that founding fathers such as Thomas
Jefferson and James Madison never intended flag desecration as a
constitutional right. The amendment, he added, would let the
American people protect the Stars and Stripes and take ``control of
the flag away from the courts.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Wheeler, president of the Citizens Flag
Alliance.MDSU/.MDNM/, said the organization would continue to buy
television time until the Senate votes. Group leaders said they
have spent $2 million so far on advertising, but would not say how
much more they planned to spend.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler said the alliance hoped pressure from constituents would
convince opponents such as Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle,
D-S.D., to support the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   But Daschle, who voted against a similar amendment in 1995, will
do so again, his spokeswoman, Molly Rowley, said. He ``thinks flag
burning is repugnant,'' Rowley added, but believes it is
constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The ad campaign also will target Illinois, where Sen. Carol
Moseley-Braun, a Democrat, voted against the 1995 proposal. Her
spokesman, Michael Briggs, said she would not bow to the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Moseley-Braun has previously said that destroying the flag is
``a horrible and reprehensible act,'' but ``foremost among the
values that make our country great is the right to express one's
view, no matter how unpopular.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The very values this flag symbolizes would be diminished if
the Congress dictates how it is to be treated,'' she said in a
statement earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed amendment reads: ``The Congress shall have power to
prohibit the physical desecration of the flag of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   The House approved it last year, 310-114. If passed by
two-thirds of the Senate _ or 67 senators _ then 38 states would
have to ratify the amendment before it could be added to the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Congress tried to bypass the Supreme Court's 1989 decision with
a federal law prohibiting flag burning, but the high court ruled
the federal law unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   .MDNM/In 1995, Rep. Gerald B.H. Solomon, R-N.Y. led an
unsuccessful push to amend the constitution to overrule the court's
decision. It passed the House in a 312-120 vote, but fell three
votes shy of a two-thirds majority in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The 1995 amendment would have given both states and Congress the
power to prevent desecration of the flag. But the current proposal
only would allow Congress to ban the malicious destruction of the
flag.
</P>
<P>
   If the amendment is passed, Congress would then have to approve
a bill that would ban flag desecration and make the act a federal
crime.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Olympia Snow, R-Maine, is one of the 64 senators in favor
of the amendment. Earlier this year, she said the amendment
protects a ``national emblem of the world's greatest democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   She said almost all the states, the federal government and the
majority of the American people support protecting the flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our flag should be treated with respect and with care,'' she
said. ``It is altogether just that we try to ensure that it is
publicly displayed with pride, dignity and honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the amendment criticize it as an attack on the Bill
of Rights.
</P>
<P>
   People for the American Way, a liberal group promoting First
Amendment rights, said in July during the release of that
organization's ad campaign against the amendment, that there are
questions of interpretation that will have to be settled if the
amendment is passed, such as the definition of desecration.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the planned TV blitz, an hour-long television
show featuring celebrity supporters of the amendment began airing
on July 26 in California, Connecticut, Illinois, Missouri, North
Carolina, Oklahoma, South Dakota, Wisconsin and Washington, D.C.,
and will continue until Aug..MDSD/.MDNM/ 23. The Citizens Flag
Alliance.MDSD/.MDNM/ also sponsored newspaper and radio ads in
South Dakota and Utah that are expected to run until the end of
August.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
