<SLUG> BC-RETHINK-`OLD'-RETIREMENT-PKG-NYTSF-WORTH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW RETIREMENT: FORGET EVERYTHING YOU'VE HEARD ABOUT BEING
OLD  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Second of four-part package, `THE NEW RETIREMENT')   (This user-friendly 725-word ``separate buy'' personal-finance
story is from ``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must
be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times
sales representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267
or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle news
files.)  
  
 By HILLARY JOHNSON  
 c.1998 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember rock'n'roll? Remember feminism? Those were the warm-up
acts. They were cultural revolutions of power and moment, but the
main attraction, the baby boomers' ultimate coup and 21st century's
first Big Idea, is yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   What? you say. Bigger than the invention of the teenager? Bigger
than civil rights? Bigger than the information age?
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes _ because the last, best thing the baby boomers are
going to do in this world they've created in their own image is to
grow very old.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't hit us yet, but soon old people will be the happening
demographic _ between the years 2010 and 2030, the over-65
population in the U.S. will increase by 75 percent, to more than 69
million souls.
</P>
<P>
   To put their consumer spending power in perspective, consider
that the Census Bureau estimates there are now just under 20
million 15- to 19-year-old ne'er-do-wells afoot. And just look at
how much marketing hype they get, given that most of them don't
have jobs, let alone estates.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a brave new world in which baby boomers redefine what it
means to be old.
</P>
<P>
   The elderly we know in 1998, our parents and grandparents,
contracted with the government (via the Social Security Act of
1935) and private industry (pension plans had become widespread by
the 1930s) to work with Protestant doggedness for 20 years or more
and then to STOP completely and play golf or else sit in a chair
and watch the neighbors come and go from the front window.
</P>
<P>
   Given the current rate of increase in both life expectancy and
quality of life, that scenario doesn't look so viable anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The soon-to-be-elderly baby boomers haven't worked in
anticipation of a gold watch and a fare-thee-well at 65. Unlike
their parents, they haven't worked for one company, they've
accumulated their own irritatingly-complex-tax-situation estates,
and they will no longer be put out to pasture.
</P>
<P>
   It's very possible that by 2030, the golf-and-bridge model of
senior citizenship will be a thing of the past. For one thing,
older Americans will want to work. In some cases they'll stay with
their jobs longer. In other cases they'll work part-time, perhaps
as interns, often as volunteers, in entirely new fields, or they'll
undertake the advanced study of fascinating but unremunerative
things (comparative lit, anyone?).
</P>
<P>
   The concept of senior leisure will evolve, too, away from
passive, pleasant time fillers toward more dynamic activities: a
sail around the world, say, instead of an Alaskan cruise.
</P>
<P>
   Work, pleasure, or a combination _ it all depends on your
priorities, and the way things are headed, you'll have time for
several of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't like to say `elderly' or `senior.' We prefer the term
`Third Age,''' says a spokesman for Third Age Media, which operates
a Web site (www.thirdage.com) for the 50-plus American.
</P>
<P>
   The division of ages into quarters of a hundred is bold and apt:
Recapture the under-65 set (the 50-plussers) and you reinvigorate
the concept of aging entirely. (Also ignore the fact that 0 to 25
isn't exactly a lifestyle category, though no less so than 25 to
50).
</P>
<P>
   The upshot of such thinking will be your 60-year-old college
students and consumers of retail goods. Pretty soon the middle
years will be the necessary evil, and retirement will come to seem
the be-all in addition to the end-all.
</P>
<P>
   There's no innate reason why it shouldn't. Among the Dagara of
West Africa, old age and childhood are held to be the important
times in life, the times when one does great work.
</P>
<P>
   Children and the ``elders,'' being chronologically closer to the
spirit world, hang out together and discuss the meaning of life,
while those in their middle years are seen as more or less taking
up space, providing little more than manual labor to feed the wise
children and elders.
</P>
<P>
   This might not be such a bad model for 21st-century America,
after all: Live like hell in the First Age, pay for it in the
Second, and do it right this time in the Third.
</P>
<P>
   And after age 75, by the year 2030, you might as well call
yourself an elder and go for broke _ the statistics are in your
favor. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Hillary Johnson wrote about the 008 Investment Club
(``I Don't Think We're in Beardstown Anymore'') for the February
issue of ``WORTH.'') &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
