<SLUG> BC-WACKENHUT20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Embassy bombings might lead to company growth
 &HT;    By Stephen Pounds
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH GARDENS _ When Americans are targets, Wackenhut Corp.
has a business opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   It's the nature of Palm Beach Gardens-based Wackenhut Corp.'s
business of guarding people and places around the world. So when
terrorists simultaneously bombed U.S. embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania on Aug. 7, killing 250 people, including 12 Americans, the
company saw it as potential for growth in government contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``These East African countries were considered a low threat.
Because of those low levels of threat or disturbance, it allowed
for those countries to be open as a target for terrorism,'' said
Alan Bernstein, Wackenhut president of North American operations
and a member of its board of directors. ``Those countries that are
complaining aren't upset at the United States. They're worried that
they will be target.''
</P>
<P>
   Wackenhut, which employs 300 at its headquarters in Palm Beach
Gardens, protects 27 embassies in conjunctionalong with the U.S.
Marines contingent stationed in those locations. The embassies are
scattered around the world, but Wackenhut was not stationed in
Kenya or Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   The company also protects U.S. operations in 26 other countries,
mainly military bases, Bernstein said.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 250 U.S. embassies, consulates and other
posts, including missions, which are lower-level State Department
offices where visas are issued and where Americans can go if they
have a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Wackenhut (NYSE: WAK, $19.81) doesn't break out its revenue from
the State Department for protecting embassies. But the business has
grown from the end of 1997, when the company stood guard at 19
embassies, according to Wackenhut's annual report.
</P>
<P>
   Its revenue from international operations, which includes
embassies and missions, improved from $146 million in 1996 to
almost $174 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``That business is one that's growing. And as embassies are
re-evaluated, we should get more of that business,'' Bernstein
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like being a doctor. No one wants to go to the
doctor but you have to at times. We, as a company ,are a necessary
component of the 21st century,'' Bernstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Another company, CTC International Group of Palm Beach, gathers
foreign intelligence for Fortune 500 companies. But company
Chairman Frederick Rustmann said he doesn't see growth in his
business from the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten a lot of calls from (reporters), including CNN.
But I don't see any new business because we don't handle
security,'' Rustmann said.
</P>
<P>
   The growth for Wackenhut will come after the State Department
finishes reevaluating the need for additional security at
embassies, Bernstein said. He stopped short of guaranteeing that
Wackenhut would be brought in because the State Department could
decide to beef up the embassy structures.
</P>
<P>
   But Bernstein has He hopes that Wackenhut will find itself in
the new mix of security measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six weeks ago, the threat in Canada was one of the lowest in
the world,'' he said. ``Though it isn't on the same par as a Saudi
Arabia, there's still a potential for terrorism. It can no longer
be considered a low threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Wackenhut (NYSE: WAK) closed at $19.81, up 19 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
