<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    I discovered America
 &HT;    By Martin Reeder
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editor's note: West Palm Beach attorney Martin Reeder pedaled
across the country this summer as part of the GTE Big Ride, a
seven-week trip benefiting the American Lung Association.
</P>
<P>
   We made it! The GTE Big Ride Across America, the largest bicycle
crossing of the North American continent, is over. About 700 of the
724 riders who started in Seattle on June 15 crossed the finish
line Aug. 1 in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Together, we rode 3,350 miles and raised $6.5 million to aid the
American Lung Association's fight against lung disease.
</P>
<P>
   I am proud to have taken part in the Big Ride Across America and
am grateful for the support of the 102 family members, friends and
colleagues who made my trip possible by donating $10,300 to the
Lung Association.
</P>
<P>
   Since I came home to West Palm Beach, everyone has asked about
the Big Ride. The experience is fresh and vivid, and I will talk
about it as long as anyone cares to listen.
</P>
<P>
   I sense, however, that most of those who ask about the trip are
looking more for wisdom than facts. They want to know what I have
learned about America and about life. How have I been affected by
the experience of escaping the confines of my regular existence for
seven weeks to ride a bicycle across America?
</P>
<P>
   I have no firm answers. I hope to have more insight after having
some time to reflect on the summer's journey and to reexamine my
familiar routines in the light of that experience. I can, however,
offer a few of my stronger impressions.
</P>
<P>
   There is a different and wonderful America beyond the urban and
suburban areas that most of us call home. It is the America
described by John Steinbeck in ``Travels with Charley'' and William
Least Heat Moon in ````Blue Highways.'' It is an America where
people still open their hearts and homes to strangers without
having to curb their generosity because of fear of violent crime,
where people do not seem to be forever in a hurry and where people
are almost uniformly more relaxed and less irritable.
</P>
<P>
   The computer revolution is giving more of us the option to live
in a small town without sacrificing economic opportunities or
cutting ourselves off from the knowledge and diversity formerly
available only in great cities. If you like small towns and can
afford to do so, consider moving to one in a beautiful place. Even
if you choose to remain an urbanite, spend some weekends or
vacation time visiting rural America. It will make you feel good
about your country. Ride a bicycle if you can. It's the best way to
really get in touch with the land. On a bike you can smell the
earth and the flowers, taste the breeze and feel the land's
undulations in your legs.
</P>
<P>
   The American West is a big place, and there is still plenty of
wilderness out there. Go see Montana, Wyoming and Idaho. Learn
about the Indians who loved these magnificent places for thousands
of years. Honor the heritage of the American Indian by regarding
the Earth as a sacred place, to be lovingly cared for and passed
down by us to the next generation in better condition than we
received it.
</P>
<P>
   The human mind and body are amazing creations. The body can
perform almost any task the mind wills. I saw a man with paralyzed
legs ride 3,350 miles over long, steep mountains by turning a hand
crank mounted in front of his chest. I saw a woman with two
transplanted lungs, whose muscles had deteriorated from taking
anti-rejection drugs, ride day after day from daybreak until dusk.
I saw a mother of five, whose doctors thought she would be dead by
now, ride across America breathing oxygen from a bottle strapped to
her bike. I saw a man whose right leg had been amputated at the hip
ride up some of the steepest mountains in America, his face a
picture of indomitable courage as his left leg pumped like a
magnificent piston.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of us on the Big Ride were blessed with strong,
healthy bodies that enabled us to complete the journey without
requiring such heroic displays, there was enough adversity to test
each of us in some way.
</P>
<P>
   For me, the biggest challenge was the weather. Try changing a
flat tire on a high mountain pass in sleet and freezing rain when
the cold has robbed the feeling from your hands. Try descending 10
miles on an icy mountain road in a gusting crosswind after the rain
has soaked your clothes and your body is shivering so hard that you
cannot hold the handlebars steady. Try riding a hundred miles in
the hot sun, being rained on all night until you are too soaked to
sleep, and then getting up to ride another hundred miles the next
day. Try living in a tent and sharing portable toilets with 800
other people for seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   All of this really happened _ and much more _ yet I can honestly
say that the Big Ride was a wonderful experience that I will always
remember.
</P>
<P>
   I think that most of us had a wonderful time despite the
adversities because the people who did the ride were special people
_ each so committed to riding across the country that nothing could
stand in his or her way. Achieving the goal required each of us to
surpass personal limits that we seldom approach in our ordinary
lives.
</P>
<P>
   First, we had to overcome all of the sensible reasons why we
could not or should not do the ride. Second, most of us had to
overcome apprehensions about taking so much time off from work.
Third, each of us had to raise more money (a minimum of $6,000)
than almost any of us had ever done before. Fourth, we had to train
for the ride and acquire all of the necessary equipment. Finally,
we had to do the ride itself, which meant getting up each day and
riding another 80 or 100 miles no matter what the weather was like
or how tired we were.
</P>
<P>
   The dreamers, the uncommitted, the unresourceful, the whiners
and the naysayers of this world were almost entirely absent from
our ranks. They never made it even to Seattle. The 724 riders were,
instead, a group of ``can do'' folks for whom adversities were just
challenges to be shared and overcome.
</P>
<P>
   I will never forget the day we rolled into White Sulphur
Springs, Mont., cold and wet after climbing over the Big Belt
Mountains in freezing rain. Riders on the verge of hypothermia took
over the town laundromat, dried their wet clothes, hopped back on
their bikes and rode another 60 miles to Harlowton.
</P>
<P>
   Or the day we crossed the Continental Divide at MacDonald Pass
in sleet and freezing rain and then descended into Helena, stopping
at a Wal-Mart store long enough to buy rubber gloves and enough
warm clothing to get through another 50 miles to our destination.
</P>
<P>
   Or the two riders who borrowed rusty old Huffy bikes after their
bikes were stolen in Huron, S.D., and rode them 60 miles until
their bicycles were recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Or the woman who separated her shoulder during the ride one day
and rode another 50 miles in that condition.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Castro, my closest friend on the ride, called me at work a
couple of days ago to see how I was handling being back in the real
world. I told him how much I appreciate each day with my daughters
after being away from them so long and how wonderful it is to sleep
in a real bed again and to enjoy a quiet evening with a friend,
eating good food and listening to good music in a cool, dry house
with a front door that opens and closes on hinges instead of a
zipper.
</P>
<P>
   We talked of returning to work and spinning our wheels as we
tried to decide where to start.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, we came to the heart of what we both wanted to talk
about. We talked about the special bond that exists between us and
the others with whom we shared the vivid, exciting and, yes,
glorious days of the Big Ride Across America. Legs and hearts were
strong, and we lived each day intensely, wringing every bit of
triumph, joy, challenge and passion it had to offer _ sharing it
all together and laughing all the way.
</P>
<P>
   There will be another Big Ride next year. Remember what Helen
Keller said: ``Life is either a daring adventure or nothing at
all.'' My advice _ if you love to ride a bike, want to see America
and are willing to help the Lung Association _ is to go for it. You
won't regret it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
