<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL-EARNINGS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dell defies PC industry with 62% profit jump
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROUND ROCK, Texas _ Seemingly impervious to weaknesses in the
personal computer industry, Dell Computer Corp. reported Tuesday,
August 18, a 62 percent increase in profits during the second
quarter to $346 million on record sales of $4.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings per diluted share were 50 cents, up 72 percent from the
second quarter last year and 4 cents higher than the consensus of
Wall Street analysts surveyed by First Call Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The company also announced a two-for-one stock split effective
Sept. 4 for shareholders of record on Aug. 28. It is the sixth
split in six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an outstanding quarter,'' Ashok Kumar of Piper Jaffray
said Tuesday. ``There's no two ways to look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's shares dropped $1 to $109.56 1/4 in Nasdaq trading
Tuesday. The results were released after the markets closed. Shares
jumped about $4 in after-hours trading, according to wire reports.
</P>
<P>
   Dell, which takes orders directly from customers and builds
computers after they are paid for, continued its habit of
outperforming its competitors and the PC industry overall. Industry
shipments of PCs worldwide increased a mediocre 7 percent during
the April-June quarter, according to International Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Low prices for PCs and the Asian economic crisis were among the
reasons cited by Compaq Computer Corp., IBM and Hewlett-Packard Co.
for disappointing results during their most recent quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Dell chief executive Michael Dell said in an interview Tuesday
that while the company's average selling price of about $2,400 for
all computers slipped 11 percent from the year-ago quarter, the
decline reflected a drop in component costs. Moreover, component
costs fell faster than Dell lowered prices, which helped preserve
Dell's profit margin, Dell said.
</P>
<P>
   Dell's gross margin, the difference between revenue and
production costs, increased to 22.7 percent from 22.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe costs of components such as DRAM memory and
hard drives may stabilize in coming months. But for now the
declining prices favor Dell, because its competitors typically have
inventories of machines that were built with higher-priced
components.
</P>
<P>
   If they lower prices on those machines, they sacrifice profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dell's model is optimal for that type of business
environment,'' said Cody Acree of Southwest Securities in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Dell's Internet sales increased from $2 million a day a year ago
to more than $6 million, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Dell said that the company's performance was strong in
all products and regions. Revenue increased 50 percent to nearly $3
billion in the Americas, 73 percent in Europe and 34 percent in
Asia-Pacific, where analysts estimate total industry shipments
declined by 9 percent in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see that kind of improvement is very much the anomaly,''
Acree said.
</P>
<P>
   Dell, which introduced a new lines of workstations and servers
this summer, said business for all its enterprise products more
than doubled for the seventh straight quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Dell said the company is being considered in a growing
number of bids for large corporate accounts in part because Dell's
computers are winning industry awards.
</P>
<P>
   Dell's performance intensifies pressure on Compaq, its
cross-state rival and the world's biggest PC company.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates by Dataquest show Dell in a virtual tie with Compaq
for No. 1 in U.S. PC shipments at about 1 million units in the
second quarter. But Compaq officials say those estimates fail to
include about 500,000 computers that were sold by retailers and
resellers during that quarter, when the company stopped shipping
for nearly a month.
</P>
<P>
   Houston-based Compaq stopped shipping and cut prices to thin a
backlog of unsold computers. IBM and HP were forced to follow with
their own price cuts or risk losing market share.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe that Compaq will have considerably more
flexibility in cutting prices in coming months because it can
subsidize the cuts with revenues from Digital Equipment Corp.,
which it acquired this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Dell scoffed at that threat, at least in the immediate future.
He said Digital wasn't profitable during the first six months of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to make money before they can use it to subsidize
something else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dell is growing in terms of employees as well. It has 14,000 in
the Austin area and 20,000 worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
