<HEADER>
A1860 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN21-COX     08-19 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   By Mary McCarty DAYTON DAILY NEWS
</P>
<P>
   ``I misled people . . . I did not volunteer information.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: ``I lied.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did have a relationship with Miss Lewinsky that was not
appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: ``I did it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This has gone on too long . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's one thing we can all agree on. But whose fault is
it this has gone on too long? Is it really the fault of Ken Starr,
Linda Tripp or ``a politically inspired lawsuit''?
</P>
<P>
   No. It has gone on for too long because you looked the American
people in the eye in January, wagged your finger and lied: ``I did
not have sexual relations with that woman, Miss Lewinsky.'' And you
went on lying for seven months, until a blue dress backed you into
a corner and left no choice but to tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   And then you couldn't even muster one simple, heartfelt,
unlawyerlike sentence: ``I'm sorry I lied to you.''
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to scream as I listened to Clinton's weasel-worded,
whiny confessional Monday night. This should have been a time for
profound and deep contrition. This should have been a time to
reflect on what you have done to the American people and not what
others have done to you. This should not have been a time for
finger-pointing _ for acting like a 6-year-old child, who, by the
way, may comprehend better than you, Mr. President, that the truth
should have been told in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Instead you gave us more defiance than remorse, more
defensiveness than self-blame.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you are a human being who was put in an impossible
situation, forced to answer ``questions about my private life,
questions no American citizen would ever want to answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Ken Starr is a ferociously partisan ``independent
counsel,'' a man who was prepared to file an amicus brief for Paula
Jones before he took the job.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the mainstream press has turned Hard Copy on this story,
pursuing it with a relentlessness and vigor they could never quite
rally for the Iran-contra affair. Yes, Ronald Reagan got away with
saying ``I can't recall'' whether he authorized arms shipments to
Iran. Now they're naming airports after him.
</P>
<P>
   I'm furious about all that, too.
</P>
<P>
   But none of that is any excuse for what you did.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Starr didn't force you to have an affair with a woman then
only three years older than your daughter is now. He didn't force
you to abandon everything you understand about women in the
workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Your political enemies didn't force you to hang out to dry your
aides, friends, supporters, wife and daughter. For seven months you
stood by and watched their loyal suffering, a heartless wager that
you wouldn't get caught.
</P>
<P>
   So don't give us any more of this ``Ken Starr made me do it''
routine. Don't try to tell us your deposition in the Paula Jones
case was ``legally accurate,'' or insult our intelligence with any
convoluted nonsense about how the acts in question weren't really
sex.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans don't want you to lose your job over this, not
based on what we know so far anyway. But we don't want any more
lies or half-truths, either.
</P>
<P>
   You're right, Mr. President, this has gone on too long. This
unprecedented witch hunt, this National Enquirer media frenzy, this
national soap opera.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, it is your lie that has gone on too long
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
