<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: A celebration to remember, under the sky
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Mass. _ Some days, the house just isn't big enough;
only the outdoors can hold the spirit of celebration that crackles
and fizzes all over the place.
</P>
<P>
   This was one of those days _ a blue-sky Sunday in August, a day
to mark a boxful of family birthdays, including those of Gran Lyn;
our daughter Cami Foley; her full-time 2-year-old twins, Nicholas
and Alexander, and her fabulous daughters, Lauren and Kathryn.
</P>
<P>
   What a day for celebration. Dry, breezy, morning temperatures in
the 60s. Pre-fall. A great day for eating with abandon.
</P>
<P>
   To prime ourselves for the big afternoon feast, we rose early
and enjoyed a lip-smacking lumberjack breakfast, prepared by our
son-in-law, John Foley. Blueberry pancakes, bacon, fruit, coffee,
juice. Thus fortified, we all went for an honest-to-goodness Sunday
drive through the verdant countryside of southern Massachusetts and
northern Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   By midafternoon we were back at the house, joined by John's
sister, Kathryn, and their parents, Pat and Emmet. Next-door
neighbor Michelle Albano came, too. All of us were in an
outdoor-eating state of mind, including Max, the floppy,
big-footed, long-tongued palooka-of-a-dog.
</P>
<P>
   There's something about a picnic, especially as summer days
dwindle to a special few. We know that, soon, it will be too cold
(here in New England, at least) to feast in the back yard, sharpen
appetites with a romp in the grass, a walk through the park, a ride
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Eating outdoors is a primeval call and response. It feels more
celebratory than eating indoors because we can slosh clam juice on
the ground and toss ice into the flower beds, spill at will. Be
free and easy.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, there's something ancient and extraordinarily
satisfying about putting fire to food under a big sky. On this day,
it was a New England boil, as textured an outdoor meal as I've
enjoyed, washed down with everything from exotic rum drinks to
microbrewery beer to soda.
</P>
<P>
   With John chefing again, the feast began. Leading the way was a
pot of steamed clams, plump and juicy. Pull one out of the shell,
dip into the broth, then into melted butter, ease it into your
mouth and _ my, my, eating doesn't get any better than this.
</P>
<P>
   Then the shrimp came, pink, succulent, so tender you could suck
off their shells before dipping them in spicy red sauce. Then,
riches on top of riches, lobster. First a claw, pried open, the
meat extracted and dipped into, yes, of course, butter.
Excessively, I sought, found and destroyed a tail, unmindful of my
ballooning waistline; this was no time to care.
</P>
<P>
   This was celebration. Picnic time. Thus no one was surprised
when Cami's broiled steaks showed up. The ultimate surf and turf.
Too: corn on the cob, wine-sauteed mushrooms, salad.
</P>
<P>
   It was the ultimate outdoor meal. One to remember when the snow
swirls and the winds howl. One to remember many summer birthdays
from now.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: leemay(at)bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
