A1870 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-LUNCH-KIDS-COX     08-19 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-LUNCH-KIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    School lunches to male kids healthy and happy
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who's going to stuff down sprouts while having sweet dreams of
cookies?
</P>
<P>
   Kids want chips, cookies and candy bars, their parents want them
to eat fruit and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   This truism of parenting goes double when you pack them off to
school and beyond your control.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to packing a lunch box, the gap between what they
want and what you want for them is so wide, in fact, it's the
third-leading cause of back-to-school arguments behind only
homework and fashion, a Quaker Oats survey reports.
</P>
<P>
   But when we asked readers how they manage to slip in a little
nutritional punch, we found it can be done with some thought, a
little effort and sometimes a twist that has nothing to do with
food.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year I think, `Oh, man, what can I come up with that's
different?''' said Julie Gillespie, after packing lunches for her
daughter, Laura, for many years.
</P>
<P>
   Laura, 13, is used to light food, isn't much of a sandwich eater
and is at an age now when ``they're so funny they don't want you to
send anything that looks baby,'' Gillespie said.
</P>
<P>
   She packs lunch every morning for her daughter to take to a
private school that has no cafeteria. Usually it's a tortilla roll,
soup or leftovers. The school has a microwave, ``a lifesaver for
me, especially in the wintertime'' when hearty black beans and rice
would be unappetizing served cold, Gillespie said.
</P>
<P>
   Trading goes on at the Duluth, Georgia school that Laura
attends, as it does even at public schools that ban under the table
trading, but it's rarely a problem for the Gillespies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find that if I'm forcing my taste on her, she ends up
trading,'' Gillespie said.
</P>
<P>
   Communication helps. Often Laura asks for larger helpings of
favorites _ not to trade but to share.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes just making food or the package more personal is
enough to help kids hang onto their own lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have one little girl, every time she comes to school her
sandwich is cut into a different shape,'' said Kathy Sullivan, a
preschool teacher and lunch packer for her three children.
</P>
<P>
   That idea _ cutting sandwiches into shapes with cookie cutters _
was by far the most often mentioned tip sent in by parents. Others
suggest adding a note, fancy napkin or even a small prize.
</P>
<P>
   But Sullivan said even the pickiest eaters need more variety
than just the shape of their sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents will get on to something that works really well one
day and go with it for two months. That doesn't work,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ask children what they like and really listen to their answers,
she said. ``Even in preschool, children know what they like.''
</P>
<P>
   Keylee Clemons of Dahlonega, Georgia, who enters sixth grade
next week, knows and packs what she and her 6-year-old sister,
Kayna, like. Typically it's tuna in a pita, with fruit. Sometimes
muffins left from breakfast. Once in a while she brings cereal and
buys milk at school or cooks a hot dog in the morning and packs it
in boiling water in a thermos.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have complimented me on lunches. They're healthy,''
said Keylee, who won a top prize and $1,000 in a national recipe
contest this year.
</P>
<P>
   A corner of the Clemonses' refrigerator holds lunch items, and
the sisters have a variety of totes and ice packs to help keep
cheese and dips chilled. The American Dietetic Association also
recommends freezing low-fat yogurt and letting it double as an ice
pack.
</P>
<P>
   While Keylee prefers her own lunches to those served in a school
cafeteria, she's in the minority at public school. In Georgia,
which has the nation's third-highest participation in the school
lunch program, 77 percent of public school students bought lunch in
1996-97, the latest figures available.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the ADA says, those lunches are nutritious. But
they're not appealing to every child.
</P>
<P>
   ``They try to do a very good job, but you know when they cook in
bulk and your child's not used to that, it's tough,'' Gillespie
said, admitting she was ``very nervous'' when her only child set
out for public kindergarten seven years ago. ``They had weird
combinations, too _ some kind of sandwich with peas and carrots.
Kids are just not prone to eat that as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Lunch should provide a third of a child's daily intake of
vitamins, minerals and calories, according to Dr. Debby
Demory-Luce, nutritionist at the Children's Nutrition Research
Center at Baylor College of Medicine in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   But if they won't eat it, it doesn't matter how nutritious it
is. ``You can put the food in front of them, but other than shoving
it in them, there's nothing you can do,'' says pediatric
nutritionist Carolyn Silzle of Scottish Rite Children's Medical
Center.
</P>
<P>
   If they want peanut butter and jelly every day, Silzle says
that's OK, as long as parents are aware of what else their children
are eating. Parents, in fact, are often part of the problem. The
east Cobb schools that her children attended ``finally had to put a
stop to all the moms bringing in fast-food for their children.''
</P>
<P>
   Her best advice? ``It helps if parents provide a good example.
Give children an opportunity to see you eating a variety of foods,
and they won't think anything of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
