<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1874 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BATS-SAFETY20-COX     08-19 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BATS-SAFETY20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Safety issue is paramount
 &HT;    By Patrick Brannan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The silence said it all.
</P>
<P>
   As Baltimore pitcher Mike Mussina lay in front of the mound
earlier this spring, blood gushing from a cut over his eye, his
teammates in the dugout were silent, some weeping. More than 48,000
people in Camden Yards were quiet. Mussina had just been hit in the
face by a line drive off the bat of Cleveland's Sandy Alomar.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks ago, Houston pitcher Billy Wagner was hit in the
head by a line drive. After the impact, the ball rolled all the way
to the edge of the third-base dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, both Mussina and Wagner suffered only minor
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   That was not the case for 17-year old pitcher Julius Riofrir of
Glendale, Calif. He was killed last summer after being hit in the
right temple by a ball hit with an aluminum bat. He was warming up
at the time and suffered a fractured skull.
</P>
<P>
   In a game where pitchers have less than a second to react to a
line drive, the three incidents clearly show how dangerous the game
of baseball can be.
</P>
<P>
   With aluminum bats being used in college, high school and youth
baseball, fielders seem to be coming under fire more often. Is it
safe to play with aluminum bats?
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers contend they are producing safe bats and the game
is still safe, according to the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The safety issue is a big one,'' Louisville Slugger executive
George Manning said. ``Discussion will continue on the safety of
the bats. But the trend has not been upwards. This issue has been
there all along.''
</P>
<P>
   Manning says in the pros, a player is hit by a batted ball an
average of once every 25 games. At the college level, it happens
once every 75 games.
</P>
<P>
   According to the NCAA's annual injury surveillance system,
college baseball is one of the safest sports in college athletics.
Over the past few years, the NCAA has conducted random surveys to
gather information on defensive players being struck by batted
balls. Yet, only 14 percent of Division I institutions have
completed that survey.
</P>
<P>
   According to Todd Breidenthal, staff liaison with the NCAA
Baseball Rules Committee, this past season, 150 pitchers were hit
by a batted ball. Of those, between 20 and 25 missed at least one
practice or game.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State pitcher Ryan Mills suffered a broken jaw several
years ago by a line drive, and a University of Houston pitcher lost
two teeth. But there have been no fatalities, according to
Breidenthal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we lucky?'' Breidenthal asked, rhetorically. ``I don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just an issue at the college level. As Mussina's
and Wagner's incidents show, it can happen at the highest levels,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that it always takes some serious injury for
(something to be done),'' Georgia State assistant coach Bob Keller
said. ``You'd think that (Mills' injury) would have been enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Major league baseball finally made batting helmets mandatory
after several horrifying incidents, including Boston's Tony
Conigliaro having his cheekbone fractured by a thrown ball in 1967.
In 1920, Cleveland's Ray Chapman was struck in the head by a pitch
and killed, the only on-field fatality in major league history.
</P>
<P>
   With 86 percent of Division I schools not responding to the NCAA
survey, no one knows the exact number of players hurt by batted
balls. But everyone knows it's become more of a problem in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think safety is an issue,'' North Carolina baseball coach
Mike Fox said. ``A lot more get hurt than get reported.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox said he doesn't remember a player being seriously hurt by a
batted ball during the 15 years he was at North Carolina Wesleyan.
He considers himself, and his program, to be fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   Keller has seen his share of players hit, but not necessarily on
the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen anybody get hit in the face,'' Keller said.
``I've seen pitchers go down, and leave the game taking one off the
ankle, getting hit in the chest and whatever. It's pretty
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most of the aluminum bat injuries that you see are
(pitchers) getting hurt in the (batting) cage. Because they're so
close and those balls are ricocheting off the poles on the side of
the cage. I know some coaches now that are making it mandatory for
their guys throwing down in the cage to be wearing helmets. Those
cages are so tight and narrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Keller recalls a third baseman in Georgia who was hit in the
head last year. He's now blind.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many incidents is it going to take?'' Keller asked.
</P>
<P>
   Starting from 60 feet, 6 inches, a pitcher usually ends up about
55 feet away from the batter after his delivery. It can be a scary
sight seeing a ball coming at your head. Sometimes you don't even
see it. Virginia Commonwealth sophomore Jason Dubois pitched
against both aluminum and wood this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm scared,'' Dubois said. ``You're the closest (fielder) to
the plate, and you're throwing the ball and moving in all these
awkward positions. You throw the ball 90 miles per hour, and the
guy hits it, it comes back at about 120. That's got to be the most
frightening thing ever when you're on the ballfield.''
</P>
<P>
   Amherst College coach Bill Thurston has studied the statistical
differences between aluminum and wood. Because an aluminum bat is
lighter and a batter can generate more force, Thurston came to this
conclusion: ``If a batted ball is hit at a greater velocity, at the
same distance and hit harder more often, the potential for more
injuries, and more severe injury, is certainly increased.''
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR:
</P>
<P>
   NCAA baseball officials have approved rules changes designed to
cut the performance of aluminum bats.
</P>
<P>
   The Division I and II championship baseball committees approved
the changes for next season. The Division III committee - concerned
about the financial impact it would have on its schools - asked
that the implementation date be pushed back seven months to August
1999.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA said the amended bats would protect pitchers and
preserve the integrity of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
