<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-LUNCH-RECIPES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kids more likely to eat what they help fix
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Love Presley's sons begged to help. When she said yes, the pair
pulled up chairs to the kitchen counter, turned them around and
hopped up and down collecting ingredients, measuring cups, wooden
spoons and bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Presley read the recipes because the boys were too young to read
and reached overhead for implements out of their reach.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of work in the kitchen, begun at an early age, can
help families grow closer and, the Eatonton woman believes, help
children eat better. Her sons, now in their 40s, liked everything
but broccoli. ``And they're both fabulous cooks,'' she adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most children like what they help prepare. Saturday is a good
time to teach your child,'' Presley advises. ``Let them do it, and
enjoy it with them. And teach them how to clean up.''
</P>
<P>
   Even kindergartners can help with some of these recipes, chosen
because they're nutritious and appealing to many children. Many
5-year-olds can slice a banana with a blunt knife for a fruit salad
to be served at school in an ice cream cone. Some third-graders can
make Not Hot Salsa, and middle schoolers who rise early enough can
make their own Tortilla Roll in the mornings.
</P>
<P>
   But because the beauty of Zucchini Bars and Sweet Potato Maple
Muffins is the way they conceal vegetables, you may want to make
those yourself.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Sunflower Tuna Fish
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Keylee Clemons, 11, of Dahlonega was a children's category
winner in the national StarKist recipe contest with this entry,
which she arranges in a sunflower shape. Keylee said she makes it
for her family nearly every weekend and packs it for a school lunch
at least once a week.
</P>
<P>
   2cans water-packed tuna, drained and flaked
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon prepared mustard
</P>
<P>
   6tablespoons mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   6tablespoons pickle relish
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons chopped green onions, plus green stems for decoration
</P>
<P>
   24crackers
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons sunflower seeds
</P>
<P>
   In a mixing bowl, combine tuna, mustard, mayonnaise, relish and
onions. Mix well and refrigerate or chill until serving.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to serve, place crackers on a plate in a circle, to
resemble flower petals. Place a scoop of tuna in the center.
Sprinkle with sunflower seeds and arrange onion stems to resemble
flower stem.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 341 calories, 24 grams protein, 14 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 20), 14 grams carbohydrates, 38
milligrams cholesterol, 842 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Wolf Pack Ambrosia
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Folks at the Eating Well test kitchen keep these ingredients on
hand so young visitors dropping by can learn kitchen skills like
cutting and measuring. Then they can eat the results _ a nutritious
combination of fruit and yogurt. To send to school, pack the salad
(with ice pack) in a container and pack an ice cream cone
separately. At lunchtime your child can pour the fruit into the
cone and eat _ without a spoon.
</P>
<P>
   1banana
</P>
<P>
   111-ounce can mandarin oranges
</P>
<P>
   1cup fresh or 8-ounce can, drained, pineapple chunks
</P>
<P>
   18-ounce container low-fat vanilla yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1cup mini-marshmallows
</P>
<P>
   Peel banana and cut into thin slices. Put slices in a large
bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Open can of oranges and pour juice into a small bowl. Add
oranges and pineapple chunks to the large bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Add yogurt to the large bowl and stir yogurt and fruit together
with a wooden spoon. Add marshmallows and some of the juice you
saved from the oranges to make it taste just right. Chill until
ready to serve. _ Adapted from Eating Well Magazine
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 101 calories, 3 grams protein, 1 gram fat (percent
calories from fat, 6), 14 grams carbohydrates, 2 milligrams
cholesterol, 31 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Spicy Chicken Little Drumettes
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chill these overnight before adding to a lunch box in the
morning, along with an ice pack. Pack condiments separately for
dipping.
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup ketchup
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup barbecue sauce
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2chicken drumettes (little drumsticks)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees. Line a baking sheet with
aluminum foil and set aside. In a small bowl, mix ketchup, barbecue
sauce and lemon juice. Add chicken and stir to coat evenly with
sauce. Spread out chicken drumettes on baking sheet. Bake for about
30 minutes or until chicken is thoroughly cooked. The chicken
should be white when you cut into it. Chill until ready to serve
with raw vegetables and Kim's Ranch Dressing. _ From ``Magic Spoon
Cookbook,'' by Suzanne Gooding (Klutz Press, $15)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 274 calories, 31 grams protein, 13 grams fat
(percent calories from fat,43), 7 grams carbohydrates, 103
milligrams cholesterol, 407 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Kim's Ranch Dressing
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 cup
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup buttermilk or yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon onion powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon dried parsley flakes
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, combine buttermilk, mayonnaise, onion powder,
garlic powder, parsley and salt; mix well. Cover and refrigerate
until ready to serve or pack in a lunch box with an ice pack. _
From ``Magic Spoon Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 53 calories, less than 1 gram protein, 6 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 94), 1 gram carbohydrates, 4 milligrams
cholesterol, 85 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Not Hot Salsa
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   4large fresh tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1carrot (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1stalk of celery (no leaves)
</P>
<P>
   2green onions
</P>
<P>
   1/2green pepper
</P>
<P>
   Fresh parsley (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Dash of oregano (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Wash all the vegetables and dry with a paper towel. Peel and
chop tomatoes and carrot. Chop the celery, green onions, green
pepper and parsley. Combine all ingredients in a large bowl. Add
salt and oregano to taste. Serve on nachos, quesadillas, chips or
baked potatoes. _ From ``Magic Spoon Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   Per tablespoon: 3 calories, trace protein, no fat, 1 gram
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 2 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Apple Blossom Biscuits
</P>
<P>
   Makes 20 biscuits
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This simple biscuit lends itself to a variety of additions,
depending on your child's tastes.
</P>
<P>
   1cup Wheat Chex cereal
</P>
<P>
   1medium apple, grated
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup apple juice
</P>
<P>
   2cups biscuit mix
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 450 degrees. Put the cereal in a plastic bag,
close the bag, and crush the cereal by rolling a rolling pin over
it several times. Pour crushed cereal into a medium bowl. Add apple
and mix well. Add apple juice.
</P>
<P>
   In another bowl, combine biscuit mix and cinnamon and mix well.
Pour the cereal mixture into the biscuit mix mixture and stir.
</P>
<P>
   Drop dough from spoon onto greased cookie sheet. Bake for 10
minutes. _ Adapted from ``The Best Children's Cook Book Ever,'' by
the Episcopal Church Women of Cunningham Chapel Parish in Clarke
County, Va. (out of print)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 189 calories, 1 gram protein, 2 grams fat, (percent
calories from fat, 24), 11 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 156
milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Sweet Potato
</P>
<P>
   Maple Muffins
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Sullivan of Roswell is the rare parent who often packs her
children's lunches after cooking in the morning. A big believer in
variety, she sometimes substitutes zucchini, carrots or apples for
the sweet potatoes in these muffins.
</P>
<P>
   1sweet potato (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups unbleached all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon ground allspice
</P>
<P>
   1/8teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   6tablespoons ( 3/4 stick) unsalted butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   2/3cup firmly packed dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2eggs, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup milk
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup maple syrup
</P>
<P>
   Granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   Bring a saucepan of water to a boil. Add the sweet potato and
simmer until tender, 20 to 25 minutes. Drain and cool slightly,
then peel and cut into several pieces. Puree potato in a food
processor until smooth. You should have 1/2 cup. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Generously butter two 8-cup muffin
tins, or line them with paper liners.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, sift together the flour, salt, baking powder,
baking soda, allspice and cloves.
</P>
<P>
   In another bowl, cream the butter and brown sugar. Add the eggs
and beat well. Stir in the milk, maple syrup and potato puree; mix
thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   Make a well in the center of the dry ingredients and pour the
potato mixture into it. Stir just until the ingredients are
incorporated. Do not overmix.
</P>
<P>
   Fill cups about 2/3 full. Sprinkle tops with a little sugar.
Bake until a toothpick inserted in center comes out clean, about 25
minutes. Transfer muffins to a wire rack to cool.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Or substitute 1/2 cup of your favorite vegetable puree.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 189 calories, 3 grams protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 25), 33 grams carbohydrates, 39 milligrams
cholesterol, 169 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   VEGETABLES
</P>
<P>
   Crispy Potato Veggies
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10-12 minutes
</P>
<P>
   On any given day, 20 percent of elementary school children eat
no vegetables, according to the USDA's Team Nutrition program. It's
a tasty way to serve veggies, good hot or cold.
</P>
<P>
   2cups fresh vegetables (broccoli or cauliflower florets,
1/4-inch carrot slices, 1/2-inch zucchini slices, 1/2-inch strips
green or red pepper, or other favorites)
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup instant mashed potatoes (dry)
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons margarine or butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon dried basil
</P>
<P>
   1egg
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Wash, drain and cut the vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, mix instant potatoes, cheese, melted butter,
garlic powder and basil.
</P>
<P>
   In a shallow dish, beat egg. Place 1/2 cup vegetables at a time
in the beaten egg. Remove vegetables, 1 piece at a time, and put in
potato mixture, turning to coat. Put coated vegetables on a cookie
sheet. Repeat with remaining vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 10-12 minutes or until light brown. Remove from cookie
sheet immediately._ Adapted from ``Betty Crocker's Cooking With
Kids'' (Macmillan, $14.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 135 calories, 5 grams protein, 9 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 58), 9 grams carbohydrates, 55 milligrams
cholesterol, 190 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SNACK
</P>
<P>
   Pizza Popcorn
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time:10-15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 15 minutes plus popping time
</P>
<P>
   Kids like pizza. Kids like popcorn. Why not put them together
for a snack that's twice as good?
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup butter
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon garlic salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon crushed oregano
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon crushed basil
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon onion powder
</P>
<P>
   10cups freshly popped popcorn
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 300 degrees. In small saucepan, melt butter. Add
cheese, garlic salt, oregano, basil, salt and onion powder.
</P>
<P>
   Put popped popcorn into shallow baking dish. Pour melted butter
mixture over popcorn and stir to mix.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 15 minutes, stirring occasionally. _ From ``The Best
Children's Cook Book Ever''
</P>
<P>
   Per cup: 97 calories, 2 grams protein, 6 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 56), 9 grams carbohydrates, 14 milligrams
cholesterol, 281 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Peanut Butter
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 1/3 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Youngsters in Ellen Powell's Science Through Cooking class at
Georgia State University's Saturday School sometimes test recipes
designed to hide certain ingredients. After making this peanut
butter, Powell often adds shredded carrots for vitamin A and makes
the ever-popular Ants on a Log, filling celery sticks with the
mixture and topping with raisins.
</P>
<P>
   2cups shelled, roasted, unsalted peanuts
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons vegetable oil, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Put shelled peanuts in bowl of blender or food processor. Pulse
until chopped. Add 1 tablespoon oil and the salt. Blend again until
mixture starts to hold together. Add oil until peanut butter is of
spreading consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Per 2-tablespoon serving: 180 calories, 6 grams protein, 16
grams fat (percent calories from fat, 42), 6 grams carbohydrates,
no cholesterol, 109 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Tortilla Roll
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1-2 minutes
</P>
<P>
   A snack category winner in the National Cheese Institute's
Balanced Meals My Way contest, this roll-up adapts well. We tried a
pizza version, too, using mozzarella cheese, pepperoni, mushrooms,
black olives and pizza sauce.
</P>
<P>
   2slices cheddar or American cheese
</P>
<P>
   110-inch flour tortilla
</P>
<P>
   1small tomato, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup chopped mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons prepared salsa
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon fat-free sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Place cheese in center of tortilla. Top with chopped tomato and
mushrooms. Roll up tortilla. Place on white paper towel or
microwavable dish and microwave for 1 minute. Cut in half. Pack in
insulated lunch box with heat pack. Put salsa and sour cream in
separate small containers and pack with ice pack.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 194 calories, 8 grams protein, 9 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 42), 19 grams carbohydrates, 22 milligrams
cholesterol, 308 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Zucchini Bars
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30-35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This dessert bar is a treat, whether or not the kids know about
the vegetable inside.
</P>
<P>
   2/3cup packed brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup margarine or butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   1egg
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1cup shredded zucchini, drained
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup chopped nuts
</P>
<P>
   Spice Frosting (recipe below)
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 350 degrees. Grease an 8-by-8-by-2-inch baking pan.
In a large bowl, mix brown sugar, margarine, egg and vanilla. Stir
in flour, baking soda, cinnamon and cloves. Stir in zucchini and
nuts. Spread batter in pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 25 to 30 minutes or until toothpick inserted in center
comes out clean. Cool completely. Meanwhile, prepare Spice Frosting
to spread on cool bars. _ From ``Betty Crocker's Best of Baking''
</P>
<P>
   BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Spice Frosting
</P>
<P>
   Frosts 8-inch square pan
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon margarine or butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   3to 4 tablespoons milk
</P>
<P>
   1/8teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   Mix sugar, margarine, milk and cloves until smooth. Spread on
cooled bars.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving with frosting: 147 calories, 2 grams protein, 7
grams fat (percent calories from fat, 40), 21 grams carbohydrates,
14 milligrams cholesterol, 109 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Three Cheese Broccoli Corn Bread
</P>
<P>
   Makes 20 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This prize-winning entry in the National Cheese Institute's
contest is good hot, warm or cold.
</P>
<P>
   3eggs
</P>
<P>
   1cup low-fat, small-curd cottage cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup melted butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1/8teaspoon hot pepper sauce
</P>
<P>
   110-ounce package frozen chopped broccoli, thawed
</P>
<P>
   27-ounce packages corn bread mix
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1cup shredded Swiss cheese
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Grease a 9-by-13-inch baking dish. Heat oven to 375 degrees. In
a large bowl, beat together the eggs, cottage cheese, butter and
hot sauce. Stir in the broccoli, corn bread mix, onion and cheeses.
Spoon batter into the greased baking dish, spreading evenly. Bake
for 30 minutes or until golden brown and a toothpick inserted in
center comes out clean. Cut into bars and serve with a salad.
</P>
<P>
   You can make corn bread a day ahead and reheat in microwave on
high for 15 seconds, then pack with a heat pack for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 240 calories, 9 grams protein, 11 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 5), 26 grams carbohydrates, 80
milligrams cholesterol, 530 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Spicy Chicken Little
</P>
<P>
   Drumettes
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chill these overnight before adding to a lunch box in the
morning, along with an ice pack. Pack condiments separately for
dipping.
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup ketchup
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup barbecue sauce
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   12chicken drumettes (little drumsticks)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Line a baking sheet with aluminum
foil and set aside. In a small bowl, mix ketchup, barbecue sauce
and lemon juice. Add chicken and stir to coat evenly with sauce.
Spread out chicken drumettes on baking sheet. Bake for about 30
minutes or until chicken is thoroughly cooked. The chicken should
be white when you cut into it. Chill until ready to serve with raw
vegetables and Kim's Ranch Dressing (below). _ From ``Magic Spoon
Cookbook'' by Suzanne Gooding (Klutz Press, $15)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 274 calories, 31 grams protein, 13 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 43), 7 grams carbohydrates, 103
milligrams cholesterol, 407 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
