<HEADER>
A1885 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-LUNCH-SAFETY-COX     08-19 0305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-LUNCH-SAFETY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    School lunch tip: Think safety
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If it's hot, keep it hot. If it's cold, keep it cold.
</P>
<P>
   That's the simple food safety rule to follow when packing
perishables for lunches.
</P>
<P>
   Bacteria that can cause sickness multiply most rapidly between
40 degrees and 140 degrees. That's why food safety specialists
recommend using ice packs with foods that would normally have to be
refrigerated, such as ham and yogurt, and heat packs or thermoses
for foods that are served hot, such as soup and leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   While ice packs and heat packs will do the job until lunchtime,
neither will last all day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any perishable leftovers after lunch should be discarded and
not brought home,'' according to Bessie Berry, manager of the U.S.
Department of Agriculture's Meat and Poultry Hotline.
</P>
<P>
   Ice packs come in a variety of sizes, materials and shapes to
fit well into insulated bags and boxes. Or freeze juice boxes or
filled plastic bottles to double as ice packs. Food should be
chilled in the refrigerator before being packed in an insulated
container with a pack.
</P>
<P>
   Heat packs are microwavable gel packs useful to help keep cooked
or heated foods hot. Make sure the food is thoroughly cooked or
reheated before packing with a heat pack.
</P>
<P>
   Some lunch totes have two or three separately insulated sections
to accommodate both hot and cold foods.
</P>
<P>
   Lunch packing is a good time to talk to children about food
safety, especially the importance of washing their hands. To help,
the USDA Food Safety and Inspection Services has an activity book
for children that can be found on the Internet at
http://www.foodsafety.gov/(tilde)dms/cbook.html/.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
