<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-LUNCH-TIPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cox News Service readers' tips on school lunches
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUNCH TIP: COMMUNICATE
</P>
<P>
   Carol Cole of Norcross, Ga. said her mother often sent messages
on banana skins, using a fork tine or knife tip, and by the time
Cole got to school, ``I love you,'' ``Have a happy day'' or a
smiley face was visible. She has continued the tradition with her
daughter and, now, grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Alice Rhodes of Lilburn, Ga. broke the day-to-day monotony
for her two daughters, both now teachers, by tucking interesting
decorated napkins into their lunches. By the time they got to high
school, she was secretly packing in other small surprises like
Tootsie Rolls. ``It adds a little spunk,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kitty Black of Douglas County(Ga.) saves cards, cuts off the
backs, and writes a message on the backside of the decoration.
She's been doing this since her now-12-year-old daughter was in
kindergarten and said she still loves it.
</P>
<P>
   LUNCH TIP: THINK SMALL
</P>
<P>
   Small, ready-to-eat foods are most likely to be eaten, parents
say, explaining why they take the time to chop, pare, peel and
package fruits and vegetables or heat and bag mini-bagels for
children's lunches. Food companies have figured out how popular
snack sizes are, too, and now offer mini-pizza kits using crackers
for the base, packages of baby carrots with dip and, now,
single-serving packs of cereal not meant to be eaten with milk.
This month Kellogg's introduced three of its popular kids cereals
in snack packs.
</P>
<P>
   MORE TIPS
</P>
<P>
   -- Spread peanut butter or flavored cream cheese on a rice cake.
Pack sprinkles, raisins or pretzels for decoration.
</P>
<P>
   -- Pack a banana. Put peanut butter in a small container, put
sprinkles in another and include a plastic spoon. Your child can
decorate the banana at lunch.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kitty Black, Douglas County(Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   -- For sandwiches, cut bread into different shapes with cookie
cutters.
</P>
<P>
   _ Several readers
</P>
<P>
   -- Shelled sunflower seeds and individually wrapped string
cheese are handy sources of protein.
</P>
<P>
   _ Anonymous e-mail
</P>
<P>
   -- ``I'll do banana nut muffins and grate some carrots in them
so fine they don't notice.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Brenda Moseley, Ellenwood , Ga.
</P>
<P>
   -- Pack fun straws or small prizes.
</P>
<P>
   -- Nutritious convenience foods include packaged carrots with
dip, apples with caramel dip, small packs of crackers and
fruit-and-grain bars.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Freeze grapes so they're super-cold for lunchtime. My kids
eat more when I do this.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Kathy Sullivan, Roswell, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   -- Cut up apples and put a little lemon juice on them so they
won't get brown.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keylee Clemons, 11, Dahlonega, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   -- Layer light or fat-free soft cream cheese, then salsa,
shredded light or fat-free cheddar/Jack cheese mix and finely
shredded lettuce. Packed in that order, the salsa blends with the
cream cheese and the lettuce doesn't get soggy. If your children
like, you can add chopped tomatoes or black olives, too.
</P>
<P>
   _ Julie Gillespie, Lilburn, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   -- Core an apple, stuff it with peanut butter and wrap in foil.
</P>
<P>
   _ Carol Cole, Norcross, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
