<HEADER>
A1887 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RECIPE-SWAP20-COX     08-19 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPE-SWAP20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nuts and bolts of preparing gelatin salad
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After Frances Allen of Atlanta requested a recipe for a layered
gelatin salad called Under the Sea, we were flooded with responses.
Twenty-eight of you sent copies _ or even original pages cut
directly from a Jell-O cookbook _ for a salad by that name.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is that while Allen recalled a lime layer and a cream
cheese one that may have contained nuts, the ``Joys of Jell-O''
recipe calls for pears, not nuts, in the cream cheese layer.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of readers sent recipes for a dish that sounded more
like what Allen had in mind, never mind the name. This one is from
Gloria Conrey of Lithonia, Georgia, who says her mother made it in
the '60s using pineapple and nuts.
</P>
<P>
   We're giving you both, so you can take your pick.
</P>
<P>
   SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Under the Sea Salad With Nuts
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 2 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 3 hours
</P>
<P>
   Refrigeration: overnight
</P>
<P>
   1large package lime gelatin
</P>
<P>
   1large package lemon gelatin
</P>
<P>
   18-ounce package
</P>
<P>
   cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   1envelope Dream Whip, prepared according to package directions,
using
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup milk and 1/2 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   18-ounce can crushed pineapple with juice
</P>
<P>
   1cup chopped walnuts
</P>
<P>
   Following instructions on gelatin packages, prepare flavors
separately. Pour lime gelatin into a large, 4-quart clear glass
bowl or gelatin mold. Refrigerate until set, about 3 hours.
Meanwhile, pour lemon gelatin into a metal ice tray or cake pan and
freeze until it crystallizes, about 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, beat cream cheese, prepared Dream Whip and
lemon gelatin. Stir in pineapple and chopped nuts. Pour mixture on
top of set lime gelatin. Refrigerate overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 207 calories, 11 grams protein, 11 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 48), 18 grams carbohydrates, 17
milligrams cholesterol, 84 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Under the Sea Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 2 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   Refrigeration time: overnight
</P>
<P>
   1small package lime
</P>
<P>
   or lemon-lime gelatin
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1cup boiling water
</P>
<P>
   1can (16 ounces) pear halves
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2small packages (3 ounces each) cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/8teaspoon ginger
</P>
<P>
   Dissolve gelatin and salt in boiling water. Drain pears,
measuring 3/4 cup syrup; add water, if necessary. Dice pears and
set aside. Add pear syrup and lemon juice to gelatin. Measure 1 1/4
cups into a 1-quart mold. Chill until set but not firm.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, soften cheese until creamy. Gradually add remaining
gelatin, blending until smooth. Add ginger. Chill until very thick.
Fold in pears. Spoon into mold. Chill until firm.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 188 calories, 9 grams protein, 8 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 37), 22 grams carbohydrates, 23 milligrams
choles-terol, 175 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   -- Merrill Frazier has grown more okra than she and her husband
can eat, so she is looking for a recipe for pickled okra _ not just
one to be adapted for okra.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
