<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1888 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MANGO-AZR &LR;      08-19 2196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANGO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANGO TANGO: TIME TO REDISCOVER JUICY, FRAGRANT FRUIT  
 (WITH SIDEBAR MANGOSIDE)  
 (ART ADV: ART HAS BEEN SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - You don't need everything but the kitchen sink to
enjoy mango mania. All you need IS the kitchen sink.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just eat 'em over the sink,'' urged local mango maven Kathleen
Vanesian. ``It's not the most attractive thing, but it's certainly
the most satisfying.''
</P>
<P>
   Mango madness comes over otherwise sensible people this time of
year, when the fruit is so juicy, so fragrant, so flowery. Now that
they're going for three for $1, it's a great time to experiment
with mangoes.
</P>
<P>
   Mangoes are native to India and now are grown in hot, humid
regions around the world. Arizona gets its mangoes year-round from
Florida, Mexico, Brazil, Ecuador, Peru and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, mangoes are artful street food, speared on sticks and
peeled open to look like edible flowers, according to Kathleen
Vandervoot, spokeswoman for the Fresh Produce Association of the
Americas, which is based in Nogales, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkled with lime juice and chili powder, they are delicious.
</P>
<P>
   And in April, Vanesian said, ``you will find Mangoes with Sticky
Rice sold on every street corner in Thailand. It's their hottest
month, and their mango month.''
</P>
<P>
   Mangoes with Sticky Rice has become a sort of national dessert
there, Vanesian said. The rice for ``sticky rice'' is widely
available in Asian stores; it's also known as sweet rice or
glutinous rice. It has a distinguishable translucence, both raw and
cooked. When cooked, it can be packed into bowls to unmold and gild
with sweetened coconut milk and fans of mango slices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination of the tangy tartness of the mango with the
creamy coolness of the coconut sauce is a combination that's hard
to beat,'' Vanesian said.
</P>
<P>
   During August, Vanesian's Viet namese friends in California send
or bring her lugs of a variety of mangoes known as Sun Da. They're
neither fibrous nor resinous, she said.
</P>
<P>
   If you're going to use the mango right away, Vanesian said,
``look for one that smells good and yields to light pressure.''
Avoid mangoes that are too soft or wrinkled. Mangoes taste best at
room temperature, but can be refrigerated if ripe to hold for a
couple of days longer.
</P>
<P>
   Think tropical when you're dreaming up your own mango dishes.
Mangoes meld well in flavor combinations with hot chiles and hot
spices, as well as cilantro, lime juice, red bell peppers, green
bell peppers, and jicama, for starters. Bell peppers and jicama and
crunchy vegetables provide great texture contrast with the velvety
mango flesh.
</P>
<P>
   The mango has a couple of odd things about it, starting with
that pit. What gives with that thing, anyway? It takes up half the
fruit's interior, or so it seems.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schneider calls mangoes ``the most clingstone and
clingpeel of fruits'' in her latest edition of ``Uncommon Fruits &AMP;
Vegetables.''
</P>
<P>
   Mango aficionados will gnaw the seed to get every last juicy
bite. And here's the other weird thing: Mangoes belong to the
cashew family and are related to poison ivy and poison oak. When
they touch the skin or sap, some sensitive people may get red
rashes or blisters. Schneider reports that these same individuals
may not be bothered by eating the ripe fruit.
</P>
<P>
   So what else can you do with a mango? Put it in fruit salad,
vegetable salad; make tarts with it over vanilla cream; saute them
as you would bananas, in brown sugar and butter, and use over ice
cream. Or pair mangoes with grilled or roasted poultry or pork, or
even cold meats. Green mangoes are used in some recipes, and could
be shredded into salads.
</P>
<P>
   Mango chutney, which is easy to make, is a standard condiment on
many continents. You can freeze mangoes by pureeing the pulp and
then pressing it through a sieve. Pack in plastic freezer bags or
containers.
</P>
<P>
   How about nutrition? Mangoes are very good sources of potassium,
according to Schneider, and superior sources of vitamins A and C.
Low in sodium but high in fiber, they are also moderately high in
calories: 70 per mango half.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their tropical lushness and because they blend so
well with hot flavors, chefs and food companies have taken the
mango to their bosoms. You can find a variety of mango products
such as juices, canned mango in syrup, and bags of frozen mango
chunks, as well as mango-accented dishes on menus all over town.
</P>
<P>
   Chef Norman Fierros of Norman's Arizona loves mangoes.
</P>
<P>
   To eat them, though, he admits, ``I have to hang over the
kitchen sink.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MANGOES WITH STICKY RICE &QL; 
(From Kathleen Vanesian) &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 254 calories, 8 g fat, 0
cholesterol, 44 g carbohydrates, 141 mg sodium, 26 percent calories
from fat.
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 cups still warm, cooked sticky rice (also called sweet or
glutinous rice)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup canned coconut milk (more if you want to follow drizzling
directions below)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons sugar (or more or less to taste)
</P>
<P>
   3 large ripe mangoes, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   To fix rice: Put rice in cold water for at least 20 minutes.
Drain, rinse, and put in a pan with an equal amount of cold water
(for 2 cups rice, use 2 cups water). Cover and cook on high until
water boils. Reduce heat to very low and cook about 12 minutes.
Remove from heat and let stand 10 minutes. Rice should be getting
very gooey.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, mix coconut milk, salt and sugar until salt and
sugar dissolves. Mix in cooked sticky rice; let sit for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Mound sticky rice in center of large platter; arrange mango
slices around mound of rice. Serve.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Cook's note: If you want to get fancy, make a little more of the
coconut cream mixture and drizzle it over everything. If you really
want to make it pretty, mold rice into a bowl and turn it out onto
the serving platter. Fan mangoes around it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
THAI SHRIMP AND MANGO SALAD &QL; 
(From ``Seattle Times``)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 185 calories, 4 g fat, 184 mg
cholesterol, 17 g carbohydrates, 558 mg sodium, 2 percent calories
from fat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 ripe mangoes or papayas, peeled and cut into small cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 medium red bell pepper, seeded and finely diced
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 pounds small cooked cocktail shrimp, drained well
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Thai fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon crushed red-pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon canola oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh cilantro
</P>
<P>
   4 cups cleaned, crisp, torn greens
</P>
<P>
   8 basil leaves, cut into shreds
</P>
<P>
   Combine the mangoes or papayas, bell pepper and shrimp in a
large bowl. In a jar, combine the lemon juice, rice vinegar, fish
sauce, pepper flakes, sugar, oil and cilantro. Close jar and shake
well to combine. Pour over the mango salad and refrigerate for
about 1 hour. Stir the greens and basil into the salad and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 to 6 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CORNISH HENS WITH MANGO SAUCE &QL; 
(From ``Mexico the Beautiful'' cookbook)
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 752 calories, 45 g fat, 266 mg
cholesterol, 5 g carbohydrates, 1,313 mg sodium, 55 percent
calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   6 small (1 1/2 pounds each) Cornish game hens
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   Sauce:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups syrup from canned mangoes
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup drained canned mangoes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   Garnish:
</P>
<P>
   Extra pieces of mango
</P>
<P>
   Remove the giblets and sprinkle the Cornish game hens with the
pepper. In a blender, puree the garlic, salt and water. Pour over
the hens and marinate, refrigerated, for 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   To make the sauce, puree the syrup and mangoes in a blender or
food processor. In a small skillet, melt the 1 tablespoon butter,
add the puree and brown sugar and stir. When the mixture begins to
boil, remove from the heat and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   About 1 hour before serving, preheat the oven to 500 degrees and
place the hens, breast side down, in a greased large baking pan.
Baste with the 6 tablespoons melted butter and bake for 15 minutes.
Turn the hens breast side up and bake another 15 minutes, basting
frequently with the butter. Lower the heat to 375 degrees, turn the
hens again and bake for 10 minutes. Remove from the oven, drain the
juices from the pan and stir in the mango sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Turn the hens breast side up and baste with the mango sauce.
Bake for another 5 to 7 minutes, or until they are golden brown.
Serve immediately, garnished with extra pieces of mango.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
BEEF SATAY WITH A HOT MANGO DIP &QL; 
(From ``Taste of Asia``) &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 155 calories, 9 g fat, 24 mg
cholesterol, 11 g carbohydrates, 206 mg sodium, 52 percent calories
from fat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 pound sirloin steak, 3/4-inch thick, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon coriander seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cumin seeds
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces raw cashew nuts
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 shallots, or 1 small onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 piece fresh ginger, 1/2-inch long, peeled and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons tamarind sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dark soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon rice or white-wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Hot Mango Dip:
</P>
<P>
   1 ripe mango
</P>
<P>
   1 or 2 small red chiles (fresh or dried), seeded and finely
chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lime
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons freshly chopped cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   Slice the beef into long, narrow strips and thread, zigzag
fashion, onto 12 bamboo skewers. Lay on a flat plate and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   For the marinade, dry-fry the seeds and nuts in a large wok
until evenly brown. Place in a pestle and mortar with a rough
surface and crush finely. (Alternatively, blend the spices and nuts
in a food processor.) Add the vegetable oil, shallots or onion,
ginger, garlic, tamarind and soy sauces, sugar and vinegar. Spread
this mixture over the beef and leave to marinate, refrigerated, for
up to 8 hours. Cook the beef under a moderate broiler or over a
barbecue grill for 6 to 8 minutes, turning to ensure an even color.
Meanwhile, make the mango dip.
</P>
<P>
   In a food processor, process the mango flesh with the chiles,
fish sauce, lime juice, sugar and salt until smooth, then add the
cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MANGO SORBET &QL; 
(From ``Frida's Fiestas``) &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 128 calories, 0.1 g fat, 0
cholesterol, 33 g carbohydrates, 2 mg sodium, 0.5 percent calories
from fat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   2 cups mango, pureed with 1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   Combine sugar and water in a saucepan and heat until syrupy.
Remove from heat. Stir in mango puree. Strain if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Chill, then place in an ice-cream maker and freeze according to
the manufacturer's instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 to 8 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
AAM CHUTNEY (MANGO CHUTNEY) &QL; 
(From ``Chutney and Rayta'') &QL; 
(LOW FAT) &QL; 
Approximate values per \ cup serving: 344 calories, 2 g fat, 0
cholesterol, 85 g carbohydrates, 6 mg sodium, .5 percent calories
from fat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 pound green, unripened mango, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   Dash of salt
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of turmeric
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 teaspoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of fennel seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 or 2 whole red chiles (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 teaspoons finely chopped gingerroot
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound fresh plums, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 tablespoons white vinegar or lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle salt and turmeric on sliced mango, and set aside for 2
to 3 hours. Combine mango and sugar in a saucepan, and cook,
covered, over low heat until mango is tender, about 15 minutes. Do
not add any liquid. The mixture will form a thick, tangy sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Heat vegetable oil in a small skillet, add fennel seeds and fry
for 2 seconds. Add chiles (if using), gingerroot and plums and
cook, stirring, for 1 or 2 minutes. Combine spiced plums with mango
mixture and continue cooking over very low heat about 30 minutes,
or until plums are tender. Mix in vinegar or lemon juice, remove
from heat and set aside to cool.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 cups. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MANGO SALSA &QL; 
(From ``Miami Spice: The New Florida Cuisine'') &QL; 
(LOW FAT) &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 7 calories, 0 g fat, 0 cholesterol,
2 g carbohydrates, 1 mg sodium, 0 percent calories from fat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups diced ripe mango
</P>
<P>
   1 cucumber, peeled, seeded and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 jalapeno, seeded and minced
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped fresh mint or cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon packed light brown sugar, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fresh lime juice, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients in a mixing bowl and gently toss to mix.
Correct seasonings, adding extra salt, lime juice or sugar to
taste. The salsa should be a little sweet and a little sour. Mango
salsa tastes best served up to a couple of hours after making.
</P>
<P>
   Refrigerate, covered, until serving. Good served with grilled
meats and fish of all sorts and also as a vegetable side dish.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 40 tablespoon servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
