<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Aug. 20, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: (888) 603-1036 or
(888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Wednesday, in the humid wake of a tropical disturbance
churning westward, heavy thunderstorms erupted over Puerto Rico.
The disturbance, one of several westward-moving systems strung out
over the tropical Atlantic Ocean, will bear down on the peninsula
of Florida on Thursday, setting the stage for clusters of heavy
showers and thunderstorms. The heaviest rains will likely occur
near the East Coast, where the leading edge of the sea breeze works
in tandem with the disturbance to rapidly lift very warm and humid
air. Street flooding is likely in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   A volley of heavy showers and thunderstorms will soak parts of
southern Louisiana as an upper-level disturbance drifts westward
from the Florida panhandle. The system will forge slowly but
steadily westward Thursday night, raising the probability of heavy
rain by Friday in east Texas. Another westward tracking,
potentially wet disturbance over the Gulf of Mexico will arrive in
south Texas by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, clusters of showers and thunderstorms will bubble up
over eastern Montana, Wyoming and western South Dakota as a jet
stream disturbance lifts gathering humid air. A few of the storms
will approach severe levels, with hail, strong winds and tornadoes
posing threats.
</P>
<P>
   After a chilly early morning in the Northeast, Thursday
afternoon temperatures will rebound under strong August sunshine,
but will stay several degrees below the average. Under the auspices
of high pressure, unseasonably low humidities will embrace the
Middle Atlantic States as far south as North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Twist of Fate
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, temperatures at Del Rio, located on the upper Rio
Grande River of Texas, soared to 105 degrees, marking an all-time
record 69th day this summer with triple-digit readings. The
tenacious south Texas heat wave also teamed with devastating
drought. In an abrupt twist of fate on Tuesday, 1.23 inches of rain
fell at Del Rio, breaking the record for the date. The high
temperature was 82 degrees, the lowest high ever on August 18. The
air over Del Rio was nearly saturated to an altitude of 20,000
feet, providing a favorably moist environment for cooling, heavy
thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
