<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1917 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UPS-DESIGN-535&AMP;ADD-NY     08-19 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPS-DESIGN-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC EYE: LEARNING TO LOVE BROWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KARRIE JACOBS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Recently, Michael Bierut, a graphic designer and
partner at Pentagram, a company known for nurturing the eclecticism
of its partners, has been busy re-examining the corporate identity
of United Parcel Service. His first instinct, he said, was to
introduce a little drama into the life of this nearly century-old
shipping company by changing the color of its trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe UPS trucks could be a lot of different colors, he
suggested, like M&AMP;M candies, with some of the trucks remaining the
familiar deep chocolate brown.
</P>
<P>
   Bierut, like all experts in corporate identity, looks hard at
the commercial paraphernalia we see all around us but rarely
notice, and revamps a logo or a typeface or a color so that, for a
moment or two, we do notice.
</P>
<P>
   When I originally encountered Bierut more than a decade ago, he
had just helped rescue the Cinzano logo. The Italian liqueur maker
had paid a company for a drastic redesign, something minimalistic
and cool, and then, horrified, ran to Bierut's former employer,
Vignelli Associates. Vignelli assured Cinzano that it was OK to go
back to its old logo.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Bierut used this anecdote to advance the notion
that graphic designers should be like historic preservationists,
shoring up beloved old corporate symbols to withstand the rigors of
time, instead of bulldozing them.
</P>
<P>
   Just the other day, Bierut made that same case. As it turns out,
UPS, though momentarily charmed by the novelty of a tutti-frutti
fleet, quickly said no. ``If someone could make a really good
business case to get rid of brown, they would,'' Bierut insisted.
``It's a hard case to make. I tried.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the designer immersed himself in the shipping company's
culture. He donned the brown uniform and rode with a UPS driver
around the Upper West Side of Manhattan. He spent a night in a
company shipping center watching brown boxes whiz by. And he
learned to really appreciate the color brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``They started out being Pullman brown,'' said Peter Fredo, UPS'
vice president for advertising and public relations, when I ask him
about the history of the brown trucks. The trucks have been brown
since 1916. ``The reason they picked up on Pullman,'' Fredo said,
``is that it was the epitome of luxury and class at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Fredo is something of an expert on the culture of brown. He
mentions the Paris exposition of 1867, where the main hall was
decorated in brown and gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a long period where brown was not in fashion,''
Fredo acknowledged, failing to mention that point in history when a
brown shirt signified a storm trooper, ``until Prada turned the
light back on.'' A few years ago, when brown was declared the new
black, Prada made a bag in UPS' favorite color.
</P>
<P>
   The familiar UPS truck, with its distinctive pug-dog nose, is a
classic, designed in the early 1960s when the company transformed
itself from a delivery service for department stores into a common
carrier. If it were a building, it would be eligible for
landmarking. The UPS logo, a simple gold shield topped by a
schematic package, was designed in 1962 by Paul Rand. ``Every
designer sees it and thinks, `I can do better,''' Bierut said. To
date, no one has.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In 1996, when the company painted a Web-site address on its
fleet, a news release noted that it was only the third time in 30
years that the company had changed the look of the truck. The
previous occasion was in 1993, when the company added the globe and
arrow symbol as well as the phrase ``Worldwide Delivery Service.''
</P>
<P>
   The company may be hard-pressed to walk away from brown, but in
the prototype for its soon-to-open storefronts, brown and gold will
be joined by sky blue, symbolizing air freight.
</P>
<P>
   I'm indebted to Bierut because, until he mentioned it, I had
never thought of the UPS trucks as objects of beauty. Nor had I
appreciated the singular nature of the corporation's color sense.
More astute observers, however, have long admired UPS brown.
</P>
<P>
   As Stan Herman, the Seventh Avenue stalwart responsible for the
design of the original Federal Express wardrobe, put it, UPS brown
is ``absolutely smack on target.'' Herman was appraising the
uniforms, but his observations also apply to the trucks: ``You
become a poet if you stick to your guns.''
</P>
</TEXT>
