<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1928 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLIOTT-SMITH-MUSIC-$     08-19 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIOTT-SMITH-MUSIC-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACING WHAT HIS CHARACTERS PROBABLY NEVER WILL: SUCCESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everybody's dying just to get the disease,'' sang Elliott Smith
about the perils of fame in ``Pictures of Me,'' one of the most
memorable pop songs of last year. It appeared on ``Either/Or,''
Smith's third album, and it was a startlingly advanced report of
dissaffection sung in a high voice by a slouchy 27-year-old Beatles
fan from Portland, Ore., with a pallid, wounded demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, ``Pictures of Me'' had a particular power because
Smith was still untainted by fame, and the song seemed to confide
the details of its author's fate.
</P>
<P>
   The song had hooks and drama and a queasy, beautiful-loser's
weariness that would almost certainly make him famous, and it was
humid with Smith's revulsion at that prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Smith could afford his reverse snobbery then, recording for an
independent label called Kill Rock Stars, whose distribution
extends only to college towns. But a year has passed, and in that
time five of Smith's songs were used in the film ``Good Will
Hunting,'' directed by Gus Van Sant _ whose primary material is
beautiful losers _ and one was nominated for a Grammy.
</P>
<P>
   Smith held hands in a stage bow with Celine Dion on national
television in the Academy Awards show, and his new album, ``XO,''
is on the major label Dreamworks. As he does on his other albums,
Smith plays all instruments, down to piano, drums and organ (except
for the strings that decorate a few songs), and his harmonies and
structures have grown more sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   Smith had something to prove when he stepped into the more
complicated waters of mass-consumption pop, and he has made an
impressive record; it's so good that he's going to have to learn to
live with the disease.
</P>
<P>
   George Harrison is Smith's patron saint, which sets him apart
from the regular stripe of John-and-Paul-favoring Beatles
enthusiast. Harrison's songs ``Something'' and ``Isn't It a Pity''
are part of Smith's live repertory, and elements of other Harrison
tunes like ``I Want to Tell You'' and ``Blue Jay Way'' are echoed
in Smith's original songs on ``XO.''
</P>
<P>
   Like George Harrison, Smith has anti-charisma. If you like him
at all, you've already gone more than half way into his psyche. And
once you're there, he operates on your expectations according to
the classic mold of the rocker or beatnik hero _ Dean, Brando,
Dylan.
</P>
<P>
   His male fans might revere him for the casual cruelty in his
lyrics or the abdication of responsibility as his characters watch
friends self-destruct or embark fatalistically on another doomed
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps his female fans want to comfort him, picking up on the
scraps of redemptive language in the songs, sensing that he's not
thoroughly cold and rotten.
</P>
<P>
   Smith comes on like a member of Deadbeats Anonymous, and his
mantra, from ``Waltz (NU)2,'' the first single from ``XO,'' uses
the appropriate language of recovery: ``I'm so glad that my
memory's remote/ 'cause I'm doing just fine hour to hour, note to
note.''
</P>
<P>
   With his unusual gift for melody amid a melody-poor generation
of rockers, Smith may be the most fully formed singer-songwriter to
come along since Elvis Costello, and like Costello's early records,
``XO'' has a perversely adversarial relationship to the listener.
</P>
<P>
   In song after song, he seems to plead for you to go away,
singing ``I'm tired, I'm tired,'' ``Don't you dare disturb me while
I'm balancing my past,'' ``I'm so angry,'' ``Leave me alone.'' Even
as the forms vary, from downcast finger-picked ballads to barbed
electric pop to the four-part harmony vocals of ``I Didn't
Understand,'' Smith works with one emotional stance, and it's
rooted in resentment and fatalism.
</P>
<P>
   He's like the boy nobody understands who both wants and rebuffs
your attention; giving in to the abundant pleasures of his craft,
as is the case with watching Smith in concert amid rapt fans, is
like being taken captive by a brilliant and petulant child.
</P>
<P>
   The choice Smith's characters have to face seems is either
addiction and failure, which he watches with head-shaking
detachment, knowing that he can't get too involved _ or the
self-imposed exile of someone trying hard to walk the straight and
narrow. He invites the women that populate his love songs to come
live with his depression, warning them that it will all end in
tears anyway.
</P>
<P>
   And without being grandiose or literary or even particularly
clever with his lyrics, he sings about drugs with a squalid
honesty. Mordant references to drugs pop up throughout the album:
``Fully loaded, deaf and dumb and done''; ``Gonna spend the day
higher than high''; ``She shows no emotion at all/ stares into
space like a dead China doll''; ``It's a chemical embrace that
kicks you in the head.''
</P>
<P>
   But as a poet of the seedy world, he's also above it, adding
pinches of moralizing: ``Once I was you,'' he sings to a
shooting-star in ``Independence Day,'' adding, ``Don't go too
far/stay who you are ... go to sleep and make the change/ I'll meet
you here tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with ``XO'' is that it feels unfinished. Smith has
performed these songs live with only an acoustic guitar, and to
hear him this way is to know that he's the real thing; the songs
translate beautifully to solo performance, as most rock songs one
hears on the radio do not.
</P>
<P>
   But here and there are inklings of a greater sound-world _
electronic tones creating weirdly inapposite harmonies at the end
of ``Baby Britain,'' deep overlays of strings, guitars and
keyboards in ``Everybody Knows, Everybody Understands''_ that make
you wonder why he didn't use more of this kind of ornamentation on
the album.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear that he hedged his greater aspirations and made the
kind of modest record he knows how to make. Still, sometimes you
want to enroll the talented and standoffish Smith in a
self-actualization course: who does he want to be? King of the
indie-boys or mass-pop communicator? What's so rare about him is
that either one lies within his grasp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 1808EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1930 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLASSICAL-CDS-NYT &LR;      08-19 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSICAL-CDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASSICAL CDS: PIANISTS WHO SHOW WHAT THE TALK IS ABOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sergei Babayan
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Babayan, an Armenian pianist who came to the United
States in 1989, was a forceful presence at last year's Van Cliburn
International Piano Competition, even though he was neither a
competitor nor a judge.
</P>
<P>
   Babayan, who is an artist in residence at the Cleveland
Institute of Music and also runs his own teaching academy, had four
students in the contest, and one heard his name evoked reverently
with unusual regularity. His disciples' playing suggested that he
demanded much of them technically and that he encouraged them to
explore some unusual repertory byways.
</P>
<P>
   One work that several of them played was an electrifying Sonata
by Carl Vine, a 44-year-old Australian. That work, a two-movement
essay in complex, propulsive rhythms and insistently expansive
chordal clusters, is the centerpiece of a new recording by Babayan
(Pro Piano PPR224517).
</P>
<P>
   Besides doing the service of putting the Vine Sonata on disc,
the recording goes a long way toward explaining the fuss about
Babayan. The repertory of varied 20th-century works puts a
spotlight both on his extraordinary technique and on his ability to
play densely harmonized works with an illuminating transparency.
</P>
<P>
   Babayan's arching accounts of ``Premiere Communion de la
Vierge'' and ``Le Baiser de l'Enfant Jesus'' from Messiaen's
``Vingt Regards sur l'Enfant Jesus'' are pictures of carefully
judged meditative intensity. Those movements surround a bracing,
sharp-edged performance of the ``Noel'' movement from the same
work.
</P>
<P>
   Two Respighi rarities _ the first of the three Preludes on
Gregorian Melodies and a gentle Notturno _ offer a sweet-toned,
impressionistic interlude before selections from Gyorgy Ligeti's
early ``Musica Ricercata,'' a group of miniatures in which a
Lisztian approach to the keyboard is refracted through a modern
harmonic lens.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly striking among the Ligeti works is No. 7, marked
``Quieto (poco rubato) _ Cantabile _ Molto Legato,'' in which a
gentle melody floats over a muted repeating bass figure played so
rapidly that it begins to sound almost like a synthesizer
recording. To produce that effect with the left hand while the
right produces a singing, free-spirited melody requires a daunting
measure of control.
</P>
<P>
   Fazil Say's Mozart
</P>
<P>
   After years of listening to critics' complaining that so many
young musicians' recordings are brilliantly polished but
interpretively indistinguishable, record companies are taking some
risks, signing players with strong personalities and
individualistic approaches to the repertory. But they seem unable
to resist turning these adventurous gestures into promotional
circuses, with campaigns that focus on eccentricity rather than
acuity.
</P>
<P>
   When Warner signed Fazil Say, a 28-year-old Turkish pianist
whose live performances have alienated some and won over others, it
put him on a pop label, Atlantic, rather than on one of its
classical lines (Teldec, Erato or Nonesuch). His debut disc, an
all-Mozart program, is adorned with a sticker in which he is
described, in a review quotation, as ``a wild man at the
keyboard.''
</P>
<P>
   In some repertory _ his recent ``Rhapsody in Blue'' with the New
York Philharmonic, for example _ that description is not far off
the mark. But it doesn't apply to the performances on his Mozart
disc (Atlantic 21970-2). That's not to say that Say's performances
are quirk-free.
</P>
<P>
   He is selective about repeats, for one thing; he plays none of
them in the C Major Sonata (K. 330). In the first movement of the A
Major Sonata (K. 331), he plays them in some variations and skips
them in others, and in the final variation he plays the first two
repeats but skips the third.
</P>
<P>
   Listeners with an ear for architecture may find this jarringly
asymmetrical, but Say may have been less concerned with the
symmetry than with the idea that the closing chords of that final
variation can make a repeat seem anticlimactic.
</P>
<P>
   At times his readings draw so fully on the dynamic and
coloristic resources of the modern piano that a listener is tempted
to regard his readings not simply as romantic interpretations but
as acts of rebellion against the period instrument movement.
</P>
<P>
   He is particularly fiery in the ``Ah, vous dirai-je, maman''
Variations, but in the Sonatas, too, he passes up few opportunities
for dramatic contrast. Often he does this to fine effect: The
Andante Cantabile of the Sonata in B flat (K. 333) has an almost
operatic quality, not only because Say makes the melodic line sing,
but also because he suggests orchestral coloration and balances in
the accompanimental figures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
