<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Morrison salute to include reading by the author
 &HT;    By Don O' Braint
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The list of major literary figures coming to Atlanta this fall
is growing. Two weeks after John Updike was announced as a featured
speaker at the Atlanta Jewish Community Center's November book
festival, Toni Morrison has been booked for a conference in
September.
</P>
<P>
   The Nobel laureate will read from her novel ``Paradise'' at 8
p.m. Sept. 26 at the Rialto Center for the Performing Arts as part
of the first biennial conference of the Toni Morrison Society.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia State University(GSU)-sponsored conference Sept.
23-27 will focus on the meaning of the American South in Morrison's
fiction. Morrison's parents, like many African-Americans in Lorain,
Ohio, where she grew up, were part of the 20th-century migration
from the South.
</P>
<P>
   As her fictional characters suggest, these migrants lived with
contradictory memories of the South. They loved the communities
they left, but could not forget the racial violence and
discrimination that forced them to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increasingly,'' says conference organizer Carolyn Denard,
``humanities scholars are focusing on the cultural and
psychological meanings of the great migration. Morrison's fiction
is an important repository of those meanings. And it is precisely
this distanced, remembered view of the South _ nurturing and
inhibiting _ articulated by those who left the region that we seek
to explore during this conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Denard, a GSU English professor, launched the Toni Morrison
Society in 1993 to encourage discussions and projects devoted to
the study of the works of the author. The society publishes a
semiannual newsletter and gives an annual award for the best book
published on Morrison.
</P>
<P>
   Among the events at the Atlanta conference are a performance by
Spelman College(Ga.)'s Readers' Theater, ``Talking Drum,'' and a
trip to the Noble Hill-Wheeler Museum in Bartow County, where
Morrison's father was born.
</P>
<P>
   For information about the conference, call 404-651-3584; for
tickets to Morrison's reading, call 404-651-4227.
</P>
<P>
   A LATE ADDITION: Speaking of the Atlanta Jewish Community Center
Book Festival, spokeswoman Esther Solin announced this week that
Pulitzer Prize-winning playwright Wendy Wasserstein will speak at
7:30 p.m. Nov. 21 at the AJCC midtown branch, 1745 Peachtree Road
N.E. Wasserstein's works include ``The Heidi Chronicles'' and ``The
Sisters Rosensweig.'' Information: 404-875-7881.
</P>
<P>
   NO BARE BONES PROMOTION: Scribner is not going to scrimp on
promotion of Stephen King's novel ``Bag of Bones'' next month. The
$1 million marketing campaign will include TV commercials,
advertising in movie theaters and radio station giveaways.
</P>
<P>
   Set on the banks of Dark Score Lake in Maine, ``Bag of Bones''
(Scribner, $28) is the tale of best-selling novelist Mike Noonan,
who still grieves for his wife four years after her death.
Suffering from nightmares as well as writer's block, he flees to a
lakeside getaway named Sara Laughs. There he is drawn into a
custody battle for the 3-year-old granddaughter of a powerful
millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   In a note in his publisher's catalog, King says he wanted to
write one more ``really good scary story'' before he hit 50. ``I
wanted something else as well: to tell a tale combining the
romantic suspense of `Rebecca' and that sense of otherworldly
terror that permeates `The Haunting' and `The Uninvited.' ... If I
had to describe it, I'd call it a haunted love story.''
</P>
<P>
   HISTORIC DEAL: Author Margaret George has signed a seven-figure
deal with Viking Penguin for her next three books. George, whose
recent historical novel ``The Memoirs of Cleopatra'' will be an ABC
miniseries next spring, plans to focus on women in history. Her
next subject: Mary Magdalene.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
