<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANE-GARDEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A plane garden: Love of aircraft propels artist to create works
using found objects, imagination
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 23: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C.Herron Briggs is a plane man. Walking through
his garden in a near-downtown neighborhood of little homes and
small businesses, you see all manner of winged craft _ dozens of
them _ floating among the sunflowers, the hollyhocks and
hydrangeas, their propellers turning in the breeze.
</P>
<P>
   You can hear them, too, whirring, whirring, a thousand
whispering counterpoints to the roaring traffic on Church Street.
</P>
<P>
   This is Briggs' gallery. His plane garden. Open to all.
</P>
<P>
   It is here, next to his cream-colored house, in the shade of a
big old split-trunk oak, that he displays his art, here that he
creates it. For nearly 30 years, Briggs has made planes, hunkered
down at a little bench facing the street in fine weather, holed up
in his tiny workshop when foul weather strikes. His creations are
fashioned from tin cans, pieces of wood, radios, fan blades, toy
wheels and just about anything else his fertile imagination calls
for. He has never flown in a plane and has no plans to, learning
all he knows from just looking.
</P>
<P>
   His planes draw visitors from near and far _ and were featured
in a recent exhibit of watercolors by Greenville artist Lynn Greer.
</P>
<P>
   Folk artist? You could call him that. Or just artist. But
there's more to what he does. In these planes that do not fly,
Briggs transports all who visit to places of the mind, far, far
away. We soar on his passion and joy, appreciating that he can
create meaningful art _ and have fun with it, too.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting him in March, I visited again in August. On this
warm, breezy afternoon, I find Briggs putting the finishing touches
on a stealth bomber, painted black, sporting a figure with a
bowling ball on its swept-back right wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just painted this plane,'' he says. ``Had to put a special
paint on it because, you know, this plane is invisible.'' His laugh
carries down the street.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby is a P-38 with a basketball player shooting over the
propeller. ``I don't know where his basket is,'' Briggs says
thoughtfully.
</P>
<P>
   His plane garden also grows passenger craft, fighters,
helicopters and others. Recently, he began experimenting with
brighter colors, such as purple and yellow, to complement his
longtime standards, red, white, blue and silver.
</P>
<P>
   After making planes by heart for more than two dozen years,
Briggs began fashioning some from a book (``1001 Images of
Aircraft,'' Crescent Books) that a visitor gave him about a year
ago. When the man wanted to become a business partner, ``I said,
`No, no, I don't need anybody to help me collect the money.''' His
wife, Lida, does that just fine, he says.
</P>
<P>
   With no book, no pictures, Briggs says he still could create _
in much the same way some musicians can play music after hearing it
once: ``I can see a plane, and if I see it from the side, I can
build it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been in me all along,'' this love of plane-making, says
Briggs, who is a fit-looking 75 years old. ``But I didn't think it
would go this far.'' While he made a plane here and there decades
ago, his production really took off when he retired from his
forklift-operator job at a cotton warehouse in 1988. ``Now, I'm
full time.''
</P>
<P>
   Not many years ago, he'd sell a plane for $25; now, they command
prices up to about $1,000, sold to people from California to
Germany. His output ranges from five or six planes some months to
as many as 30.
</P>
<P>
   There's one he won't part with. A silver-colored helicopter with
a red saw blade for its rear propeller and a red fan blade up
front. It's one of his first creations.
</P>
<P>
   When he started tinkering in the 1960s, Briggs recalls, he was a
neighborhood curiosity, especially to youngsters. ``They'd come by
and say, `Look at that man with all those cat-food cans.''' Over
time, the lookers became visitors; the curiosity became an
attraction.
</P>
<P>
   (And the cans. I started writing down Spam cans, stew beef cans
..., when Briggs interrupted, saying, ``Oh, man, you name all the
cans I use, and you got two books.'')
</P>
<P>
   Greer, the watercolorist, passed Briggs' garden gallery for many
years before she summoned the courage to stop, ``invade his
privacy'' and introduce herself to the man whose work she had
enjoyed during drive-bys. ``The first time I saw it, in the spring
of 1997, I felt like a child in Disney World. It's just so much
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   She immediately began photographing and painting the garden, and
in May presented her watercolors in a one-woman show that included
seven other gardens. ``His had to be one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes his art so appealing? Greer, whose connection with
Briggs shows with each click of her shutter, says, ``He has that
natural, childlike wonder that, in most of us, gets suppressed by
`technique' as we grow older. His creativity has not been
destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Could he maintain that delightful wonder about planes if he ever
got on one?
</P>
<P>
   Would you ever fly? I ask. Says Briggs, emphatically: ``No,
please no! I don't believe I could have that kind of nerve. I love
'em down here on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense; after all, art does not have to be life.
</P>
<P>
   For a minute or two, Briggs and I say nothing, contemplating his
certain sense of flying his way; the only sound in his garden is
the whirring propellers. Taking us away.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
