<HEADER>
A1934 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YARDSALE-COX     08-19 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YARDSALE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    450-mile-long annual rite put on by the neighbors
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 23: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sarah Brown was plumb tickled to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just bought an antique plant seeder for $25. That's a
steal,'' Brown said to her traveling companions. ``Of course, I
don't know what I'll do with it. Sit it on the porch, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown was perusing early morning bargains with Hazel Miller of
Acworth, Georgia, Gail Arnette of Stockbridge, Georgia, and Dot
Spencer of Jonesboro, Georgia in a field dotted with tents and
tarps and tables in Gadsden, Alabama otherwise known as the POB.
</P>
<P>
   The POB is the Point of Beginning for the ``World's Longest
Outdoor Sale'' _ 450 miles of flotsam and jetsam from overstuffed
attics, overstuffed barns, an overstuffed century.
</P>
<P>
   Each year on the third weekend in August, folks who live along
Lookout Mountain Parkway from Gadsden to Chattanooga, Tenn. and
U.S. 127 from Chattanooga to Covington, Ky., toss everything from
rusty farm implements to male mannequin torsos out into their
meadows and main streets for one colossal yard sale.
</P>
<P>
   And each year, more than 30,000 treasure seekers trade whooshing
down the interstate for inching along scenic highways, at times
bumper to bumper, to take their pick of props. Along the way they
feast on corn bread salad, pinto beans and swamp cabbage and share
fellowship with neighbors down the road or travelers from as far
away as California.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is American free enterprise at its purest,'' touts Lloyd
Wagnon, director of the Gadsden-Etowah Tourism Board and the wizard
of the sale. ``Who knows how much money changes hands? We don't
handle the cash boxes, but we can tell by the smiles on the faces
there are some good trades going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The sale began 11 years ago in Jamestown, Tenn., as an effort to
pull travelers off nearby interstates and into the Sequatchie River
Valley of the Cumberland Plateau. It spread like kudzu up and down
the U.S. 127 corridor, and in 1994, the Lookout Mountain Parkway
hooked up to the route.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, the spirit of the sale grows, with more buyers and
sellers joining the chain. This year, there was a somber undertone
as news spread about a recent tragedy that claimed the lives of two
and injured 19 others. An 18-wheeler lost its brakes as it came
barreling down a mountainside and crashed through an intersection
of U.S. 127 near Dunlap, Tenn., tossing cars and tumbling tables
and tents. All morning, folks traded what they had heard of the
accident and advised one another to be careful.
</P>
<P>
   The narrow, two-lane roads were built at a time when we went
along with the gentle curves of the green earth, rather than
blasting our way through, straight and wide. The two-lanes take you
up mountains, around town squares and along the curving spines of
lush valleys.
</P>
<P>
   Come upon a pasture and you're likely to see a cluster of
tables, some loaded up by locals, others by professional vendors
who've made the annual event a part of their circuit. Go around the
bend and you see a solitary soul sitting by the side of his truck,
hoping to sell home-grown tomatoes or his cousin's old eight-track
tape player.
</P>
<P>
   Go through small towns such as Pikeville, Tenn., and every sign
welcomes the ``U.S. 127 sale shoppers.'' The churches have opened
up as ``rest stops,'' and people seem genuinely pleased to sell you
their old party dish set for 50 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Some buyers come knowing what they're looking for. ``I look for
old dolls, cookbooks, cast iron and cookware,'' said Margaret Avant
of Hillsboro, who was traveling from Georgia in a motor home with
her husband, Henry. They started looking Thursday morning in
Gadsden, and by Saturday afternoon, she was in Lawrenceburg, Ky.,
with more than 20 dolls for her collection.
</P>
<P>
   Others are like Bruce Jones of Pascagoula, Miss. ``I'm looking
for the find of a lifetime,'' said Jones, traveling the route for a
second year with his wife, Ann. ``Of course, I don't know what that
is.''
</P>
<P>
   By Friday afternoon, he had spent a dime on a carpenter's pencil
and a quarter on an old military patch. Not much for two days of
scavenging. But it was clear that most buyers and sellers were as
interested in visiting as bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do this every year, and the greatest thing is the people
you meet,'' said Esther Clemmons in Signal Mountain, Tenn.
``Yesterday we had folks by from Oklahoma, Iowa, West Virginia and
New York. It's just so much fun to listen to their accents and try
to guess where they are from.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemmons said she makes a few hundred dollars every year from
the sale, which is now stocked with the overflow from the attics of
friends and family members since her stock is depleted. Fadana
Bramblett in Owenton, Ky., said her yard sale brings in about $900
each year, which she donates to the adult education program in her
town.
</P>
<P>
   Like the ``great find'' you didn't know you were looking for,
the sale is one of those tonics you don't know you need until you
travel the route.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many outdoor events involving 30,000 people, no one was
drunk or hostile. Everyone was courteous. Buyers and sellers
actually wanted to look at each other and say hello when they were
making a transaction. Rain and traffic jams were no excuse for
impatience or rudeness. And not one single person talked of the
Monica issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better than drinking and juking. I don't feel bad the
next morning,'' said Henry Avant, explaining the appeal. ``It's
just the anticipation of finding what you're looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
