</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Your guide to the new fall TV lingo
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's almost fall, which means the over-boiled hyperpole for the
new TV season is in full bloom.
</P>
<P>
   Of course every show can't be a hit, but if you're a highly-paid
network exec there's no tactful way to say, ``This show really
bites,'' without losing your job.
</P>
<P>
   After consulting with a team of crack linguists, We Who Surf
have begun deciphering the bizarre doublespeak of the men and women
who spend gazillions of dollars every year developing new
television shows only to cancel most of them 13 weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   We've compiled a handy primer to help you, the viewers at home,
figure out what the programming execs say, and what they really
mean:
</P>
<P>
   -- ``This show has plenty of attitude.'' Translation: ``This
show has plenty of cursing.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The show is a result of corporate synergy.'' Translation:
``Our parent company is forcing us to use Scott Baio in the lead
because he's got two years left on his contract.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``It has an organic feel.'' Translation: ``We hired a slew of
writers at the last minute to punch up the pilot.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``We had to punch up the pilot.'' Translation: ``After hiring
a slew of new writers, the show still doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``This show is an example of our programming for the
millenium.'' Translation: ``We have no idea what the show is
about.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``This show is an example of our new family programming.''
Translation: ``Grandma will be asleep before the first commercial
break.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``It will appeal to urban viewers.'' Translation: ``It has
all black characters.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``It has a really hip feel.'' Translation: ``It has more than
two black characters.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``It will appeal to suburban viewers.'' Translation: ``There
are less than two black characters.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``This show is kind of quirky.'' Translation: ``This show has
more than two black characters, and one of them is gay.''
</P>
<P>
   Documentry almost as good as the real thing
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's ``Waterfalls of the Southern Appalachians'' (PBS,
check local listings), is a half-hour survey of 59 cascades in five
states and almost as good as a trip to the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Impressionistic in structure, it follows Atlanta filmmaker Chris
Lockett's crisscrossing journeys to places like Amicalola Falls in
North Georgia and Dry Falls in North Carolina, and spots in South
Carolina, Alabama and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The trek, a circular sweep that dabbles in history, wilderness
theory and sociology, can sometimes feel like crossing a mountain
stream one slippery stone at a time. No matter. The photography is
breathtaking, the bluegrassy soundtrack mountain-born, and
ultimately, the raw, charging beauty of these falls are what
register most.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _Eileen Drennen, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
