   EMBASSY-SUSPECT (Undated) -- Osama bin Laden, an exiled Saudi,
has emerged as the prime suspect in the African embassy bombings.
By Anne E. Kornblut. 1400 words.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-REAL-IRA (Dublin) -- Splinter group responsible for the
Omagh bombing, the Real IRA, calls a belated ceasefire. But its
leaders are shunned by fellow republican hardliners furious over
the violence. By Kevin Cullen. 1500 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LEWINSKY (Washington) -- When Monica Lewinsky testifies
again before the grand jury she'll be asked probing questions about
gaps in President Clinton's testimony. By Michael Kranish and Brian
McGrory. 1300 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GLOBE-BARNICLE (Boston) -- New revelations about alleged
plagiarism by Boston Globe columnist Mike Barnicle result in his
resignation. By Mark Jurkowitz. 1500 words. (a and e coding)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTONS-VINEYARD (Edgartown, Mass.) -- President Clinton
celebrates his 52d birthday in a quiet party. By Ann Scales and
Ellen O'Brien. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   KLAN-TRIAL (Hattiesburg, Miss.) -- FBI informant testifies that
a former Klan leader ordered the 1966 firebombing that killed
Vernon Dahmer. By Curtis Wilkie. 850 words.
</P>
<P>
   COD-FISHERY (Undated) -- The cod fishery in the Gulf of Maine is
on the verge of collapse because the Georges Bank area has been
closed down and too many boats now are working the gulf. By Scott
Allen. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ARCH-MOBILEMEDIA (Undated) -- Arch Communications Group says it
is in talks to buy MobileMedia for as much as $520 million in cash,
stock and debt. By Joann Muller. 800 words.
</P>
