</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: CRUDUP TO STAR IN `OEDIPUS'; GARTH BROOKS IN BRAZIL;
A CABARET SYMPOSIUM; PIRATE RADIO STATIONS CLOSED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Fla.)  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As any number of performers will tell you, Hollywood
can be humbling. Take Billy Crudup, for example, the promising
young actor whose last two films, ``Grind'' and ``Inventing the
Abbotts,'' were quick-to-video releases.
</P>
<P>
   Now Crudup, who was widely praised in the 1996 production of
``Bus Stop'' at Circle in the Square, is returning to the stage to
appear as the title character in ``Oedipus,'' by Dare Clubb,
starting on Sept. 20 at the CSC Theater.
</P>
<P>
   He joins a cast that includes Frances McDormand, who won an
Academy Award in 1997 playing a pregnant police officer in
``Fargo.'' She will play Merope, the adoptive mother of Oedipus.
</P>
<P>
   Country Rambler
</P>
<P>
   Chalk up another continent for Garth Brooks. Brooks, the country
music star who conquered New York's Central Park last summer, will
stage his first show in South America on Saturday. The concert, in
Barretos, Brazil, coincides with the Rodeo Barretos, a 10-day event
that is expected to draw as many as 1.5 million visitors to the
inland city.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks is anticipating a considerably smaller audience, but more
than 30,000 tickets have already been sold. In addition to Brooks,
the rodeo will feature performances from Chitaozinho and Xororo, a
top Brazilian country duo.
</P>
<P>
   Showing Off
</P>
<P>
   Cabaret would seem to be anything but academic, but starting
Friday at the Eugene O'Neill Theater Center in Waterford, Conn.,
some of the biggest names in the song-and-dance business will be
sitting down to discuss their craft and teach some younger show
people the tricks of the trade.
</P>
<P>
   The O'Neill Cabaret Symposium, which runs until Aug. 29, is said
to be the only conference in the United States devoted to the form,
and will include performances and workshops by the singers Margaret
Whiting and Julie Wilson, and the actress Tovah Feldshuh.
Thirty-five ``Cabaret fellows'' were admitted to this year's
conference, which will also be celebrating its 10th anniversary
with a ``master teachers' special performance'' on Aug. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Tuned Out
</P>
<P>
   Continuing a recent crackdown on unlicensed radio, the Federal
Communications Commission has announced the closing of 15 pirate
radio stations in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The low-power stations were raided late last month by agents of
the U.S. Marshals Service and other federal agencies. The FCC
chairman, William Kennard, called the raids the largest action ever
against unlicensed stations, and said the commission would
``continue vigorously to enforce the law.''
</P>
<P>
   But Greg Ruggiero, co-founder of the New York Free Media
Alliance, which supports pirate radio, called the raids an attack
on free speech. Stations must maintain a minimum transmission power
of 100 watts to be licensed; most pirate stations broadcast at 10
to 20 watts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 1828EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
