<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1969 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOE-BLACK-MOVIE-NYT &LR;      08-19 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOE-BLACK-MOVIE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHLY TOUTED `MEET JOE BLACK' REPORTEDLY OVER BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ It's an unwritten Hollywood rule that action and
special-effects movies, like ``Titanic,'' go over budget.
Unpredictable weather, computer glitches and expensive crowd scenes
all contribute to soaring costs.
</P>
<P>
   A corollary to that rule is that romantic dramas and comedies,
like ``The Bridges of Madison County,'' ``Sleepless in Seattle'' or
``City of Angels,'' generally keep within tight budgetary
constraints.
</P>
<P>
   And then, or so the buzz goes, there's ``Meet Joe Black.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most anticipated films of the fall, ``Meet Joe
Black'' is a romantic drama with Brad Pitt, Anthony Hopkins and
Claire Forlani that has reached production costs of about $90
million, several agents and producers said. This would be a record
for a traditional romance.
</P>
<P>
   Producers and agents with knowledge of the movie's finances said
that the film was as much as $30 million over budget, although
Universal Pictures, which made the film, says that figure is much
too high. The movie, set to be released Nov. 13, was nearly three
hours long but will probably be pared down to two hours and 30 to
40 minutes, still at least half an hour longer than the usual
romantic drama.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Silver, chairman of Universal Pictures, said that the
movie, directed by Martin Brest, was over budget, ``but not
insanely over budget.'' He said that the rumors proliferating
around Hollywood about its cost were not true, though he declined
to say how much the film cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marty Brest is a perfectionist,'' Silver said. ``This is a
first-class production, and I committed to Marty that we'd be
making this first-class in New York and Rhode Island.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great movie, a complete home run,'' he said. ``It's
over two and a half hours in length and it didn't go anywhere near
$30 million over budget. That's nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver added that Brest's two previous films, ``Midnight Run,''
with Robert De Niro and Charles Grodin, and ``Scent of a Woman,''
for which Al Pacino won an Academy Award, had been profitable.
``This will be a commercial and critical success too,'' Silver
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meet Joe Black,'' adapted by Bo Goldman, one of Hollywood's
foremost screenwriters, and inspired by the 1934 Fredric March
classic ``Death Takes a Holiday,'' deals with a young man who
recently died (Pitt) and who embodies death as a kind of Grim
Reaper. He takes a holiday among the living, encounters a business
tycoon (Hopkins) and falls in love with his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Brest is known here as a perfectionist, albeit a successful one,
who labors over projects for years. One of his most successful was
``Beverly Hills Cop,'' the 1984 comedy that made Eddie Murphy a
star.
</P>
<P>
   Why ``Meet Joe Black'' costs so much, in contrast to other
romantic dramas, is not entirely clear. A coming Warner Brothers
romantic comedy, ``You've Got Mail,'' starring Tom Hanks and Meg
Ryan, and directed by Nora Ephron, cost $60 million to $65 million,
mostly because of the huge salaries of the two stars and because it
was made in New York City. ``Bridges of Madison County,'' another
romantic drama, cost about $35 million and grossed more than $70
million. More recently, ``City of Angels,'' a romance with Nicolas
Cage and Ms. Ryan, cost about $55 million and grossed nearly $80
million.
</P>
<P>
   Producers and others who are knowledgeable about ``Meet Joe
Black'' attributed the high costs partly to slower-than-usual
filming, which delayed the opening by about five months. That meant
post-production offices were kept open far longer than expected.
</P>
<P>
   One person close to the studio said that the shooting was at
least two months over schedule, which drove up salaries and
overtime pay. In addition, an elaborate set as well as a swimming
pool were built to serve as the glittering home of the Anthony
Hopkins character.
</P>
<P>
   The sets included highly expensive rented antiques and
furniture. Instead of using them for a limited period of time, said
one producer, the filmmaker kept the stage home going for an
extended period. .
</P>
<P>
   Various executives expressed surprise at reports of the high
cost of the movie, largely because it will have to turn into a
substantial box office success to earn its money. With marketing
costs reaching $35 million to $40 million, ``Meet Joe Black,'' just
to break even, would have to match the box office totals of a
successful film like ``Sleepless in Seattle,'' which grossed $126.5
million. The potential, of course, is far greater: the record
setter for a romance is ``Ghost,'' which grossed $217 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
