<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURY PRICES ARE LITTLE CHANGED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury bond prices were little changed Wednesday,
with the dollar continuing to slide against the yen. This was
attributed to talk of possible intervention by the Japanese to aid
the yen. Also a report of stronger-than-expected housing starts
gave investors little incentive to buy bonds with yields near
record lows.
</P>
<P>
   Traders also said that recent strength in the stock market had
drawn capital away from the government securities market, with the
shorter maturities outperforming the longer-term issues. Hedge
funds are said to be actively going into shorter-maturity bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year bond was unchanged at 99 7/32. The
bond's yield, which moves in the opposite direction from the price,
was also unchanged at 5.55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The government's report on housing starts in July, said Marilyn
Schaja, an economist with Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, suggests
that construction starts are back to the levels recorded during the
housing boom of the 1980s. Housing starts increased by 5.7 percent
last month, to an annual rate of 1.72 million units, the highest
level since March 1987. Economists had expected a decline in
housing starts.
</P>
<P>
   The low interest rates that have produced strong housing
construction may also help offset the economic slowdown caused by
the Asian financial crisis and decline in demand for U.S. products.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds did manage to ward off some of the day's weakness when the
Federal Reserve Bank bought $1.023 billion in notes and bonds. The
central bank entered the market as a buyer to add money to the
banking system, which addressed a seasonal shortage of banking
reserves, traders said.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, the Treasury announced that it plans to sell $15
billion of two-year notes next Wednesday. In when-issued trading
ahead of the auction, dealers were offering the notes at a price to
yield 5.31 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
