<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1978 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRACE-MUSIC-LADN     08-19 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRACE-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOUCH OF FAITH AND HOPE... BUT NO SPICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Call 'em the anti-Spice Girls. Or the Nice Girls.
</P>
<P>
   With a string of 15 No. 1 hits on Christian radio, Point of
Grace has rapidly become contemporary Christian music's most
popular girl group.
</P>
<P>
   No, they don't call themselves Faith Spice, Hope Spice, Charity
Spice and Chastity Spice. Even though, that is, the foursome's
Heather Floyd has boldly proclaimed on stage, ``I'm 25 and I'm a
virgin. It is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Point of Grace's lush harmonies, pop rhythms and optimistic
lyrics are in evidence on the Grammy-nominated group's fourth and
latest album, ``Steady On'' (Word/Epic), the follow-up to ``Life,
Love &AMP; Other Mysteries.'' The earlier disc sold more than 500,000
copies and is still in the top 20 on Billboard's Top Contemporary
Christian albums chart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's tragic so many people don't listen to the lyrics
they're exposed to everyday,'' Floyd, now 28, said. ``Lyrics can
have an effect on you. They can sink in. You don't see a lot of
light in the dark world we live in today.''
</P>
<P>
   That spirit is echoed in such new Point of Grace songs as ``Who
Am I,'' ``Drawing Me Closer'' and ``The Song Is Alive.''
</P>
<P>
   As the group's Shelley Breen says, ``We've always been about
encouragement. We've always been about hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Denise Jones, Terry Jones (no relation) and Floyd have been
friends since singing in church groups in Norman, Okla. They formed
Point of Grace in 1991 with Denise's roommate, Shelley, when all
four attended a small Baptist college in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, the approach was hands-on. With Denise as
musical director, Shelley focused on booking, Heather did publicity
and Terry took care of the money. Within three years, they signed
with top Christian label Word Records; their 1993 debut spawned six
No. 1 singles and the press started calling them ``the Supremes of
Christian pop.''
</P>
<P>
   The group appears Sept. 11 at the New Life Clinic's Women of
Faith: Bring Back the Joy conference at the Pond in Anaheim. The
conferences have been likened to a female version of the Promise
Keepers.
</P>
<P>
   Relating to female fans of various ages has become easier this
year for Point of Grace since both Denise and Terry have become
moms. Breen is married, too, while Floyd _ well, things haven't
changed since she made that on-stage declaration of her passion for
purity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want girls and guys to know I'm as normal as the next
person,'' Floyd says. ``I have weaknesses like everybody else. I
know I'm human. But it's encouraging to young people that I can say
I'm 28 and still a virgin. Now, the road to that is not easy. You
have to make the decision early. And you have to be prepared for
the moment when you will be tempted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know being a teen in the '90s is even harder than it was in
the '80s. But God never changes and he's the one that gives you
strength. It's an enormous message we want to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Not your typical top-40 fare by any means.
</P>
<P>
   Point of Grace has been involved with Mercy Ministries of
America, a nonprofit nationwide outreach program for unwed mothers
and troubled teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are dedicated to what we sing about,'' Floyd said. ``We
never try to water down our lyrics. We're about the Lord and if you
want to be encouraged, then great. But we never sit in judgment of
anybody. If there's anything endearing about us, it's that we love
people _ not just Christian people, all people.''
</P>
<P>
   Christian pop is one of the fastest-growing segments in the
music industry, raking in more than $750 million in record sales
and concert receipts last year.
</P>
<P>
   The quartet's new album, ``Steady On,'' has been called
something of a departure for the group in that it showcases more
personal vocals. The project marks the first pairing of Point of
Grace with award-winning producer Brown Bannister for an entire
album.
</P>
<P>
   Elisa Elder, Word's vice president and general manager, called
the disc ``a giant leap in artistic growth'' for the singers, who
shared an early appreciation for Christian pop superstar Amy Grant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a big fan of music _ classical, reggae, rock _ all
kinds,'' Floyd said. ``But I was listening to Sarah McLachlan and
started really hearing the lyrics for the first time. And they were
horrible. They didn't make me feel good at all. I respect
musicians, but a lot of times people go overboard trying to be deep
and introspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd believes the message of Point of Grace can only become
more widespread as the group grows in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   After all, she said: ``God put that in us for a reason.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
