u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIRELAND-REAL-IRA-850     08-19 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-REAL-IRA-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SIGN OF HOPE? ADAMS AND TRIMBLE ATTEND BOMBING FUNERAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAGH, Northern Ireland _ The grieving and angry people of this
town buried their dead Wednesday and heaped scorn on the guerrillas
who caused the killings in a huge car bomb explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of clergymen and politicians sought to encourage
the daunted population that the peace agreement would survive.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen of the 28 people killed were laid to rest around Omagh,
a mostly Catholic town set in dairy farm country 60 miles west of
Belfast that became the scene Saturday for the worst carnage in 29
years of sectarian violence in Protestant-dominated Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dead were three young boys, buried Wednesday in the
town of Bucrana, across the Irish Republic border in County
Donegal. In a rare appearance together, both Gerry Adams, president
of Sinn Fein, the Irish Republican Army's political wing, and his
adversary David Trimble, the Protestant leader of the Ulster
Unionist Party and First Minister of the new Northern Ireland
Assembly, attended the service.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new and welcome development,'' the Roman Catholic
Bishop of Donegal, Seamus Heggarty, said in his funeral sermon.
``Both of you are very welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the peace agreement approved by a large margin in
Northern Ireland and the Irish Republic in May was ``the only
alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no other,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble has refused to talk to Adams or his Sinn Fein colleagues
in the Assembly, and the two adversaries are likely to clash over
whether Adams gets a post in the new Northern Ireland government.
But the Sinn Fein leader has expressly condemned the Omagh attack,
which claimed both Protestant and Catholic lives, wounded 220
people and has drawn revulsion from many on both sides of the
sectarian divide.
</P>
<P>
   In Dublin, Prime Minister Bertie Ahern announced that the Irish
Republic would take what he called ``draconian'' legal measures to
fight terrorism, saying Parliament would be summoned in two to
three weeks to approve them. The steps, if approved, will make it
easier to convict people of membership in a terrorist organization.
But, significantly, they do not include a renewal of preventive
detention, allowing internment of suspects without trial. Such
detential remains legal but has not been used in years.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Britain interned hundreds of IRA suspects, but
this backfired when inmates went on highly publicized hunger
strikes in the early 1980s, becoming internationally known and, in
several cases, dying for their cause.
</P>
<P>
   Bernadette Sands, the sister of the first hunger striker to die,
Bobby Sands, is now prominent in the 32 County Sovereignty
Committee, which vehemently opposes the Northern Ireland peace
agreement. She announced Wednesday that she and her partner,
Michael McKevitt, were quitting their home near Dundalk, in the
Irish Republic a few miles from the border, because they felt their
children were being threatened by angry townspeople who suspected
the family was involved in the attack. British newspapers have
identified McKevitt as the supposed head of the Real IRA, the
splinter group that carried out the bombing on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Irish national television, Ms. Sands denied
she or McKevitt were involved in the bombing, but declined to
condemn violence for political ends.
</P>
<P>
   Her tough talk contrasted starkly with the muted outrage on the
streets of Omagh. Wednesday afternoon, on a bridge over the River
Strule, a few hundred yards from the bombing scene, people came to
stare silently at several hundred bouquets and at British soldiers
in full combat uniform guarding the area.
</P>
<P>
   Both Catholics and Protestants here were bitter and cynical
about the cease-fire announced late Tuesday by the Real IRA, which
is made up of about 100 dissidents from the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their warnings were false, so their cease-fire is false,''
said a 40-year old man who declined to give his name for fear of
terrorist reprisal. ``They'll carry out their next atrocity under
some other name.''
</P>
<P>
   The Real IRA admitted on Tuesday afternoon that it had placed
the bomb and said, incredibly to most people here, that it had not
intended to hurt anyone. It denied that its warning phone calls had
misled the police into moving people toward the bomb instead of
away from it.
</P>
<P>
   The Real IRA members broke with the main IRA over the Northern
Ireland peace agreement, which was made possible by an IRA
cease-fire now in its 13th month. The agreement included creation
of the Northern Ireland Assembly, which is to convene next month to
begin to make changes in the political structure that will give the
province's Catholic minority more power and the overwhelmingly
Catholic Irish Republic more influence in northern affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The Real IRA rejected the peace agreement because it also leaves
the province as an integral part of Britain and stipulates that the
North may only be subsumed in the Irish Republic if a majority of
the people here consent. The Protestant majority opposes union with
Dublin and is likely to prevail well into the new century.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On the bridge in Omagh, Graham McClelland, 55, a Protestant and
a government surveyor, noted that the Real IRA had said it was
reviewing its goals. ``It's a pity they didn't review their
position before the carnage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shaun O'Neill, an 11-year-old Catholic, looked at the bouquets
with his younger brothers, Ryan, 6, and Fergal, 3. ``I can't
believe it,'' he said.'' My mom was getting ready to go shopping
there on Saturday. Then just about 3 o'clock she decided not to
bother. We all were going with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan O'Neill added in a faint voice.``I'm sad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
