u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-KENYA-HOTEL-NY     08-19 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-KENYA-HOTEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAIROBI HOTEL IS FOCAL POINT OF EMBASSY BOMB PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also AFRICA-BOMBING) 
(bl) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ A low-cost hotel in a run-down neighborhood of
this capital has become a focus of the FBI investigation into the
bombing at the U.S. Embassy on Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning 12 U.S. agents, accompanied by six Kenyan
detectives, sealed off the three-story Hilltop Lodge, a three-story
hotel popular with Muslim executives.
</P>
<P>
   For two hours the agents combed two rooms on the second floor
for forensic evidence. They dusted for fingerprints, searched the
rooms and seized the hotel logbook and copies of bills, hotel
employees said. The FBI also took the hotel manager, James Nganga,
into custody for questioning. He continued to be held Wednesday
night, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon the investigators returned to take pictures
and videotapes of the rooms, a contractor at the hotel said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. law-enforcement officials declined to comment on what they
had found or why they had searched the hotel. ``The investigation
is proceeding in a logical manner, and no further comment will be
made at this time,'' FBI officials said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   An unconfirmed report Wednesday morning in The Nation newspaper
quoted anonymous police officials and said that a man arrested last
week in Pakistan in connection with the bombing had told
investigators that the car bomb that destroyed the embassy had been
built in the two hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The blast killed 247 people and injured thousands. A
simultaneous explosion outside the U.S. Embassy in Dar es Salaam,
Tanzania, killed 10.
</P>
<P>
   The detained man, Mohammed Saddiq Odeh, 34, was flown here
Friday, after having confessed to Pakistani police that he had
played a major role in planning the attack. When he first came to
the Americans' attention, Odeh reportedly had a slightly different
rendering of his name, Mohammed Sadik Howaida.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the bombings, he was arrested in Karachi on
charges that he was carrying a forged passport, just after he had
arrived on a commercial flight from Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   The raid on the hotel followed a long interrogation of Odeh by
the FBI and police, law-enforcement officials said. The report in
The Nation, which could not be verified, said Odeh had told
investigators that he and three accomplices assembled the bomb at
the hotel from Aug. 3 to Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   What is certain is that Odeh left Nairobi and flew to Pakistan
on the night of Aug. 6 on a Pakistan International Airways flight,
investigators said. According to Kenyan immigration officials, he
was traveling with a forged Yemeni passport under the name Abdull
Bast Awadah. The passport shows that he had entered Kenya on Aug. 3
at the international airport in Mombasa. It is unclear how he
traveled to the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-room hotel is in a seedy downtown section, near bus
companies that travel the route between Mombasa, a coastal port,
and the capital. Owned by a Lebanese family, the hotel is popular
with Arab and Muslim executives from the coast and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Arafad Said Abdalla, whose family owns the hotel, said the FBI
agents did not explain what they were looking for in the rooms,
A107 and B102. The agents dusted for fingerprints on doors,
closets, desks and light switches.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never told us anything,'' Abdalla said. ``They just took
some fingerprints.''
</P>
<P>
   Hotel employees had cleaned the rooms several times since the
week of the bombing, Abdalla said, and some evidence might be lost.
</P>
<P>
   Several employees said they could recall nothing unusual about
the men in the rooms in the days just before the blast, except that
they appeared to have been Muslims from the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Moses Moi, a janitor who cleaned room A107, neat quarters with
twin beds and a desk, said the room was virtually empty each time
when he entered to straighten it on those three days. ``They left
nothing in the room,'' Moi said.
</P>
<P>
   Another janitor, Francis Ishuga, who straightens room B102 each
day, said he saw nothing unusual in the single-bed room in the week
of Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Neither janitor could recall tools, wires, chemicals or any
unusual containers in the rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The co-manager of the hotel, Khalid Saleh, told reporters that
he thought that it was highly unlikely that the bomb had been
constructed there. ``That is something that is not really
possible,'' Saleh said. ``They must have assembled it someplace
else. We'd have noticed.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the employees interviewed Wednesday recalled a
Mitsubishi pickup with a covered bed like the one witnesses say
carried the bomb to the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   A porter, David Kioko, 27, said he carried several heavy bags
for the three men when they checked out Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just like any other guests,'' he told The Associated
Press. ``We cleaned their rooms every day, and they never tried to
stop us from entering.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
