<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2016 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     08-19 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; HILLARY'S REASONS TO REJOICE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At last, the news for which the first lady's been waiting:
``Headbands are acceptable again,'' reports Town &AMP; Country
magazine. Even  &UR; Leonardo DiCaprio &LR;  wears a ``thin metal band to
keep his hair out of his eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   And if that's not reason enough to make merry, the Chicago
Tribune reports that a skillet-throwing contest will be part of
this year's Martha's Vineyard country fair.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. After watching ``Wag the Dog'' (out on videotape) last
weekend, &UR; Stephen Costello &LR;  was amazed to hear a news report that
the United States had sent military personnel to Albania in
response to rumors of threat to the American embassy there. Is this
the winner in the Life Imitating Art competition, or does first
place go to the New York Times online report Monday on the
president's testimony, headed by a banner ad for Viagra?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMING TO A PRESIDENT'S DEFENSE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Monday's item about the behavior of  &UR; Ulysses S. Grant &LR;  in India,
quoted in the Oxford Book of British Political Anecdotes from a
report by his host, Viceroy  &UR; Edward Lytton &LR; , has been loudly
refuted. Readers  &UR; William Robinson &LR; ,  &UR; Mike Rice &LR;  and  &UR; Nick &LR; 
 &UR; Harkins &LR;  cite  &UR; Geoffrey Perret &LR; 's recent biography, ``Ulysses S.
Grant, Soldier and President'' (Random House; $35), which says that
Lord Lytton was a novelist, ``not a politician. He hated India,
despised the Indians, loathed his work, and was feeling at the end
of his tether at the time the Grants showed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Lytton was in the habit of writing his friends fanciful and
often untrue letters, writes Perret, who notes that no other dinner
guest ``suggested it was anything but another dull semiofficial
occasion. Lytton's fantasy may have begun as a scene he played out
in his head that evening, a novelist's way of enduring the
tedium.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Angela Richards &LR; , the 26-year-old daughter of Rolling Stone
 &UR; Keith Richards &LR;  and  &UR; Anita Pallenberg &LR; , has turned down an offer
from her father for his band to play at her wedding, says the New
York Post. Angela, nee Dandelion and raised by her mother in
England, is marrying carpenter  &UR; Dominic Jennings &LR;  in late August.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the set of the forthcoming movie ``The Yards,'' star
 &UR; Faye Dunaway &LR;  is said to have used so much juice for her hair
curlers that technicians had to install a separate power line for
them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fans of  &UR; Michael Crawford  &LR; staged rallies at Warner Bros.
Studios for two days last week, insisting that their hero, who
starred in the stage version of ``Phantom of the Opera,'' be cast
in the movie. Rumor had it that  &UR; John Travolta &LR;  and  &UR; Antonio &LR; 
 &UR; Banderas &LR;  were being considered for the role.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LESS IS MORE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Responding to a ``plain language'' directive,  &UR; Fred Hansen &LR; ,
deputy administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency, sent
staff members a memo urging them to ``expand our plain-language
efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The National Partnership for Reinventing Government (NPR) will
soon provide guidance on implementing the directive,'' wrote
Hansen, whose memo was quoted in the Washington Post. ``I have also
asked the Office of Policy to establish an agency work group to
develop tools to help you comply. You will hear from them through
your regulatory Steering Committee representative or Regional
regulatory contact. Meanwhile, consult the cross-agency Web site
...'' and so on and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   _ Self, a magazine that suggests a chic color scheme (green,
green and nothing but green) for the contents of readers'
refrigerators, lists the ``Top Five Clutter Culprits,'' items that
must be disposed of posthaste: mail, photographs, magazines,
collections and wire hangers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I prefer eating with plastic. I can't use silver cutlery. ...
I like hotels, there's something clean about hotels. I love to be
waited on when they hover all around and do stuff for you. But not
when they put your napkin on your lap. I hate that. I like to keep
it by my plate. If it's all spread out, I don't know what do with
it. Like, where do I hold it? Same with the newspaper. I don't like
to read a paper because you have to spread it all over the place.
... By the way, I like to drink water out of plastic bottles.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Billy Bob Thornton in the Australian journal New Weekly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
