<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the business news stories the Los Angeles Daily News
plans to move for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs
of Thursday, Aug. 20 and thereafter. The stories will carry the
``f'' financial news category code unless otherwise noted. For
questions about stories, contact James Laurin at the Daily News,
(818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   PAX-NETWORK (Los Angeles) _ The Pax Network plans to broadcast
its ``Great Day America'' show daily from Universal Studios
beginning Aug. 31. The fledgling network is converting the Roman
Noodle restaurant into a TV studio overlooking the tourist
attraction and the San Fernando Valley. By Dave McNary.
</P>
<P>
   RETAIL-SALES (Los Angeles) _ Retail sales in L.A. County fell
behind richer neighbors and the state as a whole in 1997,
continuing a trend that has plagued the region in the 1990s and
signaling that consumers may still be feeling the aftermath of the
recession. By Deborah Adamson.
</P>
<P>
   MGM-KERKORIAN (Los Angeles) _ Kirk Kerkorian will buy Seven
Network's stake in Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer for $389 million,
representing a premium of 40 percent above its recent stock price.
The transaction raises his ownership to 89.6 percent. By Dave
McNary.
</P>
<P>
   FHS-PLUMMETS (Los Angeles) _ Shares of Foundation Health Systems
Inc. tumbled as much as 17 percent over concern of a poor earnings
outlook for the fourth-largest publicly held U.S. managed-care
company, analysts said. By Ben Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   TELEMARKET-INDICT (Los Angeles) _ The City Attorney's office
charged seven telemarketing firms, including one company that is
the focus of a federal probe, with violating state regulations that
govern the industry. By Gregory J. Wilcox.
</P>
