<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2032 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MCHALE-ART-NY     08-19 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MCHALE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSMAN CALLS FOR CLINTON RESIGNATION ON FEARS OF `AWFUL
PRECEDENT' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (See also: CLINTON-STARR, CLINTON-POLITICS, CLINTON-VINEYARD,
CLINTON-HEARTLAND, CLINTON-NEWS-MAGS) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By KEVIN SACK    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his six years in Congress, Rep. Paul McHale
developed a reputation as a straight-shooting marine who allows
himself the occasional indulgence of a dramatic gesture.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Democrat from Bethlehem, Pa., was more dramatic
than usual when he became the first and only member of Congress
from his party to call for President Clinton to resign or face
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday in his congressional office, which is
decorated with a gleaming saber and other mementoes from his
service in the Marine Corps, McHale explained that he took his
stand reluctantly after concluding that it would set an ``awful
precedent'' to allow a public official to remain in office after
lying under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Because he is retiring this year after three terms in the House,
McHale has a degree of political liberty not enjoyed by incumbents
running for re-election. He has taken quixotic stands for political
effect in the past, like his call to reduce the number of House
members by a third to make debate more meaningful. And some
Democrats said privately Wednesday that McHale's comments may have
been influenced by disappointment that he wasn't the
administration's choice to be secretary of the Navy, a charge that
McHale vehemently denied.
</P>
<P>
   But as a critic of the president, he also speaks with
credibility because he supported Clinton enthusiastically in both
the 1992 and 1996 elections and then voted to support Clinton's
positions about 75 percent of the time in the House, according to
ratings by Congressional Quarterly. His only significant policy
feud with Clinton came three years ago when he opposed the
administration's deployment of U.S. troops to Bosnia. His district
office in Bethlehem is festooned with photographs of the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have absolutely no personal animosity toward the
president,'' said McHale, a 48-year-old veteran of the Persian Gulf
War. ``I am someone who believes that the president is a man of
enormous talent, genuine love of country, but who possesses some
tragic and equally large flaws.''
</P>
<P>
   McHale, a lawyer who is regarded as a political centrist, said
that Clinton's admitted inappropriate relationship with Monica
Lewinsky, a former White House intern, was ``predatory and
repugnant.'' But he said his call for the president's resignation
was based on legal concerns, not moral ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are to successfully pursue justice in our courts, it is
essential that witnesses feel a personal profound obligation to
tell the truth,'' he said. ``Otherwise we might as well return to
litigation by combat. I think the president breached that
responsibility and if he is not held accountable we establish a
precedent that may encourage some future president, someone more
inclined to abuse power than President Clinton, to once again
violate a judicial oath to tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   In a deposition taken in January, Clinton denied under oath that
he had had a sexual relationship with Ms. Lewinsky. He acknowledged
such a relationship to a federal grand jury on Monday and in a
public address that night, although he maintained that his previous
testimony had been ``legally accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   McHale, who is retiring, acknowledged that few other Democrats
were likely to join him. But he said that most would agree with his
principles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that if a Republican president had engaged in the very
type of misconduct in which President Clinton apparently engaged,
members of the Democratic caucus would be voicing precisely my
arguments with great passion,'' he said. ``We would not have
accepted this from Richard Nixon.''
</P>
<P>
   McHale said he worried that public disgust with the Clinton
scandal would depress voter turnout in the fall, increasing the
chances that he will be succeeded in the 15th District by a
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he hoped he would have had the courage to take the
same stand if he were running for re-election and needed the
support of his party. ``I'll never know,'' he said. ``But I would
like to think so.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
