<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPOT-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Thursday, Aug. 20, and thereafter. If you have any questions,
please call Tina May at (206) 448-8355.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-JUSTICE (Undated) A federal appeals panel handed
Microsoft Corp. another victory Wednesday, saying despositions in
its antitrust dispute with the government should be taken without
reporters or the public present. The judges granted Microsoft's
request that they block a court order issued last week, but didn't
yet rule on the merits of the legal dispute. By the time they do,
however, it may not matter _ the depositions may be over and the
trial set to begin, said an attorney for one of the news
organizations that sought access to the depositions. Separately,
Microsoft was hit Wednesday with a new antitrust action, filed by a
Connecticut company that accuses Microsoft of withholding technical
information vital to its business in order to thwart competition
from other operating systems, such as Unix. Microsoft says the
accuser has improperly elevated a contract dispute to the level of
federal court action.
</P>
<P>
   By Warren Wilson. (story will move in the ``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LOTTERY-BOGUS (Seattle) James Blair Down, the ring leader of a
bogus lottery scam that operated out of Vancouver, B.C., pleads
guilty Wednesday in federal court for fleecing senior citizens of
millions of dollars. Federal agents earlier seized more than $12
million from accounts kept by Down at a Bellevue, Wash., brokerage
house. U.S. postal inspectors identified 880 people with an average
age of 74 who bought lottery chances from Down's companies. Down
was charged with conspiring to violate U.S. gambling laws by
illegally selling chances in international lotteries. He also
allegedly used deceptive practices to get people to buy lottery
tickets when they had no chance of winning. Down's telemarketers
made more than 5 million calls and sent promotional mail targeted
at elderly citizens.
</P>
<P>
   By Scott Sunde. (story will move in the ``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Seattle) Mariners host Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   By Jim Street. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-COLUMN-VECSEY (Seattle) On Alex Rodriguez getting close to
40-40 and why he is so miserable; the Mariners are pretty dead.
</P>
<P>
   By Laura Vecsey. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
