<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, Aug. 20. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-BOMBING (Washington) _ Developments on the status of
Osama bin Laden, the Saudi financier now in Afghanistan who has
become the focus of the U.S. investigation into the bombings of two
U.S. embassies in East Africa. By Tim Weiner, Steven Erlanger and
James Risen. (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   FUNDRAISING-GORE (Washington) _ The issue of Vice President Al
Gore's fund-raising telephone calls has emerged as a focal point of
Attorney General Janet Reno's decision in recent weeks to
reconsider whether to seek the appointment of an independent
prosecutor to investigate fund-raising abuses during President
Clinton's reelection campaign, government officials said. By David
Johnston. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   BBN-CARDS-CUBS (Chicago) _ St. Louis Cardinals at Chicago Cubs:
Sosa and McGwire go at it one more time. By Ira Berkow. (Scheduled
to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``s'' news file.) Story runs under 4-col.
photo.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POLITICS (Washington) _ News analysis: The continuing
political fallout from President Clinton's speech; comparing
reaction from the public at large to the views of political
experts. By Richard L. Berke. (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in
``w'' news file.) 1,120 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   3-col. photo reefer to CABARET reopening at the Kit Kat Club on
West 43rd Street.
</P>
<P>
   GLOBE COLUMNIST (Boston) _ Mike Barnicle, the Boston Globe
columnist who was disciplined earlier this month after he used
George Carlin humor without attribution, resigns after additional
problems are found in his columns. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m.
ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Also see GLOBE-BARNICLE, the Boston Globe's article on the
resignation, and GLOBE-COLUMN, a reprint of the Barnicle 1995
column that prompted the latest inquiry in Barnicle's reporting.)
(For questions about Boston Globe stories, call Frank Perrotta at
the Globe, 617-929-2597.)
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-CROPS (San Jose De Guaviare, Colombia) _ Here in the
coca growing heartland of Colombia, coca growers remain skeptical
of the new Colombian president's plan to end drug growing in rural
areas by bringing in electricity, water and roads. Embittered by
years of confrontation with government authorities, they doubt that
the talk will go anywhere. Any plan's first obstacle may well lie
with the growers themselves. By Diana Jean Schemo. (The story has
moved in ``i'' news file.) 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   reefer: LINCOLN-PHOTO (New York) _ Christie's is scheduled to
auction what may be earliest photo of Lincoln. If the picture, made
around 1843, is of the 16th president, it would be his first
likeness, a major historical discovery. The image in question has
faced all kinds of scrutiny: by a forensic anthropologist, a
criminal identification specialist, a photographer who ``aged'' the
image by computer and two medical experts who analyzed the vein
pattern in the subject's hand. Most of them think it is Lincoln.
But skeptics persist. By Judith Dobrzynski. (The story has moved in
``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   JOBS-DISPLACEMENT (Undated) _ The most comprehensive survey of
permanent layoffs in the United States finds that in the last three
years a smaller percentage of workers were downsized than in any
other period in this decade. But the layoff rate is still
significantly higher than in the 1980s, and women are laid off
almost as often as men. By Louis Uchitelle. (Scheduled to move by
8:30 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.) With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ As more and more companies
choose to reprice their employee stock-option plans, criticism of
the practice grows increasingly vocal. Shareholder activist groups
say option repricings are inherently unfair. Now a tentative
decision reached by the Financial Accounting Standards Board last
week may be the beginning of the end of repricings. By Gretchen
Morgenson. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   NY-HIV-SUSPECT (New York) _ Nushawn Williams, the drifter who
caused a public furor after allegedly leaving a trail of infected
women and girls throughout the state, has been charged for the
first time in an HIV-related case in a rare prosecution for
exposure to the virus that causes AIDS. (Scheduled to move by 9
p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
