<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-COMPARE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves will have powerful obsticles to
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The huge gap has closed. No longer are the Atlanta
Braves far in front as the class of the National League. Several
teams are in hot pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Padres, who begin a two-game series against the
Braves tonight at Turner Field, have emerged as the most likely
threat to Atlanta's long-time supremacy. San Diego began sending
its message to the Braves last week on the West Coast, when it won
two of three games against Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have gotten a lot tougher in the league,'' Atlanta
general manager John Schuerholz said. ``When the Astros got Randy
Johnson, they got even tougher. I think San Diego is a really good
club. And you certainly can't count out the Cubs, Mets and
Giants,'' (who are in the wild-card race).
</P>
<P>
   Any among the Padres, Astros, Cubs and Mets could spell trouble
for the Braves during the NL postseason run. And waiting from the
other league could be the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to have to have your 'A' game ready from day
one,'' Schuerholz said. ``There won't be any slack.''
</P>
<P>
   While it can be said that the Braves are stronger than last
year, with the addition of Andres Galarraga and Walt Weiss, other
clubs, especially the Astros and the Padres, have taken huge leaps
through free-agency. The proof is in the playoff chase. Except for
the strike-shortened '94 season, Atlanta has had the best record in
the league starting with the 1991season. But this year, San Diego
is only two victories behind, Houston six.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other teams set their goals to get strong enough to beat us,''
Schuerholz said. ``This is not me saying this, but other clubs.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is playing better this season against winning teams,
30-19 this season, compared with 36-38 last year. But the Braves
have not fared well against Houston and Chicago, two possible
first-round opponents, going 3-6 against the Cubs and 2-2 against
the Astros. Atlanta also faltered against the Yankees (1-3) and Red
Sox (1-2), two of the best teams in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has happened is that when we have not played great
baseball, other teams like the Yankees and Red Sox have taken
advantage of that,'' third baseman Chipper Jones said. ``But
hopefully, we will get a shot at one of those clubs in October.''
</P>
<P>
   Starter Tom Glavine cited pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at some of the pitchers we have lost to; how many people
are beating them?'' Glavine said. ``The thing about us is when you
have been this good, people are always going to look for something
that is wrong. ... Every time we go out, somebody is trying to
prove something against us,'' he said. ``They use us as a measuring
stick. It might be some young pitcher whose manager tells him,
'After playing the Braves, we will see where you are at.'''
</P>
<P>
   Denny Neagle, who pitched against Atlanta while playing in
Pittsburgh, agrees with Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to get really excited about playing the Braves,''
Neagle said. ``They were the best, and you know you had something
if you beat them. Now I am on the other side and can see the other
clubs feeling the same way I did when I was in Pittsburgh. You see
other teams wanting to prove something to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz sizzles at the notion that his club wilts against
good teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's like those people who said Andres Galarraga couldn't
hit outside Turner Field,'' he said. ``We have beaten good clubs
all year long. We have won more games than anyone else (in the NL),
so that is an inaccurate observation.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine also said he doesn't think San Diego needs to prove
anything by beating the Braves in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they were a good ballclub before we played them last
week,'' he said. ``And I don't think the Padres needed to win two
of three from us to prove to themselves they were a good
ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   But many believe that is exactly what happened last year when
the Marlins took eight of 12 from the Braves in the regular season
before eliminating Atlanta in the NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   So who do the Braves want to face in the first round? More
appropriately, who do they want to avoid?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone wants to see (Houston's) Randy Johnson in
a short series,'' Glavine said. ``But we're not going to take
anybody lightly.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz said: ``We've got a good team, but it's going to be a
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   How the Braves have fared against good teams:
</P>
<P>
   Vs. teams with winning records:
</P>
<P>
   1996 44-31 .587
</P>
<P>
   1997 36-38 .486
</P>
<P>
   1998 30-19 .612
</P>
<P>
   Vs. possible playoff-bound teams:
</P>
<P>
   Padres 4-3
</P>
<P>
   Astros 2-2
</P>
<P>
   Mets 5-0
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers 5-1
</P>
<P>
   Giants 7-1
</P>
<P>
   Cubs 3-6
</P>
<P>
   Yankees 1-3
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox 1-2
</P>
<P>
   Orioles 2-1
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
