<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves on deck: San Diego Padres
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ When: Tonight and Friday at 7:40 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV, radio: WUPN-69 will telecast tonight, TBS will telecast
Friday. WSB 750-AM will broadcast both games.
</P>
<P>
   _ Probable starting pitchers: Tonight, RHP John Smoltz (11-2,
3.32; 12-7, 2.89 lifetime vs. Padres) vs. RHP Kevin Brown (15-4,
2.46; 2-2, 2.81 lifetime vs. Braves). Friday, RHP Kevin Millwood
(14-6, 4.41; 1-0, 5.73 lifetime vs. Padres) vs. RHP Joey Hamilton
(10-10, 4.58; 2-7, 5.49 lifetime vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   _ Series history: Atlanta leads the all-time series 271-215 and
is 29-10 at home against San Diego the last seven years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Past meetings: The Padres took two of three from Atlanta last
week at Qualcomm Stadium on two superb performances by starters
Hamilton and Andy Ashby, who allowed two runs in 14 innings. Only a
shutout by Tom Glavine in the third game averted a sweep. May 7-10,
Atlanta took three of four from the Padres in their first visit to
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   _ Padres leaders: Avg. _ Tony Gwynn (.323); HRs _ Greg Vaugh
(40); RBIs _ Vaughn (96); SBs _ Quilvio Veras (21). Wins _ Andy
Ashby (16); ERA _ Trevor Hoffman (1.60). Saves _ Hoffman (40).
Strikeouts _ Kevin Brown (198).
</P>
<P>
   _ Quickly: The Padres went into Wednesday night's game in
Florida with a 10-6 record this month, but it could be much better.
The pitching staff has yielded an average of 2.6 runs a game. . . .
San Diego is 35-29 on the road. Jockeying for home-field advantage
in the postseason is the only issue in this series and that
advantage would mean more to San Diego. The Braves are 40-22 on the
road this year. . . . While the Pods took two of three from Atlanta
last week, the Braves outhit San Diego 21-16 in that series and
have limited the Padres to a .207 average in their seven meetings
this year. . . . The loss of Tony Gwynn, on the DL since Aug. 13
with a strained left Achilles tendon, has put some stress on the
rest of the Padres batting order, and it has been slow to respond.
Entering Wednesday's game, LF Greg Vaughn had 12 hits in his last
86 at-bats (.140) with 30 strikeouts in his last 20 games. 3B Ken
Caminiti was forced from Monday's game with a recurring lower-back
strain, which affects only his right-handed swing. He will be
facing two righties this series. . . . With Gwynn out, the club is
starting Mark Sweeney against right-handers and either James Mouton
or Ruben Rivera against lefties. . . . The Braves had dodged RHP
Kevin Brown in their first seven games with the Padres. They have
not seen Brown since he was 2-0 against them in October's NLCS. He
is coming off his third shutout of the season in Sunday's 4-0
victory over Milwaukee and has two shutouts in his last three
starts. In his last 57 innings, Brown has struck out 68 and allowed
46 hits and has lost just once in his last 16 starts, dating to May
26. . . . On the DL: Gwynn (strained left achilles), LHP Ed Vosberg
(left shoulder surgery).
</P>
<P>
   _ Who's hot: 2B Quilvio Veras is hitting .357 over his last
eight games. RHP Trevor Hoffman is 40-for-41 in save conversions
and leads the majors. San Diego is 158-0 when leading after eight
innings, dating back to July 24, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   _ Who's not: Vaughn finally hit his 40th homer Tuesday, after
going 11 games and 40 at-bats without one. He is batting .179 over
the past 10 days. CF Steve Finley has two hits in his last 24
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
