u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QAFOWLER-COX     08-19 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QAFOWLER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q and A with U.S. Ambassador Wyche Fowler
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wyche Fowler arrived in Saudi Arabia not long after a
deadly bombing at a U.S. military facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we bombed Iraq three days after I got there,'' the U.S.
ambassador to the Saudi kingdom said this week.
</P>
<P>
   And so it has gone since the former Democratic senator from
Georgia assumed his post in Riyadh two years ago this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had several major standups and standdowns with Saddam
Hussein since I have been there,'' Fowler said. ``We have a
continuing threat of terrorism. And we always have serious
questions on how to improve the life of our troops there in that
145 degree desert and yet keep them combat ready and secure from
any terrorist attack. So there's never been a dull day. When things
are too quiet, my instinct is to sense a lull before the storm.'
</P>
<P>
   En route to Washington for consultation with government
officials, Fowler talked about his experiences in a posting that
has been intense but always interesting during a brief visit to
Atlanta this week. Here are excerpts from that conversation:
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has security been heightened at your embassy since the
bombings in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam?
</P>
<P>
   A: We have been on great alert for quite a time because of Osama
bid Laden's public threats againt civilians and the military in
Saudi Arabia, which he issued about two months ago on television
calling for the first time that it was legitimate to kill American
civilians to attack American civilians as well as military. The
Saudis have been extraordinarly cooperative in providing us
external security as well as the shared intelligence to protect
ourselves to the greatest possible extent.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden went further than anyone could have believed when he
publicly urged his followers to declare a holy war against
Americans and specifically included civilians as targets as well as
military. He's thought to be hiding out in Afghanistan but the
investigation is ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously because of his proclamation against Americans he is
certainly under suspicion (in connection with the African
bombings). It's unquestioned to all the people in the intelligence
business that if you've got two bombs going off within a minute of
each other in two different countries that that requires a degree
of sophistication that only a handful of terrorist organizations
could probably accomplish. That doesn't mean there is not a new one
that has emerged. But it was a very sophisticated operation.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you update us on the relationship between the United
States and Saudi Arabia and your mission there?
</P>
<P>
   A: We have a unique bilateral relationship with the Kingdom of
Saudi Arabia that goes back over 50 years now. We've had a unique
path of development in our relations. It began with the American
companies discovering oil in Saudi Arabia, and it has broadened to
include now most of the American multinational giants doing an
extraordinary amount of trade and business with the Kingdom. As a
result there are over 50,000 Americans working in Saudi Arabia
across the whole gamut of business activitiy, of which the energy
and oil sector has been reduced to well under 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   We also have between 5,000 and 6,000 American military forces
stationed in Saudi Arabia at a given time, as well as a huge
training mission whereby we train the Saudi military and air force
with sophisticated weaponry that they have bought from us.
</P>
<P>
   And in the political-diplomatic arena, we build on the excellent
relationship that we have had with the Saudi government over the
years. At present there are two major goals: how we finally bring
peace to the Middle East and how we fight terrorism, which is the
present scourge as recent as this month's bombings in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's been most difficult about your job?
</P>
<P>
   A: Because of my responsibility for security of all my people as
well as the security, to the greatest extent I can provide it, of
the Americans working in the Kingdom, it has been a large
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How would you characterize the level of tension in the Middle
East today?
</P>
<P>
   A: It is undoubtedly in America's interest to have a politically
secure and economically vibrant Middle East. We believe that the
key to that success is a peace process that leads to a final end to
Israeli-Palestinian hostilities. There's no question that the
greatest springboard to economic succss anywhere in the gulf is a
cessation of all hostilities. But there will remain political
instability of some sort throughout the region until those
governments in the gulf have confidence that peace in the region
will be long term.
</P>
<P>
   The Arab states do believe that we have a disproportinate
influence with the Israeli government. But what it is very hard for
any Arab government to understand is the nature of democracy _ that
another country cannot dictate to a democracy what their policies
should be or what security needs they believe are required for
thier own interests.
</P>
<P>
   Our goal should be to not allow ourselves to be isolated with
just one friend but to maintain our historic ties with the nation
of Israel and at the same time by our policies and actions convince
the Saudis and our other allies in the gulf that they are an equal
partner with us on regional interests and global interests.
</P>
<P>
   Q: To what extent must embassies be armed fortresses?
</P>
<P>
   A: Americans are open and we like to think an embassy is an
invitation to foreign citizens to come and learn about America _ as
they do. They come seeking guidance on which colleges they should
go to. They come seeking guidance on business opportunities and how
to find a joint venture partner. They come seeking every kind of
information _ where to find the best stamp collection. It is a
balance and, depending on where you are, you take appropriate
measures to secure your people from harm but without trying to make
that little corner of America look like an armed fortress.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the main things you want to accomplish in Saudi
Arabia?
</P>
<P>
   A: I hope that first of all, God willing, there will be no
terrorist attack under my stewardship, and we reinvigorate
ourselves every day with fresh eyes to see what can be done to
protect the people and the families who are there, both in the
embassy and the private American community. I hope that we will
succeed in training through our military Saudi armed forces to such
an extent that they can defend themselves without question from any
regional threat, including Saddam Hussein. And of course I hope to
bring to the Kingdom a better understanding of the economic and
political fruits of moving toward democratization and the
unquestioned insurance of human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
