<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2072 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOB-HEARING-BOS &LR;      08-19 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOB-HEARING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-FBI AGENT DEFENDS WARNING INFORMANT ABOUT MURDER THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A former FBI supervisor testified Wednesday that he saw
no contradiction in warning mobster and informant Angelo ``Sonny''
Mercurio that he was marked for murder even as he was on the run
from federal criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   Edward M. Quinn, a retired organized crime supervisor, also
insisted that he ``would have done the same'' for the reputed
gangsters seated across from him in a federal courtroom. That
remark prompted an incredulous smirk from the man on the far left,
New England Mafia boss Francis P. Salemme.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI never told Salemme that it had information in 1989 that
he was being targeted for assassination in a Mob power struggle. He
was shot and wounded outside a Saugus pancake house on June 16 of
that year.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Quinn recalled efforts by him and other agents to
warn Mercurio that he had been targeted because his mob cohorts
believed he had tipped off the FBI to an October 1989 Mafia
induction ceremony that the agency secretly recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Salemme's lawyer, Anthony M. Cardinale, as well as attorneys for
Salemme's codefendants _ Winter Hill Gang leader Stephen J. Flemmi,
fellow gangster John Martorano, and mob soldier Robert DeLuca _ are
trying to show that the FBI didn't look too hard for Mercurio.
Instead, agents went out of their way to warn him of the threat.
</P>
<P>
   Mercurio got special treatment, the defense lawyers suggest,
because he had provided the Boston office of the FBI with perhaps
its biggest coup: entree into the secret induction ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The theory underpins one of the central issues before US
District Judge Mark L. Wolf: whether to drop three-year-old
extortion and racketeering charges against Flemmi because, as he
claims, he was promised immunity from prosecution in exchange for
information he provided the FBI during three decades of sporadic
informing.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi is expected be the final witness when he takes the stand
this morning, detailing his years as a top FBI informant.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn, who headed the organized crime squad from 1990 until his
retirement in 1995, said he contacted retired FBI agent John
Connolly, who had been Mercurio's handler, when he learned on July
5, 1991, that Mercurio's life had been threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn said Connolly was in the best position to know how to get
word to Mercurio. But Quinn testified that he never knew if
Mercurio had been warned.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning by Cardinale, Quinn rejected the suggestion
that the FBI's actions were contradictory: protecting a fugitive
instead of pursuing him. Another FBI agent has testified that
Mercurio was spotted at a holiday barbeque the day before Quinn
learned of the death threat but was not arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Mercurio remained free until 1994, when he was arrested in
Georgia on drug charges.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn acknowledged that the bureau did not follow up on
information from the US Drug Enforcement Administration that put
Mercurio in Los Angeles as a participant in a cross-country drug
dealing operation in summer 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Questioned by Flemmi's lawyer, Kenneth J. Fishman, Quinn said he
didn't recall a courtroom encounter with Flemmi after he was
arraigned on extortion and racketeering charges in early 1995.
According to Fishman, Flemmi said to Quinn, ``Hey, how about a
break on bail?'' suggesting that the FBI had agreed to go easy on
him because of his work as an informant.
</P>
<P>
   But under cross-examination by Assistant US Attorney Brian T.
Kelly, Quinn said he didn't know anyone at the bureau who had
authorized Flemmi to commit crimes or promised him immunity.
</P>
<P>
   When Flemmi was arrested, ``Did he ask, `What's going on here, I
was authorized to commit crimes?'''Kelly asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Quinn replied.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
