<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2073 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS20-COX     08-19 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons Q&AMP;A with Ray Buchanan
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cornerback Ray Buchanan had a lot to do with the
Falcons' improvement in the defensive backfield last year.
Buchanan's five interceptions helped Atlanta improve from last in
the NFL in interceptions with six in 1996 to sixth in the NFL last
season with 17. He and quarterback Chris Chandler were the first
major acquisitions by coach Dan Reeves. Buchanan joined the team
when the Colts refused to match Atlanta's four-year, $13-million
offer. He has 21 interceptions in his 5-year career. Buchanan, a
smooth-talking Chicago native, has made Mr. Blackwell's annual
best-dressed list and is active in local charities. He recorded his
first album during the winter. Buchanan, 26, sat down recently with
Journal-Constitution beat writer Matt Winkeljohn.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: You took offense a couple weeks ago when a caption under
your picture said you were ``burned'' by a rookie receiver in
practice. Do you think media rules are different for star players?
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan: It seems like (star players) are fair game. If (the
media) attack a star player it will get a lot more attention. Take,
for instance, (quarterback) Chris (Chandler) when he was going
through his (injury) situation. The media was quick to jump on him.
It was something he really couldn't control. But people were
questioning his toughness. How could he control when he's going to
get hit or when he's not?
</P>
<P>
   AJC: But isn't a higher degree of scrutiny a price you expect to
pay as a very highly paid star athlete?
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan: I believe every athlete who steps on the field should
be accountable for his mistakes; he should be his own worst critic.
We knew what we were getting into as far as the realm of
professional football. It comes with the game . . . . How well can
you handle criticism, and not place blame on someone else? Still,
how could (Chandler) control things when his head gets rapped off
the turf?
</P>
<P>
   AJC: Please elaborate on the importance of self-accountability.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan: You've got to take a lot of personal pride in your
job. A lot of guys can't handle pressure and point fingers at
somebody else. I think about 70 percent of the (rookies) are good
enough physically to make it, but . . . do they have the courage?
To me, it's 80 percent mental at this level.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: What do you mean mental? Are you talking preparation or
reading keys and such during games?
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan: Both. You will get eaten up at this level as a
defensive back if you go out thinking you can get by on athletic
skill alone . . . not knowing what the (receiver) can do, what's
he's going to try to do to set you up for later in the game, things
like that.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: Given that, how aggravating is it to see teammates with
remarkable athletic abilities who just can't seem to apply them on
the field?
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan: It's tremendously frustrating. I talk to people who
have the physical talent and just mentally don't get the job done.
The coaches have said something so many times, and then veterans
try to step in, but sometimes it just blows over their heads. You
look at some guys with all the physical tools and say, 'Darn, if I
had that body and my brain, I'd be in the Pro Bowl 13 straight
years.' It seems like kids today can't take getting coached real
hard. When I was coming up, coaches would curse at you, yell, do
anything, and you'd strive not to hear that voice again. Today,
it's like they believe everything they hear, and you have to be
cautious not to say too much because they'll believe they can't do
it. But you don't want to spoon-feed them, either. There comes a
point where you just got to let them go.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: Give a quick assessment of 35-year-old free safety Eugene
Robinson and 32-year-old strong safety William White.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan: People say they're a couple of old guys, but they're
so smart they put themselves in position where they don't have to
move that much. And they communicate very well, which is a great
thing.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: My car goes into the shop Sept. 8 for repairs. Which one of
yours can I borrow?
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan: You can definitely have the (Mercedes) 500SL
convertible. It's platinum and silver. It'll be great for you and
your wife to ride around town in with the top down.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
