<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTEBOOK20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pittsburgh zone blitz to challenge offense
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the Atlanta Falcons set their preseason schedule,
they had no intention of playing the Pittsburgh Steelers, but the
NFL asked kindly if the Falcons would please play them instead of
Tampa Bay. Something about wanting more NFC-AFC matchups.
</P>
<P>
   So Atlanta will travel to Morgantown, W.Va., Saturday to face
one of just three teams in the league that uses a 3-4 alignment as
its base defense. And don't even get offensive line coach Art Shell
started about the zone blitz the Steelers play better than anybody
else.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons had enough trouble picking up a conventional blitz
Friday against Detroit. And now this?
</P>
<P>
   ``When they come with the zone blitz, the idea is you got to
figure out where they're coming from,'' said Shell, who for perhaps
the first time in training camp got loud Tuesday while working with
the linemen on blitz pickups.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may only bring five people, but where are they coming
from? You got to get your line and your backs coordinated, and your
quarterback has to get the line in the right protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Just facing a three-man front is different enough, especially
when it's not a three-man front. Both outside linebackers are on
the line most of the time, and until the ball is snapped, it's
often unclear which man is coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different because you're working against a four-man front
all of training camp, and all of a sudden here comes the 3-4,''
Shell said after a two-hour and 15-minute practice that focused on
special teams and blitz pickups. ``They bring different people, it
might be five, it might be six, they might drop a defensive lineman
in (pass) coverage, they're always slanting somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to get you sometimes because of the way they
slant, but hopefully, sometimes you get them, too.''
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, this might work out well for the Falcons. They
play another of the teams that relies on the 3-4 next week when the
Bengals come to town, and then they go to Carolina _ the other base
3-4 team _ for the regular-season opener Sept. 6, and the Panthers
come to Atlanta Oct. 4, in the fourth game.
</P>
<P>
   What's next?
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons will practice once a day from now on, including a 3
p.m. practice today. Training camp officially breaks today, meaning
veterans no longer are required to stay at the Falcon Inn motel
adjacent to the team's Suwanee headquarters. Rookies, however,
aren't going anywhere. There will be one practice Thursday and
Friday before Saturday's game against the Steelers in Morgantown,
W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   Turning up the heat
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was ``On the Border'' night in the cafeteria, as there
was a Mexican-style food line with beef, chicken and shrimp
fajitas, refried beans, rice, salsa and pico de gallo all
complemented with a three-man mariachi band. The players love this,
in part because it signifies the last official day of training
camp.
</P>
<P>
   QB watch
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at what's going on with the quarterbacks:
</P>
<P>
   Chris Chandler _ Threw in drills, and worked with all three
units.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Graziani _ Threw in drills, and worked with the first two
units. Also had holding duties with placekickers.
</P>
<P>
   Steve DeBerg _ Same as Graziani.
</P>
<P>
   John Dutton _ Used only in drills.
</P>
<P>
   The good, bad and ugly
</P>
<P>
   Good: In the hurry-up offense drill at the end of practice,
6-foot-7 tight end O.J. Santiago jumped to catch a pass at the left
sideline from Chandler and held on although linebacker Cornelius
Bennett was trying to rip it loose.
</P>
<P>
   Bad: WR Jammi German dropped a nice pass in the left flat from
Chandler in 11-on-11 work.
</P>
<P>
   Ugly: Rookie reserve left guard Bob Hallen nearly whiffed
completely against defensive tackle Shawn Swayda in one-on-one
drills, as Swayda had an almost clear path to Dutton.
</P>
<P>
   What he said
</P>
<P>
   ``(Starting right cornerback) Ronnie Bradford. I knew nothing
about him, but I can see he's a real student of the game. He has
the athletic ability to get it done at corner, but one day he is
going to be a free safety, and a very good one. He really works at
understanding everything.'' _ free safety Eugene Robinson, when
asked which member of the secondary has most surprised him since he
joined the team from Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Aches and pains
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Ron Medlin didn't report any new injuries. Here's who
missed practice with old injuries: DT Mark Campbell (knee), DT
William Gaines (back, knee), S Devin Bush (knee), WR Corey Allen
(knee/ankle), DE Barry Mitchell (elbow) and OT Nate Miller (nerve
problem in shoulder).
</P>
<P>
   I've seen you before
</P>
<P>
   There will be several familiar faces on the Steelers sideline,
including rookie receiver Hines Ward, late of the University of
Georgia, and safety Lethon Flowers, formerly of Georgia Tech. The
roster also will include former Falcons K Norm Johnson, TE Mitch
Lyons, TE Troy Sadowski (who also played at Georgia) and RB Richard
Hundley.
</P>
<P>
   Ward leads the Steelers in receiving, with nine catches for 99
yards, and he could see more time in the return game Saturday
because of injuries to Henry Bailey and Jahine Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Steelers' offensive coordinator Ray Sherman was the
Falcons' offensive coordinator in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
