<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2078 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-1STLD     08-19 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-$ADV23-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PRESIDENCY WILL SURVIVE REGARDLESS OF CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 23)   (EDs: FIXES quote in 6th graf, adding the word ``innocent.'')  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This summer the most compelling drama in movie
theaters is ``Saving Private Ryan,'' Steven Spielberg's
excruciating depiction of death on the bloody beaches of Normandy,
while the most compelling drama on the political stage is ``Saving
Bill Clinton,'' the embarrassing saga of sex and the president's
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   On the screen, Ryan survives the brutality of World War II. On
the national scene, Clinton's fate remains in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The link between these events is the fact that they cast new
perspectives on institutions that have protected liberty and
sustained the republic since its birth _ war and the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The Spielberg film offers the most graphic and honest
re-creation of the horror of the World War II Normandy invasion
ever shown in a professional movie. The Clinton drama is less
graphic, less honest and, therefore, less persuasive than the tale
of a squad of soldiers trying to find and protect a private whose
three brothers already have been killed in action.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Spielberg replaced the glory of war with the gore of
war, Clinton simply sought, in his brief televised address to the
nation after his grand jury testimony last week, to gloss over
incredibly irresponsible actions _ first the sexual encounters with
Monica Lewinsky and then, for seven months, his public denial of
those encounters. He conceded that he had misled the people and his
wife, but he did not really apologize for doing so.
</P>
<P>
   His confession failed to answer key questions about his conduct
and his veracity. And, in a self-serving move, Clinton sought to
blame Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr for an investigation that
``has gone on too long, cost too much and hurt too many innocent
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's contention that Starr's probe now must end sounded
like an echo of Richard Nixon's repeated refrain at the beginning
of 1974 that ``one year of Watergate is enough.'' Investigators
refused to bow to Nixon's plea for an end to the inquiry, and seven
months later he forced to resign the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Clinton did nor reach further back into history and
attempt to picture his labrador retriever Buddy as a reincarnation
of the ``little dog Checkers'' that Nixon described so emotionally
in a 1952 TV appearance. Then, he was defending the fact that
wealthy Californians were providing funds to help sustain him in
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   There may be ample reason to criticize Starr's investigation,
but Clinton's stonewalling is to blame for much of the length of
the probe.
</P>
<P>
   His confession was far from a total loss, however. Interviews
with people around the nation indicated that a majority of
Americans continue to approve his handling of the presidency
despite the reckless manner in which he conducts his private life.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, no matter what happens to Clinton between now and Jan. 20,
2001, the presidency will remain a powerful force.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 200 years, it has survived crisis after crisis. It
was not destroyed by the forced resignation of Richard Nixon, the
assassinations of Abraham Lincoln and John F. Kennedy, the
departure from the White House of Theodore Roosevelt or the death
in wartime of his distant cousin, Franklin D. Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Lyndon Johnson steered the nation safely through the days of
tragedy following Kennedy's death. Gerald Ford accomplished a
similar feat after Nixon's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   But as an institution, the presidency is stronger than anyone
who occupies the post. Turbulent events or weak and duplicitous
leaders can diminish its authority but only for a brief period. The
right person coming to office at the right time can breathe new
life into the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   After the bitter, often violent, division over Vietnam that led
Johnson to reject a bid for reelection in 1968, the Watergate
scandal that forced Nixon's resignation and the Iran hostage crisis
that magnified Jimmy Carter's ineptitude, the presidency was in
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Some learned Americans wrote books and articles suggesting that
the time had come to reform the office and possibly divide up its
authority. The thinking was that the world was too big and complex
for one person to handle such an all-encompassing post.
</P>
<P>
   Then Ronald Reagan sauntered into the White House and
demonstrated that the presidency was as strong and vibrant as it
ever had been. He did so by communicating brilliantly with the
people, exuding self-confidence, enunciating a limited policy
agenda that he could implement and standing firm against the ``evil
empire'' of communism.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Iran-contra scandal of the late 1980s, which led to
critics to suggest his impeachment, failed to diminish Reagan's
standing with the public.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy of Clinton's presidency is that he had a grand
opportunity to lead a prosperous and peaceful nation triumphantly
into the 21st century. Now that opportunity has faded. Many people
who once trusted him no longer feel they can.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton might learn from his friend Spielberg that there is
profit in honesty. With the passage of time, World War II _ the
seminal event of the 20th century _ has become wreathed in
nostalgia that is stripped away in Spielberg's film.
</P>
<P>
   The president also could learn something from the 19th century
French writer Henri-Frederic Amiel: ``Truth is the secret of
eloquence and of virtue, the basis of moral authority; it is the
highest summit of art and of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as a good Democrat, Clinton just might ponder some words
uttered in 1932 by Franklin D. Roosevelt: ``The presidency is ...
preeminently the place of moral leadership.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
