<SLUG> BC-FBC-GASOUTHERN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Road to College Football _ Georgia Southern
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATESBORO, Ga. _ During a recent Georgia Southern practice, a
man on the senior side of 65 stood in the shadows of a goalpost at
Paulson Stadium chomping on the remains of a cigar and watching
intensely as players moved from drill to drill.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're looking at a pretty good team,'' he told a visitor.
</P>
<P>
   Erk Russell, never known to exaggerate or overwork superlatives,
should know a pretty good team when he sees one. After all, he's
coached his share of them, including the 15-0 Georgia Southern
Division I-AA championship team in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years later, another Russell is on a Georgia Southern staff
expected to return the program to the level of success it enjoyed
in the '80s. Erk's son, Rusty, is the defensive coordinator for
head coach Paul Johnson, who himself was an assistant to the senior
Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Southern is picked as a favorite for not only its second
Southern Conference title in a row but also perhaps a national
championship, largely because of its explosive offense.
</P>
<P>
   But whether the Eagles live up to such expectations probably
depends more on how well Rusty Russell and his staff can fashion
this '98 unit into the likeness of its immediate predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 Eagles gave up an average of 330 yards in total offense
a game, but the 10-3 team led the conference in scoring defense
(17.6 points a game) and turnover margin.
</P>
<P>
   Graduation took several key components of that defense,
including all-star linebackers Chad Nighbert and D.T. Tanner and
three starters in the deep secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, as it's laid out, we're starting two seniors at
defensive end, and that's it,'' Russell said. ``Everybody else is
an underclassman. So we're not a mature defense right now. We've
got to cover some ground in that area, but we have some talent.''
</P>
<P>
   The experienced part of that talent is in the front line, where
all-star candidate Eric Davis (6-3, 260) and Benjy Harris (6-3,
238) will line up at the ends, with preseason all-conference pick
Voncellies Allen (5-11, 286) somewhere between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can be better than last year, when everything is in
place _ when the younger players learn the system and get used to
the speed of games,'' said Allen, part of a group that managed 30
quarterback sacks last season. ``Until then, it's going to be up to
the three of us to take up the slack.''
</P>
<P>
   The most experienced linebacker is sophomore Daryl Morrell (5-9,
180). Also expected to help at that position is redshirt freshman
Jason Neese (6-0, 213).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're the weak link on the defense, but I will
admit that we lack experience,'' said Morrell, who started eight
games and was involved in 65 tackles last season. ``We still have
people who played, so we know what's going on. In fact, I feel like
this group is faster and quicker, and we'll be able hold our own.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Southern hopes that speed can compensate for experience,
especially in the secondary, where Atlantan Earthwind Moreland and
Kilwaukee Thomas of Perry will line up at the corners.
</P>
<P>
   Moreland, a junior, has been clocked at 4.31 in the 40-yard
dash, fastest on the team, ahead of Thomas at 4.42. As Georgia
Southern tries to find players to find a tackle, a linebacker and
two safeties, Russell hopes that a standard set last season will be
ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that we established a tradition that we're going to
run to the ball and play harder than anybody we face,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Southern's offense produced 401 yards and 32.5 points a
game last year and is expected to be just as potent _ or more.
Junior quarterback Greg Hill, who rushed for 1,172 yards and 18
touchdowns, should have a greater grasp of Johnson's offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody can stop our offense,'' Allen said.
``But I'm sure some people will take our defense lightly. Hey, if
they do, that'll just be to our advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is hoping that the two units will complement each other
enough that Eagle fans will return to Paulson Stadium for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, there were a lot of people who said, ``Let's wait
and see,'' and it'll probably be that way this year,'' Johnson
said. ``But I think the expectation level has risen back to where
it was before. That can be good and bad, but if it will help bring
the fans back, I'm all for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming Friday: Central Florida
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
