<SLUG> BC-FBN-BROWNS-OWNERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Potential Browns buyers to vie for team until Chicago meeting
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The high-stakes ``Countdown to Cleveland'' started
officially here Wednesday when NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue
announced that the owner of the resurrected Browns franchise will
be selected on Sept. 8 at a special league meeting in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   In the 19 days leading to the vote, the level of politicking by
the seven candidate groups that made presentations to the
membership at a hotel near the Atlanta airport could be fierce. And
bids, which can be revised several times during the next 19 days,
figure to start high and grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always worry that someone is going to go crazy on the
price,'' said John Murdough, one of the seven candidates. Another
candidate Dick Jacobs, who also owns the Cleveland Indians, said,
``You can't grow trees through the sky. There's a limit to
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't try telling that to incumbent owners Jerry Jones of Dallas
and Tampa Bay's Malcolm Glazer, who still think a $1 billion price
tag is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Their rationale is that the reborn Browns will generate record
revenues and, because of a generous stocking plan approved last
month, be competitive quickly. Although owners have been asked by
the league not to speculate on the franchise fee, the consensus
among those who were asked Wednesday was that it will be between
$600 million and $800 million.
</P>
<P>
   Al Lerner, once a minority stockholder in the old Browns and the
unofficial favorite to get the new club, noted that such a fee will
squeeze profits.
</P>
<P>
   The league will present at least two finalists on Sept. 8, and
one of them must be the group with the highest bid. It will take a
three-fourths vote of the membership, or 23 of 30 teams, to select
the owner of the new Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
