<HEADER>
A2095 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MACON-COX     08-19 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MACON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marcus Giles' big season
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACON, Ga. _ Marcus Giles, then 11 years old, burst into tears
when older brother Brian wasn't taken until the second day and the
17th round of the 1989 baseball draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so upset I went to my room and cried for a long time,''
the Macon Braves second baseman recalled. ``I couldn't believe no
one saw how good he was. I knew he was going to be a
major-leaguer.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Marcus was eligible for the draft in 1996, Brian had
proved his brother right by making the Cleveland Indians. But
Marcus was about to find out just how fickle, and often cruel, the
inexact process of predicting success in pro baseball can be.
</P>
<P>
   Like his brother a standout at Granite Hills High School in El
Cajon, Calif., Marcus expected to be taken the first day. He
wasn't. Then, he thought he surely would go early the second day.
Wrong again.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,500 players were selected before Marcus was finally
picked in the 53rd round by Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a horrible few days for the whole family,'' said Monica
Giles, the boys' mother. ``It was always Marcus' dream to play in
the majors like Brian. He was crushed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Marcus didn't cry this time. He decided to get even.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marcus said he was going to make everyone regret passing him
over,'' said his father, Bill. ``It really became a driving force
for him. He was determined to prove everyone wrong. He still is.''
</P>
<P>
   Although only 5-feet-8, Giles has hit 35 homers, a Macon record
and five off the South Atlantic League mark. After hitting .348 as
a first-year player last season in the Appalachian League, he is
batting .333 at Macon and has driven in a league-best 102 runs.
Giles' 73 extra-base hits are a league record.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad start for a draft afterthought who wasn't even offered
a contract by the Braves until he completed a season in junior
college. After hitting .489 with 20 homers for Grossmont College,
his stock had risen enough to receive a bonus of approximately
$75,000 to sign just before the 1997 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza lasted until the 62nd round in 1988. Giles may be
the biggest goof since.
</P>
<P>
   ``The draft is a joke,'' said Giles, unable or unwilling to put
the bitterness aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scouts disgust me. All they care about is how tall you are or
how fast you can run. What about being a baseball player? Doesn't
that count for anything? The scouts think they have it down to a
science, and they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   The last second baseman to hit Macon with such a passion to
prove others wrong was Pete Rose, who wowed fans at Luther Williams
Field with his hustle in1962 before going on to become baseball's
all-time hits leader.
</P>
<P>
   Rose was willing to put in as many extra hours of batting and
fielding practice as it took to reach the major leagues. So is
Giles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be 100 degrees out, and Marcus will get here two
hours early to work on ground balls or take extra batting
practice,'' manager Brian Snitker said. ``I had Mark Lemke when he
was coming up, and Marcus reminds me of the Lemmer. He wears us
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially coach Glenn Hubbard, who leaves his Stone Mountain
home shortly after breakfeast many days to put in extra time with
Giles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get stuck in traffic I hear about it from him,'' Hubbard
said. ``He wants to know why I'm late. And the game isn't for four
or five hours.''
</P>
<P>
   As an Atlanta Brave for10 seasons, Hubbard was one of the
best-fielding second basemen in the National League. His pairing
with Giles didn't come by accident. Who better to take a raw former
outfielder and refine him into a sure-handed infielder?
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first met Marcus, he said, 'I'm horrible. I need your
help,''' Hubbard remembers. ``It's taken a lot of work, but you
won't find a more improved defensive player in the league. He isn't
affraid to have the ball hit to him. He wants it _ even a high
chopper over the mound, which used to give him a lot of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Giles made 20 errors in the first half of the season. He's made
five since.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we played them early in the season, he had some glaring
deficiencies, and I thought he might have to change positions,''
said Augusta coach Jeff Treadway, a second baseball with the Braves
and four other teams. ``Now he makes the plays and is as good as
anyone in the league at turning the doubleplay.''
</P>
<P>
   Giles, a muscled 185-pounder who lifts weights six days a week
in the offeason, has dominated at the plate from opening day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may not be very tall, but he can hit a ball a long way,''
Snitker said. ``He's hit a couple balls into the light towers. His
home runs are definitely not a fluke. He's a very good hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Giles won the home-run derby at the South Atlantic League
all-star festivities, then took MVP honors with a game-winning
single. He is one of the leading candidates to be named the league
MVP. Chipper Jones and Andruw Jones are the only two Macon Braves
to be so honored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scouts miss on some players,'' admitted Paul Snyder, the
Braves' director of scouting and player development. ``Marcus
always had a good bat, but he wasn't as strong coming out of high
school as he is now, and he didn't have a postition. He's put in a
lot of work to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   And Snyder doesn't mind if Giles keeps a chip on his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to have a little (attitude),'' Synder said.
``Especially when you are his size. That will help you to the major
leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   That's where brother Brian is waiting. The two always have been
close, and Marcus would visit Brian regularly as he was working his
way up with the Indians. Brian visited Macon during the All-Star
break but didn't get to see the M-Braves play, because of a
rainout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew he could hit, but you don't ever expect home-run
numbers like this from a second baseman,'' said Brian, who hit 17
homers for Cleveland last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scouts wouldn't believe me, but I've always said that Marcus
was a better hitter than Brian,'' their father said. ``That wasn't
anything against Brian. That's just how good I think Marcus swings
the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard agrees. He'll take some of the credit for Marcus'
improved fielding. But not his hitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``God gave him a special gift,'' Hubbard. ``I'm not going to do
anything to mess that up.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
