A2099 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-TOPPICK-COX     08-19 0330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-TOPPICK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Top picks not always instant hits
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACON, Ga. _ Being a first-round draft choice means instant
riches. But it also guarantees high expectations and extra
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Some players, such as Chipper Jones and Steve Avery, quickly
live up to the advanced billing. Many don't.
</P>
<P>
   Jacob Shumate, 22, was Atlanta's first-round pick in 1994. Now
in his fifth season, the right-hander is still in Class A and has
won four games _ one prior to this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has as good stuff as anyone in this league,'' Macon
pitching coach Mark Ross said. ``But you have to be able to throw
the ball over the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Shumate, 3-4 with a 7.71 ERA, finally is starting to do so after
spending two weeks in June working with special assistant Guy
Hansen at Atlanta's complex in Orlando. Mark Wohlers was part of
some of the same sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting to feel more comfortable,'' said Shumate, who
signed for $500,000 but has averaged nearly two walks per inning in
his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``With someone who can throw like Shumate, you wait as long as
you can and hope something finally clicks,'' said Paul Snyder, the
Braves' director of scouting and player development.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Cameron, the Braves' first-round pick in 1997, also is at
Macon. In his first full season after signing out of high school
for $825,000, Cameron has committed 59 errors _ the most in the
minors _ and struck out 152 times. Better in the field after being
moved from shortstop to third base at midseason, Cameron is hitting
.214 with 19 homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tough league to play in when you're 19 and only a
year out of high school,'' Macon manager Brian Snitker said.
``Cameron will be all right. Other players have made a lot of
errors in this league, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, for example. He formerly held the Macon record with 56
errors in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
