<SLUG> BC-EMBASSY-SUSPECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAUDI MILLIONAIRE SEEN AS CHIEF SUSPECT IN EMBASSY BOMBINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Osama bin Laden declared war quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Huddled in his military training compound in the Afghan
mountains, he calmly presented his holy attack on America as a
matter of fact as machine gunfire crackled outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not differentiate between those dressed in military
uniforms and civilians,'' bin Laden told ABC News in June, in a
rare interview with a Western reporter. ``They are all targets in
this `fatwa,''' or death edict.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 7, when twin bombs exploded near two United States
Embassies in Africa, that message reverberated throughout the State
Department. Bin Laden was an immediate suspect. And with the arrest
of his alleged associate, Mohammed Sadiq Odeh, the bombing
investigation this week focused squarely on the elusive Saudi
Arabian millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   The flood of FBI agents into Africa in the wake of the bombing
was but the latest episode in a much longer relationship between
Western authorities and the secretive 41-year-old, whose mythic
rise to power as the ``godfather'' of the radical Islamic world has
caught the attention of intelligence officials for nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   He is already considered an unindicted co-conspirator in the
World Trade Center bombing by US officials. He is believed to be
connected with at least three terrorist attacks in Africa and the
Middle East since 1992. In the last six months, he has issued
increasingly alarming decrees to ``evict the Americans'' from the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as April, during a visit to Afghanistan, the US
ambassador to the United Nations, Bill Richardson, pleaded with
leaders there to ``keep him under wraps.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States is vitally concerned with trying to do
something about this man,'' said former Central Intelligence Agency
counterterrorism official Stanley Bedlington. ``This shows just how
justified that concern is,'' referring to the African bombings.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban representative at the United Nations offered only a
tepid response. ``He is our guest, with the understanding that he
is not allowed to intiate any political or military action from our
soil,'' said Noorullah Zadran. ``He has been told that quite
clearly. But we really do not check every single day what he
does.''
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden's rhetoric comes from the core of the radical Islamic
movement. He has declared that the United States has ``invaded''
the Holy Land and that Americans are ``the biggest thieves in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   His profile as the ``black sheep'' of a prominent Saudi family
and a rich fanatic bent on war against Western culture from his
mountain retreat in Afghanistan has brought him unusual notoriety,
both within the Islamic world and without.
</P>
<P>
   He was born into extreme wealth, one of more than a dozen sons
of Muhammed bin Laden, a Saudi construction mogul rumored to be
worth as much as $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Osama, the youngest son, attended the King Abdul Aziz School for
Economics and Management. He later inherited his $250 million share
of the family wealth, considered the first step toward pursuing the
family business.
</P>
<P>
   His radical departure from his presumed future began at age 21
when, after hearing reports of the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan
in 1979, he ``became enraged,'' according to past interviews.
Months later he left to join the resistance.
</P>
<P>
   At the time his mission mirrored that of the United States: Both
were fighting to dislodge the Communists from Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   But bin Laden kept his distance from American support, according
to Vincent Cannistraro, a former CIA counterterrorism chief.
Instead, he ``established moral leadership,'' as a wealthy Saudi
fighting alongside the beleaguered mujahiddin, said Cannistraro.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, when bin Laden returned to Saudi Arabia, his loyalties
remained with ``his involvement and his connections to the Islamic
militants,'' Cannistraro continued. When the Gulf War broke out in
1990, his anti-Western sentiments ``exploded.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His sympathies were clearly with Iraq,'' said Arnaud de
Borchgrave, a senior fellow at the Center for Strategic and
International Studies in Washington. ``He felt we had entrapped
Iraq. Osama felt this was a stab in the back, that Saudi Arabia
opened up its country to America's war machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter Cutler, twice ambassador to Saudi Arabia in the 1980s,
said: ``He obviously went off the deep end.''
</P>
<P>
   After lambasting both the United States and Saudi Arabia, bin
Laden retreated to the Sudan in 1991. He used his fortune to
establish a legitimate construction company, US experts said. But
he also summoned allies from the mujahiddin to build his operation
and set up at least three terrorist training camps, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In the following years, terrorism shook the region, and bin
Laden's profile rose among the suspects for the following acts:
</P>
<P>
   _In December 1992, two bombs exploded in Yemeni hotels, where
American Marines were stationed on their way to Somalia. One person
was killed, but no Americans were injured.
</P>
<P>
   _In February 1993, a bomb exploded at the World Trade Center in
New York, killing six and injuring more than 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   _In September 1993, an American Blackhawk helicopter was hit
with a rocket-propelled grenade in Mogadishu, Somalia, killing
three American servicemen.
</P>
<P>
   _In November 1995, a car bomb exploded outside a US training
camp in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia. Five Americans were killed; 30 others
were injured.
</P>
<P>
   _In June 1996, a car bomb exploded near a US Air Force complex
near Dhahran, Saudi Arabia. Nineteen Americans died, and another
160 were hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Each time, evidence linked the perpetrators to bin Laden or his
training camps, yet bin Laden has taken responsibility for none of
the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   But in a June meeting with ABC News reporter John Miller, who
trekked across the border from Pakistan for the interview, bin
Laden dramatically heightened his rhetoric by vowing to deliver all
Americans out of Saudi Arabia in ``wooden boxes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We predict a black day for America,'' bin Laden said.
</P>
<P>
   The Saudi government, responding to similar remarks made
earlier, revoked his citizenship in 1994, and diplomatic pressure
in 1996 forced Sudan to expel him as well. Bin Laden returned to
his last safe haven: Afghanistan. He hides there now under the
protection of the Taliban militia, whose radical religious views
are consistent with his own.
</P>
<P>
   Within the last year outside concerns about the bin Laden
operation have increased. According to de Borchgrave, he has
fortified his military camps and communications systems, adopted a
network of laptop computers that transmit heavily encrypted
messages by satellite.
</P>
<P>
   In February bin Laden also issued his first official ``fatwa,''
against Americans, according to a State Department official. Three
more followed in the months leading up to the attacks in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The US took those threats very seriously,'' said the official,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Richardson's requests that the Taliban work toward Bin
Laden's removal from Afghanistan or at least keep him in check, the
source said, ``The Taliban said they would, and then did not follow
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, bin Laden has continued solidifying his umbrella
alliance of international terrorist sects, which now includes
representatives of eight countries from Egypt to the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Among those believed to be currently with him in Afghanistan is
the leader of the Egyptian Islamic jihad, the successors to the
group that assassinated President Anwar Sadat in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Although bin Laden himself has remained quiet since June, his
Egyptian associate, Ayman Zawaahiri, has spoken to the press in
recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Just one day before the bombings in Africa, Zawaahiri issued a
chilling warning in the Arabic paper Al-Hayat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are interested in briefly telling the Americans that their
message has been received, and that the response, which we hope
they will read carefully, is being prepared,'' he said. ``Because
we _ with God's help _ will write it in the language they
understand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
