<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-REAL-IRA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`REAL IRA,' UNDER PRESSURE, CALLS CEASE-FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ Under unprecedented pressure from the Irish government
and its citizens, the dissident republican group responsible for
the worst atrocity in Northern Ireland this century called a
temporary cease-fire Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The cease-fire, which the Real IRA said it reached after its
bomb killed 28 people in the market town of Omagh last Saturday,
was greeted with widespread skepticism. It came as the reputed Real
IRA leader, Michael ``Mickey'' McKevitt, and his family endure a
campaign of vilification in Dundalk, the town in the Irish Republic
where they live and run a printing shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said his life was being made impossible,'' said a family
friend, Rev. Desmond Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the printing shop was abruptly closed after
McKevitt's 17-year-old daughter, who works there, was threatened,
according to a family friend. People had been passing the shop,
shouting ``Shame!'' and ``Murderers!''
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Dundalk are appalled at what happened,'' said
John Woods, who is leading efforts to distance the community from
republican extremists, about the Omagh bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The cease-fire, and the public outcry that precipitated it,
could be a turning point in Ireland, where the overwhelming
majority of people in the north and south have endorsed new
political arrangements to end a conflict that has killed more than
3,500 people over the last three decades and poisoned relations
between Britain and Ireland for more than three centuries.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the public pressure on the Real IRA and
McKevitt marks an extraordinary change. For the last 30 years,
extremists from both sides of the political and sectarian divide
have intimidated ordinary people. The prospect of ordinary people
doing the same to someone regarded as the leader of an armed and
ruthless paramilitary organization is remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   Most people in Omagh, who attended some of the funerals of 16 of
the victims held Wednesday, dismissed the cease-fire as a cynical
attempt to deflect public revulsion and police attention. The
British and Irish governments greeted the news skeptically, saying
it would not deter them from hunting down the bombers.
</P>
<P>
   Irish premier Bertie Ahern Wednesday night unveiled a package of
what he called ``draconian'' laws aimed at crushing the Real IRA
and other dissident groups opposed to the peace process. Under the
new provisons, which Irish lawmakers are expected to pass in a
special session in two weeks, police could hold suspects for
questioning for up to four days, twice the current limit, while a
suspect's refusal to answer questions would be considered
corroboration of a police officer's opinion that they belonged to
an illegal group.
</P>
<P>
   Irish lawmakers will also be asked to pass a law that would
allow the government to seize the property of anyone who knowingly
allows paramilitary groups to use their home or land as a refuge
for weapons or terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Farms in the Irish Republic are frequently used as weapons dumps
and safehouses for those on the run. In a country where farmland
remains in families for generations and is considered an integral
part of the nation's cultural identity, the initiative to seize
property represents a major change in Irish thinking and
demonstrates the government's resolve.
</P>
<P>
   A priest in Dundalk, the border town where McKevitt lives with
his wife, Bernadette Sands, the sister of dead IRA icon Bobby
Sands, and their three children, said that McKevitt told him he had
nothing to do with the bombing. The priest, the Rev. Desmond
Campbell, said the McKevitts had fled their home. But friends of
the family dispute that.
</P>
<P>
   Reached Wednesday night at the printing shop she runs,
Bernadette Sands declined comment. Earlier, she told Irish national
radio that she condemned the bombing and urged anyone still using
violence to use peaceful means to bring about a united Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Father Campbell said a distraught Sands telephoned him Tuesday
night, asking, ``What is going to happen to my children?'' Campbell
said Sands collapsed in tears and McKevitt then took the phone and
protested his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he was a republican, but that he had no hand in the
bombing,'' said Father Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Since the bombing, the McKevitts have been the object of a
campaign of shunning and vilification in Dundalk, which
traditionally has been known as a place where republican extremists
hide or settle when wanted by the authorities in Northern Ireland.
Many people in Dundalk object to the portrayal of their town as a
terrorist haven and have begun a campaign aimed at driving the
McKevitts out.
</P>
<P>
   Rory Doogan, a family friend, and with Sands a leader of the
32-County Sovereignty Committee which the authorities claim is the
political wing of the Real IRA, accused the security forces of
using the news media to whip up ``mass hysteria'' against McKevitt
and Sands.
</P>
<P>
   Doogan said Father Campbell ``had condemned them from the
pulpit, and Bernie (Sands) rang him and put it on him. He's putting
their lives in danger.'' Doogan said the family was determined to
stay in their home, despite death threats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernie's in the shop today. I think she's shown immense
courage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Doogan said the campaign of vilification is part of a wider
conspiracy targeting the 32-County Sovereignty Committee ``because
we are growing.''
</P>
<P>
   McKevitt is the reputed former quartermaster of the IRA, meaning
he had responsibility over the IRA's arsenal. Sources close to the
leadership of both the IRA and the IRA's political allies in Sinn
Fein, whose leaders are almost exclusively former IRA members, say
McKevitt was the leader of those who quit the republican movement
last year after an aborted attempt to take it over.
</P>
<P>
   These sources say McKevitt, his wife and a group that consisted
mostly of activists from the Irish Republic, led the dissidents who
quit both the IRA and Sinn Fein in protest over what they saw as a
``selling out'' of the republican ideals of forcing a British
withdrawal from Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams, supported by the IRA's ruling Army
Council, has led the republican movement to change from the use of
violence to politics to create a united Ireland. But the hardliners
say Northern Ireland is an illegitimate entity, created against the
wishes of the Irish people who voted in 1919 for an all-island
nation.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of republicans consider the dissidents to be
unrealistic, atavistic ideologues, incapable of making the
compromises that were central to the Good Friday agreement which
created new political arrangements in the north and south. But
there was a minority of republicans who supported the group and
believes that violence is still justified. Some contend that
minimal support has shrunk even further after Saturday's bombing,
which the Real IRA blamed on the police for not following its
warnings.
</P>
<P>
   The police say the warnings were inaccurate and led them to
unwittingly steer large numbers of people near the hidden bomb
while trying to evacuate an area where they were told the bomb was.
</P>
<P>
   Ahern says the Real IRA has no more than 100 members. He has
vowed ``ruthlessly suppress'' what he calls an unrepresentative
group trying to thwart the democratic wishes of an overwhelming
majority of the Irish people who in May endorsed power sharing and
cross-border cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelly, a former IRA leader who is now a Sinn Fein
politician, said the Real IRA has little support. Speaking in Omagh
after the bombing, Kelly predicted, ``They're finished. They spoke
for few people. Now they speak for none.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
