<HEADER>
A2110 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFGHAN-U.S.-565&AMP;ADD-N     08-19 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFGHAN-U.S.-565&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. URGES ALL NON-MUSLIMS TO FLEE AFGHANISTAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also AFRICA-BOMBING) 
(mk) 
 By RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ The U.S. Embassy on Wednesday urged all
non-Muslim foreigners working in neighboring Afghanistan to leave
the country because of fears for their safety.
</P>
<P>
   The warning, which compounded the fears and tensions generated
by the bombings of the American Embassies in Kenya and Tanzania,
was based on threats in general, officials said, but was considered
serious enough to be announced here well before dawn Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   And in Cairo Wednesday, a coalition of militant Islamic
organizations threatened further attacks on Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coming days will guarantee, God willing, that America will
face a black fate,'' a group calling itself the World Islamic Front
for Holy War Against Jews and Crusaders, said in a statement
published in Al-Hayat, the London-based Arabic newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The group is part of a far-reaching network run by Osama bin
Laden, the Islamic militant who has publicly threatened a holy war
against the United States. American officials have said that bin
Laden, who operates from bases in Afghanistan, has been a focus of
the investigation into the bombings from the outset.
</P>
<P>
   A senior non-American diplomat here said Wednesday, ``I can
confirm from non-American and non-Pakistani intelligence that he
was involved in some way.''
</P>
<P>
   A leader of the Taliban, the Islamic movement that now controls
about 90 percent of Afghanistan and is the de facto government
there, denied Wednesday that bin Laden had any role in the
bombings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Taliban can assure the world, 100 percent, that Osama bin
Laden is not involved in any subversive activity,'' Mullah Muhammad
Omar of the Taliban told the Pakistan-based Afghan Islamic Press.
</P>
<P>
   A suspect arrested in Pakistan and sent back to Kenya for
interrogation, Mohammed Saddiq Odeh, told Pakistani investigators
that the operation was the work of bin Laden. Odeh also told
investigators that in 1993, he was sent to Somalia to carry out
operations against American troops there, The News, a major
English-language newspaper here, reported Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The troops had been sent by President Bush to protect the
distribution of relief supplies, but got caught up in Somalia's
clan warfare. In the statement to Al-Hayat, the World Islamic Front
for Holy War Against Jews and Crusaders said that the bombings were
a response to the American operation there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two embassies, which the Islamic Army for the Liberation
of Holy Shrines bombed, have supervised the killings of at least
13,000 Somali civilians in the treacherous attack led by America
against this Muslim country,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the statement from the Holy War coalition, Al-Hayat
said it received statements from the Islamic Army for the
Liberation of Holy Shrines.
</P>
<P>
   The group said it would ``continue shipping more American dead
bodies to their unjust government,'' and that it sought to
``humiliate America's arrogance and roll its dignity in the mud of
defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not known if these statements were the cause of the
American warning to non-Muslims to leave Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   After the warning was quickly disseminated to expatriate
organizations working in Afghanistan, two Americans left and more
are expected to leave on Thursday, American officials said. There
were 15 to 20 Americans working in Afghanistan for various
nongovernmental organizations, along with some 100 other
expatriates.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   American officials and representatives from nongovernmental
agencies working in Afghanistan asked that the names of the
organizations not be published because of the threats.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations reacted to the warning by suspending all
``non-essential'' programs, such as training health care workers,
said a U.N. spokeswoman here, Sarah Russell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking anybody out who wants to leave,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has 34 foreign employees working in
Afghanistan, with a variety of agencies, including Unicef and the
World Food Program.
</P>
<P>
   The most exposed organization is the International Committee of
the Red Cross, which has about 80 expatriates carrying out their
mission in Afghanistan. Traditionally, the Red Cross has been the
first to enter and the last to leave even the most dangerous
places. For the moment, the expatriates have decided to stay,
though they will take precautions, officials with the organization
said.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the tension and uncertainty here, one said, ``It
might be different tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
