<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2120 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARDS-CUBS-NYT &LR;      08-19 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARDS-CUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
  
 McGWIRE (49), SOSA (48) HOMER AS THE MARIS CHASE SPEEDS UP   By IRA BERKOW    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The chase to surpass the home run record in baseball,
perhaps the most storied achievement in American sports, took a
dramatic turn on a sun-sweet Wednesday afternoon in Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   Three dramatic turns, to be precise.
</P>
<P>
   When Sammy Sosa, the Cubs' galvanic outfielder, lined a home run
into the left-field bleachers in the fifth inning, it was his 48th
home run of the season. It put him into the home run lead of the
big leagues, literally and figuratively passing Mark McGwire, the
Cardinals' first baseman, who appeared impassive as Sosa went into
his home-run trot.
</P>
<P>
   The pair has been jockeying at the top for the last couple of
months, and came into this two-game series which began Tuesday
night tied at 47 homers each. It was the first time since mid-April
that McGwire wasn't the top man in home runs. And it moved Sosa one
step closer to Roger Maris, who is the holder of the record, having
belted 61 homers in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   What was McGwire thinking as Sosa cruised by him?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing much really,'' he said. ``Just that Sammy's an awesome
player.''
</P>
<P>
   True or not, McGwire was obviously not about to remain dormant.
</P>
<P>
   And Sosa's home run lead was short-lived. McGwire gave him and
the sellout crowd of 39,689 a charge when he not only homered in
the eighth off Matt Karchner to tie Sosa at 48 homers, but hit it
farther, knocking the ball over the bleachers and onto Waveland
Avenue. And he tied up the game, 6-6, to boot.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't finished. In the 10th inning, he lined a shot off
Terry Mulholland that cleared the wall in center field, 400 feet
from home plate, and gave him the homer lead at 49. This also gave
the Cardinals the lead in the ball game, one they did not
relinquish.
</P>
<P>
   This dual pursuit of the home run record has been one of the
better shows in sports in some time, and the fans responded to it,
and to the protagonists, often and loudly.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the fans came to this exquisite old ballpark in
anticipation of such fireworks, and the possibility of watching
history in the making, or on the road to being made.
</P>
<P>
   With 36 games left on the Cubs' regular-season schedule, and 38
left for the Cards _ who play the Mets beginning Thursday in a
four-game series, a pair of back-to-back doubleheaders _ the drama
heightens.
</P>
<P>
   But McGwire was surely very much aware of what the home run
meant, since the national media, dogging his and Sosa's steps have
not let him forget, as they have matched homer for homer for
several months now.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, Sosa lined a shot to left field which
looked like it was a home run to almost everyone in the park,
including Sosa, who observed admiringly on his jog to first base.
Alas, the ball hit about three feet from the top of the wall. John
Mabry fielded it, whirled and threw cleanly to second where Sosa,
who realized he'd better start running, was out by so large a
margin he didn't even commit a slide.
</P>
<P>
   When Sosa did hit it out of the park, off Kent Bottenfield, it
was his second home run trot of the game, and by far his most
effective. When Sosa returned to the dugout he was cheered so
enthusiastically that he emerged out of the dugout for a curtain
call. He waved his cap, then retreated onto the bench where he
celebrated by pouring a cup of water over his sweaty head.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire came to bat in the next inning, exciting the multitude
ever more. Could McGwire answer blow for blow? The crowd treated
McGwire to a loud but mixed bag of cheers, boos and whistles.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals had loaded the bases with two outs, and were
behind 6-2. Riggleman replaced his starter, Clark, with
right-handed reliever Terry Adams. When Adams got a called strike
on McGwire, the fans cheered. But a passed ball allowed in a run,
sent runners to second and third and left first base open, with a
2-2 count. Adams walked him, which was the sensible thing to do
under the circumstances. The boos cascaded from the stands.
</P>
<P>
   The game began for the sluggers with McGwire hitting a towering
fly ball to left field, which Henry Rodriguez caught with his back
against the ivied wall.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa struck out looking in his first at-bat. In the third
inning, McGwire popped out to third base.
</P>
<P>
   When McGwire was walked on a 3-2 pitch in the fifth inning, boos
rang from some precincts of Wrigley Field. Fans want to see the
march to history, and feel deprived when the slugger is not
permitted to swing _ sluggers, actually, because when Sosa and Ken
Griffey Jr., the other contenders for the record, are walked in
enemy ballparks, the home-team pitchers are routinely being booed.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Croushore got the same medicine when he walked Sosa in the
seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   What did McGwire and Sosa talk about on first base? ``We talked
about building a golf course together,'' McGwire said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa is equally coy about what the homer record means to him.
``Our team is in the middle of a pennant race,'' said Sosa. ``If we
won and I didn't hit a home run I would be more satisfied than I am
now.''
</P>
<P>
   And what was Sosa thinking in right field when McGwire passed
him with his 49th home run. ``I'm thinking, `He's the man,''' said
Sosa, who has been saying for months that he is rooting for McGwire
to break the record.
</P>
<P>
   The night before, Sosa and McGwire collectively went 0-for-9 and
struck out six times. Perhaps a little breeze toward the outfield
didn't hurt, and maybe some of the pressure was off just a bit,
since the two may have released some of it the night before.
</P>
<P>
   The game itself was a thrilling one, with the Cubs loading the
bases in the bottom of the 10th, before Manny Alexander popped to
second base to end the game and give the Cardinals an 8-6 triumph.
</P>
<P>
   For the Cardinals, who are out of the flag race, the joy of
knocking off the Cubs, a wild-card contender, was pleasurable,
along with sharing McGwire's return to the lead in the homer race.
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted that home runs were also hit in the game by
four other players, Henry Rodriguez and Jose Hernandez of the Cubs,
and Delino DeShields and Ray Lankford of the Cards. But no one's
paying much attention to that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
