<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHIPMAKERS-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIA CRISIS CUTTING INTO CHIP MAKER PROFITS
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: budgeted earlier as LSI-OUTLOOK) 
(nk) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Two computer chip makers said Wednesday that
they expected sharply lower quarterly results because of Asia's
economic crisis, and a third said its quarterly net earnings fell
81 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The warnings from LSI Logic and National Semiconductor, coupled
with the results from Analog Devices Inc., suggested that any talk
of a recovery in the chip manufacturing industry might be
premature. Chip companies are finding that they are much more
vulnerable to Asia's problems than they had thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``When something like Asia happens, it doesn't really matter how
good your products are or how well managed your company is, you're
going to feel it,'' said Drew Peck, an analyst with SG Cowen &AMP;
Company.
</P>
<P>
   LSI, based in Milpitas, Calif., specializes in custom
semiconductors and so-called system-on-a-chip devices used in
products ranging from networking equipment to video game players.
Analog Devices, of Norwood, Mass., makes chips that combine analog
and digital signals, which are commonly used in cellular
telephones, modems and small appliances. National Semiconductor,
based in Santa Clara, Calif., straddles the two other companies'
chip lines.
</P>
<P>
   LSI and Analog both attributed their revenue and earnings
situations largely to Asia. National Semiconductor cited weakness
in overall semiconductor demand, but has singled out the Asian
crisis before.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of LSI Logic closed Wednesday at $15.8125, down $2.4375,
or 13 percent, while shares in Analog Devices dropped $2.75, or 11
percent, to $21.50, both on the New York Stock Exchange. National
made its announcement after the market closed; its shares finished
down 56.25 cents, at $13.625, also on the Big Board.
</P>
<P>
   LSI's announcement marked the second time in a month that it had
warned investors about financial results. While Analog Devices had
warned of a weak quarter, its results came in below most analysts'
revised estimates. National has disappointed analysts the last two
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Analog Devices said revenue from its analog integrated circuits
had declined for the first time in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter that ended on Aug. 1, Analog earned $8.8
million, or 6 cents a diluted share, compared with $46 million, or
27 cents a share, a year earlier. Third-quarter 1998 earnings
include a $17 million restructuring charge and a $3.6 million
equity loss, equivalent to 9 cents a share. Revenue dropped 7
percent to $294.9 million from $318.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected Analog Devices to report earnings of 19
cents a share, excluding the charges.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We are part of an industry that began 1998 with an expectation
of 15 percent year-over-year revenue growth, only to see that
expectation reduced every month since then,'' Jerald G. Fishman,
Analog's president and chief executive, said in a statement.
``Currently, the industry expects to finish 1998 down 10 percent
from the previous year.'' He said the company still expected to
grow 5 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Because that expectation is far below original estimates of 20
percent growth, Analog has started cutting its work force by 5
percent, resulting in the restructuring charge. It is also planning
a series of factory shutdowns during the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   LSI's earlier guidance had been to expect flat revenue and
earnings per share in the third quarter. But it said Wednesday that
unexpectedly low orders in the first six weeks of the third quarter
would result in a 5 percent to 10 percent decline in revenue and
that earnings per share would be in the ``low-to-mid teens.''
Analysts had expected 23 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``The slowdown of the global semiconductor industry is now
completing its third year, which is the longest slow period
experienced in this industry,'' Wilfred J. Corrigan, LSI Logic's
chairman and chief executive, said in a statement.``We expect
supply and demand to come together in the next 12 months.''
</P>
<P>
   National said sales and earnings for its fiscal first quarter,
which will end on Aug. 30, and second quarter, ending on Nov. 29,
might fall below the fourth quarter of fiscal 1998, which ended in
May. Excluding one-time charges, National had a loss of $69.3
million on sales of $510 million in that quarter. The company said
it now expected sales for the first quarter to drop 8 to 10
percent, with a resulting larger loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside of a very narrow area, semiconductor demand remains
very depressed and at this time there are no data points to suggest
that will change this year,'' Peck of Cowen said. ``These companies
are fairly good representatives of what is going on in the industry
as a whole, and that's not anything good right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
