<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2127 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      08-19 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: WHITE HOUSE PLACING HOPE ON PUBLIC SENTIMENT TO `MOVE
ON'
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: CLINTON-STARR, CLINTON-VINEYARD, CLINTON-HEARTLAND,
CLINTON-MCHALE, CLINTON-POLLS) 
(sw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Inside Washington, pundits and editorial writers
rail on about a destroyed presidency. Republicans whisper, some
loudly, about impeachment hearings or resignation. Some Democrats
are putting distance between themselves and President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Washington, most people tell pollsters that they are
tired of hearing about Monica Lewinsky. They want the country to
move on.
</P>
<P>
   It is that schism between the real world and the self-styled
political elites that White House officials say is their best hope
for Clinton to withstand the Lewinsky debacle. They figure that
members of Congress, ever mindful of popular sentiment, will not
want to prolong an unpopular inquiry or press for impeachment
hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is clearly similar to the '95 State of the Union,'' said
one of Clinton's closest aides, referring to how the president's
interminable address that year was panned by pundits but won raves
from ordinary Americans. ``Reaction inside the Beltway is quite
different from out in America. I think on the numbers, we should be
encouraged.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while it may take days, or even weeks to shake out,
initial polls show that, overwhelmingly, people want the country to
put the sex scandal behind it, even if they are disappointed in
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But White House officials are not gleeful.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, some of the president's advisers expressed concern
that Clinton's address on Monday only enraged many of the elites,
who thought he was too combative and not adequately contrite. That
opens the possibility that days of scathing commentary from
Washington insiders _ and snippets on television of Clinton lying
about his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky _ will finally penetrate
the public's hitherto intense resistance to examine the tawdry
details and cause Americans to rebel against the president and his
party.
</P>
<P>
   Another danger for the president is that members of Congress do
not always take their orders from the latest opinion surveys.
Sometimes they lead, though it has proven easier for them to block
measures that the public wants than to initiate laws against the
will of the people.
</P>
<P>
   In 1941, for example, Congress reinstated the draft, despite
widespread isolationist sentiment in the country. The Senate
ratified the Panama Canal Treaty in 1978 in the face of vociferous
public opposition. And if lawmakers responded only to the polls,
tougher gun control and campaign finance laws would be on the
books.
</P>
<P>
   Already, some Republicans are calling on their colleagues to
ignore the polls. Sen. James Inhofe of Oklahoma said that once
Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel, sends a report
to Congress, then it will be time for Congress to make a judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that time comes,'' Inhofe said, ``it will be important
for members of Congress to put aside the public opinion polls and
remember their ultimate duty to protect the Constitution and
preserve the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   The critical question for the White House is how many lawmakers
will take Inhofe's position. For now, House Speaker Newt Gingrich
and some of his colleagues are taking a wait-and-see approach,
waiting for more follow-up polls, and for Starr's report. Their
calculation is that Clinton has messed things up already without
their help, and that it would be better for Republicans not to be
viewed as having egged it on if the impeachment process goes
forward.
</P>
<P>
   But judging by the harsh remarks this week by some of Clinton's
most loyal allies, including Sen. Dianne Feinstein of California,
some Democrats may be unwilling to help push the scandal aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave a speech that in my opinion should have been given
six-and-a-half months ago,'' said Rep. Jim Maloney, D-Conn. ``The
American people were entitled to the truth six-and-a-half months
ago.'' Calling Clinton's behavior ``reprehensible,'' he said
Congress should wait and see what Starr's report says. ``To fulfill
our duties,'' he said, ``that's what we need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Jones, professor emeritus of political science at the
University of Wisconsin, said Clinton should not assume that
members of Congress will stick with him if his job approval ratings
stay high. For lawmakers, he said, a president's approval rating
``is such a general indicator, and not a very clear indicator, of
awards or punishments for them at election time.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``The great imponderable for dealing with any of this
is Starr's report. You can't imagine that public opinion is going
to stay the same in the face of new information.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the White House has moved aggressively to build, or
at least hold on to, political support beyond Washington insiders.
In the events surrounding his grand jury testimony, Clinton was
clearly playing to the Democratic base: Women who are sympathetic
to Hillary Rodham Clinton, and blacks who noted that the Rev. Jesse
Jackson played a pivotal role in consoling the Clintons over the
weekend. And the second half of Clinton's public address was
clearly intended to embolden Democrats who think Starr is on an
unbridled partisan vendetta.
</P>
<P>
   But sooner or later, one side will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either elites will shape public opinion over the next several
months and bring the public to the view that the president must
go,'' said Thomas Mann, a congressional scholar at the Brookings
Institution here, ``or the elites will discover the wisdom of the
public's continued support of the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Even many of the Democrats who this week scolded Clinton for his
personal behavior and for deceiving the nation sounded like they
were reading the polls when they laced their comments with pleas
for the country to move forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Polling has indicated that two-thirds of the American people
now just want to get this whole thing behind us,'' said Sen. John
Glenn, D-Ohio, ``and get on with the very important domestic and
international matters that directly affect every family in the
country. I agree.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nita Lowey, D-N.Y., derided Clinton's behavior as
``inappropriate, irresponsible, reckless.'' But, she added, ``In
traveling around my district, the feeling by an overwhelming
majority is: Let's go on with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But already, many Republicans in particular have made clear that
they do not want to go on with it.
</P>
<P>
   Told that his call for Clinton's resignation seemed at odds with
the polls, Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the majority whip in the House,
said on Wednesday evening: ``What matters is right and wrong. I
think, frankly, the polls are a joke.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
