<HEADER>
A2128 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIGH-FASHION-AD-COLUM     08-19 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGH-FASHION-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: NOT SO HAUTE COUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is high fashion trying to speak to the masses? Flip through the
September issues of fashion magazines, and there appears to be a
subtle shift in the sensibility of fashion advertisers this fall
season.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion advertising _ especially in the all-important fall
season, a sort of Christmas for publishers of such magazines _ has
almost exclusively used images of fantasy. But there are signs that
fashion is trying to add a little realism.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few trendlets noted in advertisements in the
September issues of Elle, Marie Claire and Vogue:
</P>
<P>
   REAL PEOPLE: The most obvious way to connect a product to its
potential buyer is to show people who look as if they might
actually use it. While this theory works for soap and soda, fashion
has rarely bought into it. The idea instead is generally to create
a world where an 87-pound woman appears to be mildly distressed by
the great many men who pursue her in her high-end dress.
</P>
<P>
   But this season, real women populate the ads. Anne Klein's
campaign features a dancer, a venture capitalist, a radiologist and
a mother among other women who do not model professionally. The
fall Dockers campaign for Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. relies on women in
film, like the actress Rosie Perez, and an advertisement for Timex
watches features the faces of three sisters.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Karan's fall campaign uses professional models, but one of
them is older than 40 and no longer works regularly. The press
release for Calvin Klein's new ad for a men's fragrance boasts that
the model is a father of three and hints that the fact he is
drop-dead gorgeous and pitches in at home makes him, to use Klein's
favorite buzzword, very ``modern.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Klein pioneered the reality effect with his earlier
advertisements that featured unscrubbed, anti-model characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put model, a fantasy and fashion all together, it can
get to be too overpowering,'' said Tom Julian, a trend analyst for
Fallon McElligott's New York office. ``The fashion industry has
started to realize that if you make fashion acceptable on all
levels, you get more people to buy in.''
</P>
<P>
   BLACK AND WHITE ALL OVER: There are so many black-and-white
advertisements in the fall magazines they almost resemble
newspapers. In the 568 pages of Elle, 26 fashion houses use
black-and-white photography for their fall campaigns, or nearly
half the fashion ads. From Calvin Klein to Halston to Gucci to
Eileen Fisher, the color of newsprint is throughout.
</P>
<P>
   True, fall's palette _ grays, dark greens and beige _ lends
itself to black and white. But many of these ads resemble a
documentary. The photos tie together a narrative seemingly plucked
from real life, as in the Ralph Lauren advertisements for the
Romance fragrance line, which features four distinct images of a
couple falling in love.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black and white does seem to be the color of the moment in
fashion ads,'' said Donny Deutsch, chairman and chief executive of
Deutsch Inc. in New York. ``Black and white stand for reality,
which is ironic because life of course is not in black and white.''
</P>
<P>
   BABY AS ACCESSORY: Fashion rarely evokes family life: Sippy
cups, bath time and play dates are hardly the stuff of a Seventh
Avenue fantasy. This season, however, it seems that babies are as
important as the right handbag. Elle, Vogue and Marie Claire all
feature cute babies in their fashion editorial pages, egged on, its
seems, by Isaac Mizrahi, who recently featured rain slickers and
evening gowns with matching baby carriers in his collection.
</P>
<P>
   Marin Hopper, Elle's fashion director, said her magazine's
decision to run an entire photo feature titled ``Insouciant au
pair'' was inspired by current fashion trends and baby adoration
among her readers. ``There was a feeling this fall in fashion that
was very schoolgirl-like, a fresh innocence, from pleated skirts to
flat shoes,'' Ms. Hopper said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is also a sort of intimacy that is very in for fall,
and babies connect up with that. Baby boomers are still having
babies, and fashion is sort of returning to family values, with all
its hope for the future and good feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   Julian of Fallon McElligott said: ``In the '80s, it was the dog.
In the '90s, it is the wedding ring and the children. It makes a
customer think, `Oh, this fits into my life.' There is a certain
reality factor there, and it's good.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are only so many reality factors that a reader
of fashion magazines can take. A Bergdorf Goodman advertisement
features a woman in a Guy Laroche dress and coat, walking a llama
down a New York sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to position ourselves as a little less serious,''
said Michael Calman, senior vice president of marketing for the
retailer, a unit of the Neiman Marcus Group. ``We want to show we
can appeal to a younger audience, and that is generally not how we
are perceived.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2133 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-19 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: CLINTON ON THE WIRE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``No one is ever better on the high wire,'' said former White
House press secretary Dee Dee Myers in a television appearance
before Bill Clinton's address to the nation on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   One of the problems is that the president takes so many people
up on the high wire with him. If he falls it's a catastrophe. On
Monday night, not long after Ms. Myers' comment, Clinton lost his
balance. But he didn't fall. His performance is shakier than ever,
but he's still up there.
</P>
<P>
   The question is why the president feels the need to take such
foolish risks in the first place, risks that put him and so many
others in jeopardy. Is it all a game? Or is it a kind of sickness?
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had a chance to climb down from the wire on Monday. The
public has made it overwhelmingly clear that it is sick of the
sordid Lewinsky melodrama. The Republicans in Congress have no
stomach for impeachment, and there has been no evidence disclosed
as yet that would warrant impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, the chairman of the Judiciary Committee,
offered Clinton an out and practically begged him to take it. In an
appearance on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' early this month, Hatch
said: ``If he comes forth and tells it and does it in the right way
and there aren't a lot of other factors to cause the Congress to
say, `This man is unfit for the presidency and should be
impeached,' then I think the president would have a reasonable
chance of getting through this.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I think the American people would breathe a sigh of
relief.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a serious olive branch. It should not have been
difficult to accept. Close friends and aides to Clinton, finally
aware, like most Americans, that the president had been lying all
along, were saying the same thing. They urged him to help put the
matter to rest by telling the full truth and offering a sincere
apology to the nation for the grief and the harm he had caused.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, wobbling on the swaying wire, shook his head. ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on television and offered defiance where so many had
hoped to see contrition. He never admitted that he had lied at all.
He never apologized. And he angrily attacked Kenneth Starr, the
Whitewater independent counsel. Starr is certainly vulnerable to
attack, but most of Clinton's advisers felt that Monday night's
address to the nation was not the place to do it. All you had to do
was look at Senator Hatch's response to the president's four-minute
speech to see why they felt as they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just gonna blow my stack,'' said Hatch on NBC. Change the
channel. ``I'm just gonna blow my cork,'' said Hatch on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has not helped to put the matter to rest. The sense of
betrayal among the president's supporters, which was inevitable, is
mixed with the horrifying suspicion that he is in no way
remorseful, that he couldn't care less about the friends and the
aides who put their credibility on the line for him, the colleagues
whose legal bills in some cases have left them close to bankruptcy,
the ardent followers whose trust he has squandered like a
compulsive gambler feeding borrowed money into a slot machine.
</P>
<P>
   The president remained silent for more than half a year,
allowing people who cared deeply about him to submerge their
reputations in his lies. And, true to a decades-long pattern, he
would still be promoting those lies and playing the American people
for fools if he hadn't been confronted by what appears to be a
mountain of virtually irrefutable evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's job approval ratings remain extremely high. The public
does not want him to resign or be impeached. Among other things, it
does not want Kenneth Starr deciding who will be president.
</P>
<P>
   The high poll ratings may actually encourage in Clinton a giddy
sense that he can get away with anything. Behind the numbers,
however, is the widespread realization that this is a man who has
disgraced himself and his office and who cannot be trusted, even by
his closest friends. That view will be reinforced by each new and
dismaying revelation.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a story that can be wished away. When the president
has a problem we all have a problem. We are all on the high wire
with him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 2010EDT &QL; 
