<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS BRIM WITH GREATER EXPECTATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The freshmen reported Monday. The veterans arrive
this morning, and Saturday the UCLA Bruins begin their third
training camp under coach Bob Toledo _ one that differs from its
predecessors in attitude and expectation, if not personnel.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since 1989, UCLA is a preseason top-10 team.
And for the first time in the Toledo era, the No. 7 Bruins
seemingly have more answers than questions.
</P>
<P>
   They have a Heisman Trophy candidate at quarterback and an
established offensive system. They have a heralded freshmen class
expected to produce several impact players. Their schedule is
challenging but not overwhelming. Their health is good.
Summer-school grades are due Friday, but Toledo said he does not
expect any problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins will practice twice Saturday at Spaulding Field,
beginning a grueling stretch of 23 workouts in 15 days. Toledo's
points of emphasis will include:
</P>
<P>
   __ Evaluate the young defense. The Bruins have just four
returning starters and a new system under first-year coordinator
Nick Aliotti. In contrast to Rocky Long's unconventional 3-3-5
scheme, Aliotti will implement a traditional 3-4 alignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We plan to reintroduce them to (the defense),'' he said. ``It
was taught during the spring, so their recall ought to be pretty
fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Only two players, outside linebacker Brendan Ayanbadejo and
strong safety Larry Atkins, are established. With a large freshman
class and so many starting spots in doubt, the Bruins will
scrimmage more than training camps past.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have some 10-play scrimmages with the young guys to see
which of them can help us,'' Toledo said. ``That's the only way to
find out.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo and Aliotti will pay particular attention to the
defensive line, where junior Pete Holland and sophomore Kenyon
Coleman are the ``veterans,'' and to free safety, where Eric
Whitfield, Tod McBride and Jason Stephens are competing to replace
Shaun Williams.
</P>
<P>
   __ Find some scorers. While much of the offense returns, the
Bruins must replace tailback Skip Hicks and receiver Jim McElroy,
who combined for 37 of UCLA's 60 touchdowns last season.
</P>
<P>
   There are several talented receivers of varying experience _
Danny Farmer, Brad Melsby, Brian Poli-Dixon, Freddie Mitchell, Cody
Joyce _ and tight end, for the second year in a row, is the team's
deepest position.
</P>
<P>
   But tailback is a concern. Jermaine Lewis, Keith Brown and
freshman DeShaun Foster will compete for the starting job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice if one came forward,'' offensive coordinator
Al Borges said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Identify the best freshmen. Together, they were considered
the nation's No. 1 recruiting class. But beginning Saturday, their
paths diverge. A handful figure to contribute immediately. Most
will redshirt. Attrition might claim a few.
</P>
<P>
   The best guess is seven or eight will play this season: Foster,
for sure; at least one offensive lineman (probably Mike Saffer); at
least one defensive lineman (perhaps Ken Kocher); linebacker Robert
Thomas, a potential starter, and defensive back Lovell Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins also have two junior college transfers, offensive
lineman James Ghezzi and tight end Randy Hakes. Ghezzi is expected
to join the rotation immediately.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
