<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL OFFICES FLOODED WITH CALLS ABOUT CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ESTELLA DURAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Telephones have been ringing incessantly on Capitol
Hill since Monday, as many hundreds of angry callers have flooded
congressional offices with opinions _ often rather loud ones _
about President Clinton, congressional staffers said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers' offices report as many as 200 calls a day _ some
callers asking for the president's impeachment or resignation,
others saying leave the man alone already _ in response to
Clinton's confession of an inappropriate relationship with former
White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Republican senators' and representatives'
staffers were particularly eager to discuss the calls pouring in.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are outraged. They're upset that the president lied in
the first place, and many want him impeached,'' said a staff member
for Senator Spencer Abraham, a Michigan Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham's Washington office has received more than 200 calls
since Monday night, and another 200 callers have reached the
senator's Michigan offices. Most callers have suggested Clinton
should be impeached or resign, the staff member said.
</P>
<P>
   Other congressional staffers, who requested anonymity for
themselves and the lawmakers they work for, reported between 100
and 200 calls daily about the president's speech concerning his
relationship with the former White House intern. Still more said
they received a dozen to 50 calls a day. Letters, e-mail,
telegrams, and faxes also have rolled in.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Sullivan, press secretary for Representative Ron Paul, a
Texas Republican, said his office has taken between 100 and 150
calls daily, most critical of the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been near unanimous in terms of the calls and e-mail,
with people saying to get rid of the guy, get him out of office,
impeach him,'' Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   Staffers for Democrats were more tight-lipped about calls coming
in, but those who would speak said they did not have as many calls
about Clinton as Republicans had.
</P>
<P>
   Many such staffers reported about 50 calls a day, with about
half supporting the president and half wanting him removed from
office.
</P>
<P>
   David Williams, chief of staff for Representative John Tierney,
the Massachusetts Democrat, said the office has fielded only about
25 calls about Clinton, and opinions ``run the gamut.''
</P>
<P>
   However, most of the 30 calls to the office of Representative
Martin T. Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat, said the president
should resign or be impeached, said spokesman Bill McCann. McCann
pointed out that many of the callers were not from Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some calls are kind of vulgar. Most are yelling,'' McCann
said. ``You get the sense that these people really have a very deep
resentment for President Clinton that, if anything, has increased
with this situation but was more than likely there before anyway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
