<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECURITIES-SHUTDOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHORITIES CRACK DOWN ON BROKERS WHO `FLIPPED' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Securities authorities sought Wednesday to shut down
the Boston office of Joseph Charles &AMP; Associates and revoke the
licenses of two of the firm's brokers for ignoring their clients'
requests to sell stocks in order to increase their own commissions.
</P>
<P>
   Under the firm's ``flipping'' policy, brokers don't receive
sales commissions when customers buy shares in initial public
offerings and then sell them quickly for profit.
</P>
<P>
   According to a complaint filed by the Massachusetts Secretary of
the Commonwealth's securities division, the policy at Joseph
Charles ``encouraged its Agents to engage in unethical and
dishonest as well as fraudulent conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Broker Christopher Esposito illegally cold-called investors,
placed unauthorized trades, misrepresented facts, and failed to
honor investors' wishes to sell securities, according to the
complaint. Esposito's boss, Michael Ferraro, also named in the
complaint, allegedly promoted the illegal activity and failed to
reasonably supervise the broker.
</P>
<P>
   In one case outlined in the filing, Esposito bought 4,000 shares
for a customer, James Smith, who claimed to have wanted only 2,000
shares. When the customer discovered the error, he immediately
called Esposito and ordered him to sell the extra stock. Esposito
refused, the complaint alleges.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next two weeks, Smith allegedly called repeatedly, but
Esposito refused to take his calls. The customer finally faxed the
brokerage asking ``any authorized trader'' to sell the stock.
Esposito said, ``It's all taken care of. I sold your stock,''
according to the complaint.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he'd only sold half the stock, the complaint alleges.
When Smith discovered that fact, he again repeatedly called
Esposito, but the broker refused to come to the phone. Only after
someone else at the firm mediated a conversation between Esposito
and Smith were the remaining shares sold.
</P>
<P>
   Esposito _ who had been the subject of six prior customer
complaints for misrepresenting facts, churning, and making
unsuitable recommendations _ last year signed a consent order with
state securities regulators agreeing not to violate securities
rules again.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's filing calls for an administrative hearing to review
whether Esposito violated the terms of that order.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 2014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0388 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2142 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOBS-DISPLACEMENT-ART     08-19 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOBS-DISPLACEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY FINDS LAYOFFS SLOWED IN LAST 3 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most comprehensive survey of permanent layoffs in America
finds that in the last three years, a smaller percentage of workers
were downsized than in any other period in this decade. But the
layoff rate is still significantly higher than in the 1980s, and
women now get pink slips almost as often as men.
</P>
<P>
   These were two major findings in Wednesday's release of the
latest job displacement survey from the Labor Department, covering
the years 1995 through 1997. Eight million people were pushed out
of their jobs involuntarily, or one out of every 15 adult
jobholders. That was down from 8.4 million in the previous
three-year period, or 1 in 12 workers, the decade's worst
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing the normal cyclical behavior of the labor force
reflected in these numbers,'' Henry Farber, a Princeton economist,
said of the strong economic growth in 1996 and 1997 and the falling
unemployment rate. ``The puzzle is why has it taken so long to get
the layoff rate down this far and why is it not even lower.''
</P>
<P>
   Downsizing is still occurring at a greater rate than in the late
1980s, the last time an economic expansion had lasted as long as
the current one. Then the displacement rate was 1 out of every 18
jobholders 20 years old and over.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department's Bureau of Labor Statistics began its
biennial ``job displacement'' surveys in 1984, when widespread
permanent layoffs were just becoming an issue. Those surveys found
that downsizing fell back quickly after the 1981-1982 recession.
The 1990s were different. Permanent layoffs rose in the 1990-1991
recession and then failed to fall back. They even kept rising
despite the recovery. The pattern remains the same when the Labor
Department's figures are adjusted, through the use of a moving
average, to reconcile overlapping annual numbers from different
surveys.
</P>
<P>
   Labor economists offer various explanations for the persistent
downsizing. The phenomenon spread in the 1990s from blue-collar to
white-collar workers, and from manufacturing to service industries.
Growing competition has also played a role, and so have corporate
mergers.
</P>
<P>
   ``American companies are much more concerned than in the past
about labor fat in their organizations,'' said Jared Bernstein, a
labor economist at the Economic Policy Institute in Washington.
``Some of that has to do with a heightened emphasis on short-term
profits, achieved in part through labor-cost cutting.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the latest survey brought a bright side. While layoffs
have risen among white-collar workers and women, job losers found
themselves re-employed quickly. Seventy-six percent of the 2.4
million full-time workers laid off in the latest three-year period
found themselves re-employed in full-time jobs by the time of the
survey, which was conducted last February. The rest were still
among the unemployed or had dropped out of the labor force.
</P>
<P>
   But that 76 percent was up from 72 percent in the mid-1990s and
69.6 percent in the late 1980s. What is more, the median period
between jobs fell to 4.1 weeks from 5.1 in the 1993-1995 period,
and 6.1 weeks in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   When part-timers are added to the mix, then the rate of
re-employment falls and the average wage for those who are
re-employed also falls. It is 10 percent or more below the earnings
in the old job, according to a recent study by Farber. The Bureau
of Labor Statistics does not include such data in the published
results of its surveys. But among the full-timers who were
re-employed in full-time jobs, 55 percent earned as much or more in
their new jobs as they had in their old ones, the bureau said. That
was up from 48 percent in the previous survey, but down from 60
percent in the late 1980s, also boom years.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, seeking to highlight its assistance
programs for dislocated workers, focused on the 24 percent of
full-time workers who were re-employed in full-time jobs by the
time of the survey, but in jobs with salaries that were 20 percent
or more below their old wages.
</P>
<P>
   They are ``why the department's programs and grants to assist
dislocated workers are so important,'' Secretary of Labor Alexis
Herman said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Bureau of Labor Statistics also compiles job displacement
numbers for people laid off after having held jobs for three or
more years, a figure that most labor economists consider less
important than the broader category. The trend for the
longer-tenured jobholders was roughly the same, although the
decline sharper _ 3.6 million displaced workers in the 1995-1997
period, compared with 4.2 million in the 1993-1995 period.
</P>
<P>
   The latest survey also documented trends in downsizing that have
characterized the 1990s. The job loss rate for women is now nearly
as high as the one for men: 6.5 percent of all adult women employed
versus 6.7 percent for men. Whites, blacks and Hispanics are also
gradually converging, with the white displacement rate at 6.1
percent in the latest survey, blacks at 7.1 percent and Hispanics
at 8.8 percent. The spread was twice as great in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   And since the last survey, in 1996, the layoff rate among
manufacturing workers has declined slightly, while that for service
workers has edged up, continuing trends that go back to the 1980s,
when they were much more pronounced. Still, blue-collar workers are
more likely to be laid off, with 1 of every 20 blue-collar workers
losing jobs in the latest three-year period, compared with 1 in
every 22 white-collar workers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
