<SLUG> BC-MA-BODY-FOUND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BODY FOUND IN CONCRETE MAY BE MISSING WOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: N.C.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There is a final photograph of Kimberly Magnarelli in
her final hour: dressed in a dark party dress, standing with her
live-in boyfriend at the UMass prom.
</P>
<P>
   The picture was taken May 22, eight days before the graduation
ceremonies that Magnarelli had worked toward for eight years. Now
the snapshot is a crucial piece of evidence in a gruesome murder
case that apparently began that very night, when Magnarelli was
seen alive for the last time.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on a tip Wednesday, police discovered what appears to be
the body of the college senior, wrapped in black plastic and sealed
in concrete steps beneath her Holbrook, Mass. home. State police
detectives are now on a hunt for her boyfriend, Heath W. Saffores,
who they believe fled the country shortly after his girlfriend
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fair to characterize Mr. Saffores's conduct as
flight,'' said Norfolk County District Attorney Jeffrey Locke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Magnarelli, 25, and Saffores, 24, met as students at the
University of Massachusetts in Boston, Locke said. A university
spokewoman said Magnarelli was majoring in psychology.
</P>
<P>
   They had only been dating a short time when Saffores, from North
Carolina, moved in with Magnarelli sometime within the past nine
months. Police conducted a search of their home at 11 Orchard Place
in May, after a relative reported Magnarelli was missing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  At the time, police brought in body-sniffing dogs and a team
of investigators but found only the dress she had worn to the prom,
hanging in a closet. It was not until Tuesday night, after a tip
from a friend of Saffores, that troopers returned to the house and
found the bags that appear to contain Magnarelli's corpse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very deliberate effort to conceal this burial site,
and it did so,'' Locke said.
</P>
<P>
   After Magnarelli was reported missing, Saffores returned to
Marshville, N.C., his hometown, in early June with Sven Diemer, a
close friend who is from Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Saffores stopped to visit relatives, and even indicated that he
might remain in North Carolina for good, according to Angela K.
Saffores, who was married to his father, Skip Saffores, for several
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `So, Heath, you've come to join the farm again,' and
he said, `Yes,' '' his former stepmother recalled. ``I asked him
did he want me to find him a girlfriend, and he said yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Saffores added, ``He never mentioned the girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Police believe that Saffores and Diemer then fled the country.
Saffores never returned.
</P>
<P>
   But Diemer came back to North Carolina earlier this week,
prompting authorities there to contact Norfolk County authorities.
Investigators flew into town to interview Diemer, and quickly
learned the whereabouts of Magnarelli's body.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday night, a team of two detectives, a police
photographer and DA Locke returned to the Holbrook home.
</P>
<P>
   Within half an hour, investigators had discovered an apparent
hideaway in a flight of wooden steps in the basement, covering a
slab of relatively new concrete.
</P>
<P>
   After chipping away at the concrete, Locke said, he and the
other investigators were able to see ``some shape of the
wrappings.'' A team of crime scene specialists returned Wednesday
to continue the excavation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of steps that we have to go through before
we declare that Kim Magnarelli has been found,'' Locke said. After
the body has been removed, Locke said, it must be postively
identified through dental records and an autopsy will be performed.
</P>
<P>
   Although Locke said the murder appeared to be connected to
domestic violence, a former employer of Magnarelli said that when
Saffores occasionally visited her at work, there seemed to be no
tension between the two.
</P>
<P>
   But Brad McMenimon, owner of the Flying Locksmiths, the
Randolph, Mass. business where Magnarelli worked for about five
years as an office manager, said she had seemed annoyed at the
presence of Diemer, a native of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was supposed to stay for one night, and he stayed for two
months,'' McMenimon said.
</P>
<P>
   Locke said Diemer _ who came to Boston in January _ is not a
suspect, and is not in custody.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
