<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VINEYARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TURNS 52 IN SECLUSION WITH FAMILY, JORDAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-STARR, CLINTON-POLITICS, CLINTON-HEARTLAND,
CLINTON-MCHALE, CLINTON-POLLS) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ After a quiet day spent only with his family,
President Clinton celebrated his 52nd birthday Wednesday night with
his informal counselor, golfing buddy and locker-room confidant
Vernon Jordan Jr., resuming a close association interrupted by the
Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, his wife and their daughter spent the evening with
Jordan and his wife, Ann, at the Jordans' borrowed home here on
Martha's Vineyard, where the first family is vacationing.
</P>
<P>
   The informal birthday dinner, shared by no other guests, gave
Clinton and Jordan their first extended time together since Jordan
was subpoenaed in January by Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater
independent counsel. Jordan appeared several times before Starr's
grand jury to explain his role in helping find Monica Lewinsky a
job before she gave testimony in Paula Jones' sexual misconduct
suit against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said after his grand jury appearances that he had
testified truthfully about his efforts on Ms. Lewinsky's behalf and
that he remained a close and loyal friend of the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what loyalty is,'' he said at the time. ``And I'm not a
fool.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan is one of a handful of friends with whom Clinton feels
completely at ease talking about policy, politics or intensely
personal matters. Jordan has described their conversations over the
years as ranging from discussions of political strategy to
``locker-room talk'' about their shared appreciation for attractive
women.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely that Clinton and Jordan engaged in any
soul-searching discussion of the Lewinsky matter Wednesday night,
given the presence at the Jordan house of their wives and Chelsea
Clinton. But Jordan has continued to be a friend and ally of the
president, even as Starr's investigation has forced a separation
between them.
</P>
<P>
   Michael McCurry, the White House press secretary, said Clinton
and Jordan had seen each other at several events this year,
including a state dinner and a basketball game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not aware that they've had any long conversations,''
McCurry said, ``but I think the president will enjoy spending this
time with his friend on his birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry shed little light on the family ``repair work'' that he
said Clinton was determined to do on this 12-day island sojourn. He
said all three of the Clintons slept late Wednesday and had
breakfast and lunch together. They read and walked around the
property of their temporary home, owned by Richard Friedman, a
Boston developer and major Democratic contributor.
</P>
<P>
   As for the efforts at familial ``healing,'' McCurry said, ``I
think that's a private matter, and if they choose to say anything
publicly about that, that will be their choice, not my choice.''
</P>
<P>
   He also dismissed criticism of the president's conduct from
several members of Congress and calls from some for his
resignation. There is no chance of Clinton's stepping down, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president is confident that he enjoys the trust of
the American people, who elected him,'' McCurry said, ``and he will
continue to do the work he was elected to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton took several congratulatory calls on his birthday from
members of his family, including his brother, Roger, and Mrs.
Clinton's brothers, Hugh and Tony. But several friends of the
president who are on the island said they intended to grant him the
privacy he seemed to want.
</P>
<P>
   The novelist William Styron, who along with his wife, Rose, is
among the leading social lights of the island and has given
numerous parties for the Clintons in the past, said he would wait
for them to call him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have much to say,'' Styron said. ``They're obviously
in a kind of seclusion at the moment. I probably will see them at
one point or another. I don't think people want to intrude on their
privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   The prominent Boston lawyer Alan Dershowitz, who vacations on
Martha's Vineyard and has seen the Clintons socially over the
years, said most of the couple's friends were reluctant to initiate
social contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year we all think they need to have time to themselves
and they should not be put under pressure,'' Dershowitz said. ``If
they get a call from a big giver, they may feel an obligation.''
</P>
<P>
   The cartoonist Jules Feiffer, who had a biting cartoon about the
president in The New York Times Wednesday, said Clinton friends _ a
circle in which he does not include himself _ were hanging back
because of the situation's awkwardness.
</P>
<P>
   ``My suspicion _ based on nothing, not having spoken with anyone
_ is that people are rather embarrassed and don't know how to
react,'' Feiffer said, ``because the ones who are supporters and
like the fact he comes here and like to hang out with him, while
appalled by Ken Starr, are equally appalled by the president, so
that there are no heroes here, there are no good guys here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
