<SLUG> BC-ARCH-MOBILEMEDIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEGOTIATIONS COULD LEAD TO SECOND-LARGEST PAGING COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In another sign that the paging industry is consolidating amid
falling prices and increased competition from wireless phone
services, Arch Communications Inc. says it is negotiating to buy
MobileMedia Corp. and to take the New Jersey company out of
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   In a complex deal, Arch will pay $479 million in cash and stock,
and assume $60 million in MobileMedia debt.
</P>
<P>
   Terms were still being negotiated late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   If completed, the merger would create the nation's second
largest paging company, behind Paging Network Inc. of Dallas, with
more than seven million customers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Arch, of Westborough, Mass., provides paging services mostly
to small businesses in small- and medium-sized markets, while Fort
Lee, N.J.-based &UR;  &LR; MobileMedia, through its MobileComm subsidiary,
concentrates on big customers accounts in major cities.
</P>
<P>
   C. Edward Baker, chairman and chief executive of Arch, said the
deal would not only expand Arch's current customer base, but also
would give it the resources to satisfy customers' demands for more
advanced services, such as two-way messaging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers are becoming more discerning and more demanding,''
he said in an interview. ``They want more out of their paging
service.''
</P>
<P>
   Paging has been affected by the growing popularity of wireless
telephones, especially those with digital Personal Communication
Services features that allow customers to receive text messages on
their telephone handset. That has led many industry observers to
predict that basic pagers will soon be as obsolete as rotary
telephones.
</P>
<P>
   Customers may not want to carry two electronic devices when they
can get all the functions they need with one.
</P>
<P>
   But Baker calls that a misconception. ``There's absolutely no
evidence at all to suggest that the paging business is being
pinched by digital PCS,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   International Data Corp./LINK of Framingham, Mass. tends to
agree that people aren't going to toss out their pagers any time
soon.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent IDC survey, more than two-thirds of respondents &UR;  &LR; 
said they would not stop carrying their pagers even if their
wireless phone provided short messaging service.
</P>
<P>
   IDC/LINK analyst Callie Pottorf said paging customers find their
pagers less intrusive than wireless phones and prefer the extra
battery power and wider coverage area that pagers offer.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said he believes paging services will soon allow users to
not only send and receive text messages from the tiny box on their
hip, but also to read e-mail or log into the Internet or their
company's corporate Intranet.
</P>
<P>
   ``What paging and messaging devices do,'' he said, ``is untether
people from their e-mail and the Internet the way wireless phones
have untethered people from their voicemail and their wireline
phones.''
</P>
<P>
   Arch already provides some two-way messaging service through a
reseller agreement with SkyTel, another paging company, but plans
to use licenses controlled by MobileMedia to eventually build its
own two-way paging network, Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal is approved by Arch shareholders and various
regulatory agencies, it would get MobileMedia out of bankruptcy
court. The company sought bankruptcy protection from creditors in
January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also has financial benefits for debt-laden Arch and its
shareholders, Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of heavy spending on transmission towers and a
string of acquisitions, Arch currently has $1 billion in debt.
Based on its operating cash flow, that's a debt burden far above
industry norms, Baker said. As a result, credit rating agencies
have rated Arch's bonds below investment grade, or ``junk'' status.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with MobileMedia will actually improve Arch's
debt-to-cash flow ratio even though the combined companies' total
debt will mushroom to $1.35 billion, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Under the proposed terms of the deal, Arch will pay
MobileMedia secured creditors $262 million raised from the sale of
new bonds and $217 million in proceeds from newly issued shares and
stock-purchase rights. The new stock will be given to unsecured
MobileMedia creditors, who will end up owning 66 percent and 69
percent of the combined company. Existing Arch shareholders will
own the remainder.
</P>
<P>
   MobileMedia shareholders would get nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The deal still faces several hurdles, including approval by Arch
shareholders, by the Federal Communications Commission by the
bankruptcy court.
</P>
<P>
   The news lifted Arch shares and bonds. Arch stock rose 7/16 to 3
7/8 Wednesday, and its 10 7/8 percent bonds due 2008 rose to 60
cents on the dollar from 54, traders said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 2023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
