<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISS-PAKISTAN-380&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS JUDGE URGES INDICTMENT OF BHUTTO FOR MONEY-LAUNDERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ A Swiss investigating magistrate said Wednesday that he
had amassed enough evidence, including the purchase of a diamond
necklace, to indict former Pakistani Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto
on money-laundering charges tied to contracts with two Geneva-based
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The magistrate, Daniel Devaud, decided not to bring the charges
against Mrs. Bhutto in Switzerland, but rather to ask Pakistani
authorities to indict her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is not able to leave the country to defend herself, so I
have asked Pakistan to bring the charges,'' Devaud said. Mrs.
Bhutto was forced from office in November 1996 amid corruption
charges and has since been under travel restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   The Geneva magistrate has been conducting a wide-ranging inquiry
seeking to account for more than $13.7 million frozen by Swiss
authorities last fall. The money was allegedly stashed in Swiss
banks by Mrs. Bhutto and her husband, Asif Ali Zardari.
</P>
<P>
   Devaud, who indicted three others related to the case in June,
also asked Pakistani authorities last month to indict Zardari on
similar charges.
</P>
<P>
   For now, it is unclear if or how soon Pakistani government
investigators would act on the Swiss request, or even whether Mrs.
Bhutto could be tried for a breach of Swiss law in a Pakistani
court.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss request _ which concerns a relatively small portion of
the vast wealth the Bhuttos have amassed _ may be relatively far
down on the list of concerns for the Pakistani investigators. Only
last week, they brought the first criminal charges against Mrs.
Bhutto in their long efforts to track down what8they estimate is
$1.5 billion the couple received in bribes, kickbacks and
commissions in a variety of enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Devaud said that part of some 150 pages of evidence sent to
Pakistan officials by the Swiss included documentation of the
purchase of a $188,370 diamond necklace. That money, he emphasized,
was only a small part of the funds his investigation has uncovered.
He declined to give an exact figure, but said the amount was in
excess of $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   The money, investigators say, came from payments made by Societe
Generale de Surveillance Holding SA and Cotecna Inspection SA, two
of the world's leading goods inspections companies, to a Bhutto
family lawyer, who deposited them in off-shore accounts.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Since freezing the Bhutto accounts last fall, Swiss authorities
have cast a wide net for criminal wrongdoing. This spring, federal
officials disclosed that they had been investigating whether any
money in the Swiss accounts came from drug trafficking as well.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss federal prosecutor Carla del Ponte asked the country's
banks to review their records to match accounts with a list of
Pakistani nationals. The list included the names of some 350 people
or organizations, including high-ranking military officers,
politicians, government officials and close advisers to Mrs.
Bhutto.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss banks had until the end of May to respond, but the
findings are confidential, the prosecutor's office said. Canvassing
the banks, argued Mrs. Bhutto's lawyer, Dominique Poncet, is
``completely unfounded.'' Mrs. Bhutto has denied corruption
charges, calling them a political vendetta.
</P>
<P>
   Since the fall, Devaud says he has found additional Bhutto
accounts, but has released no official overall amount held in them.
Pakistani investigators insist that some $500 million has been
uncovered in 19 Swiss bank accounts. The proceeds, they say, are
from Mrs. Bhutto's cuts on government contracts and drug deals,
however this has not been confirmed by the Swiss.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan's anti-corruption team, headed by Saifur Rehman, has
been focusing on money and property that Mrs. Bhutto and her
husband stowed abroad in their names or that of Mrs. Bhutto's
mother, Nusrat Bhutto. In addition to Swiss accounts, six
properties and seven bank accounts in Britain have been located,
Rehman said, in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Mrs. Bhutto and her husband, the three others
indicted include a Bhutto family lawyer, Jens Schlegelmilch, and
two top executives of the goods inspections companies.
</P>
<P>
   According to Devaud, the indictments center on the commissions
paid by the companies for Pakistan's inspection business. One
company, Societe Generale de Surveillance, has been embroiled in a
long-running dispute with Pakistan following the cancellation of
its contract.
</P>
<P>
   One of those indicted on money-laundering charges is former head
of government contracts for the company, Hans Fischer.
Investigators allege that he paid money to Mariston Securities, an
offshore company controlled by Zardari, as commissions or kickbacks
for contracts awarded.
</P>
<P>
   According to documents made public by Pakistani investigators,
Societe Generale de Surveillance and Cotecna, its subsidiary at the
time, pledged to pay commissions to off-shore companies
incorporated in the names of Zardari and Nusrat Bhutto. The
commissions or fees ranged between 3 percent and 6 percent. From
1995 to 1997, the two cargo review firms inspected more than $15.4
billion in imports into Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Societe Generale de Surveillance officials have defended
Fischer, and said the company ``was not used as a laundering
machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Also indicted was Cotecna head Robert Massey. He maintained in
an interview that his family company, which operates in 50
countries worldwide, acted legally. ``We don't pay any bribes and
we never will,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While it is unclear whether charges based on violations of Swiss
law could be tried outside the country, winning any such conviction
will depend on a successful criminal case against Mrs. Bhutto and
her husband in Pakistan. This is because Swiss money-laundering law
requires that the underlying legal offense, usually corruption or
bribery, be proved in the country in which it occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't launder money unless it's a result of a crime,''
said Schlegelmilch.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss, moreover, do not recognize bribing foreign officials
as a crime. In fact, Swiss law permits commissions to be paid to
foreigners, including bureaucrats, to obtain a contract, and such
sums are tax deductible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 2024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2156 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS     08-19 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANTRAS FROM THE TUNA MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Most of the people here gained access to this
small room by using a secret code and waiting for a secured door to
open. There are others, nonmembers, who had to pound on the forest
green door and wait for an insider to appear. But everyone is here
for the same reason. We have come to hear the tangential riffs of
the Tuna Man, the football mystic.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who pack all their belongings in
bumper-stickered Volkswagens and follow bands such as Phish across
North America. There are also men and women who sit down daily for
30 minutes _ at least _ and listen to New York Jets coach Bill
Parcells preach sports at Hofstra University.
</P>
<P>
   Notice we didn't say football. It's not just football with this
man. This is part religion. Part philosophy. Part Language of Bill,
filled with symphonies of ``you knows'' and ``OKs.'' He talks about
everything, but it is understood that we are all gathered because
we love sports. Some of us are worse off than others. Which leads
me to this full disclosure: I need help; I miss the man who for
four years held his sacred sports talks in Foxborough, Mass., as
coach of the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what your position is on the Bob Kraft-Parcells
divorce, didn't Parcells always make you look at football and
sports differently?
</P>
<P>
   He enters the room. Same as usual. Very large khaki shorts, a
Jets T-shirt, white socks slightly rolled toward his sneakers, and
the famous Tuna waddle. In the next 40 minutes, he will look at his
watch a few times and say he will leave soon. But he can't. Not
yet. For all the bluster, it is obvious Parcells enjoys his
listeners as much as they enjoy him.
</P>
<P>
   Someone has asked him about old-school uniforms and logos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a traditional guy; that's one of my problems, I guess,''
he says. ``And that's not conducive to the marketing end of
everything. I am in no way attempting to diminish the importance of
that, you understand? But, you know, the greatest-looking uniforms
in sports are the ones that have kind of stood the test of time.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the essence of sports talk. Who has the nicest uniforms?
What's your favorite number? Who are the three best basketball
players from the West Coast? Parcells is right. He is a
traditionalist. He happens to be coaching in an era in which the
most basic sports trait has been whittled away: talking about past
and present players _ of all sports _ and putting them in a larger
historical context.
</P>
<P>
   Back to the uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a look at the Yankees uniform, the Dodgers uniform, the
St. Louis Cardinals baseball uniform,'' he says, pausing briefly.
``Look at the Steelers, the Packers, Kansas City ... teams that
have been the same for many, many years. I'm not saying there isn't
a place for change or difference but I just, you know, when you see
those Yankee pinstripes, you know what you're looking at. Nobody
has to tell you what that is. Or the Red Sox. Teams that have a
good, traditional, nice uniform.''
</P>
<P>
   Understand this about football coaches: Ninety-five percent of
them don't talk like this. Many of them are perpetual conspiracy
theorists. You're out to get them, aren't you? They need to
(itals)watch the films(unitals). They need to (itals)put some
points on the board(unitals) (where else are they going to go?).
They need to (itals)focus(unitals). Bill Parcells rambles. This is
good. He is the coach who isn't ashamed to say what most coaches
are thinking.
</P>
<P>
   His Jets play the Giants tonight in East Rutherford, N.J.
Someone in the front of the room is anticipating that game. Even
mentions something about bragging rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' Parcells smirks, ``two minutes after it's over, nobody
is ever going to talk about it anymore. It's another preseason
game. Bragging rights are overrated. Who you braggin' to? It's
preseason. You braggin' to somebody in preseason? Come on.''
</P>
<P>
   On and on it goes. It is never boring. Few people leave. Even
Kraft can tell you this. He used to be a regular at these Parcells
retreats. The Packers' LeRoy Butler said last year that Parcells
took too much credit for the Patriots getting to the Super Bowl. He
said many of the Patriots felt the same way and were scared to say
just that to the coach. Maybe they should have spoken up. He said
he doesn't mind someone getting in his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if anybody shouts back at me, as long as they
know what they're talking about,'' he is saying. It is getting
late. He looks at his watch. He keeps talking. ``I've never cared
about that. I tell 'em, `Say what you want to say.' Hey, if some
guy is shooting his mouth off and doesn't know what he's talking
about, then he's the same as any other guy in this business: You
tell him to shut up until he finds out what's going on. You know?
If someone knows what's going on and they've got some points to
make and just happen to do it vocally, that doesn't bother me. I
don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember: He talks about everything.
</P>
<P>
   As he talks, you begin to see how his stories fall into place.
Have you ever had a teacher who, you thought, didn't like you? Ten
years later, you find out that you were the teacher's favorite.
Contemporary players are like that with Parcells. He talked fondly
of the Giants when he was in New England. He talks fondly of the
Patriots now that he is back in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of his favorite fullbacks, he talks about Jets running
backs coach Maurice Carthon, a former fullback, and adds, ``Mo
could always see it and know what to do. And then he taught that to
(Sam) Gash, and that's how Gash got to be a great blocker. Those
kids don't get to be great by accident. There's a whole
chronological path that they have to take to be great.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bruce Armstrong?
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these offensive linemen that you've seen be successful
for so long, you know, Bruce Armstrong is a good example. He knows
how to do it. It's not tedious anymore. Sure, when it's 104 and you
have to do a drill, it's not fun. But mentally, you are not
destroyed by your occupation. 'Cause you know how to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He glances at the watch again. He says he needs food. A piece of
fruit or something. He also says he likes Glenn Foley at
quarterback for many reasons, one of which is ``I'm half Irish, if
that means anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably not. But we are here to listen to Bill. He talks about
everything. Almost. A local paper's headline blares, ``Liar,
Liar,'' referring to President Clinton and his relationship with
Monica Lewinsky. But this Bill doesn't want to talk about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about her?'' he says rhetorically of Lewinsky. ``Oh,
don't get me in that one. I'll let the other guy handle that one.''
</P>
<P>
   He leaves. He'll be back tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Michael Holley is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
