<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-UPDATE-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Aug. 23,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (`e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TANGLEWOOD-FESTIVAL (Lenox, Mass.) _ Tanglewood is, to be sure,
many things: first and foremost, a festival and retreat of the
Boston Symphony Orchestra here in the idyllic Berkshire Hills. So
when several respected teachers at the orchestra's venerable
training institute, the Tanglewood Music Center, loudly and angrily
resigned late last year in response to a redirection of the
center's activities by Seiji Ozawa, the longtime music director of
the Boston Symphony, it was not clear how much the average
festivalgoer's experience would be affected, if at all. By James R.
Oestreich. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   STUPID-KIDS-THEATER (New York) _ Written by John C. Russell, who
died of AIDS in 1994 at the age of 31, ``Stupid Kids'' opened Off
Broadway in June to a shaky start at the WPA Theater, where it
received several mixed reviews, with some critics complaining of a
thin story. Still, the 80-minute play, directed by Michael Mayer,
seemed to be finding its legs just as it closed in July. Now it has
been given another chance. It begins a commercial run on Tuesday at
the Century Theater with a gilt-edged pack of producers behind it.
By Steven Drukman. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TEA-WITH-MUSSOLINI-FILM (Rome) _ ``Tea with Mussolini,'' which
is being directed by Franco Zeffirelli this summer in Rome and
Florence, is based on his memories of wartime and the years just
before, when he was an illegitimate, motherless young Florentine.
It's a homage to a group of eccentric English ladies who
essentially adopted him, and who tried to preserve their own
civility and Florence's treasures as war closed in around them. By
Alessandra Stanley. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-CRITICS (Undated) _ For better and worse, critics find
themselves integral to the process of promoting movies, and there
are times when we gratefully seize that opportunity. Consider
``Western,'' a beguiling, offbeat French film that I adore. By
Janet Maslin. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-PLACE (Undated) _ If home is indeed where the heart is,
then the repertory in which a musician feels most at home may have
more to do with aptitude and sympathy than with where that musician
was born or lives. Yet sometimes a relationship between geography
and music holds true, and two new piano recordings, by Stephen
Hough and Leif Ove Andsnes, make a persuasive case for the power of
place. By David Mermelstein. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   RAKE'S-PROGRESS-OPERA (Undated) _ Igor Stravinsky was a slow
worker. He produced, on average, one major composition, or an
equivalent number of smaller ones, per year. Of course, he lived
many years, from 1882 to 1971, and produced many works, about 100,
though only a handful run longer than a half-hour. The longest by
far is his only full-length opera, ``The Rake's Progress.'' Each of
its three acts took a year to compose. By Anthony Tommasini.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ELLIOTT-SMITH-MUSIC (Undated) _ ``Everybody's dying just to get
the disease,'' sang Elliott Smith about the perils of fame in
``Pictures of Me,'' one of the most memorable pop songs of last
year. It appeared on ``Either/Or,'' Smith's third album, and it was
a startlingly advanced report of dissaffection sung in a high voice
by a slouchy 27-year-old Beatles fan from Portland, Ore., with a
pallid, wounded demeanor. By Ben Ratliff. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   LAURYN-HILL-MUSIC (Undated) _ On her solo debut album, ``The
Miseducation of Lauryn Hill,'' the rapper, singer and visionary
artist Lauryn Hill imagines herself as part of a very old story. It
transcends her own 23-year-old life, as stimulating as that may be
with the success of her hip-hop group, the Fugees, her highly
promising career as a musician and producer and her personal
happiness mothering a baby boy. By Ann Powers. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PRINCESS'S-PEOPLE-TV (Undated) _ With Britain bracing itself for
a relentless barrage of Princess-Diana-related television
programming in the next few weeks, it is not surprising that ``The
Princess's People,'' one of the shows on offer, has generated a bit
of unflattering advance publicity. Maybe because it shows, among
other things, Londoners swearing at the television set during the
broadcast of the Princess of Wales's funeral last year. By Sarah
Lyall. (Moved). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  MIND-TRAVELER-TV (Undated) _ A four-part PBS series called
``Oliver Sacks: The Mind Traveler,'' begins Tuesday at 8 p.m. _
stories of people with autism or total color-blindness or Usher's
syndrome, another rare genetic condition, in which a person is born
deaf and then gradually goes blind in young adulthood. By Natalie
Angier. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   DAILY-SHOW-TV (Undated) _ ``The Daily Show,'' is America's most
perfect rendering of comedy post-modernism. Running, well, nightly
at 11 p.m. on cable's Comedy Central, ``The Daily Show'' is what
happens when you give the kids who used to make fun of you their
own television show. By Jeff MacGregor. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  BAY-BRIDGE-ARCHITECTURE (San Francisco) _ When it comes to bridge
designers practicing in the world today, there's the Spanish
architect and engineer Santiago Calatrava and there's everyone
else. Isn't that awful? This fact has certainly lent an air of
independence, if not futility, to San Francisco's search for a new
design for the Bay Bridge. Why should Bay area residents settle for
genius and deprive themselves of the freedom to choose something
second rate? By Herbert Muschamp. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (`t' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-DUBLIN (Undated) _ Two takes on swank among Dublin
hotels. By Sarah Lyall. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CAUCASUS (Undated) _ a mystical aura over Georgia. By
stephen Kinzer. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CRUISE-HEALTH (Undated) _ When ship inspection misses
stowaway germs. By Edwain McDowell. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ Easing the way on two wheels. By
Sue Halpern. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Russian companion for the Queen Mary;
A cautious opening to Lebanon; Tiepolo in Paris, 300 years later;
Spiffy new theater in Lancaster County, Pa.: In Oregon, a portrait
of tribal life. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Questions and answers on travel. This
week: Frankfurt sightseeing; All aboard for the Rockies; Atlanta to
Savannah. By Paul Freireich. (Moved).
</P>
</TEXT>
