</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CLINTON-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: CLINTON ON THE WIRE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add `CLINTON' to slug)   By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``No one is ever better on the high wire,'' said former White
House press secretary Dee Dee Myers in a television appearance
before Bill Clinton's address to the nation on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   One of the problems is that the president takes so many people
up on the high wire with him. If he falls it's a catastrophe. On
Monday night, not long after Ms. Myers' comment, Clinton lost his
balance. But he didn't fall. His performance is shakier than ever,
but he's still up there.
</P>
<P>
   The question is why the president feels the need to take such
foolish risks in the first place, risks that put him and so many
others in jeopardy. Is it all a game? Or is it a kind of sickness?
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had a chance to climb down from the wire on Monday. The
public has made it overwhelmingly clear that it is sick of the
sordid Lewinsky melodrama. The Republicans in Congress have no
stomach for impeachment, and there has been no evidence disclosed
as yet that would warrant impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, the chairman of the Judiciary Committee,
offered Clinton an out and practically begged him to take it. In an
appearance on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' early this month, Hatch
said: ``If he comes forth and tells it and does it in the right way
and there aren't a lot of other factors to cause the Congress to
say, `This man is unfit for the presidency and should be
impeached,' then I think the president would have a reasonable
chance of getting through this.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I think the American people would breathe a sigh of
relief.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a serious olive branch. It should not have been
difficult to accept. Close friends and aides to Clinton, finally
aware, like most Americans, that the president had been lying all
along, were saying the same thing. They urged him to help put the
matter to rest by telling the full truth and offering a sincere
apology to the nation for the grief and the harm he had caused.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, wobbling on the swaying wire, shook his head. ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on television and offered defiance where so many had
hoped to see contrition. He never admitted that he had lied at all.
He never apologized. And he angrily attacked Kenneth Starr, the
Whitewater independent counsel. Starr is certainly vulnerable to
attack, but most of Clinton's advisers felt that Monday night's
address to the nation was not the place to do it. All you had to do
was look at Senator Hatch's response to the president's four-minute
speech to see why they felt as they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just gonna blow my stack,'' said Hatch on NBC. Change the
channel. ``I'm just gonna blow my cork,'' said Hatch on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has not helped to put the matter to rest. The sense of
betrayal among the president's supporters, which was inevitable, is
mixed with the horrifying suspicion that he is in no way
remorseful, that he couldn't care less about the friends and the
aides who put their credibility on the line for him, the colleagues
whose legal bills in some cases have left them close to bankruptcy,
the ardent followers whose trust he has squandered like a
compulsive gambler feeding borrowed money into a slot machine.
</P>
<P>
   The president remained silent for more than half a year,
allowing people who cared deeply about him to submerge their
reputations in his lies. And, true to a decades-long pattern, he
would still be promoting those lies and playing the American people
for fools if he hadn't been confronted by what appears to be a
mountain of virtually irrefutable evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's job approval ratings remain extremely high. The public
does not want him to resign or be impeached. Among other things, it
does not want Kenneth Starr deciding who will be president.
</P>
<P>
   The high poll ratings may actually encourage in Clinton a giddy
sense that he can get away with anything. Behind the numbers,
however, is the widespread realization that this is a man who has
disgraced himself and his office and who cannot be trusted, even by
his closest friends. That view will be reinforced by each new and
dismaying revelation.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a story that can be wished away. When the president
has a problem we all have a problem. We are all on the high wire
with him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
