</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORDING CHANGE SKEWED POLL AFTER CLINTON SPEECH
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: CLINTON-STARR, CLINTON-POLITICS, CLINTON-VINEYARD,
CLINTON-HEARTLAND, CLINTON-MCHALE) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A small change in the wording of a poll question by The Gallup
Organization led to a significant overstatement of the drop in
President Clinton's personal favorability rating after his speech
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a 20-point drop in personal favorability, reported by
Gallup and picked up by several news organizations, including The
New York Times in both its news and editorial pages, the actual
drop now appears to be considerably less.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's survey, taken after the president's speech,
respondents were asked: ``Now thinking about Bill Clinton as a
person, do you have a favorable or unfavorable opinion of him?''
That elicited responses from the public that were 40 percent
favorable and 48 percent unfavorable. In previous Gallup polls, the
wording was: ``Now I'd like to get your opinion about some people
in the news. As I read the name, please say if you have a favorable
or unfavorable opinion of this person.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, that traditional wording resulted in public
impressions of Clinton that were 60 percent favorable and 38
percent unfavorable. Thus, it appeared on Monday that there had
been a 20-percentage point drop in Clinton's personal ratings.
</P>
<P>
   In a poll on Tuesday, however, Gallup used the traditional
wording and measured 55 percent favorable views of Clinton and 42
percent unfavorable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
