<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA CAUGHT IN FINANCIAL QUANDARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also DEVALUE-ECONSCENE) 
(mk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Russian leaders, struggling to bail out
their nation's banks from billions of dollars' worth of currency
and bond deals with Western financial institutions, find themselves
caught in an excruciating dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   The plans that government leaders first announced on Monday
could cost foreign lenders billions of dollars, a move that could
shred Russia's lingering credibility in global financial markets.
But if the government defers to foreign lenders, as it suggested on
Tuesday, Russia's banking system would veer closer to collapse.
</P>
<P>
   These equally scary outcomes were reflected Wednesday in another
stampede out of the Russian stock market, a barometer of foreign
investor confidence. The dollar-denominated Russian RTS index fell
9.42 percent, its third consecutive tumble, leaving it at a record
low of 90.19. It has fallen nearly 40 percent this month.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations with Western banks are under way in Moscow, and no
solution is expected until next week. But in the meantime, two
problems stand out in particular, Western bankers and financial
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   The first is that Russian banks have entered more than $10
billion worth of currency deals with foreign lenders. If the
contracts are honored by the Russian banks _ an outcome that
remains in question _ and the Russian ruble continues to lose
value, the Russian banks would stand to lose billions. If the
contracts are not honored, though, Western banks would be stuck
with the losses.
</P>
<P>
   A second problem, according to Western executives, is that many
Russian banks are thought to have bought $4 billion to $6 billion
worth of Russian government Eurobonds with borrowed money, and the
market value of the bonds has plunged by about 50 percent in the
last month.
</P>
<P>
   Both issues came to light when the Russian government announced
its original emergency plan on Monday, which included a 90-day
moratorium on repaying foreign debts.
</P>
<P>
   Though most of the headlines this week have focused on Russia's
devaluation of the ruble, Western investors were far more shocked
by the moratorium, which appeared calculated to rescue Russian
banks from an enormous financial squeeze at the expense of foreign
lenders. Beyond costing money, the move angered Western
institutions because it was the first instance of the government of
President Boris Yeltsin being willing to break standard financial
contracts in midstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made a fundamental decision today that they were going to
save their local banks from insolvency and to disenfranchise
foreign lenders,'' said William Browder, head of the Hermitage
Fund, based in Moscow, one of the biggest Western mutual funds
devoted to Russian stocks. ``Foreigners have no value to them
unless they bring capital, and they haven't been bringing in any
capital.''
</P>
<P>
   One provision of the moratorium would have frozen payments on
``forward currency contracts.'' At issue was more than $10 billion
worth of currency agreements that foreign lenders had bought from
Russian banks to insure themselves against a devaluation of the
ruble.
</P>
<P>
   The currency contracts allowed foreign investors to buy tens of
billions of rubles' worth of Russian bonds, known as GKOs and OFZs.
These bonds have paid sky-high interest rates but are paid in
rubles.
</P>
<P>
   Dan McGovern, head of Merrill Lynch's research on
emerging-markets debt, said this week that Russian banks would face
a huge squeeze in October. That is when about $5 billion worth of
currency contracts are scheduled to come due, which means the
Russian banks would have to buy billions of rubles at prices that
could be far above market value.
</P>
<P>
   The October contracts are particularly worrisome, McGovern said,
because they were entered before the Asian financial crisis had
reached full strength. As a result, the contracts were priced to
reflect what have now proved to be wildly naive expectations about
the ruble's stability.
</P>
<P>
   The new moratorium was like ``a bomb had gone off,'' McGovern
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another provision bails out Russian banks that bought
dollar-denominated Russian government bonds. The Russian government
issued about $10 billion in new Eurobonds over the last two months,
and financial executives said that Russian banks bought a big share
of these.
</P>
<P>
   But many banks bought the Eurobonds on credit. The value of
those bonds plunged by about 50 percent in the last month amid
escalating panic about Russia's financial condition. Russian banks
must come up with much more money to cover the lost market value,
much as stock speculators have to make new margin payments when
they buy shares on credit and the shares' value falls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have a bit of sympathy for the government,'' said Sally
Wilkinson, senior economist at Daiwa Europe, the European arm of
Daiwa Securities. ``The alternative would have been to let the
banks fall, which would have led to the whole house of cards
falling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 2043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
