<SLUG> BC-CLINTONS-VINEYARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CELEBRATES BIRTHDAY IN SECLUSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ President Clinton's 52nd birthday arrived
Wednesday at the start of a vaction devoted more to mending his
marriage than to celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than raucous parties and star-studded musical tributes as
in years past, Clinton spent his birthday in seclusion with his
family. They later ventured out for a small birthday dinner with
Clinton's longtime pal Washington power broker Vernon E. Jordan and
his family.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner was the first time the Clintons have left the
Edgartown estate of Boston businessman Richard Friedman since
arriving Tuesday evening for a planned 12-day vacation on the
island of Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Michael D. McCurry said the
Clintons' slept late and spent the day reading and lounging. They
had both breakfast and lunch together, and walked around the
beachfront estate, as the Clintons seek to repair their marriage
strained by the president's public acknowledgement of a
relationship that was ``not appropriate'' with former White House
intern Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it's not as joyous a birthday as he's had in the
past,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner at Jordan's house was another reminder here of the
controversy endangering the Clinton presidency. Jordan has
testified numerous times before a federal grand jury investigating
Clinton's relationship with Lewinsky. It was Jordan who helped
Lewinsky line up a job offer after she left the White House, and
investigators have been looking into whether that help was an
attempt to keep Lewinsky silent about her relationship with
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's friendship with Clinton has since been the subject of a
guessing game in Washington, a town intently interested in the
status of who's in and who's out, as the two men who've often
golfed together, vacationed and dined together have limited their
public contact in the seven months of independent consel Kenneth W.
Starr's investigation of the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, however, Jordan was the first to greet the Clintons
on the tarmac at Martha's Vineyard airport. ``He's spending his
birthday evening with his friend,'' McCurry said. ``That's all I
would read into that.''
</P>
<P>
   This birthday was different for Clinton, who, when he reached
the half-century mark, led a party hosted by Whoopi Goldberg at
Radio City Music Hall. That bash was beamed by satellite to 20,000
people gathered at 76 locations around the country to raise $10
million for the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the president celebrated his birthday at a clambake
at the Vineyard farm of actor Ted Danson and his wife, actress Mary
Steenburgen.
</P>
<P>
   Some senior Clinton aides have urged the president to make more
public appearances during this vacation and project a stronger
image in an attempt to stave off calls for his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   But others said there were no immediate plans for the president
to play a more public role. ``He's on vacation, and the best way he
can spend his time right now is to be with his family,'' said a
senior adviser. ``That's where he belongs. We're not ready for a
road show right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon Hackney, who with his wife Lucy, often spend time with
the Clintons on the Vineyard and are expecting to this time, said
of Clinton's birthday: ``It's not one ending in zero. It's not an
existential self-examination probably going on.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Clintons probably will venture out more after a few
days of downtime, and he predicted that the president will get in
his usual rounds of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Of the president's current predicament, Hackney said, ``The
pressure must be intense, and I think it was telling in his face by
the time he got here. One thing the Vineyard can do is restore some
perspective as well as some rest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 2044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
