<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Electronic union warns GM: protect Ohio jobs
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The International Union of Electronic Workers is
warning the General Motors Corp. that it will be ``vigilant'' in
protecting blue-collar jobs once the automaker spins off the
world's largest auto parts company.
</P>
<P>
   National leaders for the IUE, which represents 11,000 GM workers
in the Miami Valley, said GM hasn't provided the union with ``all
the details'' of how their members would be affected after Delphi
Automotive Systems becomes an independent company next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agree that the spinoff has the potential to open new
opportunities that could benefit everyone involved, but to realize
these opportunities we truly believe that IUE must be involved in a
meaningful way,'' said Ed Fire, president if the International IUE.
</P>
<P>
   ``We join with the leaders of our local unions to let GM and
Delphi know that we will be vigilant in protecting the rights,
jobs, wages and benefits of our members as the spinoff moves
forward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   IUE and GM leaders are meeting in Cleveland this week to discuss
the spinoff and other issues, including the financial losses that
continue to threaten the survival of Delphi's suspension parts
plant in Kettering, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   GM and Delphi officials believe an independent Delphi could mean
more business for local plants that supply parts to most of the
world's automakers.
</P>
<P>
   But union leaders, including the United Auto Workers, aren't
sure if the spinoff is a good move for Delphi's hourly work force.
</P>
<P>
   Like the IUE, the UAW vowed to protect jobs in a statement
following GM's decision to spin off its parts unit.
</P>
<P>
   GM and Delphi officials said they will work closely with the
UAW, the IUE and all their labor unions during the spinoff
transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't respond to the UAW's statement either and won't
respond to the (IUE's spinoff comments),'' said GM spokesman Gerry
Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   Once the spinoff is complete, the Moraine Truck Assembly plant
will be the only factory out of nine local plants operating solely
under the world's largest automaker. A new diesel engine plant in
Moraine is expected to be a joint venture between GM and Isuzu
Motors. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the IUE continues its struggle to keep a suspension
parts factory in Kettering operating under Delphi. The plant, which
employs about 3,000, has lost more than $50 million over the past
two years and is in danger of being sold before the spinoff unless
its financial problems can be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from several automotive suppliers are interested in
buying the Kettering plant and have been touring the factory this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   IUE Local 755, which represents the Kettering plant, has already
accepted a three-tier wage scale at the Kettering plant that pays
new workers about $8 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its recent strike settlement with the UAW, GM
promised not to sell or close two Delphi brake plants in Dayton
before January 2000. But the Kettering plant doesn't have the same
promise.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Wagner writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
