<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2197 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAUL-BEGALA-COX     08-19 1526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAUL-BEGALA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Analysis: Clinton defender Begala 'disappointed'
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving on (a) general news and (w) washington wires.)
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even for Paul Begala, Bill Clinton's heat shield,
this has been the week from hell. While he's made defending Clinton
almost an art form, he'd done it in the belief that Clinton was
telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's admission Monday that he had 'misled' people, that he
really did have a relationship with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky, had to be a cruel slap in the face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be lying if I didn't tell you I was disappointed that a
story I was told, and I believed, and I repeated, was not true,''
said Begala, counselor to the President. But he added that the
President's sin involved his private life, not public, and he had
at least finally come forward.
</P>
<P>
   Begala, 37, a former University of Texas at Austin student
president, took the heat because he's a believer. It may sound
corny, but it's true: He believes in democracy, in people, in good,
in the truth, in public service _ all with a passion that is
electric and contagious.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rent you our heads, but we throw in our hearts for free,''
Begala and political mentor James Carville are fond of saying.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Eller, formerly Clinton's director of media affairs, said
that when Begala commits to a candidate, ``it's almost like a
religion.'' ``He has a very strong faith in God to start with, and
that sort of translates into the strength of faith with the
candidates he works for and the issues he believes in,'' said
Eller, who joined Public Strategies Inc., an Austin business
consulting firm in 1994, a few months before Begala.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton finally admitted Monday that he'd misled his wife
and daughter about his behavior, that also meant he'd also broken
the faith with Begala.
</P>
<P>
   The good though wounded soldier, while admitting his
disappointment Tuesday, dutifully tried to put his boss in as
positive a light as possible. Begala praised Clinton for finally
admitting he'd ``misled.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a lot of guts,'' Begala said.
</P>
<P>
   Begala is no stranger to defending Clinton. He began learning to
do it in 1991 and especially 1992, when he and Carville were
running Clinton's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Begala was a chief defender of Clinton in February 1992, when
allegations about Clinton's sexual relationship with Gennifer
Flowers almost buried Clinton's presidential campaign in the snows
of New Hampshire. After the election, Begala was a consultant for
the President on the staff of the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1995, when Clinton began to listen more to former
consultant Dick Morris than the team that had got him to the White
House in the first place, Begala returned to Austin. He worked for
Public Strategies headed by Jack Martin, who in the 1980s was
former U.S. Sen. Lloyd Bentsen's chief political guru.
</P>
<P>
   And Begala and I co-taught a class on politics and the press for
two semesters at The University of Texas at Austin, where his
passionate declaration to students that ``this (stuff) matters''
was almost a mantra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul is a genius when it comes to communicating with large
numbers of people,'' Martin said Wednesday. ``In addition, his
passion for his beliefs and convictions is very refreshing in
today's environment.''
</P>
<P>
   But after Morris resigned from Clinton's employ in mid-1996 in
the wake of revelations he had a long-term relationship with a
prostitute in Washington, the President's SOS for political savvy
reached Begala in Austin. In the summer of 1997, Clinton asked
Begala to come back as a top adviser. And Begala did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was motivated to return to Washington by a real
old-fashioned sense that he was serving his country,'' said Martin.
Steeped in political loyalty and public service from his own days
with Bentsen, Martin watched Begala go back to the White House with
a mixture of understanding and regret.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an enormous sense for me, both personally and
professionally, that I had lost not only a valuable asset of our
firm, but a dear friend,'' Martin said. ``Paul could light up a
room with his intellect and enthusiasm like few people I ever
met.''
</P>
<P>
   Begala's goal was to help Clinton make his final term one of
pushing through some vital programs to help people, and
particularly children, in areas like education, health and others.
</P>
<P>
   Then in January, the Lewinsky bombshell hit. Begala, who learned
of it when he picked up his newspaper on his front lawn in
Virginia, was stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like getting hit in the head with a two-by-four,'' he
told a reporter a few days later.
</P>
<P>
   He went for his morning run that day, but he also went on the
offensive for Clinton. He went on talk shows. The True Believer
vociferously attacked the special counsel, Kenneth Starr, for an
``out of control'' investigation. ``There are serious questions of
wrongdoing here,'' Begala said in February on the NBC TV show
``Meet the Press,'' ``and I think we need a truly independent
investigation of the investigation itself, so that we can know
who's behind these lies, who is behind these leaks, and let the
investigation continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Begala's warlike approach didn't surprise Eller. ``What that
sort of true-believer mentality also means is that Paul can be very
tough when he's defending his candidates,'' Eller said. ``He can be
partisan. He can be personal at times. But he can be very tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Begala and his friend and former co-worker at Public Strategies,
Mark McKinnon, cut their political teeth with Carville on Lloyd
Doggett's 1984 U.S. Senate campaign. McKinnon said back in January
that Begala was as good as they come in terms of loyalty and quick
wisdom under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were in that situation, the one guy I would want to have
right beside me is Paul Begala,'' said McKinnon, who has since
signed on as media consultant for Texas' Republican Gov. George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   What about what's happened now?
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul has a truly unique characteristic,'' said McKinnon
Wednesday. ``He goes to extraordinary lengths to see the good in
people. And sometimes that means overlooking flaws that may be
glaring to others.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when Paul said that he believed the president, I know he
actually believed the president. Some would say that that's naive,
but you have to know Paul to understand that his beliefs hinge on
an absolute devotion to the person or cause he's serving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul will seek and find shreds of light even in the darkest of
circumstances. He's a true believer and the ultimate soldier. He
stays in the foxhole when everyone else retreats. And so it's
painful to watch as he's betrayed by his own commander and hit by
friendly fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Begala in January: ``I've been through a lot with this guy; I've
worked for him off and on for six years. I believe him completely,
and I know he's telling the truth. There is an investigation. It
will clear the president.''
</P>
<P>
   As late as Friday, Begala still hadn't heard directly from
Clinton that he had lied about Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   What about Begala now?
</P>
<P>
   Begala is unlikely to follow the lead of some of the president's
former advisers, such as George Stephanopoulos or Dee Dee Meyers,
and trash Clinton on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is little doubt in my mind that Paul would be troubled
by some of this, but there's even less doubt that Paul would talk
about it in any way that would come across as non-professional,''
said Martin.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Begala repeated the question put to him by an
interviewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do I think now? I think, you know, like (former
University of Texas football coach) Darrell Royal used to say, 'You
dance with them that brung you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never knowlingly mislead anyone,'' Begala said. ``But
I felt like I owed, and I feel I owe the President a debt of
loyalty, based on the job he's done for the country, but also how
much he's helped me in my career. ``So if the worst thing that can
be said about me is that I was loyal to someone who had been good
to me, I am comfortable with that. But again, I would be lying if I
said I was not disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Eller thinks Begala's soft-pedaling it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's incredibly disappointed in the President,'' Eller
said. ``Paul is the most loyal person you'd ever want to have on
his staff _ a guy who, once he believes, it takes a tremendous
amount to shake it. And I think he's had his faith shaken, and his
heart broken.''
</P>
<P>
   So what does Begala plan to do? Well, while the President and
First Family are vacationing at Martha's Vineyard on the East
Coast, Begala will be some distance away. Today is the first day of
a two-week vacation for Begala, his wife Diane, and their three
young sons, in the mountains of Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going fishing,'' Begala said. ``I'm getting my boys and
going off into the mountains and catch me some big ole brown trout,
and maybe a few rainbows. Wet a line.''
</P>
<P>
   McNeely writes about politics for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
