<HEADER>
A2199 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUSTATASTE-COLUMN-KAN     08-19 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUSTATASTE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST A TASTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 1998 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're like me, you probably buy hazelnuts once a year for
holiday baking.
</P>
<P>
   Not Laura Barton.
</P>
<P>
   She freely admits to a year-round hazelnut obsession. So much
so, in fact, her office mates have nicknamed her the ``Hazelnut
Poster Child.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love hazelnut butter,'' she says. ``I can eat it with a
spoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Barton is international trade manager for the Oregon Department
of Agriculture's agricultural development and marketing division.
Oregon grows 98 percent of the hazelnuts grown in the United
States. The state produced 40,000 tons last year.
</P>
<P>
   On her many travels, Barton has collected hazelnut food products
from around the world and displays the packaging in her office. In
Europe, where chefs are especially fond of the hazelnut's sweet,
creamy flavor, she found hazelnut M&AMP;M's and a hazelnut-flavored
Kraft brand cake mix.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, more hazelnut-flavored products are making
it to supermarket. Pepperidge Farms sells two types of hazelnut
cookies. Godiva uses hazelnut butter and paste in some of its
chocolate candies. Ben &AMP; Jerry has a hazelnut ice-cream flavor
called Totally Nuts-Dilbert Ice Cream.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for growers has been to produce value-added
products such as butters, pastes, oils and even chopped nuts sold
under such labels as Blue Diamond to encourage Americans to eat
more hazelnuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't sit by the fire and crack nuts anymore,'' Barton
says of the nut's seasonal aura.
</P>
<P>
   Hazelnuts are also grown in Turkey and Italy, but the Oregon
nut, called the Barcelona, is larger than its European cousin.
</P>
<P>
   An English sailor is reported to have planted the first hazelnut
tree in the United States back in 1858. Sometimes referred to as a
filbert, hazelnuts are a valuable source of protein and vitamins B,
C and E.
</P>
<P>
   In Oregon, the nuts are mechanically harvested and dried in
kilns for a cleaner product with less field debris. ``We've
cultivated the nuts so they grow up into a big canopy,'' Barton
says.
</P>
<P>
   Roasting the nuts brings out their flavor, according to Lucy
Gerspacher, the Oregon-based author of the Hazelnuts &AMP; More
Cookbook (Graphic Arts Center Publishing Co.).
</P>
<P>
   In a preheated 275-degree oven, spread shelled nuts in a shallow
baking pan and roast 20 to 30 minutes, until the skins crack and
the meat turns a light golden color. You can roast them at
350-degrees 7 to 8 minutes, but watch closely to be sure they don't
burn. In the microwave, roast on high power 3 to 4 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   To remove skins, pour hot nuts in the center of a clean,
terry-cloth kitchen towel. Pull the towel up around the nuts and
twist lightly, making a hobo pack. Let stand to steam about 5
minutes. Vigorously rub the warm nuts in the towel until most of
the skins are removed. Don't be concerned if some of the skins
cling to the nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Store them in a freezer in plastic bags or an airtight
container. They will last up to two years.
</P>
<P>
   For a list of Oregon Hazelnut products, contact the Oregon
Hazelnut Marketing Board, P.O. Box 23126, Portland, Ore. 97281.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
