<SLUG> BC-FBN-JACOBS-BROWNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS OWNER MAKES CASE FOR CLEVELAND BROWNS OWNERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bruins owner Jeremy Jacobs made his pitch to own the Cleveland
Browns Wednesday in front of National Football League owners, but
his bid may ultimately require him to choose between the teams.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs received strongly positive reviews from various sources
Wednesdayfor his presentation in Atlanta, which included a
statement from Bruins president-general manager Harry Sinden, who
traveled with him. Among those praising the effort was an important
member of the NFL's Expansion Committee, Patriots owner Robert
Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft and the committee are now charged with whittling the
Jacobs proposal and six others presented Wednesday to a final group
of two or three before presenting them for a final vote by all 30
owners Sept. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Jeremy and his people did very, very well,'' Kraft
said. ``Indeed, the best thing that happened today is that after
the disaster that occurred in Cleveland three years ago, with the
team leaving a great football town, we now know that we really have
some good proposals to choose from. All of the groups did very
well, along with Jeremy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jacobs may face a choice of his own: Does he want to own an
NFL franchise in Cleveland or a National Hockey League franchise in
Boston?
</P>
<P>
   A league rule prohibits anyone from owning an NFL team who
already owns a team in another sport in a market where there is an
NFL team. The so-called cross-ownership rule would, for example,
prohibit owners of the Red Sox, Celtics, and Bruins from owning an
NFL team because of the presence of the Patriots in their market.
</P>
<P>
   The rule is in place, and favored by many of the more veteran
NFL owners, because it discourages owners from competing with each
other for sponsorship money, for fan support, and potentially on
some provisions of television contracts. Other potential conflicts
the rule seeks to avoid are stadium financing and siting issues
within the same market.
</P>
<P>
   A source close to Jacobs expressed confidence Wednesdaythat he
can manage to work around the rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL will tell you for the record that the rule exists and
everyone must abide by it,'' he said. ``But we think there are ways
of dealing with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``However,'' the source added, ``if owning the Bruins prohibits
him from owning the Browns, he is going to keep the Bruins. The
Browns would definitely be out.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs was not available for comment. FleetCenter president
Richard Krezwick, who also traveled with Jacobs and participated in
the presentation, said Jacobs's sympathies are strongly with the
Bruins _ one of the ``Original Six'' NHL franchises, which he has
owned for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told everyone Wednesday that he loves the Bruins,''
Krezwick said.
</P>
<P>
   However, while the Bruins are considered by observers to be
among the most profitable of NHL teams, NFL franchises are almost
always more profitable. And the Browns franchise is a particularly
handsome opportunity, with a new stadium under construction and
paid for and a solid base of rabid football fans in place.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns are considered so attractive, in fact, that some NFL
owners say they could ultimately attract a bid as high as $1
billion, and there is general agreement that they will eventually
be sold for at least $500 million and approach the record price tag
for a professional sports franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, who owns the Delaware North Companies, is said by
observers to be worth about $800 million.
</P>
<P>
   But others vying to own the Browns have similarly deep pockets,
and most have substantial contacts with Cleveland, including
enlisting former Browns players to be a part of their ownership
teams.
</P>
<P>
   While Delaware North's Sports Service concession company
provides concessions at Jacobs Field for the Cleveland Indians,
Jacobs's only other boast of roots in Cleveland appears to be that
his companies' headquarters is about 170 miles away, in Buffalo,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Others vying to own the Browns are: Bertram Wolstein, a suburban
Cleveland real estate developer who has been joined by former
Browns superstar running back Jim Brown as a consultant; Cleveland
lawyer Larry Dolan and his brother Charles, the chairman of
Cablevision Systems, one of the largest cable providers in the
country; businessman and banker Alfred Lerner; Richard Jacobs, who
owns the Indians and is no relation to Jeremy; Cleveland area toy
retailer Thomas Murdough; and New York real estaste developer
Howard Milstein.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft said the next step in the process will be for owners on
the Expansion Committee to review the relative financial strengths
of the proposals, with strong guidance from Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What made me feel very good about this meeting today was that
we are left with very strong alternatives,'' Kraft said. ``When the
Browns left the league and the commissioner set out to form a very
strong private-public partnership between the civic leaders and the
business community, that has resulted in really putting the Browns
back into business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
