<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2205 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGO-REBELLION-650&AMP;A     08-19 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-REBELLION-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KABILA SEEKS FOREIGN SUPPORT TO REPEL CONGO REBELS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By NORIMITSU ONISHI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo _ As rebels closed in on this capital on
Wednesday, President Laurent Kabila scrambled to secure foreign
military support to repel a final assault.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe announced Wednesday night that it was immediately
sending aircraft, weapons and other support for the embattled
government. Kabila also won pledges of military support from Kenya
and Angola against the two-week rebellion, which is led by ethnic
Tutsi from eastern Congo, and reportedly being backed by Rwanda and
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts increased pressure on the rebels to capture Kinshasa
quickly, before the government gains reinforcements. But Kabila was
unable to gain the larger political cover of a group of 14 African
nations. One leading member, South Africa, dismissed the idea of
sending arms.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe's support was the first real fruit of intense efforts
by Kabila, who has become known for a lack of diplomatic skill, to
obtain outside support for his weakened and disorganized army. It
followed contradictory statements made by governments whose support
he had sought.
</P>
<P>
   After a two-day meeting in Harare, Zimbabwe, of defense
ministers from the 14-nation Southern African Development
Community, the region's main political and economic organization,
Zimbabwe said, though prematurely, that the group as a whole would
supply arms and men to Kabila's forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to respond positively in a manner that will help
the government of President Kabila to restore peace and
stability,'' said Robert Mugabe, the president of Zimbabwe. In a
separate statement, Mugabe's defense minister, Moven Mahachi, told
the BBC on Tuesday that Zimbabwe would immediately begin sending
airplanes and other assistance to the Congo.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, in a statement that revealed a rift in the
regional organization, South Africa, the head of the group and a
sometimes diplomatic rival of Zimbabwe, rejected weapons shipments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our attitude is clear,'' Nelson Mandela, the South African
president, said Wednesday. ``We are not going to make the situation
worse by sending a military force. We are for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Late on Wednesday the mounting regional support for Kabila
brought about a seeming concession from rebel leaders who told
journalists at a news conference in the eastern Congolese city of
Goma that the rebellion would consider negotiations with the
government. Until now, talks with Kabila had been ruled out.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels now control a huge eastern swath of Congo and much of
the territory southwest of Kinshasa, a critical region for
transportation and power to the capital. It was unclear Wednesday
night how significant the help from individual countries would be
and whether it would arrive soon enough to stop the rebels, who
tore through military lines southwest of here and deepened the
disarray among government officials.
</P>
<P>
   The depth of confusion in Kabila's government was underscored by
a senior official who, in a briefing with reporters, used the past
tense to assess Kabila's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing at a map of the country bearing its former name of
Zaire, the official at first said that the government defense line
lay in the city of Songololo, about 130 miles southwest of here;
then, after inching his finger eastward, he agreed that the line
was most likely in Kisantu, just 75 miles from this city.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a funny kind of war,'' he said finally. He added, ``If
Kinshasa falls, it's absolutely the end.'' The official said he was
pessimistic about Kabila being able to effectively continue the war
from his southern redoubt of Lubumbashi, where he was staying.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to continue the war with what means?'' he asked.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The government's desperate need for military resources also
arose indirectly during a television interview that Didier Mumengi,
the information minister, held late Tuesday with friendly local
reporters. Mumengi said the government had been dropping bombs on
rebel areas in the southwest, after which one reporter replied;
``But Mr. Minister, we don't have an air force.''
</P>
<P>
   Government officials have used the local newspapers and
television stations to present a rosy, and often misleading,
picture to Kinshasa's 5 million residents.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the propaganda campaign, the government has been
overwhelmed with bad news. On Monday, the rebels recaptured the
huge hydroelectric dam in Inga, about 200 miles away on the Congo
River; they shut off the power supply to this region, leaving
Kinshasa in the dark, as well as Brazzaville, across the river in
the Congo Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The outage added to the city's edginess. Gunfire could be heard
throughout the night, and some shots rang out during the day.
Residents near the main prison of Makala said that a riot took
place inside the facility, and that shots were exchanged between
guards and prisoners, including former military officials of Mobutu
Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
   Sentiment in Kinshasa has turned against the Rwandans who at
first helped Kabila come to power. ``We are against these
aggressors,'' said Jeremie Kimbanzia, 43, who was sharing beers
with five other men in La Cite, a gritty residential area, after
the rebels cut off power on Monday. ``Because of them, we don't
have power, and it was difficult to find bread this morning. We
will oppose them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're devils,'' said Jose Mbele, 44.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
