<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0418 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2210 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-BOMBING-330(2T     08-19 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-BOMBING-330(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND AFGHAN OFFICIALS DISCUSS AFRICA BOMBING SUSPECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also AFRICA-KENYA-HOTEL) 
(bl) 
 This article was reported by Steven Erlanger, James Risen and Tim
Weiner. It was written by Risen.  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As U.S. officials focus on a Saudi exile, Osama bin
Laden, as a prime suspect in the embassy bombings in Africa, they
are discussing strategies for how they might negotiate his capture
with the Taliban, the group that controls Afghanistan, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Afghanistan, a high-ranking official of the Taliban opened
the door Wednesday to such discussions. Since 1996, the Taliban has
sheltered bin Laden, a wealthy Saudi whom the United States calls
one of the world's leading financiers of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Wakil Ahmed Mutawakil, the spokesman for the Taliban and the
second-highest ranking official in the Taliban's Supreme Council,
said in a telephone interview from Afghanistan that if the United
States provides hard evidence of bin Laden's involvement in the
bombings, the Taliban would be willing to meet with U.S. officials
to discuss what to do about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our understanding is that the U.S. is continuing to
investigate this matter, and there isn't any solid evidence of his
involvement,'' Mutawakil said. `If you call someone a terrorist,
you must have proof. If there is proof, we will certainly sit down
and talk to the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mutawakil's comments served more to raise difficult
questions for U.S. policy-makers than to open any immediate
prospect of a resolution to the investigation of the twin bombings
in Kenya and Tanzania on Aug. 7
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there is no way for U.S. officials to be certain that
Mutawakil speaks for a unified Taliban, or that the organization
would ultimately be willing to deliver bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   Any deal would be complicated _ or shortcircuited _ by
Washington's other longstanding complaints with the Taliban. Those
include its harsh treatment of women and other human-rights
questions and its involvement in narcotics trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   But this may be a good time to negotiate with the Taliban.
Having nearly defeated their internal opposition, the Taliban is
desperate for international recognition and economic support.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Any deal for bin Laden would almost certainly also have to
involve Pakistan. Despite Pakistan's cooperation with the bombing
investigation in recent days, U.S.-Pakistani relations remain
complicated following Pakistan's nuclear test earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, U.S. officials are deliberating whether they can provide
incentives to the Taliban win their cooperation in helping to bring
bin Laden to face any charges that may be filed against him in the
bombings.
</P>
<P>
   No such charges have yet been brought, but senior Clinton
administration officials say that he is their leading suspect.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials reacted cautiously to Mutawakil's statement,
noting that they are not yet ready to open talks with the Taliban
concerning bin Laden. ``If we get to that point, then we'll deal
with it,'' a U.S. official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had discussions with the Taliban in the past about bin
Laden. And if we were to establish information that shows he did
not live up to his obligations as a `guest' in Afghanistan, then we
would provide it to the Taliban, and certainly take up'' this
suggestion of direct talks on bin Laden, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   There have been conflicting statements from the Taliban's
leadership in recent days about their willingness to deal with the
United States on bin Laden. Mutawakil's statements came on the
heels of hard-line comments made earlier Wednesday by other senior
Taliban officials, including the fundamentalist group's leader,
Mullah Mohammad Omar, vowing to protect bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   Mullah Omar, insisting that bin Laden was not involved in the
bombings, vowed to the Pakistan-based Afghan Islamic Press that
``even if all the countries of the world unite, we would defend
Osama with our blood.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials say that such contradictions may signal a split
within the Taliban leadership over their relationship with bin
Laden, a Saudi exile who helped finance the Afghan rebels in their
war against the Soviet Union in the 1980s. Some U.S. officials
believe that there is a faction within the Taliban that sees him as
a liability that they inherited from the previous Afghan
government.
</P>
<P>
   As they deliberate how to approach the Taliban in the future,
U.S. officials said flatly that they would not trade bin Laden's
capture for U.S. recognition for the Taliban's de facto government.
But they said the administration is now weighing other ways to
convince the Afghan movement to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomacy may be the only answer, since several U.S. officials
said that a military or covert operation to capture bin Laden is
unlikely or impossible.
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence that the United States is considering a
military operation against his compound, despite rumors to that
effect in Pakistan. The U.S. ambassador in Pakistan, Thomas Simons,
has dismissed the possibility that the United States would use
Pakistan as a staging ground for a military assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't shoot a Tomahawk at Kandahar from some ship in the
ocean,'' said one diplomat in the region. ``It would take
infantry.'' Any land-based military operation would almost
certainly have to be launched from Pakistan, whose interior
minister, Shujat Hussain, flatly ruled out such a mission
Wednesday. ``We cannot be a party to that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A covert mission to flush bin Laden out of hiding is
conceivable. Last year, the CIA and FBI lured Mir Amal Kansi, the
convicted killer of two CIA employees, out of hiding in Afghanistan
to a hotel in Pakistan, where he was arrested after a
four-and-a-half year manhunt. But bin Laden has much greater
financial and political resources than Kansi, and is far less
likely to succumb to trickery or fall into a trap laid by U.S.
intelligence operatives.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A senior diplomatic official familiar with the Taliban's
leadership said: ``If bin Laden is involved, they've got a big
bargaining chip,'' one that they might use to negotiate for the
international recognition they strongly desire.
</P>
<P>
   `We may be on the verge of a new relationship of Taliban to the
world, and if they insist on calling themselves a government they
may have to act more like a government, with international norms
and responsibilities,'' another senior U.S. official added. ``That
includes restraining terrorism, which touches on the issue of his
residence in Afghanistan.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, visiting the bombed U.S. embassies in Tanzania and
Kenya, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright first raised the issue
of the Taliban's turning over bin Laden when she said that the
Taliban would improve its chances for international recognition if
it stopped sheltering known or suspected terrorists like bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   Yet U.S. officials have been frustrated in their previous
attempts to win the support of the Taliban leadership in curbing
terrorism. In April, in fact, Bill Richardson, the U.S. ambassador
to the United Nations, met with Taliban leaders in Afghanistan to
discuss bin Laden, but Taliban leaders rejected his request that
they extradite him.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the Africa bombings, the United States suspected bin
Laden had also been involved in the bombings of U.S. military
facilities in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban have told State Department officials that Bin Laden
has guaranteed them, after Saudi Arabia demanded such a guarantee,
that he will not conduct terrorist activities from inside
Afghanistan; this is thought to be an empty promise.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, bin Laden is thought to pay the Taliban for this
sanctuary, in part out of his profits from his legitimate
businesses and, allegedly, narcotics dealing.
</P>
<P>
   Any U.S. negotiations with the Taliban will have to involve
Pakistan. While Pakistan has close military and intelligence ties
to the United States _ ties that have proved crucial in the
spreading investigation of the embassy bombings _ Pakistan's rulers
are furious over U.S. sanctions imposed on the country after it
tested a nuclear weapon.
</P>
<P>
   A bargain with Pakistan could bring Washington's goal of
non-proliferation _ stopping the spread of nuclear weapons _ in
conflict with its counterterrorism goals.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott and other U.S.
diplomats will meet with Pakistani Foreign Minister Shamshad Ahmad
next Tuesday in London. U.S. efforts to get Pakistani and Indian
cooperation to halt new tests and the weaponization of their
nuclear knowledge are high on the agenda. So are the Taliban and
bin Laden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 2059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0420 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2213 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-JUSTICE-SPI     08-19 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-JUSTICE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT CLOSES MICROSOFT INTERVIEWS TO PUBLIC, NEWS MEDIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WARREN WILSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. won another victory in its antitrust battle
Wednesday when a federal appeals court ruled that chairman Bill
Gates and other executives may give pretrial depositions without
reporters or the public present.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel said it will issue a final decision in the
matter sometime after Sept. 29, three weeks after the antitrust
trial is scheduled to begin, although that Sept. 8 date could also
be moved back.
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft spokesman said the company was ``gratified'' by the
ruling, and that it ``will allow depositions of its executives to
move forward without delay.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for news organizations that sought to attend the
depositions expressed dissapointment, saying the judges gave too
little weight to the public's right of access to testimony as it is
given, without delay. They also warned that the question could be
moot if the judges don't settle it for six weeks or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time they hear it, much of this may already be under
the bridge,'' said Josh Koltun, one of the news organizations'
attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is scheduled to start Sept. 8, but that could change
at a conference this morning with U.S. District Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson. Both Microsoft and the U.S. Department of Justice
have asked Jackson for a two-week delay, in part because of delays
in taking depositions.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the judge reluctantly granted the news organizations'
motion to open the depositions, saying he had little choice given
the plain language of the 1913 statute on which they based their
request. He ordered the participants to work out the details of how
to conduct the sessions in public.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft immediately appealed, saying it feared the disclosure
of sensitive business information if reporters and the public were
allowed to watch.
</P>
<P>
   The company argued trial procedures have changed since the 1913
law requiring openness in depostions in antitrust cases. In 1937,
new Federal Rules of Civil Procedure were adopted, governing such
proceedings as gathering testimony in depositions. Those rules
appear to conflict with the 1913 law.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals panel didn't rule Wednesday on the legal issues.
Instead it gave the participants until Sept. 29 to finish filing
the documents it will consider in its decision.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the case moving forward, it said the Microsoft
executives could be questioned under the normal procedures for
legal depositions. The two sides agreed earlier on rules for
restricting access to sensitive information gathered in closed
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   In deciding to let the depositions proceed, the panel said the
``balance of harms'' favors Microsoft. If they were taken in public
and the company later wins its appeal, ``the disclosure could not
be undisclosed,'' they wrote. But if Microsoft loses, the text and
videotape of a private deposition can then be disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The case involves claims by federal and state antitrust
regulators that Microsoft has illegally forced computer makers to
accept its Internet browsing software if they also want its Windows
operating system for personal computers, for which they have no
real alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's actions have been harmful to competition, and
particularly to its main rival in the browser market, Netscape
Communications, the government says.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft says it has integrated the two software products _ the
browser and the operating system _ in ways that benefit consumers.
A June ruling by the appeals court in a related case supports that
view, Microsoft said recently when it asked Jackson to issue a
summary judgment to end the case _ a move not considered likely.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Microsoft was hit Wednesday with a new antitrust
lawsuit by a Connecticut company that accuses it of withholding
technical information vital to its business in order to impede
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol Technology of Danbury, Conn., makes software that
converts Windows programs to run on other operating systems, such
as Unix. In 1994 it signed an agreement that it says entitles it to
detailed technical information known as ``source code'' from
Microsoft to make its own products work better, as well as advance
warning if Microsoft planned to change the source code.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after ``creating a dependency'' on that information for
Bristol and its customers, Microsoft is withholding it, the company
claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bristol is very disappointed that it was necessary to sue to
obtain what Microsoft has said all along it would provide us,''
said Keith Blackwell, the company's chairman and president.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft spokesman Jim Cullinan dismissed Bristol's claim as
``wholly without merit,'' saying it was trying to elevate a
``routine business negotiation'' into a federal lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The companies have been negotiating terms of a new license
agreement, Cullinan said, but Bristol broke off the talks ``without
any prior notice to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Other companies have accepted the same license terms that
Bristol rejected, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 2100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
