<HEADER>
A2217 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISS-KLAN-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      08-19 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISS-KLAN-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-KLANSMAN TESTIFIES ON HOW FATAL FIREBOMBING WAS PLANNED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HATTIESBURG, Miss. _ In the vernacular of the White Knights of
the Ku Klux Klan of Mississippi in the violent 1960s, a ``No. 1''
was a cross burning, and a ``No. 2,'' a whipping. A ``No. 3'' was a
firebombing, and ``No. 4,'' the most severe punishment of all, was
killing. Only the highest-ranking Klansmen could order a No. 3 and
No. 4, said Billy Roy Pitts, a foot soldier in the White Knights in
the winter of 1965-66.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam Bowers was the only man who could order a No. 3 and No. 4
in the White Knights in the state of Mississippi,'' Pitts testified
here Wednesday in Bowers' murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers, a 73-year-old former Klan leader being tried for the
fifth time for ordering the death of Vernon Dahmer, a civil rights
leader killed by the firebombing of his home on Jan. 10, 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Pitts, now 54 and serving time for his part in the killing, told
the jury that he gathered with other Klansmen that winter in a
farmhouse near Laurel, Miss., for a special meeting _ special
because Bowers, the Imperial Wizard who led the Mississippi White
Knights, had come to see them in person, to order Dahmer's death.
</P>
<P>
   Pitts testified that Bowers ordered the murder of Dahmer because
he had worked to register blacks to vote in Forrest County.
</P>
<P>
   Pitts said Bowers was visibly angry at the meeting because the
Forrest County Klan had been lenient, doing nothing to silence
Dahmer, the respected merchant, farmer and local NAACP official who
offered his small store in the Kelly Setttlement community outside
Hattiesburg as a place blacks could pay their poll tax.
</P>
<P>
   Pitts said Bowers, a businessman in Laurel, later told him:
``Don't worry. No jury in the state of Mississippi is going to
convict a white man for killing'' someone black.
</P>
<P>
   He said Bowers presided over other meetings where Klansmen
planned the firebombing of Dahmer's home and store, and that the
lawyer who is defending Bowers' in this trial, Travis Buckley, also
attended discussions of the plot to firebomb the house.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted an outburst from Buckley, who demanded a mistrial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so inflammatory,'' said Buckley, who was indicted in the
Dahmer case three decades ago but was later cleared of all charges.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecuting attorney, Robert Helfrich, said his office had
filed a motion before the trial pointing out a possible conflict of
interest if Buckley tried the case, but that Bowers insisted that
Buckley serve as his lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to come up again that Mr. Buckley was there, by
this witness and other witnesses,'' said Helfrich.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Richard McKenzie denied the mistrial motion but told the
jury to disregard what they had heard about Buckley. When asked if
they could do that, the jurors _ six blacks, five whites and one
Asian-American _ nodded.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the most lively exchange in a day of courtroom
activity that opened up the Klan's strategy in the 1960s. When
another former Klansman, T. Webber Rogers, refused to tell the
court where he lived, the judge asked him if he did so because he
was afraid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell, yeah,'' blurted Rogers, who said he has been shot at
since testifying against the Klan in previous cases. The judge then
admonished him for using such language in court.
</P>
<P>
   The courtroom laughed at that, but there was only silence as the
former Klansmen explained how the killing was planned and executed.
</P>
<P>
   Though the information coming out of this trial seems new in
1998, it is hardly so. Bowers has been on trial in the Dahmer
murder four times before, always walking free after deadlocked
juries of white males. He did serve time _ six years in connection
with one of the killings of the three civil rights workers in
Neshoba County in 1964 _ but no prosecutor has ever successfully
linked him to Dahmer's murder.
</P>
<P>
   As Bowers sat in the courtroom in his off-white suit, seeming
uninterested, Rogers described how angry a younger version of the
defendant had been on a winter night years before.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to know why that job down south hadn't been done,''
said Rogers. ``He wanted it done, and he wanted it done right. He
said it should have been done two weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he and other Klansmen took part in what Bowers called a
``dry run,'' piling into cars and driving past the Dahmers' house.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers is not accused of being at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said he also did not take part in the actual killing. But
Pitts admitted being there. He told a story he has told before, in
trials that led to the convictions of four other men in Dahmer's
murder, of how eight men in two cars, the trunks loaded with
shotguns and 12 gallons of gasoline, rumbled toward the Dahmers'
home.
</P>
<P>
   They stopped at a black cemetery near there, and one of the
Klansmen urinated on a grave. Then, the others did, too.
</P>
<P>
   He said Bowers had sent him along as a guard, armed with a
pistol, to watch over the others. But as Dahmer, his body on fire,
fired a shotgun over and over from a window to give his wife and
children time to escape, Pitts said he dropped the pistol, unfired.
</P>
<P>
   He said he could hear Dahmer calling from inside the house.
</P>
<P>
   Dahmer, his lungs seared by the flames, died in a hospital 12
hours later.
</P>
<P>
   ``A man's life was taken and I was part of it,'' Pitts said.
``It's something I can't get out of my mind. I wish to God I had
never been a part of it . . . I destroyed a family.''
</P>
<P>
   After serving a short federal sentence for his part in the
killing, Pitts was supposed to serve a life sentence in Mississippi
state prison. But, probably because he cooperated in the
investigation, he never actually did time in state prison. Pitts
said he was told by authorities he did not have to, but he was
never officially pardoned. In January, The Jackson Clarion-Ledger
reported that fact, and Pitts is now serving that sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley, who has argued that his client is the victim of a
federal conspiracy, asked Pitts if the federal government gave him
money for his girlfriend in the 1960s. Pitts was married at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Pitts said federal investigators did give him about $8,000 over
time _ informants are often paid money _ but that money went to his
wife and children, not his mistress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what you're gettin' at and I'll save you a lot of
time,'' said Pitts to Buckley, when the lawyer first mentioned the
woman's name. ``I told you before, I ain't no saint.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he used the money to relocate his family, because he
feared the Klan would harm them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 2103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
