u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRISTOL-MICROSOFT-SUI     08-19 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRISTOL-MICROSOFT-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRISTOL TECHNOLOGY FILES ANTITRUST SUIT AGAINST MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Conn., Wash.)  (See also MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST) 
 (af) 
By STEVE LOHR  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. has a fresh antitrust challenge on its hands
from an unlikely source _ a small software supplier in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in broad terms the suit filed late on Tuesday by Bristol
Technology Inc. echoes the themes of the broad antitrust complaint
against Microsoft, which was filed in May by the federal government
and 20 states.
</P>
<P>
   Both cases contend that Microsoft has violated the Sherman Act
by illegally seeking to protect and expand its monopoly in the
market for desktop software for personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol Technology has hired lawyers who are veterans of the IBM
antitrust wars, just as the Justice Department has done. And while
Bristol Technology's antitrust case is a private suit, it is
seeking the enlist the support of the government and states.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut is one of the states suing Microsoft, and Richard
Blumenthal, the attorney general of Connecticut, said Wednesday
that the accusations in the Bristol Technology case appeared to be
consistent with the view of the government and states that
Microsoft is given to predatory behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exactly the type of conduct that prompted the state to
sue Microsoft, which we believe has abused its monopoly power,''
Blumenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol Technology's executives and its lawyers said they had
scheduled a meeting later this week with officials of the Justice
Department in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft says that the private antitrust suit, like the
government's case, is groundless.
</P>
<P>
   ``This company is trying to elevate a routine business
negotiation into a federal case,'' said Greg Shaw, a Microsoft
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol Technology of Danbury, Conn., makes software tools that
enable programs originally written to run on Microsoft's Windows
operating system to run also on other operating systems, including
Unix, a powerful operating system widely used on engineering work
stations, and OS/390, the dominant operating system for mainframe
computers.
</P>
<P>
   In its complaint, filed in federal district court in Bridgeport,
Conn., Bristol Technology accused Microsoft of ``entangling Bristol
in a charade to stifle competition from other operating systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Bristol Technology's programming tools are sold in the business
market to allow corporations to run many different kinds of
software. It was in 1991, according to the suit, that Microsoft
first approached Bristol Technology. That was two years before
Microsoft's industrial-strength operating system, Windows NT, was
introduced.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Microsoft was pleased to support a software
company that enabled more Windows-based applications to be used in
the corporate market, a stronghold for Unix work stations and Unix
computer networks. After lengthy negotiations, Microsoft and
Bristol Technology signed a three-year agreement in September 1994,
under which the Connecticut company licensed the programming code
for Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Access to the so-called source code helped Bristol Technology
improve its tools, so Windows applications ran smoothly on Unix
systems.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last couple of years, Windows NT has become a
mainstream operating system for corporate work stations and
networks, often replacing Unix systems.
</P>
<P>
   After the licensing agreement expired last September, Keith
Blackwell, president of Bristol Technology, said that Microsoft
offered only drastically altered terms _ a fivefold price increase
and restricted access to the Windows NT source code.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said that the conditions under which it licenses its
intellectual property to others is up to Microsoft and that at
least one other software supplier has recently agreed to its new
terms.
</P>
<P>
   At Bristol Technology, however, the shift in contract terms is
seen as an effort to speed the shift to Windows NT and away from
rival Unix systems. ``It looks as if Microsoft is trying to force
people to switch to NT,'' Blackwell said.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also contends that the Windows code is an ``essential
facility'' to a company like Bristol Technology, and it quotes from
a Microsoft document saying that Microsoft is committed to
providing its licensees ``with future versions of Windows family
source code.''
</P>
<P>
   Bristol Technology contends that Microsoft has now abandoned
that promise. ``Microsoft set out to invite this use of its
intellectual property,'' said Patrick Lynch, a partner at O'Melveny
&AMP; Myers, an antitrust litigator who represented IBM in several
private suits. ``And Bristol, while a tiny company, has a gateway
technology that helps to preserve competition between Windows and
Unix.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 2103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
