<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-INSURE-315&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALIAN INSURER AGREES TO PAY $100 MILLION IN HOLOCAUST SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Italy's largest insurance company, Assicurazioni
Generali, told a U.S. judge Wednesday night that it would pay $100
million to Holocaust survivors and the heirs of victims for life
insurance and annuity policies that it refused to honor after World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   The company also agreed to release documents that are expected
to help in recovering claims from other European insurance
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement was reached in the office of Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato, R-N.Y., York, after eight hours of talks involving the
company, lawyers for the claimants, insurance regulators and the
World Jewish Restitution Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was presented to Judge Michael Mukasey in U.S.
District Court in Manhattan, who would formally have to approve it.
The Generali board is scheduled to approve the agreement when it
meets Aug. 28, said Robert Swift of Philadelphia, a lawyer for the
nine named plaintiffs in the class-action suit against Generali and
14 other European insurers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this will bring justice for Holocaust survivors with
the other insurance carriers,'' D'Amato told Mukasey.
</P>
<P>
   In breaking ranks with the other insurance companies and
settling, Generali gained for itself a relatively small monetary
cost and the enmity of the others.
</P>
<P>
   When a Generali lawyer, M. Scott Vayer, and its vice director
general, Guido Pastore, entered Mukasey's courtroom they were met
with scowls and cold stares from lawyers for the other 14
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Vayer convinced the other parties that the majority of
obligations for policies that it wrote in Eastern Europe before the
war were now the responsibility of companies created there by
postwar communist regimes.
</P>
<P>
   The $100 million that Generali is paying is roughly the amount
that it received in settlement from the communists for seizing
Generali assets, three people involved in the negotiations said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The documents detail how the Nazis liquidated the policies of
Jews who were sent to death camps, how they funneled the money to
Deutsche Bank, Dresdner Bank and other banks and how, after the
war, the Italian government made payments to Generali and other
Italian insurers that the companies kept without telling
policyholders.
</P>
<P>
   Generali will also turn over detailed information on what share
of the market each European insurer had before the war and other
corporate documents that will shed light on how the Nazis worked
closely with insurance companies to loot Jewish assets to finance
the war and the death camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Generali documents are the key we need to get the other
companies to settle,'' said Ed Fagan, who filed the suit last year.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan and the other lawyers are expected to turn their focus to
Allianz AG of Germany, the biggest insurance company in the world,
and its Italian subsidiary, Riunione Adriatica di Sicurta. Riunione
also received payments from the Italian government after the war,
Linda Gerstel, a plaintiff's lawyer, said Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Allianz executives held high posts in the Third Reich, and the
company had the contract fire and casualty insurance at the death
camps.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Allianz, Christopher Worthley, said Wednesday
night that he expected Allianz would soon reach a settlement on
Holocaust claims.
</P>
<P>
   An important sticking point in talks Wednesday was the
insistence of state insurance regulators that they be involved in
recovering money from the insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Generali signed a separate agreement that gives a 12-member
panel, including three insurance regulators from the United States,
complete access to its files, so that claims can be investigated.
</P>
<P>
   New York State Insurance Superintendent Neil Levin said,
``Generali's agreement to sign the memorandum of understanding is a
constructive and meaningful step toward the resolution of all
Holocaust-era claims.''
</P>
<P>
   The $100 million is not all that Generali will pay. It has
already agreed to create a $12 million humanitarian fund in Israel.
The memorandum also obligates it, and any other company that
settles, to pay all administrative costs of investigating claims,
to contribute money to pay for policies of defunct insurance
companies and to contribute to two other humanitarian funds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
