<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKS END TWO-DAY RALLY ON GROWING ASIAN CONCERNS
</P>
<P>
   Stocks ended slightly lower, as shares of companies seen to be
affected by Asia's slump, like semiconductor makers and banks,
declined. Leading the Dow Jones industrial average lower was J.P.
Morgan, which fell $1.125, to $126.50. Shares of computer
manufacturers rose, encouraged by the strong earnings of Dell
Computer, which were reported after the market closed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 21.37 points, at
8,693.28. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 3.14 points,
to 1,098.06. The Nasdaq composite index decreased 12.43 points, to
1,842.69.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury bond prices were little changed. The yield on the
30-year bond was also unchanged at 5.55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   AN FCC RULING IS UPHELD
</P>
<P>
   An appeals court has upheld the Federal Communications
Commission's decision to exempt Internet service providers from
paying local phone companies the access fees that the regional Bell
companies are allowed to charge long-distance carriers.
</P>
<P>
   THE FATE OF DELTA AND UNITED DEAL
</P>
<P>
   The pilots union of Delta Air Lines has said that the carrier's
decision last week not to give it a voting seat on the board
effectively ended an alliance between Delta and United Airlines.
But Delta does not agree, and says it hopes the union will continue
to consider the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN MARKET CONTINUES TO FALL
</P>
<P>
   Russia's steps to avert default by devaluing the ruble and
delaying payments on foreign debts raised the risk that it may lose
whatever remains of its financial market credibility, Western
bankers and analysts said. Russia's stock market, which is a
barometer of foreign-investor confidence, tumbled for the third day
to a record low and is down 40 percent this month.
</P>
<P>
   De facto default-with-devaluation is not a long-term solution
for Russia, but it could help pressure an obstinate Parliament into
passing a well-crafted economic reform package.
</P>
<P>
   KOHLBERG ACQUIRING PAINT COMPANY
</P>
<P>
   Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co. plans to buy Herberts, a German
paint company with annual sales of $1.5 billion, for $1.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   NEUBERGER PLANNING TO SELL SHARES
</P>
<P>
   The investment-management partnership Neuberger &AMP; Berman plans
to sell 15 percent of its shares in an initial public offering that
would value the company at $1.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSING STARTS JUMPED 5.7 PERCENT IN JULY
</P>
<P>
   Housing starts unexpectedly surged 5.7 percent in July, to 1.718
million units at an annual rate, their highest level in more than
11 years.
</P>
<P>
   INSURER IN HOLOCAUST SETTLEMENT
</P>
<P>
   Assicurazioni Generali, the biggest Italian insurance company,
agreed in U.S. court to pay $100 million to Holocaust survivors and
the heirs of victims for policies it refused to honor after World
War II. It also agreed to disclose documents that are expected to
help claimants recover billions of dollars from other European
insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   MOODY'S REDUCING DEBT RATINGS
</P>
<P>
   Moody's Investors Service cut its ratings on the long-term debt
of automakers Mitsubishi Motors and Nissan Motor, citing worries
about their earnings prospects.
</P>
<P>
   SALES OF APPLE'S IMAC ARE BRISK
</P>
<P>
   Several retailers have reported that Apple's new iMac computer
has been selling briskly, with some stores sold out just days after
the product's introduction on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   CNBC OFF THE AIR AFTER BOMB THREAT
</P>
<P>
   The financial news television network CNBC was knocked off the
air for nearly an hour and a half because police evacuated its New
Jersey offices after a bomb threat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
