<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GEORGE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: UNDER TORRE, YANK BUBBLE IS UNLIKELY TO BURST  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joe Torre can peek into the opposing dugout Friday night in
Texas and easily recognize his rival, Johnny Oates, the Rangers
manager. Their mental scraps are always intense but friendly. Their
respect is mutual.
</P>
<P>
   Oates owns thoughts of Torre that linger.
</P>
<P>
   ``First thing, when I think of Joe Torre, I think of spring
training last year when he asked me to be one of his coaches for
the All-Star Game,'' Oates said when the Rangers came to Yankee
Stadium last weekend. ``Heck, if a coach asks you, it's usually in
late June, a week or two before the game. Joe was asking in spring
training! That shows a meticulous mind. It gave me time to prepare
and to get my family situated for the trip. I'll always remember
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates also remembers the 1976 World Series, Cincinnati versus
the Yankees, and how he was a contestant in a bubble-gum-blowing
contest. It was two catchers, Oates of the Phillies versus Gary
Carter of the Expos, before Game 3 of that World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big deal, on TV and all, and the idea was to take
five or six sticks of bubble gum and blow the biggest balloon, the
biggest bubble you could,'' Oates said, chuckling. ``Joe Torre was
the official scorer. We'd blow in front of him, and my bubble
covered the top of my head all the way down to my belly button. Joe
was to take the tape and measure the bubbles. I won that contest
with a bubble of 21 inches. But you were talking about some real
pressure on Joe. He had to get real close to measure, and the last
thing he wanted to do was to pop your balloon or bust your bubble.
That would have been a big problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre did not pop the bubble then.
</P>
<P>
   He is not popping it now.
</P>
<P>
   No, Joe Torre is riding the edge of this big bubble the Yankees
are creating, this season of records falling and opponents wilting
and championship anticipation growing, with deftness and with
grace. He is being selfless and is exhibiting character at every
turn. He is pulling out his tape measure and tinkering with the
Yankees, and they have now become a true reflection of him. All
team. All business.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up near St. Louis, I remember watching Torre hit .363 to
swipe the National League batting title in 1971. I remember those
muggy summer nights when Jack Buck, with a cool voice over the
radio, would describe how Torre would nestle in at the plate and
rock those knees and squeeze that bat and hammer another one to
left. Or how he might hit the ball the other way or even sacrifice
to give his team the best chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   During his playing career, Torre hit behind Hank Aaron in
Atlanta. He moved from catcher to third base in 1970 and then later
to first base. He was a player-manager for the Mets in 1977. His
resume is full of giving of himself in various ways for his team.
</P>
<P>
   Of respecting the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost as a player, you respect people who have
been through what you are going through,'' said Paul O'Neill, the
Yankees' right fielder. ``Joe played for 18 years. He knows the
grind, and that's a word he uses a lot. He expects his players to
do the little things and to play the game right.''
</P>
<P>
   Each and every game, whether it is against the worst or the
best. Maximum effort. And the Yankees do that. In Torre's first
season as manager, after he was dismissed in St. Louis the year
before, they won 92 games and the World Series, and they won 96 the
next year. This season they are on pace to win a league-record 122
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I left St. Louis for the Rangers,'' Texas shortstop Royce
Clayton said, ``people back there said Joe was too lax on his
players. They brought in Tony La Russa and he was supposed to be
all about discipline. You notice La Russa, but the team is still
struggling. The greatest thing I can say about Joe Torre is that
you notice his players. You notice how professional they are. Joe
just blends in.''
</P>
<P>
   In a league where managers are routinely defensive, critical,
obstinate, egotistical and stubborn, this is no ordinary Joe.
</P>
<P>
   He knows his players. He has a human touch. He is not
overwhelmed by New York. He has fashioned a team in his image to
play in his style. New York reporters who cover his team daily
marvel and write glowingly about its manner and its output. In this
gorilla market, that is no small feat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good teams are remembered by good managers,'' O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees and Torre are proving him right.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
