<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY TO BE ASKED TO PROVIDE FURTHER DETAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH   AND BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  WASHINGTON _ Monica S. Lewinsky, making a return grand jury
appearance Thursday, may be asked more precise details about her
relationship with President Clinton so prosecutors can determine if
Clinton's earlier denial of a sexual affair was ``legally
accurate,'' as he told the nation Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   While independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr's office has said the
Clinton investigation is not about sex, the definition of sexual
relations has become significant because the president said he did
not commit perjury in January by denying he had a sexual
relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton did commit perjury in his Jan. 17 deposition in the
Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit, a number of congressional
Republicans have said the president should resign or be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides said the president did not commit perjury
because the types of sexual contact he had with Lewinsky were not
included in the definition used by Jones's lawyers. However, a
source close to Lewinsky has said the former White House intern did
have a type of sex that fell within the definition.
</P>
<P>
   A legal source said Wednesday that the bulk of the grand jury
questioning centered not on issues of obstruction of justice, but
on the sexual relationship between Clinton and Lewinsky. That
source, who is familiar with the proceedings, said little time was
spent actually pursuing lines of questioning on allegations that
Clinton suborned perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers also abruptly halted questioning shortly
before 6:30 p.m., as Starr and his subordinates continued to hammer
away on sex issues. Starr requested more time for the testimony and
was denied by one of Clinton's lawyers, according to the source.
</P>
<P>
   That source, who talked only on the condition of anonymity, also
confirmed that Clinton began the session by reciting a statement to
the grand jury acknowledging an inappropriate and intimate
relationship with Lewinsky. Under questioning, Clinton broadened
that description to include oral sex, but declined to provide any
more details as he faced rapid-fire questions.
</P>
<P>
   In the Jones deposition, Clinton was asked whether he had sexual
relations with Lewinsky, under this definition: ``When the person
knowingly engages in or causes ... contact with the genitalia,
anus, groin, breast, inner thigh, or buttocks of any person with an
intent to arouse or gratify the sexual desire of any person.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky may also be asked about a news report that she gave the
president six ties, one of which Clinton wore when she first
testified before the grand jury. Clinton reportedly was asked in
his grand jury testimony whether he wore the gold-and-navy tie on
Aug. 6 as some kind of signal to Lewinsky. However, Clinton's
public appearance that day was for a Rose Garden event at 11:06
a.m., more than an hour and a half after Lewinsky entered the grand
jury room, so it unlikely she saw him wearing it beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday will also be the first time grand jurors apparently
will have a chance to question Lewinsky directly. Prosecutors had
questioned her two weeks ago. In addition to questions about the
physical contact between Clinton and Lewinsky, the grand jurors may
also ask why she initially swore in an affidavit that she did not
have sexual relationship with the president and now has changed her
story. Lewinsky was granted full immunity by Starr before she
agreed to testify before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   In an affidavit for the Jones case, Lewinsky said: ``I have
never had a sexual relationship with the president, he did not
propose that we have a sexual relationship, he did not offer me
employment or other benefits in exchange for a sexual relationship,
he did not deny me employment or other benefits for reflecting a
sexual relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was asked in his Jones deposition if Lewinsky's
affidavit was accurate. ``That is absolutely true,'' he answered.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are examining whether this and other statements by
Clinton amount to perjury.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jurors are expected to ask whether Clinton or anyone
else urged her to deny having a relationship with the president,
which could be an obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   The focus on what kind of sex Clinton had with Lewinsky has
become necessary because it has become the cornerstone of Clinton's
defense. Clinton said his January denial of having sex with
Lewinsky was ``legally accurate,'' but he has not publicly
explained how this could be possible. Nor has Clinton said why it
was legally accurate to say that he did not have an affair with
Lewinsky or that he couldn't remember he was ever alone with her.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats and legal analysts have said that although
Clinton appears to have lied in the Jones deposition, he may have
avoided committing perjury because his comments about Lewinsky were
not material to the Jones case, which was brought by a former
Arkansas state worker who alleged she had been sexually harassed by
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's admission that he had an inappropriate relationship
with Lewinsky has given new life and perhaps credibility to
accounts by a number of women who have maintained they had sexual
contact or relationships with Clinton. Jones, whose lawsuit was
dismissed, is launching an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Dolly Kyle Browning, who has alleged a longtime relationship
with Clinton that sometimes included sex, on Monday filed a
defamation lawsuit against Clinton, alleging that the president
made untrue remarks about her in a memorandum Clinton co-wrote that
became an exhibit in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   Browning's lawyer, Larry Klayman of Judicial Watch, said
Clinton's admission on Monday has ``bolstered the credibility'' of
Browning and other women who have said they had sexual
relationships with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Klayman said he will use the Browning lawsuit to investigate the
Lewinsky matter, enabling him to demand documents and depositions
under the ``discovery'' process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our case opens the discovery Pandora's box,'' Klayman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
