<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2237 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLAN-TRIAL-BOS &LR;      08-19 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLAN-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITNESS DESCRIBES KLAN RAID AGAINST BLACK LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Note strong language used in some quotes.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HATTIESBURG, Miss. _ A penitent witness who took part in a
murderous raid against a black leader 32 years ago gave a modern
audience at the trial of Mississippi Ku Klan Klan ruler Sam Bowers
an extraordinary account Wednesday of the operations of the
underground group that once terrorized the state.
</P>
<P>
   As he did in a series of trials three decades ago, former
Klansman Billy Roy Pitts testified that Bowers informed his
followers in late 1965 that he had been called to appear before the
old House UnAmerican Activities Committee and instructed the Klan
unit to eliminate Vernon Dahmer, the president of the Hattiesburg
chapter of the NAACP, ``to show the people in Washington that the
South means business'' in its resistance to civil rights
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Pitts, 54, said Dahmer's death ``was bothering me bad'' when he
decided to tell authorities of his participation in the firebombing
of Dahmer's house on Jan. 10, 1966. He was also prompted to become
a witness, he said, because he had heard Bowers ``believed I was
talking to the FBI and wanted to annihilate me.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitts's appearance came on the third day of Bowers's trial for
murder. The 73-year-old Bowers's three previous trials in state
court ended in mistrials in the 1960s, but the case was revived
over the past year after new witnesses came forward to corroborate
Pitts's story.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Klan's power has virtually disappeared here, the
organization's reputation as an intimidating force was dramatized
during the testimony of T. Webber Rogers, another former Klansman
who has testified before. Rogers followed Pitts to the stand and
recalled that Bowers once told a Klan meeting: ``Something's got to
be done about that damned nigger down south,'' referring to Dahmer,
who lived 35 miles south of the meeting site.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers did not go on the raid and said he quit the Klan shortly
after the attack on Dahmer. He said he did not want to say where he
now lived ``for my safety.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you received threats?'' asked Circuit Judge Richard
McKenzie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell, yes,'' said Rogers. Admonished by the judge for
``cussing,'' Rogers bowed his head and said, ``I didn't want to
have to go through with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Pitts, who was 21 at the time of the Dahmer attack,
detailed the culture of Bowers's White Knights of the Ku Klux Klan.
</P>
<P>
   While members of the Dahmer family watched from a balcony rail
above Bowers, Pitts told how he was initiated into the Klan under
an oath that required obedience to the ``superior officer.'' The
penalty for defying orders ``would be death,'' he said. Asked to
name his superior officer, Pitts answered: Sam Bowers.
</P>
<P>
   Pitts recalled a Klan meeting at a farmhouse in neighboring
Jones County where he exercised his rank as the Klan's ``inner
guard'' to provide security for Bowers, the statewide leader of the
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Bowers took charge of the speaking,'' Pitts said. ``He was
fixing to go to Washington and there was one back project that
needed taking care of.'' It was, he said, the ``Dahmer project,''
which demanded, in Klan language, the application of Codes 3 and 4.
Code 3 called for the burning of a building; Code 4 called for
death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam Bowers was the only one who could order a Code 3 or Code 4
for the White Knights of the Invisible Empire of the Ku Klux Klan
in Mississippi,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pitts identified about a dozen men who were on hand, but when he
mentioned the name of Travis Buckley, who is representing Bowers,
the defense attorney bolted to his feet and called unsuccessfully
for a mistrial.
</P>
<P>
   As prosecutors led him through his testimony, Pitts said Bowers
had declared the NAACP and ``communist organizations'' as mortal
enemies. ``It was our sacred duty to try and stomp them out.''
</P>
<P>
   On the evening of Jan. 9, 1966, Pitts said the ``exalted
cyclops'' of the Klan, Cecil Sessums, came to Pitts's home. Sessums
invoked the word ``kenny,'' Pitts said, which was ``a Klan code
word which meant we were obligated to come along and do the work.''
</P>
<P>
   The pair went to John's Cafe in Laurel, where Bowers often held
court with members of the Jones County Klan, Pitts said. Sessums
conferred with Bowers, his chief, and then took Pitts to Sessums's
house, where they were joined by six other Klansmen wielding
shotguns and ``pistols strapped to their sides,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They filled a dozen plastic jugs with gasoline and drove south
in two cars to inspect the Dahmer home in a rural area outside
Hattiesburg, Pitts said. After midnight, the Klansmen
reconnoitered, Pitts said, at a black church with a cemetery.
``Sessums went and urinated on a grave,'' Pitts recalled.
``Everyone thought it was pretty funny, so we all done it. Sessums
made a statement: `The only good nigger is a dead nigger.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sessums also delivered instructions, Pitts said. One carload
would firebomb Dahmer's store. At Dahmer's home next door, Pitts's
group was told to fire at the gas tanks of Dahmer's cars and to
shoot out the front window while Sessums flung the gasoline and a
torch into the house.
</P>
<P>
   Pitts, who was carrying a .22 caliber pistol in a ``quick draw''
holster, said he was told to provide cover for Sessums. Pitts said
he crouched against the house, and after the flames broke out, he
heard the cries of a man inside.
</P>
<P>
   As the group fled, one of the cars' headlights came on against
orders. One of the nightriders ``thought it was a trap'' and opened
fire on the auto, flattening two tires. The car had to be
abandoned. Pitts said he realized a further peril to the group. He
had dropped his pistol at the scene. After daybreak, authorities
found it.
</P>
<P>
   After the eight men escaped in the remaining car, Pitts said he
slept a few hours, then was reprimanded by Bowers for losing the
pistol.
</P>
<P>
   Pitts said Bowers added: ``Don't do any talking. No jury in the
state of Mississippi is going to convict a white man for killing a
nigger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 2124EDT &QL; 
