<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2238 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXASTECH-PETERS-     08-19 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXASTECH-PETERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
The way Texas Tech coach Spike Dykes sees it, Rob Peters had the
second-best position in the world. If serving as a weatherman in
West Texas might finish first, life as Zebbie Lethridge's backup
was a close second.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``If I die and there is such thing as reincarnation, I want to
come back as second-team quarterback or weatherman,'' Dykes said.
``How do you lose a deal like that? `The jet stream will dip a
little bit, and there is a chance it's going to rain.' You can't
miss. It's the same thing with the second-team quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the honeymoon is over now. Matt Tittle is the name they
want to know now.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Peters, a junior from Katy whose role at Tech had been about
as tough as predicting heat in the summer or wind in the spring,
will have to do considerably more for the Red Raiders this season.
After four seasons in which Lethridge made 44 consecutive starts
and threw more passes than any other quarterback in Tech history,
Peters takes over having registered more positions (nine) than
completions (six).
</P>
<P>
   ``Rob is a great athlete,'' Dykes said. ``He was a great high
school basketball player in a program with a great high school
basketball team. He's a guy our guys can rely on. He can do a great
job. Rob is probably as well thought of by his teammates as anyone
we ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of that goes back to Peters' academic success.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made one B while at Tech,'' Dykes said. ``I told him I
made one B when I was in college. Of course, the rest of his are
A's.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters' popularity with teammates also no doubt lies with his
willingness to play all those positions.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Peters' teammates know they will need their
quarterback to complete passes, and his popularity might not help
much in that area. There seems, however, little doubt about his
ability to fill the role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have more confidence in Rob than ever,'' receiver Tim Baker
said. ``He hasn't played that much, but when he's played, he's
proven himself. He can throw as well as anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rob is more of a pure passer. He's the kind of guy that's
going to drop back in the pocket and wait for the receivers to get
open. Zebbie is more of a scrambling quarterback. Rob can scramble,
too. He's got some speed, especially for a big guy (6-3, 237
pounds). But I think he'll be more steady in the pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Donnie Hart, Tech's All-Big 12 receiver, Peters
also might have more of a deep touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he understands more about throwing to the open area
and putting a little more air under it,'' Hart said. ``He and
Zebbie both have strong arms. They can really zing it in there. But
Rob puts more air on the deep ball. I look forward to running under
lots of touchdowns.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lethridge threw 42 touchdown passes during his Tech
career. Peters has thrown one. He showed his athleticism as a
fullback and receiver last season and again with a 64-yard
touchdown run in Tech's spring game. But there are different
pressures, far greater demands, on a starting quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't played all that much, so there's a lot of question
about what I can do,'' said Peters, who also has dabbled in defense
and special teams. ``The big question mark for this team is the
quarterback position. I've got all the confidence in the world in
myself. My teammates have confidence in me. Now, it's just a matter
of me doing what I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   What he can do, Peters said, is about the same thing done by
Lethridge, Robert Hall and Jamie Gill, all running the schemes
former offensive coordinator Dick Winder (now the Tech receivers
coach upon his return from Oklahoma) installed more than 10 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to do about the same thing we did in the past,''
Peters said. ``I'm a little bigger than (Lethridge and Hall), so
everybody thinks we're going to change the offense up. I don't
think that's the case. I think we'll see the same kind of thing,
and hopefully I'll have the same success they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys were such good athletes. Zebbie was an amazing
athlete. This year, we'll probably do more conventional drop-back
passing. That fits my mold a little bit better. But I can still do
the bootleg stuff and the quick drops and the option offense. We'll
be able to mix the two.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Raiders don't seem too concerned about any differences
or similarities. Peters might have lost the understanding of the
public that is afforded backup quarterbacks. But there seems little
concern he'll need it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a new quarterback in the spring, and he looked great,''
Hart said. ``Rob is a great athlete, and now we expect a lot out of
him. We're certainly not going to go into the season thinking,
`We've got a new guy back there. We'll struggle on offense.' We can
move the ball right now. I know he can play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can run. He's got a real strong arm. He's a big
quarterback. He's smart on the field and off. He's a good leader.
And when he comes into the huddle, he takes over. It's his
ballclub.''
</P>
</TEXT>
