</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABARET-REOPENING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LIFE FOR `CABARET,' OLD FRIEND, AFTER A PAUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Happy to see you
</P>
<P>
   Bleibe
</P>
<P>
   Reste
</P>
<P>
   Stay...''
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The words, addressed to the audience in the opening
number of ``Cabaret,'' will have a whole new meaning when the show
reopens Thursday night at the Kit Kat Club on West 43rd Street, in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   For four weeks, the theater has been shuttered and dark as a
result of the scaffolding collapse a few doors away at the Conde
Nast building. Four weeks of wondering if the show would ever
recoup its losses _ $2 million in ticket sales, rent, salaries and
other expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Four weeks of not being able to bump and grind and belt out such
critically acclaimed numbers as the sinister yet seductive opening,
``Willkommen.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, all those fears seemed to be falling away as the
cast stretched and vocalized on stage, preparing to restart a run
that was one of the most successful on Broadway last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's completely thrilling,'' said Blair Brown, who was about
to take over the role of Fraulein Schneider from Mary Louise Wilson
when the show shut down on July 21.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a sense of suspense about ``Cabaret'': Would it
reopen? If so, where? Would Natasha Richardson ever get to properly
finish her run as the lost, magnetic Sally Bowles? Would her
replacement, Jennifer Jason Leigh, ever make her Broadway debut?
</P>
<P>
   Despite these unknowns, Todd Haimes, the artistic director of
the Roundabout Theater Company, which produced ``Cabaret,'' said
there was never a question that the show would return _ it was just
a question of when and where.
</P>
<P>
   The Roundabout has continued to keep the actors on full salary,
Haimes said, as well as some members of the production staff. He
said he hoped that the Roundabout's insurance, as well as
compensation from the construction company involved in the
accident, would cover a substantial amount of the company's losses.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Richard, the company's general manager, said she would
meet with an adjuster at Liberty Mutual, the Conde Nast project's
insurance carrier, about filing a claim.
</P>
<P>
   Haimes said he harbored no hostility toward the construction
project. ``The city and the Buildings Department and the Office of
Emergency Management have been fantastic,'' he said. ``I never felt
they didn't care about `Cabaret' or about our interests.''
</P>
<P>
   When the production was suspended, Ms. Brown said there was
initially a sense of being all dressed up with no place to go. ``I
was ready,'' she said. ``I was just nervous enough; everything was
just right.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she had spent the four weeks rehearsing and
distractedly doing other things _ trying to read, for example, and
not being able to concentrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was the sense that I was always supposed to be
somewhere,'' she said, ``and that place was barricaded.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews Wednesday, members of the cast and crew said it
felt good to be back in the cool dimness of the theater after their
enforced vacations. But Ms. Leigh, the film actress who takes over
Thursday night as Sally Bowles, said she had welcomed the extra
time to prepare. While other actors took time off, Ms. Leigh
rehearsed every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like, `This is grace for me,''' she said Wednesday,
seated in the theater's empty balcony with her hair cut in a Sally
Bowlesish bob. ``This is a luxury because I'm going to have more
time to rehearse and to get it inside my body.''
</P>
<P>
   The new cast members are starting out in a heavier publicity
glare than usual. Typically, actors have the chance to hone their
performances in the relatively protected atmosphere of previews.
But because of the accident, the show has attracted as much press
attention as if the reopening were a premiere.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown said she did not mind the scrutiny, having hungered
for the heady perils of performing before an audience. ``We need
that feedback,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cast and crew members agree that the presence of Ms. Leigh and
Ms. Brown make the reopening feel very much like a new chapter.
</P>
<P>
   The director, Sam Mendes, returned to help the two women step
into their roles, and both said they were unconcerned about filling
the shoes of their predecessors, both of whom were nominated for
Tony Awards (Ms. Richardson won). ``We're utterly different in
every way,'' Ms. Leigh said of herself and her predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   And if there is any good to be gleaned from the trials of
``Cabaret,'' Haimes said, it is that things can only get better
from here. ``It certainly puts other problems in perspective,'' he
said. ``Now whenever anything happens that upsets me, I'll just
think, `But a building can fall on my head.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
