<SLUG> BC-NY-HIV-SUSPECT-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN ACCUSED OF INFECTING WOMEN WITH AIDS VIRUS INDICTED ON FELONY
CHARGE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By LYNDA RICHARDSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a rare prosecution relating to exposure to the
AIDS virus, Nushawn Williams was indicted Wednesday in the Bronx on
a felony charge of reckless endangerment and accused of having
unprotected sex with a teen-age girl months after he learned he was
infected with HIV.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury indictment of Williams, 21, appeared to mark the
first time in New York City that a reckless endangerment charge had
been brought in an AIDS-related case, Bronx prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who became the subject of a national furor in 1997
after he was accused of infecting more than a dozen women and girls
in rural Chautauqua County in upstate New York, was accused of with
having sex with the 15-year-old girl in the Bronx in May 1997. The
authorities said Williams had received counseling about HIV and its
dangers in September 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Johnson, the Bronx district attorney, would not say
Wednesday whether the girl had tested positive for the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was also indicted on charges of attempted assault,
sexual misconduct and endangering the welfare of a child. Bronx
prosecutors said Wednesday that they are continuing their
investigation against Williams and are pursuing additional charges.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' lawyer, William Cember, said his client had pleaded
not guilty to the charges in the Bronx case.
</P>
<P>
   Until Wednesday, Williams had been charged only with the
statutory rape of a 13-year-old girl in Chautauqua County.
Prosecutors there have not filed any charges related to Williams'
HIV status. However, the Chautauqua County district attorney, James
Subjack, has said that he would pursue assault charges against
Williams in those instances in which the suspect knew the risk
before he had sex.
</P>
<P>
   Chautauqua County investigators have identified 48 sexual
partners of Williams. In addition to the 13 women and girls who
tested positive, 28 have tested negative and 7 have not been
tested.
</P>
<P>
   Williams has told health officials that he had sex with 50 to 75
women in New York City, but in many instances could not provide a
name or address so officials have been unable to trace many of
them.
</P>
<P>
   Williams left upstate New York in early 1997, after living there
for more than a year. He moved back to New York City, where he grew
up, and was arrested in September 1997 in the Bronx for selling
crack cocaine.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a number of states, reckless endangerment and assault laws
have been used to prosecute people who knowingly or negligently
expose or transmit HIV to others.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 HIV related bills were introduced in the last
legislative session in New York. One proposal, which is vehemently
opposed by advocates, would impose criminal penalties on a person
with HIV who failed to warn an uninformed partner. The advocates
say existing reckless endangerment and assault laws are adequate to
cover crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Girese, the counsel to the Bronx district attorney, said
Wednesday that an HIV-specific statute would make it easier to
prosecute cases like Williams', but such laws might also carry the
controversial ramification of casting too wide a net on people who
might be charged.
</P>
<P>
   With the reckless endangerment charge, Girese said prosecutors
will have to prove that Williams' conduct created a grave risk of
death and that he was aware of that risk. ``That's a fairly high
burden,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The outbreak of HIV cases in Chautauqua County also prompted a
flurry of proposals in state legislatures for tougher laws. Some
proposals call for more aggressive efforts to test and disclose the
status of infected people, while others make it a crime to transmit
or expose others to the virus.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, many advocates for people with AIDS and health
experts say the Williams case played a role in the passage earlier
this summer of the new HIV partner notification law. Lawmakers
voted by a wide margin in June to require that the names of HIV
positive people be reported to the state and that government
workers ask infected people to name their sexual partners so they
can be notified that they are at risk.
</P>
<P>
   A large majority of lawmakers had been known to favor the
measure. But the bill passed after the Assembly's Democratic
leadership, which had resisted the concept for years, dropped their
opposition. Some Assembly members said public pressure on them to
act intensified after the widespread publicity generated by the
Williams case.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
