<HEADLINE>
BARNICLE RESIGNATION MET WITH SADNESS, RELIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Adds Patricia Smith no comment.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Like a defeated figure in one of his own columns, Mike
Barnicle resigned the only newspaper job he said he ever wanted
Wednesday _ a decision met with relief, glee, and sadness.
</P>
<P>
   When Globe Editor Matthew V. Storin announced the newspaper's
top columnist's resignation during a late-afternoon newsroom
meeting, there was pin-drop silence followed by some stone-faced
head-shaking _ and some wide smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Coming just two months after another of the paper's Metro
columnist, Patricia Smith, was forced to resign for the same
offense _ mixing fiction with fact _ most Globe staffers seemed
eager to write the epilogue to an embarrassing episode that had
stirred a national debate about journalistic ethics and had become
grist for local ridicule.
</P>
<P>
   (Reached in Austin, Texas, yesterday, Smith declined comment
when told of Barnicle's resignation.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a relief,'' said David Armstrong, a reporter at the Globe
for five years. ``I remain angered by the great harm both of these
cases caused to the reputation of all honest reporters and editors
at the Globe, but at least we can now go about the business of
repairing the damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle's resignation capped two weeks of unusual tumult at the
newspaper, which found itself defending charges of a
double-standard after it first called for, and days later,
rescinded a call for his ouster.
</P>
<P>
   His departure Wednesday was cheered by some community leaders,
who met last week with top Globe officials to discuss how the
newspaper deals with and promotes its minority employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``In trying to keep him at first, the Globe management was
putting out a fire with gasoline,'' said the Rev. Jeffrey Brown,
chairman of the Boston Ten Point Coalition. ``I'm hoping this is a
step in the right direction in terms of the Globe not only
addressing its journalistic integrity, but also addressing issues
of diversity at the newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Lichter, president of the Washington-based Center for
Media and Public Affairs, called Barnicle a tragic figure out of an
old-school newsroom that has little place in modern-day journalism
whose standards, he said, are increasingly unforgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to recognize that there's more to journalism
than printing the facts,'' Lichter said. ``There is catching the
flavor of a city and connecting with ordinary people. And in that
style of journalism, there were those who took some liberties with
the facts to make that connection. You can't justify it. And, yet,
it's sad to see it go.''
</P>
<P>
   Some veteran Globe staffers were sad to see Barnicle, who some
said was synonymous with the Globe among the newspaper's
readership, forced from the most conspicuous job at the paper after
25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a tragedy,'' said Stan Grossfeld, a Pulitzer
Prize-winning photographer and associate editor at the paper. ``I'm
really saddened by it. It's bad for the paper and the readers and
all of us. He's been the subject of a witch hunt. He's been a
franchise player for this paper and I'd like to hear from him what
he has to say about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian McGrory, who covers the White House for the Globe, called
Barnicle's resignation an ``incredibly sad day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who laughs or cheers about this doesn't understand the
institution, the business, or what we mean to the community and
what Barnicle has meant to the community for a quarter of a
century. This is nobody's victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, after Storin's unusual decision last week to retain
Barnicle after he confessed to being lazy and sloppy for allowing
jokes from a George Carlin book to appears in an Aug. 2 column,
about 50 staffers signed a petition disagreeing with that decision,
saying it sent the wrong message about the newspaper's standards.
</P>
<P>
   And, they said, any applause in the Globe's newsroom was for a
reaffirmation of those standards and not for downfall of a
long-time Globe employee.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I still strongly disagree with the Globe's decision to
simply suspend Barnicle initially, I am very pleased that the
newspaper acted quickly to seek his termination after learning
about this latest outrageous episode of fabrication,'' said Diego
Ribadeneira, a 12-year veteran and the paper's religion writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It restores some of my faith in the standards that this paper
claims to embrace,'' he said. ``I hope the Globe continues to
investigate and make public all allegations regarding Barnicle's
work that continue to stream in. Barnicle apparently is incapable
of doing his job honestly and with integrity. Someone like that _
no matter his name recognition, popularity with readers or the
clout he enjoys with the white establishment media _ has no
business working at this newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Kurkjian, an investigative reporter and editor at the
Globe for 30 years, said that once the Barnicle furor subsides and
newsroom divisions heal, he hopes people will recall the voice the
columnist gave people from Beacon Hill to Roxbury Crossing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he got too stretched from all his other outside
obligations that he couldn't maintain the past quality of his
columns; maybe he became alienated from others who work so hard
around here to make the paper compelling and straight as it is, and
forgot the rules we all operate under,'' said Kurkjian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know the specific reasons for his failings but I do
know that he was not a fraud or a trimmer. Any police reporter
working a major crime story could attest to that. Tipped off to the
tragedy by some pal in the police department, Barnicle was
inevitably there with his notebook out, and the information that
filled it _ whether observations or quotes from cops, eyewitnesses
or family members _ he never hesitated to share with any Globe
reporters who asked.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle, who had promised to reduce his outside appearances
after his suspension was rescinded last week, was not left
unemployed by the Globe's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at WCVB-TV, Channel 5, where Barnicle works as a
member of its magazine show, ``Chronicle,'' said it is keeping him
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our point of view is that in the 15 years that Mike has been
on our air, we have found one three-second transgression,'' said
Elizabeth Cheng, the station's programming director. ``The nature
of newspapers and television are very different. One person can't
get a story on the air. It takes a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Zachary R. Dowdy, a Globe reporter and president of the Boston
Association of Black Journalists, said he is relieved that the
controversy is finally over, ``putting several months of racial
tension in the city and the journalism world behind us.
</P>
<P>
   ``That the Globe asked for Barnicle's resignation because of
fabrications mirrors the punishment given to Patricia Smith, which
also obliterates the appearance of the double standard that
surfaced a week ago when the Globe flip-flopped on its decision to
release him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
