<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2254 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-5     08-19 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT ALLOWS GATES TO TESTIFY IN CLOSED SESSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related story, BRISTOL-MICROSOFT-SUIT) 
(mk) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal appeals court Wednesday ordered that
pretrial questioning of Bill Gates and 16 other Microsoft Corp.
executives be taken behind closed doors, overruling a lower court
judge who had ordered lawyers to take public depositions in the
government's antitrust case against the software giant.
</P>
<P>
   Although the order by a three-judge panel of the U.S. Court of
Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit is temporary, pending
a hearing in September, a ruling in the appeal will not be rendered
until after the depositions have been taken.
</P>
<P>
   But the appellate court judges noted that because the
questioning would be videotaped, it could be shown to the news
media and the public later if mandated by the final ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who is hearing the
government's antitrust case against Microsoft in U.S. District
Court here, reluctantly ruled that a U.S. antitrust law left him no
alternative but to force the depositions to be open to the news
media and to the public. That ruling had been sought by three news
organizations _ The New York Times, The Seattle Times and the cable
television and online news units of Ziff-Davis, a computer trade
publisher owned by Softbank Corp. Their filing was joined by two
news services, Reuters and Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the appellate judges were considering Microsoft's appeal
of Jackson's ruling, lawyers for Microsoft, the Justice Department
and the news media were drafting recommendations for Jackson on how
a public deposition in a federal case would be handled.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft had argued that taking the depositions with reporters
present would create ``a carnival atmosphere'' that would
``seriously interfere with Microsoft's ability to prepare for trial
in the short time remaining.''
</P>
<P>
   The depositions of Gates and the other executives are being
taken in preparation for a trial, which is scheduled to begin Sept.
8. Both Microsoft and the Justice Department, however, have asked
the U.S. District Court for a two-week postponement, largely
because of delays that are anticipated for arranging and taking
public depositions.
</P>
<P>
   The judges issuing Wednesday's order, Stephen Williams, Douglas
Ginsburg and David Sentelle, set out a schedule in September for
hearing full arguments on Microsoft's appeal. Their order reasoned
that ``the balance of harm favors the appellant,'' Microsoft,
because the pretrial interviews would remain private if Microsoft
eventually won the appeal, yet could be made public by means of the
videotape if Microsoft lost.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Wednesday evening, Microsoft said it was
``gratified by today's decision, and we will move ahead to schedule
the remaining depositions as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who will preside over the trial next month, scheduled a
hearing for Friday morning to determine how the pretrial
preparations should now proceed, and whether the trial can begin on
time.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last week, Jackson ruled that an obscure 1913 law left him no
choice but to open the pretrial depositions to the news media and
the public. The law states that in civil antitrust actions brought
by the federal government, the taking of depositions ``shall be
open to the public as freely as are trials in open court, and no
order excluding the public from attendance on any such proceedings
shall be valid or enforceable.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court did not rule on the applicability of that law
to this case; that is what it will decide after the hearings in
September. The court simply ordered the depositions to proceed in
private, pending its decision next fall.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Levine, the lawyer representing the news organizations,
said: ``I'm certainly disappointed, but we're not dead yet. At the
very least, we have a shot at getting the videotapes.'' Still, he
added, ``I think the public interest here is diminished to a degree
that the statute did not contemplate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department had sided with the news organizations but
on Wednesday said, ``The order is clear, and we will comply with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Jackson had refused Microsoft's request that the
depositions be allowed to proceed in private while the company
appealed his decision.
</P>
<P>
   But no depositions have been taken in the meantime because the
judge also ordered the parties to set out elaborate, detailed rules
for taking the depositions in public. Those rules, filling a
10-page legal brief, were delivered to the court Wednesday
afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
