<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2261 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOTTERY-BOGUS-SPI &LR;      08-19 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTTERY-BOGUS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLIONAIRE PLEADS GUILTY IN LOTTERY CONSPIRACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A Canadian millionaire pleaded guilty Wednesday to
conspiring to violate U.S. gambling laws for his role in selling
chances at foreign lotteries to hundreds of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the more than 800 lottery customers prosecutors
identified were elderly. Some lost their life savings after buying
the telephone pitch to invest thousands of dollars at a chance to
win millions in lotteries in Spain, Australia or Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers never got a ticket, merely a share in blocks of numbers.
Some people did win, but hundreds lost millions of dollars. The
worst case found by prosecutors was a person who lost $329,000.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his guilty plea, James Blair Down, 55, of
Vancouver, B.C., also agreed to surrender $11.7 million that
federal agents seized last year from Down's stockbrokers, Smith
Barney in Bellevue. Much of that money will go for restitution for
people who bought lottery tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The guilty plea represents the first U.S. prosecution of foreign
lottery sales, said U.S. Attorney Kate Pflaumer. It also culminated
five years of investigation across different continents. But it may
not be the last prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Pflaumer said U.S. and Canadian authorities will continue to
crack down on the lottery sales, and she cautioned U.S. consumers
against such schemes.
</P>
<P>
   Many other companies also continue to operate around Vancouver,
Montreal and Toronto, selling the idea of winning millions in an
offshore lottery to Americans, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch out: Blair Down isn't the only person out there offering
gold at the end of the rainbow,'' said Gerald Miera, agent in
charge of Seattle's postal inspectors. ``What they are offering is
baloney.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven people indicted last year with Down have yet to be
extradited to the United States to stand trial. One defendant has
reached a plea agreement, which has been sealed.
</P>
<P>
   The warning from prosecutors came too late for Monte Opsata, 94.
The Seattle area man spent $70,000 to $80,000 on lotteries after
getting calls from Down's telemarketers.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a wheelchair waiting for the court proceedings to
begin Wednesday, Opsata described himself as a ``sucker'' who
bought ``wind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan was never to give you something,'' he said. ``The
plan was to steal.''
</P>
<P>
   He described how he was convinced that by cleaning out his bank
account and betting on the foreign lotteries he could become a
millionaire. His problems only came to light when he asked his
granddaughter Virginia Guy for a loan of $40,000, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Guy and her husband made repeated trips to Vancouver,
confronting employees in basement of a parking garage where the
calls were made. Finally, they were given $42,000 for Opsata and
asked to keep quiet, Guy said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, both watched as federal marshals led a handcuffed
Down, dressed in a blue business suit, into the courtroom. He was
named with nine others last year in a 145-count indictment, then
arrested in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   He made his first U.S. court appearance Wednesday. He agreed to
a plea bargain and admitted to the conspiracy charge.
</P>
<P>
   He could face five years in prison, but prosecutors have agreed
to recommend six months. Down may get to serve that sentence in
Canada. Prosecutors will drop all charges against his wife, Joan
Livingstone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's getting off easy,'' Opsata told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors said their attempts to get Down to face trial in
the U.S. would have taken years. One Canadian court has overturned
that nation's laws that outlaw foreign lottery sales.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian courts typically won't extradite someone to the U.S. to
stand charges for something that is not a crime in Canada. So
higher Canadian courts would have to resolve the question before
extraditions could take place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many, many of our victims would be dead by the time the
extradition process was completed,'' said Peter Mueller, who
prosecuted Down.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors now hope that restitution can be made in the next
six months. People who believe they were victims of Down's should
ask for a claim package by writing to U.S. v James Blair Down
Restitution Fund, P.O. Box 2328, Seattle 98111-2328.
</P>
<P>
   Down's attorney handed out a statement that said that Down
pleaded guilty ``in an effort to bring closure to this matter and
to ensure that restitution is made to aggrieved persons entitled to
relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said they warned Down as long ago as 1992 that
selling foreign lotteries in the United States was against the law.
</P>
<P>
   Federal sources said the $12 million that Down surrendered
represents perhaps a third of his wealth. He maintains large homes
in Vancouver and on the Caribbean island of Barbados.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Richard Troberman said Down conducted his business
openly and legally in Canada. He noted that Down did not admit
guilt to nor was ever charged with fraud. ``Those people who
purchased lottery tickets received the full value of their
purchases, and, in many instances, had winnings which were paid,''
Troberman said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
   Mueller and Plfaumer, however, described a different business
that preyed upon the vulnerable elderly and made
misrepresentations.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, Down's companies marked up the lottery chances
500 to 600 percent, Mueller said.
</P>
<P>
   What people bought weren't lottery tickets, but an interest in
the lottery. Instead of tickets, they got sheets with numbers on
them.
</P>
<P>
   From 1994 to 1995, the companies made 5 million calls to the
United States, Pflaumer said.
</P>
<P>
   There were some winners, including anyone who spent $100,000,
Pflaumer said. ``They could have a TV set or a VCR or a check for
$5,000,'' Pflaumer said. ``They could get their picture taken and
say how happy they were to participate in the lottery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
