</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) RIVERHEAD, N.Y. -- Aug. 19, 1998 -- CIR-MAKING-WAVES-1,
8-19 -- At Splish Splash Water Park in Riverhead, computers control
water movement in the Lazy River. The ride pushes water - and
people, sitting snugly in inner tubes - across a flat,
1,300-foot-long surface. Water gets sucked into grates positioned
every couple of hundred feet along the floor of the river, where it
travels via large pipes to one of three pumping stations in the
park. (Maxine Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) BRONXVILLE, N.Y. -- Aug. 19, 1998 --
CIR-COMPUTER-TUTORS, 8-19 -- Jim Mulcahy, a computer consultant
with Computer Tutor (at) PCI in Bronxville, makes house calls in
the New York area for people with computer woes. He will even call
help lines so his clients don't have to. ``I'm the help desk for
people who don't work for a corporation,'' he says. (Susan
Farley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) TIJUANA, Mexico -- Aug. 19, 1998 -- CIR-HDTV, 8-19 --
High-definition TV sets at a Matsushita plant in Tijuana.
Manufacturers say some of the components used to build these sets
cost more than they had anticipated. Despite the high price, and
despite the fact that most of these televisions will be huge
rear-projectors that will dominate almost any room in which they
are placed, retailers say they expect to sell as many as the
industry can make. (Denis Poroy/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) SAN DIEGO -- Aug. 19, 1998 -- CIR-HDTV-1, 8-19 --
Augusto Sorzano examines a high-definition monitor at a San Diego
store. After more than a decade of research and political debate,
most of the world's consumer-electronics manufacturers have
announced their plans and prices for the new high-definition
television sets that go on sale in September. And talk about
sticker shock: The least expensive ones will cost $8,000. (Denis
Poroy/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) VALENCIA, Calif. -- Aug. 19, 1998 --
CIR-ROLLER-COASTERS-2, 8-19 -- The Riddler's Revenge roller coaster
at Six Flags Magic Mountain outside Los Angeles is controlled by a
special computer system, operated out of this dingy, unfinished
control center. ``The day of the ride operator with a lever and
brake is history,'' says Jim Blackie, director of maintenance at
Magic Mountain. ``It's all computer controlled.'' (Chris
Pizzello/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) VALENCIA, Calif. -- Aug. 19, 1998 --
CIR-ROLLER-COASTERS-1, 8-19 -- The technology that operates rides
like Riddler's Revenge has largely removed the risk of human error
from roller-coaster control. As riders are whipsawed around a track
in apparent pandemonium, it is machines and not people that insure
that the cars whiz down the track at the right speed, do not
collide and do not hit obstacles that block the route. (Chris
Pizzello/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NANTUCKET ISLAND, Mass. -- Aug. 19, 1998 --
NANTUCKET-DUMP-3, 8-19 -- Mary Langdon finds a framed botanical at
the island's dump. Inaugurated in 1988, the 17,500-square-foot
Nantucket Citizens Recycling Drop-Off Center and Landfill -
complete with gray shingled shed - has its own weekly social set,
from year-round local residents to summer people. (Ed Quinn/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NANTUCKET ISLAND, Mass. -- Aug. 19, 1998 --
NANTUCKET-DUMP-2, 8-19 -- A wing chair arrives, and one of the
``gulls'' moves in. This is a local scene that doesn't show up on
the postcards. A popular decorating and renovation resource,
islanders call it the Madaket Mall - aka the dump. (Ed Quinn/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NANTUCKET ISLAND, Mass. -- Aug. 19, 1998 --
NANTUCKET-DUMP-1, 8-19 -- Ole Lokensgard with his daughter Sonja in
the cottage he designed and furnished with dump materials,
including ceiling and cabinetry wood, dining table and chairs. ``I
refer to my house as the idiot savant house because of its
eccentric nature,'' says Lokensgard, 52, an architect who visits
the Nantucket Island dump twice a week. (Ed Quinn/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) SHELTER ISLAND, N.Y. -- Aug. 19, 1998--
BLIND-GARDENER-2, 8-19 -- William Price, blind for 50 years,
gardens every day, growing flowers like the northern phibiscus, at
left, from seed. ``I know all the weeds,'' says Price, 84. His
farmhouse, right, dates from the 1880s. (Fred R. Conrad/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) SHELTER ISLAND, N.Y. -- Aug. 19, 1998 --
BLIND-GARDENER-1, 8-19 -- William Price, blind for 50 years,
gardens every day, growing flowers from seed. He does all his
gardening by himself, once someone else turns the soil with a
rototiller in the spring. ``Nobody else has set foot in this garden
to work in it except me,'' says Price, 84. (Fred R. Conrad/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- Aug. 19, 1998 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 8-19 --
Real estate surveys show that most home buyers decide to buy a
house within the first 15 minutes of seeing it. This kind of
impulsive buying can have disastrous repercussions if the house has
a major flaw or defect that's not immediately detectable. While
first impressions are important, they should be buttressed by a
careful inspection. (Edward R. Lipinski/New York Times
Illustration) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ANNANDALE-ON-HUDSON, N.Y. -- Aug. 19, 1998 --
BARD-ARTS-CENTER-2, 8-19 -- Lucy Kuriger and Geoff Carter of
Montgomery Place argue their points across the Saw Kill from the
proposed site of Frank Gehry's building on the small-town campus of
Bard College. They are worried that the 105-foot stainless steel,
glass and concrete building will be seen above and through the
trees from the mansion's numerous trails. (Joyce Dopkeen/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ANNANDALE-ON-HUDSON, N.Y. -- Aug. 19, 1998 --
BARD-ARTS-CENTER-1, 8-19 -- Bard College President Leon Bottstein
is set on bringing big-name architecture to his small town campus.
Designed by Frank Gehry, who created the Guggenheim Museum in
Spain, the $28-million Bard Performing Arts Center would have some
of the same sweeping, fluttering silvery roofs and
draftsmen-defying curves as the museum. But a lot of people here
think it's in the wrong spot. (Joyce Dopkeen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BOSTON -- Aug. 19, 1998 -- MORMON-MISSIONARIES-BOS, 8-19
-- Sisters Tenille Roberts and Amanda Williams on there way to
bible study. During the last quarter-century, the Church of Jesus
Christ of Latter-day Saints has been among the nation's
fastest-growing religious communities. ``We're here because the
Lord wants us here,'' says Sister Williams. ``We're here to offer
people the truth.'' (Bill Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BOSTON -- Aug. 19, 1998 -- LOTUS-MICROSOFT-BOS, 8-19 --
Lotus Development Corp.'s chief executive, Jeffrey Papows during a
