<SLUG> BC-CAR-GORDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR RECORD FOR GORDON IS ONLY A FEW MILES AWAY  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By TARIK EL-BASHIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having already established himself as the driver to beat this
season, Jeff Gordon has a chance to preserve his place in Nascar
history this weekend with a fifth straight victory.
</P>
<P>
   A triumph by Gordon at Bristol, Tenn., on Saturday would set a
record for consecutive victories in modern Nascar Winston Cup
racing.
</P>
<P>
   Six other drivers _ Mark Martin, Bill Elliott, Harry Gant, Dale
Earnhardt, Darrell Waltrip and Cale Yarborough _ share with Gordon
the record of four straight victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to dominate in Nascar,'' Earnhardt said. ``But
Gordon and his team are certainly doing that. We did the same thing
in 1987 when everything went our way and we won 11 races. You can't
explain it, the cards just fall your way. Right now, the No. 24
bunch is head and shoulders above the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   If Gordon wins for the fifth straight time this weekend it will
be his ninth victory of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The string of victories began last month at Pocono, where the
efficient work of his pit crew late in the race put him out front
for good.
</P>
<P>
   The streak continued in Indianapolis six days later.
</P>
<P>
   After Dale Jarrett ran out of gas, Gordon drove away from the
field to become the first two-time winner of the Brickyard 400. He
collected a prize package, including a bonus from Winston, of more
than $1.6 million, the largest in American motorsports history.
</P>
<P>
   The week after that, Gordon ran down Mike Skinner at Watkins
Glen, N.Y., taking the lead with only five laps remaining as
Skinner was forced to slow and conserve fuel.
</P>
<P>
   That third straight victory was also Gordon's third won from the
pole position.
</P>
<P>
   The streak, however, appeared in jeopardy last weekend at
Brooklyn, Mich. Gordon was in position to finish high, but had not
led a lap all day.
</P>
<P>
   Then, once again, he benefited from the wizardry of his pit
crew.
</P>
<P>
   He came into the pit in third place late in the race, left in
second place, and drove by Martin a few laps later to take his
fourth straight checkered flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``The records are great because when your career is over you can
look back and say that was cool you did that,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   A victory on Saturday would be the 38th of Gordon's career.
</P>
<P>
   During his streak, Gordon has started from the pole once, the
outside of the front row once and from inside the second row. He
has led by as few as nine laps (Michigan) and as many as 154 of 200
(Pocono). Over all, Gordon has run up front for 325 of the 650 laps
in the four races.
</P>
<P>
   Working in Gordon's favor this weekend is the location of the
race.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol is a track where he has enjoyed much success. He has won
four times at the short track, which resembles a bowl because of
the high-banked turns, and was victorious there last spring. But
should he win on Saturday, it will be his first triumph under the
lights at Bristol.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Bristol a lot, but it's been up and down for me there
for the night race,'' he said. ``We're excited about it because we
know it is a good track for us, but we have to have some luck too,
some of that luck that we had at Michigan.''
</P>
<P>
   His excellent starting positions, Gordon said, have had much to
do with his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to try to go in there, qualify up front and
do what we've been doing,'' Gordon said. ``We have a 97-point lead,
but all it takes is a 40th-place finish and that lead is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his opportunity to set a record, Gordon said his focus,
and that of his team, remains on the championship.
</P>
<P>
   He leads Martin by 97 points. But it was at Bristol last season
when Martin trailed Gordon by 99 points, only to emerge 13 points
in the lead after a second-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   Of the six drivers who share the modern-day record for
consecutive victories with Gordon, Waltrip came closest to making
it five, in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   He lost his bid at Atlanta when Neil Bonnett edged him at the
finish line by less than two feet. Waltrip was in the lead when the
white flag was waived, but Bonnett pulled even with him on the
backstretch and beat him by a nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our careers parallel each other so well,'' Waltrip said.
``From the success I had in the early 80's to the success he's
having right now. I was just like he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the right car, the right team, the right driver, the
right sponsor and the right time, and that's just where he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Waltrip added, ``Bristol is a difficult track to run
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Cale Yarborough and Harry Gant also came close to recording
a fifth straight victory. But Yarborough finished second to Donnie
Allison at Charlotte in 1976, when Allison took the lead from
Yarborough on the 308th of 334 laps. And Gant was passed by
Earnhardt with eight laps to go at North Wilkesboro in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt was passed by Davey Allison with 10 laps to remaining
at Talladega in 1987 in his bid for a fifth straight victory, and
Martin dropped to sixth after dominating most of the race at
Richmond in 1993, when he went for a fifth consecutive triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Elliott was the only driver with four straight victories
not to have at least a chance at capturing his fifth race in row.
He had mechanical trouble at Bristol in 1992, wound up 30 laps down
and finished 20th.
</P>
<P>
   Should Gordon set the record at Bristol, it would seem that
Richard Petty's streak of 10 straight victories, which came during
Nascar's pioneer era up until 1972 when the series staged about 50
races each season (there are now about half), might even be in
jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   After Bristol, Nascar goes to New Hampshire and then to
Darlington, N.C., tracks where Gordon has been dominant in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
