</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMOKE AND MIRRORS AND CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some members of Arizona's congressional delegation are so upset
with President Clinton they believe he should be impeached and
removed from office. Like many other fair-minded justice-loving
citizens, I'd be more than willing to go along with that _ right
after we indict the chairman of R.J. Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the top bosses of Philip Morris, U.S. Tobacco,
Lorillard Tobacco, Liggett Group, Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco and
American Tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Matt Salmon said after Clinton's Monday night speech, ``I
personally believe he lied under oath . . . and as I recall, the
perjury laws provide no exemption for sex.''
</P>
<P>
   He's correct. The law is the law. Perjury is perjury. Members of
Congress, who swear to uphold the law, do not believe in special
treatment or exemptions.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, you're testifying about tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, seven top executives of the nation's largest
tobacco firms appeared before a committee of the U.S. House of
Representatives and stated _ under oath _ that they believed
nicotine was not addictive.
</P>
<P>
   The merchants of death also swore _ under oath _ that they
``weren't sure'' whether cigarette smoking causes disease.
</P>
<P>
   So far as I know, none of them has been charged with a crime. &QL; 
Accepted tobacco money &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of course, back in the 1980s and early '90s, Rep. Salmon was
among the thousands of American politicians accepting fat campaign
contributions from tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   So was Salmon's fellow Republican from Arizona, Rep. John
Shadegg, who also suspects Clinton of perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of these politicians takes tobacco money now.
</P>
<P>
   When the public opinion polls started going against
cigarettemakers, Salmon, Shadegg and many others ran for the hills.
(Which they could do, being non-smokers.)
</P>
<P>
   But near as I can tell, none of the politicians now condemning
Clinton has suggested the big boys of tobacco also be indicted for
perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Why not?
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton, we're talking about misleading people over some
hanky-panky with an intern.
</P>
<P>
   With the other guys, it's misinformation about a product that
kills 435,000 Americans a year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's deception took place during a deposition in the Paula
Jones sexual harassment case. Lying to Congress is worse.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Michael Deaver, a former top White House aide and
friend of President Reagan, was found guilty on three charges of
lying under oath to a grand jury and to a congressional committee.
</P>
<P>
   Each of those charges carries a penalty of up to five years in
prison and thousands of dollars in fines.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, while speaking under oath, the head of one tobacco
firm compared smoking cigarettes to eating sweets. &QC; 
Equal treatment? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, if members of Congress treated Clinton the way
they treat Joe Camel, they'd not only ignore the president's lies,
they use tax dollars to subsidize his extramarital affairs.
</P>
<P>
   And they'd pulverize anybody who tried to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   Sort of the way they killed Sen. John McCain's plan to cut
teenage smoking by giving the government authority to regulate
nicotine and increasing the tax on tobacco by $1.10 a pack.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's other senator, Jon Kyl, who piously has stated that
he, too, was ``offended'' by Clinton's speech, was among those who
voted to kill McCain's plan.
</P>
<P>
   Hypocrisy, like nicotine, is addictive.
</P>
<P>
   The president deceived us about his relationship with Monica
Lewinsky for something like seven months. With the tobacco
companies, it's been generations.
</P>
<P>
   With Washington lawmakers, it's ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   This is only one example. While cigarettes turn good people to
ash, politicians blow smoke about Clinton. I'm no surgeon general,
but that's got to be bad for your health.
</P>
<P>
   Try not to inhale. &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
