New York Times Photo Package, moving 8/19/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- Aug. 19, 1998 -- FOOD&AMP;WINE-FOUNDERS, 8-19 --
Ariane and Michael Batterberry, founders of Food and Wine magazine.
The Batterberrys believe that the history of food is more
scintillating than the history of . . . anything. ``When you start
looking at people and what they did in restaurants, you're dealing
with public life as it's lived day to day and that's real
history,'' says Mrs. Batterberry. (Librado Romero/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Aug. 19, 1998 -- TIMES-SQUARE-TICKERS-2,
8-19 -- The Nasdaq market is planning one of four signs in Times
Square emphasizing financial information. Its sign will be on the
Conde Nast building under construction in Times Square. (Don Hogan
Charles/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Aug. 19, 1998 -- TIMES-SQUARE-TICKERS-1,
8-19 -- As stock ownership has grown, so has financial information.
The Morgan Stanley Dean Witter building in Times Square has three
157-foot zippers that display stock and financial information. (G.
Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) CAMERON, Texas -- Aug. 19, 1998 -- TEXAS-GOV-CANDIDATE,
8-19 -- Garry Mauro, left, the Texas land commissioner and
Democratic candidate for governor, stops at the home of Kathy and
Bill Vogelsang in Cameron in his door-to-door campaign to unseat
Gov. George W. Bush. ``I've knocked personally on nearly 7,000
doors and my supporters have hit more than 300,000,'' says Mauro.
``We're going to hit a million doors by Labor Day and that's just
the beginning.'' (Ted Albracht/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 19, 1998 -- CLINTON-MCHALE, 8-19 --
Rep. Paul McHale, in his office in Washington on Wednesday, was the
first Democratic congressman to call for President Clinton's
resignation. He says that he took his stand reluctantly after
concluding that it would set an ``awful precedent'' to allow a
public official to remain in office after lying under oath.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Aug. 19, 1998 -- CABARET-REOPENING, 8-19 --
Jennifer Jason Leigh stretches and the orchestra warms up while
waiting to begin a rehearsal of Cabaret, which reopens Thursday
night at the Kit Kat Club on West 43rd Street. For four weeks, the
theater was shuttered and dark as a result of the scaffolding
collapse a few doors away at the Conde Nast building. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) HOLLYWOOD -- Aug. 19, 1998 -- FILM-EDITING, 8-19 -- Tina
Hirsch, with digital film-editing equipment now widely used in
Hollywood. Some editors and directors still prefer to cut their
films on old-style Moviolas. At first, the film editor was,
literally, the director's secretary,'' says Ms. Hirsch. ``Each
scene was a single master shot, and the secretary would assemble
them for a 10-minute movie.'' (Steve Goldstein/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) KENNEWICK, Wash. -- Aug. 19, 1998 --
CIR-ONLINE-COLLECTING, 8-19 -- Chuck Windisch collects campaign
buttons for his son, Tommy, age 4. The reach and immediacy of the
Web are becoming irresistible for history buffs and collectors of
political paraphernalia, even among those who see impulse as the
enemy and whose collections tie them so tangibly to the past they
love. (Andre Ranieri/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) SAN FRANCISCO -- Aug. 19, 1998 -- CIR-PIRATE-RADIO, 8-19
-- Richard Edmondson and his equipment. In the lexicon of the
Federal Communications Commission, he and dozens of other operators
of unlicensed low-power radio stations are ``pirates'' - criminals
who interfere with licensed programming and with air traffic
control frequencies, creating a safety hazard. But to hundreds of
appreciative listeners, Edmonson has been Patrick Henry with an FM
frequency. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) RIVERHEAD, N.Y. -- Aug. 19, 1998 -- CIR-MAKING-WAVES-2,
8-19 -- At Splish Splash Water Park in Riverhead, three
150-horsepower turbines make the waves for the Wave Pool. The waves
are produced by blowing tremendous gusts of air into the water at
different intervals, much like the way real waves are produced
except that the wind has to be manufactured. (Maxine Hicks/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) RIVERHEAD, N.Y. -- Aug. 19, 1998 -- CIR-MAKING-WAVES-1,
8-19 -- At Splish Splash Water Park in Riverhead, computers control
water movement in the Lazy River. The ride pushes water - and
people, sitting snugly in inner tubes - across a flat,
1,300-foot-long surface. Water gets sucked into grates positioned
every couple of hundred feet along the floor of the river, where it
travels via large pipes to one of three pumping stations in the
park. (Maxine Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) BRONXVILLE, N.Y. -- Aug. 19, 1998 --
CIR-COMPUTER-TUTORS, 8-19 -- Jim Mulcahy, a computer consultant
with Computer Tutor (at) PCI in Bronxville, makes house calls in
the New York area for people with computer woes. He will even call
help lines so his clients don't have to. ``I'm the help desk for
people who don't work for a corporation,'' he says. (Susan
Farley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) TIJUANA, Mexico -- Aug. 19, 1998 -- CIR-HDTV, 8-19 --
High-definition TV sets at a Matsushita plant in Tijuana.
Manufacturers say some of the components used to build these sets
cost more than they had anticipated. Despite the high price, and
despite the fact that most of these televisions will be huge
rear-projectors that will dominate almost any room in which they
are placed, retailers say they expect to sell as many as the
industry can make. (Denis Poroy/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
