<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2277 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-ART-2TA     08-19 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS SEEK CLINTON DNA SAMPLE TO VERIFY SEXUAL ACTIVITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-POLITICS, CLINTON-VINEYARD, CLINTON-HEARTLAND,
CLINTON-MCHALE, CLINTON-POLLS; graphic on Nielsen ratings is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JAMES BENNET and DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a sign that prosecutors are dissatisfied with
President Clinton's limited admission of an intimate relationship
with Monica Lewinsky, they demanded Wednesday that he provide a
sample of his genetic material to establish forensic proof that the
relationship was sexual.
</P>
<P>
   The move strongly suggests that the FBI crime lab has determined
that a dress turned over to prosecutors by Lewinsky contained DNA
from semen. One person familiar with the findings said the lab
technicians had found semen on the dress. Prosecutors are trying to
determine whether Clinton stained the dress in a sexual encounter
with Ms. Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   The request by Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr came on
Clinton's 52nd birthday, which he marked privately with his family
during a vacation on Martha's Vineyard. It signaled that
prosecutors do not plan to soften their aggressive tactics after
Clinton's admission to a grand jury Monday that he had
``inappropriate intimate physical contact'' with Ms. Lewinsky in
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's team had believed that the results of testing on the
dress were mooted by the president's admission, as well as by a
brief speech he gave Monday night calling the relationship ``not
appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   White House press secretary Mike McCurry said any sample turned
over to the FBI would be obtained from the Bethesda Naval Hospital,
where Clinton undergoes annual physicals and where supplies of his
blood are stored.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately known how Clinton's lawyers would respond
to the request. It came a day before Ms. Lewinsky, who was said by
friends to feel hurt by the president's terse public description of
their relationship, is scheduled to appear for a second time before
the grand jury here.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's request suggested that he is determined to learn what
specific type of sex Clinton and Ms. Lewinsky had. But such an
effort could work to the president's political benefit as Congress
weighs conducting impeachment hearings, some of his advisers
believe. They think it could make prosecutors appear sex-obsessed,
even as most Americans tell pollsters that they already know more
than they would like about lies, betrayal and sexual indiscretion
at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But Starr is clearly dissatisfied with the president's
testimony. Clinton refused to give prosecutors a detailed
description of his sexual contact with Ms. Lewinsky, after reading
a statement admitting the affair at the beginning of his four-hour
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has been seeking to determine if Clinton committed perjury
in January, when he denied any sexual relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky during a deposition in the Paula Jones sexual misconduct
suit.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony Monday, Clinton argued that the type of sex he
had with Ms. Lewinsky did not fit the definition of sex used by the
Jones lawyers. Although he rebuffed prosecutors' questions about
his sexual contact with Ms. Lewinsky, he did answer a series of
questions about what types of sex he considered to be covered by
that definition, one Clinton adviser said Wednesday. The president
said that oral sex, among other acts, was not covered by the
definition, the adviser said.
</P>
<P>
   But the adviser to Clinton said the president did not
acknowledge having oral sex or any other type of specific sexual
contact with Ms. Lewinsky, instead referring prosecutors back to
his initial statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over and over, he said, `I've already said that it was
improper,' '' said the adviser, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Because Starr has asked the president for a DNA sample, it is
highly unlikely that he had not been told what was found on the
dress.
</P>
<P>
   But Starr chose to wait to ask for a sample of the president's
genetic material until after Clinton completed his grand jury
testimony. Law enforcement officials dismissed the possibility that
Starr would have asked the president for a sample in an attempt to
``bluff'' him.
</P>
<P>
   A careful vagueness about his encounters with Ms. Lewinsky is
central to the president's legal and political strategy, his
advisers say, since it may help deflect a possible perjury charge
while also walling off seamy details from an already queasy public.
Clinton was even more vague in his four-minute address Monday night
than in his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   That speech was watched by 67.6 million people, Nielsen Media
Research said Wednesday. Some 53 million viewers watched his
far-longer State of the Union Message, delivered shortly after
Clinton was first accused of having an affair with Ms. Lewinsky and
covering it up.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton advisers have said that Clinton answered every question
put to him that did not deal with sex. That position is also
central to the president's political defense: If Starr demands
further testimony, the president's team would like to be able to
argue that prosecutors are intent on grilling him only about
intimate matters. ``We want to make the argument that Starr's
investigation is just about sex,'' the adviser said.
</P>
<P>
   David Kendall, Clinton's private attorney, did not agree to
extend his testimony more than a few minutes beyond the four-hour
time limit, even though prosecutors had more questions. Starr said
that he might subpoena Clinton for further testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The White House would not confirm the request from Starr's
office. It released a two-sentence statement: ``On Monday night the
president acknowledged an improper relationship and apologized for
that. The president also said it's time to reclaim his privacy, and
we will respect that by not commenting on every leak generated by
this investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In recalling Ms. Lewinsky, who testified to the grand jury
August 6, Starr is seeking to determine if there are
inconsistencies between her account and Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Lewinsky prepared to testify again, she was said by
friends to be unhappy about Clinton's speech Monday night. Ms.
Lewinsky, her friends said, was dismayed to hear what she regarded
as a romance with Clinton _ a lengthy relationship that included
gifts of poetry and neckties _ acknowledged as merely an
inappropriate dalliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an older man who made all the instances and
references to a younger woman that this relationship was not just
about sex,'' one friend said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky's friends said that she had always intended to tell
the truth before the grand jury, so her feelings would have no
impact on her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Since the president acknowledged an intimate relationship with
Ms. Lewinsky on Monday night, White House advisers and prominent
Democrats have been disclosing their wounded feelings over the
intimate revelations of recent days. Some appear to be bidding for
public sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   Others are just downright mad. Among them is Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, D-Calif., who said Tuesday that her trust in Clinton's
credibility had been ``badly shattered.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days just after the Lewinsky accusations were disclosed
last January, Clinton sought to reassure Feinstein by privately
telling her that Ms. Lewinsky had had to be transferred from the
White House because she was fantasizing about him, and ``on the
verge of stalking him,'' a person close to Ms. Feinstein said
Wednesday. Friends said that helped explain Ms. Feinstein's strong
statement of disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   On vacation at a borrowed Martha's Vineyard estate, Clinton
celebrated his 52nd birthday on Wednesday night with Vernon Jordan,
his friend and confidant. It was the first extended time that the
two men and their families spent together since Jordan was
subpoenaed by Starr to explain his role late last year in helping
Ms. Lewinsky find a job in New York. He has denied any effort to
help hide her relationship with the president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton awoke Wednesday to calls for his resignation from some
editorialists and Republican congressmen. His advisers dismissed
such statements as the chattering of Washington elites, saying that
the public had heard more than it wanted to hear about the Lewinsky
investigation, and was anxious for the federal government to turn
to matters of policy.
</P>
<P>
   Some longtime Clinton allies argued that Starr was seeking to
make crimes out of private indiscretions. ```I think the
criminalization of bad sexual judgment is something we ought not to
be doing,'' said James Carville, Clinton's former campaign manager.
``It's just loony.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
