<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2280 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAZI-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      08-19 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAZI-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL ENDS FOR BUSINESSMAN ACCUSED IN NAZI WAR CRIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The civil trial of Jack Reimer, the retired
businessman accused of concealing his role in Nazi war crimes,
ended Wednesday after two weeks of anguished courtroom
recollections from Holocaust survivors and numbingly detailed
descriptions of how a Nazi training camp worked.
</P>
<P>
   It is likely to be several months, however, before Judge
Lawrence M. McKenna of U.S. district court in Manhattan rules on
the Justice Department's request to have Reimer, 79, stripped of
his United States citizenship, a first step toward his deportation.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said he would hold open the already-voluminous court
record to accept further evidence while three more potential
witnesses are sought by Reimer's lawyers. McKenna gave no deadline
for finding the witnesses, who are elderly German war veterans and
may have known Reimer at Trawniki, a training facility for Nazi
guards and a concentration camp, in Poland.
</P>
<P>
   The government maintains that Reimer, who was born in the
Ukrainian Republic of the Soviet Union and served in the Soviet
Army until his capture by the Nazis, helped train guards at the
camp and led his units on duty that involved killing Jewish
prisoners and liquidating Jewish ghettos. He came to the United
States in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   Edward A. Stutman, a Justice Department lawyer, said that
although Reimer began his service for the Nazis as a Soviet
prisoner of war at Trawniki, he ultimately became a favored and
trusted officer with all the privileges of leave, salary and
commendations from the German command.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has given contradictory statements about what he
did, Reimer told McKenna that he trained only one group of men at
Trawniki, never entered any ghetto, never killed anyone and served
most of his time at the camp as its paymaster.
</P>
<P>
   As his civil trial wound down, he made one more protest against
the government's charges and the shouts of ``Nazi'' from some
spectators at the trial. ``I just can't stand it when they call me
that,'' Reimer told the judge. He added, ``They always have the
attitude: You were there, so you must be guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   McKenna said that before ruling on the crux of the case, he
would determine the admissibility of crucial documents submitted as
evidence, as well as testimony referring to those documents. The
record includes German wartime archives, interviews with former
Russian prisoners of war who had served at Trawniki, and
self-incriminating statements made by Reimer during a 1992
interview with government lawyers that he later asserted were
coerced.
</P>
<P>
   Calling himself a ``child of the Cold War,'' the judge said he
had questions about the reliability of some of the Russian material
_ mainly the statements given by Russian witnesses to investigators
right after the war, when Stalin was shipping Russians returning
from prisoner-of-war camps to Siberian labor camps as traitors, and
to the KGB in the mid-1960s, when the Communist regime embarked on
a fresh campaign to root out Nazi collaborators and publicize Nazi
war crimes in Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In previous cases to revoke the citizenship of people accused in
war crimes, Soviet-era evidence has been ruled admissible, said a
Justice Department lawyer involved in such cases, who insisted on
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last seven years, documents from the archives of the
former Soviet Union and Eastern bloc countries have played an
increasingly significant role in the Justice Department's hunt for
Nazi war criminals who slipped through the postwar immigration
screening procedures.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Reimer, such archive material could prove pivotal
because it contains some of the only witness accounts of people who
placed Reimer at certain events and, in one case, identified him as
a Nazi officer who pushed Jews into a pit for massacre.
</P>
<P>
   The main government evidence from Soviet files is a set of 1964
interviews by the KGB with two Russian war veterans, both of whom
had been captured by the Germans and transferred to Trawniki in
1941.
</P>
<P>
   English-language translations of the KGB records show that both
men identified Reimer as a junior officer, and as entering the
Lublin ghetto at the time of its liquidation and assisting in
killing several dozen people in a pit in a forest outside Lublin.
</P>
<P>
   Reimer has denied ever having been in a Jewish ghetto, much less
having participated in rounding up Jewish prisoners for dispatch to
the Nazi death camps or participating in the Lublin-area murders.
</P>
<P>
   But the Russian evidence may also prove problematic. Justice
Department lawyers traveled to northern Russia in January to
interview one of the war veterans in person. But the man, Nikolai
S. Leontev, now 86 and half-blind from a war injury, gave them an
ambiguous and decidedly more befuddled account of what he saw
Reimer do during the war, according to transcripts of the
government's interviews with Leontev.
</P>
<P>
   The transcripts revealed, for example, that Leontev said he
exaggerated some figures in his account to the KGB 34 years
earlier. Pressed for details about the activities of his unit,
which he had said served under Reimer, he protested repeatedly that
he could not remember, the transcripts showed.
</P>
<P>
   He contradicted some of his earlier testimony, specifically
concerning whether Reimer had ever entered the Lublin ghetto.
</P>
<P>
   When he finally said he remembered Reimer, according to the
transcript, Leontev described him as ``a nice fellow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't the type to hand out punishment,'' Leontev told his
American visitors. ``He never said an unkind word.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
