<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2282 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-BELLS-500&AMP;AD     08-19 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-BELLS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET RULING A BLOW TO LOCAL PHONE COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Internet service providers won a major victory Wednesday when an
appeals court upheld the Federal Communications Commission's
decision to exempt Internet service providers from paying local
phone companies the access fees that the Bells are allowed to
charge long distance carriers.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was a blow to local telephone companies that had
argued that Internet service providers, like long-distance
companies, use local phone lines to connect users to global
networks and thus should have to pay the same fees. In fact, the
Bells argue that on a per-customer basis, Internet users tend to be
a greater drain on local phone networks than long-distance callers
are because Internet connections frequently last for hours, while
most long-distance calls are measured in minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The decision on local access fees was handed down by the 8th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in St. Louis as part of a broader
opinion that ruled on a number of issues stemming from portions of
the 1996 Telecommunications Act, in which Congress attempted to
encourage cuts in long-distance rates.
</P>
<P>
   In another setback for the Bell companies, the judges also
upheld FCC regulations intended to reduce the $23 billion that
local phone companies collect from long distance carriers by $1.7
billion. The commission estimated the savings would be worth about
$2 a month to the average long distance customer.
</P>
<P>
   The exemption for Internet service providers was especially
controversial because so much had changed since it was implemented.
More than a decade ago, long before the Internet was a mass medium,
the FCC defended the exemption from access charges for the
fledgling data communications industry on the grounds that
assessing the same fees exacted from long-distance companies would
stifle the young industry's growth.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief filed in the case ruled on Wednesday, BellSouth Corp.
and Bell Atlantic argued that times and the data services industry
had changed. Describing the exemption as a ``new, implicit and
discriminatory subsidy'' for the Internet service providers, they
contended that the rise in Internet usage was overburdening their
systems and forcing the Bells to make huge investments in
additional capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Phone networks were originally designed to handle only 10
percent usage, meaning that no more than one in 10 phones would be
in use at one time. With the increasing growth of Internet users
who spend infinitely more time online than traditional telephone
callers, Bell companies maintain they are the ones shouldering the
burden.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel ruled that the FCC's exemption did not
discriminate in favor of Internet service providers because such
companies did not use the services and facilities of the local
phone companies ``in the same way or for the same purposes as other
customers who are assessed per-minute interstate access charges.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike long-distance companies, which charge users per minute,
most Internet service providers offer unlimited access for a flat
monthly fee.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Analysts had predicted that if the Bell companies won, online
services would have to raise their rates and might be forced to
abandon the flat-rate pricing that had helped propel the rapid
growth of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ruling maintains the status quo,'' said Scott Cleland, a
telecommunications analyst in Washington for Legg Mason Precursor
Group. Referring to Internet service providers, he added, ``This is
a win for ISPs.''
</P>
<P>
   America Online, the largest Internet provider in the country,
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Local phone companies argued that the access fees subsidized
phone service for poor people or people living in rural areas or
other places where the cost of building and maintaining a telephone
infrastructure would otherwise be prohibitive.
</P>
<P>
   Long-distance carriers maintained that the access charges were
still too high because they ``are set at billions of dollars more
than what it cost the Bells to provide the service,'' said Peter
Lucht, a spokesman for MCI. Still, he said, ``the FCC's decision
last May to reduce access charges was at least a step in the right
direction, and the court was right to uphold it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same decision, the court also upheld another FCC decision
to increase the federally mandated ``subscriber line charge'' for
businesses and residences that have multiple phone lines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
