<SLUG> BC-DELTA-UNITED-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELTA AIR'S PILOTS THREATEN ITS DEAL WITH UNITED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The grand alliance between United Airlines and Delta Air Lines
may be threatened by a labor dispute at Delta.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's pilots union, which has the power to veto the most
critical part of the link with United, said Wednesday that Delta's
decision not to give the union a voting seat on the board
effectively ended the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told them that we are ceasing our consideration of the
alliance and that is what we have done,'' said Karen McGuffey, a
spokeswoman for the Air Line Pilots Association. ``It's over.''
</P>
<P>
   But Delta apparently is not getting the message. ``We hope that
ALPA will go forward with its consideration of the alliance,'' said
Delta spokeswoman Kay Horner.
</P>
<P>
   The contradictory statements go beyond the all-too-common
miscommunication between labor and management to disclose the weak
foundations of the three alliances that have swept up the six
largest domestic airlines this year. The announcement by Northwest
Airlines in January that it was buying a controlling stake in
Continental Airlines set off a mad scramble among the other major
airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing that a Northwest-Continental combination would attract
their passengers, United and Delta formed an alliance, while
American Airlines joined with U S Airways Group.
</P>
<P>
   Each pair of airlines agreed to combine their frequent-flyer
programs, but Northwest and Continental and United and Delta also
said they would code share, or sell seats on each other's flights.
</P>
<P>
   United and Delta say that their alliance will bring them $600
million in additional revenue every year. But that assumes that the
other airlines do not go ahead with their alliances. If all three
deals are implemented, the competitive landscape remains unchanged.
``It's a zero-sum game,'' said Kevin Murphy, an analyst at Morgan
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   The Northwest-Continental deal is now in limbo, awaiting
approval from the antitrust division of the Justice Department. A
decision is not expected until next month at the earliest, analysts
said. Until then, the pressure on United and Delta is off.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Northwest and Continental begin code sharing, that will put
pressure on Delta to find a new avenue to approach the pilots,''
said Samuel Buttrick, an analyst at Paine Webber in New York.
``Right now there is no urgency.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when Delta announced its decision Monday, seemingly
scuttling the alliance, shares of both Delta and United rose.
Murphy said that investors have not even factored the alliances
into their buying decisions. ``People know that the announcement by
Northwest and Continental is not a sure thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots at both Delta and United have clauses in their
contracts giving them the right to veto code-share agreements with
other airlines. But United's pilots also have a full seat on the
airline's board of directors, while Delta's pilots only have a
non-voting representative.
</P>
<P>
   The Delta pilots held up the announcement of the alliance in
April when they insisted on full board representation. The deal
only went ahead after the union agreed to give Delta management
until Sept. 30 to convince the company's board to give them a vote.
But Monday, Delta chief executive Leo Mullin said the board had
rejected the idea because ``an independent board best serves Delta
and its constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   The airline said that it would go ahead with its plans to
combine its frequent-flyer program with United's beginning Sept. 1,
a move that does not require pilot approval.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe that the pilots will have little choice
but to bend if the other alliances are poised to siphon off Delta
passengers, reducing their flying opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   So is the alliance over? As Buttrick of Paine Webber, put it:
``It's over until it begins again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
