<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0463 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2288 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVITRO-SUIT-BOS &LR;      08-19 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVITRO-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-HUSBAND FILES WRONGFUL PREGNANCY SUIT AGAINST CLINIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOREEN IUDICA VIGUE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a case that could set precedent in the burgeoning
world of reproductive science, an ex-husband is suing a Boston
clinic for wrongfully impregnating his former wife with frozen
embryos fertilized with his sperm.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Gladu has filed a lawsuit alleging breach of contract
and medical malpractice against Boston IVF and Dr. Selwyn P.
Oskowitz for implanting an embryo that resulted in the birth of a
baby girl without his permission. When his former wife filed for
child support for the couple's three children, Gladu objected to
being held financially responsible for a baby produced without his
consent.
</P>
<P>
   In what Gladu's lawyer, Ernest Murphy, is calling a ``wrongful
birth'' action, Gladu is asking for $3 million in damages from
Oskowitz and Boston IVF, the clinic that performed the procedure on
Meredith McLeod, Gladu's former wife, in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Gladu, a Wayland firefighter who says he loves his
daughter, is charging that as patient of Boston IFV, he should have
been notified by the agency of the procedure, and was shocked to
learn his then-estranged wife had gone behind his back to have a
baby he did not want.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the birth, Gladu claims in his lawsuit filed at
Middlesex District Court, he has endured ``the infliction of severe
and continuing emotional distress'' which will require ``medical
and psychological treatment therefor (sic) indefinitely.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He feels his embryo _ his property _ was stolen, and his right
to be a knowing parent was stolen,'' said Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   This case offers its own factual twist to a chain of actions
around the country concerning the unusual status of frozen embryos.
With steadily increasing numbers of couples using the procedure,
unimplanted embryos often end up in the freezers of fertility
clinics, where they can remain viable _ and sometimes fought over _
for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some sense, he volunteered to go under this program, and he
assumed some risk that everything was not going to work out,''
George Annas, chairman of the health law department at Boston
University School of Public Health, said of Gladu. ``You can argue
contracts. But you can't treat those like a typical commercial
deal. Children aren't products. They dynamics of having a baby are
complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Annas said that parents usually are reluctant to file suits over
in vitro procedures, because ``these are very personal family
matters, and they're mostly not winners unless there is something
wrong with the child,'' indicating possible malpractice.
</P>
<P>
   Gladu and McLeod, who also have an older adopted daughter and a
four-year-old son conceived by consensual in vitro fertilization,
were separated but not divorced at the time of the second
pregnancy. They divorced in 1997, and McLeod received custody of
the three children.
</P>
<P>
   Gladu, who earns $40,000 per year, according to Murphy, was
ordered to pay McLeod $1,000 per month in child support _ a sum
that he found financially crippling. The portion of the amount to
cover the baby's upbringing, which his lawyer estimates to be $350
per month, was enough to drive him into financial ruin, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really financially in dire straights right now and I don't
see any vast improvements for the foreseeable future,'' said Gladu,
who claims he has had to sell his Wayland home and move into an
unheated cottage in Dennis in order to make ends meet. ``I'm no
crusader, but I don't want this to happen to any loving father
again. I should have had a choice. This has turned my life upside
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Gladu claims his former wife, a nurse, went ahead with the
pregnancy on her own as a last-ditch effort to save their marriage.
McLeod, who has not been named in the lawsuit, could not be reached
for comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Donnelly,, an attorney for Oskowitz, issued a statement
without making further comments: ``We have looked into the
circumstances of this matter and found that Dr. Oskowitz acted
appropriately and within the highest standards of care.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent to Murphy responding to the suit and filed in
court, Donnelly wrote that Gladu had signed a statement agreeing to
have remaining embryos ``returned to the body (womb) of the female
spouse so named on (the form) within three years from the date of
embryo freezing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Implicit if not explicit in these options selected by Mr.
Gladu is the request that the embryos be maintained for transfer to
Ms. McLeod unless certain specified contingencies arise.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``contingencies'' were not specified.
</P>
<P>
   Donnelly's letter also said that Gladu and McLeod had
contracutally agreed to inform Boston IVF if their marriage were to
dissolve, but the couple had not done so.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, however, claims the contract said no such thing. He
claims that, according to a document Gladu and McLeod signed with
Boston IVF in April of 1993, when they were undergoing medical
procedures to have their 4-year-old son, all embryos not used in
that procedure would be discarded or donated to another couple.
</P>
<P>
   Five embroys were fertilized, two were used to conceive their
son, and the remaining three were frozen but, apparently, not
discarded or donated. McLeod announced her pregnancy to Gladu in
January, 1996, when the couple was separated, but still living
together and going through counseling.
</P>
<P>
   According to the lawsuit, a stunned Gladu called Oskowitz to
inquire how this happened without his knowledge or permission, and
Oskowitz replied that a mistake had been made and he should get to
the clinic right away.
</P>
<P>
   Gladu maintains he was duped by his ex-wife and by Boston IVF,
who did not hold to their contract or inquire why he had not
participated in the second procedure at all, when he was completely
involved in the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can imagine, in your wildest dreams, someone sticking a
baby in your hands and saying, `This is yours, it's your natural
child and you must support it for the next 18 years and put it
through college, how would you feel?'' said Murphy. ``Everytime he
(Gladu) holds that child he has feelings of ambivalance. He loves
the girl. He just hates the way she came to him and someone must
pay for that.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Gladu admits that pursuing the lawsuit could have
a devastating affect on his daughter someday. He insists he has
loved her from the first time he held her when she was three days
old. Still, he knows his fight may ultimately cost him his
daughter's love in return.
</P>
<P>
   ``How am I going to explain this to her?'' said Gladu. ``There's
no book on the subject. It's very gut wrenching for me. I know this
will be a story that people carry with them and she'll find out.
But I think, I hope, there is a way I can explain it to her so she
understands someday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
