<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT CLOSES MICROSOFT INTERVIEWS TO PUBLIC, NEWS MEDIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WARREN WILSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. won another victory in its antitrust battle
Wednesday when a federal appeals court ruled that chairman Bill
Gates and other executives may give pretrial depositions without
reporters or the public present.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel said it will issue a final decision in the
matter sometime after Sept. 29, three weeks after the antitrust
trial is scheduled to begin, although that Sept. 8 date could also
be moved back.
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft spokesman said the company was ``gratified'' by the
ruling, and that it ``will allow depositions of its executives to
move forward without delay.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for news organizations that sought to attend the
depositions expressed dissapointment, saying the judges gave too
little weight to the public's right of access to testimony as it is
given, without delay. They also warned that the question could be
moot if the judges don't settle it for six weeks or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time they hear it, much of this may already be under
the bridge,'' said Josh Koltun, one of the news organizations'
attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is scheduled to start Sept. 8, but that could change
at a conference this morning with U.S. District Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson. Both Microsoft and the U.S. Department of Justice
have asked Jackson for a two-week delay, in part because of delays
in taking depositions.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the judge reluctantly granted the news organizations'
motion to open the depositions, saying he had little choice given
the plain language of the 1913 statute on which they based their
request. He ordered the participants to work out the details of how
to conduct the sessions in public.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft immediately appealed, saying it feared the disclosure
of sensitive business information if reporters and the public were
allowed to watch.
</P>
<P>
   The company argued trial procedures have changed since the 1913
law requiring openness in depostions in antitrust cases. In 1937,
new Federal Rules of Civil Procedure were adopted, governing such
proceedings as gathering testimony in depositions. Those rules
appear to conflict with the 1913 law.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals panel didn't rule Wednesday on the legal issues.
Instead it gave the participants until Sept. 29 to finish filing
the documents it will consider in its decision.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the case moving forward, it said the Microsoft
executives could be questioned under the normal procedures for
legal depositions. The two sides agreed earlier on rules for
restricting access to sensitive information gathered in closed
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   In deciding to let the depositions proceed, the panel said the
``balance of harms'' favors Microsoft. If they were taken in public
and the company later wins its appeal, ``the disclosure could not
be undisclosed,'' they wrote. But if Microsoft loses, the text and
videotape of a private deposition can then be disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The case involves claims by federal and state antitrust
regulators that Microsoft has illegally forced computer makers to
accept its Internet browsing software if they also want its Windows
operating system for personal computers, for which they have no
real alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's actions have been harmful to competition, and
particularly to its main rival in the browser market, Netscape
Communications, the government says.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft says it has integrated the two software products _ the
browser and the operating system _ in ways that benefit consumers.
A June ruling by the appeals court in a related case supports that
view, Microsoft said recently when it asked Jackson to issue a
summary judgment to end the case _ a move not considered likely.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Microsoft was hit Wednesday with a new antitrust
lawsuit by a Connecticut company that accuses it of withholding
technical information vital to its business in order to impede
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol Technology of Danbury, Conn., makes software that
converts Windows programs to run on other operating systems, such
as Unix. In 1994 it signed an agreement that it says entitles it to
detailed technical information known as ``source code'' from
Microsoft to make its own products work better, as well as advance
warning if Microsoft planned to change the source code.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after ``creating a dependency'' on that information for
Bristol and its customers, Microsoft is withholding it, the company
claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bristol is very disappointed that it was necessary to sue to
obtain what Microsoft has said all along it would provide us,''
said Keith Blackwell, the company's chairman and president.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft spokesman Jim Cullinan dismissed Bristol's claim as
``wholly without merit,'' saying it was trying to elevate a
``routine business negotiation'' into a federal lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The companies have been negotiating terms of a new license
agreement, Cullinan said, but Bristol broke off the talks ``without
any prior notice to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Other companies have accepted the same license terms that
Bristol rejected, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
