<SLUG> BC-MIAMI-FRAUD-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-MIAMI COMMISSIONER GETS YEAR IN JAIL FOR VOTER FRAUD COVER-UP
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A former Miami City commissioner was sentenced Wednesday
to a year in jail, the maximum penalty, for trying to cover up
voter fraud in last November's election. Humberto Hernandez, until
recently one of the city's most powerful politicians, had been
convicted last week on a misdemeanor charge.
</P>
<P>
   The jury last Friday found Hernandez, 35, guilty of being an
accessory after the fact to a conspiracy to cover up the fraudulent
absentee votes cast by a former City Hall secretary and her
husband, a Miami police officer. The scheme was part of a pattern
that, prosecutors alleged, enabled Hernandez to clinch a
comfortable victory in his district in last November's citywide
elections.
</P>
<P>
   He was acquitted of more serious charges, including conspiracy
and fabricating evidence. On Monday, however, Gov. Lawton Chiles
removed Hernandez from his post as commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez appeared to choke back tears Wednesday, his head bent
forward, as Judge Roberto Pineiro meted out the sentence with a
stern lecture.
</P>
<P>
   `'I cannot envision a more felonious misdemeanor than the one
you were convicted of,'' Pineiro said. `'Our elections must be
fair, free and untainted by even the hint of fraud to insure the
continued existence of that democracy. You sought to destroy all
this simply for your political advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez's legal troubles are not over, however. Since late
May, he has been in custody awaiting trial on federal charges of
mortgage fraud and money laundering. His father and his former
chief of staff, who are behind bars, face similar charges. That
trial is scheduled to begin late next month.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say that Hernandez would have to serve his misdemeanor
sentence separately, in a county jail.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hernandez had close ties to Xavier Suarez, who won last
November's mayoral election. However, Suarez was removed from
office earlier this year after Joe Carollo filed a civil suit
alleging that the election was invalid because it was tainted by
widespread voter fraud.
</P>
<P>
   During that trial, lawyers for Carollo, who narrowly lost the
election, charged that hundreds of absentee ballot votes cast in
favor of Suarez were either invalid, cast by people who gave false
addresses or, in one case, cast in the name of a person who was
dead. In early March, a judge voided the election and later ruled
that Carollo should assume office.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, the son of Cuban immigrants, was known for his charm
and good political connections. He enjoyed a large following in the
Little Havana district.
</P>
<P>
   His tangles with the law have been regarded as the ultimate
symbol of justice officials' fight against wrongdoing by powerful
politicians in this scandal-ridden city of 360,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest piece of evidence against him was a series of tape
recordings in which he is heard discussing ways to tackle the fact
that a City Hall secretary, Evelyn Herbello, cast her ballot using
a false home address. Ms. Herbello became a witness for the
prosecution after her name appeared in a local newspaper in
connection with investigations of widespread voter fraud, and
agreed to wear a wire.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, Hernandez's lawyers maintained that the former
City Commissioner was being penalized for the actions of aides and
friends who had committed fraud without his knowledge. Hernandez
even lashed out at his detractors on Spanish-language radio
stations here accusing them of targeting him because he is of
Hispanic descent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
