A2292 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION     08-19 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON KEEPS LOW PROFILE, SPURNS CALLS FOR RESIGNATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
and NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton spent his 52nd birthday with
family and close friends in Martha's Vineyard on Wednesday as
details emerged from his grand jury testimony, including reports
that he admitted engaging in specific sexual acts with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, independent counsel Kenneth Starr reportedly has
secured an agreement from the president to provide a blood sample
that can be genetically compared to a stain found on a dress
Lewinsky told prosecutors she wore during a sexual encounter with
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, the 25-year-old former White House intern, spent part
of the day with Starr's deputies preparing for her return visit
with the grand jury Thursday to respond to questions growing out of
Clinton's unprecedented testimony. Linda Tripp, whose secret tapes
of Lewinsky's telephone conversations with her triggered the
investigation, also was summoned to appear before the grand jury
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's appearance comes three days after Clinton answered
some questions from prosecutors, refused to answer others, then
went on national television to confess to an improper relationship
and to misleading the public about it for the past seven months.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton remained out of the public eye Wednesday,
through a spokesman he dismissed calls for his resignation, a
chorus that included House Republican Whip Tom DeLay of Sugar Land,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   At Martha's Vineyard, an island off the Massachusetts coast,
presidential spokesman Mike McCurry said Clinton ``is confident he
enjoys the trust of the American people who elected him.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry reported that the president, first lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton and their daughter, Chelsea, spent most of the day to
themselves. The president took birthday calls from his brother, his
brothers-in-law and his stepfather.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the evening, the first family celebrated the
president's birthday at the vacation home of Vernon Jordan, a
Washington power broker who helped Lewinsky find a job as she was
being summoned to testify in a sexual harassment lawsuit against
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was among 70 witnesses summoned before the federal grand
jury since January, when Starr expanded his investigation of
Clinton's Arkansas business dealings to include whether the
president or his associates obstructed justice by trying to cover
up his relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, the first president to testify in a criminal
investigation of his actions, appeared by closed-circuit television
before the grand jury Monday afternoon and read a statement
admitting an 18-month relationship with Lewinsky, according to
sources knowledgeable about his testimony. Clinton's statement
included admissions that the relationship was inappropriate and
included intimate, physical contact.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors pressed for additional information, and Clinton
initially balked, then reportedly acknowledged specific sexual
encounters in which Lewinsky performed oral sex. When Starr and his
deputies pushed for a more detailed accounting of the trysts,
Clinton declined to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with Clinton's refusal to answer all their questions,
Starr and his deputies reserved the right to again issue a subpoena
for the president's testimony, a summons they earlier served, then
withdrew after he agreed to testify voluntarily. If the subpoena is
reissued, it could lead to a lengthy court fight that would further
delay Starr's plan to issue a report to Congress early this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday, Clinton's private lawyer, David Kendall,
acknowledged the impasse saying the questions were ``highly
intrusive'' and ``to preserve personal privacy and institutional
dignity (the president) gave candid, but not detailed, answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources familiar with Clinton's testimony said that before the 5
1/2-hour session ended he denied trying to hide his relationship
with Lewinsky. Clinton told the grand jury he did not ask Lewinsky
to lie under oath in Paula Jones' sex harassment lawsuit against
him. He also did not ask Jordan to find Lewinsky a job to buy her
silence and did not ask her to hide gifts from him, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
   Four hours after his testimony, the president went on national
television and acknowledged an inappropriate relationship with
Lewinsky. He also assured the nation that his denial of engaging in
sex with Lewinsky when questioned in the Jones lawsuit was
``legally accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the definition approved by a federal judge overseeing the
Jones case, sexual relations occur when a person ``knowingly
engages in or causes ... contact with the genitalia, anus, groin,
breast, inner thigh, or buttocks of any person with an intent to
arouse or gratify the sexual desire of any person.''
</P>
<P>
   When questioned Jan. 17 by Jones' lawyers about whether he
engaged in sexual relations with Lewinsky, Clinton was shown the
definition, then responded: ``I have never had sexual relations
with Ms. Lewinsky. I've never had an affair with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, who issued a similar denial in an affidavit submitted
to Jones' legal team in January, changed her story early this month
after Starr agreed not to prosecute her in return for her
cooperation in the investigation of a possible cover-up. On Aug. 6,
Lewinsky met with the grand jury and reportedly testified that she
performed oral sex on the president and that they engaged in
telephone sex and manual stimulation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
