</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wohlers' return brings with it another decision
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mark Wohlers is expected to rejoin the Braves Friday,
which begs the question: Then what?
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, it means the demotion of a bullpen member,
which will probably be rookie Adam Butler, heading back to Class
AAA Richmond. Though right-hander Russ Springer is also eligible to
come off the 15-day disabled list Friday, the club is still
undecided on sending down another pitcher to open a second roster
spot, particularly if the Braves want to give veteran left-hander
Norm Charlton a fair chance to show he can still pitch. And with a
run and three hits allowed in 2 1/3 innings, Charlton has yet to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   But those decisions only foreshadow the bigger ones the Braves
must make by Aug. 31, when postseason rosters must be established
come midnight. Every year, the Braves drop a pitcher from their
11-man staff for October and add a 15th position player. Manager
Bobby Cox drops to a three-man rotation for the five-game Division
Series and then a four-man rotation for the seven-game LCS, meaning
fifth starter Kevin Millwood moves to relief duty.
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers returns to Atlanta as he left last week _ as the staff's
11th man _ and barring a miraculous turnaround, he will not be
included on the postseason roster (though he and anyone in the
system as of Aug. 31 would remain eligible for the October roster
in case of injury to one of the first 25).
</P>
<P>
   General manager John Schuerholz, who spoke with Wohlers
Wednesday, maintains the club has not yet determined how it will
proceed, but it is clear it will need Wohlers' roster spot on the
31st (though he can immediately rejoin the club as a September
call-up). Wohlers will again have to accept an optional minor
league assignment, since the Braves cannot force a player with his
service time off the 25-man roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the issue that he's a five-year man and in order for
him not to be on our (25-man) team, he has to be in the minor
leagues,'' Schuerholz said. ``And in order for him to be in the
minor leagues, he as to give his permission to go, which he has
done twice. I can't imagine he'd not do it a third time.''
</P>
<P>
   But if he declines?
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have to ask him. I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Raffy to Richmond
</P>
<P>
   Exactly 19 weeks after tearing his left quadriceps, shortstop
Rafael Belliard accepted a rehab assignment to Richmond, where he
has roughly 10 days to show the club he can still help. Since going
on the 60-day injured list, Belliard's spot as reserve shortstop
has been taken by Ozzie Guillen but because Belliard can also play
second base, he does provide a defensive option, should the team
wish to go that way with a postseason roster. He will be in uniform
today against Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   ``First,'' said Cox, ``we have to see if he can play.''
</P>
<P>
   The 200 Club
</P>
<P>
   Typically, a player reflects the day after he reaches a
milestone, when he has had the chance to put the last game behind
him. The day after his career 200th victory, Greg Maddux could not
do that, simply because Maddux refuses to reflect on anything,
which may help explain some of his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``The individual stuff is nice,'' he said, ``and I'm real proud
of it. But it's important not to lose sight of what it's all about,
and right now, that's trying to finish up our division and get
ready for the postseason and get ready to make a good run through
the playoffs. What I really want is the ring. I'm glad to get to
200, but I really want a ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
