<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REDSKINS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Stubblefield, Wilkinson give Redskins' run defense a big-time boost
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Free agency in the NFL is a crap shoot, but the Washington Redskins
believe they hit the jackpot when they stole defensive tackle Dana
Stubblefield from San Francisco to improve a run defense that
ranked 28th in the NFL last year. In his final season with the
49ers, Stubblefield registered 15 sacks and was named the league's
Defensive Player of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Just to make sure they solidified the weakest area on the team,
the Redskins traded for Cincinnati defensive tackle Dan Wilkinson,
who signed a new multimillion-dollar contract. Now, Stubblefield
and Wilkinson take up more room in the middle than a duplex.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard we got both of them, I was in shock,'' cornerback
Darrell Green said. ``Any time you bring in two guys like them,
you've really upgraded your team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins hope Stubblefield and Wilkinson have upgraded the
team so much that they win the NFC East for the first time since
1991, when they won their last Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Giants are the defending champion, but Washington
plans to dethrone them in coach Norv Turner's fifth season. If they
do not at least make the playoffs, Turner's job could be in
jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the division's wide-open until someone knocks
off the Giants,'' Stubblefield says. ``They're the division champs,
and everyone wants to beat them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you this: There's no limit to how good we can be.
We've got so many good defensive players. There's no limit to what
this defense can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they have compiled winning records the last two years,
the Redskins haven't reached the playoffs since 1992, Joe Gibbs'
last season as coach. After the Redskins finished 8-7-1 last year,
Turner and general manager Charley Casserly identified the areas
that needed to be improved in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Turner had hired Mike Nolan as his defensive
coordinator, and the defense improved from 28th to 16th. The
Redskins were third in pass defense without much of a rush from the
defensive linemen. What hadn't improved significantly was the run
defense.
</P>
<P>
   A big part of that could be traced to the season-long holdout of
defensive tackle Sean Gilbert. The Redskins refused to give in to
what they thought were preposterous demands, and he sat out the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were 30th and 28th in run defense the last two years, and
we knew we had to get better,'' Casserly says. ``A lot of defensive
tackles were available in free agency, so this was the time to make
the move. Our division's going to be a dogfight again, and we think
we've improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, we were only going to get one, but the more
we thought about it, the more we thought we could get two to do
this right. The owner made the (financial) commitment to get it
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Owner John Kent Cooke gave his braintrust the millions it took
to sign Stubblefield. When Gilbert, the franchise player, signed
with Carolina, the Redskins received two No. 1 picks in return.
Knowing they would have the Panthers' draft choices, Casserly dealt
picks, including this year's No. 1, to the Bengals for Wilkinson,
who was the first player selected in the 1994 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan was a young guy (underclassman) coming out of college, and
we thought he played better with the Bengals than people gave him
credit for,'' Casserly says. ``Bringing him here and surrounding
him with good players, especially good veteran players, should help
him improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not asking Dan to be the guy. We just want him to be
part of this defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson, who grew up in Ohio and played at Ohio State, never
lived up to the high expectations the Bengals had for him. The
Redskins are hoping the change of scenery will be ideal for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been fired up from the first day they traded for me,''
Wilkinson says. ``When I first visited with the Redskins, they told
me they were going to try to sign Dana, and they did a couple of
weeks later. I was fortunate they were able to trade for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``This organization's ready to win right now. Not many teams
would have put up that kind of money for two tackles. That reflects
on the organization and their commitment to getting the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson had only five sacks last season when he was forced to
move outside in a three-man front and back inside in a four-man
front. But there is far less pressure on him in Washington compared
to Cincinnati. He is expected to share the load, not carry it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great opportunity for me to play next to an All-Pro
like Dana,'' Wilkinson says. ``He makes a lot of plays. I'm
learning a lot from him. The communication and awareness are
getting better as time goes on. We'll have everything ironed out
and be on the same page by the first regular-season game.''
</P>
<P>
   Green, in his 16th season, is the senior member of the team. He
also is Washington's best recruiter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Dana at the Pro Bowl about coming to Washington,''
Green says. ``My wife hosted his wife when they visited. When he
signed, we were real excited because we felt part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I really like about Dana is the leadership he's
showing the young defensive linemen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins aren't quite sure what to expect from offenses now
that they have Stubblefield and Wilkinson in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``My role can vary depending on how offenses play me and Dan,''
Stubblefield says. ``Are they going to double-team me or
double-team him? Are they going after the linebackers right away
and let us through? It just depends on how offensive coordinators
scout us and play us.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Redskins wanted to improve the pass defense, so
they signed cornerback Cris Dishman to pair with Green. The pass
defense improved from 20th to third, and Green and Dishman were
considered the best pair of corners in the league.
</P>
<P>
   All the defensive backs should be able to breathe a little
easier if Stubblefield and Wilkinson stay healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a big difference to have them, let me tell you,''
Dishman says. ``When the quarterback walks up to the line of
scrimmage and sees Dana and Dan, there's got to be a fear factor.
Both of them can rush the passer, and they're good run stoppers.''
</P>
<P>
   Green is 38 and Dishman 33, so they know they better take
advantage of every opportunity. They don't want to waste the
decision to sign Stubblefield and trade for Wilkinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a hell of a lot of potential on this team,'' Dishman
says. ``This is probably the best defense in the league on paper,
but if we don't perform on Sunday, it won't mean anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
