</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-WNBA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ITS SECOND SEASON, WNBA TAKING HOLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jody Conradt probably knows a little bit about the appeal of
women's basketball, having coached her Texas Lady Longhorns playing
before more than a few raucous crowds.
</P>
<P>
   And being a face in the crowd during her numerous visits to
Houston Comets games this season has enabled Conradt to witness how
this summer league known as the Women's NBA is catching on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been really impressed with how involved the crowds are,''
Conradt said. ``They're really participating in the event, and that
gives it even greater hope for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The future seems bright for the WNBA, which concluded its second
regular season last night. The league generated a reported average
attendance of more than 10,000 fans per game this season, something
the NBA needed 29 years to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   Television ratings have dropped from 1.9 to 1.6 per game on NBC
and less on the other two networks that televise games. ESPN is at
.65 after a .84 last season; Lifetime is at .49 after a .56 last
season. The rating is the percentage of television households in
the nation tuned to a program, and each point for a broadcast
network represents 980,000 homes. Each point for a cable network
represents fewer homes since not all home with televisions have
cable. But scoring in the league is up, turnovers are down and the
game is popular enough that the team with the worst record, the
Washington Mystics, has the league's best attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fan response has been terrific to our game, and I'm very
excited,'' WNBA commissioner Val Ackerman said. ``But I still
believe we have a long ways to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along that this is going to be a long process.
But it's hard not to be encouraged when we've made that much
progress in just two seasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Going into last night's regular-season finales, 69 of this
season's 146 WNBA games drew crowds of at least 10,000 fans.
Attendance at WNBA games this season was up more than 11 percent
from last season. The league was averaging 10,729 fans this season
after pulling in 9,669 last season.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Los Angeles and Sacramento are the only members of
the WNBA's eight charter franchises that failed to increase
attendance this season. But two first-year franchises _ Washington
and Detroit _ acquitted themselves well.
</P>
<P>
   Going into last night's game against the Charlotte Sting,
Washington led the league in attendance with 15,721 per game.
Detroit, which closed the season at home against the New York
Liberty, was averaging 9,799 fans per outing.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people said this wouldn't work,'' Conradt said. ``But
I think, logically, it had every chance to work, because there is
not anything to really be passionate about in the summer months
except baseball. And that doesn't appeal to everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA's second season seems to have generated some passion,
or at least drama. Going into the final night of the season,
Charlotte, New York and Phoenix were battling for the final two
playoff spots.
</P>
<P>
   And the league does have a budding marquee attraction in the
defending champion Comets, who ran off a 26-3 season, and their
star triumvirate of Cynthia Cooper, Sheryl Swoopes and Tina
Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have a Chicago Bulls in the WNBA right now, it's
certainly Houston,'' Ackerman said. ``They've got a great core, and
in every respect it's become our glamour team. They've been fun to
watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only have they had a great impact in Houston with
attendance up this year in Houston in large part because of the
great success they've had on the court. But I think it's clearly
helped create additional recognition for the league to have a team
with such star power.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston has increased its scoring from 71.1 points per game to
78.9 and cut its turnovers from 19.6 to 14.9 per game. Eastern
Conference champion Cleveland, the only WNBA team to win a game in
Houston this season, has also increased its scoring, as have
Phoenix and Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman's long-range goal is to have a WNBA team in each of the
29 NBA cities. Also, next season the league will play its first
all-star game, and increase the regular-season schedule from 30 to
32 games.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Ackerman will like to move to a 40-game schedule.
For that to happen, she said the season would have to start
earlier, because she doesn't want the WNBA to compete against the
NFL or college football.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the summer months they can attract families that are
vacationing, and they can attract kids who don't have to worry
about it being on a school night,'' Conradt said. ``I think all of
us believe that the WNBA _ with the support it has from the NBA and
the kind of marketing effort that they've made _ is going to be
something that's going to be long-term.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 2157EDT &QL; 
