<HEADLINE>
KOHLBERG KRAVIS TO ACQUIRE PAINT COMPANY IN GERMANY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Texas)   (af)  
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co. said Wednesday that it
would buy Herberts, a German paint company, for $1.7 billion in a
deal that represents the American buyout firm's growing ardor for
buying, revamping and selling companies in Europe the way it has at
home since the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Kohlberg Kravis will join with Herberts managers to acquire all
of the company from Hoechst AG, the German conglomerate, which is
seeking to shed some holdings that do not complement its core drug
operations. Herberts ranks as Europe's largest supplier of paints,
with annual sales of $1.5 billion and 7,500 workers.
</P>
<P>
   European investors, especially in Britain, have long used
private capital to buy companies. But the large-scale leveraged
buyout is much rarer there than in the United States. In such
transactions, private financiers use borrowed funds to take control
of a company, including some that are publicly traded, with the
idea of remaking its operations and selling it off again.
</P>
<P>
   Kohlberg Kravis and other leading United States buyout firms,
including Hicks, Muse, Tate &AMP; Furst and Clayton, Dubilier &AMP; Rice,
have all recently stepped up their presence in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Industry specialists say they hope that Europe will prove to be
fertile ground for American-style, finance-driven reorganizations.
Such opportunities in theory will arise more as companies there go
through the painful adjustment to global competition that United
States companies went through in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have invested a lot of time and know-how in Europe,'' said
Scott Stuart, a Kohlberg Kravis general partner. ``We feel that the
market is finally breaking the way we wish it had a long time
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, after more than a decade of sniffing around for deals in
Europe, Kohlberg Kravis has announced several successful buyouts
recently. Last month the New York-based firm announced that it
would buy the British-based insurance broker Willis Corroon Group,
a deal valued at $1.5 billion. Kohlberg Kravis officials said the
Willis purchase is the first leveraged buyout of a publicly owned
European company.
</P>
<P>
   Kohlberg Kravis previously bought Newsquest, a British regional
newspaper publisher, and Rhine Re, a Swiss reinsurance company. &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS &QC;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   European conglomerates that once branched out into many
different areas are increasingly streamlining operations and
selling parts that do not make strategic sense. That pries open the
once-cloistered market, buyout specialists say.
</P>
<P>
   ``European economies are about where the U.S. was in the
mid-70s,'' said Jack D. Furst, a partner in Dallas-based Hicks,
Muse. ``Conglomerates need to focus on core niches. That creates
wonderful opportunities for new capital to enter the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, Muse made its first stand-alone acquisition in Europe
just last week, agreeing to buy Glass' Group, a closely held
British automobile information company, for $205 million.
</P>
<P>
   The European deals come at a time when the United States market
has become less friendly to buyout firms. Company stock market
valuations are near all-time highs and easy revampings are past
news.
</P>
<P>
   Some buyout firms have become accustomed to earning returns of
30 percent for their investors annually, attracting record sums of
investment capital. But now, more funds are chasing fewer deals.
</P>
<P>
   For big buyout deals _ those valued at $500 million or more _
firms on average paid 7 times earnings in 1994. So far this year
they are paying closer to 8.5 times earnings, according to
Portfolio Management Data.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to make straight buyout deals in the U.S. these
days,'' said Josh Kosman, associate editor of Buyout Newsletter, an
industry journal. ``You pay too much for the company to make it
work.'' He added that the average European buyout is done for a
much lower price, relative to earnings, though figures for
transactions there were not available.
</P>
</TEXT>
