<HEADLINE>
CHARGERS OVERHAUL OFFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ In the heyday of Air Coryell, when the San Diego
Chargers delighted their fans with a point-a-minute offense _ and
dismayed purists with a defense that nearly matched that pace _ a
joke used to run through the organization as the annual NFL draft
neared:
</P>
<P>
   The only way to keep coach Don Coryell from using up all the
high picks on flashy pass-catchers was to prepare for the draft's 8
a.m. start _ and tell Coryell it was getting under way at noon.
</P>
<P>
   Today, nearly two decades later, the Chargers seem to have
revived their fascination for stockpiling offensive players _ but
with a notable exception. This time, as the team attempts to climb
out of the dregs of a 4-12 finish in 1997, some of the prominent
newcomers weigh in at 305, 297, 297, 248 and 245 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was pretty much our plan,'' said Bobby Beathard, who
gained fame as a general manager for constructing a system at
Washington in which a jumbo running back battered opponents behind
a line that came to be called the Hogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't as if we didn't need anything defensively, but we
felt our shortcomings were more on the other side of the ball _
quarterback being the main thing, then the offensive line.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, let's not forget that quarterback, another critical
acquisition. San Diego this year was forced to replace an
established quarterback, as Stan Humphries, at age 32, heeded
doctors' advice and retired after suffering two major concussions
in an 18-day span last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers maneuvered into position to select towering,
strong-armed Ryan Leaf of Washington State second overall. They
named him the starter before they even played an exhibition game.
</P>
<P>
   But by then, the support staff was already firmly in place.
Today, while standing along the sideline at UC San Diego watching
training-camp workouts, you need a program only for the guys in
white jerseys, the offense. That's where the new faces are
concentrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being 4-12, obviously you have to win with players,'' said
linebacker Junior Seau, the senior member of this team. ``Dean
(Spanos, the club president) and Bobby did a great job of stealing
players from other teams via free agency, and Dean opened the
wallet. And you can see that.''
</P>
<P>
   But only on one side of the ball?
</P>
<P>
   ``The best defense is a defense that is on the bench,'' Seau
continued. ``If we can get some rest and keep our players healthy
on the defensive side, we're going to have a solid defense. As for
us being jealous (about the offensive emphasis in the offseason),
no, we're not. The more points we get, the more times we can get
into a nickel situation and let loose.''
</P>
<P>
   That might be getting ahead of things a little bit. By all
indications, the Chargers will see more rough times before they
experience prosperity. It probably doesn't help that they reside in
one of the more rigorous divisions in the NFL _ where, in '97,
Kansas City and Super Bowl champ Denver combined to go 25-7.
</P>
<P>
   But at least San Diego seems to be going about the
reconstruction in the proper way.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the most important newcomers are John Jackson, Aaron
Taylor and Roman Fortin, free agents signed away from Pittsburgh,
Green Bay and Atlanta, respectively. They now comprise an entire
flank _ in order, left tackle, left guard and center _ and bring
experience and nearly a half-ton of heft to the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Another important figure is a reacquisition, 245-pound running
back Natrone Means, who returned to the Chargers as a free agent
after two seasons with Jacksonville. Still another addition is
248-pound H-back John Burke, whose blocking ability is probably
evidenced by the fact he had no pass receptions last year with the
New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers also used a high draft pick, a second-rounder, on
wide receiver Mikhael Ricks of Stephen F. Austin. They have already
written him into the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   And then they hired some people to coach these folk. The San
Diego offense was in chaos last year, as new coach Kevin Gillbride
often operated at cross purposes with assistants Mike Sheppard,
George DeLeone and Tyrone Dixon. The latter two are gone now, and
Sheppard, who was out of position last year, has moved from
quarterbacks to wide receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Brought in are two former NFL head coaches who have solid
reputations as position coaches: June Jones, the former Atlanta
coach, who will tutor Leaf, and Joe Bugel, who escaped Oakland and
will attempt to make this offensive line in the image of the one he
once had in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The trigger man for all of this was 2 years old when Dan Fouts
unleashed his first pass for Coryell. NFL convention holds that it
is folly to throw a rookie quarterback into the fray so quickly,
but the Chargers insist they're impressed with what Leaf has shown
so far. And, besides, they don't have much else.
</P>
<P>
   Terrified rookie? ``Oh, no, not at all,'' said right tackle
Vaughn Parker, the UCLA alumnus who is only one of two holdovers
from last year's line. ``He's very confident in his abilities. He's
good in the huddle. He's got a good command of the field when he's
out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, the learning curve for a quarterback is huge. It's
going to take some time before he's totally comfortable. But you
don't see him holding back out there. He's not tentative at all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This kid,'' adds Beathard, ``has been maybe even better than
we expected. He's tremendously talented. Being around him _ his
attitude and the way he acts _ his leadership really comes out.
He's a very emotional player. You can sense that burning desire to
be great.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard some off-the-field things about him, where he's
immature and does foolish things, but we haven't seen it here. It's
been all football here.''
</P>
<P>
   With a deep breath, the Chargers will put all of this into play
when they open at home against Buffalo on Sept. 6. They're staking
their resurgence to the new look. Even if the method has a faintly
nostalgic feel to it.
</P>
</TEXT>
