<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOBBY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOBBYISTS GET GOP `MARCHING ORDERS' ON CANDIDATE FUND-RAISING  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS MOESER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Senate President Brenda Burns has assigned the state's
most powerful lobbyists to raise money for specific candidates in
races Republicans must win this fall to retain control of the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Burns also warned the lobbyists that they will suffer political
retribution in the next session of the Legislature if they raise
money for Democrats, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Arizona Republic'' obtained a memo that shows lobbyists
were assigned to help raise money for GOP candidates Larry Nelson
in Yuma, Darden Hamilton in Glendale, and Senate Majority Whip Gary
Richardson in Tempe. All are considered vulnerable in this
election.
</P>
<P>
   Burns said coordinating lobbyists' fund-raising efforts was
``absolutely appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the memo confirms what many voters suspected:
That special interests have a stranglehold on the legislative
process in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the smoking gun that reveals the quid pro quo of the
current system,'' said Kaia Lenhart, political director of
Arizonans for Clean Elections. The group is supporting a ballot
measure that would provide public funding for state elections in
exchange for strict limits on campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public officials should not be bought by the highest bidder.
Arizonans want and deserve elections, not auctions,'' Lenhart said.
</P>
<P>
   The influence of lobbyists on the Arizona Legislature has been
controversial since a law-enforcement probe in 1991, nicknamed
``AzScam,'' revealed that lawmakers had taken bribes from a
lobbyist, actually a police agent, who wanted them to legalize
gambling. Since then, citizen-inspired initiatives have attempted
to curb the influence of lobbyists, with limited success, and bills
to impose new limits on lobbyists' gifts and entertainment have
been repeatedly turned down by lawmakers. The influence of
lobbyists has been the subject of an occasional ``Republic''
series, ``The Invisible Legislature,`` since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the Burns strategy, according to the memo and
sources familiar with the discussions, was to name ``champions'' in
the corps of corporate lobbyists who could direct campaign
donations from both lobbyists and political action committees from
the industries they represent.
</P>
<P>
   In notes in the margin of the memo, someone wrote, ``Need
champion for each campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are making a strong bid to pick up three seats in the
state Senate, which would deadlock the chamber at 15-15. That would
make it difficult for Burns to hang on to her power and could
severely hamper the conservative agenda at the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The three-page memo came from a meeting held July 15 at
Republican Party headquarters in Phoenix. It includes four columns
of information: The first is titled ``Industry'' and contains a
list of 13 major Arizona industries, such as agriculture, mining,
and real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Under each entry is a handwritten list of lobbyists who
represent those industries in contacting state lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The next three columns are headed by the candidates' names. Two
lobbyists' names were written in the corresponding boxes in the
form, which was not completed in the version obtained by ``The
Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was attended by a number of high-profile lobbyists,
including John Mangum, Wendy Briggs, Jim Klinker, Connie
Wilhelm-Garcia, Chuck Coughlin, Sidney Hoff Hay and Mike Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Burns, who made the pitch to lobbyists for their support at the
meeting, said nothing out of the ordinary occurred. The point was
not to get lobbyists involved in campaigns, but to reach the groups
they represent.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was an opportunity to get the word out about the GOP
candidates in those races, to let people know about their
philosophies and ideals, and find people willing to help with the
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The idea was to provide industry officials with the information
so they can match their own beliefs with candidates.
</P>
<P>
   It's ``absolutely appropriate,'' Burns said, to ``suggest to a
lobbyist that they inform the people they represent who the
candidates are.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said the purpose of the memo was to provide candidates a
``funnel,'' that is, a way to tap information and resources at the
beginning of a campaign without making ``thousands of calls.''
</P>
<P>
   The lobbyist-coordinators named for each campaign, as suggested
by the memo, would be a starting point for candidates.
</P>
<P>
   And she added that the list is so encompassing _ including
everything from firefighters to farmers _ that virtually all public
interests were represented.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would actually be extremely difficult to find groups who
were left out,'' Burns said. ``Those groups represent the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you campaign, people choose who they're going to give
their funding for the campaign that is closest to their
philosophies. I make no apologies. There's absolutely nothing wrong
with that. That's exactly what people should be doing. They need to
be as informed as they can about the candidates, and the only way a
candidate can get their message out is typically by things that
cost money.''
</P>
<P>
   But according to several people familiar with the discussions,
Burns' sales job included discouraging lobbyists from ``hedging
their bets'' in the three races by giving money to other parties
than the GOP, a common practice.
</P>
<P>
   The message to lobbyists was that donations to Democrats would
be remembered in next year's legislative session, according to one
lobbyist, who characterized the meeting as receiving ``marching
orders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a subtle message, but it wasn't so subtle,'' said
another source, who attended one of the discussions. ``It was along
the lines of, `We need you guys to stand up for Republican
candidates.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Stan Furman, Darden Hamilton's Democratic opponent in District
16, said several lobbyists have told him that prominent Republicans
have warned them that if they support Furman, ``They can forget
about their bills being heard next year.''
</P>
<P>
   According to another source familiar with the discussions, Burns
was paraphrased as saying, ``We've been very pro-business,'' and to
keep it that way, ``we need your help.''
</P>
<P>
   The source added, ``What she's doing is exactly what a
Democratic or Republican leader should be doing. . . . She's
putting together an effort to helping candidates out.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Burke, executive director of Arizona Common Cause, said
he doubted the veracity of the claim that lobbyists were warned
against giving to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't sound like Brenda Burns,'' he said, adding that she
has a ``good government'' reputation.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Burns said she doesn't remember encouraging lobbyists
to avoid giving to Democrats. But she acknowledges the business
angle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a pro-business Legislature. The message is, if you want
this philosophy to prevail, support the candidates who hold those
philosophical values,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Burns added that she didn't put the July meeting together. Party
officials arranged it, she said. But state GOP chairman Mike Hellon
said the party didn't sponsor the event, although he said retaining
the three Senate seats is a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not at that meeting. I know what you're talking about,''
Hellon said. ``That was not something that we put together. That
was done by the people themselves. I think the intent was to sort
of go around the table of interested parties and say, `These are
races that are crucial. Who's interested in helping whom?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Hellon, like Burns, isn't worried about the perception that the
GOP's campaign efforts are too closely tied to lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   There are so many interests involved, Hellon said, ``they
basically neutralize each other.'' Everyone is at the table. As
long as there is full disclosure about who is supporting whom, he
added, it's fine.
</P>
<P>
   And that's one of the reasons for the meeting, he said. It gave
competing interests a chance to sort out which candidates to back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to control it through the party. We're
saying, `Here are our guys, for those of you interested in the
election _ you know, get involved,'' Hellon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as everyone participates, then I don't think you have
inordinate influence on the part of one select interest group or
another. As long as everybody is involved, then they balance each
other out.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the three Republican candidates, Hamilton and Larry
Nelson, said they were aware of party efforts to help them. Gary
Richardson said he was getting a lot of assistance, but he wasn't
aware of any specific aid.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton said Burns was being extremely helpful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there's an effort out there,'' he said. ``As far as her
strategy and how she picked people to pull the campaign and the
lobbying effort together, I'm not clued into that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when I meet with (lobbyists), it's clear they've talked
with her. The rails have obviously been greased by the time I get
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, of Yuma, said Burns had been very supportive, writing
letters of endorsement to lobbyists and business leaders. But he
said he's not heard of any heavy-handed ``thou shalt support''
approach.
</P>
<P>
   But Nelson's District 5 opponent, former House member Herb
Guenther, says he's convinced that some lobbyists are being
persuaded to avoid his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have been a little timid to offer financial
support and that might be one of the reasons,'' Guenther said of
the GOP effort. ``These are people who have historically
contributed to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Tempe Mayor Harry Mitchell, Richardson's opponent in
District 27, said he had been warned by a lobbyist that Burns had
``laid down the law'' about contributing to the three Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   That angers Sen. Chris Cummiskey, D-central Phoenix, who calls
the effort by Burns and others a blatant attempt to use the
influence of special interests to win the election.
</P>
<P>
   The result, Cummiskey says, is a Legislature in which lawmakers
are beholden to groups that raise money for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a snapshot of what's going on in these campaigns. It's
a litany of lobbyists that are tapped to maintain the status quo,''
Cummiskey said. ``In this case, it sounds like just about every
primary interest that does business at the Capitol.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns responded that Democrats would do the same thing if they
had a majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect they're doing all that they can in the minority,''
she said. ``I know they are. You would expect them to.''
</P>
<P>
   She added a shot at the national Democratic party, which has
been beset by a fund-raising scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the way, we're not going to Red China,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Burke says both parties live off lobbyists and special interest
money. According to Arizona Common Cause, 80 percent of state
campaign donations comes from lobbyists and their spouses.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the amazing truth of Arizona politics. It's funded by
lobbyists. They own the process,'' Burke said. ``The party with the
votes has the most to sell.'' &QL; 
Chris Moeser can be reached at 444-8069 or at
chris.moeser(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
