<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TENN-PILOT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN-AGER DISCOVERS SAMPRAS IS NO AGASSI  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ Pete Sampras has no fear of prodigies. He can
almost remember how it felt to be one a decade ago when he first
played Ivan Lendl, and he can definitely remember what happened to
him the first time Lendl glared in his direction from across the
net on a blood-red Italian clay court. The teen-age Sampras didn't
cry, but he did cringe. And lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was completely overwhelmed with his power and how tough he
was,'' said Sampras, who was impressed enough to sign on briefly to
do some hard time training with Lendl, then No. 1, at his
Connecticut estate. ``You're completely in awe of him,'' Sampras
remembered.
</P>
<P>
   These days it's Sampras who, despite taking what he intends to
be a temporary dip to No. 2 in the rankings, expects to be the
intimidator whenever he faces teen-age hotshots like Lleyton
Hewitt, whom he spanked, 6-1, 7-6 (7-4), Wednesday in the second
round of the Pilot Pen International.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was first winning the Open in '90, he was 9,'' Sampras
said of the 17-year-old Hewitt. ``He didn't seem to be that
intimidated by me, but I really didn't feel like losing today.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, who hasn't captured a title since winning his 11th
career Grand Slam at Wimbledon, hopes to regain his No. 1 ranking
from Chile's Marcelo Rios by winning the title here.
</P>
<P>
   According to the 151st-ranked Hewitt, the pleasant prior
experience of dethroning Andre Agassi in January at the Australian
Hardcourts in his hometown of Adelaide, had sent him into
Wednesday's match against Sampras with some semblance of optimism.
After all, Hewitt's semifinal upset of Agassi not only came against
the player he considers his idol but also made Hewitt the ATP
Tour's third-youngest title winner ever.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, it didn't take Sampras long to put a crimp in the
youngster's confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good counterpuncher,'' Sampras said of Hewitt, whose
resume since his breakthrough at Adelaide has contained a string of
first- and second-round losses. ``In today's game, you need some
sort of weapon, something that stands out, and I'm not sure he has
that, but he's still young,'' Sampras added.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt tends to keep to the baseline and hasn't yet beefed up
his serving capacity to compete with ace artists like the one he
faced Wednesday. So, once Sampras, who hadn't played in New Haven
since getting off on the wrong foot with a first-round loss to
Michael Chang in 1989, sent up his radar and got his bearings in
the windy stadium, where the surface and balls are a dead ringer
for what's soon to come when the U.S. Open starts Aug. 31, Hewitt
was scrambling to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a set and a break down before I knew it,'' said Hewitt,
who broke Sampras in the opening game of the match but was breaking
racquets by midway through the opening set. ``I didn't even hold
serve in the first set.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Hewitt, Sampras' well-rounded game bothered him far
more than Agassi's had. More than once, Hewitt was relegated to
applauding Sampras' volleys instead of returning them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got such an all-court game, such a bigger serve,'' said
Hewitt, whose next challenge is qualifying for the Open after
accepting a wild card here. ``You can see how he wins Wimbledon
year after year.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras then addressed his next challenge _ winning the Open and
equaling Roy Emerson's career record of 12 Grand Slam crowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not treating this Open any differently than any other
one,'' Sampras said. ``The 12 is just a number, and I'm pretty
patient.''
</P>
<P>
   More immediate is his attempt to win his first-ever title in New
Haven. Still smarting from Sunday's final-round loss to the
defending U.S. Open champion, Patrick Rafter, in Cincinnati,
Sampras admitted ``it's pretty obvious'' he is looking for a
rematch with Rafter here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember my losses much more than my wins,'' said Sampras,
who next faces Leander Paes of India. ``I don't like losing
matches. I don't like losing, period.''.
</P>
<P>
   MATCH POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Several other highly seeded players reached the third round:
third-seeded PETR KORDA handled ANDREI MEDVEDEV, 6-3, 2-6, 6-1;
sixth-seeded TIM HENMAN eliminated VINCENZO SANTOPADRE, 6-2, 6-3;
eighth-seeded GORAN IVANISEVIC defeated GEOFF GRANT, 6-3, 3-6, 6-3,
and 11th-seeded GUSTAVO KUERTEN downed ALEX O'BRIEN, 6-3, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
