<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU STARTER SEES INJURY END CAREER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ When the sun rose over Amon Carter Stadium
yesterday, Eric Anderson was there ... waiting to say goodbye to
his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just sat there in the stadium, in the dark, waiting for the
sun,'' said Anderson, a TCU defensive back and former star at L.D.
Bell High School. ``Somehow, I knew I would never walk on that
field again.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's fears were confirmed late yesterday when team
physician Jack McCallum told Anderson his football career was over.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, projected as the team's starting strong safety, was
injured during Tuesday morning's workout when he landed on his neck
after leaping high in the air to block a pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost a fine football player and a great person,'' coach
Dennis Franchione said, ``but the good thing is, it could have been
a lot worse. They'll operate on him Friday, and except for not
playing football, he's going to be just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU trainer Ross Bailey said Anderson ruptured disks between the
sixth and seventh cervical vertebrae, and ``a micro fracture of the
facets at C7. Those are the little feet that the vertebrae sit on.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he goes in Friday, they'll fuse the vertebrae and he'll
recover, and should do just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a serious neck injury. When he came down, he basically
just T-boned the ground. But luckily he's going to be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, a District 5-5A defender of the year at Bell and
Junior College All-American at Blinn College, was returning to his
natural position this year after playing linebacker for the Horned
Frogs last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was rushing the passer in a drill,'' he said of the play on
which he was injured, ``and I leaped really high in the air. They
tell you to never leave your feet, but it's just an instinct.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was up really, really high, and I think one of the backs hit
me on a block. I kind of rotated in the air and came down on the
back of my neck. I think I would have been OK if I hadn't gone up
so high.''
</P>
<P>
   When he came down, Anderson faced a chilling prospect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the ground, and I suddenly realized my arm was numb.
I couldn't feel anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just lay there on the ground and said, `Oh, my God' ...
</P>
<P>
   ``But after a few minutes, it went away, and I felt OK. Later in
the day, I was joking about it with the guys in the film room, and
I thought it was no big deal. It was weird.''
</P>
<P>
   But after undergoing X-rays, a magnetic resonance imaging exam
and a CT scan, Anderson began to have doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I went to the stadium in the dark,'' he said, ``and I just
sat there and thought about life.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially, a new life.
</P>
<P>
   On July 17, Anderson's girlfriend, TCU track star Shareen
Sharrieff, had a son, Eric Jr. And as the sun rose, he thought of
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be married, and we have a baby, and a future
life,'' he said. ``It's a funny thing, you think about all these
things like playing pro ball and all, and you kind of lose
perspective. Those of us who play this game, sometimes we look at
things kind of weird, like we lose track of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my life, I have loved football. But it's just a game ...''
</P>
<P>
   So Anderson went to Dr. McCallum, who gave him the test results.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was showing me all this stuff,'' Anderson says, ``and
explaining what had happened to me, and what needed to be done. He
was talking about similar injuries. He mentioned Christopher
Reeve,'' the actor who was paralyzed in an equestrian accident in
May 1995.
</P>
<P>
   McCallum ``told me I should give up football,'' Anderson said.
``When he told me that, I just smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it surprised him, but I wasn't smiling because my
career was over. I was smiling because I still have a normal life.
I was smiling because I won't be in a wheelchair, and someday I can
play baseball with my son and toss the football to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Anderson is a psychology major, he is determined to be
a coach _ a high school coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I want to do,'' he said, ``because in high school,
you can mold young boys, and turn them into men. You can instill in
them the determination to go to college, and be educated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went the hard route, through junior college. But I will
guarantee, you give me four years with you in high school, and I
will get you to college. It has been such a great experience for
me, and I have been blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson may get the opportunity to coach sooner than he
figured.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to coach,'' Franchione said, ``and I told him that
when he is recovered he can join us as a student assistant.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, a senior with 4.5-second speed in the 40-yard dash who
had seven interceptions and 15 sacks in two years at Blinn, was
outstanding for the Frogs in an unnatural position last year, and
counted on heavily in this year's rebuilding effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I can walk away from this game, although I love it,'' he
said. ``But I'm not gone. I'm still on this team, and they're going
to have my spirit with them on every play this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
