<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2338 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLOBE-BARNICLE-BOS &LR;      08-19 1607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBE-BARNICLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARNICLE RESIGNS AFTER NEW QUESTIONS ON REPORTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Ending a tumultuous two-week period during which he was
asked to resign from The Boston Globe and then successfully battled
to retain his job, Metro columnist Mike Barnicle resigned from the
newspaper Wednesday after new questions arose over his credibility.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-year columnist, already serving a two-month suspension
for writing a column that used jokes by comedian George Carlin,
agreed to quit after being unable to verify the facts contained in
an Oct. 8, 1995, column about two children being treated for cancer
at Children's Hospital, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks to the Globe newsroom Wednesday afternoon, editor
Matthew V. Storin said that ``in light of his failure to follow the
most basic reporting requirements as well as the duplicitous way in
which the story was written, it is clear that Mike Barnicle can no
longer write for The Boston Globe ... I think this has been a
horrendous period, but now we can at least put it behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached last night, Barnicle, 54, said, ``I'm sorry Matt thinks
I'm duplicitous. I believe that story to be true. I was told it by
a nurse. I've been trying all day to track down two people involved
in that column.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that he agreed to resign because ``of the weight of
this thing. ... It was too much, it was absurd. ... The feeding
frenzy that has disrupted this paper. Matt Storin doesn't deserve
it, the Globe doesn't deserve it, and I don't deserve it.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1995 column told a detailed and poignant story of two
families _ one black and poor, one white and affluent _ that bonded
because they both had young sons suffering from cancer. After the
poor child died, the wealthy family sent a $10,000 check to his
family, which was struggling for economic survival.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper began probing the latest charge against Barnicle
Tuesday when Storin received a letter from Kenneth Tomlinson, a
former editor-in-chief of Reader's Digest who was writing a story
on his experiences with Barnicle for The Weekly Standard magazine.
Tomlinson said that in 1995 he had wanted to reprint the Barnicle
cancer column as the lead article in the digest's January 1996
issue. But, Tomlinson said, ``Barnicle declined to help me''
confirm the facts, and after ``exhaustive efforts'' to verify the
story, ``we concluded the column was fabricated.'' The magazine did
not tell the Globe of its suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Tuesday morning, assistant managing editor Walter
Robinson, who last week was appointed Barnicle's supervising
editor, attempted unsuccessfully to verify key facts of the column
through conversations with Barnicle, and with officials at
Children's Hospital and the Massachusetts Department of Public
Health.
</P>
<P>
   According to Robinson's account of his conversations with the
columnist, Barnicle said he heard the account from a nurse who
worked at the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute and who had heard the
story from the affluent family with the surviving child. But
Barnicle was unable, said Robinson, to provide the name of the
nurse or further corroborating details.
</P>
<P>
   When Robinson told Barnicle that he was troubled by his reliance
on a third-hand source for the graphic details in the column,
Robinson said the columnist told him, ``That's the way I do it.''
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday afternoon the Globe decided to ask for Barnicle's
resignation and Barnicle agreed to quit during a phone conversation
with Globe chairman William O. Taylor. In addressing the staff
Wednesday, Storin said Barnicle ``could offer no account of
attempting to check out details of the story by calling Children's
Hospital or either set of parents. In fact, he said he did not know
the parents' names. Yet he quoted the black parents in the story
and quoted from the letter the white parents had purportedly sent
with the check.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The story may well prove to be true or essentially true,''
Storin added Wednesday. ``But the reporting procedures violated any
basic journalistic standard.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Globe was investigating Barnicle's 1995 column, The
Boston Phoenix Wednesday released a story it was preparing for
print containing what it called ``the most damning evidence of all
that Barnicle has, indeed, plagiarized.'' The column in question
was a Jan. 20, 1986, piece in which Barnicle attributed a series of
anecdotes about infamous Louisiana politician Earl Long to his
cousin, Gillis Long.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix story reported that the column had ``lifted exact
quotes, complete with idiosyncratic spellings,'' from author A.J.
Liebling's 1961 biography of Long. The Phoenix piece, by media
critic Dan Kennedy, pointed out that Gillis Long died a year before
the column appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Storin Wednesday said that ``we've been aware of the Phoenix
story since this morning,'' adding that the column singled out by
the weekly ``may have been just as bad (as the October 1995
column), but it wasn't a factor because we were already down the
track on this one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Undoubtedly, a number of factors went into the Globe decision
to sever their relationship with Mike Barnicle,'' said Phoenix
editor Peter Kadzis, pointing out that his paper had faxed the
Globe a copy of its story Wednesday morning and suggesting it
played a role in Barnicle's demise. ``Let the readers draw their
own conclusion,'' Kadzis said. ``This isn't about trophies. It's
about getting at the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday marked the second time in two weeks that the Globe
asked for Barnicle's resignation. The prolonged episode began when
an Aug. 2 Barnicle column was found to contain eight jokes similar
to those in comedian Carlin's 1997 book ``BrainDroppings,'' a
resemblance first noted in a Boston Herald story.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 5 Storin, accepting Barnicle's explanation that he had
not read the book and got the jokes from friends, initially
suspended him for a month without pay. But later that day, WCVB-TV
(Channel 5) ran a clip of Barnicle endorsing the book on a June 22
edition of its ``Chronicle'' show, on which Barnicle appears. At
that point, Storin, concluding that the columnist had
``misrepresented himself either to his television audience or to
his editors,'' first asked for Barnicle's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle, saying he had not read the book and did not recall
endorsing it on television, declined to resign. He took to the
national and local media circuit to plead his case, prompting
thousands of calls and messages to flood the Globe seeking his
reinstatement. Staples chairman Thomas G. Stemberg wrote a letter
implying he might withdraw advertising were Barnicle not brought
back on board.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 11, following three meetings between Barnicle and top
Globe officials, Storin, who had been out of the country when the
allegations arose, acknowledged acting too ``hastily,'' rescinded
the resignation request, and suspended Barnicle for two months
without pay. That decision led to two days of contentious meetings
inside the Globe and protests outside the paper.
</P>
<P>
   When the two-month suspension was announced at a staff meeting,
Barnicle apologized for his ``sloppiness,'' but faced a barrage of
tough questions, as did Storin. One huge factor hanging over the
episode was the requested resignation June 18 of Patricia Smith, a
Metro columnist who is black. She quit after acknowledging she
fabricated characters and quotes in several 1998 columns.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 12, more than 50 Globe employees signed a petition
presented to Storin and to publisher Benjamin B. Taylor, stating
that Barnicle's ``reprieve gives the appearance of a double
standard.'' The paper also faced criticism from the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, the National
Association of Black Journalists, the Urban League of Eastern
Massachusetts, the Rev. Eugene F. Rivers III, and from a tough
editorial written by New York Times editorial page editor Howell
Raines. The Times owns the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as Wednesday afternoon, a group of black activists
met with Globe editors to express their concerns alleging unequal
treatment of Smith and Barnicle. Sadiki Kambon, president of the
Black Community Information Center, called the Globe a ``racist
publication'' and asked people of color to boycott it.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining why he had given Barnicle another chance last
week, Storin said Wednesday that conversations with the columnist
revealed that ``the origin of the (Carlin) joke material was
muddy'' and that Barnicle's bosses became convinced ``we could
restore the trust between the editors and him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite all the furor of last week, I feel good in the sense
that I made the right call last week and I made the right call
today,'' Storin said.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Globe readers last Sunday, Storin discussed the
decision to retain Barnicle, but noted that he is ``under perhaps
the greatest scrutiny a newspaper writer has ever had to endure. He
knows he is on a high wire without a net. Room for legitimate
errors? Yes. Room for an ethical lapse? No.''
</P>
<P>
   Storin also alluded to just how traumatic the past few weeks had
been for the Globe, facing internal and external questions about
its standards, judgment, and credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't feel good yet,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, when announcing Barnicle's resignation to a newsroom
full of anxious and drawn faces, Storin said it was time to move
forward after a nightmarish few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, ``We have everyone on the same ethical page.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the assemblage burst into applause.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 2218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
