<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2347 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLOBE-COLUMNIST-1STLD     08-19 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBE-COLUMNIST-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1,065&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACED WITH MORE QUESTIONS, BARNICLE RESIGNS FROM BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Recasts throughout with new material, quotes from newsroom.) 
(Also see GLOBE-BARNICLE, The Boston Globe's article on the
resignation, and GLOBE-COLUMN, a reprint of the 1995 Barnicle
column that prompted the latest inquiry into Barnicle's reporting.
For questions about Boston Globe stories, call Frank Perrotta at
the Globe, 617-929-2597.) 
(nk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eight days after salvaging his career at The Boston Globe,
columnist Mike Barnicle resigned Wednesday, at the newspaper's
request, when editors could find no evidence that two young cancer
victims he described in a 1995 column had ever existed.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle told his editors on Tuesday that he had been given the
story by a nurse whose name he could not recall. He also said he
had never tried to speak with the boys' families.
</P>
<P>
   Globe Editor Matthew Storin said in a statement Wednesday: ``In
light of his failure to follow the most basic reporting
requirements as well as the duplicitous way in which the story was
written, it is clear that Mike Barnicle can no longer write for The
Boston Globe.''
</P>
<P>
   The abrupt end of Barnicle's quarter-century career at the
Globe, owned by The New York Times Co., was another act in a
wrenching summer at the newspaper, which in a matter of only weeks
has lost two of its most popular metropolitan columnists, Patricia
Smith, and now Barnicle.
</P>
<P>
   Storin had been alerted to the Barnicle column at issue on
Monday by Kenneth Tomlinson, a retired editor of Reader's Digest.
Tomlinson, whose own son had survived a spinal tumor, was moved
when he read the Oct. 8, 1995, column and sought to reprint it
around that time.
</P>
<P>
   But fact-checkers from Reader's Digest, who contacted various
cancer societies and Children's Hospital, where by Barnicle's
account the two boys had been patients, and could find no evidence
of the boys' existence. Eventually, Tomlinson said Wednesday, he
decided the column had been fabricated.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement that was by turns gracious and resentful,
Barnicle said Wednesday that he felt consumed by a ``media feeding
frenzy,'' with his work of 25 years _ some 4,000 columns _ under
scrutiny. ``Just in the last 24 hours, I was asked to explain
circumstances and columns written in 1973, 1981, 1986 and 1995 and
was given 24 hours _ a single day's news cycle _ to rebut all the
allegations at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, this is not what I want to do with my life. And it is
hurting the paper I love. This burden has made it impossible for
Matt Storin and the editors of the Globe to publish the terrific
product they put on the street each day.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked in a telephone interview how he had come to write the
column on the young cancer victims, Barnicle said that a nurse had
told the story to a telephone operator at the Globe who then told
it to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believed the story to be true,'' he said, ``and I wrote it
after talking to the nurse.''
</P>
<P>
   The telephone operator, Rose Berry Devine, an old friend of the
columnist's, Wednesday agreed with Barnicle's account, saying that
she remembered that a call had come in from a nurse's aide who was
suffering from AIDS and has since died.
</P>
<P>
   The column told of a friendship that had developed between the
two boys _ one black, one white _ while they were hospitalized
together. It reported details like the downsizing that had cost the
black youngster's father his job at a high-technology company, and
began with a passage in which that child's mother received a
$10,000 check from the white family:
</P>
<P>
   ``She opened the letter as she strolled up the driveway from the
mailbox. As she finished the first paragraph, she stopped in her
tracks, unable to focus because of the tears in her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a few seconds, she lifted her head toward the perfect
sky and, for a brief, wonderful moment, she could hear her son
singing his favorite song.''
</P>
<P>
   The column went on to quote her husband as saying, ``There
really is a God.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the questions raised by Tomlinson _ who said he was
now writing an article about the cancer-victim column for The
Weekly Standard, a Washington magazine _ The Boston Phoenix, the
city's alternative weekly, had prepared an article showing strong
similarities between the writer A.J. Liebling's biography of former
Louisiana Gov. Earl Long and a 1986 column by Barnicle.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Wednesday why he had not alerted the Globe to his
suspicions back in late 1995, Tomlinson said it was because, in
part, he had assigned one of his own reporters to do a piece on how
a column can be fabricated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't get a lot of interest going,'' he said. ``It was
one of those good ideas that fell by the wayside.''
</P>
<P>
   When he read about the forced resignation of another Globe
columnist, Ms. Smith, in June, and the paper's decision to review
some of Barnicle's past work, Tomlinson said, ``I thought, `Any
examination by the Globe will turn this up.'' But that examination
of Barnicle's work since January 1996 turned up no problematic
columns, according to Globe editors.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Tomlinson said, two weeks ago, when The Boston Herald
disclosed the similarities between Barnicle's Aug. 2 column and
jokes in a 1997 book by comedian George Carlin, he said he thought
Barnicle's career would be over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a foregone conclusion he was going down and
his sins had caught up to him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe the massive pressure brought to bear on the
Globe to keep him,'' Tomlinson added, referring to the support of
popular radio talk-show host Don Imus, prominent journalists, a
major Globe advertiser and hundreds of Globe readers who deluged
the newspaper switchboard with protest calls.
</P>
<P>
   Only after Storin had reversed his initial decision to ask for
Barnicle's resignation for misleading the Globe about the Carlin
situation did Tomlinson send a fax to Storin questioning the
cancer-victim column.
</P>
<P>
   In the Globe's newsroom, where there has been a crescendo of
complaints in recent days about Barnicle's standards, the mood
lightened perceptibly Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think by and large the staff feels better than they've felt
in two months,'' Storin said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   When he read his statement to the staff, the final words _ ``I'm
glad we can now move forward with everyone operating from the same
ethical page'' _ provoked a smattering of applause and some nervous
laughter from a relieved staff, said two people present.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're all glad it's all over, but nobody is dancing on
his grave,'' said Anne Kornblut, a metropolitan reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he would do now, Barnicle, who has seven children
ranging in age from 5 to 34, said Wednesday: ``I don't know.
Tomorrow is my precious boy's 14th birthday. My job is to make sure
that he knows that everything will be OK.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While the Globe's newsroom was recovering from the Barnicle
episode, the newsroom of The Wall Street Journal was getting word
that James S. Hirsch, who has covered the Boston area for the
Journal, had been fired. Hirsch wrote last week, erroneously, that
The New York Times Co. had declined to comment on Storin's decision
last week to keep Barnicle on staff.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal published a correction on Tuesday noting that The
Times Co. had not been asked for comment. Richard Tofel, a
spokesman for Dow Jones, The Journal's parent company, said that
the reporter ``knew that that sentence in the story was not true.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can confirm that he doesn't work for us,'' Tofel said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
