<HEADLINE>
LIVENT SAYS ACCOUNTING WOES MAY CUT NET WORTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN and GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The new managers at Livent Inc., the producer of
Broadway shows, said Wednesday that the company's accounting woes
could significantly reduce its already slender net worth.
</P>
<P>
   But after more than a week of speculation and questions, the
company's five-page statement Wednesday gave few new details to
help unravel the mystery surrounding the suspension of the
company's founders, Garth Drabinsky and Myron Gottlieb, from their
executive positions last week.
</P>
<P>
   The new managers, headed by Michael Ovitz, the former Hollywood
power broker, said they still could not estimate the value of the
accounting irregularities that they said they unearthed last week.
Better financial estimates of those problems, they said, may not be
available until late October, when an internal investigation is
completed.
</P>
<P>
   But in the statement, the new managers tried to reassure
investors and theatergoers, saying the financial problems would not
affect the company's current shows or the productions planned for
the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have spoken with all of our partners in our major creative
and business projects,'' said Roy Furman, the company's new chief
executive, ``and we don't expect any of these projects to be
delayed by the recently discovered irregularities.''
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky and Gottlieb have denied any wrongdoing. But they say
that they cannot respond further since the company has not given
them details of the allegations. Drabinsky ``believes that it is
inappropriate to respond to rumors and speculations,'' his
spokesman said Wednesday. ``As the facts emerge, he will be in a
better position to respond.''
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's statement, management said that the company was
now technically in default of its bond agreements. But executives
said that they believed those problems could be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   They said that the accounting problems are likely to reduce
significantly the company's shareholders' equity of $46 million.
And, while executives earlier had said that the problems dated back
to the beginning of 1996, they said Wednesday that earlier years
may also be affected.
</P>
<P>
   The statement said that the irregularities relate to both the
understatement of expenses and the overstatement of revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Management said the company may also have to take further
write-downs _ amounts that would come directly off the company's
bottom line _ that do not stem from the irregularities discovered
last week. Earlier this spring, the new management had assured
investors when it announced the most recent $20 million write-down
that there would be no more surprises.
</P>
<P>
   The assets being written down relate mostly to musicals that
have closed. As regular accounting practice, the company does not
immediately expense a show's costs like advertising, stage sets and
costumes. Instead, it capitalizes those costs and gradually
amortizes them over the show's run, which the company estimates
will be five years.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have long criticized the company for that
practice, saying that many of the capitalized expenses should have
long ago reduced the company's bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   In the statement, the company was eager to promote its
successful productions, and the release painted an optimistic
picture of its long-term future. Furman, who left his Wall Street
investment banking firm to become Livent's chief executive, said:
``We are even more optimistic than when we first arrived in June
about the strength of our current slate of shows, our development
projects and our ability to forge new relationships.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Among other potential moneymakers, the company cited a North
American touring company of ``Ragtime,'' now booked into the year
2000. However, there are questions about that tour. The Vancouver
production of ``Ragtime'' was closed prematurely at the end of
July, a decision that a company spokeswoman said was made ``for
good financial reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   And according to the latest figures supplied to Variety, the
entertainment trade paper, ``Ragtime,'' which was close to sold out
in New York, was playing to considerably less than full houses in
both Washington and Winnipeg last week.
</P>
<P>
   And though the company had high hopes for the success of its
``Showboat'' abroad, it has recently said that the London
production, which opened on April 28, would close in late
September. An Australian production of ``Showboat'' is also closing
early.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fosse: A Celebration in Song and Dance'' is currently playing
in Toronto, but the theater, which Variety reported took in
$344,831 last week, has not sold out despite good reviews.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokesman for Livent claimed that he did not know
where Variety got the numbers. But Variety numbers are typically
supplied by personnel connected with the show. Livent owns both the
theatres and the production.
</P>
<P>
   The company also took pains to assure Wall Street that a number
of the projects in development would go forward. Those include
``The Sweet Smell of Success,'' with director Nick Hynter, author
John Guare and composer Marvin Hamlisch, as well as a Canadian tour
of ``Phantom of The Opera,'' though the show is an aging one that
has toured North America repeatedly with multiple companies since
it opened in 1988.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
