A2364 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     08-19 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tyson merits a shot &QL; 
at more humiliation
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SO now Mike Tyson is returning to Nevada to apply for the
reinstatement of his boxing license because, after all, it is the
proper place, the right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   And the cow jumped over the moon.
</P>
<P>
   The more likely truth is that the sudden change of venue had
more to do with New Jersey Gov. Christine Whitman's impersonation
of Tyson, chewing on the ear of state boxing chairman Larry Hazzard
for his willingness to be used as a facilitator to get the sport's
most famous carnivore back into the ring as soon as possible,
preferably at one of Atlantic City's hungry casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's newest tapeworm/adviser, Shelly Finkel, had originally
gone to New Jersey for approval because word had it that the
powers-that-be in Nevada _ site of the June 1997 Evander Holyfield
buffet _ were prepared to rebuff his man, mainly on the grounds it
would be bad for the image of Las Vegas, which on the meter of
cheap and tawdry affairs these days falls just short of the White
House and the Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   One suspects political correctness being behind Gov. Whitman's
sudden interest and intervention into the fight game, a sleazy
business that has pumped millions of tax dollars into her state's
coffers and never been given the bum's rush, though numerous bums
have certainly been rushed into the ring. Or maybe it was Tyson's
outburst of obscenities during a July 29 licensing hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Nevada unlikely to say no
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Nevada is now where the legal battle will be fought,
along with the comeback bouts of Tyson. And by the way, shouldn't
his first fight be against Liz Taylor _ Man-eater vs. Man-eater?
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt the Nevada commission will eventually give
Tyson permission to fight. After all, there are thousands of hotel
rooms to fill out in the desert, and nothing does that like the
scent of blood in the air, which seems a certainty as long as Tyson
continues to treat his rivals as hors d'oeuvres.
</P>
<P>
   The debate will then rapidly heat to a boil as the cry will come
that Tyson should never be allowed back in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Why? To keep the fine, gentlemanly activity of boxing pure?
</P>
<P>
   This is a sport where, at the heavyweight level, the object is
to beat the other man senseless. It is also a bottom-feeding
business, where the movers and shakers would drown kittens on
pay-per-view television if they thought there was a buck in it.
Thus, there is a place for the Don Kings and the Tysons of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   King is simply the latest in a long line of con artists who have
manipulated the sweet science to their own larcenous ends. There
once was a manager named Jack Hurley. When a low-life acquaintance
bragged that he had just rolled a drunk for $400, Hurley rolled his
eyes in scorn. ``You're an amateur,'' he chastised. ``You should go
right back now and put $200 back in his pockets. When he wakes up,
he'll just think he blew the $200. I mean, he'll think, `Why would
somebody rob me and leave $200?'''
</P>
<P>
   That is the history of boxing. So, too, are names like Sonny
Liston and Leon Spinks, predecessors to Tyson, stepping out of a
shadowy world straight off the streets and ascending to the rank of
heavyweight champion, where they provided amusement for the
celebrity and monied set until they took too many beatings and
their brains were scrambled.
</P>
<P>
   Terror of old is history
</P>
<P>
   To ban Tyson now would be like handing out punishment in prisons
for bad behavior. Redundant.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is a convicted rapist, unrepentant. He is antisocial and
still out of control, as evidenced by the explosion during the New
Jersey hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Why keep Tyson out of the ring now, when assaulting Desiree
Washington and beating his ex-wife, Robin Givens (``the best punch
I ever threw,'' he once said), were not enough to turn off the
public? When they start charging $39.95 for his comeback fight on
pay-per-view, the phone lines will ring.
</P>
<P>
   There are many who still want _ and expect _ to see the young
monster who worked his way up the heavyweight ranks by annihilating
opponents in the space of 90 seconds. That boxer hasn't fought
since 1988 against Michael Spinks. That man no longer exists.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is 32 now. Older, not wiser or better. He spent two years
in jail. He has fought just six times in the past seven years, 22
rounds total. A shell of his former self, having rejected the
managers and handlers who helped make him invincible, he is
unchanged, still angry at the world and wanting one more chance.
</P>
<P>
   So why not give it to him? In a boxing ring with Holyfield.
After all, isn't a good beating one of the few things a bully can
understand?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
