<HEADLINE>
INTERNET USERS VIEW HEART BYPASS SURGERY OF TEXAS WOMAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Includes update on condition of woman) 
 
By RUTH SoRELLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Upstaged by a Seattle surgeon in a bid to perform the
first open-heart surgery live on the Internet, Dr. Denton Cooley
declared the quadruple bypass he performed on a Houston-area woman
a success because of its educational value.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, we wouldn't let people see what we were doing
(in the operating room),'' Cooley said. ``Some people have a
burning curiosity to know what we do. It's astounding to me that
this is available to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The curious numbered in the millions, said Web Golinkin,
chairman of America's Health Network, which broadcast the operation
live on the Internet and cable television. A final tally of
``hits'' on the Internet has yet to be completed.
</P>
<P>
   The audio remained clear throughout the broadcast although there
were a few glitches in the video.
</P>
<P>
   Cooley and Golinkin announced last week that the surgery would
take place Wednesday at the Texas Heart Institute at St. Luke's
Episcopal Hospital in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough to stimulate Providence Seattle Medical Center
to move up a scheduled Internet surgery to Monday, said hospital
spokesman Serge Gregory.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we found out about Dr. Cooley's plans last week, we
decided to seize the opportunity,'' he said. ``We did one on Monday
as a test run.''
</P>
<P>
   That broadcast was not advertised and only hospital personnel
saw it, Gregory said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Robert Lazzara of the Seattle hospital performed two
coronary artery bypass procedures Tuesday, Gregory said. Because
the hospital made the public aware of this one, ``we think 7,500
people viewed the first (Tuesday) procedure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear that the Houston physicians were ready for
thousands, if not millions of viewers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cooley's assistant, Dr. J. Michael Duncan, began the procedure
on 48-year-old Rena Fluker of nearby Pasadena at 1:07 p.m., CDT.
After nearly an hour of preparatory work opening the chest and
removing the artery and vein to be used in the bypass procedure, he
gave way to Cooley. The two finished the operation in a little more
than three hours.
</P>
<P>
   A hospital spokeswoman said Wednesday that Fluker was ``doing
very well.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 570,000 coronary artery bypass operation are expected
to be performed in the United States each year.
</P>
<P>
   Fluker's husband, Jerry, said he hoped the broadcast would help
people better understand heart disease and the operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't look at it today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, he said, had the patient been someone other than his
wife of 32 years, he might have wanted to view the procedure. He
hopes the operation will give the couple many more years together.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Walter Larimore of America's Health Network narrated the
surgery and interviewed the surgeons as the operation proceeded.
</P>
<P>
   Larimore explained the activities of the surgeons as they
performed each task, but he also had to provide ``filler'' comments
much like that of sportscasters.
</P>
<P>
   He said Rena Fluker, the mother of three, was a diabetic,
somewhat overweight and had a family history of heart disease
before she was diagnosed with clogged coronary arteries.
</P>
<P>
   The first symptoms were shortness of breath during exertion, her
husband Jerry Fluker told Larimore during a broadcast interview.
Then she began to suffer a feeling of pressure in her chest. At
that point, she sought care at a local hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The surgery went smoothly until Cooley came to the left anterior
descending coronary artery, a major blood carrier to the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Cooley said the clogged artery was no bigger than a piece of
kite string. It took longer than he expected to remove some of the
material and prepare the blood vessel so that the mammary artery
could be used to bypass the clogged portion.
</P>
<P>
   Larimore said he hoped the operation would emphasize the
importance and value of heart disease prevention, as well as
informing people about the most common procedure to correct it.
</P>
<P>
   Cooley said he was not concerned that millions of people were
peeking over his shoulder. ``I was worried more about the patient's
welfare,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would like to see more such procedures as long as
they are done in a manner that is respectful of the patient's
privacy and dignity.
</P>
<P>
   The 77-year-old surgeon, who performed the nation's first
successful heart transplant in 1968, admitted he is not
particularly computer savvy and does not surf the Internet. ``But I
plan to become more knowledgeable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Seattle surgeon, Cooley grinned. ``I don't want to be
critical. It's part of human nature to want to be first.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
