<SLUG> BC-RETAIL-SALES-LADN </SLUG>
 
L.A. COUNTY RETAIL SALES FELL OFF LAST YEAR TO MIRROR '90s TREND 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Retail sales in Los Angeles County fell behind
those of richer neighbors and the state as a whole in 1997,
continuing a trend that has plagued the region in the 1990s and
signaling that consumers may still be feeling the aftermath of the
recession.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's well below the surrounding areas,'' said Tom Lieser,
executive director of the UCLA Anderson Business Forecasting
Project in Los Angeles. ``The county is losing out in terms of
regional growth in sales.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, retail sales in Los Angeles rose 3.7 percent to $55
billion, compared with a 7.8 percent increase in Orange County to
$21 billion and a 5.6 percent gain for Ventura County to $4.9
billion, according to preliminary figures from the California Board
of Equalization. For the state, retail sales -- which exclude
business-to-business sales and sales of construction materials --
rose 5.6 percent to $217 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recession was deeper in Los Angeles and the recovery was a
little slower,'' said Jeff Reynolds, statistics manager for the
state Board of Equalization, which collects taxable sales figures.
``Southern California as a whole has lagged the Bay Area in overall
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   An overdependence on the defense industry crippled Los Angeles
in the early 1990s, as the national economy shifted gears at the
end of the Cold War. The county has since struggled to diversify
and pull itself out of the slump.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the entertainment industry and international
trade have lifted the local economy, but these two sectors might be
slowing down. Hollywood isn't making as many movies, and the Asian
crisis has hurt trade with the Pacific Rim.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, homeowners had to contend with sliding real estate
values in much of this decade, further hurting consumer spending,
Lieser said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Los Angeles had to pull out of a deeper recession than did
other regions, its effect on consumer spending was more severe.
Therefore, it's not surprising that Los Angeles did not show the
strong rebound of other areas, economists said.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the weaker growth is a shift in spending.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kyser, chief economist of the Economic Development Corp. in
Los Angeles, believes there is some sales ``leakage'' to other
regions, with residents flocking to places such as the outlet
stores in neighboring Ventura County.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Camarillo Premium Outlets has seen more customers from
Los Angeles as it expanded its shopping center. So far this year,
customer traffic is up more than 50 percent from a year ago, said
Michelle Rothstein, vice president of marketing at parent company
Chelsea GCA Realty in Roseland, N.J. The mall did not track figures
in 1996 and could not supply a comparison for 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``A major part of our advertising is in Los Angeles,'' she said.
``We draw from a wider radius since people don't visit outlet
centers as often.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyser also believes the lower per-capita income in Los Angeles
County -- $25,402 in 1997, compared with those of Ventura and
Orange counties, at $30,264 and $27,197, respectively -- could have
depressed sales.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the recovering real estate market last year also
hurt consumer spending. Kyser said consumers who bought homes were
left without as much discretionary income to spend on other things.
</P>
<P>
   But Kyser and Lieser don't believe the local economy is
weakening. They cite the lower unemployment figure of 6.1 percent
in July and thousands of new jobs the county continues to add.
Retail sales figures are important, but by itself it's not the
definitive report card on the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one economic indicator among many,'' Lieser said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
