<SLUG> BC-MGM-KERKORIAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KERKORIAN TO RAISE STAKE IN MGM WITH $389 MILLION DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Kirk Kerkorian, capping weeks of speculation
about the future of the troubled Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer studio,
announced he will boost his stake to 89.6 percent in a $389 million
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Kerkorian, who has owned MGM for most of the last three decades,
will pay $24 a share for Seven Network's 24.6 percent stake,
representing a premium of 32 percent to Wednesday's closing stock
price. MGM shares, depressed by recent disclosures of a bleak
outlook, rose 19 percent by gaining $2.875 to $18.1875.
</P>
<P>
   Kerkorian and the Australian broadcaster bought the fabled
studio in 1996 for $1.3 billion. Seven, suffering from financial
problems, had been expected to bail out after refusing to
participate in an impending rights offering and said Wednesday its
funds could be better used in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street has been trying to decipher Kerkorian's motives
since Aug. 6, when he announced MGM was holding talks with
unidentified buyers, believed to be Burbank-based Walt Disney Co.
and News Corp. Arthur Rockwell, a Drake &AMP; Co. analyst and former
MGM executive, declared: ``This means MGM is back in business. It
shows Kirk believes in the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell said the buyout talks were held to demonstrate to Seven
head Kerry Stokes that there were no immediate buyers for MGM.
</P>
<P>
   MGM also said Wednesday it will double the value of the rights
offering, which allows shareholders to buy discounted stock, to
$500 million. Barry Hyman, analyst at Ehrenkrantz King Nussbaum,
said Wednesday's deal may be the first step toward a sale of the
entire studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``The confusing part is why he was willing to pay $24 a share
(to Seven Network),'' Hyman said. ``It may be a statement that
MGM's available at that price.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
