u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-ART-1ST     08-19 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS SEEK CLINTON DNA SAMPLE TO VERIFY SEXUAL ACTIVITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs lead graf for rewriting; shortens and moves down original 2nd
graf; removes material on Lewinsky reaction to speech; changes
throughout)  (See also: CLINTON-POLITICS, CLINTON-VINEYARD, CLINTON-HEARTLAND,
CLINTON-MCHALE, CLINTON-POLLS; graphic on Nielsen ratings is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By JAMES BENNET and DON VAN NATTA Jr.   c.1998 N.Y. Times News
Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Prosecutors have demanded a sample of President
Clinton's genetic material to establish forensic proof that his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky was sexual, a lawyer familiar
with the request said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton admitted to a federal grand jury Monday that he had
``inappropriate intimate physical contact'' with Ms. Lewinsky in
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The move by Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr strongly suggests
that the FBI crime lab has determined that a dress turned over to
prosecutors by Ms. Lewinsky contained DNA evidence of a sexual
encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's team had believed that the results of genetic testing
on the dress were moot after the president's admission in his
testimony, as well as by a brief speech he gave later, on Monday
night, calling the relationship ``not appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior presidential adviser said Clinton's lawyers would not
challenge Starr's request. White House press secretary Mike McCurry
said any sample could be obtained from tissue samples stored at
Bethesda Naval Hospital, where Clinton undergoes annual physicals.
</P>
<P>
   The request became public a day before Ms. Lewinsky, who was
said by friends t feel hurt by the president's terse public
description of their relationship, is scheduled to appear for a
second time before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's request suggested that he is determined to learn the
specific nature of the physical contact between Clinton and Ms.
Lewinsky, presumably in an effort to find inconsistencies between
Clinton's and Ms. Lewinsky's accounts and to establish whether he
committed perjury in his deposition in the Paula Jones case when he
denied having a sexual relationship with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his advisers believe that such an effort could work to
the president's political benefit as Congress weighs conducting
impeachment hearings. They say it could make prosecutors look
sex-obsessed, even as most Americans tell pollsters that they
already know more than they would like about lies, betrayal, and
sexual indiscretion at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   A careful vagueness about his encounters with Ms. Lewinsky is
central to the president's legal and political strategy, his
advisers say, since it may help deflect a possible perjury charge
while also walling off seamy details from an already queasy public.
Clinton was even more vague in his four-minute address Monday night
than in his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton refused to give prosecutors a detailed description of
his physical contact with Ms. Lewinsky, after reading a statement
admitting an inappropriate relationship at the beginning of his
four-hour testimony. Starr has been seeking to determine if Clinton
committed perjury in January, when he denied any sexual
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky in a deposition in the Jones sexual
misconduct lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony Monday, Clinton argued that the type of
relationship he had with Ms. Lewinsky did not fit the definition of
sex used by the Jones lawyers. Although he rebuffed prosecutors'
questions about his sexual contact with Ms. Lewinsky, he did answer
a series of questions about what types of sex he considered to be
covered by that definition, one Clinton adviser said Wednesday. The
president said that oral sex, among other acts, was not covered by
the definition, the adviser said.
</P>
<P>
   But the adviser to Clinton said that he did not acknowledge
having oral sex or any other type of specific sexual contact with
Ms. Lewinsky, instead referring prosecutors back to his initial
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over and over, he said, `I've already said that it was
improper,''' said the adviser, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   That speech was watched by 67.6 million people, Nielsen Media
Research said Wednesday. Some 53 million viewers watched his far
longer State of the Union Message, delivered shortly after Clinton
was first accused of having an affair with Ms. Lewinsky and
covering it up.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton advisers have said that Clinton answered every question
put to him that did not deal with sex. That position is also
central to the president's political defense. If Starr demands
further testimony, the president's team would like to be able to
argue that prosecutors are intent on grilling him only about
intimate matters. ``We want to make the argument that Starr's
investigation is just about sex,'' the adviser said.
</P>
<P>
   David Kendall, Clinton's private lawyer, did not agree to extend
his testimony more than a few minutes beyond the four-hour time
limit, even though prosecutors had more questions. Starr said that
he might subpoena Clinton for further testimony.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The White House would not confirm the request for samples of
Clinton's genetic material from Starr's office. It released a
two-sentence statement: ``On Monday night the president
acknowledged an improper relationship and apologized for that. The
president also said it's time to reclaim his privacy, and we will
respect that by not commenting on every leak generated by this
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Lewinsky prepared to testify, she was said by friends to
be unhappy about Clinton's speech. Ms. Lewinsky, her friends and
associates said, was dismayed to hear what she regarded as an
18-month, emotional relationship with Clinton, which included gifts
of poetry and neckties, acknowledged as merely an inappropriate
dalliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an older man who made all the instances and
references to a younger woman that this relationship was not just
about sex,'' one friend said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky has told friends that she was trying to protect the
president when she signed the affidavit falsely in January that she
had not had a sexual relationship. And in the seven months since,
Ms. Lewinsky has been ``profoundly disappointed'' that the White
House has quietly attempted to smear her.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky's friends said that she had always intended to tell
the truth before the grand jury, so her feelings would have no
impact on her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Since the president acknowledged an improper relationship with
Ms. Lewinsky on Monday night, White House advisers and prominent
Democrats have been disclosing their wounded feelings over the
intimate revelations of recent days. Some appear to be bidding for
publicly sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   Others are just downright mad. Among them is Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, D-Calif., who said Tuesday that her trust in Clinton's
credibility had been ``badly shattered.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days just after the Lewinsky accusations were disclosed
last January, Clinton sought to reassure Senator Feinstein by
privately telling her that Ms. Lewinsky had had to be transferred
from the White House because she was fantasizing about him, and
``on the verge of stalking him,'' a person close to Ms. Feinstein
said Wednesday. Friends said that helped explain Ms. Feinstein's
strong statement of disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   On vacation at a borrowed Martha's Vineyard estate, Clinton
celebrated his 52nd birthday Wednesday night with Vernon Jordan,
his friend and confidant. It was the first extended time that the
two men and their families spent together since Jordan was
subpoenaed by Starr to explain his role late last year in helping
Ms. Lewinsky find a job in New York. He has denied any effort to
help hide her relationship with the president.
</P>
<P>
   The president awoke Wednesday to calls for his resignation from
some editorialists and Republican congressmen. His advisers
dismissed such statements as the chattering of Washington elites,
saying that the public had heard more than it wanted to hear about
the Lewinsky investigation, and was anxious for the federal
government to turn to matters of policy.
</P>
<P>
   Some allies of the president said Starr was trying to make
crimes of private indiscretions. ```I think the criminalization of
bad sexual judgment is something we ought not to be doing,'' said
James Carville, the president's former campaign manager. ``It's
just loony.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-98 2300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980819.0508 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
