<HEADER>
A2409 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SENATE-GREEN-440&AMP;A     08-19 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-GREEN-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEN URGES CUTS IN DEFENSE TO PAY FOR SOCIAL PROGRAMS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mark Green, a Democratic Senate candidate, called
Wednesday for substantial cuts in Pentagon spending over the next
five years, saying the nation was wasting money on defense that
should instead go to school construction, health care for children
and other domestic initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Green, the New York City public advocate and one of the three
major Democratic candidates seeking to challenge Republican Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato this fall, asserted that the Pentagon was relying
on an outdated view of the world in determining the nation's
defense needs.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Green disputed the assumption that the nation
should be prepared to wage simultaneous wars in two theaters, now a
core component of the Pentagon's military strategy.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to an organization of young Democrats, Green
asserted that his defense cuts would not jeopardize national
security. He estimated that they would save $100 billion over the
next five years that could go to rebuilding schools, connecting
classrooms to the Internet, providing children with health
insurance and other spending programs he has proposed during this
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Green urged an end to the Trident D-5 missile program and the
F-22, the Air Force's new attack fighter jet. He also said the
Pentagon should abandon continuing efforts to construct a national
anti-missile program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether we waste $100 billion on Pentagon spending that buys
us no real security, or, on the other hand, invest it in children,
does not appear to be a very difficult proposition,'' Green said at
a breakfast sponsored by Democratic Leadership for the 21st
Century.
</P>
<P>
   Green's speech signaled his latest, and most direct, effort to
court what has historically been the heart of the Democratic
primary electorate: liberal voters. Green moved again to draw a
contrast with both of his major Democratic opponents _ Geraldine
Ferraro, the former congresswoman from Queens, and Rep. Charles
Schumer of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato had no comment Wednesday on Green's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Ms. Ferraro and Schumer said they supported cuts in
defense spending, but not necessarily as extensive as those
proposed by Green.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's campaign manager, Josh Isay, said Schumer supported
the Trident missile but wanted an end to the anti-missile defense
program.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ferraro's press secretary, Stephen Gaskill, said that Ms.
Ferraro supported cuts in defense spending, but he was unable to
say whether she favored the specific measures proposed by Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality of a post-Cold War world is that we can afford to
cut more from the defense budget,'' Gaskill said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In making his proposal, Green took a position that put him at
odds with the broad consensus of Republicans and many Democrats in
Washington. There has been no discussion in Congress about reducing
defense spending, certainly along the lines Green suggested, and
Pentagon spending has been held essentially flat since the end of
the Persian Gulf war in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, there have been calls among prominent
Republicans and conservative Democrats to increase military
spending, most likely starting next year.
</P>
<P>
   Green's strategy, which is to a large extent shaped by the fact
that he does not have the money to afford television
advertisements, is not without its risks. In calling so directly
for cutting defense to finance social programs, it allows D'Amato,
in a general election campaign, to attack Green as a liberal, a
strategy that the Republican incumbent has employed in past
campaigns, including in 1986, when D'Amato defeated Green in
winning his second term.
</P>
<P>
   The defense budget this year is $271 billion. Green said his
proposed cuts totaled $100 billion over five years, though his
opponents said that his figure was inflated.
</P>
<P>
   The $100 billion figure would translate into $20 billion a year
for each of the next five years, or about 7 percent at the current
rate of spending. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
