<HEADLINE>
LOW SCORE NOT IMPORTANT TO VOGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mitch Voges makes another trip to the U.S. Amateur
Championship next week, hoping for the best while not expecting too
much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play almost nothing now,'' he said. ``I've played two
competitive rounds all year.''
</P>
<P>
   But the 1968 City Section champion from Birmingham High will
trek back to Rochester, N.Y., with the satisfaction that he has
already achieved everything he ever wanted from the game.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, more than a decade after he spent six months in a body
cast recuperating from three-level spinal fusion, Voges won the
U.S. Amateur at The Honors Course in Chattanooga, Tenn., outlasting
Manny Zerman 7 &AMP; 6 in the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little bit like that guy in `The Natural,' '' Voges
said. ``Good when he was young, then coming back when he was old
and beat up.''
</P>
<P>
   It worked out as well for Voges as it did for the mythical Roy
Hobbs in that 1984 movie, when the aging ``Natural,'' played by
Robert Redford, hit a pennant-winning home run in the last at-bat
of his abbreviated career.
</P>
<P>
   While Voges has lower expectations for himself next week, he'll
show up at famed Oak Hill Country Club with a high appreciation of
what he has already accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if doesn't turn out well for me, it doesn't make any
difference,'' he said. ``Because I'm satisfied with my competitive
ability. All I ever wanted to do was pull the trigger a few times
when it mattered, and I was able to get that satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Voges wound up satisfied and thrilled in '91, when he overcame
100-degree heat, soaring humidity and a near early-round derailment
in match play to become the first and only San Fernando Valley
golfer to win the U.S. Amateur.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all good,'' he said of his memories of that long, hot
week. ``The best part was that I had my family with me and my (then
13-year-old) son on the bag.''
</P>
<P>
   Voges trailed by three holes with four remaining early in match
play before finishing birdie-par-eagle-birdie to win 1-up in
regulation and advance. It turned out to be his toughest match in a
competition he closed out on the 11th hole of the championship
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``To go all the way, it takes a pretty solid game, a lot of
stamina, a lot of emotional stability,'' he said. ``It's just a
grind, so many rounds of golf. It's not just going out, playing 18
holes and going in. As soon as you think you're getting tired, it's
time to go out again.''
</P>
<P>
   Voges said the grind is matched by the difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like downhill ski racing,'' he said. ``The difference
between getting the gold and not getting anything is a fine line.''
</P>
<P>
   His assured gold next week is his automatic entry, courtesy of a
10-year exemption for winning in '91.
</P>
<P>
   ``With me not playing much golf, going back there is almost
ludicrous,'' Voges said. ``I got to match play last year. That will
be a lofty goal for me this time.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Million Dollar Shootout: Senior PGA star Jim Colbert has come
up with a novel idea in his campaign to raise funds to fight
prostate cancer, which he and Arnold Palmer have overcome in recent
years. The Million Dollar Shootout, scheduled for Sept. 21-26 at
Los Alamitos Racetrack, offers amateur golfers a chance _ at $1 per
shot, no limit on shots _ to win $1 million by hitting a 141-yard
hole-in-one over the Los Alamitos grandstand.
</P>
<P>
   The competition, open to amateur golfers aged 18 and over, will
be held from 1-4 p.m. at the track Sept. 21-25. The two golfers
closest to the hole on those five days will be eligible for the
Sept. 26 final.
</P>
<P>
   Proceeds will benefit Senior PGA Tour For The Cure, the
fundraising and awareness program to help fight prostate cancer _
the most-frequently diagnosed cancer in the nation, with a new case
diagnosed every two and a half minutes.
</P>
<P>
   __ On the marketfront: Tracking the junior golf boom launched
and nourished by Tiger Woods, the nation's largest clubmaker has
introduced a line of golf clubs for children.
</P>
<P>
   Little Berthas, produced by Callaway Golf Co. of Carlsbad, are
woods and irons designed in proportion to children's bodies and
equipped with lightweight, flexible, grafite shafts. Features
include grips for smaller hands and club faces designed to
compensate for children's' swings.
</P>
<P>
   A set, including driver, 6-iron, 8-iron, wedge, putter and bag
sells for a suggested retail price of $500.
</P>
<P>
   The move by Callaway is the latest example of clubmakers testing
the growing market in junior golf. According to the National Golf
Foundation, juniors represented the biggest percentage growth in
play during 1997, when golfers aged 12-17 produced a 33.8 percent
increase over rounds played by that age group during 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Agoura-based Gripps Golf Gear introduced its line of junior
clubs in April and will have them on display at the PGA
International Golf Show next week in Las Vegas. Selling for a
suggested retail price of $139, a set of composite-shafted Gripps
clubs includes a driver, four irons and putter plus bag.
</P>
<P>
   __ Skins saver: Discount tickets are now on sale for the $1
million Skins Game, scheduled for Nov. 28-29 at Rancho La Quinta
Country Club. Season tickets purchased before Sept. 1 cost $60.
After that, the cost is $75.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Tom Lehman and three players to be announced
will compete for $300,000 in the Saturday nine holes and $700,000
on Sunday. Information: 800 914-9075.
</P>
</TEXT>
