<HEADLINE>
KICK COVERAGE IN DAVIS' FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The encounter came early in training camp.
Michael Irvin saw Billy Davis' new blond haircut, and he couldn't
resist this barb: ``Why'd you think you had to go out and get a new
identity?''
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward to yesterday. Davis only wished his new 'do was
causing his identity crisis. Already in competition with Ernie
Mills for the starting wide receiver position opposite Irvin, Davis
learned he'd have to play more special teams this summer.
</P>
<P>
   He did not know whether to be flattered or flabbergasted.
</P>
<P>
   Being one of the Cowboys' best at running down field on punts
and kickoffs, Davis said he could appreciate being needed to
solidify a unit that suffered two fumbles and was a penalty away
from allowing a punt-return touchdown against the Patriots on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis also feels that playing on fourth down will limit his
effectiveness on first, second, and third downs. So the question
that was left to be answered was this: Does the club's use of Davis
on special teams mean that the Cowboys have privately given the
first-team job to Mills?
</P>
<P>
   When asked this question before practice yesterday, Davis did
not know what to think. But no one needed to remind him that
starting wide receivers in the NFL do not play on special teams
unless they are returning kicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is definitely going to set me back as far as competing with
Ernie for the second wide receiver position,'' Davis said of
missing reps with the first team to compete on special teams. ``I
really don't know what it means. I've come to a point of where I'm
tired of figuring it out, of asking where I stand on the field.
Hey, I'm on the field, so that's what's important. Secondly, they
paid me to come in here and have an impact at wide receiver. I'm
working on that, and I'll continue working on being the best
athlete I can be to help this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Wide receivers coach Dwain Painter acknowledged yesterday that
Mills ``has the slight edge'' over Davis because of his experience
with the offense. But head coach Chan Gailey said nothing should be
made of Davis being asked to play more on special teams. The job
hasn't been settled, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Gailey said Davis will get his second start this summer
against the St. Louis Rams on Saturday _ something that was
scheduled before the preseason began.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's such a valuable special teams guy, but he's more than a
Steve Tasker guy,'' Painter said, referring to the retired Buffalo
Bills special teamer. ``Billy is not a backup wide receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis has more receptions than Mills (5 to 2) during the
exhibition games, but Davis acknowledges that he has done nothing
to stand out from Mills. Part of that, Davis said, is because he is
still thinking too much about Gailey's complex offense, which calls
for him to make route-running decisions on the fly. In the Cowboys'
old offense of Ernie Zampese, Davis ran to a spot and Troy Aikman's
pass was already on the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to quit worrying about trying to please the coaching
staff by running the perfect route,'' Davis said. ``I just need to
be alone when the ball gets there. I've got to make plays and not
worry about anything else. And with my size and speed and strength,
I can make an impact with the ball in my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' 23-yard reception against the Patriots has Cowboys
coaches thinking Davis can adapt to this offense, Painter said. The
original play called for Davis to run a 10-yard out pattern toward
the sidelines. But when the Patriots defense switched from a man to
a zone defense at the snap, Davis changed his route to a deep fade
pattern, catching Jason Garrett's pass in front of the safety to
set up the Cowboys' only score of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy has made progress,'' Painter said. ``He just needs the
experience of doing things the way we do them. I have no
reservations about Billy Davis. There is a big upside to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis just hopes that side leads to a starting role.
</P>
</TEXT>
