<SLUG> BC-TIMES-SQUARE-TICKERS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET IS BULLISH ON TIME SQUARE NEON 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(duplication alert: also sent with `a' code)  
 (bl)  
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ever since Trimble's Whiskey erected the first neon
sign there nearly a century ago, Times Square has been New York's
glowing, pulsating marketplace for everything from steam irons to
video cameras, Camels to Calvins. Now, though, it is beginning to
hawk a very different kind of product: the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest of those advertisers _ at least in terms of neon
acreage _ will be the Nasdaq market, which is waging an upstart
campaign to overtake the New York Stock Exchange. Nasdaq recently
signed a deal to build the largest single sign in Times Square: a
$15 million, multimedia kaleidoscope of stock tickers, video
screens and colorful billboards that will festoon the cylindrical
tower of the building now rising at the southeast corner of the
square.
</P>
<P>
   The sign will be big _ roughly the size of three basketball
courts _ but it will hardly be alone. Times Square will soon be a
visual metaphor for the way the stock market _ news about it, talk
about it, anxiety about it _ seems to pervade life these days.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq sign, on the skyscraper known as the Conde Nast
building, will stand directly across the street from Dow Jones'
electronic zipper, which encircles the signpost tower at 1 Times
Square. That, in turn, is directly across the street from where
Reuters will hang a series of electronic signs on its new U.S.
headquarters, at Seventh Avenue and 42nd St.
</P>
<P>
   And those three signs will be only five blocks south of three
157-foot-long stock and financial information zippers that strut
across the Morgan Stanley Dean Witter building, at 1585 Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be a shootout in Times Square between Nasdaq,
Reuters, Morgan Stanley and Dow Jones,'' said George Stonbely,
president of Spectacolor Communications, the electronic sign
company that designed the giant Kodak, Hertz and AT&AMP;T signs on the
face of the Marriott Marquis hotel, at Broadway and 47th Street.
``They're all talking about mega-hardware on the outside of their
buildings. It's going to be funny to see so much financial
information in Times Square, instead of a Coke bottle or a can of
Planters peanuts. Someone who hasn't been here in many years is
going to think they're in the wrong place.''
</P>
<P>
   Stocks and bonds are certainly a far cry from the products that
were traditionally hawked on the district's billboards and neon
signs, like Maytag washers, Wrigley's Spearmint Chewing Gum and
Trimble's Whiskey, which was depicted on that first neon sign in
1904.
</P>
<P>
   The most famous billboard of all was the Camel cigarette sign,
designed by sign specialist Douglas Leigh, which blew rings of
steam over Broadway between 1941 and 1966.
</P>
<P>
   But with Times Square now the symbol of New York's resurgence,
it is fitting that the businesses fueling that boom _ finance,
along with media and entertainment _ should be jostling for space.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times Square has always been a little bit ahead of the game in
displaying the rawest edge of commercialization of our society,''
said Thomas Bender, a history professor at New York University.
``It makes sense that Wall Street should display itself on the
biggest public stage available at a time when we have the most open
celebration of the marketplace in history.''
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, the changing images on the signs reflect the
changing nature of the business being done in the offices behind
them.
</P>
<P>
   As a longtime entertainment district, Times Square was a logical
location for media giants like Reuters and Viacom. But the
financial services industry has become a large and growing
presence, most notably Morgan Stanley, which signed a tentative
deal last week to erect its third tower at the north end of the
square.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for the financial industry, Times Square's greatest charm
is its advertising might, especially at a time when the number of
Americans who own stock has soared to 43 percent of adults, from 10
percent only two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to compete in the global marketplace, what
better place than the international crossroads of the world,'' said
David Arena, who heads Morgan Stanley's corporate real estate
department and is well aware of the estimated 20 million visitors
who pass through the square annually, not to mention the 250
million television viewers who watch the ball drop from the former
Times Tower on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the unbridled proliferation of signs in Times Square
has some people worried that the billboards will eventually all
look like undifferentiated ``wallpaper.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never this much clutter, this much clamor for
attention,'' said Jason Perline, who has put up signs in Times
Square for 32 years. ``It's anybody's guess how long it'll be an
attractive media buy. Time will only tell, but I do question it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reuters is going to great lengths to insure that its signs will
be unique among that ``clutter,'' by hiring the designer Edwin A.
Schlossberg and by dropping plans for a zipper, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Frank Zarb, chairman of the National
Association of Stock Dealers, which owns the Nasdaq market, has
made no secret of his plans to build a world financial market that
would rival the New York Stock Exchange. The NASD has already
acquired the American Stock Exchange and may move it, together with
the association's headquarters, to Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   With its giant sign and other attractions in Times Square,
Nasdaq hopes to sell itself to the public by creating a virtual
trading floor that rivals the much-televised opening bell of the
New York Stock Exchange, which is larger and better known. Unlike
the telegenic trading floors of the New York exchange, Nasdaq is an
electronic market composed mainly of telephone lines and computers.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jones, a senior vice president at the NASD in
Washington, confirmed that Nasdaq was planning to move its
marketing operation to Times Square, but he declined to provide
details. Sign builders and real estate executives say, though, that
the NASD's board approved a 65,000-square-foot leasing deal Aug. 6
for the gigantic sign, a television studio and marketing center at
4 Times Square, at 43rd Street and Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
