<HEADER>
A2529 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FHS-PLUMMETS-LADN     08-19 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FHS-PLUMMETS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANAGED-CARE COMPANY'S SHARES LOSE NEARLY 15 PERCENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Shares in Foundation Health Systems, the nation's
fourth-largest publicly traded managed-care company, fell sharply
on apparent concern that the company will not make as much money
this year as expected.
</P>
<P>
   At one point Wednesday, Foundation shares were off nearly 24
percent, trading at a four-year low of $12.375. But late trading
helped the issue regain some ground to close down $2.375, or 14.61
percent, at $13.875. More than 1.95 million shares traded hands, or
more than four times the stock's three-month average daily volume.
</P>
<P>
   Though Foundation last week announced trouble with several of
its Medicare programs that could hurt year-end earnings, analysts
and company officials were at a loss to explain the sharp sell-off
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could make up 50 stories that all sound plausible, but I
don't know why the stock is down,'' said Mary O'Connell at San
Francisco-based Josephthal &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   At the request of the New York Stock Exchange, Foundation
officials addressed the price drop Wednesday, saying in a written
statement that they were ``aware of no corporate developments that
would account for the unusual trading activity'' in the company's
stock.
</P>
<P>
   The managed-care sector in general has come under investor scorn
lately, as giants like United Healthcare Corp. have reported heavy
losses, and even profitable firms have seen their share price fall.
Humana Corp., which last week reported a 24 percent increase in
quarterly earnings, has lost more than half its market
capitalization since late July.
</P>
<P>
   Foundation last week reported that before a one-time charge from
the sale of its workers' compensation unit, its profit dropped to
$31.3 million, or 26 cents a share, from $54.8 million, or 43 cents
a share in 1997. But analysts said any effect from that drop should
have been felt last week, when the news was released.
</P>
<P>
   Foundation spokesman David Olson speculated that the company's
shares were under pressure from short sellers who borrow shares in
a company, sell them and then replace the shares later with ones
bought at a lower price. So-called ``shorts'' are often accused of
starting rumors about a company in investor circles in the hope
that it will send the stock price down.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
