<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-19 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2530 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIMES-SQUARE-TICKERS-     08-19 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMES-SQUARE-TICKERS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: and Broadway.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Real estate executives who have seen the plans said the Nasdaq
marketing operation would move from an obscure berth on the ninth
floor of 33 Whitehall St. in lower Manhattan to 4 Times Square.
There would be a broadcast studio with a curving wall of television
monitors looking out on Times Square from behind a semicircular,
two-story glass wall, where daily briefings and public stock
offerings would be announced. A public entrance would lead to the
second floor, where there would be an auditorium and interactive
displays for visitors wanting to track the progress of various
stocks. The NASD is also taking some office space.
</P>
<P>
   The huge sign itself would rise from the third story and ascend
about 125 feet, the executives said, and is expected to cost $15
million, about three times the price of Morgan Stanley's giant
electronic zippers, but only half of what Reuters may spend to
build 15,169 square feet of sophisticated, high-resolution video
signs on the side of its building.
</P>
<P>
   Though ever popular, signs in Times Square have only in recent
years generated big money. Last year, a German investment group
bought 1 Times Square for $110 million, or nearly four times the
price paid by Lehman Brothers two years earlier. The value of the
deal was in the signs, not the building. The four large signs that
climb up the front of 1 Times Square, home of the New Year's Eve
ball drop, generate more than $7 million a year in rent from
Budweiser, Nissin, ITT and Panasonic.
</P>
<P>
   The current Times Square revival is in stark contrast to the
1970s, when many New Yorkers avoided the area and neon signs fell
out of fashion. By the time Leigh sold his 14 billboards in Times
Square to the Van Wagner sign company, 13 were blank. The sole
renter was Sony.
</P>
<P>
   Perline, a founder of Van Wagner, said that as hard as he tried
he could not sell space to U.S. companies because of the image of
Times Square as dowdy and dangerous. He recalled a salesman for
Philip Morris saying, ``We don't want a sign seen only by pimps and
prostitutes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Who smokes more than pimps and prostitutes?'''
Perline said. ``But it wasn't a good sales pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Wagner turned its attention to Sony's contemporaries in
Japan, emerging companies looking to make a name for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many New Yorkers, the Japanese realized that millions of
camera-laden tourists were stillpouring through Times Square every
year in a kind of civic pilgrimage akin to visiting Mecca or
Lourdes. Soon Hitachi, Minolta, Konica and Fuji were pitching up
billboards and neon spectaculars in Times Square, the first step
toward becoming household words in America.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, U.S. companies did not return for another
decade, and not until the city imposed an ordinance in 1987
requiring new buildings in the Times Square district to display
oversize, bright signs on new buildings along Broadway and Seventh
Avenue. At the time, civic groups hailed the ordinance as a tool to
save Times Square, but real estate developers who were trying to
douse the bright lights and create a new office district disliked
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investment bankers and lawyers don't want to work in an
environment surrounded by flashing lights,'' David Solomon, the
developer who built the Morgan Stanley building and then lost it in
the recession, said at the time. ``They want museums and sidewalk
cafes.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when Morgan Stanley moved into the tower in 1995, it was
reluctant to dangle bright, garish signs off the side of its
buildings. But Disney has moved onto 42nd Street, and a museum,
albeit Madame Tussaud's, is on the way, making the area more
respectable.
</P>
<P>
   And Morgan Stanley has since merged with Dean Witter, providing
the investment bank with a vast retail clientele that can be
reached through the signs in Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``The signs of the '20s _ Presto steam irons and Royal
typewriters _ were about liberation from drudgery,'' said Tama
Starr, co-author of ``Signs and Wonders: The Spectacular Marketing
of America'' and president of Artkraft Strauss, a family-owned sign
maker. ``Now the signs are about the world market and the
information age.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
