<HEADLINE>
NO WORD FROM WOODS; OFFENSE LOOKS SHARP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC quarterback Quincy Woods had not been heard
from Wednesday as he continued to ponder his future with the
Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, upset that he is no better than third-string, was given
some time off by USC coach Paul Hackett but was expected to contact
the coach Tuesday night. No USC player or coach has talked to Woods
for at least 48 hours and he took all his belongings when he left
UC Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't heard a word,'' Hackett said. ``I was pretty
flexible as far as sorting things out. I told him, `I will support
you.' He doesn't feel comfortable to tell me (his plans) yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett has urged Woods to play wide receiver this season, but
he will not force him to quit playing quarterback. Woods could
transfer to a lower-division school and gain immediate eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   __ Improved scrimmage: USC's offense rebounded during a 92-play
scrimmage at the Coliseum on Wednesday, the Trojans' final tune-up
before the Pigskin Classic on Aug. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver R. Jay Soward had five receptions for 133 yards
and one touchdown as the Trojans' offense produced six touchdowns.
Freshman quarterback Carson Palmer completed 11 of 15 passes for
166 yards while Mike Van Raaphorst completed eight of 10 passes for
126 yards and two touchdowns, including a 47-yard scoring strike to
Soward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the offense felt the repercussions from last
weekend,'' Hackett said. ``The running-back group stepped up. I'm
pleased with the quarterbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   There could have been more scoring, but Soward dropped a 62-yard
scoring pass from Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Achilles' heel,'' Hackett said. ``You drop one and it's
likely to cost you the game. R. Jay knows it's a weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Jason Thomas threw a 71-yard TD pass to walk-on Jason
d'Autremont.
</P>
<P>
   Malaefou MacKenzie led the running backs with 78 yards in five
carries and two touchdowns. Ted Iacenda had 61 yards on two
carries, including a 55-yard run. Freshman Frank Strong had another
impressive performance, with 39 yards in three carries.
</P>
<P>
   Strong's elusive moves have been one of the surprises of
training camp, especially considering Nebraska recruited him to
play linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``The line's doing such a great job, it's easy,'' Strong said.
``They're the ones that set the tempo today.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Sitting it out: About 15 players did not scrimmage, including
Grant Pearsall (knee), Larry Parker (hamstring), Marc Matock
(shoulder), John Fox (back spasms), Lawrence Larry (ankle), Marvin
Powell (knee), Ken Bowen (elbow) and Mark Cusano (hamstring). None
has been ruled out of the Purdue game. Troy Garner sprained his
right ankle during the scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   __ Grain at left guard: Junior Jason Grain appears to have
locked up the starting left guard position. He worked out with the
first unit in the scrimmage and has received compliments from
Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling good about the left side,'' Hackett said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
