<HEADLINE>
SEEING FOOD AS HISTORICALLY AND ESTHETICALLY PROFOUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a rare example of marital and professional
alignment, Michael and Ariane Batterberry _ gatekeepers of
Manhattan's foodie culture _ are celebrating almost every possible
anniversary a couple could in one year.
</P>
<P>
   Food and Wine _ the magazine they created that guided Americans
through Perrier, the purple Peruvian potato and Patagonian
toothfish _ celebrates its 20th year next month. Food Arts, the
professional chef's bible they founded and still edit, turns 10. In
November, Routledge Press publishes the 25th-anniversary edition of
the Batterberrys' culinary history, ``On The Town in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and May 15 was their 30th wedding anniversary, which they
celebrated at a meeting of the National Restaurant Association.
</P>
<P>
   So when Batterberry, a well-appointed man who favors slim
Italian suits and cultivates an accent as plummy as George
Plimpton's, and Mrs. Batterberry, a cool ashy blonde with an old
New York rhythm to her voice, talk food, they speak profoundly, as
if eating were a political, or even religious, movement.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Batterberry talks about the revolution that transformed a
Wonder-Bread-adoring America into a country that embraced the
Australian blue squash and the smoked-salmon pizza. Lob any food
question their way and they have an answer. Where was vodka sauce
invented? He said: ``The White Elephant, in Rome, in the '60s.
Everybody thought, `Has the chef thrown a Bloody Mary on the
pasta?''' Carpaccio? She said: ``It was 1971, Harry's Bar in
Venice.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the Batterberrys believe that the history of food is
more scintillating than the history of ... anything. ``When you
start looking at people and what they did in restaurants, you're
dealing with public life as it's lived day to day and that's real
history,'' Mrs. Batterberry said over a cup of tea and a petit four
in the Four Seasons lobby lounge.
</P>
<P>
   The Batterberrys won't reveal their ages (``Age entries should
be reserved for wine lists,'' he said), but let's just say that a
bottle of Quinta Do Noval ``Nationale'' port about his age would
cost a few thousand dollars. Ariane Ruskin grew up on the Upper
East Side _ where the couple still live _ graduated from Barnard
(class of 1955) and got a degree in classics from Cambridge
University. He was born in England 60-ish years ago, moved to New
York with his family before high school, and knew he would stay
forever when he celebrated his 12th birthday with his parents by
seeing ``Parsifal'' at the Met, then going to Harlem's Cafe Society
to hear Hazel Scott sing and Zero Mostel tell jokes.
</P>
<P>
   The Batterberrys met on the St. Regis roof in the mid-1960s at a
benefit for an arts society. After sharing a house in the Hamptons
with Hugh Johnson, the wine writer, they decided to work with him
on a book about the history of New York restaurants. They weren't
food writers, but esthetes: Batterberry had spent much of his 20s
painting and writing in South America and Europe; she had published
a history of art. But they both loved restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, coincidentally, or maybe just politely,
Johnson bowed out of the book project.
</P>
<P>
   The book was published in 1973, a few years after they were
married, because, as Batterberry puts it, ``New York was in such a
miserable state then'' _ the late '60s _ that the publisher decided
no one wanted to read a book about Manhattan entertaining or night
life. By 1973, though, Burroughs Mitchell, Ernest Hemingway's last
editor at Scribner, had seen the light _ or perhaps had just eaten
at some great new restaurants _ and decided to publish the book,
long a staple in culinary libraries.
</P>
<P>
   The Batterberrys see all history through the social prism of
food: the Depression, World War II, technology, feminism. In fact,
in the mid-1970s, the couple decided that feminism had created a
market for a food magazine aimed at both men and women, and created
Food and Wine, with start-up money from Hugh Hefner. They edited
the magazine until they sold it to American Express in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a big changeover at the moment we founded Food and
Wine in the late '70s,'' Mrs. Batterberry said. ``Before feminism,
it was the little wife in the kitchen.'' Many of the world's most
famous chefs are and have always been men, but when more women went
to work outside the home, the Batterberrys explained, more men
wandered into the nonprofessional kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys were starting to go off to college with woks,''
Batterberry said, adding, ``You know, it was like bra-burning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything changed!'' Mrs. Batterberry exulted, with enough
gusto to rattle her teacup. ``New York today is kind of like
Florence during the Renaissance. There's a genius on every corner,
someone young who is doing something very exciting everywhere you
look.''
</P>
<P>
   And what happens when the stock market crumbles like an
overbaked scone and all those bankers with a yearning for haute
cuisine and $600 bottles of Chateau Lafite-Rothschild start eating
Thai takeout?
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you mean will we become like the Baths of Caracalla?''
asked Mrs. Batterberry, referring to ruins left behind by the
Romans. ``Will we leave behind these huge vast empty restaurants?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we do,'' her husband said, ``at least the Olive Garden
uses fresh tomatoes and basil in the summertime now,'' he said.
``So the revolution has achieved something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
