<SLUG> BC-NY-CHARTER-MAYOR-ASSESS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MODEST CHARTER PLAN SERVES A BIG MAYORAL GOAL
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Mayor Rudolph Giuliani created his Charter
Revision Commission last spring, he described its mission in the
noblest of terms: to present to the voters a series of much-needed
changes to the City Charter, the hallowed how-to list for the
governance of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Although a furrowed brow may have masked a mayoral grin, few
missed Giuliani's inside joke. The immediate need for such a
commission was less to save Gotham from chaos, and more to trump a
political adversary on a matter of _believe it or not _ baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Having his commission place a Charter-related question on
November's ballot would, under state law, block the plans of City
Council Speaker Peter Vallone for a referendum on whether city
funds should help pay for a stadium in Manhattan for the New York
Yankees _ which the mayor saw as an affront to his skills as a
leader and negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the commission nears completion of its task, the mayor's
gambit is drawing fewer smiles. Its members have weathered brutal
public hearings at which they were ridiculed as Giuliani go-fers.
As predicted by its many critics, the commission did not have
enough time to meet its most ambitious goals.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the commission emerged this week with just a single
proposal: a stripped-down campaign-finance plan that has little
support outside the rooms in which its 12 members gather. But the
proposal, however modest, has one alluring attribute. It has been
drafted in time to appear on the November ballot, thereby serving
the mayor's political needs.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, which the commission is scheduled to vote on
Thursday night, calls for a referendum on whether to ban city
candidates from taking contributions from corporations. Advocates
for campaign-finance reform say that the measure is tepid at best
since corporate officers could still make donations as individuals
or through political action committees. They prefer a comprehensive
City Council bill that would lower contribution limits and provide
more money from the city treasury to candidates who participate in
the city's campaign-finance program.
</P>
<P>
   The full Council is expected to approve its bill next week.
Whether the mayor plans to sign the bill into law remains unclear,
but his defiance on the matter of the commission is not. Wednesday,
the mayor was asked whether the commission's proposal was worth the
time and money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is worth a great deal of time and money given the fact that
Speaker Vallone wants to misuse the referendum process,'' he said.
``And there is no other choice but to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's political victory comes at a cost, said Gene
Russianoff, the staff attorney for the New York Public Interest
Research Group and an early critic of the charter panel. ``The
charter process has been a disgrace,'' he said. ``The worst
predictions we had for it came true. It was sloppy, hasty, and in
search of any purpose.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Assessments like that of Russianoff _ and there are many _
rankle Peter Powers, a close friend of the mayor's and a former
deputy mayor who is chairman of the commission. ``I think we can
hold our heads high and say we did our job responsibly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani administration's peculiar entree into charter
reform began in April, shortly after Vallone announced plans for a
referendum on the possibility of building a stadium for the Yankees
in Manhattan. Vallone's measure was intended to keep the team in
the Bronx, and thwart the mayor's plan to offer midtown Manhattan
as an alternative to losing the Yankees to New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   His aides say that Giuliani was genuinely offended by Vallone's
plan. He thought it would compromise his responsibilities as the
city's leader and raise the political profile of the speaker, who
is a Democratic candidate for governor.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor responded by creating the charter commission, assigned
with the task of coming up with something in time to block
Vallone's referendum.
</P>
<P>
   The commission held public hearings in each of the five boroughs
to solicit comments that were often abusive or frivolous. All the
while, it had to contend with an ever-closer deadline of the first
week of September to insure that its proposals would appear on the
November ballot. But as the criticism continued and the complexity
of their task proved more time-consuming, the panel's members began
to shed their ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-July, the commission dropped several goals to focus on
campaign finance, nonpartisan elections, and the part-time duties
of the City Council. Then, two weeks ago, it winnowed its goals
further, to campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, this week, the commission abandoned the centerpiece of
its campaign-finance proposal, which was to to bar candidates from
accepting campaign contributions from people who do business with
the city. Now, aside from some minor changes to the city's Campaign
Finance Board, the panel's ballot proposal is to ban contributions
from corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Schrader, director of Citizen Action of New York City, a
public advocacy group, said that he had met several times with the
commission to try and develop an effective campaign-finance
proposal. But those talks abruptly ended.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he has seen the commission's ballot proposal, he senses
a rush job.
</P>
<P>
   ``They squandered a real opportunity to create a really strong
campaign finance initiative,'' he said. ``It feels like they're
lurching for anything to block Yankee Stadium. It makes you suspect
it's done not for policy but for politics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
