<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOFTY GOALS FOR NEW MATADOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If Melvin Blue is even ONE-THIRD as good as he
thinks he is, Cal State Northridge should contend for the Big Sky
Conference title this season.
</P>
<P>
   Blue, a senior running back who transferred from Utah State this
year, has his sights set high. Make that ridiculously high.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is unbelievable,'' Blue said, accurately. ``But I want
to run for 3,000 yards.''
</P>
<P>
   This despite playing at pass-happy CSUN, where no back has ever
rushed for more than 1,500 yards. But Blue's got an agenda. He
wants to play in the NFL, and he has the attention of pro scouts.
But in Division I-AA, Blue figures a good season won't be enough.
He needs a great season. Like 3,000 yards great.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just me. I know I can run for 2,000, but just to go for
3 (thousand).... I think the higher your goals, the more you do,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the euphoria of returning to his native Los Angeles has
simply gone to Blue's head.
</P>
<P>
   He describes the four years spent in Utah as the toughest time
of his life. He feuded with his coach, groused about splitting time
with other backs and struggled to adjust to a program heavy on
discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Then, six months ago, Blue's girlfriend in Hawthorne gave birth
to their daughter, Symphony, and everything changed. Blue wanted to
be close to his daughter, wanted to be near his family and needed
to find a new football home to make the most of his senior season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where I come from (Compton), a lot of people grow up without
their parents. I didn't want to see my daughter go through it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   New CSUN head coach Ron Ponciano was more than happy to bring
Blue, a Walter Payton Award candidate, back to Southern California.
At 6 feet, 232 pounds, Blue combines size and speed and could be
CSUN's best running back since Robert Trice, an NFL draftee in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Melvin is a powerful runner who can make people miss,''
Ponciano said. ``He can run over them, he can catch the ball. He
can do a number of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Even rush for 3,000 yards?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like a little more reality with that thought, but it's
nice he's ambitious,'' Ponciano said. ``I think everyone's looking
for ... well over 1,000 yards.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue rushed for 741 yards and nine touchdowns last year,
including a 224-yard, three-TD effort at Idaho. That, Blue figures,
should translate into even higher numbers in the Big Sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's (Division) I-AA. Not to talk bad about it, but the
competition is not as strong as it is (in the Big West
Conference),'' Blue said.
</P>
<P>
   And the Matadors' passing game should leave Blue with big
running lanes. ``A lot of teams play Northridge with dime and
nickel coverage, where they take their linebackers out, which
leaves litte (defensive backs) in there for me just to run
through,'' he said. ``So I'm looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Ouch report: Four Matadors went down with groin injuries
during Wednesday's morning practice, and Ponciano blames a poorly
maintained practice field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting strains and pulls due to our sloppy pratice
field. I'm just irate over it right now,'' Ponciano said.
</P>
<P>
   The injured included receiver Anthony Ramos and defensive backs
Donnell Day, Chris Karibee and Quincy Watkins.
</P>
<P>
   __ Also: Though junior Josh Fiske is designated the starting
quarterback, he continues to split snaps with junior David Lins,
freshman Marcus Brady and sophomore Mitch Ryerson. The rotation
will probably continue until one player sets himself apart from the
pack.... The Matadors will hold their first full-contact, full-pads
practice today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
