<SLUG> BC-NJ-AIRPORT-COMPLEX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANS UNVEILED FOR HOTEL COMPLEX AT NEWARK AIRPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ The developers of a proposed hotel and conference
center complex on the fringes of Newark International Airport
Wednesday detailed their plans for the project, which would tap
into a growing need for hotel rooms and meeting space within easy
reach of the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The 55-acre site will include a 50,000-square-foot conference
center, a 550-room deluxe hotel and a 250-room limited service
hotel, said Emanuel Stern, president and chief executive of Hartz
Mountain Industries, the developer. He said work on the project
would create 3,000 construction jobs and 2,500 permanent jobs once
the work was completed. Construction of the $150 million project is
to start early next year, company officials said, and is expected
to be completed by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the site, stretching along the long-unused Waverly
rail yards a little over a mile west of the airport, have for much
of the last decade been little more than a gleam in the eye of
developers and Newark officials. The expectations have risen and
fallen with the changes in Newark's fortunes, the real estate
market and air travel.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, the chances of development on the site
have increased tremendously as the Port Authority of New York and
New Jersey planned and began construction of a monorail from the
airport to a new terminal for New Jersey Transit commuter trains
and Amtrak trains adjacent to the Hartz Mountain property. Last
spring, the developer won in its bid to build a pedestrian walkway
connecting the hotel and conference center complex to the terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Smith Jr., executive vice president of operations with
Hartz Mountain Industries, said the property the developer acquired
from Newark in 1988 had gone from being a likely industrial site
with little access to the airport to a vastly more valuable
property with a direct line into the stream of 30 million people
who pass through the airport annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the current upturn in the economy which really makes this
possible,'' he said. ``And we have been hearing that there is an
increasing business travel meeting space requirement for companies
that might want to fly people into a single airport in the morning,
get them to an all-day meeting near the airport and then fly them
home that same night.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Hartz Mountain spent between $3 million and $5
million to rid the site of hazardous materials like heavy metals.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the plans were revealed Wednesday as Hartz Mountain
executives and other business people joined Newark Mayor Sharpe
James and Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., on a tour of a number of
economic development sites in the city, which has been undergoing a
resurgence and attracting the interest of developers after years of
economic decline. As Stern described the company's plans, a steady
stream of airplanes could be seen just over his shoulder, noisily
sliding down the glide path to the airport's runways.
</P>
<P>
   James called the wedding of the proposed conference center
complex with air, rail and highway connections ``a home run'' for
the city economically.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg, who was instrumental in winning federal financing
for the monorail and the commuter and Amtrak rail terminal, said
the transportation links and the need for meeting space would make
the location ``a premier site'' in the region.
</P>
<P>
   There are now about 3,700 hotel rooms within two miles of the
airport, Newark economic development officials said, and the
proposed Hartz Mountain complex will, by itself, increase that
number by more than 20 percent. Newark was listed as the 16th
busiest airport in the world in terms of takeoffs and landings in
1997, by the Airports Council International _ ahead of La Guardia,
which was 33rd, and Kennedy International, which was 34th. In total
passengers, Kennedy was 15th, Newark 16th and La Guardia 37th.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, Newark has been the fastest growing airport in
the New York area, Port Authority officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
