<SLUG> BC-BBO-LITTLE-LEAGUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELAWARE GAINS IN LITTLE LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the most dramatic play imaginable, a bases-loaded, two-out
delayed steal of home in extra innings, Georgetown, Del., beat
Staten Island, New York City, 3-2, on Wednesday in the semifinals
of the Little League Eastern Regional tournament at Breen Field in
Bristol, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Delaware will play Toms River, N.J., on Thursday night (ESPN2, 8
p.m. ET) for the regional title, with the winner advancing to the
eight-team Little League World Series in Williamsport, Pa.,
starting Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Delaware-Staten Island game was tied at 2-2 after the
regulation six innings. In the last of the eighth, with Delaware
runners on second and third, Staten Island intentionally walked the
Delaware pitcher, Donald Lewis, to fill the bases.
</P>
<P>
   With the count 1-2 on Justin West, Staten Island catcher Matt
Broms threw the ball back to Matt Castellano, his pitcher. When
Castellano turned his back on home plate, Delaware manager Bill
West told the runner on third base, Jared Lineweaver, to race home.
</P>
<P>
   Castellano did not see Lineweaver take off. When Broms yelled to
alert his pitcher, Castellano turned, saw what was happening and
threw home. Lineweaver slid and kicked the ball out of the
catcher's glove, ending the game. Paul Alesse, the official scorer,
called it a stolen base because, he said, ``The play was too close
to give an error to anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was dominated by the pitchers. Lewis, the winner,
pitched a six-hitter, struck out 13 and had 80 strikes among his
124 pitches. Castellano yielded only 4 hits and struck out 17, but
also walked 10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
