<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS GAME JUST AN EXHIBITION, JETS INSIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ They may be wearing the helmet designs of a
bygone era on Thursday, and they may be facing the team that once
symbolized the Establishment, but to the Jets, the meeting with the
Giants has become just an exhibition game rather than a rite of
passage.
</P>
<P>
   Jets Coach Bill Parcells, who coached the Giants to a 9-2 record
against the Jets, including 2-1 in the regular season, said:
``Bragging rights are overrated. Who are you bragging to? You're
bragging to somebody in preseason.''
</P>
<P>
   And after their 33-0 loss to the Baltimore Ravens on Saturday,
the Jets are bragging to nobody. Thus, the game is really more
about the Jets getting back on track as a team, getting ready to
start the season with many new faces.
</P>
<P>
   All the regulars will see action into the third quarter,
including the special teams, the most improved unit a year ago when
the Jets had the best field position in pro football, on both
offense and defense.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Ravens, 10 players who were backups the week before
were starters.
</P>
<P>
   Now Jumbo Elliott is back at left tackle after recuperating from
an ankle injury, and Todd Burger is at left guard after being
sidelined for most of the opening half, perhaps as a motivational
tool. Glenn Foley is the starting quarterback, as Parcells
promised, after Vinny Testaverde started against the Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Parcells has created what he describes as ``a two-headed
middle linebacker'' and a ``two-headed fullback.'' Pepper Johnson
will start in the middle, while Dwayne Gordon will see special
teams action and then relieve Johnson. Keith Byars and Jerald
Sowell will split the fullback spot.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are concerned about themselves, not the Giants. The
first time the Jets faced the Giants, it was six months after their
stunning triumph over the Baltimore Colts in Super Bowl III.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were champions of every place but New York,'' linebacker
Ralph Baker liked to say. ``It was as if we had to beat the Giants
to really be the champions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets did, and handily, with Joe Namath starring and a player
named Mike Battle _ who used to chew glass in barroom bets _
hurdling the opposition returning a punt.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Jets are once again wearing the helmet logos they donned
when their game with the Giants in 1969 began a tradition that
keeps fans excited. This is the 30th meeting between the teams,
with the Giants holding a 16-12-1 edge.
</P>
<P>
   But the matchup has increasingly turned into merely a summertime
exhibition. In fact, Foley doesn't remember that it was against the
Giants a year ago that he came in off the bench and tossed a
touchdown pass to Dedric Ward for the deciding score.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the significance of Thursday night's game, Foley
said, ``I think right now we're trying to turn this thing into
where it will be in the regular season.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley, who is from Cherry Hill, N.J., and knows more about the
Jets and Giants than most players, said of his performance last
year: ``I can't remember anything about the game. You can't get
caught up in it. It's a fun atmosphere but we're grinding out
two-a-days and you're in the process of getting ready.''
</P>
<P>
   For linebacker Chad Cascadden, the game, and not the opposition,
is what is important over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't execute well last week,'' he said. ``We just need to
worry about what we need to do. Who we play isn't important. It's
not like I want to beat the Giants to win the New York
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Burger is one of several players with uncertain outlooks.
Burger, a free agent who played previously for the Chicago Bears,
didn't start against the Ravens. Parcells is looking for better
pass protection from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not starting got me going,'' he said. ``The message was: get
in gear or get ready to watch on Sundays.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, a former Giant, said: ``I look at this game as trying
to dominate the line. Sure there's a little more excitement, but
it's still an exhibition game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
