</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TV-SHELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S HEAD-TO-HEAD, AND MADE FOR TV 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BRADLEY S. KLEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORANJESTAD, Aruba _ Terry Jastrow, executive producer of
``Shell's Wonderful World of Golf'' TV series, knew he had a
winning site the first time he looked out upon Tierra del Sol Golf
Course in Aruba. Here he was on a desert island in the Caribbean
Sea, with golf holes that brought the beach and water into full
view. A perfect setting, he thought, for a match between Nick Price
and Payne Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one problem, he told his would-be hosts. Jastrow
pointed to the famed California Lighthouse, a 120-foot-tall
landmark that dominates Aruba's rocky northwest coastline looming
over the back nine. ``It's a little faded and rusted,'' Jastrow
said. ``Any chance we can paint it white? It'll show up much better
on television.''
</P>
<P>
   Jastrow has an eye for detail. He has to: he is the man who has
taken charge of a television series that had long been familiar to
golf fans. From 1961 through 1972, ``Shell's Wonderful World of
Golf'' was a Saturday afternoon staple. Starting with a match
between Gene Littler and Byron Nelson at Pine Valley Golf Club in
New Jersey, the series featured big-name golfers in an 18-hole
match contested on a famous course.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, the show emphasized the game's global
appeal. Viewers were transported to the Old Course at St. Andrews
for a match between Gene Sarazen and Henry Cotton or to Cape Breton
Highlands Links in northern Nova Scotia for a match between the
Canadians Al Balding and George Knudson. Classic golf writers like
Herbert Warren Wind and Al Barkow wrote for the show, and Sarazen
was ultimately recruited to serve as a host. All told, 92 episodes
were broadcast _ until sponsors discontinued the show because of
mounting production problems and lagging network ratings.
</P>
<P>
   A generation later, the show was revived, this time as a
prime-time cable show, and was broadcast up to five times a year.
``Shell's Wonderful World of Golf'' was restarted in 1994, with a
match between Arnold Palmer and Jack Nicklaus at Pinehurst No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   As president of Jack Nicklaus Productions, Jastrow has handled
all 19 of the new episodes. His responsibilities include locating
sites, arranging matches and overseeing the taping. ``There are
three stars to each show,'' he said. ``The two golfers and the
site.''
</P>
<P>
   Each year, he inspects some three dozen potential sites. What
does he look for? ``A good natural setting and strong local
sponsorship.'' Total production costs for each show come to about
$400,000, including the purse. Local business interests get
involved to showcase tourism and real estate. For the Aruba show,
resort operators joined the local tourism authority in publicizing
the island's newfound status as a golf destination.
</P>
<P>
   Until the opening of the Robert Trent Jones Jr.-designed Tierra
del Sol layout in 1996, the island's only golf course consisted of
a burned-out nine-hole tract with sand greens. Folks here now hope
that all those aerial views of the golf course and surroundings
will entice viewers to think about a golf getaway in Aruba.
</P>
<P>
   Jastrow, always looking for good visuals, is happy to comply. As
the golfers leave the sixth green, Jastrow points to a caravan of
all-terrain vehicles making the trek along the beach. ``Make sure
you get a shot of that,'' he reminds a cameraman.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1961, Littler's share for winning was $2,000, with
Nelson settling for $1,000; today, winners receive $100,000, while
second place pays $50,000. Of course, not everyone takes these
matches as seriously as did Ben Hogan.
</P>
<P>
   For his match in 1966 against Sam Snead at the Houston Country
Club, Hogan arrived a week in advance and played six approach shots
from the left side, six from the center and six from the right into
each of the greens.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, a few casual practice rounds sufficed for
Price and Stewart, enough for them (and their regular PGA Tour
caddies) to acclimate to the 30-mile-an-hour wind.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1960s, filming an 18-hole round required two days
of shooting. The 35-mm motion-picture cameras were clumsy to handle
and frequently had to be refocused and relighted. Occasionally,
golfers would have to replay shots that the cameras had missed. All
of that has changed now, thanks to six video cameras and a crew of
30 that virtually swarms over the golf course. The match between
Price and Stewart took all of four and a half hours to tape.
</P>
<P>
   Announcers Jack Whitaker and Bob Rosburg followed the action and
did some live voice-overs. Much will also be added during the weeks
of editing needed to boil the show down to 90 minutes. The air date
is Oct. 28 on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jastrow will have plenty of time for scouting more
sites and putting together other matches. He still bristles over
having nearly secured Tiger Woods against Jack Nicklaus at Merion
Golf Club outside Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger's a big fan of the series,'' he said. ``I'm told he
spends time at the Golf Channel watching old tapes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
